<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9806 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     12-09 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAL `D' FOR DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ You always could count on Dave Taylor to do
the dirty work. In the late 1970s and early 1980s he was the
undervalued jewel on the Kings' Triple Crown Line, the one who'd
dig the puck out of the corners and sweep opponents out of the way
so Marcel Dionne and Charlie Simmer could do their scoring.
</P>
<P>
   There was no tinsel in Taylor's game, no glitzy moves or jazzy
improvisations. He paved a long and industrious NHL career by being
as colorful as asphalt. His deliberate, workmanlike approach paid
dividends when he was a player, but it's costing the Kings dearly
now that he's their general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The road back to respectability Taylor has spent the past two
years methodically laying down is littered with potholes and
debris. It has more dead ends than a maze. In rebuilding the
organization in his image, he has forgotten what makes teams go.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, it's hard to make any real headway when you're a
carburetor short of an engine. With their leading scorer ahead of
his pace of last season yet averaging under a point a game, the
Kings clearly don't have the combustion to keep pace with the
Colorados and Dallases and, criminy, even the Calgarys.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind a win, the Kings will go into their game tonight
against the Washington Capitals in search of a lead. They haven't
enjoyed one since Nov. 21, a span of five games. You want
frightful? In the 16 games the Kings have played since Halloween,
they've held a lead in only seven of them (and if you blinked, you
surely missed the five-minute span in which they held the upper
hand over San Jose and Dallas last month before losing both).
</P>
<P>
   They've been outscored 11-1 in the first period of their past 10
games. Their most exciting offensive player is their radio color
analyst Cammie Granato, a standout on the women's national team.
Trust us, this is not how you go about wooing locked-out NBA fans
and would-be Staples Center season-ticket holders.
</P>
<P>
   You have to go all the way back to 1971, four years before
Taylor was taken by the Kings in the 15th round of the draft, to
find a more doddering squad of Angeleno icemen.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have gotten nicked and dented the first two months,
it's true. But it's not injuries that have dragged them all the way
down to the bottom of the NHL, it's Taylor's inertia.
</P>
<P>
   The time is long overdue for Taylor to pick up one of those
roadside emergency phones and, as the 1998-99 season noisily
whizzes by him in the background, dial for help. Goodness knows he
has plenty of options.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a marquee talent with the charisma to knock the smug
smile right off Shaquille O'Neal's face that Taylor wants, he
should dial the Pittsburgh Penguins and stubbornly hang on the line
until Craig Patrick is ready to deal and/or his phone is
disconnected because of a pile of unpaid bills.
</P>
<P>
   There's no better player in the league right now than Jaromir
Jagr and no financially worse-off team than the Penguins, who'll
have to decide pretty soon whether or not to hang onto Jagr for
collateral or deal him for cash and warm bodies.
</P>
<P>
   If Jagr's available, the Kings need him the same way the Dodgers
have to have Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   But seeing how time is of the absolute essence, we could
completely forgive Taylor if it's a fantastic finisher he wants and
he wants it now, no strings or bankruptcy courts attached. If
that's the case, he can ring up Calgary and complete a deal for
Theoren Fleury on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Of all his options, this is the one we'd endorse and not just
because it would be a marketer's delight, selling a team with both
the tallest player presently in the league (6-foot-8 Steve McKenna)
and the shortest. Yes, that would be the 5-foot-6 Fleury, who makes
up for in speed and grit what he lacks in height.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be an unrestricted free agent at the season's end, which
is why the Flames are resigned to moving him. A relatively youthful
30, Fleury figures to have plenty of mileage left in those
tree-trunk legs of his.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Taylor's options get riskier (not one of them,
however, is as treacherous as doing nothing). If it's an exciting
scorer with a lot of baggage that he wants, he can buzz Vancouver
and battle it out with the New York Rangers for the services of
Pavel Bure. The Russian Rocket has been grounded all season after
having a falling out with the Vancouver front office.
</P>
<P>
   Bure is the most exciting player this side of Paul Kariya. But
as fast as he is he can't outskate the worrisome rumors that he has
ties to the Russian Mafia. His memory is also a concern; he has a
penchant for forgetting there are two or three or four teammates
skating with him on any given shift.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a proven scorer with excellent hands and a quick first
step that he wants, Taylor can call the Islanders about Zigmund
Palffy. The 5-foot-10 left winger averaged 45 goals in his first
three full seasons with the Islanders. He is sitting out what would
have been his fourth because of a contract dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor could swap his unsignable for Mike Milbury's. Idle Kings
defenseman Aki Berg surely could help shore up an Islanders defense
that gave up 12 more goals than the team scored in its first 26
games.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a puck (and chick) magnet that he wants, Taylor can ring
Ottawa about Radek Bonk. The 22-year-old center has good size
(6-foot-3) but so far inexplicably small numbers (90 points in 258
NHL games, including 10 in 22 this year).
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, if it's a smooth-striding, soft-handed scorer with
stars in his eyes that he wants, Taylor can dial Philadelphia for
Alexander Daigle. Daigle has a world of talent but is thinking of
throwing it all away for an acting career. In L.A. he could
straddle both worlds, a la Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   So you see, searching for a goal scorer right now is not like
shopping for a Furby. They're out there for the taking. If we were
Taylor, we'd bull our way to the front of the line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
