<HEADER>
A9807 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PRESIDENTS-CUP-HN     12-09 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PRESIDENTS-CUP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MELBOURNE, Australia _ Jack Nicklaus has been there once as the
guinea pig, the sacrificial lamb, the guy who took one for the good
of golf _ if not for the good of his team.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Nicklaus who led the U.S. charge at the 1987 Ryder Cup.
The event was in his hometown, no less, with the matches at
Muirfield Village, which Nicklaus designed just outside of
Columbus, Ohio. The team he captained would go on that year to be
the first to lose the Ryder Cup on American soil.
</P>
<P>
   It was a humbling moment _ certainly not on Nicklaus' personal
highlight reel, although he now says it may have been the best
thing that ever happened to the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, while he would prefer not to repeat the process,
Nicklaus says he would willingly do so this week if it's for the
betterment of the game of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be misled. Nicklaus and his U.S. squad are focused on
winning the Presidents Cup, the Ryder clone that features Americans
against an international team of non-Europeans. When the first shot
is fired Friday at Royal Melbourne Golf Club, things will be
intense.
</P>
<P>
   But Nicklaus is making it his mission to ensure that the
Presidents Cup is not a conflict of global proportions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's much of a war,'' he says. ``We would like
to win, sure. But the most important thing is that the game of golf
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like it won in '87. It was Nicklaus' second tour as captain
of the U.S. Ryder Cup team. In '83, his team had won at Palm Beach
Gardens, Fla. That was the last in a run of 13 consecutive Ryder
wins for America.
</P>
<P>
   Europe won the Cup in '85 in England, and when the Americans
couldn't regain it in '87, it galvanized the Ryder Cup as an elite
sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '87, it was the first time that the Ryder Cup made money
and all of the sudden became an absolute viable financial event,''
Nicklaus says. ``It had always been a loser before that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Presidents Cup came on because it (that Ryder Cup) opened
the doors for that type of event to happen. And so even though I
was the losing captain at Muirfield Village, that was not the
important issue. The important thing was that the game of golf grew
tremendously in Europe because of the win by that European team on
American soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I didn't like being the losing captain, of course. It was
an experience that I didn't enjoy. But I think what that did for
the Ryder Cup was something very special.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that happened with it (losing) were only good for
the game of golf, and I think that's far more important than
whether I was the losing captain or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``And no matter what happens here this week, the game of golf in
general and golf in Australia in particular are going to be the big
winners.''
</P>
<P>
   His dignity will be intact regardless. Nicklaus will go down in
history as one of golf's greatest players, a superb golf-course
designer and an ambassador of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But if he had his druthers, he would just as soon not be
remembered as the man who captained the U.S. to its first Ryder Cup
loss on home turf and its first Presidents Cup loss. The Americans
won the first two in '94 and '96 on a course in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   From Nicklaus' perspective, this Presidents Cup actually throws
as much pressure on international captain Peter Thomson as it does
on Nicklaus and the U.S. squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his hometown,'' Nicklaus says. ``Peter has to avoid
that this year. Muirfield was my hometown.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus also is of the opinion that his job as captain is far
less important than some people would believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have 12 highly successful, qualified players,'' he says.
``My job is to match them up, keep everybody from fighting, keep
everybody happy and make sure they have plenty of tees, towels,
spikes, things like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, what does a captain do? A captain stands up for his
team and makes speeches on their behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he does a little more than that. In fact, pairing up his
team members and giving them the best chances for success are
factors that a captain can control to some extent.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Nicklaus has one rule of thumb he will follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably won't pair unlike games together,'' he says.
``Unlike games come together sometimes. But oftentimes, they go
very far apart.''
</P>
<P>
   He's drawing on personal history for this rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember playing a lot of foursome, or alternate-shot,
matches with Arnold Palmer or Tom Watson or Tom Weiskopf,''
Nicklaus recalls. ``Most of the time, we won. Not all the time but
most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then one time in St. Louis (at the 1971 Ryder Cup), I was
paired with Dave Stockton. He would hit it short and in the
fairway, and I would hit it long and in the rough. He wasn't used
to hitting 8-irons out of the rough for his second shots, and I
wasn't used to hitting 2-irons from the fairway. We got beat
something like 6-and-5. So that kind of stuck in my head, and I
thought, `Jack, don't do that again.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I was talking with Tiger (Woods) on the team bus when he
came out with Mark O'Meara, and I said, `You and Mark had a little
hard time over at the Ryder Cup.' He said, `Yep, we felt like oil
and water. We didn't mix very well.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So probably the only thing you might find is that they won't
play together.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus emphasized the word ``probably'' in that statement. He
also hopes that his players, all of whom are winding down into a
short ``offseason'' after a full 10 months of play on the PGA Tour,
will be in quality form for the matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who plays well that day is what it boils down to,'' he says.
``Obviously, I haven't been calling my guys every day to see
whether they have been practicing or not. So I can only assume that
they are ready. And there isn't anybody who has told me they
aren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our guys really enjoy not being at each other's
throats once in a while. They enjoy their competitions against each
other during the year, but it is fun to be able to take guys back
and feel like it's your college days again. It's fun. It becomes a
team sport, which is something that you don't find that often in
golf.''
</P>
</TEXT>
