<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL COMMISSIONER ANSWERS TO PERRY MASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL)The Tribunal of American Sports Justice is now in
session.
</P>
<P>
   Hon. Perry Mason, chief of tribune, presiding.
</P>
<P>
   Case No. 666: Sports Fans vs. NFL. (END ITAL)
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Is it true, Commissioner Tagliabue, that one of your
executives told the coach of the Seattle Seahawks that the reason
for the mistaken call on the final touchdown of Sunday's game at
the Meadowlands between the Seahawks and New York Jets is that the
line judge mistook the helmet of Vinny Testaverde for the football?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: I, uh, believe that is correct.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Is it true that the helmet in question is white and the
football in question is brown?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Is it true that the football does not have a face mask
and the helmet does not have two pointed ends?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: Of course.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Are you familiar with the Laws of Holes, Mr. Tagliabue?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: I'm not sure what you mean.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Let me recite to you the First Law of Holes: When in one,
stop digging.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: I don't understand.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: I'm not surprised. In your position as commissioner of
the NFL, let me ask your professional opinion on which was more
outrageous: The commission of the miscall, or the preposterous
excuse for the miscall.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: Well, I think it's a matter of interpretation. You
can look at it like ...
</P>
<P>
   Mason: No equivocation, Mr. Tagliabue. You make the call on the
spot, just like your officials.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: Well I suppose if I had to choose ...
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Too late, Mr. Tagliabue. The tribunal finds you in
contempt of this proceeding. The sentence is a ban on the NFL
seeking public funding for any of the next three stadium projects
in its cities.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: Now wait a minute. That strikes at the very economic
foundation of our league _ public subsidy for private business.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: It is clear to this tribunal that the NFL's tolerance of
sudden, irreversible and unjustifiable officiating judgment has
economic as well as emotional impacts on sports fans and their
teams. Therefore the consequence to the league should also be
economic.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: Who makes up this procedure?
</P>
<P>
   Mason: That's for us to know and you to find out. Think of our
operations in the same way your business handles accountability by
its game officials.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: Wait a minute. All that happened Sunday was one blown
call. I will grant you it was a bad one, as was the excuse, and it
had serious consequences for the Seahawks. But every sport has
officiating mistakes. Errors by players, coaches and referees are
an inevitable part of all sports.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Isn't it true, sir, that the NFL plays far fewer games
than any other major professional sport?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: Yes, it is.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Isn't it also true that although most games last more
than three hours, the actual time the ball is in play is less than
30 minutes?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: That's true.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: So doesn't that put a higher premium on every call than
in any other sport?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: I suppose so.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Isn't it also true that the game is played on a large
field, with 22 players, that includes action that can spread
farther faster than any other sport?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: Well, I hadn't thought about it that way, but I
suppose it's true.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: And isn't it true that the NFL adopted a large
technological advance called instant replay from 1986 to 1991 as a
visual aid to help in the accuracy of some officiating calls?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: It is.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Were some calls reversed, and accuracy increased?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: Well, yes. But a lot of calls were upheld, too. And
many of the games were held up. The system forced a lot of time
delays. We concluded that the scarcity of errors didn't justify the
complications or the expense.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Nevertheless, given your testimony, isn't it possible to
conclude that NFL officials have more pressure than any other
sport?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: I suppose you could say that.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: And are they the only part-time officials in major
sports?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: So doesn't it stand to reason that any technical aid
given to these part-time employees in order to help them render a
fair judgment in a fast, complex game not only enhances your
organization's credibility but is in the public interest?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: We certainly plan to give it every consideration,
perhaps as soon as this season's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Now you're considering it? Mr. Tagliabue, where have you
been for seven years?
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: I resent the tone of your inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: The tribune recognizes your remark as criticism, which is
not tolerated in a public forum. You are fined another three
projects' worth of public subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue: This is so unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Welcome to your world, Mr. Tagliabue. Next case, bailiff.
</P>
<P>
   Bailiff: Sports fans vs. NBA, your honor.
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Are these people capable of telling the difference
between a football and a helmet?
</P>
<P>
   Bailiff: Testimony is inconclusive so far, your honor. What is
known so far is they cannot distinguish between a hole in the
ground and their ...
</P>
<P>
   Mason: Proceed, bailiff.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
