r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TCU-TEXAS-TECH-TE     12-09 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-TEXAS-TECH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU PASSES TECH TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU coach Billy Tubbs gave his players a pop
quiz before last night's game against Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   He asked the usual stuff, numbers of Tech's players, the
defensive assignments.
</P>
<P>
   His players failed, prompting a fiery pregame lecture from
Tubbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't pass the pop quiz,'' said point guard Prince Fowler,
his measly quiz score of 35 leading his Horned Frogs teammates.
``But when we stepped on the floor, we passed the test.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU easily defeated Tech, 105-86, shooting 66 percent, including
71 percent in the second half, and forcing 24 turnovers along the
way.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs (8-2) didn't miss a shot until Lee Nailon's dunk 6:51
into the first half rattled off the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave them a makeup quiz tonight,'' Tubbs said. ``Extra
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs said he had been worried coming in against Tech (4-3) that
his team wasn't ready. They didn't seem fired up to play, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs were clicking from the get-go in front of season-high
crowd of 6,581 at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum and a regional television
audience on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight we got beat by a better team,'' Red Raiders coach
James Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   The inside duo of Nailon and Marquise Gainous was again dominant
for the Frogs. Nailon had 26 points and 10 rebounds, and Gainous
chipped in 24 and six. They took turns dumping it inside to the
other for thunderous dunks.
</P>
<P>
   The perimeter game also played well, delivering a second
consecutive solid effort.
</P>
<P>
   The outside scoring came from Shannon Long and Vladimir Jaksic.
Long had a career-high 19 points, and Jaksic chipped in 14 points,
including going 4-for-7 on 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Malcolm \RJohnson\S and Mike \RJones\S. They were
great players,'' Jaksic said of the guards TCU lost after last
season. ``But it's time to move on. We can be good players too.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead, as usual, came from Fowler.
</P>
<P>
   The fiery guard with the in-your-face-for-40-minutes-game
attitude keys the Frogs' defense. The job he did on Tech's Rayford
Young had Tubbs raving.
</P>
<P>
   Young couldn't get free, and as a result the Red Raiders'
offense couldn't get on track. The Red Raiders shot 44 percent, and
turned over the ball 24 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned the ball over too many times,'' Dickey said. ``In a
game like this, you can't turn the ball over.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler was right in the middle of most of it.
</P>
<P>
   His line wasn't as impressive as some, save for a school-record
15 assists. He finished with 11 points and three steals.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no doubt that nights like last night start with him,
his defense, his intensity.
</P>
<P>
   To look at him, though, it's hard to see it. He's as laid-back
as they come most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   So Fowler's the perfect guy to explain the seeming disparity
between the team that acted nonchalant before the game and the team
that dismantled Texas Tech with relative ease during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready,'' Fowler said. ``We passed the real test.''
</P>
<P>
   So what was hard about the pop quiz?
</P>
<P>
   ``Remembering the players' numbers,'' Fowler said. ``You see
them on TV all of the time, but you don't remember their numbers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
