<SLUG> BC-HELLS-ANGEL-BODIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELLS ANGEL, GIRLFRIEND FOUND SHOT TO DEATH AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- ``Large Larry'' Lajeunesse, a 468-pound Hells
Angel, and his longtime girlfriend, Tami Ann Brannigan, were shot
to death in the converted industrial garage where they lived,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police suspect robbers killed Lajeunesse, 44, and Brannigan, 35.
</P>
<P>
   So do family members who walked through the couple's ransacked
home and scrap-metal and car-repair business in suburban Chatsworth
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lajeunesse, who called his 6-foot-5-inch brother a ``big
teddy bear,'' said he noticed that gems, antique watches, knives
and swords the couple collected appeared to be missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought the little trinkets were more important than my
brother and Tami's lives,'' said Michael Lajeunesse, who was
present when the bodies were taken away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've got an ice pick in my heart,'' he said. ``I
hoped it was somebody else and not my brother, but when I saw the
size of that bag on that gurney, I knew it was him.''
</P>
<P>
   Two fellow Hells Angels from the chapter in nearby San Fernando
who had not heard from Lajeunesse for several days stopped by his
home Monday and found him dead on his bed in a back room, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   They called police, who found Brannigan in the adjoining
industrial unit the couple also rented, said Officer Dwayne White
of the Los Angeles Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD Robbery/Homicide Division detectives were at the industrial
park through the night, but would not comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   After police left Tuesday, family members walked through the
collectible-filled garage. The family was together two weeks ago in
Simi Valley for their first reunion in about 15 years, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Lajeunesse's shiny, maroon Harley-Davidson motorcycle remained
in one room alongside a glass showcase of miniature model cars. In
another room, his Hells Angels jacket hung on a cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lajeunesse said his brother had a Hells Angels tattoo on
his back and was wearing his new 10-year Hells Angels belt buckle
when they last saw each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was proud about being a Hells Angel,'' Michael Lajeunesse
said. ``I play the bad guy in the movies, but he's living it. But
he was a big teddy bear.''
</P>
<P>
   He described his brother's girlfriend as a quiet, friendly
person who was into computers, sewing on her 1900 antique machine
and tending to her cats.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was skinny. He was heavy. I guess they loved each other,''
Michael Lajeunesse said of the couple, who were together at least
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   As he sifted through rooms, some packed to the ceiling with
tires, auto parts, antiques, law books and collectibles, Michael
Lajeunesse, older than his slain brother by 18 months, recalled
growing up with three brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Working on cars was a natural for Larry, he said. ``He could
pick up a transmission by himself that weighed 300 pounds and throw
it on the truck. Changing a motor to him is like changing socks.''
</P>
<P>
   As she walked through her son's home Tuesday, Agnes Vooris held
a clay hand print Larry Lajeunesse made when he was 6. On the back
it read, ``Mother's Day 1960, Larry.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and neighbors in the industrial complex described
Lajeunesse and Brannigan as quiet and always willing to lend a
hand. Larry would offer spare auto parts to his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disturbing,'' said Larry Bjork, who works at a business
next door. ``He was a real good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
