<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURED BLAKE SAYS HE'S READY TO RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The most important 20 minutes of the Kings'
failing season might have occurred Tuesday, an off day, when
defenseman Rob Blake skated on the Forum ice and stated confidently
he expects to return to the lineup after missing just one more
game.
</P>
<P>
   For a team with 11 losses in 12 games entering tonight's home
game against the Washington Capitals, the Kings (6-17-3) will take
good news wherever they can find it. And the best possible news
would be the return of Blake, the NHL's top defenseman last season,
who tonight will miss his 15th game because of the broken foot he
suffered more than five weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to stay out there and play (tonight),'' Blake said
after his skate. ``I'll play Saturday (at home against Vancouver).
It's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are 2-12 in Blake's absence and their playoff hopes
are in jeopardy at a relatively early stage in the season, but he
said the team's woes are not hastening his return to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come back when you're ready,'' he said. ``I've had enough
injuries to know you don't rush back.''
</P>
<P>
   Winger Steve McKenna is cleared to return tonight after missing
a month with an abdominal strain, which means that when Blake
returns, the only injured Kings will be wingers Russ Courtnall
(broken ankle) and Sandy Moger (back strain).
</P>
<P>
   __ Winning time: Blake said he is aware that even with 56 games
remaining, the Kings find themselves in danger of missing the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 11 games under .500,'' he said. ``If we play .500 hockey
from here on out, it's not good enough. Right now, between now and
Christmas, it's a pretty important time to get something going.
We've got to get on a roll and get back to .500.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have eight games between now and Christmas, just two
against teams with winning records.
</P>
<P>
   __ Stumpel improving: Center Jozef Stumpel had two assists in
Saturday's loss to Detroit and has shown signs the last couple of
games that his injury problems might be behind him and that he
might be regaining his form of last season, when he led the Kings
with 79 points.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel set up a 2-on-0 break with a beautiful behind-the-back
pass from the blue line on Saturday, a play that resulted in a goal
by Luc Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last game against Detroit, I was feeling almost in
shape,'' said Stumpel, who has been slowed by ankle and hip-flexor
injuries, missing 13 games. ``After 15 or 20 seconds, I was dead
and I couldn't move my feet (when first returning from his
injuries). Now, I don't have that problem. I'm staying 30 or 40
seconds out there and I'm working hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
