<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWA-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWA IS SET TO ORDER JETS FROM BOEING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Trans World Airlines is expected to announce an order
for at least 50 Boeing 717 jetliners on Wednesday to help replace
its aging fleet, people close to the transaction said on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The order, worth about $1.5 billion, would insure the future of
the 717, a short-range plane developed by McDonnell Douglas before
Boeing bought the one-time rival last year.
</P>
<P>
   Orders for the 717 have been lacking since the first customer,
Airtran, formerly known as Valujet, ordered 50 three years ago.
Pembroke Capital, an Irish leasing concern, ordered 10 717's
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and TWA declined to comment on the TWA order, but a
person close to the deal said TWA would announce it Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms, TWA is expected to order 50 of the planes and
take options for 50 more, giving the order a potential value of $3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The order would be the first large-scale purchase of Boeing
aircraft since it announced an extensive cutback last week because
of slowing demand, mostly from Asian customers. Boeing said it was
reducing production and cutting 48,000 jobs in the next two years,
20,000 more than it had announced some months ago.
</P>
<P>
   TWA is expected to use the 717's as replacements for its aging
DC-9's, which were built by McDonnell Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   TWA is also expected to buy an undisclosed number of Airbus
A318's, which are short-range aircraft that Boeing's European rival
is developing to compete with the 717. The Seattle Times, citing
unnamed sources, reported on Tuesday that TWA is planning to buy 75
A318's with an option for another 75, a deal potentially valued at
$5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear why TWA would split the order between two
competing models, however. Many airlines choose to avoid that as a
way to simplify maintenance procedures and reduce costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 0057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9846 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     12-09 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MickeyHerskowitz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INSTANT replay.
</P>
<P>
   To re, or not to re, that is the question. Whether 'tis nobler
in the mind to suffer the slings and arrows of outrageous fortune
or to get it right, even at the cost of adding four or five minutes
to the length of a game.
</P>
<P>
   Gingerly, as if dealing with a live hand grenade, the lords of
pro football are wrestling with the issue of bringing back instant
replay, possibly in time for this year's playoffs. In the interest
of our national health, we pray that they do. Nearing the end of
the most contentious season of officiating in the recorded memory
of mankind, owners, coaches and fans have reached the point of
emotional meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   You remember the arguments offered when this technology was
ash-canned after a six-year run: The TV reviews took too long and
were too often ruled ``inconclusive.'' The camera angle was not
always reliable. The officials on the field were inhibited by the
eye in the sky. And these doubts were aggravated by a general
impression that everyone in the replay booth was out to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   These complaints no longer matter. What we are dealing with is a
crisis that is spreading like crabgrass. Games are being lost on
bad officials' calls in full view of the millions watching at home.
If they can see the replays, why shouldn't the officials?
</P>
<P>
   It is our belief that, hardened by bitter lessons, the fans _
even the coaches _ are now mature enough to live with the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it matter which format or system is adopted. Give those
in the stadium, including the men in stripes, the same opportunity
as the television viewers. This must be done before a call occurs
that inflames the crowd, causing the fans to take matters into
their own hands. The stadium would be destroyed by those who built
it, like the Bridge on the River Kwai, only without the stirring
music.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly a game has failed to produce a wail of anguish, and at
least four in four weeks have been decided by blown decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers lost in overtime when the referee blew the coin
toss, giving the Detroit Lions the crucial first possession. This
is believed to be a first in pro football history. Coin tosses are
like elevators. You have only two ways to go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Bills were knocked off by New England after time had
expired, the result of an interference call on the game's last
play, a foul that was not apparent on the replay, or anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Jets squeaked past Seattle when quarterback Vinny
Testaverde was credited with a touchdown, a foot short of the goal
line. The ball was under cousin Vinny's chest, but the officials
may have ruled that the top of his helmet broke the plane.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dallas Cowboys held on to beat the Arizona Cardinals
when the officials failed to call interference on Kevin Smith on
the final play. Smith held the receiver tightly in his embrace, a
touching moment but a costly one for the Cards.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the officials are darned if they do and darned if they
don't. But if the television cameras would help them correct one
wrong call, why shouldn't they have that option?
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much point in raising your blood pressure by
reciting other atrocities. The Oilers, the Tennessee Oilers,
received two letters of apology from the NFL office, regretting
calls that may have cost them two games.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nostalgia fans will no doubt remember that the Oilers
were the team most responsible for this innovation. When the Oilers
still lived in Houston, they had a touchdown taken away from them
during the 1979 AFC Championship Game. The call kept them from
tying the Steelers and gaining momentum in what turned out to be
their best chance to reach the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The officials ruled that Mike Renfro had caught Dan Pastorini's
pass out of the end zone, but the replays showed clearly that his
feet were in bounds. What they did not show was whether he had
control of the ball. Eyewitnesses, including Renfro, insisted that
he did.
</P>
<P>
   This play, and the controversy it unleashed, inspired two
changes. NBC realized it was lacking a reverse-angle camera, and it
quickly became a part of the game-day hardware. To this day, the
camera is referred to as The Renfro.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, with the improvements in camera placement and slow
motion, the league voted to employ instant replay. They pulled the
plug in 1992, having decided that while the theory was fine, the
system itself did little more than whip to a greater frenzy those
who were already paranoid.
</P>
<P>
   But there is now a larger concern _ namely, the perception that
too many games are decided not by the skill and bloody effort of
those in the arena but through acts of robbery perpetrated by
people in striped shirts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
