<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BURTON-TEXAS-MOTOR-SPEEDWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURTON GIVES ENDORSEMENT TO IMPROVEMENTS AT TMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Jeff Burton says the reconfigured and
repaved Texas Motor Speedway really is different and better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty damn nice,'' said Burton, winner of the inaugural
500-mile NASCAR Winston Cup race at TMS in April 1997. ``This is a
racetrack that's been improved. There'll still be people who say
they don't like it, but nobody who will say it's not better.''
</P>
<P>
   But Burton also warned that the 1.5-mile trioval automatically
will not shed its reputation as a ``one-groove racetrack'' and
produce side-by-side racing during the Primestar 500 on March 28.
</P>
<P>
   Testing tires on behalf of Goodyear, Burton became the first Cup
regular to hot-lap around TMS since it underwent a massive
reconfiguration and repaving after the water-plagued Texas 500 in
early April. The reconfiguration included installation of a new
drainage system and elimination of the 8-degree ``dual-banking''
originally intended for open-wheel, Indy-style cars. The changes
added eight feet of racing surface to the layout, which now
measures 58 feet at its widest point through the 24-degree banked
turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that mean we're going to race side-by-side?'' said
Burton, driver of the No. 99 Exide Batteries Ford Taurus. ``I don't
think we're going to race side-by-side. But I've said all along
that a lot of the side-by-side racing question has been blown way
out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the bottom is the fastest groove, by a lot more than the
top, then you can't run the top and be competitive. That's the way
this racetrack is right now. What we've seen over the years is that
as racetracks get older, and the pavement gets worn out, the groove
always seems to get bigger. Seems to get wider. I think that will
happen over here in \Rturns\S 3 and 4.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the new drainage system, the management of
Speedway Motorsports Inc., opted to redesign the steep transition
entering Turn 1 and the tight and narrow exit of Turn 4.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-day reconstruction project cost developer Bruton Smith
approximately $3 million. Four events, including a NASCAR Craftsman
Truck Series race, have been run at TMS since without complaint.
But Eddie Gossage, the track's executive vice president and general
manager, eagerly has been awaiting the first laps run by a Cup
regular since April 5.
</P>
<P>
   Burton rang up 65 laps yesterday morning before delivering his
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe there's been huge improvements made to the
racetrack,'' said Burton, who won two races and finished fifth in
Cup points in 1998. ``Turn 4 has much more of a wider groove. So
now when you approach Turn 3 and get in the gas, if you miss the
groove off Turn 4, you don't feel like you're going to wreck. The
momentum now takes you to the wall, where before it tried to drive
you into the wall. That's a definite improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Turn 1 is better. It was almost like you'd run down in
a hole, and you never knew where your car was going. Now you can
drive down in there as deep as you want to and if anything happens,
the car just gets a little bit tight. That's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said Burton's favorable comments were ``just another
step'' in management's effort to remove all doubts about the racing
surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone has wanted to see what the changes made to
the racetrack meant to a Winston Cup car,'' Gossage said. ``It's
very pleasing to hear that he feels good about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we've experienced, what the drivers say is what counts. I
don't know that it's our place to tell you it's fixed or not fixed
or it's perfect. That's up to the drivers. We'll leave it to them
to talk about the racetrack.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
