<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS AND FLYERS TIE, 5-5 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils and the Flyers want to
establish some kind of superiority against each other during the
regular season, but they are dead even right now, or at least until
they meet again in two nights.
</P>
<P>
   After splitting the first two games of their season series, each
winning at home, the Devils and the Flyers fought to a 5-5 deadlock
on TUesday night at Continental Arena in a game in which both
squandered two-goal leads _ the Flyers at the start and the Devils
at the end, a development that displeased New Jersey Coach Robbie
Ftorek.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to control those two-goal leads,'' Ftorek said.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils (15-7-3) took a 5-3 lead with 7 minutes 56 seconds
left in the third period when Brian Rolston scored against Ron
Hextall, who replaced John Vanbiesbrouck at the start of the third
period. Vanbiesbrouck had allowed goals to Bobby Holik, Jason
Arnott, Dave Andreychuk and Patrik Elias.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, who defeated the Islanders by 7-5 on Saturday, have
allowed 10 goals in their last two games, and they know they cannot
keep up their own production.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get carried away and try to score too many goals
every game,'' Andreychuk said. ``We can't force to get offensive
chances. We have to be patient, because we create turnovers. There
were too many turnovers, and that was the difference in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing for the first time this season without their captain,
Scott Stevens, who was nursing flu-like symptoms, the Devils turned
the puck over consistently in the neutral zone.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Lindros had two goals for the Flyers (12-8-5). Jody Hull,
Dainius Zubrus and Rod Brind'Amour had the other goals for
Philadelphia, which will play host to the Devils on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Brind'Amour got credit for the game's last goal, with 3:45 left
in regulation, on a play in which the puck hit Martin Brodeur's
stick, went in the air and ended up in the net. ``It hit my stick
and I never saw it after that,'' said Brodeur, who faced 20 shots,
one in the overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros and Hull scored goals 55 seconds apart, starting at
11:11 of the opening period, to give the Flyers a two-goal lead.
The goal by Lindros was his 13th and came on the first manpower
advantage for the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   Goals by Holik and Arnott tied it for the Devils. Holik's goal,
his seventh of the season, came with 3:24 left in the first period,
and Arnott scored his seventh just 2:01 into the second period on
the power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had a chance to take the lead about six minutes later
during a 2-on-1 break, but Krzyszstof Oliwa fell with no one around
him, and the Devils found themselves behind in the same sequence.
Zubrus went down the right flank after a lead pass by Mike
Sillinger and beat Brodeur from the right circle to the far post.
</P>
<P>
   Zubrus' goal seemed to awaken the Devils, who took the lead for
the first time on goals by Andreychuk, at 13:33 of the second, and
by Elias, with 3:18 left in the period. But the Devils squandered
their lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
