<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-AVALANCHE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVALANCHE DEFEAT ISLANDERS, 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Patrick Roy, the superstitious Colorado
Avalanche goalie, has been known to talk to his goal posts. Surely
several ``thank yous'' were among his comments to them on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Four times in their 2-1 loss to the Avalanche on Tuesday night,
an Islander was staring at an open net but managed only to clank
the puck off of the three-inch-wide red cylinder. The defeat,
before 9,450 at Nassau Coliseum, continued the Islanders' slide,
which reached six straight losses.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Linden, Mariusz Czerkawski, who did score once, Robert
Reichel and Bryan Smolinski all came within inches of scoring
tonight for the Islanders. Roy, who was outstanding, stopped 31
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Lady Luck was not with us,'' said Mike Milbury, the
Islanders' coach and general manager. ``We carried the play and did
what we were supposed to. But we were guilty of one mistake, and
they made us pay for it. When you're not winning, somehow you find
a way to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The mistake Milbury referred to was more of a miscommunication
between the Islanders' goalie, Tommy Salo, and defenseman Rich
Pilon. Early in the third period, Pilon misplayed the puck, which
bounced over his stick and into the Islanders' zone. Salo saw the
blunder and skated 25 feet from his crease to play the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Forsberg, the speedy Avalanche center, picked up the puck
at the blue line and steered it around Salo for a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to go out there,'' said Salo, who made 20 saves.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders' league-leading power play went 0 for 5 on Tuesday
night. Entering the game, it was successful 23.4 percent of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Since opening the season with four straight losses and a tie,
Colorado (12-11-2) has climbed into contention and has now won
eight of its last 11 games. The Avalanche has also won its last
eight against the Islanders, outscoring them by 37-18.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the Islanders (10-17) can look forward to
Saturday's game against the Tampa Bay Lightning for a couple of
reasons. They have not lost to the Lightning in six games and Kenny
Jonsson, their best defenseman, is expected to return after missing
eight of the last nine games with a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   That the Islanders' slide has occurred with Jonsson out is no
coincidence. Jonsson holds the point on the power play, kills
penalties, and routinely sees more ice time than any of his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche took a 1-0 first-period lead when Cam Russell
slapped the puck past a screened Salo from the point for his first
goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders tied the game at 1-1 on a goal by Czerkawski at 14
minutes 21 seconds of the second period. He redirected a Smolinski
slap shot over Roy's shoulder for his seventh goal of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
