<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9866 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-LOMBARDIAWARD-HNS     12-09 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOMBARDIAWARD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
The rest of the holiday season might be a little anticlimactic for
Texas A&AMP;M's Dat Nguyen.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He and the Aggies already had made merry on Saturday by
upsetting then-No. 2 Kansas State for the Big 12 championship.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday night, Nguyen got a nice little stocking stuffer
when he walked off with the 1998 Lombardi Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``This past week what more can you ask for?'' asked A&AMP;M's senior
linebacker and career tackles leader. ``You win a big game, and
then you come in here and win an award like this. I'm just honored
to be the recipient of the 1998 Lombardi Award.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen beat out three others to take home the 40-pound
granite-and-silver trophy given each year by the Houston Rotary
Club to the player deemed the best lineman in college football.
</P>
<P>
   Finalists Aaron Gibson, the 6-7, 386-pound senior offensive
tackle from Wisconsin, and Andy Katzenmoyer, the 6-6, 290-pound
junior linebacker from Ohio State, were also present at Tuesday's
29th annual award dinner and ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth finalist, senior offensive tackle Matt Stinchcomb of
Georgia, was unable to attend. He was in New York receiving an
$18,000 postgraduate scholarship from the College Football Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   As Nguyen rose from the head table in the Imperial Ballroom of
the Hyatt Regency to accept the award, he stood for much more than
being crowned the nation's best lineman. The son of Vietnamese
immigrants, the 6-1 Nguyen has over the last few years become a
towering role model for youngsters, using football as his vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that's different,'' Nguyen said. ``It's a
unique story, one of the most unique stories in college football.
It's one of those things that everybody wants to talk and write
about. It's neat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives a lot of kids out there dreams and aspirations to
play college football or any other sport they want to do. It's just
opened the doors for them. It lets them know that regardless of
what race you are, the door is wide-open for you if you put your
heart and soul into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen said he was caught by complete surprise when his name was
called Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I had that big of a chance,'' he said. ``At
first, I thought they were joking when the announcer opened the
envelope and said, `Gig 'em, Aggies.' He had told me he was going
to joke with me before he got on the podium. But I'm just real
honored to represent Texas A&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum, Nguyen's presenter, praised his player's
latest accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really fitting because Dat has been one of our
unselfish guys throughout his career,'' Slocum said. ``This is not
one of those cooked-up deals. Dat played himself into this deal. He
made himself into one of the best players in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Though several Aggies had been chosen as Lombardi finalists in
the past, Nguyen became the first to take home the hardware.
</P>
<P>
   He is also the only A&AMP;M player to lead the team in season
tackles four times. He has 517 career stops, and in the 36-33
double-overtime win over K-State, Nguyen set a Big 12 Championship
Game record with 17 tackles.
</P>
<P>
   In starting all 50 of his games for A&AMP;M, Nguyen has helped his
team win the last two Big 12 South titles. Now, the eighth-ranked
Aggies (11-2) are headed to the Sugar Bowl to face No. 3 Ohio State
(10-1) and Katzenmoyer on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great opportunity for us to go to a bowl game,''
said Nguyen. ``Everybody played well (at St. Louis). We fought to
the end and came out on top. So it's a great opportunity for the
seniors to play another game on the collegiate level and for us to
play another game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (Big 12 championship) win proves that we can play up
there with some of the top 10 teams in the nation. And now we're
being rewarded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
