</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX SIGN FREE AGENT PORTUGAL TO BOLSTER ROTATION 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, Jose Offerman has company.
</P>
<P>
   One day after bidding farewell to three pitchers who were in
their rotation at various times in 1998, the Red Sox Tuesday signed
free agent Mark Portugal, a 36-year-old righthander who won 10
games for Philadelphia last season but after three operations in
two years was deemed too much of a health risk for the Phillies to
ask back.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, who went to high school in Southern California but now
lives in Barrington, R.I., signed a one-year, $3 million deal, with
a club option for the 2000 season. His salary will be $2.7 million
for 1999 and would be $3.3 million the following season if the club
does not buy him out for $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   He is the second free agent acquisition by the Sox this
offseason, joining Offerman, the team's new leadoff man.
</P>
<P>
   While six teams, according to Toronto general manager Gord Ash,
remain in the running to trade for five-time Cy Young Award winner
Roger Clemens, Red Sox GM Dan Duquette took a far more modest step
in bolstering a rotation that will no longer feature Steve Avery,
Butch Henry, or Pete Schourek. The Sox declined to offer the three
salary arbitration, which prohibits Boston from re-signing them
until May 1, essentially guaranteeing that they'll be elsewhere
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, who figures to assume the No. 4 spot in the rotation,
has actually won one fewer game (29) in the last four seasons than
Avery and six fewer than Schourek.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies, who decided against trading Portugal last season
when they thought, briefly, that they could stay in contention for
the National League wild card, held a $2.75 million club option on
him but declined to exercise it.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal was on the disabled list three times in his two seasons
with the Phillies. He missed almost all of 1997 after he tore the
flexor group of muscles in his right elbow and needed surgery. He
also had surgery on his left knee. In all, he has been on the DL 10
times in a big league career that began in 1985 with the Twins and
has included stops with the Astros, Giants, Reds, and Phillies. He
had two earlier operations, one to remove bone chips in his elbow
in 1992 and one to repair a torn anterior cruciate ligament in his
right knee in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But after undergoing arthroscopy on his right knee following his
first start last season, Portugal bounced back, going 10-5 with a
4.44 ERA in 26 starts. A changeup specialist, he was sought by a
number of teams before the July 31 trading deadline, but Phillies
GM Ed Wade elected to retain him.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, who came back five weeks after the knee surgery and
shut out the Dodgers on two hits over eight innings, went 7-3 with
a 3.69 ERA after the All-Star break. He pitched at least seven
innings in eight of his last 16 starts, including two complete
games.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's best season was 1993, when he went 18-4 for the
Astros. That November, he signed as a free agent with San
Francisco, and in 1995, he was traded along with current Boston
center fielder Darren Lewis to the Reds in the deal that netted the
Giants Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had talked on and off with the Red Sox, but it just came
into focus the last couple of days,'' said Barry Meister,
Portugal's agent. ``They feel Portugal's a good fit, and he's happy
for the chance to pitch for the Red Sox and come home.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, who figures to take the spot in the rotation behind
Pedro Martinez, Bret Saberhagen, and Tim Wakefield, had offers from
two other clubs, according to Meister. He was signed as a free
agent by the Phillies following the '96 season by then-GM Lee
Thomas, now one of Duquette's aides.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dennis Eckersley, cut loose by the Red Sox Monday,
will decide by next week whether he intends to continue his playing
career, his attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley, 44, had said last month that he was leaning strongly
toward coming back, but only with the Red Sox and only if he felt
his right shoulder was healthy again; he spent seven weeks on the
disabled list last summer.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Eckersley met with Duquette in the Boston offices
of the player's attorney, Jack Sands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan was very forward, very straight up,'' Sands said. ``Dan
said the team was looking at people for Dennis's position that
could help the club for more than one year, so they were going to
explore other alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Dennis's age, what have you, he wasn't surprised, but he
was slightly disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley has expressed an interest in broadcasting and this
past fall did some work on ESPN during the World Series. If he
elects to retire, a strong possibility, he would probably have
interest in talking to the Sox about a broadcasting role but will
most likely have to wait until the team's TV rights situation is
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things facing Duquette this winter is the need to
replenish the bullpen. He's set at closer with Tom Gordon and has
two above-average setup men in Jim Corsi and Derek Lowe. But the
Sox have only one experienced lefty reliever, Ron Mahay, after Greg
Swindell signed as a free agent with Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball winter meetings begin Friday in Nashville, where
Duquette's top priority will be to find a slugger to compensate for
the loss of Mo Vaughn. But there were strong indications that the
market may be a tight one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
