<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-AUCTION-ART-1STLD     12-09 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-AUCTION-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUCTION IS PLANNED FOR HOME RUN BALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 3rd graf to correct fact that news conference did not take
place at Guernsey's auction house) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At age 46, John Grass is the head groundskeeper for
the Mehlville School District outside St. Louis. He earns $30,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   At 26, Philip Ozersky is a research scientist at the Washington
University School of Medicine in St. Louis. He, too, earns $30,000
a year.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Grass caught Mark McGwire's 63rd home run and
Ozersky caught the 70th and last of McGwire's record-breaking
season. For Grass, Ozersky and a few others who caught historic
home runs this season, the jackpot is five weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Tuesday, Guernsey's, a New York auction
house, announced an auction Jan. 12 at The Theater at Madison
Square Garden to sell seven baseballs from this year's home run
derby. The balls are the 63rd, 67th, 68th and 70th homers by
McGwire of the St. Louis Cardinals and the 61st, 64th and 66th by
Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs own the ball from Sosa's 61st home run and say they
will donate the auction proceeds to Sosa's foundation. The owners
of the other balls are represented or advised by Mike Barnes, a
28-year-old lawyer and agent from St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he expected the 70th home run ball to bring more
than $1 million and the others to bring more than $100,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   The highest price ever paid for a baseball was $110,000 at a New
York auction this year for the ball Babe Ruth hit for the first
home run in Yankee Stadium history. For the McGwire-Sosa balls,
Barnes said, ``The sky is the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have written offers of more than $1 million for No. 70,''
Barnes said. ``Most buyers are collectors or plan to donate the
balls to museums. It's a matter of ego. You're buying a piece of
American history, not a baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   To people who believe the huge potential prices are incongruous,
Sosa, who attended the news conference, took a different tack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad much of this money will go to charity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arlan Ettinger, Guernsey's president, said he expected half the
proceeds to be donated to charities. He said the owner of one ball
was a veterinary student who said he would use part of his money to
repay student loans.
</P>
<P>
   Grass, who owns McGwire's No. 63, said he didn't care how much
he made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to take care of my family,'' he said. ``I have a
son, two daughters, a grandchild, six brothers and two sisters.
That's a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky, who owns McGwire's No. 70, was looking more to the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I got the ball,'' he said, ``I was trying to live my
life out. This is a lot different from my life as a research
scientist. I will give some of this to charity, a significant sum,
I hope. I'm not married, but I'm trying to provide for my kids when
I have them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
