<HEADER>
A0152 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-ECONOMY10-COX     12-09 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ECONOMY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas outlook bright, says Reserve Bank economist
 &HT;    By Kim Tyson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas job growth has cooled considerably in the
last year, but the state's economic outlook is still good for next
year.
</P>
<P>
   That was the view of Sheila Dolmas, an assistant economist for
the Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas, who is on the team that keeps a
regular check on the state's economic pulse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Texas economy is still very healthy. Employment growth has
slowed, but we expect the (state's economic) expansion to continue
next year,'' said Dolmas.
</P>
<P>
   While Texas' job growth exceeded the U.S. average job growth
this decade, the rate of new job creation has ``slipped
considerably'' over the last year, Dolmas said.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the latest month for which numbers are available,
Texas' job growth rate was 2 percent. That's down from the 3
percent job growth rate in the previous 12 months, and 4.6 percent
for all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   The semiconductor industry struggled with an oversupply of chips
even before Asian economic problems cut into demand. The result was
layoffs at big Austin employers like Motorola Inc., Applied
Materials Inc. and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect this slowdown to be temporary, however, as the chip
industry sees inventories stabilize and sales start to recover and
the Texas economy continues to expand _ albeit at a slower rate,''
Dolmas said. Dolmas also attributed the slowdown in Texas this year
to a tight labor market, continued weakness in some sectors like
agriculture and energy, and the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with those problems, Texas exports are lagging. In the
first three quarters of 1998, overall Texas exports fell 10 percent
from the comparable period last year, with exports to Asian
countries dropping 30 percent, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a worldwide oil glut has sent oil prices down 40
percent from prices prior to the 1973 oil embargo. Low oil prices
also have hurt Mexico, a major oil producer and Texas' biggest
trading partner, which in turn has hurt its trade with Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, Dolmas said, is recent signs of improvement in
the U.S. economy _ which is the biggest determinant of how well
Texas will do next year.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market is back up from its October lows. Consumer
confidence also has improved. And interest rates _ which help drive
consumer spending and big economic engines like home buying _ also
remain low, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Tyson writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 0857EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
