<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 08:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0153 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELSO-COLUMN10-COX     12-09 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On a mission to cure the humorless
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I see GRUMP as a snitch group whose mission is
to turn in the chuckle-deprived.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is for their own good.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it will work. Members of Good Riddance to
Unrelentingly Morose People, or GRUMP, will keep a diligent eye out
for grumbly behavior in the community.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when they see it, they'll call me, GRUMP's CEO, and report
the laugh-challenged. Next, a GRUMP team will contact this person's
family and hold a GRUMP intervention session at the person's home
to help him overcome his humorless condition.
</P>
<P>
   The movement has begun, folks. There was so much response to my
column last week suggesting starting a political action group to
get rid of humorless people that I've decided to actually form
GRUMP.
</P>
<P>
   GRUMP membership cards are in the works. And maybe later there
will be GRUMP bumper stickers: ``GRUMP: This Vehicle Brakes for
Jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to help with Good Riddance to Unrelentingly
Morose People,'' wrote Will Cook, who works for a company that
sells computer software. ``Can one of our first assignments be my
boss's boss? I have attempted some humor with this man in the past
and received just a blank stare.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook was one of about 20 people who wrote in to join GRUMP.
Consider yourselves signed up, folks. You have been designated foot
soldiers in the war against angst.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's room for more troops. If you want to become
part of this army, just e-mail me at the address at the bottom of
this column. This could be the start of something big.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an example of the sort of problem that GRUMP needs to
fix.
</P>
<P>
   I recently said in a column that the reason I wanted to find a
Furby is that I would like teach it to swear like a parrot.
</P>
<P>
   A Furby is one of those hard-to-find computerized interactive
plush toys that starts out speaking its own language, called
Furbish, then picks up English.
</P>
<P>
   I figured you probably couldn't really teach one of these Furbys
to swear, but I said it anyway, figuring everyone would know I was
kidding. Hah. Silly me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that you haven't done proper research on the
subject of today's column,'' a Furby owner wrote. ``Furbies don't
actually learn words from you, and therefore can't learn to speak
profanities.''
</P>
<P>
   You've got to wonder how many hours this person spent on the
living room floor with Furby, trying to teach the Furby to talk
trash, with no success. I can see it now: ``Come on, Furby, say
$%&AMP;, say (at)$&AMP;.'' Otherwise, how would this person know Furbies
can't cuss?
</P>
<P>
   You wait. Now I'll get a letter from the writer telling me no
such thing happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had my share of humorless people giving me weird looks or
scathing remarks,'' wrote another person who has joined GRUMP.
``GRUMP is the ultimate solution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The more someone says 'You can't joke about that!' the harder
I try to come up with a joke about 'that,' `` wrote Chris Glenn.
``Here's an idea for a motto _ 'I won't stop joking if you won't
stop whining!'''
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
