<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A packrat on wheels
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Traveling has always brought me pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving home without all my stuff has always brought me anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   The only time in my life that I have traveled without suffering
packing remorse was when I was in the military. Then I was told
what to take. No more and no less.
</P>
<P>
   But in civilian life packing for trips involves choices. Way too
many choices for me.
</P>
<P>
   I leave on vacation trips with the car so heavily loaded that it
scrapes backing out of the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   On motorcycle trips I leave home with gear crammed, stacked and
strapped all over the bike. That's never enough, of course. I send
large boxes of more stuff to hotels along my planned route.
</P>
<P>
   Mailing ahead boxes of clean clothes, equipment and other
belongings overcomes difficult packing decisions. But it requires
work.
</P>
<P>
   I have to plan where I will stay and when I will arrive. Before
I make reservations, I make sure that someone at the hotel will
accept delivery of the box. I want to know who this will be. At the
very least, I want to know where the box will be stored.
</P>
<P>
   I've learned the hard way that boxes sent ahead need to be
entrusted to a service that requires someone to sign for the box
every time it changes hands. It's a terrible feeling to check into
a hotel and discover that you do not have 50 pounds of extra stuff
waiting for you.
</P>
<P>
   I include pre-addressed mailing labels in the boxes I send
ahead. I also include a fresh marker pen and plenty of packing
tape. That way I can send my dirty clothes and gear I no longer
need back home.
</P>
<P>
   By mailing boxes ahead, I can arrive at a hotel on a motorcycle
and in a few hours be dressed in a tuxedo ready to take in an
opera. I've never done that. But I like the idea that I could if
someday I develop a taste for opera and buy a tuxedo.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent trip to Europe, I was told that I had to keep my
luggage to two bags _ one to check through and the other small
enough to carry on the plane and fit under the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Sending boxes ahead to various European countries was far too
expensive. Friends predicted that I could never pack in only two
bags.
</P>
<P>
   I bought the largest rolling garment bag sold on this planet and
spent three months agonizing over what to put into those two bags.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote and rewrote packing lists, which, over the years, I have
collected into a fat stack. My early packing lists include ointment
for pimples. More recent packing lists remind me to bring my AARP
card for discounts.
</P>
<P>
   I keep my personal packing lists together in a drawer along with
articles on packing and two books that offer packing and travel
tips.
</P>
<P>
   Computers have made all this a lot easier. Before there were
home computers, I made packing lists on typewriters. Before that, I
used goose quills and ink made from lampblack and bear grease. No,
excuse me. That last part was an impeachable lie.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to pack for the European trip, I used a guest bedroom
as a staging area. I carried stuff I thought I might need to
bedroom. I studied travel catalogs and travel sites on the
Internet. I pored over my packing lists. I practice packed.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the night before my flight to Paris, I was packed in
only two bags. I figured the larger bag was heavy enough for the
two roller-blade wheels to crystallize marble, but what the heck.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the airline lost my huge checked-through garment bag.
In return, they gave me a tiny complimentary shaving kit. Somehow,
I survived.
</P>
<P>
   Now my brother wants me to join him and other family members in
San Francisco in February to attend his youngest daughter's
graduation ceremonies. I agreed. I am already working on my new
packing list.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas. E-mail: RNeth(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
