A0156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISCOUNT-COFFINS10-CO     12-09 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCOUNT-COFFINS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who knew death could be had at such a bargain price?
 &HT;    By Matt Reed
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It takes nerve to comparison shop for
your own coffin. You're not just browsing, after all. You're
confronting your own mortality.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's leaving this world alive,'' says Angelo Rolon.
</P>
<P>
   This could be his sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Rolon sells discount coffins to penny-pinchers planning for the
day they breathe their last, pass on to eternal glory, tee-off at
the great golf course in the sky. His showroom, the recently opened
Factory Caskets Direct on Dixie Highway in West Palm Beach,
features caskets with names that sound vaguely like American luxury
cars: the Winston, the Grant, the Primrose, the Dartmouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not morbid at all,'' Rolon says. ``Once they see they're
saving money, they feel good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so good, though, that anyone has been willing to try out a
coffin before deciding which to buy.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand why.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a casket, it's a snug fit. The sidewalls touch your
shoulders, so your hands must rest on top of you somewhere, hence
that ``he looks so peaceful'' pose. The satin upholstery, should
you choose the satin option, comes right down against your nose.
</P>
<P>
   It's dark in there. Cramped. And, yes, kind of eerie.
</P>
<P>
   There's no hiding from the truth at Rolon's store. On display at
the front door is The Lord's Supper, a metallic casket with a small
mural of the biblical feast inside the viewing lid. All together,
he has 12 caskets in stock, with stickers contrasting Rolon's
prices to those you might pay at a funeral home.
</P>
<P>
   At the pricey end, Rolon sells the Pieta: 18-gauge bronze-tinted
steel, elegant ruffled lining, a pillow, and subtle rubber gaskets
to seal the thing shut. You can almost hear a pitchman like Ricardo
Montalban purring about its ``rich Corinthian styling.'' Price:
$2,025 _ a $1,420 savings.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end,: the Abraham, a plain pine box that costs
$495. Its only distinguishing features are three holes drilled in
the bottom (Rolon wouldn't elaborate on what those do). You'd
probably pay $695 for the box at a funeral home, he says. One
customer took it home to use as a coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't carry the very, very expensive ones _ the Honduran
mahogany,'' Rolon says as you browse. ``But I can get one for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   At Factory Caskets Direct, you choose your coffin, and then
Rolon has it stored and delivered to the funeral home when you pass
away.
</P>
<P>
   You pay upfront. His chances of collecting on delivery are
understandably iffy.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Reed writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
