<HEADER>
A0157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FURBY10-COX     12-09 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURBY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Having a hot-selling toy is `good for the entire industry'
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ No, it didn't start with Cabbage Patch
Kids.
</P>
<P>
   You want to know about holiday-hyped, media-driven,
tantrum-inciting toy fads? Ask Grandma whether she felt the
slightest guilt about begging for a Shirley Temple doll in the
middle of the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   (You can bet she got plenty of lectures about starving children
and people selling apples on street corners. You can also bet she
got the doll.)
</P>
<P>
   Ask anyone who's seen A Christmas Story.
</P>
<P>
   Ralphie doesn't badger his parents into getting him just any BB
gun, does he? Like any real Saturday matinee junkie of the 1930s or
'40s, Ralphie absolutely has to have an official Red Ryder gun like
the one his favorite cowboy star fires at rustlers.
</P>
<P>
   From the very first time his parents warn, ``You'll shoot your
eye out,'' you know two things:
</P>
<P>
   1) They're right.
</P>
<P>
   2) They'll give in anyway.
</P>
<P>
   You also know that the bawling, bleeding Ralphie at movie's end
will learn nothing from his brush with disaster. He is not only
every kid, he is every parent-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   He is a born sucker. Does that seem harsh? It won't two months
from now.
</P>
<P>
   All parents know that the surest way to light up a child's eyes
is with a 9-volt battery. But we all learn soon enough that Math
Whiz Gumby or whatever seemed so captivating when the wrapping
paper came off is destined to be tossed behind the couch long
before the battery runs down.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, every parent learns that each trip to the toy
store for the latest craze results in an equal and opposite trip to
the Goodwill bin or the local kids shelter.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with Care Bears and Power Rangers and Ninja Turtles.
So it will be with Furby. (Maybe not with Beanie Babies, which are
really for adults who believe they are collector items on a par
with Cleopatra's jewels.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet we continue on an unprecedented national toy-buying binge
that last year worked out to about $350 a child, according to
industry figures. We rang up more than $1bil-lion on action
figures, twice that much on regular-old dolls and more than $4
billion on video games.
</P>
<P>
   In all, toy sales topped $22bil-lion, up nearly $10 billion in
10 years. That's enough money to raise serious expectations: We put
men on the moon for $24 billion. So it's no wonder we've come to
believe there will be something miraculous each year _ something
worth the longer lines and higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it's Furby, an odd-looking marvel of microchips like
two other recent fads, Tickle Me Elmo and Tamagotchi. The gimmick
is that Furby's nonsensical utterances (the Furbish dialect of
gibberish) gradually turn to English in a manner that mimics
learning.
</P>
<P>
   Whether great numbers of children will find that entertaining,
much less intellectually stimulating, remains to be seen. For most
people, so does Furby. Rave reviews in national publications and on
tele, and you have a powerful and increasing urge to spend wildly
on toys that impress.
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach sees more than a little blame-shifting in the notion
that parents are helpless to say no to fads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids get caught up in all this,'' she says. ``It's the
parents who have some deeper need to brag to the neighbors or who
think they have something to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   What kids really want is a warm lap and a little attention,
Auerbach says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to sit down and play a game, or put together a
puzzle,'' she says. ``They want what they need, a chance to develop
their language skills, their artistic expression, their
dexterity.''
</P>
<P>
   On her wWeb site (www.drtoy.com), Auerbach offers a list of 100
toys that parents and children can play with together. They're all
toys that require children to think and imagine, rather than toys
that simply dazzle.
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach spreads her message through the Internet, magazine and
newspaper articles, television and books, including her latest,
Smart Play.
</P>
<P>
   And still, people miss the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been getting e-mail every day begging me for help finding
a Furby,'' she says with exasperation. ``I couldn't care less. It's
the last toy I'd put on my list.''
</P>
<P>
   TOY FACTS
</P>
<P>
   Toys that are still going strong:
</P>
<P>
   Hot Wheels, introduced in 1968, continue to be the
hottest-selling toys in the country. They don't have motors or
computers, and they don't do anything except roll really fast
downhill. More than a billion have been sold.
</P>
<P>
   More than 230 million eggs of Silly Putty have been sold since
1950, about 3,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
   After 90 years, Crayola Crayons are still being produced at a
rate of 5.4 million a day. The count so far: more than 100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Logs were designed in 1916 by John Lloyd Wright, son of
architect Frank Lloyd Wright. He adapted the idea from the
technique his father used to design the earthquake-resistant
foundation of the Imperial Hotel in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Lionel makes almost a million new train cars each year, enough
to make a toy train 50 miles long.
</P>
<P>
   Two out of three American boys own a GI Joe. Boys 5 to 10 own an
average of 10.
</P>
<P>
   The world's population of Barbies and Barbie pals is nearing a
billion in more than 140 countries. American girls between 3 and 11
own an average of eight.
</P>
<P>
   Legos turned 25 this year. Scrabble turned 50. And Tinker Toys
turned 85.
</P>
<P>
   That old spuddy-duddy Mr. Potato Head has the distinction of
being the first toy advertised on television back when the Boomers
were still babies in 1952. Sales grossed $4 million the first year.
</P>
<P>
   The Slinky sprang to life when a steel coil used to test
battleship engines bounced off the desk of marine engineer Richard
James. He made 400 and persuaded Gimbel's department store to let
him demonstrate them to Christmas shoppers in 1945. He sold every
one within 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Toy Manufacturers of America
</P>
<P>
   Doug Kalajian writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
