<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 09:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0158 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREG-HAUPTNER10-COX     12-09 1710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREG-HAUPTNER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Just who is Greg Hauptner?
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The quote from billionaire oilman Nelson
Bunker Hunt tells you all you need to know about Greg Hauptner.
</P>
<P>
   Decide what you want to do and resolve to pay the price to get
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken that quote as one of the building blocks of my
existence,'' says the full-time hairdresser, part-time TV show host
and round-the-clock entrepreneur. ``I only added as long as what
you do is moral, ethical and decent.''
</P>
<P>
   Meet Greg Hauptner _ a former long-haired hippie turned savvy
(some might say shameless) self-promoter. Or, as one friend put it,
a man who knows how to get his name in the papers.
</P>
<P>
   And in magazines and on TV. Hauptner, 52, has been featured in
People, Vogue, Family Circle and was even selected by CBS News as
one of the six most successful business people in Florida in the
late '70s.
</P>
<P>
   One glance at Hauptner's extensive four page _ yes four page! _
resume shows he's been a hairdresser (he once owned a string of
shops, but is now stylists director at Elizabeth Arden in Palm
Beach Gardens), author (five motivational-style books), management
seminar leader (he recently worked with Jonathan's Landing Golf
Club in Jupiter) and even stuntman in the awful 1992 film Cop and a
Half (he fought with Burt Reynolds during a barroom brawl).
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Reynolds, from 1979 to 1987, Hauptner was the
official stylist for the Burt Reynolds Theater, where he coifed
such stars as Farrah Fawcett, Loni Anderson and Kirstie Alley.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can add another occupation to Hauptner's job-filled
resume _ TV host. Since April the gregarious New York native has
hosted In Style with Greg Hauptner, a low-budget version of
Lifestyles of the Rich &AMP; Famous. The hour-long show has featured
segments on Donald Trump, Sylvester Stallone and Tommy Lee Jones at
The Mar-a-Lago Club.
</P>
<P>
   Like Robin Leach, Hauptner's show attempts to give viewers an
up-close-and-personal look at some of South Florida's richest
residents and visitors. The show has done segments on Rolls-Royces,
luxury yachts and The Breakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seek out class, style and elegance,'' says Hauptner.
</P>
<P>
   But who is Greg Hauptner? A publicity seeker or a man who works
hard for the money and the fame?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, it seems, is a little bit of both.
</P>
<P>
   Murray Green, the senior vice president of government relations
for Raycom Media Group, has known Hauptner for 17 years. Green
describes Hauptner as a smart salesman, and a sincere, ``no B.S.''
guy as well. ``When he had his own shops, he marketed his stores
very well. He managed to get his name in the papers. He knew how to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hauptner, who says he earns a six-figure salary from his various
endeavors, is probably best known for dumping his 1967 Rolls-Royce
Silver Shadow into the Atlantic in 1985 to protest the lack of
artificial reefs for fish. The stunt was typical Hauptner. Of
course, the widely publicized move didn't hurt business for his
Great American Hair Experience salon.
</P>
<P>
   Hauptner says he knows how to get attention because he works at
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I buy tons of audio cassettes on being successful in business
and the philosophy of how to treat people nicely,'' says a nattily
dressed Hauptner, while sitting in one of Elizabeth Arden's
shoebox-sized facial rooms. ``I love networking and I meet people
constantly. But I always find out first what I can do for them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how Hauptner got his TV show. In fact, Hauptner wasn't
even looking to get on TV. Jan Orazio, a local television station
president and general manager, met with Hauptner to get her hair
styled.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she wanted to do local programming,'' recalls the
quick-thinking Hauptner. ``So, I said, `I'll do a show for you.'
And she goes, `Really? What would you do?' I thought, `I'll do, uh,
a Lifestyle of the Rich and Famous show.' It took me like 12
seconds to make up the show and sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   Orazio, however, was only willing to give Hauptner one segment
on the program. But when the show's main segment didn't pan out,
she had to put something on the air, so she gave the eager Hauptner
a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a real presence before the camera and he projects a
lot of confidence,'' Orazio says.
</P>
<P>
   But the first-time TV host admits he's not going to make anyone
forget Johnny Carson, or even Robin Leach. Initially, Hauptner read
from a script. He came off as approachable as a corpse. His
solution: ad-lib everything.
</P>
<P>
   He also ditched holding a 1950s-looking microphone that made him
look more like The Price Is Right's Bob Barker than a hip host.
``When I was holding up that microphone, I looked terrible,''
Hauptner admits.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some production problems, Orazio says In Style with Greg
Hauptner is one of her station's most popular programs. She notes
that about 30 viewers have called in, requesting tapes. With a
potential local viewership (Channel 19 in West Palm Beach) of
120,000 and a potential Comcast viewership of 140,000-150,000,
Orazio says she believes Hauptner's show can capture an even bigger
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to meet to discuss the direction we want the show
to go in,'' says Orazio, declining to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Hauptner admits the show's low-rent production values are slowly
improving. ``We're all learning together,'' he notes. ``Now we have
production meetings ahead of time, instead of just showing up and
shooting like we did before.''
</P>
<P>
   While it may not look like a slick, network production, the show
often covers interesting topics for a well-heeled audience. But
Hauptner says his favorite show was when he got to fly the Goodyear
Blimp. ``The feeling was absolutely tremendous,'' he says. ``It was
a feeling of floating. But it's much tougher to fly than it seemed
it would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out what he wanted to do with his life was once tough
for Hauptner, a tall, ruggedly handsome man with salt-and-pepper
hair and a bushy mustache. While attending Palm Beach Junior
College in the mid '60s, Hauptner had no clue what he was going to
do with his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went there for five years and never got out of a two-year
college,'' he cracks. ``I went to too many parties. So, I took $200
and a beat up van and went to California in 1969 to become a hippie
and live forever. That lasted a couple of years since I had no idea
what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Florida in 1973, he met a hair salon owner who lost all
his money in a get-rich-quick scam. Hauptner and the man became
fast friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed me his books and how much money he was making,'' he
says. ``He said, `If you ever want to get out of what you're doing,
go to beauty school and you can work at my shop.'''
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what Hauptner did. He went to hairdressing
school for one year in West Palm Beach and Miami. He figured he'd
make some quick money, cash out and ``get a real job.'' The chatty
Hauptner, however, discovered he actually liked being a
hairdresser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked the people part,'' he notes. ``If you really
think about it, it's unique because there's no other business where
you can touch somebody's head and talk to them and you have a
captive audience for a half-hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Hauptner invested much of his earnings back into his education.
He took private lessons and went to hair shows all over the world.
The work paid off _ he once owned six shops.
</P>
<P>
   Hauptner, however, says he sold the salons one-by-one because
they were becoming difficult to operate. ``They went under because
of my lack of focus,'' he says. ``I would go out and do other
projects and my businesses suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Working for Elizabeth Arden, he adds, gives him time for other
projects.
</P>
<P>
   One of those projects was writing books. Hauptner has written
five self-help books, three of which were self-published. He says
the idea to become a part-time author came about 20 years ago when
his first salon ran into financial difficulties. After talking to
friends, who gave him advice on turning around his business,
Hauptner decided he could ``write a book for novice people.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hauptner has had some setbacks (a photography business in
the late '70s also went under), one of the biggest blows came when
his five-year marriage ended. Hauptner doesn't like to talk about
it, but his barely-above-a-whisper voice makes it clear the wounds
remain fresh. But that hasn't stopped him from spending time with
his three kids, Gregory, 5; Jake, 2 and Chloe, 1.
</P>
<P>
   Hauptner, however, still spends most of his time doing hair and
thinking of ways to get rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I schizophrenic?'' he asks. ``No, I'm just an easily bored
person. I like working on a lot of things. . . . Some people have a
passion for model airplanes, I just have a passion for doing all
these little things to see if I can turn them into big things.''
</P>
<P>
   STYLIST RECALLS BRUSH WITH STARS
</P>
<P>
   For eight years, Greg Hauptner was the official hair stylist for
the Burt Reynolds Theatre, meaning he had close encounters with
several stars. Here's how he remembers some of them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kirstie Alley: ``She's a sailor's delight. That woman doesn't
care what she says, when she says it or what words she uses. She's
the kind of girl who'll prop her feet up, play cards and drink with
you until you pass out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Loni Anderson: ``She has the purest skin I've ever seen on a
human being. She's also very candid and very open about everything,
almost to the point of sounding naive. She would tell you anything
_ even the intimate details of her romances and her relationship
with Burt.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dom DeLuise: ``He just loved to talk dirty. His favorite thing
was to be in a situation like opening night, when everybody's in
tuxedos, and he'd wear these old Italian shirts with the stripes
down the middle. He loved to get women who were in furs and
diamonds all chuckling by saying the filthiest and dirtiest
things.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Farrah Fawcett: ``She was so sweet. If she got an inkling that
you were thirsty, she would stop the production and personally get
you a glass of water.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin D. Thompson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
