<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOAN-LUNDEN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lunden's all about thinking positive, getting some sleep
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ You'd think, after 20 years on TV, where
mere seconds can make or lose millions, Joan Lunden could answer
questions quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Not today, my friend.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because she's off the tube. Or maybe it's because the
presence of a tuna sandwich in a Styrofoam box makes her want to
chat like she's in a school cafeteria with a full hour before
fourth period. Or maybe it's because she doesn't realize I have all
of 10 minutes with her before her book signing.
</P>
<P>
   We're nestled in an office in Boca Raton, where about 100 folks
have gathered to fetch a copy of A Bend in the Road Is Not the End
of the Road (which whips ABC's Two Guys, A Girl and a Pizza Place
for longest title in '98). I fire questions like shrapnel, she
replies like I've lobbed cannonballs. But her leisurely manner is
testament to her new life: Lunden, 48, finally has time on her
side. Here are a quick five with the former Good Morning America
co-host:
</P>
<P>
   1) There are tons of don't-worry-be-happy books. Why'd you write
one?
</P>
<P>
   Many are written by stress experts and psychologists. A lot of
people who'd walk by those books would come in to buy mine because
they're used to seeing me when they're in their bathrobes. The
viewers have even lived with me through three pregnancies (Jamie,
18; Lindsay, 15; and Sarah, 11).
</P>
<P>
   2) It seems as if you want to make clear that leaving GMA was
your call ...
</P>
<P>
   That really didn't have anything to do with it. I wanted people
to see that everyone must face change in a positive manner.
</P>
<P>
   (Excerpt: ``Just before the last contract, I remember saying: `I
just don't know if I can actually sign back on to this grind.''')
</P>
<P>
   3) How'd you meet Jeff? (She and husband, Jeff Konigsberg, 37,
have been married nearly two years. He runs a boys' camp.)
</P>
<P>
   At a deli in Greenwich, Conn. He came over to talk to me _ we
had a mutual friend _ and I remember wishing I'd ordered some melon
and a salad instead of a huge turkey sandwich with mashed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   4) How long did it take you to select your ``final outfit''?
(Lunden wore a fuchsia jacket over a black top and pants Sept. 4.)
</P>
<P>
   I didn't have time to mull it over. There was just so much going
on _ radio, TV shows, newspapers. It was a whirlwind. I just wanted
to look really bright. And slim.
</P>
<P>
   5) Do you think doing Claritin ads compromises you as a
journalist?
</P>
<P>
   I never worked for ABC News. I was very much under ABC
Entertainment. I'm a broadcaster, period. I've never claimed to be
more than a disseminator of information. And I really am the poster
child for allergies.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
