A0160 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BENGALS-FRANCIS10-COX     12-09 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENGALS-FRANCIS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Francis helping those who may one day replace him at linebacker
position
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ National Football League players don't have the
right to choose their own successors, but James Francis is going to
have some input when the Cincinnati Bengals start looking for a new
left outside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the 30-year-old Francis' playing time has
diminished, partly because of a knee injury and partly because the
2-11 Bengals want to look at younger players such as rookie
linebackers Adrian Ross and Steve Foley.
</P>
<P>
   Foley is still trying to come back from a sprained ankle, but
Ross, a free agent from Colorado State, has been splitting time
with Francis.
</P>
<P>
   In last Sunday's 33-20 loss to Buffalo, Ross had one
interception and a deflection that led to another. He also had four
tackles, three of them for minus yardage.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, a 6-foot-2, 245-pounder, said he has leaned heavily on
Francis for guidance and support. ``James has helped me a lot. He
tells me how to play against certain guys, how to adjust in certain
situations, even little things like what to expect in different
stadiums. I don't think I'd be in the situation that I'm in now if
it wasn't for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis sees nothing extraordinary about helping younger players
who are trying to take his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything these guys ask me, I'm going to tell them the
truth,'' he said. ``If I help them, I'm helping the team. I'm not
going to stop being the kind of person I am. Just because they're
after my job, that doesn't mean I'm going to stop being their
friend and stop trying to help them on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals are starting rookies Takeo Spikes and Brian Simmons
at the two inside 'backer spots and second-year man Reinard Wilson
at right outside.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has been struggling all year, but most of the
problems have been with the line and secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take pride in the way these young guys are playing,''
Francis said. ``They're going to be here for a long time. I know I
can still play the game. If the team decides to go another way next
year, I'll accept that and move on. I know I'll be playing next
year, whether it's here or someplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross was a smallish defensive end at Colorado State and drew
free agent interest only from Jacksonville and Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a linebacker at heart,'' he said. ``In
college, I didn't move to end until my last two years. I played end
like I was a linebacker. The coaches were always telling me,
'You're not a linebacker any more.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ross is still raw, but his play has attracted attention.
``Adrian is going to be a factor next year in who's going to start,
if he continues to improve,'' said coach Bruce Coslet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of thing you find out when you put these guys
in the game. You can get an idea out of practice and in training
camp, but when you get them in a real game, that's when you find
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross said there is a direct correlation between playing time and
reaction time. ``I'm starting to know the defenses a lot better.
Now when the defense changes because a guy goes in motion or
something like that, I know what I'm going to do before the
defensive backs call the change.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Williams writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
