A0161 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NUHN-COLUMN10-COX     12-09 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NUHN-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good riddance to employees like Johnson
 &HT;    If you criticize the boss, expect to be fired
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ I'd have fired him.
</P>
<P>
   You'd have fired him, too.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Johnson wrote his own ticket out of Cincinnati on Sunday.
He's an intelligent man. He knew what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   If you're employed by a company, you don't say, ``I wouldn't buy
its product.'' At least you don't say it out loud for public
dissemination.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Johnson did Sunday when he said there was no way
he'd attend a Bengal game as a fan.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if it's true. This is about common sense.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if I went on television and said I wouldn't buy this
paper. What would I expect management to do, ignore it?
</P>
<P>
   Mike Brown did what Johnson forced him to: He released his
punter and went on to the next page.
</P>
<P>
   If I own the team and you tell me I have no idea what I'm doing,
you're gone. It doesn't matter if I actually don't have an idea.
That's not an issue. The only thing that matters is that you have
certain obligations to the man signing the check _ one of which is
you don't trash him.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you're so intrinsic to the business,
management couldn't afford to get rid of you. Mike Brown, for
instance, wouldn't have released offensive tackle Willie Anderson,
if Anderson had said that stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee Johnson isn't Willie Anderson. And he isn't Brett Favre.
And he isn't Bruce Smith. Lee Johnson is replaceable.
</P>
<P>
   As for what Johnson said, some of it's true, some of it's not.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wouldn't go to a Bengal game if he were a fan. The
problem is, people have bought their tickets up front, so they can
either throw $40 or $80 or $160 in the waste basket, or go.
</P>
<P>
   When he said, ``The formula the Bengals have developed is not
working,'' who could possibly disagree with that?
</P>
<P>
   But when he added, ``Their financial formula is not working,''
he went over the edge. The Bengals are a cash cow. Bengal
management is eating well and living well, as are the players.
</P>
<P>
   And when he said, ``They're always building. The days of
building are over. When free agency arrived, building was
destroyed,'' he was wrong, too.
</P>
<P>
   And naive.
</P>
<P>
   No team just goes out and signs a bunch of free agents and wins.
Football is far too complicated and the salary cap precludes that.
The foundation must be there in advance.
</P>
<P>
   When the 49ers signed Ken Norton Jr. a couple of years ago, they
already had a solid framework. He was just another piece. Same
thing when the Packers signed Reggie White.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals' puzzle has so many missing pieces, there isn't
enough money to lure free agents to buy them all.
</P>
<P>
   You have to build with the draft and free agency, which is what
Mike Brown has tried to do.
</P>
<P>
   No, he hasn't been successful. He's had bad judgment or bad luck
or both.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bengals certainly haven't ignored free agency. They
threw a $5 million bonus at Neil O'Donnell. They tried to bulk up
their defensive line by giving big contracts to Clyde Simmons and
Michael Bankston.
</P>
<P>
   They've spent the money. Just not wisely.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like Mike Brown is trying to lose.
</P>
<P>
   I agree he has to spend more money on his infrastructure. I
agree he has to hire more full-time scouts and should hire a
full-time general manager.
</P>
<P>
   I also doubt if he will. And there's no guarantee if he did that
everything would turn out rosy.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Bengals lousy?
</P>
<P>
   Even Mike Brown wouldn't argue that with you.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're working for him, and you trumpet that fact, be
ready for the recriminations.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
