<HEADER>
A0162 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOODNETWORK-CHEF10-CO     12-09 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODNETWORK-CHEF10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV chef adds seasoning to show
 &HT;    By Bob Batz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When Ming Tsai is preparing one of his
specialities on the Food Network, there's a good chance the
ingredients include a dash or two of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Tsai, who lived here for 18 years, hosts East Meets West With
Ming Tsai , which debuted Sept. 29 on the Food Network. The
34-year-old chef mentions Dayton often on the 30-minute program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do it,'' he says,'' because I cooked my first restaurant
meal in Dayton and I have many fond memories of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsai, who was born in Newport Beach, Calif., was 12 when he went
to work at the Mandarin Kitchen, one of the first businesses to
open in Dayton's renovated downtown Arcade in 1980. At that time,
the takeout restaurant _ which specialized in the food of Northern
China _ was owned by his parents, Iris and Stephen Tsai, who now
live in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first dishes were fried rice and Mongolian beef, and that's
when I got hooked on cooking,'' Tsai recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Tsai received a mechanical engineering degree from Yale
University, then moved to Paris to study at Cordon Bleu and work at
Fauchon and Natacha, where he encountered east-west cuisine for the
first time. He got his big break in television after executive chef
stints at restaurants in Palo Alto and Santa Fe, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did guest shots on several Food Network shows, including
Dining Around, Ready, Set, Cook and Chef de Jour , then the
producer of Dining Around told me I had a knack for TV,'' he says.
``At his suggestion, I enrolled in a two-day crash course with a
professional media trainer, whose job is training chefs for TV. It
cost me a bundle _ $1,500 _ but it was worth it because he taught
me a lot of the tricks of the trade, like how to move plates around
on the set and how to talk to the cameras.''
</P>
<P>
   On East Meets West , Tsai combines Asian cooking techniques with
Western ingredients to create international menus featuring
everything from Chinese vegetables to French sauces. Recent
episodes, which are taped in New York, featured such dishes as
Sesame Noodles With Cucumber, Shredded Ahi Tuna Tartare and Red
Roast Duck With Bok Choy Fondue.
</P>
<P>
   ``People nowadays want more than meatloaf and right now Asian
food is very popular,'' Tsai explains. ``It's good for you, offers
flavors that don't exist in other cuisines and is relatively
inexpensive to prepare because even Kroger sells ginger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Food Network, which reaches 31.5 million cable TV
subscribers with its 24-hour programming, is a fascinating place,
according to Tsai.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's 15 fridges and you wouldn't believe the number of
people who work here. It takes 25 or 30, including a kitchen staff
of six or eight, just to tape one episode of East Meets West ..
It's quite a hoot for me and sometimes things get pretty wild
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   On-air goofs are commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   `` Just today, we were making a balsamic vinegar syrup and I
left the pan on the stove too long. I splashed hot vinegar on my
arm, then the kitchen started filling with smoke. We didn't
re-shoot the episode, though, because little mistakes are part of
cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tsai's not creating culinary masterpieces in front of the
Food Network cameras, he and his wife, Polly, own and operate Blue
Ginger, a chic eatery in the Boston suburb of Wellesley. They
opened the restaurant in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a casual, upbeat bistro that has the feel, but not the
stuffiness, of a classy restaurant,'' he says. ``We seat 120 and
prices range from $5 to $12 for appetizers and $16 to $25 for
entrees.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Ginger's most popular menu item is miso sake marinated
Chilean sea bass served with soba (buckwheat noodles).
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell the hell out of that dish,'' Tsai says, adding that
the restaurant is also noted for its shiitake and leek spring rolls
that are served with three chili dipping sauces.
</P>
<P>
   Tsai, who commutes between Boston and New York, isn't sure what
he'll be doing 10 years from now. ``I'll probably be involved with
something that's related to what I'm doing right now. Polly and I
aren't interested in making a million, because were not that gung
ho, but we are having fun. We definitely aren't dreaming of opening
five more Blue Gingers and having a restaurant chain.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsai's frequent on-air plugs of Dayton have trigged numerous
reponses from the Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are coming out of the woodwork,'' he says. ``Just the
other day, my old tennis pro e-mailed me out of the blue. I've
heard from lots of other people, too, including some I haven't
talked to for a long, long time and a few I've never even met. I
love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are recipes for two of Ming Tsai's specialties - chicken
with snap peas and shiitakes and mushroom and leek spring rolls.
For more recipes, check the Food Network website at www.foodtv.com.
</P>
<P>
   Chicken with snap peas and shiitakes.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   6 chicken thighs.
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sesame oil.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup oyster sauce.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoon cornstarch.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoon minced garlic, divided.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoon minced ginger, divided.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound sugar snap peas.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup canola oil.
</P>
<P>
   4 sliced scallions, separate green and white.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chicken stock (if canned, use low sodium).
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sliced shiitake mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Marinate chicken in sesame oil, oyster sauce, cornstarch, 1
tablespoon of the garlic and 1 tablespoon of the ginger for 30
minutes. Blanch snap peas al dente iin hot salted water followed by
an ice bath. Keep the peas crisp. In a hot wok, coat bottom with
oil and add remaining 1 tablespoon of garlic, 1 tablespoon of
ginger and white scallions. Stir quickly to avoid burning. Season
chicken and brown. After about 8 minutes, add chicken stock and
reduce by half. Add mushrooms and quickly stir for 1 minute. Add
peas just to heat up and serve. Check for seasoning. Sprinkle with
fresh cracked black pepper. Serve with rice.
</P>
<P>
   Mushroom and leek spring rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Makes12 servings
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablesooon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 serrano chile, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup hoisin sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sliced shiitake mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced button mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced cepes, chanterelles or oyster mushrooms (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups leek, julienned
</P>
<P>
   1 cup bean sprouts
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped scallions
</P>
<P>
   1 (4-ounce) package bean thread (rice vermicelli), blanched,
refreshed in cold water and cut up
</P>
<P>
   salt and black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 package lumpia wrappers (Other types are egg roll and spring
roll wrappers. I prefer lumpia)
</P>
<P>
   Eggwash (1 egg and 1/2 cup of water)
</P>
<P>
   In a hot wok or saute pan add the oil followed by the garlic,
ginger and chile. Be careful not to burn. Add the hoisin and
briefly saute to get the raw taste out. Add the mushrooms, leeks
and bean sprouts. Check for seasoning. Let cool in a strainer and
drain well. When cool, add cilantro, scallions and bean thread.
Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Lay out a lumpia wrapper with corner facing you. Place a small
mound at the bottom, moisten edges with eggwash and roll bottom
corner toward the middle. Fold in both sides and continue rolling.
Finish roll and let rest. Deep fry at 350 degrees until golden
brown, about 5 minutes. Serve with mint dipping sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Mint dipping sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh mint chiffonade
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Mix all the ingredients in a small bowl. (Editor's note: to make
mint chiffonade, stack mint leaves, roll like a cigar and slice
crosswise into shreds.)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Batz writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
