<HEADER>
A0163 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KITCHEN-GIFTS10-COX     12-09 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-GIFTS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Help friends, family stock cupboards with the items they really
need
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Christmas is the perfect time to give someone the
gift they would never buy for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And one place to start is in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the possibilities are the gadgets and tools that
cooks don't need very often _ but when you need them you probably
can't borrow from the neighbors, who may not have a turkey baster,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Even people with state-of-the-art kitchens and cupboards full of
Calphalon may not have a nutmeg grater.
</P>
<P>
   I've been in fine kitchens that didn't have a decent, readable
measuring cup.
</P>
<P>
   You may have to do some research, poking around in the shelves
and drawers to see what's missing. I've got the list of things to
look for and buy if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'd mislead you if I said that they'll ``ooh and ah'' on
Christmas morn and say, ``Oh, it's what I've always wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   They just didn't know they needed an instant-read thermometer.
My sister didn't until I tucked one in her Christmas stocking;
she's still talking about how she uses it all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my checklist:
</P>
<P>
   Nutmeg grater: The traditional dime-store grater, with a little
pocket to hold the whole nutmeg, does the job, though you also may
grate your fingers. It's less than $3 and available everywhere. But
newer models range from the utilitarian Zyliss to acrylic grinders
that look and work like a pepper mill. And fresh nutmeg makes all
the difference. One grind and you're inspired to bake.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger grater: Lots of today's recipes call for fresh grated
ginger, and nothing does the job like the oroshigane developed by
the Japanese. It has fine teeth to trap the fibers. Inexpensive
metal ones can be found at some Asian stores. Ceramic versions,
with teeth that are not quite as sharp, are also available in most
cookware stores. T
</P>
<P>
   Bulb baster: You may need it only once or twice a year, but
there's no substitute. Do hold out for one made of stainless steel.
The hot fat siphoned off a duck or Christmas goose can melt a
plastic baster.
</P>
<P>
   Zester: So many recipes call for lemon zest, and no matter how
many times we explain it, people ask, ``What is lemon zest?'' It's
the flavorful outer peel, and you need a special tool to remove it
so you don't get into the bitter white pith. The traditional 6-inch
zester has five little holes to remove strands of lemon zest with
precision. The newest tool, called a microplane, looks more like a
rasp from a woodworker's shop. Just pull it across the lemon in one
long slide and you have lemon zest.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus juicer: Sure, everyone has a lemon juicer, either plastic
or glass (the old ones are collectibles), but often there's the
problem of picking out the seeds and pulp. This new gadget is a
three-piece device. Put in the lemon half, cover and twist to
juice. The seeds are strained out and you can pour the juice from
spout in the container. Called the Mini Citrus Juicer.
</P>
<P>
   Instant-read thermometer: Most cookware stores are reordering
the battery-operated digital models, which sell out during the
Thanksgiving rush. This model holds the reading for easy reference.
But the cheaper model, about $10 to $12 at most stores, is good to
have on hand as a backup for when the batteries go out in the
high-tech digital version.
</P>
<P>
   This tool is essential because food temperature is a major
safety issue. The old-fashioned models that cooks stuck into the
roast should be discarded. After years of cooking along with the
roast, it's inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable peeler: They probably bought one years ago at the
supermarket or discount store, which means the peeler has been
through the dishwasher a zillion times and is starting to rust or
just corrode. So it's a good time to pitch it and get one that
really works.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxo Good Grips peeler is the choice of chefs who have to
peel more than the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Mouli grater: If I had to pick three tools to take to a desert
island, this rotary grater would be one. It is the perfect gadget
for grating fresh Parmesan, and it does a wonderful job with nuts
and chocolate. The tool has been around for decades, and my early
version had three interchangeable drum graters.
</P>
<P>
   The newer stainless-steel version promises a longer life than
the earlier aluminum or plastic models. A stainless model with one
drum is around $20.00.
</P>
<P>
   Knife sharpener: If you think they'll use it, buy a hand-held
sharpening steel, but if they're into gadgets buy one of the manual
countertop sharpeners by Chef's Choice or Henkel. Regularly slide
the blade through the correctly aligned diamond hone sharpeners to
keep knives sharp.
</P>
<P>
   If money is no object, and noise is not objectionable, the
Chef's Choice electronic model is the one to get. Never buy the
discount-house variety that allegedly sharpens knives and opens
cans. Those will destroy a knife's sharp edge.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk: When the gravy recipe says to whisk the broth into the
flour and fat, this is the tool to use. Versatile in the kitchen
for whipping everything from egg whites and cream to polenta, it
can get regular use. Whisks come in many prices and varieties,
including the flat whisk, medium-sized sauce whisk and the big
balloon whisk. Stainless steel is preferable; avoid wood-handled
whisks, which will crack.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate measuring spoons: There was a cook at the design
board when they came up with these spice spoons sold through the
King Arthur Baker's Catalog . They call them Spice Measuring
Spoons, and they're my favorite find of '98. The spoons fit deep
into the tallest, narrowest spice can or bottle. If you've ever
made a mess pouring mustard powder into a fat 1 teaspoon measure,
you'll know these are the solution. Priced at $12.95; to order,
call (800) 827-6836.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
