<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 09:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0164 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS10-TAKE     12-09 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS10-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes.)
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about the Indian guide who is the
proposed subject for the new U.S. dollar coin?
</P>
<P>
   A: First, her name: According to the U.S. Mint, historians
disagree over how it's spelled (Sacagawea or Sacajawea, among
others), and how it's translated (either as ``boat launcher'' or
``bird woman''). Regardless of the spelling, Sacagawea _ as it's
listed on the Mint's Internet site _ was the teenage guide who in
1804-06 accompanied the expedition of Meriwether Lewis and William
Clark from the northern Great Plains to the Pacific Ocean and back.
</P>
<P>
   Captured at age 11 by a Hidatsa raiding party and taken from her
Shoshone tribe, Sacagawea subsequently was bought from the Hidatsa
by a French-Canadian trader, Toussaint Charbonneau, who made her
one of his wives. In 1804, Toussaint was hired by Lewis and Clark,
not for his own skills but for those of Sacagawea. She knew several
Indian languages, and being Shoshone could help the explorers make
contact with her people and acquire horses that were crucial to the
expedition. She also provided knowledge about the rugged
topography, and she taught the explorers how to find edible roots
and plants.
</P>
<P>
   Little is documented about what happened to Sacagawea after the
expedition, but she is believed to have died Dec. 20, 1812. She is
buried in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the address to request greetings from the White House
to someone celebrating a birthday?
</P>
<P>
   A: Requests for presidential greetings for a person 80 or older
must be made in writing. Mail to: The White House, Attention
Greetings Office, Room 39, Washington, DC 20502; or fax it to
202-395-1232. The same procedure is followed if requesting
greetings for couples observing 50th wedding anniversaries. The
White House says a response will be mailed 10 days before the
birthday or anniversary. For recorded information, call
202-456-2724.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the late-night sky recently, I noticed an incredible
circle around the moon, like a fog or mist of some sort. What was
it?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a common phenomenon in winter, said astronomer David
Dundee at Fernbank Science Center in Atlanta. Whenever it happens,
Fernbank gets calls from people asking if it's a UFO, he added. The
apparent ``halo'' is created by ice crystals and water vapor in the
upper atmosphere. It's the same phenomenon that causes rainbows
during the daytime, and occurs because of the process of refracting
or bending light by water or ice in the upper atmosphere. If the
temperature had been lower than it was that night, you'd have seen
a tighter, multicolored ring, Dundee added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Chinese are upset because the Japanese government has
never apologized about World War II. Has the Japanese government
ever apologized to the United States for attacking Pearl Harbor?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, but many years after the fact. The first time a Japanese
official publicly apologized for that country's role in the war
came in August 1995, when Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama made a
somber address on Japanese national television. In it, he became
the first prime minister in Japanese history to use the word
``apology'' instead of ``remorse'' or ``regret'' in a public speech
about the war. A month later, a Japanese envoy made what was
believed to be the first official apology on American soil for the
attack 50 years earlier. ``With utmost anguish, we squarely face
the agony of our deeds,'' said Mutsuyoshi Nishimura, the Japanese
consul general to Chicago. He was addressing a group of World War
II veterans and foreign dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Because Japan long has considered itself a war victim, not an
aggressor, it has been extremely reluctant to offer any sort of
apology. In early 1995, for example, the Japanese parliament
refused a resolution expressing remorse. In 1994, Japan's
government apologized for failing to break off diplomatic
negotiations before the attack on Pearl Harbor, but that was
addressed to the people of Japan, not to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Q: News reports say the new space station is a joint venture of
16 nations, among them Russia and the United States, which is
paying most of the costs. What are the other participating
countries, and how much are they contributing?
</P>
<P>
   A: Others taking part in the International Space Station are
Japan, Canada, Brazil and the 11 member countries of the European
Space Agency: Italy, Germany, France, Britain, Belgium, Denmark,
the Netherlands, Norway, Spain, Sweden and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Money predictions vary widely, but the most recent suggested
cost for construction and hardware alone was about $40 billion.
Officially, the U.S. share is expected to be almost $25 billion.
The original Russian contribution was expected to be $8 billion to
$10 billion, but that was before the current economic crisis hit.
Since Russian Proton rockets and Soyuz spacecraft are vital to the
enterprise, it's believed that U.S. taxpayers may well have to pick
up much of Russia's original contribution. The other partners'
shares are about $3.1 billion from Japan; $850 million from Canada;
$200 million from Brazil; and $3.8 billion from the European group,
with a separate $550 million from Italy. With shuttle flights and
operational expenses added to engineering and construction costs,
the price tag is expected to reach or exceed $100 billon during the
station's planned 10-year operational lifetime. The target date for
its completion is 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the term ``jaywalking?''
</P>
<P>
   A: The expression dates to the early part of the century,
according to Morris Dictionary of Word and Phrase Origins, when
``jay'' was a popular slang term meaning ``countrified'' or
``rustic.'' A jay was pretty much the same as a rube and the word
was so used by George M. Cohan in the lyrics of one of his most
famous songs, ``45 Minutes From Broadway.'' A farmer _ strange in
the ways of a city, and perhaps frightened by all the newfangled
autos churning down the streets at fantastic speeds up to 15 mph _
might have been expected to cross the street without paying
attention to vehicles, signs or crosswalks, if there were such.
Hence, ``jaywalking.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I live in Dayton, Ohio, a city where I-70 and I-75 intersect,
with heavy congestion. I've heard that there's a pattern to the way
highways are numbered, related to their direction. Is that true?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, U.S. and Interstate highways on east-west routes have
even numbers, and on north-south routes have odd numbers. Thus, in
your situation, I-70 goes east-west, I-75 north-south.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Nearly 20 years ago, a nuclear reactor failed at the Three
Mile Island power plant in Pennsylvania, creating a crisis. What is
the current status of that failed reactor? Has it been completely
cleaned up? What have been the costs?
</P>
<P>
   A: The nuclear power plant, site of the most serious accident in
the history of America's nuclear power industry in 1979, was back
in the news in July when it was announced that its owner, GPU Inc.
of Morristown, N.J., planned to sell it to a joint venture between
Peco Energy Co. and British Energy PLC. The reactor that was ruined
in the accident March 28, 1979, was not part of the sale, and would
continue to be owned by GPU, which spent $100 million refurbishing
the plant and its other reactor and retraining workers after the
incident. As reported by Bloomberg News in July when the sale was
announced, the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission now considers
Three Mile Island to be one of the better-run U.S. nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction, the first sale of a nuclear plant by a U.S.
utility, is expected to take one to two years to win approval from
regulators, including the NRC. Peco, a power company with 1.5
million customers in the Philadelphia area, and British Energy, an
electricity generating company in the United Kingdom, are in a
partnership to purchase U.S. nuclear plants. The two companies
formed a joint venture in September called AmerGen Energy Co. to
buy the plants.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
