<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 09:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0166 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS10-TAKE     12-09 1671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS10-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: PART TWO OF TWO TAKES.)
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: This season, the undefeated Denver Broncos almost lost to the
struggling Cincinnati Bengals. Could you print the scores of the 17
games that the 1972 Miami Dolphins won in their undefeated season?
</P>
<P>
   A: The teams they beat, in order: Kansas City 20-10, Houston
34-13, Minnesota 16-14, New York Jets 27-17, San Diego 24-10,
Buffalo 24-23, Baltimore 23-0, Buffalo 30-16, New England 52-0, New
York Jets 28-24, St. Louis (Cardinals) 31-10, New England 37-21,
New York Giants 23-13, Baltimore 16-0, Cleveland 20-14 (AFC
divisional playoff), Pittsburgh 21-17 (AFC championship),
Washington 14-7 (Super Bowl).
</P>
<P>
   Miami is the only team in National Football League history to go
through an entire season, including postseason games, unbeaten and
untied. For the Broncos to go undefeated this season, they'd have
to win 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We watched the lighting of the Christmas tree at Rockefeller
Center on TV. I didn't hear how many lights are on it, or if any
ornaments or other decorations are used. Do you know? Also, how
tall is the tree? Where did it come from? How long has Rockefeller
Center been doing this?
</P>
<P>
   A: The tree is decorated with 26,000 lights and a star on top,
but has no other ornamentation, said Nora King of Rockefeller
Center's marketing department. A 75-foot-tall Norway spruce, the 7
1/2-ton tree came from the yard of Adolph and Ethel Szitar of
Richfield, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller Center's holiday celebration began in 1931, when
Depression-era workmen building the skyscraper complex placed a
small, unadorned tree on the site to help lift their spirits. In
1933 another tree was set up, this time with 700 lights. Over the
years, the tree and the ceremony both have grown. In 1951, the
tree-lighting was televised for the first time on NBC's ``The Kate
Smith Show.'' This year's ceremony, televised nationwide on NBC,
drew an ``enormous'' crowd, the largest in years, King said. She
attributed the turnout, estimated in the thousands, at least partly
to the unseasonably balmy early December weather.
</P>
<P>
   The lights were turned on precisely at 8:52 p.m. by first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton and country singer Garth Brooks. Other
participants in the ceremony were singers Jewel and Cyndi Lauper,
and Olympic gold medal ice skater Kristi Yamaguchi, who took a few
turns on Rockefeller Center's ice rink.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With respect to inheritance taxes, can you tell me the dollar
amount of the estate that is exempt from taxation?
</P>
<P>
   A: By federal law, for estates of people who died in 1998, if
the total estate is less than $625,000, no estate tax return is
required. The amount of estate valuation excluded from taxation
will rise in increments from $625,000 to $1 million by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has any U.S. president ever visited, or been allowed on the
grounds of, Area 51 in Nevada?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Air Force says it has no information about any
presidential visits to Groom Lake, the official name of the site
you refer to as Area 51. The White House press office says
President Clinton has never been there, and wasn't sure if any
previous presidents had visited.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't know, Groom Lake is about 90 miles northwest
of Las Vegas. It's the home of a super-secret U.S. military base
that goes by such other names as Dreamland (the call sign of its
control tower), The Ranch, Paradise Ranch, The Darkside of the
Moon, and The Container, as well as Area 51. The base is in
Emigrant Valley north of the Papoose mountain range. Many planes
have been built and/or tested there, including the U-2 spy plane of
Gary Powers fame, the SR-71 and the F-117 stealth fighter. Rumors
fly as fast as a speeding UFO about the existence in Area 51 of a
hypersonic aircraft called the Aurora, as well as a
triangular-shaped aircraft with rounded corners called the TR-3
Black Manta. Airspace over Groom Lake is said to be off-limits to
civilian and military aircraft, and visits by anyone on land are,
to put it mildly, not encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution reporter Bill Hendrick went to
Nevada and described Area 51 in an article published in June 1997.
His opening paragraph sets the tone of the place: ``Something weird
is going on in the Nevada desert and the Pentagon is dead set on
keeping it secret.'' He went on to say the Air Force base at Area
51 ``is said by UFO buffs to be one of the places where aliens and
'flying saucers' have been taken for study by the military,'' but
added that there's little evidence to back up such claims, and the
Pentagon dismisses them as ludicrous. The secrecy surrounding the
base naturally gives rise to all sorts of rumors, making the nearby
town of Rachel, Nev., a great place for UFO-minded tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Mel Allen, the famed Yankees broadcaster, still living?
When I was 13, he wrote me a note about becoming a man at age 13.
As I'm approaching my 50th birthday, I wanted to track him down and
thank him for the note he sent so many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a nice thought, but sadly it's too late. Allen, the
voice of the New York Yankees for a generation, as well as the
voice of television's ``This Week in Baseball,'' died in June 1996
at age 83. He was with the Yankees from 1939 to 1964 and was
inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1978. After Allen died,
the Yankees wore black armbands on the left sleeves of their
uniforms for the remainder of the '96 season in his memory.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard politicians on both sides of the Clinton-Lewinsky
issue say the other side someday would have to eat humble pie. Can
you explain that expression?
</P>
<P>
   A: It means to suffer humiliation, to apologize, or to abase
oneself. The Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins says it has
nothing to do with the word humble, in the sense of lowly. Instead,
it's traced to ``umbles'' (from the Latin lumbulus, or litte loin).
It had to do with the custom in centuries past for the lord of a
manor to serve his guests meat _ venison, for example _ with the
manor's lowly workers given only umble pie made with the animal's
innards. Because the pie was associated with a position of
inferiority, it came to have its present meaning. The encyclopedia
says an anonymous punster in the time of William the Conqueror
added the ``h'' to umble _ but it didn't affect the pronunciation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When was the first college football game televised? When was
the first professional game televised?
</P>
<P>
   A: The first televised collegiate game was Sept. 30, 1939,
between Fordham University of New York and Waynesburg College of
Waynesburg, Pa. It was played in New York at Randalls Island and
televised by W2XBS of the National Broadcasting Corp. in New York.
Fordham won, 34-7. The first pro game to be televised was Oct. 22,
1939, at Brooklyn's Ebbets Field, also by W2XBS. The Brooklyn
Dodgers defeated the Philadelphia Eagles, 23-14.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There are two census forms, one long and one short, but how
is it determined who gets which one? What is the penalty if someone
doesn't complete a census form?
</P>
<P>
   A: A computer randomly selects which households get which forms,
with the computer selecting simply by addresses. The Census Bureau
says it doesn't know who lives in each household. In a big city,
perhaps one in every eight households gets the long form, a
spokeswoman said; in a rural area, it's perhaps every other
household. The short form has seven questions; the long form has
those same questions, plus additional ones.
</P>
<P>
   So far as penalties are concerned, the Census Bureau's approach
is not to punish people who choose not to participate, although by
law the taking of a census is mandatory, and that same law says
anyone refusing to answer questions is subject to a fine. The
Census Bureau says it prefers that people understand how important
it is to participate, and because of that will be willing to fill
out whichever form they receive.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there an easy way to find out a person's ZIP code? Because
I'm handicapped, it's hard to get to a library or even to the post
office to look at a directory, and I don't have a computer for
Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Postal Service operates a hotline to answer this and any
other postal question. Call 1-800-275-8777.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard a radio commentator talking about a recent Ann
Landers column in which someone wrote that they resented long
letters at the holiday season about ``happy news'' that had
occurred during the previous year. The commentator then mentioned
an organization called Happy People. Can you fill in the details on
the Landers column, and the Happy People group?
</P>
<P>
   A: The issue came up in Landers' Nov. 29 syndicated column. In
it, Landers endorsed the idea that people should keep their ``happy
news'' _ or, as the letter writer put it, ``ghastly Christmas
letters'' _ to themselves. The letter writer, identified only as
``Your Cousin in Illinois,'' resented hearing about ``your new
$700,000 home or the Lexus your husband had parked in the driveway
as a surprise,'' adding that many people have a rough time making
ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   The Happy People group the commentator mentioned is the Secret
Society of Happy People, based in Irving, Texas. It responded to
the Landers column by issuing a press release saying it was
``shocked to see such a blatant example'' of the way popular
culture discourages the sharing of happy moments. Pam Johnson,
founder of the Secret Society of Happy People, has asked Landers
for an apology, so you're likely to read more about this in the
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Happy People organization can be contacted at 5330 N.
MacArthur Blvd., Suite 148-215, Irving, TX 75038 (972-791-0028) or
at http://www.sohp.com for online information. If you want to join,
membership is $30, and you'll receive a T-shirt and other items, as
well as a quarterly newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
