 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 412 - December 9, 1998   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 412 -- Dec. 9, 1998 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. EDWARD NORTON'S 'HISTORY' LESSON In a short but controversial
career, Edward Norton has played a psychotic killer in ``Primal
Fear,'' a singing lover in ``Everyone Says I Love You'' and Hustler
Magazine's defence attorney in ``The People vs. Larry Flynt.'' But
his latest film, ``American History X,'' is his most controversial:
he plays a neo-Nazi leader. In this interview Norton talks about
the new film, how he learned to think like a Nazi, why he doesn't
expect it to help race relations in America and what led to the
rift between him and director Tony Kaye (who has disowned the film
after accusing Norton of re-editing his work.) By Jeanne Wolf.
1,400 words + photo. 2. COMMERCIALS DIE IN MOVIE BLOODBATH HORROR!
Advertisers who pay for expensive TV slots in the middle of films
like ``Reservoir Dogs'' could be wasting their money. Screen
violence seems to impair viewers' memory for advertising. By Sara
Abdulla. Nature News Service. 400 words. (N/A France and Spain.) 3.
VINCE VAUGHN : SERIAL KILLER? How many times have you seen the
classic Hitchcock film ``Psycho?'' It's a question an interviewer
can't help but ask when talking to actor Vince Vaughn, who is
reprising the role of Norman Bates in the much-anticipated remake
of ``Psycho.'' Vaughn, 28, has only seen the original film twice.
``Once as a kid and when I found out I'd be playing the part,'' he
says. ``My thing was not to go and mimic Anthony Perkins ... I
decided to approach it as a play, like something powerful you see
once on stage, and then take the material and interpret it
differently.'' Interview by Molly Knight. From The Daily News
Record. 1,000 words + photos. 4. BRIDGET FONDA'S NOT-SO-SIMPLE PLAN
As a third-generation movie star, Bridget Fonda has some big shoes
to fill. But Fonda - daughter of Peter, niece of Jane,
granddaughter of Henry - has carved out a solid career for herself
in films such as Francis Ford Coppola's ``The Godfather Part III,''
``Single White Female,'' Quentin Tarantino's ``Jackie Brown'' and
her current film, ``A Simple Plan.'' In this interview Fonda talks
about the new film, her break-up with actor Eric Stoltz, an
upcoming role as a Marilyn Monroe imitator and why she's beginning
to rethink her career-long uninhibitedness about nude scenes. By
Jeanne Wolf. 1,400 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   5. PETER FONDA : EASY RIDER TACKLES SHAKESPEARE His role as
Prospero in an innovative new version of Shakespeare's ``The
Tempest'' caps a memorable year for Peter Fonda. It follows his
Oscar nomination as Best Actor for ``Ulee's Gold,'' and the warm
reception given to ``Don't Tell Dad,'' his candid memoir of life
with his beloved but obstinate father, the late actor Henry Fonda.
In this interview Fonda talks about ``The Tempest,'' how ``Ulee's
Gold'' has changed his life, how his sister Jane reacted to his
autobiography and why he thinks so many people see echoes of their
own families in his. By Ian Spelling. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
LEVAR BURTON'S LONG, STRANGE TREK LeVar Burton's career started in
the past - as Kunta Kinte in the acclaimed TV miniseries ``Roots,''
- and has brought him to the future - as Lt. Cmdr. La Forge in the
TV series ``Star Trek : The Next Generation,'' and several movies,
including ``Star Trek : Insurrection.'' Burton explains why he
thinks ``Star Trek'' has such enduring appeal and how his blind
``Trek'' character reacts in the current film to the chance of
having his vision restored. By Jeanne Wolf and Shep Morgan. 1,400
words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
ROMANCE IS BACK FOR TOM HANKS Tom Hanks talks about his new film,
``You've Got Mail,'' (a sparkling romantic comedy co-starring Meg
Ryan,) how he managed his unlikely rise from the inane TV sitcom
``Bosom Buddies'' to his current success and why he thinks
Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan'' struck such a chord in both
veterans and younger Americans. By Ian Spelling. 1,400 words +
photo. 8. FACE VALUE : MAIL CALL (TOM HANKS / MEG RYAN) In this new
cartoon feature, artist Ricardo Castaneda depicts Tom Hanks and Meg
Ryan in the upcoming film, ``You've Got Mail.'' 9. METALLICA SHIFTS
GEARS Even the tough guys in the band Metallica need a break from
their rigorous schedule sometimes. ``You fall into so many traps as
a popular band who loves what they do,'' says drummer Lars Ulrich.
``Metallica still needs to have fun. We made three pretty serious
albums in a row. It was time to do something different.'' Their new
album ``Garage Inc.'' has just been released. Profile by Carrie
Bell. Billboard. 800 words. Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or
33.1.47.42.18.81 I am interested in story no. ______ from summary
