<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0242 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS10-COX     12-09 1682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tight-fitting sleepwear OK for kids, safety agency says
 &HT;    (Eds: A compilation of health stories that moved from Cox News
Service in the past week.)
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sleeping in oversize T-shirts could create a firetrap for
children, the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission warns. But
snug-fitting cotton pajamas, previously considered dangerous,
should be OK.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, the agency advised the public that
flame-resistant pajamas were the only safe garments children should
wear to bed. However, those standards were relaxed this year, after
the commission decided that the way pajamas fit is more important
than the fabric they're made of.
</P>
<P>
   ``By fitting close to the skin, you don't have oxygen underneath
that feeds the fire,'' said Ken Giles, a commission spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, up to 300 children are burned by being near a flame _
a space heater, kitchen range or candle, for example _ while
wearing loose-fitting sleepers, the safety commission said. Hence
the warning about loose T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Flame-resistant fabrics, such as polyester, stop burning when
removed from a flame, prompting the agency's earlier warning about
fabric types. Cotton was one fabric the commission used to warn
against, because it can burn rapidly. But Giles said that is not
the case if the cotton garment is tight.
</P>
<P>
   Report says states not curbing animal pollution
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- At least 30 states are failing to curb pollution
from large livestock and poultry operations, a report says. The
waste from these ``animal factories'' fouls drinking water and
threatens public health, according to the Natural Resources Defense
Council, an environmental group that released the report last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most states have few regulations and do little to enforce what
laws might be on the books,'' said Robbin Marks, one of the authors
of the report. ``The result is unchecked pollution leading to
contaminated well water, fish kills, sickness from toxic gases in
the air and plummeting property values for neighboring
landowners.''
</P>
<P>
   Livestock industry representatives say the report lacks
scientific evidence and is packed with old information.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this (the report) was food, it would have salmonella,''
said Steve Cohen, spokesman for the National Pork Producers
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups, however, say much more needs to be done.
The report details specific environmental problems in 30 states.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, for example, groundwater contamination near
animal factories is increasing, posing a potentially serious
drinking water problem for nearby residents, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Shock waves tested for orthopedic pain
</P>
<P>
   Clinical trials are under way in five U.S. cities to determine
if extracorporeal shock wave therapy can benefit those with foot
pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not completely well; I've probably got about a third of
the pain left,'' says Rick Waits, 47, of Atlanta, whose foot pain
kept him from playing golf or going for walks. ``But the beauty of
it now is all I have to do is get off my feet for 15 or 30 minutes
and I start to get relief. That was never the case before.''
</P>
<P>
   The treatment that turned Waits' life around and healed his heel
involves a machine called an OssaTron, which uses high-energy shock
waves to blast away calcifications and re-tear injured tendons in
heel spurs and tennis elbows. By doing this, doctors can dissipate
old scars and cause tendons to heal correctly, thus alleviating
pain.
</P>
<P>
   The technique, called extracorporeal shock wave therapy, has
been around since the mid-1980s, when it was first used to
disintegrate kidney stones. Researchers suspected that the process
had a number of orthopedic applications as well.
</P>
<P>
   Mental health officials try to get a hold on `basket' restraint
misuse
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Unless national standards for training
and the use of physical restraint are developed, state and national
experts believe more people like 17-year-old Laura Hanson will die.
</P>
<P>
   Police are still investigating Hanson's death, which was ruled a
homicide by asphyxia. She died Nov. 19 after two employees put her
in the controversial ``basket hold,'' a restraint that has lead to
the deaths of mental health patients across the country. The hold
becomes deadly when the patient is placed face-down, pressure is
placed on the backs and the patient's arms are criss-crossed over
the chest.
</P>
<P>
   The Child Welfare League of America, the nation's oldest child
advocacy organization, is pushing for national standards regarding
the use of restraint, said Lloyd Bullard, director of residential
care for the Washington-based nonprofit agency. Bullard said the
group wants federal legislation that will require training and
mandatory reporting of restraint deaths.
</P>
<P>
   It's head lice season again
</P>
<P>
   The start of the school season means the return of head lice
season. If your kids come home with head lice, don't expect a quick
solution. Here are a few tips:
</P>
<P>
   _ Use the lice-killing shampoo. While common over-the-counter
pediculicides are only 70 percent to 80 percent effective at
killing the eggs, that's the only way to start. Most contain
pyrethrum, a naturally occurring pesticide derived from
chrysanthemum flowers. Lindane, the prescription pesticide used for
pubic lice, is considered somewhat toxic and should be used only as
a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get a metal comb. Those plastic combs that come with
lice-killing shampoo are practically useless at trapping nits. Give
it to your daughter so she can disinfest Barbie's hair while you
work on hers with a sturdy metal comb, which costs about $5.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get a few small plastic hair clips and a fine-tooth plastic
comb with a long handle. You can and will learn to part and repart
the kids' hair like a stylist cutting a shag.
</P>
<P>
   _ Every night: Get the children sitting in position with water,
toys and treats. Comb their hair out with a regular comb. Check the
scalp thoroughly for live and dead lice, pick them out and put them
in a cup of water. Next, nits. Take a small ( 1/2-inch to 1-inch)
bunch of hair, and scrape the nit-removal comb through it, making
sure the shafts of hair push against the top of the comb. Check the
hair carefully and pick out nits the comb misses; deposit in the
cup of water. Repeat with the next bunch of hair.
</P>
<P>
   _ Change kids' sheets and pillowcases every night for the first
week. Then change their pillowcases every night until the nits are
history.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call the National Pediculosis Association
at 1-800-446-4672 or visit the nonprofit agency's Web site:
http://www.headlice.org.
</P>
<P>
   Shelters, school lunch programs focusing on nutrition
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Those who feed the poor, from the federal
government to local food pantries, are increasingly aware of the
role proper nutrition should play in their programs. Some say it is
paying off in more healthful diets for low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   ``My general observation is that . . . the nutritional quality
of the foods that are currently coming through the system are some
of the best I've seen in a very long time,'' said Lisa
Hamler-Podolski, director of the advocacy group Ohio Food Policy
and Anti-Poverty Action Center.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA also prepares its food differently. Where it once
packed fruit in sugar solutions, it now uses natural juice. It
eliminated the use of tropical oils. It developed items such as
lower-fat beef patties and cut the sodium content in cereals.
</P>
<P>
   Government-backed public school lunches _ which low-income
students can eat free or at a reduced cost _ have also gone
wholesome.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dayton schools, where 75 percent of students get free or
reduced-price meals, cooks have slashed their dishes' fat and
sodium levels, according to Nutrition Services Director Nancy
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't fried anything to speak of in years _ except french
fries,'' she said. ``And we use olive oil to fry them.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida bans online Viagra prescriptions
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Concerned about the danger of Web sites that
offer Viagra prescriptions without any face-to-face doctor-patient
contact, the state's Board of Medicine said that doctors who
prescribe the drug online could face criminal prosecution or board
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have at least a basic history and physical and an
impotence workup,'' said Dr. Abraham Woods, a urologist and member
of the board. ``This is clearly not an issue you want to treat
lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   The area of Internet prescriptions is so new that the board had
never before discussed setting rules for the issue, but the board
made it clear that they frown upon online Viagra prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem, board members said, is that doctors who
prescribe over the Internet know very little about the patient.
Woods said some patients may be impotent as a result of diabetes or
elevated testosterone levels, and therefore Viagra would not be
appropriate. Also, taking Viagra in conjunction with heart medicine
can be extremely dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need follow-up and care, he said. ``You can't just put a
person on medication and leave them out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Year's end spurs eye-care business
</P>
<P>
   Eyeglasses often make it on the list of holiday purchases _ not
as presents, but as a way for patients to squeeze out the last
dollars of their yearly health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   As more employees participate in medical flexible spending
accounts _ a pool of tax-free funds they can use for health-related
expenses _ some discover they did not use as much money throughout
the year as they'd anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   And that means they must find ways to spend it by the end of the
year, or lose it _ one of the few conditions of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see an upswing in business as individuals search for ways
to use their spending accounts,'' said Dr. Peter Gordon, an
ophthalmologist with Eye Physicians and Surgeons. ``Sometimes, they
just buy the frames and wait to buy the lens.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
