<P>
   NEW NOTICE: Versions of some of these stories are available in
paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   CHIMNEYCARE _ A guide to chimney care. Looking at chimney sweeps
(how often you need one and how much you should expect to pay).
(John, Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer; not for use by NYT
clients). 30ish. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CHIMNEY-WOOD _ What woods to burn; fireplace accessories;
fireplace safety tips and box on organizations/Web sites to
call/visit for more information.(John, Atlanta Journal-Constitution
freelancer; not for use by NYT clients). 15.
</P>
<P>
   FUNERAL _ One night recently, Sandy Whittington stretched out on
her living room floor in Douglasville, Ga., and instructed her
disbelieving son to measure her body. A few weeks later, it
arrived: a mail-order coffin in a packing crate labeled ``Casket _
Empty.'' She had it hauled into the attic, where it holds
out-of-season clothes and waits for the inevitable day that awaits
us all. The American funeral is changing. The standard open-casket,
two-day visitation, earth-burial of a generation ago is giving way
to new customs: shorter services, bodyless commemorations, more
personalized ceremonies, a fast-growing number of cremations. We
trace the history of American funerals by visiting the National
Funeral Museum in Houston and look at the way the industry is
changing as it consolidates into chain operations (the biggest:
Houston-based Service Corp. International) and tries to address
criticisms that funeral homes take advantage of consumers in their
time of greatest vulnerability. (Auchmutey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FUNERAL-ADVICE _ sidebar about the consumer do's and don't's of
shopping for funeral services. Should you buy pre-need contracts?
Probably not. Is embalming required by law, as some morticians
imply? Absolutely not. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FUNERAL-GLOSSARY _ The vocabulary of death, a short glossary of
funeral euphemisms. Think of it as our parting floral tribute.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPER-COLUMN _ Personal shopper column. (JSabulis, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution freelancer; not for use by NYT clients).
16-18.
</P>
<P>
   FURBY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sooner or later, every parent
learns that each trip to the toy store for the latest craze results
in an equal and opposite trip to the Goodwill bin or the local kids
shelter. So it was with Care Bears and Power Rangers and Ninja
Turtles. So it will be with Furby. A history of popular toys for
good girls and boys. (Kalajian, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DISCOUNT-COFFINS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It takes nerve to
comparison shop for your own coffin. You're not just browsing,
after all. You're confronting your own mortality. ``No one's
leaving this world alive,'' says Angelo Rolon. This could be his
sales pitch. Rolon sells discount coffins to penny-pinchers
planning for the day they breathe their last, pass on to eternal
glory, tee-off at the great golf course in the sky. His showroom
features caskets with names that sound vaguely like American luxury
cars: the Winston, the Grant, the Primrose, the Dartmouth. (Reed,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
