<HEADER>
A0279 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-IMMIGRATION-BU Dec.9 1998 &LR;  12-09 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-IMMIGRATION-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
  
</HEADLINE>
   ednesday, Dec. 9, 1998
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file a four-day series called
``Fortress Europe,'' which examines the European Union and its
immigration crisis. The series by the Houston Chronicle is
available for use beginning this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Like the southwestern United States, the EU is grappling with
immigration. Some experts think that up to 1 million people could
try to breach the EU's external borders this year. And many
Europeans are in no mood to play host.
</P>
<P>
   The series was written by Carl Honore with photos by Kerwin
Plevka. The photos, graphics and maps are available on the New York
Times photo service.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAY 1 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-MIGRANTS (Melilla, Spain) _ Like thousands of migrants
before him, like thousands more sure to come, Hamid Uld-Mohamed is
here on a mission: to use this Spanish port on the coast of North
Africa as a springboard to a shiny new life in the European Union.
``Even if they put up electrified fences all along the borders of
Europe, even if they put up the barriers of hell, people will keep
on coming,'' he says. (With two photos, one graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-SMUGGLERS (Prague, Czech Republic) _ As in the United
States, the tightening of border security is forcing would-be
migrants into the arms of professional traffickers. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-PROSTITUTION (Amsterdam, the Netherlands) _ Many women
selling their bodies in the windows of Europe's famous red-light
district are immigrants trapped in sexual slavery. The trafficking
in women is an ugly sub-current in the immigration flow to the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAY 2 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-BORDERS (Eissenhuttenstadt, Germany) _ German border
guard Jan Steenfatt patiently scans the woods and fields that fan
out into the distance. The narrow Neisse River down below, which
marks the line between Germany and Poland, is a favorite crossing
point for illegal immigrants seeking a better life in the West.
Across the European Union, governments have tightened immigration
laws and beefed up their borders. But nothing they have done is
enough to staunch the flow of illegal immigrants. (With two
photos.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TEXAS (Eissenhuttenstadt, Germany) _ On foreign trips,
German border guard Jan Steenfatt likes nothing better than to drop
by the local police station to swap badges and a little chat. His
dream is to spend a day along the Texas-Mexico frontier with the
U.S. Border Patrol. As the European Union fights to secure its own
borders against illegal immigration, the experience along the
U.S.-Mexico frontier stands out as a benchmark. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-ENTRY (London) _ The Schengen agreement, which was
designed to create border-free travel within the European Union,
has been a boon to criminals and illegal immigrants. (With
graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAY 3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-FOREIGNERS (Vitrolles, France) _ As Europe seals its
borders against illegal immigrants, sentiment across the continent
builds against foreigners. For example, the extreme right-wing
National Front in France is offering to give ``birth bonuses'' to
villagers who add to the white population. (With two photos.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-SKINHEADS (Magdeburg, Germany) _ For a lot of angry young
men, xenophobia sparks a wave of violence in Germany. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-WELCOME (Badolato, Italy) _ An Italian town has defied
conventional wisdom and has opened its arms to immigrants. (With
two photos.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAY 4 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-ACCEPTANCE (Antwerp, Belgium) _ In a region proud of its
liberal traditions, many new immigrants, particularly those with
dark skins, say they find it hard to be accepted as equals and to
get ahead in daily life. (With two photos.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-IDENTITY (London) _ Europeans still have a lot of fun
with national stereotypes. The uptight English sipping tea. The
snobbish French dunking croissants in their cafe au lait. The
mechanical Germans searching for a sense of humor. Nowadays,
though, such portraits are largely the stuff of comedy sketches and
cartoons. Defining national identity in Western Europe has become a
subtle and slippery matter. In many countries, a debate is raging
over a question that never needed asking before: What does it mean
to be French or Dutch or English? One reason for the crisis of
identity is European integration. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-SUCCESS (London) _ To most Europeans, buying a suit on
Savile Row means the same thing as it did 200 years ago. Immaculate
craftsmanship. Sky-high prices. Traditional English service. But
the old image of rich white men buying sober suits from staid white
tailors is starting to fray like an aging lapel. Today, Andrew
Ramroop, a black immigrant from the Caribbean island of Trinidad,
owns and runs Maurice Sedwell, a shop on ``The Row.'' Some might
see Ramroop's rise to the top of his profession as a beacon, as a
sign that the immigrant story in Europe is not all exclusion and
failure. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
