<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER 
 JACKSON HOLE, WYO.: A WINTER `HOT SPOT'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact Nirdi Relis at (212) 499-3333; fax
(212) 499-3382.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It's a white-on-white day with snow dusting the hoarfrost and
fog layering the horizon line. The only hues breaking the
monochromatic color scheme are startling ski jackets, teasing
tassels on striped mufflers, wild woolen caps and rosy cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, we visited Jackson Hole, Wyo., a place we thought
we'd never spend any winter days. We don't do snow any more _ not
since our early years in Minnesota and Kansas. We never have
learned how to glide down a hill on two pieces of wood with any
grace.
</P>
<P>
   So what's there to do in Jackson if you don't ski and aren't a
snow lover? Try the nature show:
</P>
<P>
   How about a sleigh ride near a herd of 8,000 elk?
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for this winter-wonderland ride can be purchased at the
National Museum of Wildlife, (307) 733-5771. The vastness of the
white landscape is reduced to Lilliputian size beneath the craggy
Gros Ventre mountain backdrop. Thousands of elk spread across the
valley floor, moving in slow motion, as your sleigh steadily enters
their midst with a creak and lurches over the rutted valley floor.
</P>
<P>
   One ambles slowly toward you, stopping to paw the snow for a bit
of food.
</P>
<P>
   Crack! Two bulls butt antlers in a ballet of sorts, while others
lie on the snow-covered field saving their strength to forage for
food later.
</P>
<P>
   The National Elk Refuge just north of Jackson, Wyo., protects
8,000 to 10,000 elk each winter. The daily sleigh rides for
visitors grew out of early efforts to feed the elk.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, horse-drawn hay wagons were used to distribute
food to the elk, and an occasional visitor was taken along. In
1965, sleigh rides for visitors were started officially, and now
from December through March visitors climb aboard haywagon sleighs
to spend about an hour in the middle of the migrating herd.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the first-come, first-serve elk refuge rides cost
about $10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON SAFARI &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the museum and refuge have whetted your appetite to talk to
the animals, a Wildlife Discovery Safari aboard Serengeti-style
vehicles will bring you even closer to nature.
</P>
<P>
   With sliding windows, opening roofs and binoculars at the ready
for all participants, the safari ride will let you ``play biologist
for a day'' says Tom Segerstrom, founder of the Great Plains
Wildlife Institute. (And you'll keep warm, too!) The institute
operates in Jackson with safaris throughout the surrounding area.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo, moose, whitetail mule and bighorn sheep get up close
and personal as Segerstrom explains why ``The more diverse the
ecosystem, the healthier it is'' and that ``bison are not
endangered any more. Your grandchildren will always be able to come
here and see them ...''
</P>
<P>
   Segerstrom lectures every step of the way, letting the
half-dozen people in the van know that ``the best way to be around
wildlife is do what they expect.'' However, he does offer one
warning: Don't force animals up and out of their beds.
</P>
<P>
   The full-day adventure, which is priced at $140 per person,
allows participants the time to locate more species, help with
hands-on wildlife research projects and share stories over lunch.
</P>
<P>
   And if you choose, you can join a brief snowshoe expedition that
may help find, count or track species that are included in the
institute's stewardship projects. Some winters the institute also
offers a shorter sunset or sunrise safari for $80.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call (307) 733-2623; write P.O. Box 7580,
Jackson Hole, Wyo. 83002; or visit www.wildlifesafari.com on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSH! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of our travel companions raved about their dog-sled tours
aboard modern sleds. Musher-guides signaled the sights of wildlife
with the shussing sounds of winter _ wind in their faces, dogs
panting and the sled's runners streaking across the snow.
</P>
<P>
   Full-day dog-sled tours travel 20 to 22 miles round trip for
$225 per person, while half-day tours are 10 to 12 miles for $135
per person.
</P>
<P>
   My friends traveled from Granite Creek Hot Springs trailhead to
the springs, where they took a soak. On their return they ate lunch
in front of a fire in the Granite Creek Ranch lodge.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call (800) 554-7388 or write Jackson Hole
Iditarod Sled Dog Tours, P.O. Box 1940, Jackson Hole, Wyo. 83001.
</P>
<P>
   Other dog-sled adventures are available at Grand Targhee, (800)
827-4433; $115 for an adult.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PARKS VIA SNOWCOACH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1968 yellow Bombadier snowcoach is not a quiet nor peaceful
ride with its clackety-clack skis and tank-style tracks, but it is
a guaranteed sightseeing route in Yellowstone Park in winter if you
don't cross-country ski.
</P>
<P>
   For $100 a person, the interpretive tour leaves Flagg Ranch just
south of Yellowstone's South Gate at 8 a.m. with stops at Moose
Falls, Tom Thumb Geyser Basin and views of even more wildlife. It's
a round trip totalling 80 miles.
</P>
<P>
   As you and nine others make your way through the park at a top
speed of 35 mph, you find yourself waving at snowmobilers on the
road or sitting within your own cocoon of silence as you get a
glimmer of Mother Nature's artistry in winter _ snowy ermine drapes
on the evergreens and frozen ``statues'' beside the waterfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked into unlikely places are hard-to-spot creatures such as
bison waiting until the warm days of spring.
</P>
<P>
   Time is of the essence as you near Old Faithful, since the
geyser now spouts on a less predictable schedule. When the coach
arrives, head for the geyser, since you'll get only one chance per
tour to see it erupt.
</P>
<P>
   To study Jackson Hole's wildlife more closely, try Elderhostel
programs at Targhee Institute. They stress topics such as wildlife
tracking and snow travel. The price for the week is $400, including
meals.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact Elderhostel Inc. at (877)
426-8056.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE WALL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Wapiti Gallery at the National Museum of Wildlife Art is an
interpretive center for the National Elk Refuge. This jewel is
tucked into a jagged landscape and showcases more than 100 artists'
impressions of North American animals in its permanent collection.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling exhibits each year expand on Western and wildlife
themes. Admission is $5 for seniors, $1 off the regular price. For
more information, call (307) 733-5771.
</P>
<P>
   There's lots to see and do in Jackson _ from art galleries and
shops, to the Cowboy Bar, where you can climb into a saddle aboard
the bar stool to sip your beverage. Energetic types can try ice
skating ($5), hot-air balloon rides ($185) or dinner sleigh rides
in the moonlight (about $50). So what if you don't do snow, you can
still do Jackson in winter.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you DO do snow, there are senior ski values to
explore. A broad range of special packages throughout Jackson Hole
are available through Central Reservations, (800) 443-6931. Call
the Jackson Chamber of Commerce at (307) 733-3316 to get your copy
of the area's ski and vacation planner.
 &UR; ----- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
</P>
<P>
   The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
