<HEADER>
A0295 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOTELS-WITH-PERKS-TRA     12-09 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTELS-WITH-PERKS-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUR ROOM IS READY ... 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact Nirdi Relis at (212) 499-3333; fax
(212) 499-3382.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EVERETT POTTER &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when a hotel could get away with simply
offering a room for the night. In an ongoing attempt to attract
guests, many hotels have added special services that go way beyond
overnight shoeshines and in-room coffee makers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hilton Hotels &LR;  (9336 Civic Center Drive, Beverly Hills, Calif.
90210; 800-HILTONS) has been a leader in adapting rooms to better
suit guests.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, they introduced Sleep-Tight Rooms, which feature
blackout drapes, a light box to help adjust circadian rhythms and
noise machines to block out unwanted sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company is testing 16 Health-Fit Rooms and Stress-Less
Rooms in nine properties, including the Hilton Chicago O'Hare
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The Health-Fit Rooms come with a Reebok Cross Conditioning
System, an SPRI Xertube for in-room exercises as well as a
20-minute in-room workout plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Stress-Less Rooms boast an in-room fountain to provide
soothing noises, a Massaging Seat Topper seat pad to massage the
body and a Living Yoga beginner's yoga video, among other
amenities.
</P>
<P>
   New York City's chic  &UR; Soho Grand Hotel &LR;  (310 West Broadway, New
York, N.Y. 10013; 800-965-3000) is owned and operated by Hartz
Mountain Industries. Not surprisingly, dogs and cats are not only
welcome but are catered to with an in-room menu.
</P>
<P>
   A bowl of dry dog food with a bowl of water is $10, a full-body
pillow is $20 while assorted toys are $8 for three toys.
</P>
<P>
   Cat owners can rent a litter pan with liner for $10 per day, and
dog-walking and cat visitations can be arranged. For guests who
arrive without a pet but would like one, a goldfish is delivered to
their room.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast is considered to be the most important meal of the
day, so Norma's, the new restaurant at  &UR; Le Parker Meridien &LR;  (118
West 57th St., New York, N.Y. 10019; 800-543-4300), serves it all
day long.
</P>
<P>
   Chef David Rangel provides Molten Chocolate French Toast with
Pineapple Chutney in addition to Krispy Kreme Donuts, H&AMP;H Bagels
and McCann's Irish Oatmeal.
</P>
<P>
   At  &UR; The Mark Hotel &LR;  (25 E.77th St., New York, N.Y. 10021;
800-THE-MARK) on New York City's Upper East Side, there's a free
shuttle twice a morning downtown to Wall Street and a shuttle to
the theater district on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Complimentary cellular-phone rental with call forwarding is
available, with per-minute charges billed at $1.75.
</P>
<P>
   For skiers who need to be pampered, Aspen's  &UR; Little Nell &LR;  (675
E. Durant St., Aspen, Colo., 81611; 888-THE NELL) boasts a ski
concierge to store and warm skiers' boots and have guests' skis
ready the next morning. They can warm up with free coffee cake and
hot chocolate before taking what the hotel says are just 17 steps
to the Aspen Mountain gondola.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimpton Hotel Group, which has 24 hotels in San Francisco,
Seattle, Portland, Tacoma, Denver and Chicago, is known for their
innovative design and guest amenities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at the  &UR; Hotel Monaco Denver &LR;  (1717 Champa St.,
Denver, Colo. 80202; 800-397-5380) there are guest rooms set aside
for tall guests. These are high-ceilinged rooms with 90-inch-long
beds and raised showerheads. A pet-friendly hotel, the Monaco also
provides guests with a pet goldfish during their stay.
</P>
<P>
   Bemoaning the poor quality of airline food,  &UR; The Peninsula
Beverly Hills &LR;  (9882 Santa Monica Blvd., Beverly Hills, Calif.
90212; 800-462-7899) offers a Pen-Air In-flight Menu that's in the
shape of an airline ticket. It's a selection of food to-go from the
hotel's kitchen that's meant to be consumed on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The Peninsula's club sandwich is $11.50 while a chocolate walnut
brownie is $5.25.
</P>
<P>
   At the  &UR; Four Seasons Resort and Club &LR;  in Dallas at Las Colinas
(4150 North MacArthur Blvd., Irving, Texas, 75038; 800-332-3442),
guests are offered complimentary tai chi, yoga and meditation
classes as well as workout clothes and tennis shoes in case they
forget their own.
</P>
<P>
   Fussy sleepers will be happy to hear that the first menu they'll
see upon arrival at  &UR; Cotton House &LR;  (Mustique, W.I. 800-826-2809) on
the Caribbean island of Mustique is a pillow menu. There are nine
free choices, including a Snore Stoppers Pillow, a Maternity Pillow
and a Bed Rest Pillow ideal for reading in bed.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Schrager, who runs such chic hotel properties as the
Royalton, Morgans and the Paramount in New York City; the Delano in
Miami's South Beach; and the Mondrian in Los Angeles, has carefully
chosen the room amenities in his hotels.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at the  &UR; Mondrian &LR;  (8400 Sunset Blvd., West
Hollywood, Calif., 90069; 323-650-8999) guests will find a minibar
that includes what the hotel calls an Intimacy Kit featuring two
condoms, lubricant and a towelette. The price? $11.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Colorado's  &UR; Best Western Movie Manor Inn &LR;  (2830 W. US
160, Monte Vista, Colo., 81144; 800-771-9468) has the ultimate
in-room movie. The hotel, 100 miles west of Pueblo, provides
virtually every guest with complimentary access to a first-run
movie at the Star Drive-In Movie Theater _ without leaving their
room.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of the hotel's guest rooms have picture windows
that face the movie screen, and there's a speaker next to the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Movies are shown nightly during the summer and on weekends
during the spring and fall. (Popcorn is extra!)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance travel
writer.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
