<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0319 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     12-09 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Dec. 9, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   POWER-OUTAGE (San Francisco) _ Plunged into a six-hour power
outage, San Francisco's city officials launched a well-rehearsed
plan to maintain vital emergency, medical and transportation
services. Many city officials saw the episode as an almost welcome
test run for a big quake or other major disaster. By CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   POWER-TALES (San Francisco) _ For better or worse, people who
live, work or shop in San Francisco learned firsthand Tuesday just
how much they depend on electrical power. The prolonged blackout
caused a number of inconveniences, discoveries, bright ideas, bad
hair days, missed appointments and excuses for drinking. By RAY
DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   POWER-ERROR (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco blackout began
when a Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co. worker forgot to do something
very elementary _ remove a grounding wire before restarting the
power. ``Grounding is a pretty basic procedure,'' said Carl
Bellone, PG&AMP;E's director of distribution operations. ``It's as
basic as it gets.'' By JULIE CHAO, ERIN McCORMICK, ELIZABETH
FERNANDEZ and ANASTASIA HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   POWER-BATTERIES (San Francisco) _ San Francisco's information
revolution went to battery power Tuesday morning, showing just how
dependent our communication-rich lifestyles are on the electric
grid. The outage also led some to believe they had witnessed a
preview of the much-ballyhooed Y2K computer meltdown. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   POWER-AIRPORT (San Francisco) _ Nobody was going anywhere.
Planes couldn't take off. Passengers couldn't check in. Baggage
couldn't be picked up. And there wasn't a caffe latte or toasted
bagel to be had for any price. At San Francisco International
Airport Tuesday, when the lights went out, the world stood still.
By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   WWI-VETS (San Antonio) _ Three San Antonio area veterans were
young men when they fought on French soil during the Great War.
Now, 80 years later, a grateful French government is honoring them
and other allied veterans with France's highest decoration. By
CARMINA DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPLANE-SAFETY (Albany, N.Y.) _ Contrary to a nationwide
decrease in near midair airplane collisions, the number of
high-altitude close calls over New York state has doubled since
last year, according to the Federal Aviation Administration. Two
harrowing incidents in the past week brought talk of near midair
collisions, or NMACs, into sharp focus. By PAUL ZIELBAUER.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-DUST (San Francisco) _ The sky is falling _ literally _ in
the form of dust, dropping to Earth from outer space. This rain of
particles may vary in cycles, periodically dimming sunlight and
cooling Earth. The variations may partly trigger ice ages every
100,000 years or so, some scientists think. Others are skeptical.
By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   SAMARITAN-BILL (Sacramento, Calif.) _ The bathroom rape and
murder of a 7-year-old girl, a crime seen in progress but not
reported by UC-Berkeley student David Cash, has prompted three
lawmakers to introduce ``good Samaritan'' laws requiring people to
report assaults they may witness. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   OLDEST-ARSENAL (Watervliet, N.Y.) _ The U.S. Army's oldest
arsenal is in discussions with defense contractors about taking
over some of its operations. By BOB GARDINIER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RETIREMENT-SAVINGS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Financial planners and money
managers say this year's topsy-turvey stock market may be a
blessing in disguise. They say people can learn valuable, lasting
lessons about how to handle their retirement planning from the ups
and downs. We offer some retirement-planning tips for weathering
the best and worst of times. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   BOFA (San Francisco) _ Two U.S. senators have asked the head of
the newly merged North Carolina-based Bank of America to
demonstrate its commitment to serving California. Sen. Barbara
Boxer, said the resignation of BankAmerica's former CEO David
Coulter was ``highly troubling.'' She also referred to the
resignation in the past two months of several top women executives.
By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-GIFTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The majority of American
households will buy at least one electronic item for the season,
according to the Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association, a
trade group based in Arlington, Va. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TAVERN-CHEF (New York) _ It's just before noon on a recent
Tuesday and the kitchen at Tavern on the Green appears ready for
battle. The kitchen's commander-in-chief, Sam Hazen, is decidedly
down to earth despite his high-profile position. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-HENDERSON (Oakland, Calif.) _ Rickey Henderson could be an
Oakland Athletic again, even if it is only as a slab of bronze in
Cooperstown, N.Y. Let's put it this way, though. Neither
possibility is very likely, and given the latest bum's rush he has
been given, neither should be. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ This was the third wake-up call
in a week, and this one was without coffee. God is telling us
something, something about stocking up on batteries, food, bottled
water and a camp stove to make our own joe. Stock up at the ATM
too, because the forces of darkness at PG&AMP;E control our cash. By
ROB MORSE.
</P>
