<HEADLINE>
THINKING DIFFERENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a Christmas story for you: A cynical journalist, given to
frequent jibes at the expense of Apple Computer Inc., adopts an
Apple iMac computer. Against his will, he's delighted by its
simplicity, thrilled by its impressive performance, moved by its
ineffable cuteness. The journalist becomes a new man _ witty, warm,
filled with love for all mankind except for that wretch Bill Gates.
He has learned to think different.
</P>
<P>
   Well, life's not that simple _ and neither am I. It'll take more
than the iMac to make a convert of me.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not warming up for a bout of Mac-bashing. The iMac has
served me well for the past two months. It's like at first sight.
Feast your eyes on the monitor: a 15-incher that looks even bigger,
thanks to its crisp text display and opulent color reproduction.
The iMac also feels good; its keyboard is the most comfortable I've
ever used. It's almost good enough to atone for the iMac's clumsy
mouse.
</P>
<P>
   I still resent the iMac's lack of a floppy drive, but I use the
Globe's internal network to move files to a Mac in our graphics
department, which has an Iomega Zip drive. I've got a Zip plugged
into a PC at home. Windows machines will only accept PC-formatted
disks, but Macs read and write to PC disks without a qualm. So I
can easily tote my files home.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, I suspect the months of griping over this issue
secretly pleased Apple execs. Otherwise, more people might notice
that the iMac is still just another Macintosh, running Apple's
aging operating system. Five years ago, the Mac OS was much better
than anything offered by Microsoft. Not any more.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, I found myself wishing the Mac did things the
way Windows does. Of course, much of this is a matter of taste, or
lack thereof. For instance, I like the way Windows uses a
two-button mouse, so you can use many commands merely by clicking
the right mouse button. I resent the Mac's one-button mouse; others
like its simplicity. It's a judgment call.
</P>
<P>
   Other Mac OS features are flaws, pure and simple. At first,
programs would often refuse to run because of lack of memory. It
seemed 32 megabytes was not enough, even though my PC cruised along
on the same amount. But Windows machines make better use of
``virtual memory,'' a system that lets a computer use blank hard
drive space as imitation memory chips. Windows machines
automatically set the right amount of virtual memory. But on the
``easy-to-use'' Mac, you set virtual memory by hand. Too little,
and programs died. Too much, and they ran so slowly they might as
well be dead.
</P>
<P>
   I bought RAM Doubler from Connectix Corp., a $50 program that
fixed the problem. Then some Apple technicians said the new Mac OS
8.5 and a little more fiddling would do the trick. It did. Still,
why so much trouble over a feature most PC users never even think
about?
</P>
<P>
   Even now, with my iMac nicely tuned up, I can find no compelling
reason to prefer it to a PC. This may change next year, when Apple
unleashes Mac OS X, a promising operating system upgrade based on a
version of the advanced Unix operating system.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier incarnation, OS X was named Rhapsody, and was to
have been available in a version for PCs. That plan was scrapped
last year, so that Apple could focus on its core market, the key to
its survival. By doing this, Apple has missed an immense
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the growing popularity of the Linux operating system,
with 7 million to 10 million users worldwide. It's proof that
people long for Windows alternatives. But why aren't they choosing
Mac OS? In some ways, it's better than Linux; it's certainly easier
to use.
</P>
<P>
   But Linux has one vast advantage. It runs on anything _ Macs,
PCs, even pocket-size Palm Pilots. Opt for Linux, and a universe of
hardware platforms is open to you. Choose the Mac OS, and you have
to buy a Mac _ and lose out on the plunging prices and rapid
innovation found in the PC hardware market.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac, with its blue-green shell, is a glowing metaphor of
Apple's problem. It's different all right _ like a lovely beast
that evolved in isolation on the Galapagos Islands, and can't
thrive anywhere else. But I've no intention of moving to the
Macintosh Archipelago, no matter how pretty the computers are
there.
</P>
<P>
   (E-mail Hiawatha Bray at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-03-98 1340EST &QL;
</P>
