<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-SENSITIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, A PLACE TO ASK QUESTIONS THAT AREN'T POLITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PATTI HARTIGAN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Why do white people smell like wet dogs when they come out of
the rain?'' asks Cass in Detroit. ``Why do black folks get agitated
when they see the Confederate flag?'' asks Wallace in Suwanee, Ga.
``Why do gay men feel they have to sound gay?'' asks Derek K. in
Duluth, Minn. ``Why do Asian women seem to date more white men than
Asian men?'' asks Victor in Secaucus, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Why, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   These aren't exactly the kinds of questions you'd overhear in
casual conversation at a crowded train station or in the grocery
checkout aisle. They're the kinds of things an adult might ponder
in private, but only a child would blurt out in a public place. But
they're also whispers on the Web, real questions posted in a
virtual forum where folks are encouraged to seek answers to
questions they'd be too embarrassed to pose in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing fancy or glamorous about this Web site. It's
simply called ``Y? The National Forum on People's Differences.'' It
doesn't offer gee-whiz plug-ins, real-time audio, or images that
gyrate with each click of your mouse. It's just simple text, page
after page of questions typed by users worldwide, from Delhi to
Duluth. And frankly, it's one of the most inventive uses of a
technology that is too often dismissed as a glorified toy or a
gigantic shopping mall. The Web site doesn't make any money, but it
might make the world a better place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y?'' is the brainchild of one Phillip J. Milano, a workaday
newspaper editor for the Florida Times-Union in Jacksonville.
Milano, 36, is a self-described ``white kid'' who grew up in the
posh suburb of Glen Ellyn, Ill. ``It was a pretty segregated place,
and I didn't have a lot of contact with too many people,'' Milano
recalls. ``There was one black kid in my high school class.'' The
fifth son of a metallurgical engineer and a homemaker, Milano was
always encouraged to ask questions _ on music or politics or art or
diversity. He was taught that curiosity is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   When he became an editor, he launched a project called the
National Diversity Newspaper Job Bank, an on-line clearinghouse for
positions at newspapers. Then last fall, he had a simple idea. What
if he started a Web site where folks could ask painfully
embarrassing questions in a safe, anonymous environment? What if he
asked others to answer those questions? He set up the computer in
his den, signed up for a Web address (www.yforum.com), and launched
the forum.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Milano wasn't sure it would work. Heck, he wasn't even
sure it was necessary. Are people really that isolated? But then
the questions started to trickle in, and folks started posting
responses. Then a startling query came across his screen: ``What
would take place during a typical weeknight in a black family?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a woman in Philadelphia who was so far removed from
other groups that she couldn't even imagine what it would be like
to live in a black household,'' Milano recalls. ``I went running to
my wife and said, `This is going to work.'''
</P>
<P>
   And it has worked. This low-tech site gets about 400,000 hits a
month, and has a loyal group of followers who check in daily, the
same way a sports fanatic turns to the ESPN Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Clardy, an industrial engineer for Ford Motor Co. who
lives in Southfield, Mich., is one of those regulars. A single
mother who serves on Ford's diversity council and is a member of
its gay and lesbian employee group, she frequently posts answers to
questions about sexuality. ``Some of the questions really surprise
me,'' she says. ``I've never seen so many people who seem to think
other people smell funny. Where on earth do they get these ideas?''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that people have these ideas is the very reason Y?
Forum works. This isn't Oprah, where audience members do the
talk-show version of ``We Are the World.'' Nor is it one of those
canned ``town meetings'' on race, where the dialogue is as natural
as a snowman in Bali. The dialogue here can make your face turn
red, but it's also refreshingly honest.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its success, the Y? Forum hasn't been able to attract
many sponsors. Milano pays for the site and works on it late at
night, when his three children are asleep. That might change soon,
though. Milano just forged a partnership with a startup interactive
entertainment outfit called EnterMedia Network Co.; together,
they're going to launch a live version of the Y? Forum that starts
preproduction next week and launches in January. It will be a kind
of talk radio on the Web, where a panel will discuss diversity
issues in real time and users can participate in chat rooms and
fire off questions for the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there's nothing new about the concept of live chat on
line. But this isn't idle chatter. It's vital stuff. The question
here isn't why this forum exists. The question is simply, why did
it take so long for someone to think of it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_____ &QC;  It's comforting to know that people like Milano are using
the Net to ask important questions. But what about Monica? What
would take place during a typical weeknight in her household?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was only a matter of time before someone launched the
``first full-scale Web biography'' of Lewinsky. Earlier this week,
a British on-line publisher called Atlantic Productions was hyping
``Monica: Behind the Myth,'' an on-line book about our own Helen of
the Oval Office. For about 3 British pounds (about $1.65), browsers
can see home movie footage of Lewinsky, and scroll through pictures
from her ``best friend's photo album.'' As a matter of principle,
the only pounds we're interested in losing are the ones we gained
at the dinner table yesterday, so we skipped the salacious details.
But inquiring minds can check it out at www.atlantpro.demon.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
______ &QC;  Search of the week. Monica scribblings aside, where do you
find real books on-line? A good place to start is at the Internet
Public Library (www.ipl.org), an extremely helpful site run by
librarians at the University of Michigan's School of Information.
It starts with this premise: ``The Internet is a mess. Since nobody
runs it, that's no surprise. There are a lot of interesting,
worthwhile, and valuable things out there _ and a lot that are a
complete waste of time.'' Run by librarians, the site sifts through
the dreck and suggests useful places to help folks find useful
information. In addition to exhaustive reference materials, it also
has links to more than 7,700 books on line, featuring the full
texts of classic and contemporary fiction and nonfiction. There's
no time like a holiday weekend to check out what people are saying
about race at the Y? Forum and then curl up at your computer and
scroll through, say, ``Great Expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-03-98 1331EST &QL;
</P>
