 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Some Electronic Holiday Products Are So Hot This Year, They're
Cool  
 By David Einstein   
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some holiday gifts are so hot, they're cool.
</P>
<P>
   We took a look at the computers and related electronics
available this year and picked out a few items that stand out for
their style and performance. Price also was a consideration _ we
didn't include anything beyond the means of the average
computer-geek consumer.
</P>
<P>
   The following items share one thing in common: They all contain
cutting-edge technology that would make them the star attraction of
the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   It's Absolutely Clear
</P>
<P>
   First up is a personal computer monitor unlike any you've seen
before. The ViewSonic VPD150 is one of the new generation of ``flat
panel'' displays that have been under development for years. It's
got a full 15-inch screen, it's just 3 inches deep, and it takes up
almost no space on your desk. It pivots for either landscape
(horizontal) or portrait (vertical) mode. The picture quality is
stunning, offering up to 1,024 x 768 pixels of sharp resolution.
And to top it off, it includes integrated speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Although initially aimed at medical, industrial and government
applications, it would look right at home in a state-of-the-art
home office.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manufacturer:  &LR; ViewSonic (www.viewsonic.com)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Price:  &LR; $995
</P>
<P>
   Printing With Style
</P>
<P>
   Color inkjet printers have become so good that they can
faithfully reproduce photographs. And the cream of this year's crop
is the Epson Stylus Color 640. It combines high-end performance
with a low price that's hard to beat. You get 1,440 x 720 dots per
inch for sharp images, and photo quality when you use special
photographic paper.
</P>
<P>
   The printer comes with a bundle of respectable software,
including Adobe PhotoDeluxe, American Greetings Creatacard and
Broderbund's Print Shop Premiere Edition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manufacturer: &LR;  Epson (www.epson.com)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Price:  &LR; $199
</P>
<P>
   Picture Perfect
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest gifts this holiday season is sure to be
digital cameras, which are rapidly becoming more of a challenge to
traditional cameras in performance while at the same time getting
less expensive. There are several nifty models to choose from, but
one that tops a lot of lists is the Kodak Digital Science DC260.
</P>
<P>
   This little gem combines point-and-shoot ease with exceptional
image quality _ up to 1,536 x 1024 pixels, which is enough for a
super-sharp 8-by-10-inch photo.
</P>
<P>
   The camera has autofocus and a 6X zoom. It also lets you
override the automatic controls for lighting and focus, in case you
want to use it like a traditional camera and get really creative.
</P>
<P>
   You can transfer photos from the camera to your PC using a USB
connector or infrared signal. Or you can display the photos right
on your TV.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manufacturer: &LR;  Kodak (www.kodak.com)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Price: &LR;  $899
</P>
<P>
   A PC for Under $400
</P>
<P>
   Powerful PCs have never been more affordable, and leading the
pack is the new Etower from eMachines. For $399, you get a Cyrix
266 megahertz chip, 32 megabytes of RAM, a 2.1 gigabyte hard drive,
a 24x CD-ROM drive and a 56K modem. For an additional $100, you can
add a 14-inch monitor. This isn't some kind of toy. It's a fully
configured system that's more than powerful enough for word
processing, home finances and surfing the Web. And with its ATI
Rage graphics, it's even good enough for many video games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manufacturer: &LR;  eMachines (www.e4me.com)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Price: &LR;  $399 ($499 for a model with a 300 MHz Intel Celeron
chip and a 3.2 gig hard drive)
</P>
<P>
   Lean Mean Machine
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to laptop computers, thin is in, and no model
typifies the new lightweight trend better than the Sharp Actius
A150 UltraLight Notebook PC. Its 3-pound, 1-inch-thick magnesium
case packs everything you'd expect from a great sub-notebook _
except the high-end price. It comes with a 266 MHz Pentium MMX
chip, 64 megs of memory, a 4.3 GB hard drive and a 56K modem. A 20x
external CD-ROM drive is optional.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, the A150 has an 11.3-inch active matrix display
that provides a beautiful 800 x 600 picture. It's the biggest,
brightest display in its class.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manufacturer:  &LR; Sharp (www.sharp-usa.com)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Price: &LR;  $2,299
</P>
<P>
   Pilot Still No.1
</P>
<P>
   This year has witnessed an invasion of personal digital
assistants _ handheld devices for keeping track of your schedule
and contacts. But nobody has been able to dethrone the PalmPilot
and its successor, the Palm III. Less than 5 inches tall and
weighing just 6 ounces, the Palm III can hold 6,000 addresses, five
years' worth of appointments, 1,500 memos and 200 e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a snap to use. It's fast, goes a long time on a set of
two AAA batteries and its handwriting recognition technology lets
you print right onto the screen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manufacturer:  &LR; 3Com (www.palm.com)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Price:  &LR; $369 ($249 for the PalmPilot Professional, a slightly
less robust model)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-02-98 2143EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
