 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Road to telecommuting more likely just a cow path 
By Bill Husted  
c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I am telecommuting today. Instead of sitting behind my
two work computers _ a G3 Macintosh and a Pentium II PC _ that are
connected to a high-speed data line and all the various news
services that pump information into any modern newspaper, I have my
feet propped up on my desk in a spare bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   The cat is curled up in the sunshine nearby, and I am
barefooted.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommuting is fine for what I am doing at this moment:
writing a column. And if that were all I did in my newspaper job,
there would be no reason to trek into the office at all, unless
someone were retiring and chocolate cake were being served.
</P>
<P>
   But because my job involves so many different things _
discussing stories with reporters who cover technology, sometimes
talking to readers with a question and often pacing around waiting
for a reporter's story to edit _ telecommuting isn't a real
substitute for being there.
</P>
<P>
   In my old-fogey opinion, at least, that daily commute in your
car is unlikely to be replaced _ on a day-to-day basis at least _
with a cyber-office at home.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you picture regular commuting as driving along the
interstate in a modern automobile, this telecommuting stuff amounts
to pedaling to work on a rickety bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder if _ despite the appeal of working from home _ it would
work for most folks I know. Among my friends are physicians who
would be hard-pressed to work in a cyber sort of way, a fellow who
installs and maintains commercial roofs (I can't picture him
pouring on an extra layer of tar this way, no matter how fast the
Internet connection) and several graduate students who spend their
days arguing in class. Typing out messages might work for them, but
it sure wouldn't work as well.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that I have spoken before at telecommuting
conferences and certainly despite the fact I like the notion that _
in just a moment or two _ I'll be able to eat some of my sister's
famous Thanksgiving fruit salad and eat it here at my desk, I have
real doubts that telecommuting represents an important future in
the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   It is a lot like wrapping a leaking radiator hose with duct tape
_ it works better than nothing but isn't a permanent solution. So
today _ forced to stay home by a stomach that is riding some kind
of internal roller coaster _ I'm glad I can sit here with the cat.
And I'm sure the reporters I edit are happy I am not pacing about
their desk, trying to look unconcerned as I wait for their stories.
</P>
<P>
   But there are so many things _ little and big _ I can't do
today. And I won't be able to see how fast the other guy is typing,
or spend a moment to ask about his Thanksgiving. The real problem
isn't goofing off _ I'm typing as fast as I can _ but work without
the human touch is a pretty bland sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   Look, there are plenty of folks who disagree, and maybe my
telecommuting today represents some real future. But I'm glad to
tell you what I think anyway. With all the voices for change and
all those eloquent people who explain how technology will make life
better, it is good to have one lonely voice here in the
cyber-wilderness who understands the value of being a human in a
cyber world.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-07-98 0959EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
