<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Internet-stock investing requires love of risk  
 By Arthur M. Louis   
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until three months ago, you probably never heard of eBay, a
little San Jose company that maintains an online flea market where
people can trade things like Beanie Babies, firearms and
aphrodisiacs over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, if you haven't heard of eBay, you probably haven't heard
of Monica Lewinsky either.
</P>
<P>
   EBay has become the quintessential Internet stock. Although the
company boasts scant revenues and earnings, its stock market value
is a staggering $7 billion. The company went public on September 24
at $18 per share and closed Monday at $174.25.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the latest installment of the Great Tulip Craze.
</P>
<P>
   Speculators have been making huge profits this year on
practically any company that promises to exploit the commercial
potential of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Turner, president of Pring Turner Capital in San Ramon, says
today's market reminds him of the late 1960s, when everyone was
looking for the next Xerox. ``If a company's name had an `x' in it,
you bought it. Now, `x' has become `dot com.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If all the ruckus, and those easy profits, tempt you to plunge
into these stocks yourself, you're only human. But don't do it
unless you have money to burn and are willing to accept huge risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later, this mania will end _ like all other manias _
with a really stiff correction,'' warns Tony O'Bryan, a technical
analyst with A.G. Edwards &AMP; Son in St. Louis. ``It will be across
the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Wall Streeters acknowledge that the Internet already ranks
among the greatest technological revolutions in history. And they
expect companies that effectively exploit the Net's commercial
potential to succeed beyond the dreams of avarice.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody can be certain which companies will succeed and which
will fail. What's more, the market prices of virtually all Internet
stocks have risen so sharply that few, if any, still look like good
buys.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question about the future of the Internet _ it's
huge,'' says Will Weinstein, head of Genesis Merchant Group
Securities in San Francisco. ``But the prices of these stocks today
are just an outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Internet stocks can't be evaluated by traditional means.
Price-earnings ratios are meaningless in most cases, because few
Internet companies are profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Even some Internet issues that analysts include among the
``first tier'' _ the most likely to succeed _ are still losing
money.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are Santa Clara's Yahoo, which maintains an immensely
popular search engine, and Amazon.com, of Seattle, the dominant
Internet book retailer.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, the Virginia Internet service provider that is
generally considered tops among the first-tier companies, eked out
a small profit in the fiscal year ended in June after suffering a
big loss the year before.
</P>
<P>
   People who buy these and other Internet stocks are betting on
the Net in general, and on promising concepts in particular.
</P>
<P>
   But how does one evaluate a concept? Companies that look
promising today could be dead and gone two years from now.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of earnings, analysts must look at other ratios.
For example, they are comparing the total market value of a
company's stock to its revenues, or its cash flow, or the number of
daily hits on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon has lately been selling for more than 20 times revenues.
AOL, now that it is profitable, sells at an absurdly high 350 or so
times earnings, but only about 13 times revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Those price-to-revenues ratios don't seem so high considering
that Microsoft, a much larger company, currently trades at around
20 times revenues. Can Amazon and AOL grow faster than Microsoft
from here on? Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't necessarily warn people away from all Internet
stocks, even at these levels,'' says Jessica Martin-Rice, an
analyst with Chicago's Driehaus Capital Management. Driehaus
pioneered momentum investing, which involves buying stocks that are
moving up rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Investors might want to at least hesitate before buying Yahoo,
which is trading at an eyebrow-raising 120 times revenues, or eBay,
now selling for around 300 times revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Internet stocks can go down as well as up.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's Books-a-Million, until two weeks ago a little-known
chain of retail bookstores in the Southeast, announced on November
25 that it would sell books on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Its stock rose from $4.38 the day before the announcement to $47
three market sessions later.
</P>
<P>
   But investors had second thoughts after the Wall Street Journal
reported that the company's executives were selling shares like
crazy at the lofty new levels. Books-a-Million closed Monay on
Nasdaq at $14.94.
</P>
<P>
   As Internet stocks have soared, many institutional investors
that bought them at much lower prices have either sold them or
stopped buying.
</P>
<P>
   Even some momentum investors are getting scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a lot of money on Internet stocks we've held for a
long time, but now things are getting crazy,'' says Jamie Atwell,
head of Nasdaq trading with Nicholas-Applegate Capital Management
in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Wrona, co-manager of the PBHG Tech Fund, sold a small
holding in eBay recently. ``We bought it at the time it came out,
and even then it was expensive, but within the realm of reason,''
he says. ``Now it's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   With institutions largely on the sidelines, the market for
Internet stocks has lately been dominated by day traders _
individuals who trade in and out of stocks many times per week and
even per day. Appropriately enough, many of them trade on the
Internet itself, through online brokerage sites.
</P>
<P>
   The day traders typically trade an average of only a few hundred
shares at a time, compared to the thousands of shares that an
institution might buy or sell in a single trade. But there are so
many day traders trading so frenetically that the total mounts
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   On one recent market day, for example, 8.2 million shares of
Books-a-Million changed hands. The average trade was 437 shares, or
less than $12,000 worth.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, the trading volume of General Electric, an
institutional favorite, was 4.8 million shares. The average trade
was 1,171 shares, worth more than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Spewing out orders like so many tommy-gun slugs, the day traders
have helped push the turnover in eBay stock to more than 5 million
shares per day five times in the past seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty amazing considering that eBay's float _ the number
of shares held by the public, rather than by management and other
insiders _ is only 3.5 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Trading in Internet stocks may simmer down a bit now that many
online brokers are tightening the rules for investors buying these
stocks on margin.
</P>
<P>
   Ameritrade, DLJ Direct, E-Trade, Charles Schwab, Suretrade and
Waterhouse, among others, recently increased the so-called
maintenance requirements for Internet stocks bought on margin, or
with some borrowed money.
</P>
<P>
   They have done this because they fear the stocks will plummet,
causing investors to default on their debts.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage firms routinely reassess their margin requirements for
individual stocks that become volatile, but they rarely crack down
on an entire industry at once.
</P>
<P>
   Customers with margin accounts can buy stocks with up to 50
percent margin _ meaning that half the price is paid with the
buyer's own money and the other half with money borrowed from the
broker.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, brokers require investors to hold cash or un-margined
securities in their accounts with a total value equal to at least
30 percent of the value of the margined stocks in the account.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the brokers have boosted the maintenance
requirement to between 40 percent and 100 percent for certain
Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Schwab boosted its maintenance requirement to 50
percent from 35 percent on 22 Internet stocks starting last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``To investors that want to drive these stocks, we're saying you
have to wear seat belts,'' says Schwab spokesman Tom Taggart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-07-98 2148EST &QL;
</P>
