<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 How to Get Your Web Site in the Limelight  
 By Peter Sinton   
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Question: &LR;  I am a small e-commerce business owner trying to
grow my business online. How can I promote it, the inexpensive way,
besides getting listed in the search engine?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Getting your name listed on search engines such as
Yahoo and Excite is definitely a place to start. It can help spread
word of your business and requires simply filling out a form at
each site. But so many businesses are lining for free references
that it might take days or weeks to get listed.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say it is important to use all means available _ online
and off _ to promote an e-commerce business.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco consultant Mitchell Friedman, who teaches college
courses about public relations on the Internet, says this includes
setting up links to your site from other sites; identifying
newsgroups, forums, chat rooms and other appropriate venues to
promote your venture; and using mailing lists to inform potential
customers via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman recommends several Web sites: You can locate
appropriate mailing lists at www.liszt.com, create a free mailing
list of your own at www.listbot.com, discover news groups at
www.dejanews.com, find Web forums at www.forumone.com and create
your own forum by visiting www.delphi.com.
</P>
<P>
   America Online and CompuServe also offer many forums that might
be places to discuss your work. However, you need to subscribe to
these proprietary services to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Offline, you should mention your Web site in all printed
materials (such as business cards, brochures, letterhead,
advertising, invoices and phone directory listings) and any other
ways you reach prospects, including voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   Relocation Checklist
</P>
<P>
   Q: My two partners and I have a technology consulting business
that we have been able to run out of a live/work space in the
Mission District. We recently agreed to lease actual office space
and wonder if there is some sort of checklist to help a company
plan its move?
</P>
<P>
   A: There isn't the same standard checklist for businesses
planning to take off for a new location. Beyond obvious chores like
getting a new phone lines and letterhead and changing your mailing
address, San Francisco's Burr, Pilger &AMP; Mayer accounting and
consulting firm has some suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   You might start by analyzing your physical space requirements.
Specifically, what are your current needs? Is there room for future
growth? Do you want to be a subtenant or have one?
</P>
<P>
   Landlord-tenant negotiations can be especially complex, says
Jenise Gaskin, a Burr, Pilger partner. ``Three years ago, there was
plenty of space available and tenants were able to negotiate all
sorts of improvements,'' she said. ``Now that's much harder so
there are plenty of hidden costs if you have to pay for walls or
put in computer wiring.''
</P>
<P>
   It is important to ask whether tenant improvements are included
in the lease. Can you put the improvements out to bid, or are you
required to use a specified contractor? What about
repair/maintenance costs for your space and common areas?
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other issues:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Moving arrangements &LR; . Do you have to use union or nonunion
movers? When can you move in? During business hours? Should you get
damage insurance?
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Utilities. &LR;  What is covered in the lease and what is
considered ``extra?'' How is the building metered for public
utilities?Is each space metered separately? Is the building
air-conditioned, and if so, what are the hours of operation?
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Insurance. &LR;  What is a tenant's liability? Check the lease for
minimum coverage required by landlord. You also are required to get
Workers' Compensation insurance for any workers and might consider
comprehensive general liability, nonowned auto liability, fire and
theft property loss, earthquake damage, business interruption, and
errors and omissions coverage.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Parking and storage. &LR;  What is available and what are the
costs?
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Options &LR; . Can you get options for additional space or first
right of refusal for upcoming space in the building? Can you get an
option for a lease extension?
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Real estate taxes &LR; . If taxes and operating costs increase over
time, what is considered the ``base year?'' Is there an adjustment
if the building is not fully occupied?
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Rules and regulations. &LR;  What sort of security and safety
training does the building owner provide? How often are fire drills
conducted? What are the procedures for after-hour arrivals and
departures, and delivery of packages? How does the janitorial
service operate? Are there sign requirements or restrictions? Does
the building regularly perform air quality testing and what are the
results?
</P>
<P>
   If you are moving, you probably need new equipment such as
phones, answering and/or paging service, fax and copy machine,
computers and network cabling, postage meter and furniture. You can
rent, lease or buy.
</P>
<P>
   If you are hiring more employees, you should check the laws for
a company your size. If you need to offer health insurance to
attract employees, consider HIPC (Health Insurance Plan of
California) for organizations with fewer than 50 employees. Obtain
federal and state employer ID numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are plenty of self-help books, Gaskin advises
getting an attorney to review your lease on new office space before
signing it. You might also study the literature or consult
professionals on the appropriate structure for your business (such
as partnership versus incorporation) as well as tax and other
filing requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Year-End Bonuses
</P>
<P>
   Q: My company is doing OK but not great but wants to reward its
employees. Any suggestions for making employees feel good and
giving them incentives to work even harder without breaking the
bank?
</P>
<P>
   A: Awards can be tricky. Bonuses should not generally be a
surprise, says Jim Horan, an El Sobrante business consultant and
owner of Rent.a.CFO. He believes employees should know what the
specific goals are all year and realize if they are on track or
not. While surprises are nice, they do not re-enforce desired
behavior year-round.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard for most small businesses to impress their employees
with year-end cash grants because either it's never enough or they
know a neighbor, friend or fellow employee who got more. And if you
gave $1,000 last year and can only afford $500 this year, it's
bound to be taken badly.
</P>
<P>
   If your company has limited cash, Horan recommends other types
of recognition as inexpensive as a catered lunch, specially printed
T-shirts or plain old praise.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling ``Men Are From Mars, Women Are From Venus'' author
John Gray's observation that men get ``the same number of points''
whether they give a single rose or a dozen, it might be better to
give a single rose 12 times a year. In other words, recognize
employees throughout the year for their accomplishments. Make it
part of your culture, and if you can afford it, make it part of
your business plan and budget.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs(at sign)sfgate.com
or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-08-98 2216EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
