<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITERATE SMUT  
 CISCO EYES CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Watershed Year for Sex
</P>
<P>
   What with matters Lewinsky and the Viagra sensation, 1998 has
been a watershed year for sex, in the view of Rufus Griscom,
editor-in-chief of the online magazine Nerve (www.nerve.com).
Previously unutterable topics have infiltrated public discourse,
and this can only be good news to someone in the business of
offering readers ``literate smut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tom Brokaw says `erectile dysfunction' on the air, when
puritanism is pushed back, it's permanent,'' Griscom said.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, at the onset of a holiday season that many have
proclaimed an ``e-Christmas,'' Griscom feels that his magazine's
foray into electronic commerce is well timed. As with its stories
and essays, which have been contributed by established authors like
Erica Jong, Nerve's online store leaves much to the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone asks us, `Are you selling lotions and sex toys?'''
Griscom said. ``We clearly, very intentionally, decided not to do
that.'' Instead, there are provocative gifts like silk pajamas and
candles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps it should come as no surprise that apple pie is the
scent American males find most arousing. If you're not the sort to
bake your man a pie (or whisk your woman off to an ocean bluff),
put our aromatherapy candles to work for you,'' reads the
promotional copy for the ``Nerve Boutique: Supplies for the
Thoughtful Hedonist.''
</P>
<P>
   But pushing for a renaissance of the game Twister _ ``people
should get their limbs entwined with other people's limbs as often
as possible'' _ is just one facet of Griscom's efforts to extend
the 18-month-old Nerve brand.
</P>
<P>
   In raising money and signing deals, Griscom (who has a scholarly
demeanor and an Ivy League degree) has learned that perhaps even
more than love, sex is vastly misunderstood _ particularly when the
word ``intelligent'' is used to describe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is not to turn people on but to make people think
about it,'' he said. ``Erotica tends to follow the arc of the
sexual act and is more about arousal, whereas what we tend to
publish is more thoughtful and might make people feel decidedly
unaroused.''
</P>
<P>
   In this paradox, Griscom finds an intriguing challenge for the
new millennium, a time in which e-mail and chat rooms factor
increasingly into the romantic lives of a great number of people.
To accommodate the shift, the site will soon allow the creation of
personal home pages, the better to swap personal data and one's own
erotic writings.
</P>
<P>
   A television show is also possible, and a book _ ``Nerve:
Literate Smut'' _ is already on the stands.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA NAPOLI &QR;
</P>
<P>
   From the Electronic Innards to the Everyday Cash Register
</P>
<P>
   Is the Cisco brand moving to a store shelf near you?
</P>
<P>
   That was certainly the impression that John Chambers, chief
executive of Cisco Systems, gave last week. After speaking at the
president's electronic commerce news conference in Washington on
Monday, Chambers said his company, the No. 1 manufacturer of data
communications equipment, was seriously considering ways to move
into the retail consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking to the Panasonics and Sonys of the world,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A vast majority of Cisco's business is selling products to other
businesses. But as high-speed data communications become available
to more people through cable modems and the telephone wire
technology known as DSL, a market opportunity may open to Cisco in
selling directly to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, most people who use an advanced data service get their
modem-like device directly from the company that provides the
service, with few choices _ similar to the way the cellular
telephone market operated years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But now, in the wireless market, people can often choose their
phone first and their service provider second. And if a similar
evolution occurs in the high-speed data market, Cisco wants to be
there.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Panasonics and the Sonys, Chambers said, Cisco is
preparing itself for the day when advanced communications
capabilities are built into consumer electronics of all sorts.
Cisco would love the makers of VCRs and cameras, for instance, to
point out that their products include Cisco technology, just as
some PC makers boast of ``Intel inside.''
</P>
<P>
   _ SETH SCHIESEL &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-06-98 1511EST &QL;
</P>
