<HEADLINE>
MARINE WHO BLASTED CLINTON IS REPRIMANDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANDLER, Ariz. - A Chandler Marine reserve major who wrote an
opinion piece calling for President Clinton's impeachment has been
taken to the woodshed by his superiors.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Maj. Daniel J. Rabil said Tuesday, his military
career is over.
</P>
<P>
   Rabil, 34, was placed on inactive reserve and had an official
counseling letter placed in his personnel file last weekend after
meeting with Marine authorities in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my career is effectively over,'' Rabil said. ``I can
hang around, but it's very clear that I won't be going anywhere.
Having an official counseling note in your file is a career
killer.''
</P>
<P>
   But Maj. Paula Buckley, spokeswoman for the commander of Marine
reserves in New Orleans, disputed Rabil's interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't even call this action punishment,'' Buckley said.
``He retains his rank and is just being placed in the same reserve
status as he was in when he left active duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just an administrative action which is intended to be
corrective.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabil, who works as a commodities trader in the southeast
Valley, wrote an opinion piece published in the ``Washington
Times'' last month attacking Clinton's sexual misconduct with
Monica Lewinsky and calling for the president's removal from
office.
</P>
<P>
   In the article, Rabil referred to Clinton as a ``morally
defective leader with a demonstrated disregard for his troops'' and
a ``highly skilled perjurer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabil also called the president a ``known criminal,'' ``lying
draft dodger'' and an ``instinctively anti-American man.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Article 88 of the Uniform Code of Military Justice,
officers on active duty are prohibited from making critical remarks
of the president and other civilian leaders. The code does not
address the question of freedom of speech as it applies to reserve
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Since Rabil is not on active duty and did not write the article
during his one weekend a month with the reserves, Marine officials
indicated initially that he might not be punished at all.
</P>
<P>
   Rabil said he also thought he might be in the clear after not
hearing anything for three weeks from Marine commanders. But all
that changed when he was summoned to New Orleans late last week to
meet with Maj. Gen. David Mize, commander of Marine reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Rabil was chastised by Mize and another commander during a
30-minute meeting that Rabil described only as being ``very
formal.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Rabil's article was published, Marine Maj. Shane
Sellers, who works at the Defense Intelligence Agency, received a
written warning after writing a column for the ``Navy Times.'' In
that column, Sellers referred to Clinton as ``an adulterous liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley said that the Marine high command sent an e-mail to all
general officers after Sellers' column appeared, reminding them of
Article 88 and the restriction on criticizing civilian leaders.
Rabil said he never saw a copy of the e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it would have mattered. Rabil is unrepentant.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only regret is that the senior leadership took it the wrong
way. I'm doing the right thing by the Marine Corps. You don't
strengthen an organization by tolerating those who are trying to
weaken it,'' Rabil said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that we have a president who is untrustworthy. Why not
use the facts now to remove him before later on, when soldiers are
sent off for whatever questionable reasons? It would be more
honorable.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabil served four years on active duty as a lieutenant in the
late 1980s before entering the reserves in 1990. Most recently, he
had been attached to an active reserve unit assigned to Camp
Pendleton, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1222EST &QL; 
