<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEN&AMP;JERRY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEN AND JERRY SHARE SECRETS OF SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JANE LARSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The secret ingredient to Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade Inc.'s
success isn't just in the milk from growth-hormone-free cows or the
intense flavors that tantalize Ben Cohen's taste buds.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of high-quality products, against-the-grain
marketing and strong corporate conscience have taken Cohen and
partner Jerry Greenfield way past the Vermont ice-cream parlor they
started for fun in 1978. Twenty years later, the adventure they
launched with a $5 correspondence course and $12,000 in savings and
loans has grown into a publicly traded company selling $174 million
in ice-cream products a year.
</P>
<P>
   The ice-cream entrepreneurs were in the Pheonxi area last week
to address small-business owners at US West Communications' New
Ventures Forum. For Greenfield, it was a bit of a homecoming _ he
lived in Tempe in the early '80s while his wife attended graduate
school at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   Still sporting a collegial look of untucked T-shirts and no
ties, Cohen and Greenfield recalled that their product came at a
trendy time for homemade ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``What ice-cream manufacturers had been making up until that
time was ice cream that was easy to make, that machines were
designed to make, as opposed to making ice cream the way people
really wanted to eat it,'' Greenfield said.
</P>
<P>
   But selling their super-premium version during Vermont winters
was difficult, even when they dropped prices along with the
temperature. To survive, they turned to the wholesale market where
their products _ hand-mixed with chunks of cookies and candy _
stood out against the air-filled, inexpensive ice cream sold then.
</P>
<P>
   Their down-home image also differed from the concoctions labeled
with foreign-sounding names.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out with Ben &AMP; Jerry's, being very honest about who
was making it, where it was being made, putting our faces on the
cover, not trying to be eloquent and classy, but trying to be
essentially what we are. And that broke through the clutter,''
Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The final ingredient, he said, came from building a company that
gives back to the community and uses its power to solve social
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you can relate to your customers on the basis of values,
when the customers believe in the company, believe what the company
stands for, as opposed to basing it on advertising and . . . a
really cool ad campaign, the latter is much more ephemeral, and
it's only as good as your latest ad campaign,'' Cohen said. ``But
building this strong values-based relationship with the customers
ends up with long-term customer loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Those loyal customers have done everything from flood Ben &AMP;
Jerry's with 22,000 entries in an ``I Want to Be CEO'' contest to
suggest new names and flavors for ice cream. The idea for Cherry
Garcia, for example, came via an anonymous postcard from a Grateful
Dead fan, Greenfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two can point to successes now, there were plenty
of low points.
</P>
<P>
   For the first three or four years, all they did was work and try
to pay the bills, Greenfield said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my strongest memories is of walking outside and seeing
Ben lie down in the gravel,'' he said. ``He just fell asleep, right
on the gravel.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the time a 1,000-gallon tank of liquid ice cream
mix went horribly rancid.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time that was just a huge financial hit for us, plus I
had to go into the bulk tank and clean it out,'' Greenfield
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, so torn by the '60s perception that business takes
advantage of employees and the community, the pair put Ben &AMP;
Jerry's Homemade up for sale. They changed their minds when a
friend convinced Cohen that he didn't have to run his business that
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a real turning point,'' Greenfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the company's ``two-part bottom line'': profits, and the
quality of life in its community. Yet the company has wrestled with
the fact that resources devoted to one take away from the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized the solution to the dilemma is to choose the ones
with a positive effect on both,'' he said. Consequently, Ben &AMP;
Jerry's buys its dairy ingredients from family farms and its
brownies from an inner-city bakery.
</P>
<P>
   They rewrote the business book with their first stock offering
to the Vermont public, done to raise $750,000 to upgrade vintage
facilities. Advisers thought they were crazy, Greenfield recalled,
when they refused to seek venture capital and decided to make
Vermonters owners of the business.
</P>
<P>
   They registered as stockbrokers, set a per-share price of $126,
and took their show on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a real way for us to try to take a hold of our values
and integrate it into our need for financing,'' Greenfield said.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, however, their distrust of the business world
proved true.
</P>
<P>
   When Pillsbury Co. bought Haagen-Dazs and insisted distributors
drop Ben &AMP; Jerry's, they were mad enough to sue but frustrated that
the courts were full of similar cases.
</P>
<P>
   That spawned a ``What's the Doughboy afraid of?'' campaign aimed
at the public, complete with ads in ``Rolling Stone'' and on the
sides of buses, an 800 number and T-shirts supporting their legal
defense fund. Today, Haagen-Dazs distributors also carry Ben &AMP;
Jerry's.
</P>
<P>
   Growing and going public have posed new conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Where gut and heart used to help with decisions, millions of
dollars now goes into market research, ``which ends up coming out
no better,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The compensation philosophy has changed, too. Originally, to let
people know their work was valued, the highest-paid person made no
more than five times that of the lowest-paid person. Four years
ago, in a move to hire a CEO to take over day-to-day operations,
the policy, symbolic as it was, was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very controversial decision,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   After a switch in CEOs and two years of flat earnings, sales are
back up at Ben &AMP; Jerry's. Greenfield credits price increases,
better operations and ``a real shift back to eating ice cream and
away from good-for-you products.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has 170 retail outlets, including one in Tempe, and
plans to add 30 a year for the next five years. It also is
expanding internationally, including stores in Japan, Israel and
France.
</P>
<P>
   As the business grows, Greenfield admitted, keeping the passion
for it is hard. The feeling around the company, now up to 700
employees and three manufacturing plants, is much different than 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to have a mission that includes more than just making
money is a way that can make the job and the work more meaningful
to people,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jane Larson can be reached at jane.larson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
