<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini movie reviews of ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' and ``Mendel''
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' (PG-13) _ Think ``Romancing the
Stone'' . . . only without the romance or the adventure. Harrison
Ford is a gruff charter pilot and Anne Heche is a New York magazine
editor. They wind up stranded on an island near Tahiti _ an
abandoned place, except for some pirates. The pair bicker, bond and
kick some pirate butt. Available in VHS and DVD. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Mendel'' (Not rated) _ In the years after World War II, a
young Jewish boy comes to terms with his identity in this
affectionate drama. But he doesn't understand why his questions
about the Holocaust disturb his parents, who have emigrated from
Germany to Norway. Interweaving everyday chatter with nightmare
visions of the Holocaust, the film captures the tension between the
need to start a new life and the necessity of remembering the past.
In Norwegian with subtitles. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
