</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kick the Christmas habit with these flicks
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The movies of Christmas are as familiar as our favorite tree
ornaments. The original ``Miracle on 34th Street.'' ``A Christmas
Story.'' ``Home Alone.'' The various versions of ``A Christmas
Carol.'' And the shining, can't-ignore-it star on top of the tree,
``It's a Wonderful Life.''
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes you want something a little less obvious, a little
less traditional. If you've had your fill of Tiny Tim and ZuZu's
petals, here are some alternatives. Consider them outsider
Christmas flicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Midnight Clear'' (1991)
</P>
<P>
   Here, as Rod Serling might say, is a carol for another
Christmas. It is 1944 in the Ardennes Forest on the French-German
border in the waning winter days of World War II. A small squad of
young GIs, led by the movie's narrator (Ethan Hawke), occupies a
deserted chateau. Their mission: to monitor enemy troop movements.
Trouble is, the enemy refuses to behave like an an enemy. Based on
an antiwar novel by William Wharton (``Birdy''), this literate,
funny, harrowingly self-aware film is a minor classic.
</P>
<P>
   Tinsel tip: Look for a then-unknown Gary Sinese as one of the
soldiers. And film buffs may recognize director Keith Gordon's
name. In his former life as a teen actor, he starred in ``Dressed
to Kill'' and ``Christine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fanny and Alexander'' (1983)
</P>
<P>
   This glorious plum pudding of a movie is not, strictly speaking,
limited to Christmas. Set in Sweden in 1907, it actually follows an
extended theatrical family through the plots of several Dickens
novels (not literally, but close enough). The first hour, however,
is the most festive Christmas celebration ever committed to film.
It's the feast, the presents, the arriving friends and family, all
seen through the eyes of 10-year-old Alexander. A breathtaking
evocation of everything Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Tinsel tip: In his autobiography, director Ingmar Bergman said
that it was while making this film that he decided to quit making
films. Nothing catastrophic, just, ``I had seen too many of my
colleagues falling in the ring like tired clowns, bored by their
own dullness.'' Of course, he has since returned to the camera with
a film called _ I'm not kidding _ ``In the Presence of a Clown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter's Friends'' (1992)
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's more of a pre-New Year's Eve bash (and bashing),
but the decorations are still up and everyone's trying to summon up
that holiday cheer. Directed by Kenneth Branagh (he's part of the
acting ensemble, too), this Brit spin on ``The Big Chill'' brings
six old college friends _ plus assorted lovers, spouses, etc. _
together for a 10-years-after reunion. It's the sort of
well-meaning house party where too much wine is drunk and too many
truths _ some hilarious, some not _ are told.
</P>
<P>
   Tinsel tip: Popular stand-up comic Rita Rudner wrote the script
and plays Branagh's wife, a very-Hollywood TV diva. And the titular
Peter is Stephen Fry, who turned in an Oscar-worthy performance
earlier this year as Oscar Wilde in ``Wilde.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tales From the Crypt'' (1972)
</P>
<P>
   The first short film in this collection of five stories taken
from the old EC Comics is called ``All Through the House.'' It
stars Joan Collins as a single mother celebrating Christmas Eve
with her little boy. Everything looks set for a picture-perfect
Christmas. Then she hears on the radio that a psycho wearing a
Santa suit has escaped from the local asylum. Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   Tinsel tip: Though not exactly what you'd call a prestige
production, this nifty little horror anthology attracted a pretty
classy cast. Try, Sir Ralph Richardson and Peter Cushing. The
director, Freddie Francis, is also an A-list cinematographer. Among
his films: ``The Elephant Man'' and the remake of ``Cape Fear.''
</P>
<P>
   A final consumer tip: If you want to know more about Christmas
flicks, famous or obscure. check out American Movie Classics'
special ``Great Christmas Movies,'' which premieres at 10 p.m. Dec.
15. There's also an excellent companion book to the program called
``Great Christmas Movies'' (Taylor, $29.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
