<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0607 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAYTON-ANNIVERSARY-$A     12-09 2178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTON-ANNIVERSARY-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THREE YEARS LATER: DAYTON ACCORDS UNABLE TO REPAIR DAMAGE
ALREADY DONE
 &HT;    With BOSNIA-FAMILY-$ADV13, DAYTON-TIMELINE-$ADV13,
DAYTON-PLAYERS-$ADV13.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    EDs: There are maps available from IFOR, the Implementation
Force which proceeded SFOR, the Stabilization Force. The maps are
called ``BH Majority Ethnic Distribution 1991'' and ``BH Ethnic
Distribution (majority) 1996'' IFOR's Web site address:
www.nato.int/ifor/ifor.htm
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSANNAH A. NESMITH 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Hercegovina _ Three years after the Dayton
Peace Accords ended the ethnic war here, a lot of progress has been
made in the reconstruction of Bosnia. Bridges and roads have been
rebuilt, schools reopened, electric lines re-connected. Food
shortages are a thing of the past, as is the systematic violence of
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the peace here remains tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, and the result, is 1.1 million Bosnian refugees who
haven't gone home yet, people like Jusif Mujic and Ilic Marko.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton Peace Accords, signed in Paris three years ago
Monday(Dec. 14), divided Bosnia into two states: the Serb Republic,
and the Muslim/Croat Federation. The two states are largely
autonomous, each with the right to elect its own president and
parliament, maintain its own military and even negotiate agreements
with other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Mujic, a Muslim schoolteacher, fled his home at the beginning of
the war when Serbian special forces stormed into his hometown. Now
he lives in the Federation in an apartment owned by Serbs who fled
that area. The apartment he owns, now in the Serb Republic, is
being occupied by Serbs who fled fighting somewhere else in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Marko's case is similar. A retired engineer and a Serb, he fled
his home when his town was taken by Muslim forces. He's living in a
Muslim's home in the Serb Republic while the house he owns is being
occupied by a Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Peace Accords reached at Wright-Patterson Air
Force Base in Dayton, Ohio, accomplished the most important goal,
ending the war and the ethnic cleansing that so horrified the
world.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been unable to undo the resulting damage. Bosnia is
still sharply divided along ethnic lines. And while enabling people
to go home wasn't the first goal of the peace plan, it remains the
one that cannot be achieved. That failure has confounded all other
attempts to rebuild Bosnia into a country that doesn't need
international peacekeepers to prevent it from tumbling back into
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a quantum leap forward in the coming year,'' said
Carlos Westendorp, Bosnia's international supervisor. ``This
country is not going to be reconstructed unless there is a degree
of multi-ethnicity, unless people are living together.''
</P>
<P>
   The Peace Accords give Westendorp extraordinary powers over
Bosnia. He can impose legislation, suspend laws passed by Bosnian
lawmakers and even remove officials from office. But that power
does not reach into the hearts of people, and he is frustrated by
his inability so far to solve the critical problem at the core of
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we fail, then I am very pessimistic about Bosnia,''
Westendorp said. ``Last year, we had only 30,000 returns. With
every year that passes, the number reduces by half. People get used
to living where they are. In a way, it's now or never.''
</P>
<P>
   The Peace Accords also included guarantees that refugees would
be allowed to go home. But it didn't anticipate that some would
refuse, like a tragic game of musical chairs in which some of the
players refuse to get up when the music starts.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Bosnia began after Communist Yugoslavia fell apart in
1991. While the other republics of Yugoslavia had ethnic majorities
that controlled politics, Bosnia's society was a mixture of Croats,
Muslims and Serbs. The three groups fought each other, with the
Croats and Serbs getting help from neighboring Croatia and Serbia,
for 44 months. At the end of the war, there were almost no
multi-ethnic communities left.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, less than 300,000 Bosnians have gone home and of
those, only about 55,000 went to areas where they were ethnic
minorities. Another 800,000 refugees are still scattered around
Bosnia, most of them occupying homes of other refugees. And more
than 300,000 are living in other countries in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of waiting to go home, Mujic and Marko have
done exactly what Westendorp feared they and others like them would
do. They've given up.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I was sure I'd go home after the war ended,'' Mujic
said. ``But I still don't feel safe here. And the people in my
apartment, they're just not leaving. They don't want to go home.
They like my apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men met on the street in Brcko, in northern Bosnia, one
morning this fall. Over a beer in a small cafe, the Serb and the
Muslim, perfect strangers until that morning, discussed exchanging
the apartments they owned before the war because they had given up
on ever returning to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any problem with each other, Serbs, Muslims,
Croats, as people, individuals,'' Marko said. ``But so much has
happened. At some point, you just have to forget about life ever
being the way it was before the war and make a new life.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the war ended, politics here have been dominated by ethnic
nationalists who have done little to help the country recover. The
economy, social services, taxes, none of those are issues in
election campaigns here. The only issue is the degree of
nationalism of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb Republic has usually chosen the most fervent
nationalists. NATO bombed the Serbs here in order to bring them to
the negotiating table and end the war. Many feel like the peace
that was negotiated left them as second-class citizens of a nation
they fought a war against.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the Serb Republic elected a hard-line,
anti-Western, anti-Dayton president.
</P>
<P>
   Nikola Poplasen, a former political science professor and
military leader during the war, is cagey with the media. He has to
walk a thin line, satisfying the people who voted for him while
placating the international community. He knows Westendorp can
remove him from office if he says too much.
</P>
<P>
   Poplasen declines to say what he thinks the future holds for
Bosnia or for the Serb Republic, saying only that he hopes the
people will decide their own future. If a referendum were held to
decide whether the Serb Republic should be allowed to break away
from Bosnia, he would vote for secession.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I would try to vote several times,'' he said, laughing.
Then he got serious. ``But that would be possible only if the
Muslims and the Croats agreed. Otherwise it would lead to violence.
I'm not inclined to resolve political problems with violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she didn't vote for him, Natasha Predojovic, a
20-year-old Serb interpreter working for the international
community in the Serb Republic, agrees with Poplasen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I myself, my friends, my family, we didn't want to be part of
Bosnia. We didn't vote for that,'' she said. ``It was imposed on
us. I don't have any feelings for my country. I would never cry at
the national anthem. You might as well tell me I'm Romanian or
Bulgarian.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the issue of refugees going home, she's not sure it will
ever be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we can't live together anymore, but at least we can be
good neighbors,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb Republic and the Federation exchange very few refugees
each month. But even within the Federation, Bosnians are having
trouble being good neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there have been 70 violent incidents, mostly arsons
but also two murders, prompted by Muslims trying to return to Croat
neighborhoods in the Mostar area. Though the Croats and the Muslims
formed an alliance against the Serbs towards the end of the war,
and though they agreed to live in the same state when Dayton was
signed, they haven't been able to reconcile their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Haris Silajdzic, prime minister of Bosnia, says reasonable
Bosnian citizens of all three nationalities will never be able to
reconcile their difference with the extreme nationalists among the
Serbs and Croats.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those who say why can't we agree, the answer is, why didn't
you agree with Hitler,'' he said. ``It was impossible. The man
wanted a racially pure land.''
</P>
<P>
   Silajdzic, a Muslim, believes justice is the only thing that can
guarantee peace in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The only way Bosnia can have justice, he said, is for all the
refugees to return to their homes. Thats the only thing that would
undo the results of ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have territory under Serb control in which close to one
million Serbs lived,'' he said. ``They are not there now. So who
lost? We all lost by allowing that to happen. The project (of
ethnic cleansing) still lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But Silajdzic resorts to the same answers Poplasen does when
talking about refugees who want to return to his backyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those now in Sarajevo were expelled from their homes,'' he
said. ``They came here because this was the only safe point. What
should we do with them? Expel them again?''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence of the continuing divisions in Bosnia, and the
Bosnian government's inability to overcome them, sometimes borders
on the absurd. To call Bosnia from another country, the caller must
first determine which part of Bosnia he's calling. There are three
phone systems here, a Croat system, a Serb system and a Muslim
system, each with a different country code. An operator on the Serb
system, asked recently how to make a call to a phone on the Croat
system, said it simply couldn't be done.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Westendorp ordered the government to fix the phone
system. He has also ordered the issuance of passports, a common
currency and car license plates that didn't reveal the driver's
ethnicity. And when it came to something that might seem simple,
like adopting a national anthem, his office took over the job after
the Bosnian government failed to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia's economy is as unreconstructed as its government.
Unemployment hovers around 40 percent, higher in some regions.
Westendorp says the economy is growing at about 35 percent a year,
but he qualifies that by pointing out that there was no economy
here when the war ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war interrupted a normal transition from communism and a
lack of a market towards democracy and a free-market economy,'' he
said. ``We've had to start almost from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   For Marinko Misic's daughter and son-in-law, the economy is the
reason they won't come home. Even though they are Croats and
welcome in their hometown of Sarajevo, seven months ago they moved
from Germany, where they spent the war, to Akron, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a house here, but no job. That's why they didn't
come back,'' he said. ``The international community, they give
someone a new roof. But what can that man do now that he has a new
roof? He doesn't have a job. We need jobs before we can be a
country again.''
</P>
<P>
   Westendorp knows the governments of the world are beginning to
wonder how much more they'll have to spend making Bosnia into a
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bosnia is dependent on the international community, of course,
right now,'' he said. ``This dependency syndrome must
little-by-little disappear. We must do things here and then say to
them, 'OK, this is your responsibility. We are not going to support
you forever.' But more risky and more expensive would be to
withdraw the troops.''
</P>
<P>
   He looks to the small steps that have been taken here as proof
that international efforts are working, however slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Lipovac is one of those small steps. The tiny village was on the
frontlines during the war and was completely destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   But Lipovac is going to be rebuilt because the 31 families who
used to live there, some of them Serb, some Muslim and some Croat,
have decided they can live together again.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, humanitarian organizations, eager to
encourage multi-ethnicity, will have rebuilt almost all the houses
in the village. It may be the first truly multi-ethnic village in
all of post-war Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Lipovac offers hope that lasting peace may be
attainable, it shows why the wounds of war are too deep to be
healed quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Risto Djokic, a Serb from Lipovac, went back to
see his farm after the war, he ran into one of his old neighbors, a
Croat man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me, 'Screw Alija, screw Tudjman, screw Milosevic,
screw Karadzic. They caused all this.''' Djokic related. His
neighbor was referring to the presidents of Bosnia, Croatia and
Serbia and the leader of the Bosnian Serbs during the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, 'Alija and Tudjman and Milosevic and Karadzic,
they didn't do this to my house. They weren't here with the
dynamite. My neighbors did this.'''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
