<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0611 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-FAMILY-$ADV13-     12-09 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-FAMILY-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOSNIAN, SERBIAN REFUGEES THREATEN FRAGILE PEACE, DAYTON ACCORDS
 &HT;    With DAYTON-ANNIVERSARY-$ADV13.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSANNAH A. NESMITH 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALANKA, Bosnia-Hercegovina _ Sevala and Suad Pobric were
supposed to move into their new house on May 1, 1992. The young
couple had spent their entire savings building the four-bedroom
house, their dream house, with plenty of room for the family they
wanted to raise together.
</P>
<P>
   But on April 28, a unit of the Serbian Special Forces arrived in
their hometown of Brcko and the Pobrics, who are Muslims, had to
flee. More than six years later, they still can't go home.
</P>
<P>
   A Serbian family that fled fighting in another part of the
country is now living in the Pobric's house. Sevala has met them,
even had coffee with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing, when you go to your house, is when you go
outside and the lady there goes inside and closes the door and you
have to go God knows where,'' she said, tears welling up yet again
as she looked around the tiny apartment without running water where
she and her husband are trying to raise their two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The Pobrics, and the Serbian family occupying their house, are
among the more than one million Bosnian refugees who either aren't
able or aren't willing to return to their pre-war homes. They are
all survivors of ethnic cleansing and war. And three years after
the conflict ended here, they each represent a weakness of the
fragile peace here.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Pobric went to visit her house, she brought a bag
of clothes her daughter had outgrown for one of the girls living
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children aren't guilty of anything,'' she said. ``Only
stupid people at the top think we can't live together. We're both
bad off. It's not impossible for us to live together. We did for
years before.''
</P>
<P>
   Like so many of the people displaced by the war, her husband
can't find steady work. The family lives from week to week on the
tips he makes at a black market restaurant. Before the war, he and
Sevala worked in a battery factory -- he a manager, she a clerk --
both making good salaries. They had plans to send their daughters
to college.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they're trying to decide where to send their oldest
daughter to high school. If she goes to the nearest high school, a
trade school, she won't be able to go to college. But the nearest
pre-college high school in the Muslim part of the country is two
hours away. With no car to take her every morning, the 14-year-old
would have to rent a room and live by herself.
</P>
<P>
   She could go to one of the pre-college high schools in Brcko,
just 20 miles away, if her family could move back there.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Tuesday afternoon, Sevala Pobric serves a
thrown-together lunch of chicken and canned peppers to a group of
relatives and a reporter who dropped by without notice. Without a
phone, she never knows when she'll have company. She has to go
downstairs to borrow eating utensils from a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life of a refugee,'' she says, laughing as she comes back with
two forks and a spoon. But a shadow crosses her face as she
explains that none of the furniture in her apartment is hers, that
even some of the clothes she owns are donations from refugee aid
centers where she lived during the war.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dayton Peace Accords ended the fighting here in
December 1995, she remembers being so hopeful. The war was bad, but
it was over. Everything would be normal again soon, she thought.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, she's thinking about immigrating to the
United States. Her cousin has a daughter in Atlanta who's been able
to find work and even buy a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard, not having anything when you used to have
things,'' she said. ``I hope someday, we'll be like the United
States or Germany, where no one can take away what I made with my
10 fingers. But things are going so slow here.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, she received a certificate verifying the home she
and her husband built is indeed theirs. She applied for the
certificate two years ago. It doesn't give her the right to go
home, but it's a start. The international community here has vowed
not to put anyone out on the street, so the family staying in her
home will probably be able to stay as long as they want. And she'll
have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about the future and the plans she used to have for it,
Sevala can't help crying. Maida, her four-year-old, asks her why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mommy's just a little disappointed, that's all,'' Sevala tells
her.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
