<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0612 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAYTON-TIMELINE-$ADV1     12-09 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTON-TIMELINE-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TIMELINE OF WAR AND PEACE IN BOSNIA-HERCEGOVINA
 &HT;    EDs: Trim to fit.
 &HT;    With DAYTON-ANNIVERSARY-$ADV13.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSANNAH A. NESMITH 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1914 -- Austrian Archduke Franz Josef assassinated in Sarajevo,
prompting World War I.
</P>
<P>
   1918 -- Kingdom of Serbians, Croatians and Slovenes formed. Name
changed to Yugoslavia in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   1946 -- Josip ``Tito'' Broz forms Yugoslavia, encompassing the
same territory as the former kingdom. Bosnia-Hercegovina is one of
the six republics in the new communist state.
</P>
<P>
   1980 -- Tito dies, leaving no obvious successor.
</P>
<P>
   June 1991 -- Slovenia and Croatia declare their independence
from Yugoslavia
</P>
<P>
   June-July 1991 -- The ``Ten Day War'' in Slovenia. Yugoslav
People's Army (JNA) loses and Slovenia becomes an independent
state.
</P>
<P>
   July -Dec. 1991 -- War in Croatia between Croatian Territorial
Forces and Serbian irregulars, backed by Yugoslav People's Army.
Serbs and JNA take Vukovar in Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 1992 -- Former U.S. Secretary of State Cyrus Vance
negotiates peace in Croatia -- though sporadic violence continues
until 1995. JNA pulls out of Croatia, moves to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 29, 1992 -- Bosnia-Hercegovina declares its independence
from Yugoslavia. Bosnian Serbs declare their independence from
Bosnia-Hercegovina.
</P>
<P>
   March 1992 -- In prelude to war, Serbian irregulars begin
fighting Bosnian police, ethnic cleansing begins in eastern Bosnia.
Croatian forces begin taking control of Hercegovina in western
Bosnia
</P>
<P>
   April - May 1992 -- JNA begins siege of Sarajevo then supposedly
withdraws from Bosnia although troops and equipment remain under
new Bosnian Serb commander.
</P>
<P>
   March 1993 -- Bosnian Croats and Muslims begin fighting over the
30 percent of the territory not controlled by Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 9, 1993 -- Croatian shelling destroys 400-year-old bridge
in Mostar. The town, which straddles the Neretva River, is divided,
with Croats on the west side and Muslims on the east.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 5, 1994 -- Mortar attack in Sarajevo marketplace kills 68
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 28, 1994 -- NATO forces shoot down Serb aircraft over
central Bosnia. This was NATO's first use of force since it was
founded in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Mar. 18, 1994 -- U.S. brokered agreement between Bosnian Croats
and Muslims is signed. The two sides agree to join forces to defend
the territory against Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   July 11, 1995 -- Srebrenica, one of the U.N. declared safe
zones, falls to Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 30, 1995 -- NATO airstrikes begin. They last until Serbs
withdraw their forces around Sarajevo and other places on Sept. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 1, 1995 -- All three sides begin peace negotiations at
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in Dayton, Ohio. An agreement is
reached three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 3, 1995 -- First U.S. ground troops sent to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 30, 1995 -- U.N. protection force (UNPROFOR) mandate
extended to Jan. 1996 to maintain the cease-fire
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 14, 1994 -- The Dayton Peace Accords are signed in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 15, 1995 -- United Nations authorizes the establishment of
a multinational force of troops to implement the peace plan (IFOR).
IFOR is supposed to be in Bosnia for one year.
</P>
<P>
   March 1996 -- NATO expands role in Bosnia, peacekeeping troops
begin to provide security for war crimes investigators from the
International War Crimes Tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 1996 -- First general elections are held in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 12, 1996 -- U.N. extends the mandate for peacekeeping
troops in Bosnia another 18 months, changing the name to
stabilization force (SFOR).
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 9-10, 1997 -- Bonn conference of the Peace Implementation
Council, made up of the country's supporting the peace-keeping
efforts in Bosnia. New interpretation of the Peace Accords gives
the Office of the High Representative powers to remove elected
officials and impose laws.
</P>
<P>
   June 1998 -- U.N. extends the SFOR mandate again.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 1998 -- Second general elections since the war. Hardline
nationalists gain several important seats though overall results
are in favor of moderates.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
