NYT-12-09-98 1322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0614 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAYTON-PLAYERS-$ADV13     12-09 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTON-PLAYERS-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE MAJOR PLAYERS IN BOSNIA
 &HT;    With DAYTON-ANNIVERSARY-$ADV13.
 &HT;    With photo mugs to be placed in the International folder on the
Cox Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSANNAH A. NESMITH 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHO RUNS BOSNIA? A LOOK AT THE SIX MEN IN CHARGE:
</P>
<P>
   CARLOS WESTENDORP -- A Spanish diplomat, Westendorp has been
Bosnia's international supervisor since June 1997 when he replaced
French diplomat Carl Bildt. The Office of the High Representative
was established by the Dayton Peace Accords to oversee the plan's
implementation. Westendorp has the authority to remove public
officials from office and order the adoption of laws or even
suspend laws after they've been passed by local legislators.
</P>
<P>
   ZIVKO RADISIC -- Chairman of the three-person national
presidency, Radisic is a moderate Serb and member of the Socialist
Party of the Serb Republic, a party advocating the reintegration of
Bosnia. He was a hard-line communist before the war and is
therefore not trusted by some Serbs. However, he defeated an
ultra-nationalist candidate in the September elections. Not much is
known about him.
</P>
<P>
   ANTE JELAVIC -- The Croat member of Bosnia's three-person
presidency, Jelavic is the Bosnian leader of the Croatian
Democratic Union Party, a party based in neighboring Croatia. Born
in Croatia, he was a general in the Croatian Army during the war.
His party has resisted integration of the Muslim/Croat Federation,
one of the two states in Bosnia, and has argued that Croats in
Bosnia should be allowed to establish a special relationship,
almost like a treaty, with Croatia. He is seen as slightly more
moderate than some of the leaders of his party, though still a
hard-line nationalist.
</P>
<P>
   ALIJA IZETBEGOVIC -- The president of Bosnia throughout the war
and leader of the Bosnian Muslims, Izetbegovic was re-elected to
the national presidency in September almost without opposition.
Before the war he was imprisoned in Yugoslavia in the 1980s for his
extremist writings on the future of Islam. His apologists point out
that he never wrote anything calling for Bosnia to become a Muslim
state and most in the international community believe he is fair to
the other ethnic groups, even if his support of an integrated
Bosnia-Hercegovina is sometimes weak.
</P>
<P>
   EJUP GANIC -- President of the Muslim/Croat Federation, one of
the two states within Bosnia, Ganic is a moderate who favors the
re-integration of the country and cooperation with international
officials. A U.S.-educated engineer, he was born in Serbia and
served in the Bosnian government during the war. He was
instrumental in negotiating the peace agreement between the Muslims
and the Croats that preceded Dayton. He is considered a crafty
politician.
</P>
<P>
   NIKOLA POPLASEN -- The president of the Serb Republic, the other
state in Bosnia, Poplasen is a member of the Serbian Radical Party.
The party based in neighboring Yugoslavia with goals of uniting all
Serbs in one country. Poplasen says he would never work toward
those ends because that would violate the Dayton Peace Accords,
however, he's shown little interest in working with members of the
international community either. Before the war he was a political
science professor. During the war, he was a leader in the Serbian
Army.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
