<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-PATTEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTEN SEEKS CONSENSUS ON POLICING IN NORTHERN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ It's a Monday morning, and Chris
Patten already looks bleary-eyed. He knows this is the first of
many days of angry crowds, of hurt feelings, of people who want
things to change, of people who want things to stay the same.
</P>
<P>
   As the last British governor of Hong Kong, Patten knows the
complexity of managing historic change. But as the man now in
charge of the commission that will recommend how to make the police
force reflect the seismic changes in Northern Ireland's political
landscape, Patten faces a task perhaps even more difficult than
preparing Hong Kong for its handover to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodbye Hong Kong, hello ding-dong,'' fundamentalist
preacher-politician _ and foe _ Ian Paisley greeted Patten one day.
</P>
<P>
   Patten managed a smile, because he knows Northern Ireland,
having served here in the 1980s as a junior Cabinet minister before
taking on Hong Kong. He knows that Belfast people in particular
have great, dark senses of humor. Ding-dong, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   But Patten also knows this is no laughing matter. Many people
believe that if the peace in Northern Ireland is to hold, the way
the police conduct themselves is likely to prove to be the cement
that holds it all together, or the corrosive that brings it all
crashing down.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, without the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the IRA
would not exist today. But if not for the constabulary, the IRA
would have killed far more people than it has.
</P>
<P>
   It was the heavyhanded reaction by police to modest demands by
the Catholic civil rights movement in the 1960s that breathed life
back into what was an IRA that existed largely in name only.
</P>
<P>
   After the police beat peaceful Catholic demonstrators and stood
by while Protestant extremists burned out nationalist
neighborhoods, the IRA was flooded with a new generation of young
men who decided only violence could change Northern Ireland.
Overzealous policing guaranteed that generations of Catholics would
respond to arbitrary searches and gratuitous beatings by joining
the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   And yet there are many good and some remarkably brave men and
women in the RUC, and they are credited by the Protestant community
with holding the line against an IRA they believe was determined to
exterminate them. More than 300 police officers have been killed by
republicans over the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Patten and seven other people, including a former
Massachusetts public safety secretary, Kathleen M. O'Toole, are now
charged with reconciling those two conflicting images of the RUC.
They must recognize what the force does right and change what it
does wrong so that the force is acceptable to both communities in
Northern Ireland. On the table are issues such as making the
Protestant-dominated force more reflective of Northern Ireland's
divided religious heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his modest office on the third floor of the
Interpoint building in downtown Belfast, Patten says he is aware of
the importance of a job that cynics say is by its nature a
Catch-22. He exudes a confidence that many admire and that some
criticize as arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be judged by how successfully we can offer a
vision of policing in Northern Ireland that can command the maximum
support,'' he said. ``It's a difficult job, but not an impossible
one.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the difficulties is that so many people claim the
commission's work is a foregone conclusion. Protestant unionists,
who want to remain British citizens, see Patten as someone too
quick to appease nationalists. Some recall he was the official who
in the 1980s approved changing the name of Londonderry district
council to Derry, the name used by nationalists. Some, like
Paisley, say Patten can't be trusted because he is Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme nationalists in Sinn Fein, the party that represents
republicans, those who say violence is justified in trying to bring
about a united Ireland, say the RUC must be disbanded. Many of them
dismiss Patten as a British establishment figure. As someone who
served under Margaret Thatcher, the British figure most hated by
republicans, Patten labors in her shadow, even though he was
appointed to his new post by Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Having worked here before, Patten is aware of the tendency of
both sides to assume the worst about British politicians,
especially English ones. But he thinks many of the complaints about
his and the commission's appointment were ``formulistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I may be vainglorious for a moment, I think my appointment
was pretty well received,'' he said. ``I think most people knew
from my time as a junior minister in Northern Ireland that I've
been committed to the community, continued to be in touch with it,
that I care about what happens here. I don't think my Catholicism
mattered greatly to moderate unionists any more than my former
status as a Conservative Cabinet minister mattered greatly to
moderate nationalists.''
</P>
<P>
   With those words, Patten hinted at the commission's strategy, to
find the common ground occupied by moderates on both sides who
helped the politicians make a historic compromise with the Good
Friday Agreement, then endorsed the agreement by nearly 3-to-1 in
May's referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Patten's plan to find consensus on policing is centered on
holding some 30 public hearings over the next month. He has made
O'Toole, now an administrator at Boston College, his chief deputy.
In order to get the broadest possible sampling of opinion, Patten
is heading one group while O'Toole leads another, crisscrossing the
province.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very keen that everybody will get the chance to express
their concerns, their anger, their passions, their aspirations,''
said Patten. ``I hope the process can lead to a more informed
discussion about our conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people believe those conclusions have already been reached.
A recent report in The Irish Times purported to have an early draft
of the commission's conclusions. Just where the document came from
remains unclear. In his office, Patten dismissed the report as
unfounded, the product of dirty tricks. But he will not issue
public repudiations of purported leaks, which are expected to
become a flood as the commission's report is prepared for release
next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that every time one of these stories comes out,
you can't get led into denying the specifics because otherwise
you're announcing your report as you go along,'' he said. ``What
this persuades me of is we should get on with our work as rapidly
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The hearings so far have been well attended, and passionate. In
Crossmaglen, the bastion of republican resistence, speakers
bitterly criticized Peter Smith's membership on the commission. A
Belfast lawyer, Smith represented two British soldiers who shot and
killed a local man who allegedly ran an army checkpoint eight years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Ballymoney, three police officers, speaking in a personal
capacity, said it would be an insult to the memory of their dead
colleagues if, as has been proposed, the name of the RUC is changed
to make it more acceptable to nationalists. One officer described
poignantly how his father was shot dead by the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   O'Toole said she has been impressed by ``the intelligence of the
submissions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't find the apathy you did at home,'' said O'Toole, in
a veiled reference to her efforts to reform the Massachusetts State
Police, which fell largely on deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
   Although she jokingly calls Patten ``a slave driver,'' she
admires his determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris understands the seriousness of the job at hand,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after he made his party's submission to the
commission here last week, Sinn Fein chairman Mitchel McLaughlin
said republicans do not believe that a commission appointed by the
British government is capable of recognizing that the RUC is by its
nature unacceptable to nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The RUC was not created to protect the people. It was created
to protect unionism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Patten is determined to press ahead, critics be damned. Time, he
says, is of the essence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one lesson I got from government is that the doctrine of
unripe time is always, always wrong,'' he said, preparing to hit
the road yet again. ``There are some things when it's never the
ripe time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
