<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE OLD HANDS HAVE WORTHWHILE ADVICE ON OFFICIATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They didn't listen to him two decades ago because of who he is,
and they won't listen to him now.
</P>
<P>
   But Al Davis was right then, and he is right now.
</P>
<P>
   At a league meeting back when the late Pete Rozelle was NFL
commissioner, Davis threw out a bold proposal. But unfortunately,
no one listened. If they had, the league most likely wouldn't have
the problem it is having with game officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted the league to build and fund a facility in the middle
of the country _ someplace like Dallas or St. Louis, a central
location _ to train the game officials,'' said Davis, the principal
owner of the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to have pro football's version of NASA. The
complex would have three or four football fields, living quarters.
It would be the headquarters for the officiating in our league.
Everything would be done out of there, not the league headquarters
in New York. We would still have part-time officials, but they
would have to spend a lot more time doing their job than they do
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the league did nothing about it. They want to control the
officials out of the league office in New York. I don't think that
is the best way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least once a month, I think every official in the league
should be brought up to speed on what is going on on the field
during games. You'd bring them into the central facility _ I called
it a training academy or something like that at the time _ on a
regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both during the season and in the offseason, you bring the
officials in and work them out, in the field and in the classroom.
Meanwhile, you have a lot of young people who want to be officials
in the NFL training there trying to get good enough to work in our
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be regular film study and workouts _ actually
bring them out on the field and work on their positioning. Go over
every one of their calls individually. Go over all the bad calls
that have been made to see why things happen and how they can be
corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the many recent controversial calls, the league
office has raised the possibility of using instant replay for the
playoffs. Davis doesn't see that happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, there is no way they can get the votes for it
at this time in the season,'' he said. ``But we should have instant
replay. We should have a system that works.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bill) Parcells was right the other day when he said we as a
league should do everything we can to make sure the right call is
being made, and instant replay would certainly help. Howie Long
said the other day on TV that we have the technology to drop a bomb
from 45,000 feet out of a plane and down someone's chimney, but we
can't get technology to help make the right call?''
</P>
<P>
   Tex Schramm, the former Dallas Cowboys general manager and, like
Davis, one of the most creative minds in the history of the game,
is recognized as the father of instant replay in the NFL. He was
chairman of the Competition Committee and got it passed back in the
1980s when Rozelle was commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do bring instant replay back for the playoffs, I hope
they do not use what happens to judge using it in the future,''
said Schramm. ``Anything is better than what they have now, but the
NFL has to bring it back and use all of the electronic technology
available to make it better than ever in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't compare the electronic technology when we started
replay in the '80s to where it is today. Hell, you can't compare it
to seven years ago when they last used replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league should have instant replay. The problem we had when
I was there was that it was only voted in one year at a time. You
never had enough time to experiment to make it better for the
future. We were battling every year to keep it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I would like to see happen is the league bring it back,
but with a five-year commitment. Not for a year at a time. Make a
long-term commitment and then bring in all of the best technicians
from the television industry as consultants on how the league could
best use what these people have developed in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``These officials are good people. They want to get the calls
right. But it is a tough job. When the league had replay, we did
not take the right approach. We used former game officials and
people out of the league office to be the replay official at 14
games around the league each week. We put a lot of people in jobs
they should not have been doing. We did not go out and get the best
people available. Like everything else, there are just some people
who would have a better aptitude for a job like this compared to
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Dallas, we had a coach name Ermal Allen. You
never saw a guy who could break down film, and make the right call
every time, as fast as he did it. He just had that knack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should develop a test to find this kind of a person, just
like they do when they test for astronauts. You test their
judgment, their reaction time. But most importantly, don't do
replay unless you are going to do it right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners seem to be afraid of technology. This is not the
game of the 1940s and 1950s anymore. Officials could get away with
mistakes because that was before (games on) television and long
before replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many fans today do you think realize that the quarterback
has a transmitter in his helmet and they send all of the plays in
electronically? I bet no more than 10 percent would realize that.
Yet we've had it for years, and the owners didn't want it at first.
It is no longer an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would it be impossible to put some kind of computer chip in a
football that would tell if the ball went across the goal line?
They have minicams in race cars and little cameras on the heads of
catchers in baseball. No one would have thought of these things 10
years ago, and now they are the wave of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started in this business nearly 60 years ago, the three
big sports in this country were baseball, horse racing, boxing.
Baseball is dying. And the other two are close to dead compared to
what they used to be. The NFL better realize that it might not
always be the great game it has been.''
</P>
<P>
   Schramm told a little story that illustrates the plight of the
present official in the NFL:
</P>
<P>
   ``This was back a few years ago when we had instant replay. I
was talking with one of our game officials, and he told me that if
he made a bad call during a game and it cost the losing team that
game, he has the worst trip to the airport. The worst flight home.
The worst night's sleep. He said he welcomed replay to help because
it could change his mistake. All he wanted was to make the right
call. He didn't want to cost any team a game. The NFL should feel
the same way as a league.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Schramm realize that officiating in the league should
head in a new direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with Tex the other day,'' said Davis. ``We talked
about the central training facility for officials. We talked about
it being the experimental laboratory for replay officials.
Officiating is so much a part of our game that we should do
everything we can to perfect it as much as we can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me give you an example. We lost to Denver twice this year.
In those two games combined, the NFL told us that Denver scored
five touchdowns _ three in one game and two in another _ that
should have not been allowed if the right calls were made. That's
not me saying that, this is the NFL in the report that comes back
to us. I'm not saying we would have beaten Denver if those plays
were called right. That's not the purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I am trying to say is that if we trained the officials as
hard as we train the players, and we scouted and recruited the
officials as hard as we do to get the the best players, and then we
combined it with the best possible instant replay system, there is
no question that these things would make the officiating better
than it is now.''
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1338EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
