<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-HOSPITAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HONDURAS, A HOSPITAL HAS FALLEN ILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras _ Normally at the Hospital Escuela, nine
elevators work. Now, only two of them do.
</P>
<P>
   A clock in the main lobby marks 8:37, but no one can remember
when it stopped running. Nearly everywhere along the white ceiling
panels of the country's largest medical facility are plate-sized
water stains. And a musty stench wafts through the narrow hallways
near the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   These, however, are the minor problems facing Honduras's only
teaching hospital, whose name in English means, ``school.'' Now,
almost two months after Hurricane Mitch barrelled through this
country with heavy winds and nearly four straight days of heavy
rains, the doctors, nurses and administrators here are finding
harder than ever to keep people healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more of everything,'' Carlos Bueso, the hospital's
44-year-old director, said Tuesday while sitting in his office,
filled with a pyramid of boxes of recently donated supplies. ``We
need more medicines and more doctors, but we especially need more
nurses.''
</P>
<P>
   As the country continues to rebuild itself after Mitch, health
officials are concerned that diseases such as cholera,
leptospirosis, malaria and dengue could spread to epidemic
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   In Honduras, scores of medical teams are combing the cities and
countryside to examine and vaccinate residents. Tegucigalpa has
three other public hospitals, but Escuela remains the country's
main healthcare institution.
</P>
<P>
   Escuela, which opened 31 years ago, is a rambling,
salmon-colored structure that sits in the heart of the capital,
Tegucigalpa. As the country's population has grown, so has the
hospital, which now holds 1,500 beds and operates several
out-patient clinics.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital treats about 4,500 patients a day, Bueso said. It
has about 250 staff physicians, 910 nurses and another 80
post-graduate residents.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the hurricane, Escuela's annual budget of about $12
million was running close to $1 million a month. That figure is
probably higher now, Bueso said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take in patients from all over Honduras, most of them very
poor,'' he added. ``And on top of all that, we got hit with
Mitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said the hospital has seen an increase in patients with
fevers, diarrhea and other symptoms typically associated with
exposure to contaminated mud and water, although not the kind of
large-scale epidemics that the government reportedly stated last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Escuela was hit hard by Mitch. The storm severely
damaged its water piping system and left it without usable water
for the first few days after the hurricane. Its supplies of
vaccines are running low.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the elevator problem, most of the staff and visitors
had to climb dimly lit stairs, while patients on gurneys and in
wheelchairs were forced to wait in long lines to get to their next
lab test or back to their rooms. Those patients who could walk made
their way slowly up the stairs, holding tightly to the metal
railing.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials don't know exactly how many people have died
at Escuela since Mitch. As of Tuesday, four children have died from
dengue, a mosquito-borne fever which, in its most serious form, can
cause pain and deadly hemorrhaging.
</P>
<P>
   On the hospital's sixth floor, which serves male patients with
varying illnesses, four men lie in a room where beds are two feet
apart. There are no IVs, and the closest bathroom was in the main
hallway. The toilet and sink were backed up.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors scurried in white coats and sneakers, examining doe-eyed
boys and frail old men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to fill out all these forms just to get my patient into
surgery,'' said one young doctor. ``With all this bureaucracy and
the time we'll have to wait, he'll probably die.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of another hall, Mariano Lobo, 55, sat on the edge of
his bed next to a plastic bag filled with his clothes. After
arriving to the hospital two weeks ago with deungue-like symptoms,
he was feeling better and ready to go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person next to me had the same symptoms, but he died,''
said Lobo, a watch repairman whose face, arms and eyes were still
yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Hector Rolando Galdanez, 42, another patient in the same room
who contracted malaria, fidgeted as he talked about the work he'd
missed over the last seven days that he has been in Escuela.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work with pigs, so that's probably how I got sick,'' he
said. ``But I'm very bored in here and I need to get back to work.
I think I have to be more careful about the things I touch from now
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
