<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0634 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CULTURE-2TAKES-B     12-09 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CULTURE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURAL RECIPES BRIGHTEN THIS YEAR'S COOKBOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life moves so fast it's hard to squeeze everything in _ even the
nightly family supper. Perhaps that's why this year's cookbooks
have a girl-next-door quality, offering volumes about familiar food
or enticing dishes integral to faraway cultures. As the century
rushes to a close, we seem drawn to slower times. In past years,
this emotion translated into nostalgia for, say, meatloaf and
mashed potatoes. Today's writers are more sophisticated, better
traveled, and less satisfied with the ordinary. Recipes might still
carry a homespun quality, but they're intriguing in the kitchen,
loaded with surprising flavors, yet true to their origins. These
days, someone else's mother, who might live at the end of a dirt
road in Turkey, Tunisia, or Thailand, is now invited to unravel
family fare for our dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   The new cultural aspect to cookbooks is one of the most exciting
elements of the modern kitchen. You can make a recipe using
ingredients you've used all your life, yet the way they're prepared
for the pot can teach you something new. An ingredient or technique
adapted to classics in your own repertory is a gift. Finding a
recipe that becomes a family ritual is worth the price of the book.
</P>
<P>
   The writer who practically invented cultural cookbook writing is
Paula Wolfert. After 30 years, she remains the master. Her sixth
book, ``Mediterranean Grains and Greens'' (HarperCollins, $27.50),
covers grains from the earliest civilizations and greens that might
have been collected by hunters and gatherers. Wolfert has a cult
following among restaurateurs because she can sift through the
markets in a foreign country and come up with the one ingredient
chefs will fall on. In ``Grains and Greens,'' she offers Maras
peppers from Turkey, which are delightfully smoky, and hot but not
fiery, and the Spanish paprika ``pimenton,'' made from peppers
dried over wood fires. Her main ingredients include nettles,
salsify greens, wild mustard, borage leaves, farro, couscous,
barley couscous, bulgur, and rice.
</P>
<P>
   The list does seems to add up to an odd stew but, stoveside,
``Grains and Greens'' is fascinating. Even if you aren't foraging
for greens before you begin, you do have to hunt for a superb
specialty market or Middle Eastern store because her seasonings are
what make this food exceptional. In her Spanish gratin of leafy
greens and crispy potatoes with smoky paprika and whipped eggs,
layers of sauteed greens go into the baking dish with sliced roast
potatoes and an egg custard. Seasoned with the Spanish pimenton,
the dish is beautiful _ mildly bitter, sweet, creamy, and smoky all
at once. Her tabbouleh is mostly salad with only a little grain,
seasoned with cinnamon, cumin, and Turkish red peppers. Mustard
greens with black-eyed peas, rice, and ground lamb was an
intriguing pilaf-style dish, simmered with tomato paste, red pepper
paste, and hot pepper flakes. Arugula, cabbage, and spinach, a
salad from Cyprus with cilantro and olives and plenty of lemon, is
delightfully tart. Wherever you open this book, you'll find some
exciting flavor or technique never written about before.
</P>
<P>
   Like Wolfert, Barbara Kafka just keeps getting better. Her
``Soup, A Way of Life'' (Artisan, $35) is part cookbook, part
culinary memoir, filled with stories of the important people in her
family: her grandmother Dora, poor but generous, willing to water
down the chicken soup to put one more plate at the table; her
grandmother Sara, who supported 13 children by running a bakery and
inn; her mother, Lilian, who served her father split-pea soup made
with laundry starch, so he was forced to hire a cook for the
family. ``When I am tired and want comfort,'' writes Kafka, ``when
I want to share happiness, or when I want flavor, my first desire
is soup.'' Recipes include Vietnamese chicken soup, Chinese chicken
in the pot, white bean soup with confit and tomato, Portuguese cod
soup. In the recipe for red Russian soup, Kafka explains that her
heritage is a long line of socialists rather than observant Jews,
so she prefers to make borscht with pork. You can also use beef
short ribs. It is an endless amount of work, but certainly worth
the effort.
</P>
<P>
   When Jeffrey Alford and Naomi Duguid came to Boston last month
to lecture to the Culinary Historians of New England, Duguid
mentioned that Publishers Weekly had called the couple
``agricultural geeks.'' ``The name suits us perfectly,'' she said.
So it does. This husband-wife team travels several months of the
year, including long stretches with their two young sons, in search
of growing fields. Their subject this time took them through China,
Japan, India, and the Mediterranean. ``Seductions of Rice,'' by
Jeffrey Alford and Naomi Duguid (Artisan, $35), is a comprehensive
guide to every major rice in the world, a cultural glance at the
way people in rice-eating regions live, at how they grow and
harvest the grain, feed their families, and spend their days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yellow Farmhouse Cookbook,'' by Christopher Kimball
(Little, Brown, $27.95), recalls meals at a time when life in
America moved more slowly, when families had Sunday dinner after
church, and when no one had to guess what was in the food. Kimball
writes nostalgically about the yellow farmhouse he visited as a boy
in Vermont, near the country house he now owns with his wife and
four children. As in his magazine Cook's Illustrated, what you get
here are perfect renditions (with excrucriatingly exact
instructions) of very familiar recipes. What saves the book is that
they work (gorgeous baking powder biscuits among them) and they're
not altogether predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Legal Sea Foods threw its consulting chef Jasper White a book
party earlier this year and the food _ all from ``Lobster at Home''
(Scribner, $30) _ was fabulous. The foodie crowd dined on crunchy
lobster pad Thai, rich lobster tomalley toasts, hot Vietnamese
cabbage salad with lobster, and refreshing gazpacho with lobster.
``Lobster'' is White at his best. He understands this rich
crustacean and, as an adopted New Englander and former restaurant
owner, he brings a refreshing palate to some tired regional
specialties. His celebrated ``Jasper White's Cooking From New
England'' (Biscuit Books, $14.98) is a reprint, issued by a
division of Jessica's Biscuit of Newton. Creamy haddock chowder,
made with fresh and smoked fish, salt pork, and new potatoes,
garnished with chopped hard-cooked eggs and common crackers that
are split, buttered, and toasted, is the gold standard. At least in
my house.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional Jewish cooking of Joyce Goldstein's Crown
Heights, N.Y., childhood was turned upside down when she went to
live in Italy and happened to stay in an Italian Jewish home. What
it had in common with her family table, she writes in ``Cucina
Ebraica: Flavors of the Italian Jewish Kitchen (Chronicle Books,
$29.95), was watery chicken soup and dry meat. But it made
Goldstein curious to learn more about the Sephardic cooking of
Roman Jews, one of the oldest Jewish communities in the West. This
cuisine was established before the New World, so tomatoes, peppers,
and potatoes, foods that give the cuisine character today, were not
in the old recipes. But there was an affinity for the sweet-sour
foods that Arab traders brought, along with eggplant, pine nuts,
rice, raisins, and artichokes. Goldstein, who used to own Square
One restaurant in San Francisco, researched the cooking for years.
Some of it ended up on her restaurant menu, much adapted to modern
tastes. She felt obliged to shorten cooking times, she writes, add
more seasoning, and make the food delicious _ not just authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Authenticity has its shortcomings. It can sometimes drive the
cook away. I stuck with ``The Basque Table,'' by Teresa Barrenechea
with Mary Goodbody (Harvard Common Press, $22.95), because I know
the French Pays-Basque. Basques seem like cowboys, which is fitting
when you consider that they live, fairly isolated, in the
mountainous region of the Pyrenees. On the Atlantic side, the
coastline is very rugged, filled with fishing boats. The food lives
up to this coarse landscape, loaded as it is with oil, rich fish,
and meat. Nothing is particularly light, but it's all very good.
``The Basque Table'' offers the Spanish tradition. Barrenechea, who
comes from Bilbao, where the new Guggenheim Museum is located, owns
the Marichu restaurants in New York.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
