<HEADER>
A0637 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE10-COX     12-09 2016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crumble cookie rut with gift ideas from Web
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Besides the gifts we give to our nearest and dearest, the
holiday season presents an opportunity to show our appreciation and
give back something to the people we come in contact with every
day, who make a difference in our daily lives. From the security
guard who bids us good morning, to the waitress at the coffee shop,
the teller at the bank, the bus driver, mailman, parking lot
attendant, store clerk _ all familiar people who often make our day
with a smile but whom we may take for granted during the year.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours spent in a warm, cozy kitchen can yield gifts for
all these people and engender good feelings throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   The most familiar kitchen gifts around the holidays include jams
and jellies, fudge, brownies, chocolate chip cookies and, of
course, fruitcake, mostly packaged in colorful tins. While these
more predictable homemade gifts are always appreciated, they may be
a bit ho-hum. With the help of the Internet, this may be the year
to think out of the box (or the tin, if you will) and go for the
squeal of delight instead of the polite, ``how thoughtful.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of sites on the Internet offer innovative
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   You will find easy recipes for Crunchy Biscotti, Chocolate
Truffles, Almond Bark, Rum Balls and Peanut Brittle, all in
imaginative containers, listed at
http://www.systechcanada.com/christmas/gifts.html. If you are
determined to continue the fudge, brownie and cookie tradition,
that's fine, too, but how about varying the container from a tin to
a jar to add interest? At http://members.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   /kyrene/kitgifts.html you'll find directions and ideas for
putting baked goods in jars.
</P>
<P>
   To get away from the sweet stuff, take a look at
http://members.aol.com/kyrene/kitgifts.htmlEasy for easy-to-make
cheese spreads, glazed nuts and homemade vanilla extract.
</P>
<P>
   Unusual jams and jellies are featured at
http://soar.berkeley.edu/recipes/jams/index0.html, where you will
find things like garlic, horseradish and apricot-jalapeno jelly,
all guaranteed to be one-of-a-kind gifts.
</P>
<P>
   At http://secure.foodwine.com/food/egg/egg1096/slth1096.html
find a list of simple-to-put-together beverage mixes that you can
make from available ingredients. For instance, a cappuccino mix
needs only instant nondairy creamer, chocolate milk mix, instant
coffee, sugar, cinnamon and nutmeg. A few years ago, flavored oils
were a popular homemade gift. If you are thinking of going in that
direction, better check out http://www.news.uconn.edu/rel95422.htm,
which is a university study indicating the dangers in making
flavored oils that you may as well avoid.
</P>
<P>
   For the best-all-around site for kitchen gifts, we nominate 
http://www.kitchenlink.com/cgi/publicautoframes?dir &QC; holiday&AMP;page &QC; mer
rygifts. There are the requisite imaginative recipes, including
those for candies, jellies and liqueurs, but also articles from
newspapers and magazines on homemade gifts and information on
containers and precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you decide to make, you will know that a gift made in
the heart of the home, the kitchen, comes from the heart of the
giver.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.systechcanada.com/christmas/albark.html
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Almond Bark
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 1/4 pounds
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 1 to 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   1pound white chocolate (in block form, not chips)
</P>
<P>
   1cup unsalted natural almonds
</P>
<P>
   Butter a cookie sheet or line with parchment or wax paper. Cut
white chocolate into small pieces. Be careful to use dry bowls,
boards, pots and utensils, as water will cause the candy to seize.
In a heavy pot on low heat, melt chocolate slowly,
stirring &UR; BC-FOOD-SOUP-RECIPES10-2TAKES-COX
</P>
<P>
   By Elizabeth Lee
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Any of these soups would make a warm and comforting welcome for
a special occasion _ or for no occasion at all.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Wild Mushroom and Artichoke Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Using wild mushrooms in soups is a favorite technique of
``Souper'' Jenny Levison, who specializes in from-scratch
concoctions.
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped carrot
</P>
<P>
   2 cups diced shiitake mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   2 cups diced oyster mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sliced domestic white mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   8 cups vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped water-packed artichoke hearts, drained, rinsed
and drained again
</P>
<P>
   Fresh parsley, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cream (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in Dutch oven over medium-low heat. Add onion, celery
and carrot and saute until softened, about 10 minutes. Add
shiitake, oyster and white mushrooms and cook until most of the
water is evaporated, about 7 minutes. Add sherry and cook 5
minutes. Add vegetable stock; cover and cook on low heat for 25
minutes. Add artichoke hearts, parsley and salt and pepper to
taste. Simmer for 5 minutes until heated through. Add a touch of
cream if desired. _ From Jenny Levison, owner of Souper Jenny's in
Buckhead
</P>
<P>
   Per cup: 122 calories, 4 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 42), 13 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 85
milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Simple White Bean Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cookbook author Barbara Kafka, who admits she frequently uses
canned beans, says that this soup gives good results in a hurry.
It's easy to put together using store-bought ingredients; she
recommends making the pesto sauce yourself, without nuts. But it,
too, can be picked up at a grocery store. Our tester notes it would
also be good pureed.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken stock or broth
</P>
<P>
   5 cups cooked small white beans, or two 19-ounce cans small
white beans, drained and rinsed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons pesto sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, bring the stock and beans to a boil. Lower
the heat. Stir in pesto sauce, cheese and pepper. Simmer for 1
minute. _ From Barbara Kafka's ``Soup: A Way of Life'' (Artisan,
$35)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 324 calories, 18 grams protein, 7 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 19), 49 grams carbohydrates, 4
milligrams cholesterol, 107 milligrams sodium, 10 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Tomato, Sausage
</P>
<P>
   and Eggplant Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A hearty filler for cold winter nights from Atlanta caterer
Robbin Churchill of To Dine For, this soup makes a good main course
for a gathering of friends.
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup plus 2 tablespoons olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2 cups cubed eggplant ( 1/2-inch cubes), about 1 large
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped fennel or celery
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground or crushed fennel seed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 teaspoons dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 pound sweet Italian sausage, casing removed
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1 29-ounce can heavy tomato puree
</P>
<P>
   1 28-ounce can whole peeled tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   In a 4-to-5-quart saucepan, heat 1/3 cup olive oil. Add the
eggplant and 1/2 teaspoon salt. Saute over medium-high heat,
stirring frequently, for 4 to 5 minutes, or until just tender.
Transfer the eggplant to a bowl. In the same pan, heat the
remaining 2 tablespoons olive oil. Add the onions, fennel or
celery, garlic, fennel seed, pepper, bay leaves, remaining teaspoon
of salt, basil and thyme. Cook over medium-high heat, stirring
frequently, for 5 to 6 minutes. Add the sausage and saute, breaking
up the meat into small pieces with a spoon. Add the chicken stock,
tomato puree, chopped tomatoes with their juice and the eggplant.
Cover and simmer 10-15 minutes. If the soup seems too thick, add
more stock. Remove bay leaves before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per cup: 181 calories, 6 grams protein, 13 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 65), 12 grams carbohydrates, 15 milligrams
cholesterol, 496 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Oyster Stew
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 first-course servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Retired caterer Linda Wible, who tends a community herb garden
in Buckhead, has been making this wonderfully rich stew for years.
She cooks soup at least once a week and shares the extra. It's her
holiday gift to neighbors, ladled out once a week throughout the
year. With this recipe, she recommends using thyme to add piquancy
without overwhelming the oysters. This stew makes a good first
course for an elegant dinner party.
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons ( 1/2 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, chopped (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 to 1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 8-ounce bottle clam juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup white wine (optional if you want soup thinner)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh thyme or chives, or 1 1/2 teaspoons dried
</P>
<P>
   1 pint oysters
</P>
<P>
   Minced parsley (for garnish)
</P>
<P>
   4 half-teaspoons butter (for garnish)
</P>
<P>
   In a large saucepan, melt butter and add oil over medium-high
heat. When butter has melted, add onion and shallots and cook until
soft but not brown, about 3 minutes. Add flour to make a light
roux; cook 3 to 5 minutes, stirring constantly, but do not brown.
Add salt, white pepper, cream (adjust quantity for desired
consistency of soup) and clam juice. If you'd like a thinner soup,
add the white wine. Reduce heat to medium and simmer until slightly
thickened, about 10 minutes. Add thyme or chives and oysters. Cook
oysters just until edges are curled, about 1 minute. To serve,
ladle soup into bowls and top with a sprinkling of chopped parsley
and a pat of butter. _ From Linda Wible
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 314 calories, 11 grams protein, 25 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 72), 12 grams carbohydrates, 130
milligrams cholesterol, 1,188 milligrams sodium., 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Wild Rice Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour, 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Dill and almonds elevate the flavor of this soup above the
everyday, and bright colors give it a visual punch. Wild rice makes
it even more special. Wild rice is expensive (we paid $4.29 for the
12 ounces the recipe calls for), and some supermarkets may not
carry it. If you have trouble finding it, check out a farmers
market. Try to get hand-harvested rice; it has a softer texture and
subtler flavor than machine-harvested rice.
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons ( 1/2 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   4 celery ribs, diced
</P>
<P>
   2 large carrots, diced
</P>
<P>
   2 small onions, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sliced green onions
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup slivered almonds
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh dill
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon turmeric
</P>
<P>
   3 quarts chicken stock (or low-sodium canned chicken broth) or
as needed
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups wild rice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup white rice
</P>
<P>
   4 cups diced cooked chicken
</P>
<P>
   3 cups sliced mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in large heavy skillet over medium heat. Add celery,
carrots, onions and almonds and cook until slightly softened,
stirring occasionally, about 5 minutes. Mix in dill, bay leaves and
turmeric. Bring 3 quarts of stock, wild rice and white rice to boil
in large pot. Reduce heat. Add celery mixture and simmer 30
minutes, adding more stock if soup is too thick. Add chicken and
mushrooms. Discard bay leaves and simmer 10 minutes or until
chicken and mushrooms are heated through. Salt and pepper to taste.
_ From Kathie Jenkins, food editor of the St. Paul Pioneer Press
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 308 calories, 21 grams protein, 12 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 36), 30 grams carbohydrates, 53
milligrams cholesterol, 144 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
