<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Homemade tops cheesy canned soup
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marjorie Baker (e-mail) sent this recipe for Annette Wade, who
misses the Campbell's version, which has been taken off the market.
Baker thinks this one is better and hopes it will be an adequate
substitute.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Broccoli Cheese Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 quarts
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3cups water
</P>
<P>
   210-ounce packages frozen chopped broccoli, thawed
</P>
<P>
   4chicken bouillon cubes or 4 teaspoons chicken-flavored instant
bouillon
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   3cups shredded Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1cup low-fat milk
</P>
<P>
   In Dutch oven, melt margarine. Add onion and cook until tender.
Stir in flour until smooth. Gradually add water, then broccoli,
bouillon and Worcestershire sauce. Cook and stir over medium heat
until thickened and broccoli is tender, about 10 minutes. Add
cheese, half-and-half and milk. Cook and stir until cheese melts
and soup is hot, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per cup: 335 calories, 16 grams protein, 26 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 69), 12 grams carbohydrates, 63 milligrams
cholesterol, 974 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sheila Richardson of Dahlonega(Ga.) seeks a corn bread salad
recipe such as one served at Ancheaux's restaurant in Clemson, S.C.
It includes moist corn bread, cucumbers, tomatoes, bell peppers,
corn and other ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Leslie Booth of Fayetteville(Ga.) is looking for a recipe for
restaurant-quality wing sauce _ something with more to it than
Tabasco sauce and butter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  No responses came when Caryn Hanrahan (e-mail) asked last
summer for a cold salad with black-eyed peas and pineapple. We're
trying again, since we agree with her that it sounds good to serve
on New Year's Day.
</P>
