<HEADER>
A0645 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWER-MERGERS-BOS &LR;      12-09 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-MERGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID MERGERS, N.E. ELECTRIC DOESN'T PLAN TO BE LEFT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does New England Electric System have the juice to compete in
the rapidly consolidating electric utility market?
</P>
<P>
   That's the big question following the formal announcement Monday
that BEC Energy, parent of Boston Edison Co., will acquire
Commonwealth Energy System for $950 million in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   New England Electric, based in Westborough, Mass., is expected
to respond to the combination of its two big Massachusetts
counterparts by doing some shopping of its own, according to
industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``New England Electric has to look at other utilities in
high-density areas that can give them some cost advantages without
too many problems, while at the same time fielding inquiries from
out-of-state utilities that want a foothold in New England,'' said
Stephen Maloney, president of Devonrue Ltd., a Hingham consulting
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Sergel, New England Electric's chief executive, was not
available to comment Monday, according to a company spokesman. But
Sergel has said previously that his company, which serves 970,000
customers in 146 cities and towns in Massachusetts, will expand
through acquisitions. Like BEC Energy, New England Electric sees
its future as the predominant distributor of electricity in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Just how both large companies would compete _ BEC/Commonwealth
Energy together will have 1.3 million customers _ has fueled
renewed speculation of a possible deal between them. Such a
combination was considered more than 20 years ago but was rejected
as monopolistic.
</P>
<P>
   But much has changed.
</P>
<P>
   New rules took effect in March that will allow businesses and
eventually consumers to choose their electricity supplier much like
they pick a long-distance telephone company. Investor-owned
utilities have decided to exit the power generating business and
focus on providing services to subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like BEC and New England Electric _ and state
regulators _ view mergers and acquisitions as a potential way to
lower rates by spreading costs over a larger base of customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until 1994, regulators were skeptical about mergers and
acquisitions because the premium one company paid for another would
limit any benefits to consumers, so we looked at deals on a
case-by-case basis,'' said Janet Gail Besser, commissioner of the
state Department of Telecommunications and Energy, which regulates
utilities. ``But with competition, we recognize that combinations
of companies will reduce costs to customers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people believe the utility industry will consolidate
and the Boston Edison-Com/Energy deal is the first step,'' said
John Stephens, president of Boston-based Eastern Utilities
Associates, which serves about 200,000 customers in Southeastern
Massachusetts and 100,000 customers in Rhode Island. ``In fact, we
have said publicly that we too are open to a merger or
acquisition.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike California, which is served by just three investor-owned
electric utilities, Massachusetts has six investor-owned companies
and more than 30 small municipal-owned firms.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney, the consultant, maintains New England Electric may
consider some of the municipal firms or some of the other
investor-owned utilities in Massachusetts such as Eastern Utilities
_ deals that would expand the company's customer base with
relatively few problems.
</P>
<P>
   Larger potential candidates from outside the Bay State would
present New England Electric with significant hurdles, adds
Maloney. Central Maine Power, for example, recently said that
Florida Power &AMP; Light Co. had backed out of a deal to purchase its
generating plants. United Illuminating Co. of New Haven is burdened
by a high cost structure and aging electric generation facilities.
</P>
<P>
   And the big wild card is Northeast Utilities, New England's
largest electric company with operations spread across western
Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Connecticut. The Berlin,
Conn.-based company has been hobbled by financial, operational, and
regulatory problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``New England Electric is in a good position as one of the
strongest and best run companies, but they want to be the acquiring
company, not the acquiree,'' said Stephen M. Tuleja, president of
Alternate Power Source Inc., a Westwood energy broker.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal announced Monday, BEC Energy will pay $950
million, or $44.10 a share, for Commonwealth Energy, based in
Cambridge, Mass., and assume $600 million in debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
