</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SOUP-RECIPES10-2NDTAKE-CO </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Red Pepper Soup With Corn Bread Croutons
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 55 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Silky smooth and richly flavored, this soup lets you enjoy
garden goodness even in dreary winter weather. Its colors _ deep
red, dotted with green marjoram _ make it especially nice for a
holiday meal.
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 small potato, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped marjoram, plus extra for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   3 or 4 large red bell peppers, roasted and coarsely chopped
(procedure follows)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sweet paprika
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly milled pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 quart water or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   Balsamic vinegar to taste
</P>
<P>
   Corn bread croutons (procedure follows)
</P>
<P>
   To roast peppers: Cut off the top of the peppers, then slice
them in half lengthwise, remove the seeds and veins and press down
on each half to flatten. Brush the skins with olive oil, then set
them, skin side up, on a cookie sheet. Bake at 400 degrees or broil
5 to 6 inches under the heating element until the skins are
blistered and charred, about 15-20 minutes. Remove peppers, stack
on top of each other and place in covered bowl or plastic bag to
let steam for 15 minutes. Rub off the skins and discard them.
</P>
<P>
   For croutons: Cube a couple of pieces of room-temperature corn
bread and place on a cookie sheet at 200 degrees. Bake about 15
minutes, or until dry throughout. To save time, we bought corn
bread from a restaurant rather than baking our own, then followed
the steps above for turning it into croutons. It worked just fine.
</P>
<P>
   For soup: Heat the oil in a soup pot and add onion, potato,
garlic, bay leaf and marjoram. Saute over high heat, stirring
often, until potato and onion begin to brown, about 12 minutes. Add
tomato paste and cook for 1 minute. Add the peppers, paprika and 1
teaspoon salt. Pour in the water or stock and scrape the bottom of
the pot. Bring to a boil, then lower the heat and simmer, partially
covered, for 25 minutes. Remove the bay leaf and blend the soup
until smooth. Taste for salt, season with pepper and add a teaspoon
or so of vinegar. Put croutons and a sprinkling of chopped marjoram
on top. _ Adapted from Deborah Madison's ``Vegetarian Cooking for
Everyone'' (Broadway Books, $40)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without croutons): 124 calories, 2 grams protein, 9
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 64), 11 grams carbohydrates,
no cholesterol, 32 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Potato, Escarole and Country Ham Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking time: 48
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Another colorful soup, this one combines a traditional Southern
favorite, country ham, with some unexpected ingredients. Get the
best ham you can find, because its taste figures so prominently in
the soup. The ground black pepper really pops the flavors in this
soup.
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 leek, white and light green portions, washed and minced
</P>
<P>
   1 stalk celery, trimmed and diced
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 potatoes, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 sprig fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (about 8 ounces) escarole, cleaned and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced country ham
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Heat the butter in a soup pot over low heat; add the onion,
leek, celery and garlic and stir until they are evenly coated with
butter. Cover the pot and cook until tender and translucent, 6 to 8
minutes. Add the broth, potatoes and thyme. Simmer the soup until
the potatoes are beginning to disintegrate, 15 to 20 minutes. Add
the escarole and diced ham and simmer the soup for another 12 to 15
minutes, or until all ingredients are tender. Add salt and generous
amounts of pepper to taste. Serve in a heated soup tureen or
individual bowls. _ From the Culinary Institute of America's ``An
American Bounty'' (Rizzoli, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 151 calories, 11 grams protein, 7 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 40), 11 grams carbohydrates, 29
milligrams cholesterol, 1,139 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Butternut Squash With Spiced Apple Garnish
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour, 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Pretty is as pretty does, and this soup, courtesy of dick &AMP;
harry's restaurant in Roswell, is pretty delicious as well as
good-looking, with its coral-pink apple garnish over a
pumpkin-colored puree. The soup can be blended until very smooth,
or left slightly chunky. It also can be made ahead and frozen. If
you're going to freeze it, don't add the cream.
</P>
<P>
   Spiced apples:
</P>
<P>
   2 cinnamon sticks
</P>
<P>
   1 star anise
</P>
<P>
   2 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean split in half or 1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups maraschino cherry juice (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 medium apples (Fuji, Mitsu, McIntosh or Cortland), peeled,
cored and quartered
</P>
<P>
   Soup:
</P>
<P>
   5 pounds (3 or 4) butternut squash
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions
</P>
<P>
   3 leeks
</P>
<P>
   5 ribs celery
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 gallon chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon mace, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup molasses, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 cups warmed heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   For the spiced apples: Blend spices, juice and sugar in medium
saucepan. Bring to a boil and turn off heat. Add apples and let
cool while preparing soup.
</P>
<P>
   Note: You can use the juice from two 16-ounce jars of maraschino
cherries and return the juice to the jars after using with the
apples.
</P>
<P>
   For the soup: Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Cut squash in half
and remove seeds and strings. Spray a baking sheet with nonstick
cooking spray and roast the squash, cut side down, for 45 minutes
or until tender.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, saute the onion, leeks and celery in a small
amount of oil in a heavy stockpot until the vegetables are
transparent, about 7 minutes. Scoop out the squash and add to the
pot, discarding the skins. Add the chicken stock and mace. Simmer
until all the vegetables are tender. In a food processor, puree the
soup in batches and return to the pot. Add molasses and salt and
pepper and adjust the seasonings. Stir in the cream. Drain the
apples and garnish each serving with 1 quarter-apple. _ From Harold
Marmulstein, chef of dick &AMP; harry's restaurant in Roswell
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 299 calories, 4 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 38 grams carbohydrates, 56
milligrams cholesterol, 65 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
