<HEADER>
A0648 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SOUP10-COX     12-09 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SOUP10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spoonfuls of hearty nourishment add a festive fillip to the
holidays
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tired, hungry man walks into a village. By the time he leaves
the next day, he's wrangled a soft bed, an evening of good cheer
and a hearty meal _ all courtesy of a promise to make soup.
</P>
<P>
   Potent stuff, that Stone Soup.
</P>
<P>
   The power of soup is more than folklore, though. Think about the
healing taste of chicken soup, the camaraderie of sharing a pot of
chili and a Falcons win, even the souped-up recipe enhancements of
the ubiquitous canned cream of mushroom.
</P>
<P>
   Comforting stuff, soup.
</P>
<P>
   Comforting for the cook, too. After the rigors of preparing a
multi-course Thanksgiving dinner, there's something seductively
simple about just fixing soup for a crowd _ even potions as dressed
up for holiday entertaining as shiitake mushroom and artichoke or
wild rice soup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes me feel cozy,'' says Barbara Kafka, author of
``Soup: A Way of Life'' (Artisan, $35). ``It's loving and
undemanding. Somehow the food itself says, `I'll take care of you,'
which is pretty good for a food.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty good, indeed. Kafka's book lists a couple of soups as
day-after-the-party hangover remedies, for those brave enough to
slurp up menudo or onion soup on a queasy stomach.
</P>
<P>
   But before overindulging, think about another benefit of soup:
It's filling. Serve it as a first course, and diners might be less
likely to overeat during the rest of the meal _ a welcome gift to
them during the holiday party season.
</P>
<P>
   Consider serving a rich oyster stew to start a New Year's Eve
dinner, or, for Christmas Eve, a festively colored roasted red
pepper soup. Save chicken noodle soup and other home-
</P>
<P>
   style fare for dreary January and February; now's the season to
dazzle, to spoon in the wild rice, wild mushrooms, fresh herbs and
seafood with abandon.
</P>
<P>
   Best yet, such soups aren't as complicated to make as they
sound. ``If you can boil water, you can make soup,'' promises
Kafka. ``Soup is very relaxed cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also very tolerant cooking, ``Seinfeld's'' Soup Nazi
notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Don't have time to make chicken stock? Use canned, low-sodium
broth. Feel like experimenting? Try wild mushrooms instead of
buttons, pumpkin instead of butternut squash, seafood instead of
chicken or beef. Make a mistake? Chances are it won't be noticeable
or can be fixed by adding more ingredients and enlarging the
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   If soup's the main course, it's even easier to throw a
get-together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a huge pot of soup on the stove, and everyone helps
themselves,'' says Jenny Levison, who recently opened the
from-scratch soup restaurant Souper Jenny's in Buckhead. ``You make
a salad, and that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Easiest of all _ convince your guests to bring the ingredients,
while you supply the stockpot, the water, the fire and a nice,
smooth stone.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
