<HEADER>
A0650 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORAH-COP-BOS &LR;      12-09 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORAH-COP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORAH DETECTIVE TAKES ORTHODOX APPROACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Only in New York could there be a cop like Mordecai
Dzikansky.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever anyone steals a Torah in this town, Dzikansky is the
guy who roams the rambling backstreets of Brooklyn and the Lower
East Side, goes undercover, snares the thief, and recovers the
missing treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Dzikansky, 36, is chief detective of the New York Police
Department's Torah Task Force. And New York, whose metropolitan
area is home to one-third of the nation's 6 million Jews, is the
only city in America that could support such a crime-fighting unit.
</P>
<P>
   The Torah _ the parchment scroll containing the first five Books
of the Old Testament, known as the Five Books of Moses,
painstakingly inscribed in Hebrew _ is the most sacred object in
any Jewish synagogue and the centerpiece of its religious services.
</P>
<P>
   A fine Torah, handwritten over the course of a year by a trained
scribe and emblazoned with crowns and breastplates made of inlaid
silver and gold, is worth more than $25,000, in some cases much
more.
</P>
<P>
   And so, Dzikansky noted, ``every few years, there's a rash of
Torah thefts.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force came into being six years ago, when 15 Torahs
were stolen over nine months from synagogues all over the city, as
well as from such facilities as Mount Sinai Hospital and the Jewish
Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   Dzikansky, a 16-year police veteran, was brought in on the case
for obvious reasons. He is a practicing Orthodox Jew. His father,
now retired, was for many years a prominent rabbi at Yeshiva
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were left to an average police officer, they wouldn't
know where to begin,'' said Lieutenant George Pagan, commanding
officer of the four-man task force and of the Midtown North
detective squad, where the task force works.
</P>
<P>
   Dzikansky knew the city's Jewish community, especially the
insular world of the second-hand Judaica shops concentrated in the
tiny Orthodox enclaves around Essex and Hester streets on
Manhattan's Lower East Side, in the Williamsburg and Borough Park
sections of Brooklyn, and Kew Gardens in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people in these shops are very legitimate,''
Dzikansky said. ``But some of them, I wouldn't buy a sandwich
from.''
</P>
<P>
   In the most celebrated Torah-theft busts, some of these
secondhand dealers served as middlemen between the robbers and the
innocent purchasers, who were usually in Israel, where an expanding
number of synagogues provided a ready-made market.
</P>
<P>
   The shop owners, decent and corrupt alike, were a tough bunch to
penetrate _ old men with beards who eye even non-Orthodox Jews,
much less gentile police officers, with hostile suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Dzikansky, by dint of his background, could gain their trust.
</P>
<P>
   One problem in tracking down stolen Torahs, especially if the
suspected thief is Jewish, is that the Torah, which Orthodox Jews
read literally as God's word, forbids testifying against a fellow
Jew in a secular court.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a wall we face,'' Dzikansky said.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike just about any other New York detective, Dzikansky
knew a way around the wall.
</P>
<P>
   By the same Jewish law, he noted, ``the Torah is considered as
holy as a human life. You're allowed to do whatever is possible to
rescue a human life that's been kidnapped. So that pushes aside the
prohibition about testifying against another Jew. It's a powerful
tool. There's not a rabbi who can argue with that.''
</P>
<P>
   So, as the Torah Task Force became widely known among the
dealers, they grew more hesitant to take in goods that seemed
remotely hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you came in eight years ago and tried to sell a Torah,
there'd be no problem,'' Dzikansky said. ``Now, they'd be more
apprehensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The first cases that the task force cracked, the spate of 15
thefts in 1992-93, all turned out to be the work of one thief. He
was not caught until early 1996, and then by pure luck, or as
Dzikansky put it with a smile, ``divine intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   The thief, Richard Stevens, was caught trying to break into a
room at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel, which is in a part of town
covered by the Midtown North detective squad. Dzikansky, who works
there as a general detective when he's not solving Torah thefts,
happened to be in on the arrest and the debrief.
</P>
<P>
   When he started routinely asking about knowledge of other
crimes, Stevens admitted to stealing all those Torahs. He also
named the fence who put him up to the thefts and sold the
merchandise to dealers. The fence was a Hasidic Jew named Markus
``Morty'' Fogel, who ran a silver shop on West 47th Street, the
heart of the diamond district.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was astonished that a Jew could do this,'' Dzikansky
recalled. ``That someone who understands the significance of a
Torah could desecrate it by stealing one _ it's reprehensible to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force set up a sting operation, wiring Stevens and
sending him to Fogel with a Torah to sell. Fogel took the bait, the
arrest was made, both pleaded guilty, and were sent to prison.
Stevens was recently released.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent case, which took place just last October,
involved two Torahs stolen from a synagogue in Englewood, N.J. By
now, the task force's operations have become so routine, it took
just two weeks to solve.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Englewood police department called the task force in
for help. Then, its members _ among them Detective Mitchell Parker
and Sergeant Brian McCabe _ made the rounds and the phone calls,
alerting dealers and others to the situation.
</P>
<P>
   When one source called back to say he had just been offered two
Torahs, Dzikansky set up a meeting place, went there dressed up as
a rabbi, and offered to buy the Torahs for $30,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting a bargain,'' he said with a laugh. Each of them
was worth over $40,000. The transaction was made, then the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The seller, it turned out, was also the thief. ``He'd rehearsed
a story of how he came to have the Torahs,'' Dzikansky said. It
belonged to a friend in Israel who died, the story went, and his
family needed the money. ``To a layman, it would have sounded
convincing.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force had an easy time making a criminal case because
both Torahs had been treated with unique markings by the Universal
Torah Registry.
</P>
<P>
   The registry was the brainchild of David Pollock, head of the
Jewish Community Relations Council, a New York-based organization
that regularly works with the task force.
</P>
<P>
   Pollock came up with the idea in 1980, during an earlier spate
of Torah thefts, but it took several years to take hold, until a
panel of scientists figured out a way to mark the parchment without
defacing it. (A Torah consists of 60 sections sewn together; the
technique involved making 30 nearly invisible markings along the
seams.)
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of rabbis, worldwide, are registering their
Torahs, making it easier for police to recover stolen scrolls and
to prove where they came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the registry, it would be hard to prove that this is
the Torah the guy stole because you could say all Torahs look
alike,'' Dzikansky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market for used Torahs is fairly limited to begin with,''
Pollock added. ``So if you can convince people that it is hard to
sell a stolen Torah, you have most of the battle won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
