<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARKANSAS-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE WHITEWATER GUSHED, DIRT REMAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLIPPIN, Ark. _ This is the land that time and Kenneth Starr
forgot.
</P>
<P>
   As Congress drives this week toward a historic vote on whether
to impeach the president, the Whitewater Estates development that
started it all is nowhere on the agenda, nowhere in the independent
counsel's report, nowhere but here.
</P>
<P>
   In the national conversation, the only remnant is the Whitewater
name, used as shorthand to suggest presidential misdeeds, though
even that has been supplanted by the more salacious ``Lewinsky
affair.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Washington and the rest of the country have moved on,
anticipating a rendezvous with destiny over a rendezvous with an
intern, this Ozark Mountain home to 1,364 souls remains in its own
idiosyncratic orbit, stubbornly resistant to change yet in some
ways altered forever by its brush with notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all got caught up in something political, and it ruined the
deal for us, as far as privacy is concerned,'' said Whitewater
resident John Lauramoore, who has become the answer to a Whitewater
trivia question as the owner of the only home the Clintons ordered
built on the property.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor, Flippin Police Sergeant Tom Fleming, continues to
marvel that ``so much was made over a bunch of dirt and scrub. I
mean, it's two ticks and a rock, is all it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's a bit more than that: all 44 lots in the 230-acre
development have been sold _ the last one just a few months ago _
and the going rate has been around $1,000 an acre, though some
riverfront property is worth much more. Pitted dirt roads are the
only way around. To call it inhospitable is to be kind.
</P>
<P>
   But once, in the minds of Bill and Hillary Clinton, it was going
to be so much more. And once, in the eyes of Starr and his
prosecutors, it was Exhibit A in the unmaking of a president.
</P>
<P>
   The road to Whitewater goes through Flippin, a four-hour drive
north from Little Rock. The winding, undulating route glances past
the town of Toad Suck and plows directly through Clinton, Ark. It's
a lot farther from Hope, the town as well as the concept.
</P>
<P>
   A half-mile into town is a banner with the official slogan:
``Welcome to Flippin. A Place for All Seasons.'' Pontoon boats fill
some driveways, pickup trucks rule the road, and Confederate flags
snap in the wind, some with a woven patch that reads: ``I ain't
coming down.''
</P>
<P>
   Crime is low and unemployment is lower. There are more jobs than
people, in fact, as long as factory work doesn't offend.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton remains popular, and almost everyone seems to have a
story of meeting him _ at a Chamber of Commerce dinner, during a
campaign stop, at a leadership breakfast, at a high school
graduation. ``Bill Clinton could be reelected governor of Arkansas
tomorrow, and I'm a Republican,'' said Ron Lechtenberger, an
accountant from nearby Mountain Home.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists still come to town to see what all the fuss was about,
but the pace has slowed to a trickle. ``Just about two a month
nowadays. They want to tell their friends they saw Whitewater, but
all they see is trees and rocks,'' said John Thompson, clerk at the
101 Handy Mart near the development.
</P>
<P>
   There once was a sign at the entrance to Whitewater, but someone
stole it several years ago, said Fleming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just a nice little town,'' insists Brenda Young,
Flippin's clerk-treasurer. ``Whitewater put us on the map, but we
pretty much take it all in stride.''
</P>
<P>
   That's easy to say now, with the Arkansas grand jury having
closed up shop _ after 15 criminal convictions _ and Starr saying
last month he had developed no proof of impeachable offenses by
Clinton related to Arkansas activities. Some interpreted it as
exoneration of Clinton on Whitewater, but Starr said he would still
pursue wrongdoing by Clinton on land issues. Still, Whitewater
won't be Waterloo or Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   The story, briefly, dates to 1978. The Clintons, while Bill was
attorney general, teamed up with political friends Jim and Susan
McDougal to make money in what is known affectionately here as the
dirt business.
</P>
<P>
   The partners borrowed $203,000 to buy the land, most of it from
the Citizens Bank &AMP; Trust in Flippin. Shaped vaguely like an
elephant's trunk, the Whitewater site is at the junction of the
White River, famous for trout, and Crooked Creek, renowned for
bass. The partners carved out roads and awaited buyers, using
Flippin real estate agent Chris Wade as their chief salesman.
</P>
<P>
   But their timing couldn't have been worse. When interest rates
hit the high teens, Arkansas vacation homes became untouchable,
even at prices below well below $40,000. To spur sales, the
partners had a prefabricated home built on Lot 13, but even that
didn't help much. That home, dubbed the ``Hillary House,'' is the
one now owned by Lauramoore and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   One month after winning the White House, the Clintons sold their
remaining interest to McDougal for $1,000. The First Family
estimated its Whitewater losses at $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   For Starr, the question was whether the project was an ill-fated
real estate deal or an illicit way to funnel money to the
ambition-rich but dollar-poor Clintons. Similar suspicions drew
Starr to scrutinize a later, larger McDougal development outside
Little Rock, called Castle Grande, financed by loans from the
Madison Guarantee Savings and Loan Association.
</P>
<P>
   Madison, founded by McDougal, failed in 1989, at a cost to
taxpayers of more than $65 million. The investigation by Starr
included questions of whether fraud played a role and whether
Clinton, as president, tried to block Starr's inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Whitewater investigation never reached the president,
among those convicted were the McDougals and one local player:
Wade, the real estate broker and one of Flippin's most prominent
citizens. He was sentenced to 15 months in prison after pleading
guilty in 1995 to bankruptcy fraud and making a false loan
application; he said he entered the plea only because the
independent prosecutor wore down his will to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Wade is out of prison now, back at work at his Ozark Realty Co.
on Main Street. On the wall inside is a framed plot plan of
Whitewater Estates. Next to it is evidence of a moneymaking scheme
Wade dreamed up when the media hordes descended: ``dirt deeds''
signed by the McDougals that entitle the bearer to one cubic foot
of Whitewater dirt. Price: $19.95, shovels extra.
</P>
<P>
   Wade has sold dozens of the deeds, but other than that,
``nothing good has come out of any of this,'' said Darla Pemberton,
an agent in Wade's office.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has few fans here, and others are even more harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took a simple land deal that shouldn't have made the
front page of the local Yellville newspaper and turned it into a
multiyear, multimillion-dollar investigation,'' said local banker
Ron Proctor, who oversaw the Whitewater loan for more than a decade
and eventually testified about it to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the development, the Lauramoores end their day by
cozying up in front of the television in the Hillary House. It is a
modest, three-bedroom home, with wood-paneled walls and furniture
longer on comfort than style. They paid $28,000 a decade ago;
though it was sold by the Clintons, the Lauramoores said they dealt
only with Wade, the broker.
</P>
<P>
   A large man in bib overalls, John Lauramoore sat back in a
chair, spat some tobacco and complained about the media, the
government, and the loss of privacy. Then he offered a comment that
could apply not just to himself but also to the Clintons, the
McDougals, the town of Flippin, and even to Starr:
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out for us to be a complete flop, for what we
wanted, what we thought it would be. Nothing but trouble. More
trouble than it's worth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
