<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUN ARTFULLY BEARS CROSS OF CRITIC'S FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her assistant prefers not to meet at the hotel restaurant
because he worries that fans would interrupt too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to meet her, it seems,'' said David Wilcox.
</P>
<P>
   This sought-after celebrity is not a movie or music star. She's
a Roman Catholic nun who lives with an order of sisters in England
who spend most of their lives cloistered in a country monastery.
</P>
<P>
   But Sister Wendy Beckett _ with her trademark smile and
ankle-length black habit _ has emerged from behind monastery walls
to possibly become the most unlikely and famous television art
critic of our time.
</P>
<P>
   She has starred in three British television series about art,
the most recent of which, ``Sister Wendy's Story of Painting,'' was
broadcast last year in the United States and has won her a loyal
and growing following here.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Wendy was recently in Boston, where she spent several
days at the Museum of Fine Arts on a new project for US public
television focusing on six great American museums. The series of
six one-hour programs on museums in New York, Los Angleles,
Cleveland, Chicago, Boston, and Fort Lauderdale will be aired
sometime in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got an awful lot of good stuff,'' said Sister Wendy,
68, when asked why she chose the MFA as one of the great US
museums. ``It's a wonderfully thought-out museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Wendy seems a bit perplexed, even bothered by her growing
renown. She doesn't enjoy traveling to make television programs or
to promote her books, including her latest, ``Sister Wendy's
Nativity.''
</P>
<P>
   She would be just as happy, she says, leading a secluded,
anonymous life in her trailer on the grounds of the Carmelite
monastery in Quindenham in Norfolk, England. ``But this is what God
intends for me to do and so if this is the cross I must bear, so be
it,'' said Sister Wendy, who uses a wheelchair because of her
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Her celebrity happened quite by accident. Sister Wendy had
written about art for British newspapers and magazines for years,
and was asked in 1991 to participate in a program on the National
Gallery by the British Broadcast Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, as she tells it, one of the network's executives said
to other network officials: ``The only one we understood was Sister
Wendy. Give her a series.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Wendy's plainspoken but well-informed commentaries have
fueled her popularity. That style, along with her rapturous and
sometimes quite sensuous descriptions of the sexual overtones of
famous masterpieces, have Sister Wendy in high demand on the
lecture circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has got the capacity to respond to art,'' she said,
sitting in a quiet corner of a Back Bay hotel lobby during a break
from studying the MFA's collection of American decorative arts.
``Great art is about beauty, about being open to life. Art can free
us from the prison of our involvement in day-to-day concerns. It
can, at least for a moment, transport us to another dimension.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sister Wendy doesn't want her work as an art critic
regarded as having religious overtones, she does see a connection
between art and God. ``If I can show people what art truly is, they
have come nearer to God because, after all, God is beauty and
truth,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She was never tempted, she said, to become an artist or art
professional instead of a nun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born wanting to be a nun,'' she says. ``I wish I could
tell you why, but I can't. I just don't remember ever having to
decide what I wanted to do with my life. But I wouldn't recommend
it today. I would recommend young girls need to experience a bit of
life before making such a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Because she belongs to a cloistered order, Sister Wendy had to
get permission from the other sisters to travel the world promoting
art. ``They have been enormously supportive and encouraging,'' she
said. ``As I get older and as I move around I feel closer and
closer to God. I have never wavered about the choices I have made.
To be surrounded by such beautiful things and to have God. I am a
very lucky woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   Facing a growing shortage of priests, the Canadian Roman
Catholic Archdiocese of Edmonton may have to close as many as half
of its 166 parishes.
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese, which covers much of the province of Alberta
and has about 300,000 Catholics, is dealing with the same critical
issue affecting the Catholic church in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a phenomenon that is hitting every diocese in
North America and Western Europe,'' said John Acheson, author of a
110-page report, ``Faithful into the Future,'' which makes the
recommendations on closing half the Edmonton archdiocese's
parishes.
</P>
<P>
   With only 79 priests serving 166 parishes, Mass in some churches
is said only once or twice a month.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ecumenical News International, the Geneva-based
religion news agency, the recommendations have been accepted by
Archbishop Joseph MacNeil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is to move ahead with the recommendations,'' Acheson
told reporters in Canada. ``At the same time,'' he added, this is
not to be seen as a crisis for us. I think society is changing, so
our church has to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Send comments to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego Ribadeneira, Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; via e-mail to religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
