u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-09 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC SCHOOL ON PRIVATE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Massachusetts is spending hundreds of millions of public dollars
a year to close the spending gap between rich and poor school
districts. But in the end, the haves find ways to retain their
advantage over the have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Brookline High School kicked off a fund-raising
campaign with a tony $10,000-a-head cocktail party for some of its
most illustrious _ read, affluent _ alumni. The goal is to create a
$10 million endowment.
</P>
<P>
   A $10 million endowment? For a public school? Do we really think
this is what Horace Mann had in mind?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel we'll ever bridge the gap between rich and poor
because you are never going to end one-upsmanship,'' said William
Samaras, the principal of Lowell High School, who admires the
initiative of Brookline High headmaster Robert Weintraub even as he
envies his roster of rich alums.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising drive in Brookline is just the latest move
among many that is effectively privatizing public education in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Committee for Parental Choice in Education in Massachusetts
this week fell only 2,000 signatures shy of the 57,100 required for
a ballot question on the use of public funds for private schools.
The broad support for such a voucher program reflects a national
trend: A majority of Americans tell Gallup pollsters they favor the
use of tax money to pay for private schools.
</P>
<P>
   It is not an easy time to be a public school administrator, even
in Brookline. Tempting as it might be to dismiss Brookline's
endowment drive as yet another scheme to help the rich get richer,
the realities of education funding are not that simple. When the
courts ordered Massachusetts to equalize public funding for
education in 1993, wealthier communities saw their share of state
money shrink as resources were redirected to long-neglected, more
impoverished cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a good thing, to correct the imbalance and send the
money to Holyoke and Chelsea and Lowell and Lawrence. I support
that, but the reality is it left me in Brookline with declining
resources in an extremely demanding community'' says Weintraub.
``To do more things with less money, I need to find new
resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. But, given the unequal distribution of millionaires
in the Commonwealth, headmasters in places like Brookline
inevitably will have more and deeper wells to tap than principals
in places like Lowell. An endowment drive might yield big bucks in
Brookline, but how would a similar effort fare in Athol or Fall
River?
</P>
<P>
   Former governor Michael S. Dukakis is one of the Brookline grads
who traded quips with Conan O'Brien, the late-night television talk
show host (Class of '81) and Mike Wallace, the ``60 Minutes''
correspondent (Class of '35) at the endowment kickoff party Monday
night. There is an equity issue only if other school systems fail
to follow Brookline's lead, Dukakis insists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every community has its proud, successful graduates,'' Dukakis
contended. ``I will be disappointed if this idea doesn't spread to
other cities and towns. This is not a substitute for state aid,
fairly distributed, but why shouldn't we do all we can to support
our schools?''
</P>
<P>
   The $50 million in state funds that the Massachusetts Education
Reform Act has directed to Lowell in the last few years has gone a
long way toward redressing years of neglect, but Samaras says
principals in poorer communities still have to hustle to make ends
meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``No principal can sit around and wait for his superintendent to
tell him what his budget is. I have to get out there and raise
money to keep competitive. Bob Weintraub is smart to do what he's
doing. Public schools today are competing with charter schools,
with parochial schools, with vouchers, with the public's negative
image of public schools. Could I use a $10 million endowment out
here? Sure I could.''
</P>
<P>
   A $10 million endowment is pocket change compared to the
endowments of many elite Massachusetts prep schools, of course. The
endowment of Phillips Academy in Andover alone is a stunning $367
million, larger than that of many colleges. And alumni associations
and private foundations have always raised money to supplement
local public school budgets and to pay for scholarships for local
graduates.
</P>
<P>
   But Bob Weintraub has much more ambitious plans than a kitty to
pay for extra school supplies or field trips. He wants to endow
faculty chairs, to allow teachers to take sabbaticals to write
books or to further their education. He wants to expand the school
day to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the private schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
