<HEADER>
A0659 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PREPPIE-HATE-ART-BOS &LR;      12-09 1783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREPPIE-HATE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREPPIE HATE NOTE VICTIM WINS APOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE AND HILARY SARGENT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One fall day last year, 15-year-old Lucy Weber and a friend
returned from a field hockey game to her dorm at The Middlesex
School and discovered a virulent anti-Semitic note on her dresser.
</P>
<P>
   A swastika followed, and later, a note in the shower: ``Gas for
the Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   As more notes appeared over the next two months, Lucy quickly
went from victim to suspect; from school legacy _ the
great-granddaughter of the library benefactor _ to school outcast.
The prestigious Concord, Mass. prep school asked her to take a
lie-detector test and then, according to her parents and others,
whispered to parents, students, and trustees that the test's
results were inconclusive only because Lucy had a multiple
personality disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Though a police investigation was suspended and the case was
never solved, the school sent a letter to parents strongly
suggesting that Lucy had written the notes to herself. Lucy,
frustrated, withdrew from the school. And in the clubby
constellation of East Coast prep schools, the gossip went out: Lucy
was troubled, mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   After a year of chatter, Middlesex last month was forced to pay
a settlement and issue an apology to avoid a lawsuit threatened by
two prominent attorneys hired by Lucy's parents, who say the school
sacrificed their daughter's reputation to save its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were victimized more by the administration than we were by
the notes,'' says her mother, Katherine. ``The administration of
that school was motivated by expediency above all. They tried to
protect the school's image, by saying it was Lucy Weber who wrote
these notes. Because if Lucy Weber wrote the notes, then there was
no hate crime at The Middlesex School. They needed it to be Lucy,
and they rammed that square peg into that round hole.''
</P>
<P>
   At the school's insistence, neither Middlesex nor the Webers and
their attorneys could disclose the amount of the settlement, though
several sources say the school compensated the family for tuition
covering the three months remaining in the year Lucy withdrew from
the school, as well as legal fees, for a total of several tens of
thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The school unequivocally denies it was motivated by public
relations. ``Its entire motive in this matter was to get to the
bottom of what was going on so that it could remedy it,'' says John
Mason, the school's lawyer, who works at the Boston firm Ropes &AMP;
Gray. ``The school very much wanted to protect its people. It
wanted to protect Lucy.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Webers say the school ignored evidence implicating
others, coming up with a series of theories to implicate Lucy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not their problem if it's my problem,'' says Lucy,
sipping a Diet Coke at the restaurant across from her new prep
school in Connecticut. ``They totally made it my problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Middlesex, one of the nation's most exclusive prep schools,
counts former governor William F. Weld, actor William Hurt, and US
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson among its alumni. Its sprawling
grounds and colonial dorms are so much the picture of the New
England prep school that they were the setting for the 1980s movie
``School Ties,'' a film about anti-Semitism that Middlesex shows
freshmen every fall.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Weber's great-grandfather, FDR brain trust member James P.
Warburg, had perhaps the family's first encounter with
anti-Semitism at Middlesex as a student there in 1913.
</P>
<P>
   When he would pass his papers to the front of the class with
``J. Warburg'' on top, they would inevitably come back with an
``e'' in between the ``J'' and the ``W.'' That, Katherine Weber
says, was the reason he began using his middle initial.
</P>
<P>
   But Warburg liked the school enough that he sent his sons there
and even co-donated the library.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy, who is of mixed Jewish-Protestant ancestry, wasn't
thinking of family ties when she chose Middlesex. ``We never wanted
to trade on the family connection,'' Katherine says. Still, when
Lucy's acceptance letter arrived at her Conecticut home in 1996,
the Webers became, in Katherine's words, ``a Middlesex family.''
Katherine rushed to the car to affix the Middlesex decal on the
rear window. By her first month, Lucy was so happy that she vowed
in a phone call home that she would send her own children to the
school.
</P>
<P>
   There were slight glitches: a falling out with a friend, the
theft of her wallet and Prada handbag, and of the $200 that arrived
on her birthday in October. But her reports home at midterm glowed:
Lucy was ``wonderful,'' ``a delightful young woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really happy there,'' Lucy says. ``That was probably the
happiest I've ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   In early November, Lucy says, she discovered the first note.
Middlesex ordered an all-school assembly, at which it identified
Lucy, attending with her father, as the recipient of a hate note
and insisted that the school would not tolerate hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, when the swastika appeared, Middlesex called
Concord police.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy returned home for Christmas and told friends that despite
the nastiness, she loved Middlesex and wanted to go back. Yet, when
she returned in January of this year, Lucy says, she and the same
friend who discovered the first note discovered the note in the
shower. Within days, there were more notes, one with unprintable
language, and a fifth one reading, ``Lucy should have her head
smashed in by a train.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember being surprised that someone could hate me
that much,'' says Lucy, now 16. ``I didn't know I had any enemies.
It was a pretty unpleasant way to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   The school fixed a camera outside one door of her suite to try
to catch anyone leaving the notes. Around that time, the Webers
say, the school began to suspect Lucy, because she was always
around when the notes were found. The school's student newspaper
had reported an earlier incident where a black student reported a
hate note, then confessed to writing it himself.
</P>
<P>
   A report by a handwriting expert suggested the school had asked
the expert to analyze whether Lucy might have copied another
suspect's handwriting. The report says the expert could not exclude
that possibility, but neither could she rule out the other suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The school asked Lucy to take a lie-detector test, and Lucy
eagerly agreed. Katherine Weber says the polygrapher told her Lucy
passed, and complimented her on raising a lovely daughter. The
school says the polygraph was inconclusive, that Lucy neither
passed nor failed.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Lucy says, she found her field hockey team picture
scrawled with the words, ``Can't catch me ugly bitches.''
</P>
<P>
   A week after that, Lucy's father, Nick, got a call on his cell
phone from Deirdre Ling, the head of the school, as he rode home on
the New York commuter train to New Haven. Lucy, he recalls Ling
saying, was ``splitting'' between her multiple personalities, and
would have to be taken home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking we would sell our house to send Lucy to Austen
Riggs,'' he says, referring to the Stockbridge, Mass. hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents brought Lucy to a New Haven psychologist, who called
and wrote to Ling that there was no sign of mental disorder.
</P>
<P>
   The school said it would hold a judiciary committee meeting to
decide whether Lucy wrote the notes.
</P>
<P>
   At home, with Ling not returning her calls, Katherine went out
into the rain and scraped the Middlesex decal off the car.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The judiciary committee posted its verdict a week later, and a
letter from Ling went out to parents March 10. The police, the
letter said, had completed an exhaustive review and determined
there was no hate crime, ``and that the student apparently targeted
by the notes may herself have been the author of some or all of
them.'' The letter went on to note that the judiciary committee
``could not conclude that the evidence definitely implicated the
student apparently being targeted by the notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy met with Ling and the head of the judiciary committee, a
group of teachers, who told her, she says, that she had brought ``a
dark cloud'' to the school, and that there would be a dark cloud
over her integrity.
</P>
<P>
   She could stay, they told her, but Lucy said she was leaving.
She returned to public school. But over the summer, she kept
hearing stories that parents and students were saying she had been
expelled, or was mentally ill. Her roommate's mother reported being
told by Ling that Lucy was disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made it clear that she felt that Lucy had some
psychological problems,'' says the mother, Ann Guite. ``It seemed
like it was part of her defending or explaining why she was
convinced that Lucy had done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Worried that the chatter was so widespread it would affect her
prospects for college, her parents hired noted Boston lawyer Harvey
Silverglate and former assistant US attorney John Markham, who
wrote a letter to the school's trustees.
</P>
<P>
   They met with Mason and several trustees at his office, and over
several hours reached the settlement. Mason told the Webers the
school would love to take Lucy back, and denied, as he still does,
that anyone told the Webers or anyone else that Lucy was mentally
ill.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 5, a letter went out to parents, staff, and trustees
from Ling and James M. Oates, president of the school board of
trustees, apologizing for ``misleading statements'' in the March
letter. There had been no police report, it admitted, and, rather
than an exhaustive investigation, the investigation was suspended.
The implication that Lucy had written the notes was ``regrettable
and unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason, the school's lawyer, who said he would speak for Ling and
the trustees, responds, ``The school was confronted with
circumstances which it viewed as possibly pointing to Lucy. The
school did not believe the evidence was conclusive, and that's why
it didn't take any action. It also recognizes that reasonable
people can disagree on this, as to whether the school had any
evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Webers and their lawyers insist there was no evidence that
Lucy had written the anti-Semitic notes herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was supposition without any reason for it, except their
despair,'' says Nick Weber. ``You recognize your kid in agony, just
as you recognize your kid telling a half truth about a minor
matter. This was totally different from a minor matter. These
horrible things happened to her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
