trolley and bus lines until they went out of existence. No, you
don't miss things.
 &HT;    Put me in a room with a pad and a pencil and set me up against
100 people with 100 computers. I'll outcreate (everyone) in the
room.
 &HT;     (c.1998 Conde Nast Publications Inc.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (John Geirland is co-author, with Eva Sonesh-Kedar, of
``Digital Babylon,'' a book on the new-media industry, which will
appear next year.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0664 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-09 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESERVING KANSAS STATE SYSTEMATICALLY DENIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The coach doesn't strike me as being particularly warm and
cuddly, so let's not worry about him.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Snyder is not the issue. Kansas State as a team is. What
they _ and ``they'' know who ``they'' are _ have done to this team
is an embarrassment and a disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State is screaming, and well it should be. We're all
supposed to be big boys and girls, and thus in full possession of
the knowledge that life is most manifestly not fair, but what the
football establishment has done to this team by relegating it to
the Alamo Bowl and its relatively modest $1.1 million payout is, if
not criminal, absolutely shameless and cold-blooded.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, unbeaten after leading a Perils of Pauline existence
all season, plays for the national title in the Fiesta Bowl.
Florida State, a loser to 7-4 North Carolina State, will be the
opponent. Wisconsin, which lost to 9-3 Michigan, goes to the Rose
Bowl, where it will play UCLA, which lost to 8-3 Miami. Ohio State,
which lost to 6-6 Michigan State at home, will play Texas A&AMP;M
(11-2), K-State's double-overtime conqueror, in the Sugar Bowl.
Syracuse (8-3) will play Florida (9-2) in the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these eight teams will get between $11 million and $13
million for participating in what we now refer to as the Bowl
Championship Series. Kansas State, whose loss to Texas A&AMP;M on a
neutral field in a bizarre game stands out as the ``best'' of all
the solo miscues, and which is actually ranked No. 1 by one of the
ratings systems employed by the folks who bring you the BCS, is
left on the sidewalk much sadder and presumably wiser than it was a
week ago. Now the purple-clad Wildcats know that it doesn't so much
matter how you play in 1998 as it does who you are in the eyes of
football power brokers.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Kansas State Wildcats, what they are in the
judgment of the people who matter is an annoying insect buzzing
around the picnic table. Alter a play here and there, such as
quarterback Michael Bishop being impeded by his own teammate on
what might have been a game-winning touchdown jaunt, and Kansas
State would be making plans for Tempe. Now the Wildcats are stuck
in San Antonio Dec. 29, and that's not meant as an insult to San
Antonio, where a feller has been known to have a good time. San
Antonio is a fine place. But at this point in time, it's just not
the proper place for a team as deserving as Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas State people must face facts. They are not considered
members of The Club. The stated reason for their exclusion from the
Orange Bowl in favor of Florida is the assumption that the Gators
will bring a sufficient amount of people to fill the stadium.
That's probably true, but to suggest that K-State would not have
brought people in huge numbers is a huge lie. K-State has proven
itself to be an exceptional ``traveling'' school during its recent
rise to football prominence. You give 'em a bowl game, and their
fans will come and they will spend money. You can look it up.
</P>
<P>
   Let's declare this BCS business to be a farce and move on. Its
proponents say, au contraire, it has done its job, which was to
select Nos. 1 and 2 for the national championship game. Well, maybe
it did and maybe it didn't. Jeff Sagarin, whose computer still has
K-State No. 1, is very comfortable with those findings. And trust
me, he is no, as he puts it, ``Wally Cox'' who wouldn't know a
linebacker from a linotypist. He is a flesh-and-blood fan who
``shut off the telephone during the Ohio State-Michigan game.'' He
can't help it if his Maker also gave him an aptitude for
mathematics that enables him to marry the two pursuits _ math and
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Kansas State were playing Tennessee, Florida State, Ohio
State, or anyone else in this discussion on a neutral field and I
were being forced to wager $100,000 in a pick-'em game,'' says
Sagarin, ``I'd pick Kansas State. Their `on' game is better than
anyone else's `on' game.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that they are 11-1 and Tennessee is 12-0? Doesn't faze
Sagarin a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any good sports fan knows that the best team doesn't always
win,'' he points out. ``They lost a strange game to a team, Texas
A&AMP;M, that everyone has ranked in their Top 7. These things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   No system that sends Syracuse to a potential $13 million bowl
game and Kansas State to one worth $11.5 million less can be
considered to have anything to do with justice. But justice is not
the goal, anyway. The goal is to make these damnable bowl people
happy, which means full houses, period.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has changed. We are where we were a year ago, 10 years
ago, and 50 years ago; that is to say, we are without an acceptable
way to determine a national collegiate football champion.
</P>
<P>
   It's just not that hard. You have two obvious choices to come up
with an eight-team, three-week tournament.
</P>
<P>
   1. Do what they do in basketball for the NCAA tournament. A
committee, armed with charts and its own humanity, selects the
at-large teams and seeds them. Period. It's not perfect, but it
gets the job done.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, your committee, which has representatives from
administration (i.e., knowledgeable athletic directors), the
coaching ranks, and the media, picks the eight participants in the
NCAA football tournament. Eight is plenty. Four is generally
enough, but eight would make more people happy. You pick the eight,
you seed them, and you play. Period.
</P>
<P>
   2. Keep the current BCS mechanism and apply it to the task at
hand. Let the computer spit out eight teams and then let them play.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't this eliminate the bowl games, you say? Yes! And
hallelujah! Who cares about the Blazer People? This bowl game
nonsense has gone on long enough.
</P>
<P>
   The worst thing that would happen would be an unhappy No. 9
team. Boo-hoo. I'd rather have that than an unfairly trashed No. 1,
2, or 3, which is the absolute least you can say about Kansas
State.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the money, it's the principle. Oh, well, so what if it
is about the money? K-State was hosed. We all know that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
