<HEADLINE>
IN FINLAND, IT'S A RIVALRY REUNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the United States women's ice hockey team plays Canada
Thursday in the first game of the annual Three Nations Cup, the
archrivals will face each other for the first time since the Nagano
Olympics. There, the US surprised Canada with a 3-1 victory to win
the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's more difficult to come back from a big win than
a big loss,'' said Julie Sasner, who will coach the US team for
this tournament, when asked about a letdown. ``But most of them are
just thrilled to be skating together again.''
</P>
<P>
   While both rosters feature a solid core of Olympians, there are
some notable absences. In addition to several retirees, including
Massachusetts defensemen Colleen Coyne and Vicki Movsessian and
forward Sandra Whyte, a number of key players from that magical
fortnight in Nagano _ including A.J. Mleczko, Angela Ruggiero, and
Tara Mounsey _ are in the thick of their college hockey seasons and
are not a part of the US Select Team that left Monday for Finland,
although they may opt to vie for a spot on the US team that will
play for the World Championship, also in Finland, in early March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we have more youth, and we have more speed (than the
Olympic team),'' said Sasner, who will gain some valuable
international experience before returning the reigns to Ben Smith
for the World Championship. ``We have a little less size and a
little less experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasner, who played on the 1990 national team as Julie
Andeberhan, recently left her coaching post at Cornell for the
University of Wisconsin, which launches varsity hockey next season.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, only Chris Bailey and Sue Merz return from the
Nagano squad. Joining them are Winny Brodt (Roseville, Minn.) and
Amy Coehlo (North Truro), both of whom were on the 1996 US Select
Team; Kelli Halcisak, a Michigan high schooler; and Catherine
Hanson (Providence College).
</P>
<P>
   Sara DeCosta returns to goal, where backup Lauren Goldstein of
Milton and Brown University will see her first international
competition. Sarah Tueting, in net for the gold-medal game, has
returned to Dartmouth College as a pre-med student, although she,
too, could be back for the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   At forward, the US brings back a wealth of talent. Cammi
Granato, Karyn Bye, Laurie Baker, Alana Blahoski, Tricia Dunn,
Katie King, Shelley Looney and Jenny Schmidgall all return. Meaghan
Sittler, Colby's all-time leading scorer and a member of the 1996
national team, will join them, as will Brandy Fisher, the all-time
leading scorer at the University of New Hampshire and last year's
Patty Kazmaier Award winner as the outstanding player in women's
college hockey; Krissy Wendall, a Minnesota high schooler; and
Natalie Darwitz from Eagan, Minn., who just turned 15 on Oct. 13
and becomes the youngest woman every named to a US Select Team.
</P>
<P>
   For Canada, the most glaring change is in goal, where neither
Manon Rheume, who is pregnant, nor Leslie Reddon return. Also
absent will be Hayley Wickenheiser and Harvard freshman Jen
Botterill, who will instead compete for Canada in an Under-22
tournament later this month. But the team led by Danielle
Sauvageau, who had been an assistant to ousted Olympic coach
Shannon Miller, will abound in experience: witness the return of
32-year-olds Danielle Goyette, the second-leading scorer in Nagano,
and Therese Brisson, the top-scoring defenseman. France St. Louis,
who has been on the national team for a decade, turned 40 in
October _ almost 25 years to the day older than Darwitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an obvious look at the rivalry between the US and
Canada, but Finland is on the verge,'' cautions Smith. ``Finland is
doing what we were trying to do, and that's climb over somebody.
This tournament gives them the chance to get in that mode.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, the US signaled it was ready for Nagano
by beating Canada in the championship game of the Three Nations
Cup, the first time it beat Canada, still the reigning world
champions, in an international tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
