A0677 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOM-GRANATO-ART-BOS &LR;      12-09 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-GRANATO-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANATO STILL IN THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALPOLE, Mass. _ The same faceguard that protected Cammi
Granato's smile failed to hide it as she circled back to her
teammates last week, high-fiving during a lively drill at Iorio
Arena. She was back on the ice. With the US team. Still in love,
after all these years.
</P>
<P>
   Those who thought Granato might retire in well-deserved glory
after leading the US women's ice hockey team to a gold medal at the
Olympic Games in Nagano this past February are hereby required to
think again. The 27-year-old Olympic captain is now the only player
who has been with the national team since it was born in 1990, and
_ despite pursuing some post-hockey career options _ she is far
from ready to say die.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's enough for you then, yeah, that's a wonderful way to
go out, because there might not be a better way,'' Granato said
last week after practice for the Three Nations Cup, which begins
Thursday in Finland with a US-Canada rematch of the Olympic gold
medal game. ``I don't think there is. But if you have a lot of
passion still left in you and you still want to play the game of
hockey, it's very much a part of what you enjoy, then you can't
give it up.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither, in the US at least, can you play it regularly after
college. So just when Granato thought her stereotype-smashing,
gate-crashing days were history, she signed a three-year contract
this fall as radio commentator for the Los Angeles that made her
only the second woman NHL broadcaster, following sportswriter
Sherry Ross, who was with the New Jersey Devils from 1992-1995.
</P>
<P>
   A newcomer to the booth, Granato has sometimes struggled.
Knowing when to talk, knowing when to be silent, and quickly
organizing thoughts into concise snippets does not come as
naturally for her as playing the game itself. ``It's not like
picking up a hockey stick,'' she acknowledged. ``It's pretty much
the biggest challenge I've ever had to deal with. Some days, the
real world is a lot harder than playing hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the reaction of listeners, who sometimes are
skeptical despite Granato's credentials. ``I'm the only woman, so
I'm in the spotlight,'' she said. ``You don't get to be just a
rookie, there's a lot of focus on it. I'm a little uncomfortable
with it. I keep saying it builds character.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Smith, the Gloucester native and Olympic coach, said he's
sure it does. ``She's not somebody who backs away from anything,''
he said. ``She doesn't know a word that begins with the letter Q.''
</P>
<P>
   The job definitely brings its perks: games of three-on-three
after practice; tips on how to beat defensemen from Kings coach
Larry Robinson, who played the back line for 17 years with the
Montreal Canadiens; help from Luc Robitaille in finding a strength
trainer; time off to play in international tournaments. And each
new broadcast brings with it less unease, fewer glitches, and more
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really fortunate because the experience I'm gaining,
you can't replace it,'' she said. ``It's an amazing opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   But . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also miss hockey so much,'' she said. ``I watch the guys
every day, we'll go to the hotel and they'll be gearing up for
their pregame meal and it's like it's not my . . . we're not
playing a game. I envy what they have. We got to live that
lifestyle for a year (while preparing for the Olympics) and then
they take it away from you. It's kind of bittersweet. I honestly
said I haven't smiled more in my life than I did last year, just
because something that we were passionate about, we were given the
chance to do. You're given it, and then it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said other team members have expressed the same longing _
not for the glory of the gold, but simply for the chance to play
their sport again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there's a double-edged sword,'' said Smith. ``Not
only are they coming down off the height of their personal lives,
but when they come down they realize the sport just isn't up to
their speed yet.''
</P>
<P>
   With several plans for a women's professional hockey league on
indefinite hold for lack of financing, ``it kind of settles back to
the college level as the highest level of play in the country,''
said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was surprised Granato didn't retire after Nagano,
Smith paused. ``Yes and no. I know there's a part of me that says,
why would I want to coach again, because it was so exciting and
fulfilling. But coaching is what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   And playing is what she does. Why not? She's fit and strong,
with a lower back that's healthy again after aching throughout the
Olympic campaign. (``She's such a marked player,'' said Smith of
Granato keeping the injury quiet. ``She doesn't need any more
attention on the ice than she normally gets.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, yeah, I would like to be there (in 2002), only because
this is it for us,'' said Granato. ``This is our pinnacle. That's
basically our pro league, our Stanley Cup, that's where we can
flourish as athletes, where we can be elite athletes. That year
last year, and I'm not even talking about the Olympics, I'm talking
about the pre-Olympic tour, that's what I enjoyed the most. Being
on the ice every day at this level, being with my teammates, having
games, focusing on being a team, being in hotels. And I want to do
it again. I miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Cammi Granato will never again be the first female hockey
player to have a gold medal put around her neck, as she was in
Nagano. She knows that. She will never again be part of a team that
goes from such obscurity in October (women play ice hockey?
really?) to such fame in February (the White House, not to mention
Letterman's Top 10). She knows that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no replacing how special that moment was in our
lives,'' she said. ``That is something we will all cherish. But you
can't stop living. There are so many more beautiful things in life
to enjoy. There's more than one special moment in your life. Who
knows? There could be something out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
