<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0679 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-09 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP'S LOPSIDED LEADERSHIP PRESSING FOR IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Over-the-Cliff Society, also known as the Republican
congressional leadership, to employ the oxymoron, is about to risk
the stability of the nation's economy and foreign policy on an
inept, incompetent, doomed effort to impeach a president who needs
nothing more than a good dressing-down.
</P>
<P>
   The closer this lame-duck House of Representatives comes to
impeaching Clinton, the more likely that the House elected 23
months from now will turn Democratic. And the Senate may also
revert to the Democrats. If Al Gore or some dark horse Democrat
becomes president, this GOP leadership team will have blown it
bigtime.
</P>
<P>
   They shut down the government and got clobbered; they pinned
their political star to smearing Clinton with Whitewater,
Travelgate, Filegate, and Monicagate, and the first three of those
went poof! Never before has a political party with majorities in
both branches been so fellatio-fixated, betting the House's thin
majority and the Senate on bringing down a popular, twice-elected
president with the public holding consistently at a solid 2-1 for
letting him finish his term.
</P>
<P>
   Time after time, the Republican dunderheads raise partisan
posses to shoot down Clinton. Soon-to-be-ex-Senator Al D'Amato
tried it, Senator Fred Thompson tried it, House Chairman Dan Burton
tried it, and they went oh-for-three. Now it's Henry Hyde and the
Judiciary Committee trying to raise Monicagate to the level of high
crimes and misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   When will they learn? One big reason for the Republicans'
impeachment death-wish is the leadership's lopsided tilt. Nine of
10 GOP leaders in the two branches are from the south or west. In
the House, where Louisiana's Speaker-elect Bob Livingston of takes
over from Georgia's Newt Gingrich, all of the leadership
Republicans are antiabortion southerners.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Armey is from Texas, as is Tom Delay, the former
exterminator-turned-majority whip, who's been bullying the GOP
moderates to get them to vote to impeach. Delay's nickname is ``the
Hammer.'' Which makes me think of the Republican members
collectively as ``the Thumb.'' The new faces include Tom Davis of
Virginia, replacing a Georgian as head of the Republican
Congressional Committee, the fund-raising entity. J.C. Watts of
Oklahoma, the GOP's only black member, defeated an Ohio man, John
Boehner, to chair the party caucus.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Mississippi's Trent Lott kept his job as majority
leader despite loud grumbles over the GOP's failure to improve on
its 55-45 edge. Many more Republican seats than Democrat are at
risk next time, when the presidential turnout is much larger and
usually boosts Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's team? The whip is Senator Don Nickles of Oklahoma, who's
regarded as a lean and hungry Cassius ready to pounce on Lott when
he feels he has the votes to topple the leader. The chairman of the
GOP Senate Campaign Committee is Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, the
Darth Vader of campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   While Hyde is from Illinois, the heavy work in tearing down
Clinton is done by a pair of Sun Belt sons, Bob Barr of Georgia and
Bill McCollum of Florida. Barr is the one who looks like the
villainous forecloser harassing Scarlet in ``Gone With the Wind.''
McCollum is the one who looks like Howdy Doody.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston is a popular insider, ``a Louisiana deal-maker,'' in
the words of one northern Democrat. His ``Bob PAC'' raised $1
million in three weeks from lobbyists to finance his leadership
bid. But he's been astonishly silent as the House mud-wrestles with
Monica-gate, beyond saying he hopes impeachment moves out of the
House one way or another while Gingrich is still at the throttle.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston seems to have been muscled aside by Delay and the
rest of the Get Clinton crowd. Unless he takes charge of the
runaway locomotive, Livingston's first significant action will be a
failure. It'll mean he whiffed on impeachment, the biggest decision
he'll ever face. What a way to begin your reign. If the House votes
to impeach, Livingston will likely be a one-term speaker, a job he
holds by the barest majority.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans elected in the north and east, and Republican
governors who tend to be less ideologically sharp-edged than their
congressional brethren, don't want impeachment to bog down the
Senate and risk either the economy or foreign policy in a partisan
parliamentary train wreck. Governors Cellucci of Massachusetts and
Rowland of Connecticut, Mayor Rudy Giuliani of New York, and a lot
of other GOP officials, say: Don't go there!
</P>
<P>
   The regional cleavage in the ruling congressional party is
dramatic when you look at committee chairmanships. Southern or
western senators run Appropriations, Armed Services, Budget,
Commerce, Energy and Natural Resources, Foreign Relations,
Governmental Affairs, Indian Affairs, Judiciary, Rules, Small
Business, and Intelligence. In the House, southerners or westerners
run Agriculture, Appropriations, Commerce, Oversight, National
Security, Resources, Small Business, Ethics, Veterans Affairs, Ways
and Means, Intelligence, and Taxation.
</P>
<P>
   The Deep South, the Bible Belt, and the Sagebrush Rebellion crew
want Clinton impeached. The rest of the country does not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
