<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EATON THRIVES ON THE ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Long moments after the Patriots reached
their locker room in Pittsburgh Sunday afternoon, defensive line
coach Ray Hamilton was still sitting in an unusual position _ on
the bench in front of a player's locker, one particular player's
locker.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Eaton's locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've finally got this guy playing a little bit,'' Hamilton
said as a media member approached. ``It's about time he did
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The obvious pride in Hamilton's voice could not be hidden by the
joshing of his star pupil. Eaton has developed immensely this
season, becoming clearly one of the most improved defensive linemen
in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been kicking him all year,'' Hamilton went on, ``and
he's finally done something. 'Bout time, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   Then, all joshing aside, Hamilton said some heartfelt words to
Eaton: ``Good job, Chad. You did a really good job out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And the question was put to Eaton: How has it all happened?
</P>
<P>
   So the lineman turned to the coach and did his own joshing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be the coaching, huh?'' said Eaton. ``Ray Hamilton's a
great coach.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that the New England defense has played two
stronger games than it had been playing since Eaton returned after
a leg injury. Eaton has played two immense games, leading the team
in tackles against the Bills and again against the Steelers, also
sacking Pittsburgh quarterback Kordell Stewart three times and
causing a key fumble in the second half when he knocked the ball
out of Jerome Bettis's grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Eaton _ who always speaks his mind _ said before the
Buffalo game that the Patriots would do a better job stopping the
Bills' running game than they had two weeks earlier. The
difference? ``I'm the difference,'' said Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills obligingly posted Eaton's words on their locker-room
bulletin board, but he backed them up. Buffalo had gained 213 yards
rushing against New England in the first meeting _ when Eaton was
out of the lineup _ but was held to 99 in the rematch at
Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   But in Pittsburgh, Eaton topped that effort. That's because he
was often going against Dermontti Dawson, who is almost universally
regarded as the most dominant center in the NFL. But it was Eaton,
not Dawson, who dominated that matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Was this his best game ever?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Eaton. ``Wasn't it last week against the
Bills?''
</P>
<P>
   For once, Eaton gave a stock answer when asked to explain more
about his superlative play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just being healthy,'' said the lineman. ``It's just
coming back from injury and being healthy enough to make the
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, any rational observer would have said that Eaton
would be the last player in the NFL to ever be in such a spotlight.
He seemed a fringe player at best, and a frivolous one going
through a Dennis Rodman phase, dyeing his hair a different hue week
by week.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, after a dramatic 28-25 come-from-behind victory over
the Bills in Foxborough in 1996, Eaton shocked media members when
they chatted with him the next day. ``Did we win?'' he asked with a
straight face.
</P>
<P>
   But now Eaton's hair is his natural blond color week to week,
and his fame, if not notoriety, is being earned on the field, not
off it. Word of defensive linemen spreads slowly in the NFL, as
does a growth in reputation, but any who watch the tapes of Eaton
against Dawson would have to come away impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawson's great _ the best,'' said Eaton. ``No question about
it, he's the best. He's amazing. I had to have a game like this to
develop confidence for myself. You know, for me to say, `If he's
the best and I play well against him . . .' ''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton let that thought remain hanging. But the thought can be
completed by any who watched the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know what? I'm maturing,'' Eaton said. ``I'm becoming
a good defensive tackle here in the NFL. But the real thing
happening is the way our defensive line works together. We work
together to shut down the run and we make them throw the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   That's happened two weeks in a row, against teams supposedly
with strong running attacks, as first Doug Flutie had to throw and
scramble more than expected, and then Stewart had to do what he
does not do particularly well _ throw time and again from the
pocket. Even then, the pressure from Eaton and the Patriots'
blitzing left Stewart with little time to make the right throw. And
with Stewart strangely no longer a running quarterback, the New
England defense held the upper hand. All told, the Steelers gained
just 54 yards on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   All this happened with Ted Johnson gone from the field with a
torn biceps two plays into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't let down then,'' said Eaton. ``Out on the field,
you can't sit there and say, `Oh, it's over with, Ted's gone, we're
screwed.' We needed guys to step up then. Marty Moore stepped up,
and a lot of guys stepped up.''
</P>
<P>
   None more so than Chad Eaton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
