<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0687 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OXYGEN-HOTSPOT-BOS &LR;      12-09 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OXYGEN-HOTSPOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN L.A., BREATHING SPACE WITH FLAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Crashed on the couch, head back, legs stretched
forward, Jackie Burke breathed deeply through the tube in her nose.
She felt something. She was sure of it. She just wasn't sure what.
</P>
<P>
   ``My nose itches, I know that,'' she said after 20 minutes of
gentle inhalation.
</P>
<P>
   Added her friend Gail Nesbitt, ``I just wish it was quieter. I
wanted the most out of my air.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Burke and Nesbitt felt, they said it wasn't bamboozled,
even though they had just paid $15 a pop for flavored,
oxygen-enriched air. For their money, they had gotten to hang out
at a new West Hollywood hot spot, the aptly named O2, and get in on
a trend before it takes off or dies. As Burke, a freelance producer
with the E Entertainment Network, put it, ``I just thought, `Where
else can you go to buy air that tastes like orange or mint?' ''
</P>
<P>
   O2 _ owned by actor and hemperor Woody Harrelson, his wife Laura
Louie, and a physician and holistic healer who goes by the moniker
Dr. D _ pitches itself as the place to rejuvenate in smoggy LA.
Located on Sunset Boulevard, across the street from Spago's and a
block from the Viper Room, where actor River Phoenix died of a drug
overdose, O2 is anti virtually everything in the neighborhood _
except, of course, celebrity. Ted Danson, Mary Steenburgen, and
Bill Maher all hooked up to oxygen tubes for the October opening.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent weeknight, the crowd was less recognizable but clad
in head-to-toe black. The live music was jazzy, and the mood was
calculatedly earthy in a see-and-be-seen way. With only four
tables, the front-room restaurant that serves uncooked organic
vegan food and has a domed ceiling replete with painted clouds and
stars was full for hours. The bar was packed with people ordering
$6 drinks that contain no alcohol but are still purported to pack a
punch. The pungent herbal and fruity concoctions, with names like
``Don Juan Colada'' and ``Fast Screw'' are supposed to boost the
libido, banish anxiety, or make mind magic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no hangovers here, but people still get off,'' said
Dr. D, whose real name is Richard DeAndria. ``You won't see the
walls melting, but you will become more open to other things.''
</P>
<P>
   But the oxygen sold in the back room is what makes O2, well, O2.
</P>
<P>
   The oxygen, as Dr. D explained, run through a device that
extracts it from the air then remixes it in purer form. There are
no storage requirements, no fire hazards. Flavors are optional, for
$2.
</P>
<P>
   The customers swig the oxygen through clear plastic nose tubes,
just like the kind hospitals use. They are, obviously, disposable
and recyclable. But the overall effect is less medical than
mystical; the tubes are attached to tall eastern smoking pipes
known as hookahs, giving the room a playful casbah feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel all tingly,'' said Andriano Serafini, an actor who was
buying oxygen for the first time the other night. ``My senses are
aware. My nose, my eyes, my skin. . . . Curiosity made me do it
this time. I think I'd do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   So would Douglas Walth, a billboard printer who was sitting
cross-legged with his eyes closed on the couch that takes up an
entire wall. Sandwiched between strangers, he was inhaling oxygen
flavored with ``Joy,'' and insisted it was having the desired
effect. The taste was ``incredible,'' he said softly, plus he felt
``light and energetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, reported feeling no buzz at all.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through her 20 minutes, the standard ``hit'' of enriched
air, administrative assistant Oksana Lynyova was still waiting for
the oxygen to kick in. But, she added, she hadn't had any
expectations and so it was impossible to be disappointed. And this
being LA, she added that she was glad for the New Age-y experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd come back, but only for the food,'' Lynyova said. ``It's
an excellent idea, because it's a new way of experiencing things.
But I can tell you that for me, meditation is much better.''
</P>
<P>
   The medical community, in fact, is divided over the benefits of
oxygen-enriched air. While few oppose it, many doctors do stress
that there is sufficient oxygen in the atmosphere for most people,
except those who have special breathing problems. Too much of it,
some say, can even be unhealthy, oxidizing certain tissues and
speeding up aging _ anathema in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents of extra helpings of oxygen say a deficiency can
make people more susceptible to allergens and infections, and cause
cell degeneration. The US Food and Drug Administration approves of
oxygen therapy for migraines and headaches, among other medical
problems. And O2 isn't the only, or even first, oxygen bar. New
York, Toronto, even Hong Kong, can claim them, too, but Boston
can't yet.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Dr. D said he gulps oxygen every day and he looks
healthy enough in his green wool cap, beaded hemp shirt, and
fashionably baggy pants. Then again, he hasn't eaten meat products
in seven years and doesn't even cook his food anymore, preferring
to preserve every possible nutrient. When he's not at O2, he runs a
West LA practice that combines Chinese medicine, chiropractic, and
other alternative medical therapies, including oxygen therapy. Dr.
D declines to give his age _ saying he will when someone can give
him a good definition of time. But he must be in his 30s, though he
looks to be in his 20s. The oxygen, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a place where there was good, nutritious food for the
body, oxygen as a deep breath for the soul, and mind-altering
drinks,'' said Dr. D, who approached fellow vegan Harrelson with
the idea for O2. ``Oxygen has different effects, depending where
you are. It brings you back to zero point. If you're jittery, it
calms you. If you have a headache, it'll help relieve it. If you
get stuck in traffic and feel uptight, you go in there for 20
minutes of oxygen and you're fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The oxygen, according to Dr. D, also works on hangovers. Since
O2 serves no alcohol, it can stay open until 4 a.m., turning it
into an after-hours club for the drinking crowd. Twenty minutes on
the nose tube and a couple of $6 herbal mixes later, Dr. D said,
and the unhealthy are almost but not quite as healthy as new. At
least they feel that way, and fads have been born from less.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
