<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOR MADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes fashion colors quiz)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember back in preschool when you learned the primary colors?
Red was red. Black was black. And your parents could order clothes
from a catalog easily.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, are those days over. Now, no one dares use a boring name
like yellow. By order of marketing gurus everywhere, it seems it
was decided: to be chic, color names must be as obscure as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, this year we have the Eddie Bauer holiday preview book,
which includes ``tobacco'' cardigans (not smoking jackets, merely
dark brown sweaters); ``maritime'' corduroy pants (they're navy
blue but not necessarily for the sea) and ``saddle'' coats (tan and
not to be confused with riding jackets).
</P>
<P>
   Flip through J. Crew's latest book and you'll find a ``port''
sweater (burgundy), a ``stone'' coat (off-white, although it could
have been pink when you consider all the colors of stones in the
world), and a ``barley heather'' sweater ( a.k.a.beige).
</P>
<P>
   L. L. Bean's fall catalog offers ``rich navy'' (as opposed to
dull navy?), ``banker's gray'' (is there any other kind?), and
ocean green (is the ocean green?). And the Donna Morgan book is
downright appetizing with a ``cappuccino'' pant suit, a
``portabello'' satin evening dress, and a ``cafe latte'' satin
gown.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say shoppers can thank the cosmetics industry for the
silly trend, which started in the late 1980s and gained momentum in
the '90s among clothing companies. ``Cosmetics companies have new
palettes every season,'' says Jill Carey, an assistant professor of
fashion at Lasell College in Newton. ``They give them these really
rich-sounding names. It's all part of attractive advertising . . .
and young people love it. It's like a status symbol somehow. They
know the colors of their makeup and the palettes of their garments.
If I say `I like your lipstick,' they say `It's MAC and it's
cappuccino.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fashion houses insist the trend isn't a marketing gimmick _ that
fabric mills worldwide require them to make up quirky names every
season so the mills can distinguish one dye from another over the
years. ``There's a specific formula for each color,'' says Sharon
Goldsmith, design assistant at Donna Morgan in New York. ``They
have a formulation for brown. If we change the fabric slightly,
they can't use the word brown again. So we say cappuccino . . .
It's really very technical,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And it's become such a headache for fashion houses like Morgan
to come up with original names that they're now turning to flower
and plant encylopedias, spices, foods, precious stones, metals,
mother nature, and even museum exhibits for ideas. ``For us, it's
hard,'' says Goldsmith. ``We might have 15 different colors per
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the darn marketing department to please. Some color
names are deemed too wordy. Others are too silly. Still others _
like ``pastoral green'' _ just too vague. Morgan's sales department
nixed it for ``kiwi.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, with copywriting like this, there's the issue of
redundancy. How many different shades of greens are there, for
heaven's sake? Eddie Bauer uses celadon, basil, alpine green, dark
pine, cactus, mallard, juniper, dark spruce, and thyme. Its blues
include peacock, lagoon, twilight, loganberry, patriot blue,
brilliant blue, admiral blue, bluebell, and oh, blue.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the problem of consistency. Just when a shopper
gets used to the shade of ``twig'' in one book, he or she may find
it a very different tone in another. The mills, theoretically,
could have a dark ``twig'' recipe for Donna Karan and a light
``twig'' recipe for Calvin Klein.
</P>
<P>
   After all the effort involved in making up fabulous color names,
one has to wonder _ do customers really want to consult color
charts and dictionaries before they decide on an order? Why can't
the industry revert to the old days and just have one color formula
for black? ``I just want to buy something that's red,'' groans
Marilyn Santiesteban, president of the image consulting firm First
Impressions in Newton. ``What they've done to colors is complicate
the whole thing . . . Catalog shopping is supposed to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Think you know your colors? Here's a quiz for you. Match the color
names on the left with the descriptions on the right. The answers
follow &UR;  &LR; ($ used as column separator): &QL; 
 &QL; 
Colors: $ Descriptions: &QL; 
1. Fawn $ A. Dark brown-gray &QL; 
2. Clay $ B. Off-white &QL; 
3. Bittersweet $ C. Beige &QL; 
4. Sagebrush $ D. Gray &QL; 
5. Jute $ E. Green &QL; 
6. Oatmeal Heather $ F. Orange &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quiz Answers: &QL; 
1. Fawn is gray. &QL; 
2. Clay is green. &QL; 
3. Bittersweet is orange. &QL; 
4. Sagebrush is dark brown-gray. &QL; 
5. Jute is beige. &QL; 
6. Oatmeal Heather is off-white. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
