A0697 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-LIBERATION-ARM     12-09 2745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-LIBERATION-ARMY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 FROM BROOKLYN to KOSOVO, WITH LOVE and AK-47s  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.  By STACY SULLIVAN  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    A single photograph decorates the office walls of Triangle
Contractors in an old house on Cortelyou Road in Brooklyn. It
depicts a young man with a Kalashnikov slung across his chest, a
pistol tucked into his belt and another automatic weapon in his
hands.
 &HT;    It is a rainy day several months before the peace agreement in
Kosovo, and I have come to find out about the Kosovo Liberation
Army, the ethnic-Albanian guerrilla movement fighting for
independence from Serbia.
 &HT;    Nobody seems to know how the group started or who is in charge
of it, but word among Albanians in New York is that Triangle's
owner, Florin Krasniqi, is one of its principal fund-raisers.
 &HT;    The 34-year-old contractor has a muscular build, dark, serious
eyes and a no-nonsense manner. He is friendly, but it is clear he
has things to do and talking to me is not one of his priorities. I
ask if he raises money for the guerrilla army.
 &HT;    ``I thought you knew that,'' he says matter-of-factly. He hands
me an Albanian newspaper, ``Zeri i Kosoves,'' The Voice of Kosovo,
which has an ad for a ``Homeland Calling'' fund that lists accounts
in the United States, Switzerland, Germany, Australia, Austria,
Norway, Denmark, France, Sweden, Italy, Belgium and Canada.
 &HT;    A mobile phone rings, and even though he speaks in Albanian, I
sense that the news is not good.
 &HT;    ``The Serbs seized a convoy of our weapons,'' he says, looking
down for a second before looking up with a mischievous smile.
``They didn't kill any of our guys, though. They were waiting for
us. We walked right into their trap, and they didn't manage to kill
one of our guys, not a single one!'' He brushes off the incident as
a minor setback.
 &HT;    Florin has been a leading supporter of the KLA for nearly three
years, helping raise between $12 million and $15 million while
changing a once-obscure clutch of rural militants into an
insurgency. His business has suffered as a result, forcing him to
cut down from 32 employees to 10.
 &HT;    But that's no longer his primary concern. Under U.S. law, a
citizen may legally aid a foreign army as long as it is not
considered a terrorist organization by the State Department. The
KLA is not, so Florin is confident that he is doing the right
thing, morally and legally.
 &HT;    The rebel army is amorphous, Hydra-headed, disorganized and
plagued with infighting. It is certainly no match for Serbian Army
and police forces. But the KLA has put Kosovo, a tiny province of
fewer than 2 million people, at the top of the international
agenda.
 &HT;    Even though the Western powers are united with Serbia in
opposing an independent Kosovo, nobody seems able to dissuade the
rebels from their goal. The KLA is like a chronic infection that
periodically flares and subsides; it is unruly, persistent,
seemingly indefatigable.
 &HT;    Florin points to the photograph on the wall. ``Did you see the
picture of my cousin Adrian?'' It's a rhetorical question _ the
photograph is impossible to miss _ so Florin doesn't wait for an
answer. ``He was one of the first KLA fighters to die. I'm doing
this for him.''
 &HT;    While Kosovo has drawn a lot of attention lately, the conflict
dates to 1989 when Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president,
revoked Kosovo's autonomy within the Yugoslav federation, fired
Albanians from state-run institutions and banned teaching of the
Albanian language and literature.
 &HT;    Long a part of Serbia, Kosovo had become increasingly populated
by ethnic Albanians _ and deserted by Serbs, who left in droves for
the more comfortable surroundings of Serbia proper. By 1989, the
population was 90 percent ethnic Albanian, assuring that
Milosevic's decree would stir widespread resentment. Ultimately,
that coalesced in the murky form of the KLA.
 &HT;    Florin and his extended family began their revolutionary
activity in 1995. At the time, Adrian was a 23-year-old engineering
student with wholesome good looks and a masterful chess game. In
March, after one of his friends was killed by the Serbian police,
he tried to organize a student demonstration. He was stopped, not
by the Serbs but by his fellow Albanians.
 &HT;    Ibrahim Rugova, the Kosovar political leader, feared _
correctly, as subsequent events would bear out _ that active
resistance would provoke a Serbian crackdown.
 &HT;    Adrian protested Rugova's decision, circulating a petition that
was signed by 900 students. When the Serbian police found out, he
was arrested, locked in a dark cell and beaten unconscious. Upon
his release, he fled to Albania to buy a gun. When he returned
three months later, he killed his first Serbian cop.
 &HT;    ``I was furious about it,'' Florin says. ``I tried to get him to
calm down, but Adrian was stubborn. He said he wouldn't stop until
we were liberated.''
 &HT;    That was back when Florin still believed in the politics of
peace. A former geometry teacher, he left Kosovo in 1989 as part of
a wave of more than half a million refugees who sought political
asylum abroad, principally in Germany and the United States.
Eventually he found his way to Brooklyn.
 &HT;    Like many of his compatriots in the diaspora, Florin donated 3
percent of his income to Rugova's political party and kept his
faith that the Albanians would be rewarded by the West for their
peaceful struggle.
 &HT;    But at the end of 1995, Florin snapped. ``It was Dayton,'' he
says. The Dayton peace accord ended the war in Bosnia, but left the
status of Kosovo unresolved.
 &HT;    Every other disgruntled minority in Yugoslavia _ the Slovenes,
the Croats, the Bosnians _ fought for independence and got it, he
says. The Albanians took the peaceful road and were ignored.
``That's when I realized fighting was the only way. Peaceful
resistance brought us nothing.''
 &HT;    He started small, sending two-way radios, flashlights,
camouflage uniforms, bulletproof vests. But after Adrian was killed
during an attack on a police station in October 1997, he decided to
dedicate his life to the KLA.
 &HT;    ``It wasn't easy raising money at first,'' he says. The
estimated 300,000 Kosovar refugees in the United States _ clustered
mainly in New York, Detroit, Chicago and Boston _ supported Rugova.
``Things have changed now,'' Florin says in April. ''Everyone
realizes Rugova is not the answer. The money is coming in so fast
that we don't know what to do with it.''
 &HT;    While exact figures are hard to come by, refugee groups claim to
have raised in excess of $100 million to support Rugova and, now,
the armed resistance.
 -0- 
 &HT;    I fly to Albania to meet Florin's family and see where the money
is going. Bajram Curri, in the desolate and lawless north of
Albania, sits on the edge of the Sar Mountains. Even at the end of
June, snow still lies deep on the 8,000-foot peaks that overlook
the villages of Kosovo.
 &HT;    The eight-hour trek there from Tirana, the Albanian capital,
involves three legs _ five hours on a narrow, winding road, two
hours on a ferry and another hour by car. The ferry runs once a
day, snaking its way along the turquoise Drin River between jagged
cliffs. The scenery is spectacular, but the beauty seems lost on
most of the passengers, who are preoccupied with their livestock
and weapons. Chickens, goats and cows are crammed in between vans
and trucks loaded with guns.
 &HT;    Poverty in northern Albania rivals that of undeveloped Africa.
The villagers of Bajram Curri still use the barter system, and most
of their energy goes into fulfilling the basic needs of food and
shelter. Blood feuds are the law of the land _ children live
indoors for fear of being gunned down if they set foot outside. The
lack of formal institutions means the only things that really
matter in Bajram Curri are how big you are, how many guns you have
and whom you know.
 &HT;    Besnik Krasniqi, Florin's uncle, is big, well armed and knows
everybody. I find him sitting in a cafe on the town's main
boulevard. He is a burly man in his mid-50s with a massive belly
and Florin's mischievous smile. He and his family were isolated
from the rest of the Krasniqi clan in Kosovo.
 &HT;    I introduce myself to Besnik and tell him Florin sent me. When I
say I would like to visit a KLA training camp, he eyes me
suspiciously. ``Nobody is supposed to see the training camps,''
Besnik says. ``But if Florin says it's OK, you will be able to do
everything.'' We agree to call Florin by satellite telephone.
 &HT;    Besnik's house is full of KLA soldiers, Kosovars who have
recently returned from Germany, Switzerland and the United States
to fight. Stacks of ammunition boxes clutter his courtyard, and
pistols and rifles are strewn around inside. Besnik's wife and
daughter spend their days cooking for the soldiers.
 &HT;    His two sons, who have returned from studying in Switzerland and
Pakistan, shuttle soldiers and guns in his two four-wheel-drives.
Six Albanians from Alaska have just arrived with a briefcase of
cash they raised among Alaska's 300-strong Albanian community. They
are sunburned and complaining about the heat, which even in the
evenings is stultifying.
 &HT;    When I manage to reach Florin by phone in Brooklyn, I tell him I
am at Besnik's house. ``That's where everything started,'' he says.
``On the second floor.''
 &HT;    Back in 1996, soon after Florin started sending supplies to
Adrian, the Serbian police accused Adrian of terrorism. To avoid
arrest, he fled across the border to Albania, where he moved in
with Besnik and ran small quantities of arms over the border to
Kosovo.
 &HT;    So things stayed until early in 1997, when the Krasniqi boys hit
the jackpot. A string of fraudulent pyramid-type investment schemes
collapsed in Albania, bilking thousands of average people out of
their life savings. In the violent antigovernment demonstrations
that followed, people stormed military arms depots, taking anything
they could get their hands on.
 &HT;    Suddenly, there were guns everywhere, and it didn't take all
that much money to accumulate a sizable cache of arms. ``You could
walk up to a fruit stand and behind the watermelons there would be
weapons,'' Florin says.
 &HT;    ``Kalashnikovs were going for $10 each. The villagers were
giving us ammunition for free.'' As the motherland imploded, the
Krasniqis quietly collected all the arms they could and stored them
in a farmhouse, which became the KLA's rear base. Adrian meanwhile,
began moving weapons across the border to Kosovo with convoys of
horses and mules.
 &HT;    ``I had to show him how to pack a horse,'' Florin laughs. ``He
probably would have kept carrying the guns himself.''
 &HT;    But in October 1997 Adrian was shot and killed. Serbian
television repeatedly showed Adrian's corpse with a grenade in his
hand, instantly transforming him into a martyr for Kosovo's
independence movement. An estimated 13,000 people attended his
funeral.
 &HT;    The poster of him with his AK-47 and battle fatigues _ the same
one that decorates the wall in Florin's Brooklyn office _ became a
fixture in Albanian homes and the centerpiece of a suddenly potent
KLA fund-raising effort.
 &HT;    From Brooklyn, Florin explains that the old camp is gone but
that the KLA has set up a new base that I can visit. I hand the
phone to Besnik, who speaks for about 30 seconds and hangs up.
``Come over at 10 o'clock tomorrow morning,'' he says.
 &HT;    The KLA camp, in the mountains a few miles north of Bajram
Curri, is something of an anticlimax. It sits forlornly in an
abandoned army barracks. Inside, hundreds of bedraggled recruits
are bedded down on the hard floor; more sleep on the grass outside.
They have no cooking or bathing facilities. Trucks and minivans
drive in and out, adding more guns, grenades and ammunition to the
already sizable cache inside the base.
 &HT;    I had heard rumors that Iranians, Chechens and Albanians who had
fought in the Bosnian army were training the raw KLA recruits, but
the squalor and disorder of the camp suggest there is no training
at all. Rather, the camp is a staging post for Kosovars to rest and
get a weapon and a patch with the Albanian two-headed eagle before
heading back across the border.
 &HT;    Throughout the spring, young men and boys _ some no more than 13
_ set out from the camp in groups of 100 or so with convoys of
mules and horses loaded with weapons. In less than three months,
following the Serbs' winter offensive, the KLA mushroomed from a
collection of rural militants into an insurgency.
 &HT;    But by the beginning of July, the young men in the camp say they
are having trouble crossing into Kosovo. Serbian forces have moved
in along the border to stop the arms-smuggling, and it seems to be
working.
 &HT;    Two weeks after my visit, at the end of July, Milosevic's forces
embark on an offensive ostensibly aimed at eliminating the KLA. In
fact, Serbian troops roll through village after village with tanks
and heavy artillery. The KLA and the civilians flee in advance of
the army, which means there is very little actual fighting. Serbian
police follow the army to loot valuables and set homes on fire. The
KLA is in retreat.
 &HT;    I go to Vranoc, Florin's family's hometown, in mid-August while
the Serb offensive is still under way. They haven't leveled Vranoc
yet, but they've reached the neighboring village. It is only a
matter of time.
 &HT;    It's another month before I speak to Florin again, and the news
is bad, though hardly unexpected. ``Vranoc was leveled,'' he says.
There is a wire story in The New York Times reporting that 40,000
refugees are on the run in western Kosovo. Florin's family is
missing. They are probably among the refugees.
 &HT;    On Oct. 2, Florin leaves Brooklyn for Albania to deliver another
supply of cash for the KLA. He has got word that his family is safe
in Pec, the city nearest Vranoc.
 &HT;    The KLA, for the most part, appears to have been thoroughly
routed by the Serbs. There are about 300,000 new refugees, some 400
villages have been destroyed, hundreds have been killed and the
Western powers are threatening airstrikes if Serbian police and
military forces do not pull out of Kosovo.
 &HT;    ``As long as NATO airstrikes are a possibility, we will keep
confrontations at a low level,'' Florin says. ``If they start
bombing, the KLA will be back within 10 hours. But I don't think
that will happen. Milosevic will pull back at the last minute.''
 &HT;    I ask him about Adrian. ``If Adrian were alive, he would be
commanding the KLA He had lots of energy and he was a bad loser.
His only problem was that he had no patience. I knew he would get
killed. He didn't know when to stop.''
 &HT;    I ask him about a few other KLA soldiers. He says he knows
nothing about them. ''I don't like to know personal things. I
always know which ones are going to die. That's why I don't get too
close.''
 &HT;    It's mid-October when we meet again at his house on Chester
Street in Brooklyn. Just a couple of days earlier, the U.S. envoy,
Richard C. Holbrooke, had brokered a peace providing for a Serb
withdrawal and the placing of international monitors. A month
hence, it would become clear that the KLA had risen again, newly
energized. But even now, it is clear that it won't be vanquished.
 &HT;    ``We want to wait for Milosevic to pull back as much as possible
and for as many monitors as possible to come into Kosovo. With the
monitors on the ground, the Serbs won't be able to attack our
civilians.
 &HT;    ``Then,'' he says quietly, ``we can fight man to man.''
 &HT;     c.1998 Stacy Sullivan  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Stacy Sullivan is a Pew Fellow in international journalism at
the Johns Hopkins University School of Advanced International
Studies.) &LR;
</P>
