 Wednesday, Dec. 9, 1998     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following story
for Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT (Washington) _ White House witnesses tell
the House Judiciary Committee that President Clinton is being held
to a tougher standard of conduct than an ordinary citizen would be
and therefore should not be impeached. Republican committee members
respond that the president is not an ordinary citizen. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   RUFF-PROFILE (Washington) _ We profile the 59-year-old White
House counsel, Charles F.C. Ruff, who sums up President Clinton's
defense against impeachment with a no-nonsense solemnity. By
STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   LAHOOD-IMPEACHMENT (Washington) _ The least popular job on
Capitol Hill _ presiding over the House's historic impeachment vote
expected next week _ will fall to Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill., an
even-keeled veteran known for his efforts to bring civility to the
House. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   LAMPSON-IMPEACHMENT (Washington) _ Insisting he's ``not trying
to play hard to get,'' Rep. Nick Lampson of Texas, says he won't
make up his mind about impeachment until the Judiciary Committee
finishes its deliberations. He's one of a few Democratic
fence-sitters on the issue. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ A look at the lessons of the 20th
century and hopes for the 21st century. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1402EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0702 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CULTURE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     12-09 1556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CULTURE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... New York.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is cross-fertilization here with other Spanish cookery, as
in the famous tortilla de patata, the potato omelet served as
tapas, and angulas a la cazuela, baby eels in sizzling garlic.
Barrenechea keeps making the point that her restaurant food and the
food in this book are completely authentic. But a
delightful-sounding roast duck cooked with carrots, onions, apples,
and dates _ fruit is probably an influence from the Moors, early
settlers in this region _ never instructs the cook to remove the
excess duck fat from the pan. Will it be edible? Then a chicken
dish asks you to combine peppers and tomatoes cooked in six
tablespoons of olive oil with chicken sauteed in another six
tablespoons of oil. So for pork simmered in milk, I felt perfectly
comfortable cutting down on the oil, and it did produce beautifully
tender meat. There was much too much sauce, and no instruction to
turn the meat. In addition, the milk curdles so badly during
cooking that if you weren't familiar with this sort of recipe
(blending later smooths it out), you would surely think you erred.
</P>
<P>
   When I made two pie pastry recipes from ``The Pie and Pastry
Bible,'' by Rose Levy Beranbaum (Scribner, $35), I almost gave up
before I began. I've baked from Beranbaum for years, but I don't
remember the recipes being this nit-picky. I couldn't make the
deluxe flaky pie pastry because I couldn't get pastry flour. So I
made basic flaky pie crust with unbleached, rather than bleached,
flour. She lists ingredients in cups, ounces, and grams, which is
hard to read (probably a service for pastry chefs). Persevere, I
told myself.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, you've got to freeze one portion of butter, refrigerate
another. Then you have to freeze the flour. And when the pastry is
done, you can't bring it together to form a dough. But you know
it's done because if you pinch it, it'll hold together. Then you
pack it into a plastic bag and you land up smushing the dough
together and kneading it through the bag. Is this woman for real?
It did bake into a nice crust, but I'd never repeat the process.
Ditto for flaky vegetable shortening pie crust. Beautiful when
baked. Too weird.
</P>
<P>
   Elinor Klivans is much more compatible. ``125 Cookies to Bake,
Nibble, and Savor'' (Broadway Books, $25) is perfectly sweet, page
after page. What I like about Klivans, who lives in Camden, Maine,
is that she's not trying to knock my socks off. There are ordinary
cookies here and if something is complicated, you can always stop
before the tricky parts set in. I made triple-chocolate-topped
chocolate butter cookies and though instructions said to roll them
in my hands, the dough was too wet. So I dropped them off a spoon
and that worked perfectly. I couldn't get the melted chocolate to
drip smoothly off the tines of a fork as instructed, though the end
result, lumpy chocolate lines and all, looked quite nice and tasted
wonderful. Parisian toffee crisps were just as easy. Again, no luck
in forming balls of dough in my palms, but it didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   I keep Saveur magazines long past their shelf life because I'm
enchanted by the photography and layout. ``Saveur Cooks Authentic
American,'' by the editors of Saveur magazine (Chronicle Books,
$40), captures the best of their regional American stories with
dishes like smoked trout hash made with Maine's Ducktrap smoked
fish (delicious, though they give the wrong, too-long cooking time
for the potatoes), and Georgene's fluffy rolls, a recipe from a
cook in Memphis. (so sweet they have a cakey quality). It's a good
overview of some of the things we do best: lobster, steak, ham,
fried chicken, sandwich bread, mac and cheese. Beautiful
photography and interesting vignettes on the cooks are dropped
throughout the text.
</P>
<P>
   Many years ago I had lunch with Lorenza de'Medici at her
11th-century estate, where Badia a Coltibuono wines and olive oils
are bottled. We drank gorgeous wines with her husband, Piero
Stucchi-Prinetti, and ate tomatoes stuffed with tuna fish salad.
De'Medici sat in a dining room from another era and she looked like
a duchess and the tomatoes in the center of the dish were pure
Family Circle. I was thoroughly charmed by the contradiction.
Today, she produces grand-looking cookbooks that are evocative but
not weighty. Of course, she has little to do with the paper and
design. The cooking is hers. And often, it sounds a lot like those
stuffed tomatoes. ``Lorenza's Antipasti'' (Clarkson Potter, $40)
has some ordinary food, photographed on distressed plates and
backgrounds and then processed so the photographs have their own
salvaged-from-the-ruins look. This is the first I've seen of this
vampy photography, probably in vogue in Europe right now. I look to
Lorenza for inspiration and use her books as reference. I loved her
finger food and one hungry afternoon I was so taken with
zucchini-omelet sandwiches _ very thin slices of bread filled with
very thin wedges of frittata _ that I could have pulled them off
the page. Maybe I'm still snowed by that lunch at her winery.
</P>
<P>
   Last year a group of friends gathered at someone's house and
produced a Turkish banquet. Several of us had been to Istanbul and
we wanted to see what we could reproduce. We had all sorts of
books, but what we really needed was ``The Sultan's Kitchen, A
Turkish Cookbook,'' by Ozcan Ozan (Periplus Editions, $29.95),
which is a gem. Ozcan (pronounced Urz-jon) Ozan owns Sultan's
Kitchen in the financial district, where the specialty of the house
is lamb kebab with yogurt sauce and salads with finely chopped
vegetables. This is real Old World cooking and perhaps you need a
team of people to work from this book (the first sultan's kitchen
in Topkapi had 1,000 cooks). But there are simple things from
Ozan's mother's kitchen, like red lentil and bulgur soup garnished
with paprika and mint; lamb stew on a bed of creamed eggplant; and
rice pilaf with chicken, almonds, and pistachios. There are stuffed
pastries that are too difficult for most home cooks and not enough
dreamy text to match the breathtaking array of and inspiring
photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Longteine ``Nyep'' De Monteiro is a long way from home. She was
raised in an upper-class Cambodian household where many servants
did the cooking and food played an important role in the family. As
the wife of a diplomat, she entertained all the time. When Cambodia
fell to the Khmer Rouge, she and her husband, Ken, were living in
Taiwan. They went to the French southwest and opened a restaurant.
In 1991, when she and her daughter and son-in-law, Nadsa and Bob
Perry, opened Elephant Walk in a basement in Somerville, no one
could have predicted its success. ``The Elephant Walk Cookbook,''
by Longteine De Monteiro and Katherine Neustadt (Houghton Mifflin,
$35), recalls this chapter in De Monteiro's life, with her saga
about Cambodia, her family there, the history of the country, and
the marketplace. Now that the family has opened Carambola, in
Waltham, many of these dishes appear on their menu. Classic
Cambodian chicken and rice works as promised, but it seems to be
missing an ingredient or technique, since it doesn't taste like the
restaurant's. The chicken broth that is combined with the rice is
good enough, but at the restaurant it contains tiny dried shrimp,
which add lots of depth. So the results are slightly disappointing.
Spicy sauced pork contains both fish powder and fish sauce and
still isn't a bit salty. Even though no coconut milk was added, the
dish had a nutty creaminess. Fresh cilantro stems added a nice,
clean taste to the spice paste. No ``lesser galangal'' was in the
markets, just regular galangal, which worked out fine. To cook from
this book, you have to be invested in an ingredient search.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, you can go to the supermarket to cook from
``Vegetables,'' by James Peterson (William Morrow, $35), and make
something, he writes, that you would serve after rushing in from
work on a Wednesday evening. This is a book for new cooks, who need
to look up how to trim artichokes or glaze carrots.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of ``The Figs Table,'' by Todd English and Sally
Sampson (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25), are the shots of the extremely
photogenic English in action at his restaurants, Olives and Figs,
and the details of ingredients and simple foods photographed there
as well. English's voice doesn't come through here, but all is
forgiven when you make his fig pizza, spread with a jam made from
dried mission figs and balsamic vinegar, then topped with
Gorgonzola and prosciutto.
</P>
<P>
   When the guests are gone, when the doors are closed, and the
curtains are pulled tight, all I really want is a big bowl of soup.
So that's what I do all winter long, varying the pot from week to
week, beginning with homemade stock, and tossing oddments into the
soup as the week progresses. ``Saved by Soup,'' by Judith Barrett
(William Morrow, $23), whose recipes are all low-fat and simple to
execute, will be my January salvation. I'm dipping into shiitake
mushroom soup with Thai rice noodles in an Asian broth, three-bean
minestra with Swiss chard, and creamy carrot soup that has no
cream. After a brutal December, my figure will be saved by soup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alison Arnett and Fiona Luis of the Globe staff contributed to
these reviews.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
