<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ADDIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTRAIT OF THE ARTIST AS A YOUNG WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
ADDIE 
A Memoir 
By Mary Lee Settle 
University of South Carolina Press, 257 pp., illustrated., $24.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometime after the death of her husband in 1907, Addie Tompkins
made herself a coat of many colors out of his old silk ties _ a
Joseph coat, she called it, pieced together with her own rickrack
feather stitching. Years later, when the house was closed up, Miss
Addie's granddaughter, Mary Lee Settle, found the coat lying on the
floor. She had always loved it, so she picked it up and took it
home; today it hangs as a talisman in the room where she wrote
``Addie,'' a memoir of her grandmother and of her family _ ``I
inherited the residue, as we all do, of habits, gestures, genes,
hopes, fears and lies which are called Family.''
</P>
<P>
   Settle is now 79 and one of the best American novelists. Her
proudest achievement is probably a quincunx of books collectively
known as the ``Beulah Quintet,'' which survey centuries of American
history as they were experienced in daily life in a valley in West
Virginia where Settle's own ancestral home stands _ Cedar Grove,
built by money from the salt mines back in 1844. ``Addie'' tells us
directly the source of many details in Settle's other books, and
indirectly reveals where all of them came from, because the book is
a portrait of the artist as a young woman.
</P>
<P>
   Settle's profound conviction is that ``An autobiography that
begins with one's birth begins too late, in the middle of the
story, sometimes at the end.'' Settle's book opens in 1927, when
her mother returned to Cedar Grove after her husband's latest
failure, her tail, as she put it, between her legs. But the real
beginning is prehistoric, with the millennial processes that led to
seams of coal, and mines of salt, and natural gas beneath the
earth. Settle sets the family history in its social and political
context. She gives the early history of the valley, which lingers
like arrowheads in the soil; in a defining experience in the
basement of the British Museum, she discovers a tea chest filled
with the scalps of the farming settlers. Slavery and the Civil War
darken the book's pages, and so do the later boom-and-bust cycles
of the economy. Mother Jones arrives to cause trouble by doing the
right thing. The Tompkins's estate and fortune arose from and
depended on natural resources, but the family's enduring strength
came from its women.
</P>
<P>
   Addie lived a difficult life. Married soon after childhood to a
drunken and abusive miner with whom she had three children, she won
an early West Virginia divorce after she met Henry Preston Tomkins,
from the valley's most prominent family _ which never accepted her.
After they had been married 15 years, Tomkins was run down by a
train, most likely a suicide, leaving Addie with five more children
and ``a poverty of land'' to run. A determined woman, Addie took
charge, surviving the crises and tragedies of her children,
lecturing them in prayer over the dinner table, and finding
consolation in unceasing toil, her garden, and an uninhibited
Church of God Holy Roller religion that was radically opposed to
the chilly Presbyterianism of the rest of the family.
</P>
<P>
   Settle herself was an inquisitive and unruly little girl who
heard and remembered everything, even things it took her decades to
understand. ``(The grown-ups) tended to treat all the cousins as if
we couldn't hear, which has made this book easier to write.''
Settle was never interested in the lies of the grown-ups, their
sentiment and sentimentality, in their protective colorations,
stiff and ironclad as armor, of gentility. She sought the wonder
and mystery of the truth. ``(Aunt) Minnie was a morphine addict,
and my mother knew it from the time she was a child. She would, my
mother said, when she finally realized that I knew, drive the
hypodermic through her dress into her hip as she sat beating egg
whites in a china platter with a wire whisk and not even stopping.
Then she added, `She was a marvelous pastry cook.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There are places in Settle's capacious book for passion and
politics, for social comedy, for the tragic rape and plunder of the
land and of lives, for the follies and pain of old hatreds, for
lasting resentments and enduring gratitudes. Every portrait is
three-dimensional. Kindly Aunt Myrtle loved animals and children _
and used them to manipulate the other grown-ups. Above all, Settle
is profoundly grateful to those who taught her empathy and the
``right, true pitch.'' ``I can still hear their voices and watch
them move at their own paces.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of the parti-colored patches of family and national history,
Settle has stitched together her own Joseph coat of memory, with
its repeating patterns and its anomalies; the patterns of her
language ring like the refrains of old ballads, funny, violent,
terrifying, primal. The book has not been well-served by its
publisher, however. The old family photographs are so badly
reproduced that you can't make out the detail Settle so lovingly
describes in them; surely someone at a university press should
know, or care, how Katharine Cornell spelled her name or that it
was the ``Liebesnacht'' that Flagstad and Melchior recorded
together. Nevertheless, ``Addie'' will stand as a classic American
memoir. This reader finished, wept, turned back, and read it plumb
through all over again, for ``Addie'' is a book to love as well as
to read, a book to pass from hand to hand, generation to
generation, like a talisman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
