<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-IRISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CD OFFERS `HOPE' FOR OMAGH VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ Around here, just about everyone's
getting the same thing for Christmas: a CD called ``Across the
Bridge of Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Ireland's most popular recording artists have donated
their talent and songs to the CD to benefit the Omagh Fund, created
to help the victims of the bombing last August that killed 29
people, injured 250 others, and tore the heart out of this friendly
little market town in County Tyrone.
</P>
<P>
   Among the contributors are some of the biggest names in
contemporary music, all of them Irish: Sinead O'Connor, Boyzone,
the Corrs, Enya, and U2.
</P>
<P>
   But even more poignant is the appearance of artists who hail
from Northern Ireland, who know firsthand of what they sing: Van
Morrison, who grew up in East Belfast; Ash, the rock band from
Downpatrick; singer-songwriter Paul Brady, a Tyrone man; and Juliet
Turner, a little-known but talented singer from Omagh. Liam Neeson,
the actor who hails from Ballymena in nearby County Antrim, opens
the recording by reading a poem by the County Derry-born Nobel
laureate Seamus Heaney.
</P>
<P>
   It was Turner whose aching rendition of the ballad ``Broken
Things'' captured the heartbreak and sense of loss when she sang at
a memorial service a week after the bomb exploded, when Omagh
paused to remember its dead and injured.
</P>
<P>
   On that sunny day in August, accompanied by just her guitar,
Turner's voice was, like Ireland itself, simultaneously haunting
and beautiful. Her lament, based on a psalm, appealed to a God who
seemed absent when the bomb exploded, killing mostly women and
children doing back-to-school shopping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can have my heart, if you don't mind broken things.
</P>
<P>
   You can have my heart, if you don't mind these tears.
</P>
<P>
   But I heard that you make all things new,
</P>
<P>
   So I give these pieces all to you.
</P>
<P>
   If you want it, you can have my heart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to find a dry eye in Omagh after Juliet Turner sang
that song. Although the version on the CD was recorded in a studio,
it has the same effect on anyone who was in Omagh that day.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who is not enamored with the bottom-line thinking in the
mainstream music industry, said she was moved by the generosity of
the more famous artists who collaborated on the recording.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Corrs were a good example,'' she said in an interview.
``They got up and organized a lot of publicity, put their money
where their mouths are. It is amazing to see the spirit of these
artists.''
</P>
<P>
   The recording takes its title from a poem, ``The Bridge,''
written by 12-year-old Shaun McLaughlin, one of the six children
aged 12 or younger who were killed by the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orange and green it does not matter,'' Shaun McLaughlin wrote
after the political settlement reached in the Good Friday Agreement
offered people in Northern Ireland something other than an endless
cycle of violence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   United now, don't shatter our dream,
</P>
<P>
   Scatter the seeds of peace over our land,
</P>
<P>
   So we can travel, hand in hand
</P>
<P>
   Across the bridge of hope.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The people who planted the bomb left 500 pounds of explosives in
a car parked in the middle of the shopping district here. The
public outrage that followed the Omagh bombing led the dissident
republican group that planted the bomb to call a cease-fire and
disband.
</P>
<P>
   Those killed and injured by the bomb, many of them maimed and
disfigured, are the human toll of the worst atrocity in 30 years of
the Troubles, as the Irish call their interminable, intermittent
civil war with characteristic understatement.
</P>
<P>
   But those who recorded ``Across the Bridge of Hope'' are hoping
it becomes the biggest-selling charity recording in Ireland of all
time. The organizers of the Omagh Fund had initially hoped to raise
almost $20 million for the victims and their families. They have
since scaled back their aim to about $8 million. So far, they have
collected about $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Graham, who produced the CD, said it is available in the
United States by mail order and will soon be available as an
import. In the meantime, Graham, who runs freerange Records in
Killinchey, Northern Ireland, is trying to line up American artists
to contribute songs for an American version of the CD that
organizers hope to have ready for sale by St. Patrick's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``James Taylor's people have already been on to us. His song
`From Belfast to Boston' has a certain resonance,'' said Graham,
who has also spoken to Bonnie Raitt and Nanci Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   On the CD, Morrison's soulful, acoustic version of ``The Healing
Game'' underscores what's needed in Northern Ireland these days. He
is joined on the track by Belfast singer Brian Kennedy on backing
vocals. The musicians include Paddy Maloney, leader of The
Chieftains, and Phil Coulter, the Derry troubador who wrote ``The
Town I Love So Well,'' the bittersweet lament for his hometown,
which suffered so much during the Troubles but which has been
rebuilt and offers an example of post-conflict development.
</P>
<P>
   Brady's lyrics from ``The Island,'' written in 1986, are
prescient, and so chilling, when the horrific scenes of Omagh are
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They're showing pictures on the television,
</P>
<P>
   Women and children dying in the street . . .
</P>
<P>
   Up here we sacrifice our children,
</P>
<P>
   To feed the worn-out dreams of yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   And teach them dying will lead us into glory . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a palpable, profound sadness here, more pronounced
during the holiday season, which is celebrated throughout Ireland
with gusto. Many people are ambivalent about celebrating Christmas
so soon after what happened Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a brave town, and most put a brave face on last week
to light the Christmas tree in the town center, not far from where
the bomb exploded.
</P>
<P>
   One of the bomb's victims was released from the hospital
Wednesday. Pauline Green, 19, lost part of her left leg. She
hobbled out of the hospital on crutches and urged the politicians
to get beyond the current impasse and not let the peace process
collapse because of a dispute over what to do with paramilitary
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace is within our grasp,'' the teenager said. ``Everyone
wants it. Keep talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Green prays that Heaney was right when he wrote the words that
begin ``A Bridge Called Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Human beings suffer, they torture one another.
</P>
<P>
   They get hurt and get hard.
</P>
<P>
   No poem or play or song can fully right a wrong inflicted and
endured.
</P>
<P>
   History says don't hope on this side of the grave.
</P>
<P>
   But then, once in a lifetime, the longed for tidal wave of
justice can rise up and hope and history rhyme.
</P>
<P>
   So hope for a great sea change on the far side of revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Believe that a farther shore is reachable from here.
</P>
<P>
   Believe in miracles and cures and healing wells.
</P>
<P>
   Call miracles self-healing the utter self-revealing doubletake
of feeling.
</P>
<P>
   If there's fire on the mountain and lightning in the storm and a
God speaks from the sky that means someone is hearing the outcry
and the birthcry of new life at its term.
</P>
<P>
   It means once in a lifetime that justice can rise up and hope
and history rhyme.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Information about ``Across the Bridge of Hope'' can be found on
the Web site www.omaghcd.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1406EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
