<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUND MANAGER PUTS IT ALL ON THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about putting your money where your mouth is.
</P>
<P>
   Money manager Michael Malouf just moved from San Francisco to
Boston to start a new mutual fund focusing on small-capitalization
stocks for Neuberger &AMP; Berman Management Inc. His first order of
business: buying a townhouse in Boston's South End. Then he put the
rest of his entire net wealth, about $500,000, into his new fund.
</P>
<P>
   Managers of hedge funds, private investment vehicles for the
wealthy, will sometimes put most of their money in their own fund.
And mutual fund managers are expected to invest something in their
own funds. But rarely do you see a fund manager making this big a
bet on himself. Is this 31-year-old money manager sure of himself
or what?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that I know what kind of risk I am taking,'' says
Malouf. ``I think that small-caps are that attractive. I know the
manager _ it is me. I thought it was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The kind of small-cap stocks that Malouf follows have been
getting clobbered for so long it is sometimes hard to remember
which way is up. Measured from May 1996 to the low this October,
the Russell 2000 index, which tracks smaller stocks, was down 12
percent while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, which tracks large stocks,
was up 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since hitting bottom on Oct. 8, however, the Russell 2000 is up
29.62 percent compared with a gain of 23.41 percent for the S&AMP;P.
For the year, the Russell 2000 is still down 7.11 percent while the
S&AMP;P is up 23.47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The small-cap market has given signs of awakening from its long
slumber only to doze off again. But even before the most recent
run, the historic spreads in valuations between the big and small
stocks have been encouraging fund companies to reopen small-cap
funds that had been closed to new investors and to start new ones
to take advantage of the discrepancies.
</P>
<P>
   Among the funds that have reopened in recent months: State
Street Research Aurora, Oakmark Small Cap, two funds run by Wasatch
Advisors Inc., and Heartland Value. Fidelity Investments' Small Cap
Stock, shut shortly after it opened when it was swamped with money,
has reopened to existing investors.
</P>
<P>
   The new funds include the Small Cap Value, run by John Bogle's
N/I Numeric Investors in Cambridge and just started this month.
Like all Numeric's funds, Small Cap Value will leave the
stockpicking to its computer models, which will select the 120 or
so best stocks from a universe of 1,500. The fund has only $400,000
in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle says his ``gut'' tells him small-caps are undervalued, but
he doesn't pretend to know where the market is going. ``It is
probably not a whole lot different than me putting my chips on red
or black,'' Bogle says. The point of starting the no-load fund now
is to fill out his product line.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Malouf, the Neuberger &AMP; Berman manager, is an
active stockpicker and believes the values in the small-caps have
never been more appealing. He better be right _ with all his money
riding on his new growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the standard measures of valuing stocks are on his side.
The price-earnings ratios of small stocks, for instance, are just
80 percent of the large stocks, the biggest difference since at
least the '60s. In addition, when the Federal Reserve cuts rates,
as it just did, small stocks have tended to historically outperform
the big stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it turns, it is dramatic,'' says Malouf.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Malouf is running very short money, even by
small-cap standards. He has but $12 million in his new Millennium
fund, but he managed $1 billion in small-cap money for Dresdner
RCM's Small-Cap Growth and the firm's separate accounts. Malouf
spent seven years at Dresdner as an analyst and fund manager.
</P>
<P>
   So far, his timing couldn't have been better. Since launching
the fund on Oct. 20, the fund was up 28 percent through Monday
compared with 12 percent for the Russell 2000. But such short-term
numbers for a new fund are just about meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Malouf has 30 percent of his fund in technology. His top five
holdings: Karrington Health Inc., RSL Communications, SFX
Entertainment, Comfort Systems USA, and Quanta Services Inc. Among
the Internet stocks his favorite is Infoseek Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Malouf was hired by former Putnam Investments' money manager
Jennifer Silver, who Neuberger &AMP; Berman brought in 18 months ago to
add growth funds to its longtime emphasize on value stocks. Silver
now oversees about $1.75 billion in its mid-cap fund, the Manhattan
fund, and private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said the issue was whether to add a large-cap fund or a
small-cap fund. The huge gulf in valuations made that an easy call,
she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
