<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0709 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-NO-BOMBING-NYTSF     12-09 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-NO-BOMBING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBING WON'T SETTLE THE CRISIS IN IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    PARIS _ It is foolish to regret the cancellation of a bomb
attack on Iraq, as some seem to do out of frustration and anger at
having to acknowledge the limits of America's power. The goal of
military destruction cannot only be a show of strength.
 &HT;    In Iraq's case, the goal must be an assurance that Saddam
Hussein is not accumulating weapons of mass destruction in the
absence of U.N. disarmament teams. In Washington's eyes, the
purpose has to be the all-but-avowed hope of provoking Hussein's
ouster in a coup. Neither one was very likely to be achieved by the
planned campaign.
 &HT;    President Clinton, against the feeling of senior aides but with
the strong support of National Security Adviser Sandy Berger,
decided to accept yet another Baghdad promise rather than unleash
bombs and missiles, likely to cause a large number of civilian
casualties as well as military damage.
 &HT;    ``We have to be able to take `yes' for an answer when we say
that if he (Hussein) capitulates, it is a better outcome here to
test that and see whether UNSCOM can get back in and do the job,''
Berger told reporters, who were arguing that ``Saddam won again.''
 &HT;    It took courage on Clinton's part to expose himself to charges
of weakness and wavering. Had he bombed, the United States
certainly would have been denounced for cruelty and arrogance,
despite official statements that appeared to revive the broad
coalition which opposed Iraq in the 1991 Persian Gulf War. The
attack almost certainly would have settled nothing.
 &HT;    Still, Washington is either misleading the public or fooling
itself with claims of strong international backing, even from Arab
states, for action against Hussein. Whatever their leaders say at
the moment, the public in Arab countries no doubt would react
angrily to the infliction of intense further suffering on the Iraqi
population.
 &HT;    Even Le Monde of Paris chose to avoid comment on French
endorsement of the U.N. Security Council resolution and argued
instead that the reaction should be ``disarmament _ yes, sanctions
_ no.'' It's a clear reflection of the underlying French wish to
get rid of the punishments and just hope Saddam will behave better.
 &HT;    Further, it is impossible to delink the gulf situation from
Israeli-Palestinian developments, which do not look promising
despite Washington's hurrahs. The Wye accords actually may be
implemented, but it's proving much more difficult than promised. If
they fail, the United States will be held to account for Israeli
intransigence and Hussein will no longer seem to be the region's
prime villain.
 &HT;    By now there is a general expectation that the latest escape
from crisis in Iraq is only temporary. Clinton is right in saying
it will take a different kind of regime in Baghdad to reach a real
solution. But he isn't very clear on how that's to be achieved.
 &HT;    Ahmed Chalabi, a leader of the Iraqi National Congress, insists
that Hussein can be ousted from inside, if the United States will
provide the kind of aid proposed in the Iraq Liberation Act,
recently passed by Congress. It calls for $97 million in equipment
and training for Iraqi rebels and $2 million for a radio station.
Chalabi says opposition forces were actually on the verge of
victory in 1995, but for lack of U.S. help they were knocked out by
Baghdad.
 &HT;    It is true that the opposition, both clandestine within Iraq and
in exile, has a history of chronic quarreling and occasional
betrayal. The United States has been reluctant to give decisive
help, for fear of splitting up Iraq. Indeed, the greater danger is
to inadvertently launch a new, unending Afghanistan-type civil war
among Iraqi factions which clearly lack a solid political
organization.
 &HT;    There is no easy, assured solution and sooner or later, the
Iraqis will have to work their way out of this dreadful regime.
Certainly outside help, if reasonable and intelligent, is no worse
an interference in Iraq's domestic affairs than bombing the country
and starving its economy. It can be tried. It won't work quickly.
Meanwhile, it is better to be persistent and patient on disarmament
than to bomb.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1998 Flora Lewis 
