<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, Dec. 10,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ WASHINGTON _ Main lead from the impeachment hearings.
(Sherman/Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TEXT_ Excerpts from hearings. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CENSURE _ WASHINGTON _ As the hearings unfold in the public eye,
Democrats are working feverishly behind the scenes to convince
Henry Hyde to allow a vote on a censure motion. And some Democrats
say they think the Illinois Republican will eventually see it their
way. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-PUBLIC _ WHITE HALL, Va. _ ``It's gotten real old,''
Lauren Morris says of congressional efforts to impeach President
Clinton. She and the blue-collar workers and hunters who gather at
her father's country store each morning prove the point of
Democratic pollster Fred Yang: ``the farther away you are from
D.C., the less people care'' about the impeachment drama in the
nation's capital. (Shepard, Cox News Service 800).
</P>
<P>
   Cox photos are available for this story.
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ Dole and Clinton are expected to get
an early Christmas present from the FEC. The FEC meets Wednesday
and Thursday, and at one of those sessions is expected to vote to
eliminate virtually all of the recommendations from its staff that
Dole repay more than $17 million and Clinton about $7 million of
the taxpayer funds they received for their 1996 campaigns. Story
will move the day the FEC votes. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ The White House summit on Social
Security concludes Wednesday. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ James Gosling, chief scientist for Sun
Microsystems Inc. and creator of the Java programming language that
is seen as a threat to Windows dominance, returns to the witness
stand at the Microsoft antitrust trial. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-COLLEGES-TEXAS _ WASHINGTON _ Higher education officials
comment on the effect of a Black Enterprise magazine survey that
listed no Texas college among its 50 best schools nationwide for
black students. (Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   FAULDER-EXECUTION _ As Texas settles into the routine of
executing its death row inmates and goes four for four Thursday,
Canada is outraged over our indifference to the condemned. We
explore how a Canadian's scheduled execution Thursday is
galvanizing our neighbor to the north and try to capture a sense of
their outrage when they learn that most Texans consider it a sure
bet that their man is going to die. Also fold in the day's legal
developments. (Harmon/Ward, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   IDCRIME _ Fear rather than fact is driving juvenile justice
policies throughout the United States, according to a national
study from the MacArthur Foundation released Wednesday morning,
Dec. 9. The study charges that teens today are no more prone to
violence than they were 20 years ago and that tougher laws aimed at
youthful lawbreakers are based on ``deeply flawed analyses of
juvenile violence statistics.'' (Martz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CLIMATE _ The flipflop from summer's heat and drought to
October's floods may seem like typical Texas weather. But
scientists say it also fit right in with the forecast for global
warming: i.e., more weather extremes, dryer drys and wetter wets,
particularly more floods. But such forecasts are in doubt because
the computer models that make them have too many flaws. UT
scientists are trying to improve the models by building in what
they currently lack, such as rivers and their effect on
precipitation. (Stanley, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TX-WELFARE-REFORM _ Gov. George W. Bush and Human Services
Commissiner Eric Bost discuss a study of the state's welfare reform
efforts. (Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   MACARTHUR _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For a few moments today, the
Florida land will be the center of attention for the board of the
John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation. The 16-member
board's Nobel Prize-winning physicist, its storied radio
commentator and its epidemiologist who helped rid the world of
smallpox will cast aside the vexing questions of global population
growth, environmental degradation and nuclear wa/They will stop
thinking about how they should give away $150 million and start
thinking of how they can make more than $200 million. They will
turn to who should buy their land and in so doing shape the future
of northern Palm Beach County and parts of the Treasure Coast.
(Engelhardt, Palm Beach Post). 18.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-ECONOMY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas job growth has cooled
considerably in the last year, but the state's economic outlook is
still good for next year. That's the view of Sheila Dolmas, an
assistant economist for the Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas, who is
on the team that keeps a regular check on the state's economic
pulse. ``The Texas economy is still very healthy. Employment growth
has slowed, but we expect the (state's economic) expansion to
continue next year,'' said Dolmas. While Texas' job growth exceeded
the U.S. average job growth this decade, the rate of new job
creation has ``slipped considerably'' over the last year, Dolmas
said. (Tyson, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
