<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENT-A-MANAGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO RUNS YOUR FUND? OFTEN, IT'S A RENT-A-MANAGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To some investment managers, setting up a mutual fund is akin to
planting the corn and slaughtering the pig just to make a pork
chop. After all, why spend time and money assembling a research
team, portfolio manager, performance record, and sales and
marketing forces when you can farm out the tasks?
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers do it. Payroll departments do it. And
increasingly, asset management firms do it. Outsourcing, already an
engine of growth for the mutual fund industry, will put even more
funds on the table in coming years by allowing investment companies
to increase quickly the breadth of their offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these guys are for rent _ why would I want to own
one?'' asks Bradford K. Gallagher, whose small Boston firm, Cypress
Tree Investments, uses companies from Salomon Brothers to
Wellington Management Co., one of the biggest managers of other
firms' funds, to run most of its mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   What might be dubbed the ``rent-a-fund-manager'' trend has
swelled in recent years, driven by investment firms racing to
create more funds faster and by institutional money managers who
have looked with envy at the lucrative fund industry and scurried
to offer their services. Known as subadvising, the practice has
also spawned the growth of ``virtual'' fund shops that lack the
frenetic trading desks, high-cost money managers, and costly
research teams of traditional investment houses.
</P>
<P>
   But amid growing pressure in the industry for ever more flavors
of funds, subadvising may generate too many funds and more consumer
confusion in an already crowded field. And an investment adviser
who hands over control of his assets to someone else could be
viewed as lacking experience.
</P>
<P>
   Even though fund prospectuses clearly state who oversees a
portfolio, ordinary investors might be surprised to learn how many
mutual funds are actually run by a money manager at another
company. Nearly one in seven mutual funds is subadvised, including
32 percent of all international stock funds, according to Financial
Research Corp., or FRC, a Boston consulting firm. For US
diversified stock funds, the figure is nearly one in three.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most well-known fund firms, including Fidelity
Investments, use subadvisers, particularly for exotic overseas
offerings or for obscure products, such as variable annuities, for
which they may not have in-house expertise. Vanguard, one of the
hottest brand names around, has Wellington, hardly a household
name, run many of its funds, including the troubled $18.3 billion
Windsor fund.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, a cradle of both the mutual fund industry and the
subadvisory business, the use of other companies' money managers
will play an increasing role, consultants say.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement is appealing. An investment firm wanting to
expand into, say, an airline stock fund but not wanting to hire an
expensive sector analyst can pay someone else, often a well known
specialist, to take the reins. The practice is particularly common
for funds with international stocks, since a fund firm doesn't just
wake up one day and start picking winners in, say, Hungary. Mutual
fund and other asset management firms, even investment banks, are
all too glad to oversee more fee-generating assets without the onus
of marketing to investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a growing trend, and it is likely to really take off as
soon as international investing takes off,'' says Louis S. Harvey,
president of Dalbar Inc., a Boston consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   By contracting things out, investment firms are not just gaining
efficiencies of scale and economy. They are also responding to
growing consumer demand for a fuller range of funds within
individual firms. Such pressure has created more than 11,000 mutual
funds (including mutiple share classes), more than triple the
number of listed companies on the New York Stock Exchange. With
trillions of dollars in retirement money expected to come searching
for mutual funds when Baby Boomers leave the work force in coming
years, analysts expect ever more funds to be created, many through
subadvising. ``With subadvising, you can have a full-blown product
line without the full-blown operations,'' says Thomas P. Sorbo, a
partner at Standish, Ayer &AMP; Wood Inc., a Boston subadvisory firm.
</P>
<P>
   Since testing a fund in-house before selling it to the public
can take years, it is faster to go straight to an outside money
manager with an established record. ``You can move quicker in not
hiring the expertise as staff,'' says Russell J. Kinnel, equity
fund editor at Morningstar Inc., the Chicago-based fund tracking
firm. ``But you can also lack internal growth and the proprietary
feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Does the world need more mutual funds and virtual investment
shops?
</P>
<P>
   The rent-a-fund-manager trend is already adding elaborateness to
a complex fund industry. Increasingly, single funds are run by
managers spread out across several companies. For example, a firm
with a large capitalization fund with a heavy technology component
might hire a name-brand tech stock picker just for that part of the
fund. The Star Advisers Fund, a growth fund that is part of NVest's
New England Funds family, has three subadvisers, each overseeing a
different part of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   That practice will grow, says FRC analyst Ray Liberatore. In
all, Liberatore predicts subadvised funds will account for 20
percent of all funds, compared to 13.5 percent now.
</P>
<P>
   If past returns mean anything, that could be good for investors.
Subadvised US equity funds returned from a half to a full
percentage point more than their internally managed counterparts
over one, three, five, and 10 years through November, according to
Morningstar. And that is after slightly higher fees, which are
split between the subadviser and the company marketing and selling
the fund, are factored in. Liberatore attributes beefier returns to
the fact that marquee-name managers are often chosen as
subadvisers.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, subadvised international funds have lagged
their internally managed peers, perhaps because they compete
against a few powerhouse firms already rich in overseas research
and stock-picking skills.
</P>
<P>
   Once confined to secretive shops like Wellington and Standish,
Ayer, subadvising is increasingly attractive to mainstream
investment banks and institutional money managers who want more of
the hot ``retail'' fund business that caters to ordinary Americans,
who have fueled the investment boom this decade.
</P>
<P>
   But the field is fraught with peril. Subadvisors can be _ and
are _ sacked more readily than in-house portfolio managers, since
they are not full-time staffers with complex employment contracts.
``The subadviser doesn't control his own destiny,'' says
Philadelphia-based fund consultant Burton J. Greenwald, citing the
subadvisor's inability to influence how a fund is marketed. ``He
lives a precarious existence.''
</P>
<P>
   At Cypress, Gallagher is gearing up to cut ties to a sub-par
subadviser for one of his 16 North American funds. ``If these guys
don't perform, we fire them,'' Gallagher says. He grins, then adds:
``With subadvising, you have no human resources or personnel
issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
