u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-09 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAY-CARE DILEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Margarita Morales and Kamalah Fletcher have a lot in common:
Both are preschool teachers who are struggling to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, 24, a single mother of two, supplements the $10.19
hourly wage she earns as a head teacher at a center in Boston's
Jamaica Plain neighborhood by bagging groceries at a Costco
Wholesale store in suburban Dedham, Mass. She uses those weekend
earnings to help pay for day care and afterschool services for her
toddler daughter and 6-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher, 22, sells sporting goods on weekends. But while
Morales plans to remain in day care, Fletcher has other plans for
her future. She has enrolled at Boston University and is studying
psychology in preparation for a future career as an elementary
school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't value the work we do with young children,'' says
Fletcher, who earns a scant $9.37 per hour. ``They see us as baby
sitters. There is a lot more to it than that, but you can't live on
the money. It just isn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   With thousands of welfare recipients now entering the job
market, one of the most critical questions facing parents, policy
makers, and employers is how to expand day-care programs and keep
top-notch teachers from leaving the field.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, is to pay them more.
</P>
<P>
   But poor and middle-class parents, already burdened with
skyrocketing day-care bills, say they are hardly prepared to pay
more to boost child-care wages. In Greater Boston, for example,
child-care costs now range from over $100 per week for older,
preschool children up to $250 per week for infants. A good
afterschool program can cost as much as $4,000 per year, and weekly
family day care costs an average of $125 to $150 _ too high for the
working poor, but barely enough to meet day-care providers'
operations and programming costs.
</P>
<P>
   A catch-22, but there is some movement afoot. In Boston, state
Senator David Magnani (D-Framingham) introduced a bill last week
that would provide grants to help family day-care and child-care
centers become certified, improve programming, and pay their staffs
more. Under such a grant program, centers would be rewarded for
instituting career ladders and encouraging workers to pursue
courses or degrees in early childhood education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there is a push to create more slots to accommodate
children whose parents are on welfare, but the creation of slots
without looking at program quality could be a problem,'' says
Magnani. ``Secondly, there is a high turnover among day-care
teachers and family providers. We also know that only 14 percent of
all home-care providers and day-care centers in the state are
certified. The rest, 86 percent, are not certified by the National
Association for the Education of Young Children in Washington, D.C.
So, the goal is to raise standards and pay.''
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for workers like Morales and Fletcher, but what
about parents? Just trying to locate suitable care for infants or
toddlers can be frustrating. Although nine years have passed since
my own 13-year-old daughter was in day care, I still cringe when I
recall those roller-coaster years.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a divorce and the need for a higher income, one
home-care provider quit when my child was 2. I fired a second
provider, though she came highly recommended, after discovering a
pair of sewing shears on her livingroom floor, in the path of her
rambunctious 4-year-old and my curious toddler. The third time
around I got lucky. I found a preschool teacher who not only loved
my child, but later became a close friend and surrogate
grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to any working parents, and they can tell you about
day-care trauma. Many point to day-care centers that do not accept
children under three, lengthy waiting lists, and such high turnover
that they worry about the emotional and psychological impact on
their children's ability to form close attachments.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Child Care Action Campaign, which is trying to
increase public interest in child-care issues, says the national
turnover rate for child-care providers is now 36 percent per year.
Compare that to the 5.6 percent turnover rate for public school
teachers. The fact that preschool teachers are bailing out is
hardly surprising, when you consider that they make, on average,
$12,057 per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Boston, 47 percent of all providers now have some sort of
training,'' says Bernadette Davidson, director of The Childcare
Careers Institute. Still, she says, the child-care worker has
become a stepchild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caring for other people's children is a learned skill,'' she
says. ``It's not innate. We have people who really love their jobs
and some have associate's or bachelor's degrees in early childhood
education, but because of the stress associated with the work and
the low pay, people are leaving the field.''
</P>
<P>
   For parents, high turnover can translate into longer waits for
space, poor quality, and the stress of having to find a new
provider. To secure good care in the face of one-, two-, and
three-year waiting lists, Mark Smith, 38, of Roslindale, went so
far as to put his unborn child on the waiting list for a center at
Shattuck Hospital to ensure her admission 15 months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were looking for day care, we had no idea how
difficult it was to find good care or what the costs would be,''
says Smith. ``Infant care in Boston averages $12,000 for a
full-year, full-day program, and some preschool programs are as
high as $10,000 a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a staff member of Parents United for Child Care, says the
organization conducted a survey of 450 parents with children in day
care this year and discovered that 5 percent were forced to take on
a second job to pay for care. ``The biggest chunk of people are
middle class who can't save any money, which is the situation my
wife and I are in,'' he says. ``If you are spending $700 or $800 a
month on child care, you can't save for college or secondary
education. It's impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Smiths' two children are in day and afterschool
care only part time, the couple spend, on average, $700 per month,
more than their mortgage payment.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Parents United for Child Care filed a bill
called Childcare for Everyone. The measure would increase the
amount in day-care costs parents can deduct on their state tax
forms.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Morales is still trying to make ends meet. She
started out as a substitute teacher and fell in love with the job.
So, she went back to school _ to UMass Boston's Urban College.
There, she took early childhood education classes in preparation
for what she thought would one day become a career.
</P>
<P>
   But Morales' dreams haven't quite panned out. She still loves
children, ``But I can't live off what I make, not with two
children. I thought about leaving, but I enjoy it. Plus, I'm a good
teacher. That makes it hard to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane E. Lewis's e-mail address is work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
