<HEADLINE>
NET CAN'T DECK THE MALLS -- YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On-line shopping is supposed to be going mainstream
this holiday season, so why is Jeff Levine still hunting for gifts
the old-fashioned way at CambridgeSide Galleria?
</P>
<P>
   A 28-year-old city planner for nearby Somerville, Levine is
young, educated, and computer-savvy, going on line almost every
day.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, he seems an ideal candidate for hunkering down in
front of his personal computer and buying gifts from some trendy
electronic-commerce retailer like Amazon.com, which bills its World
Wide Web site as the world's biggest book store.
</P>
<P>
   Yet early December finds Levine in a mall, undaunted by the
prospect of big crowds, long lines, and scarce parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to beat a mall when you just want to browse,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   If the hype of e-commerce advocates is to be believed, 17
million Americans will buy something on line this holiday season _
many of them dressed only in their pajamas. After a few years of
experimenting and buying items such as software and hot sauce, many
consumers are at last comfortable with electronic shopping.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, on-line holiday sales are expected to double,
growing from last year's $1.1 billion to $2.3 billion _ or so
claims Jupiter Communications, a New York research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's no need to start writing obituaries for the mall
and the department store just yet. While nearly half of US
households now own a personal computer, on-line sales will account
for only about 2 percent of the more than $170 billion US consumers
are expected to spend this holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet shopping is still so small it hardly shows up,'' says
Britt Beemer of America's Research Group, a firm that surveys
consumer shopping patterns.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not to say the Internet won't change the way people
shop and the way retailers do business.
</P>
<P>
   At the Boston Consulting Group, vice president David Pecaut is
eager to dispel some myths about on-line shopping.
</P>
<P>
   What's likely to emerge is not a battle between hip e-commerce
retailers on one side and old-fashioned brick-and-mortar retailers
on the other. As Pecaut sees it, shrewd retailers are likely to
operate both in stores and on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, some brick-and-mortar retailers continue to shy
away from the Net, afraid a Web site may cannibalize store sales.
Such fears, Pecaut says, are unfounded _ and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones who get on the Web late will struggle,'' falling
further and further behind those who got there first, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's, the hallowed department-store chain, may offer one
blueprint for future success. In June, Macy's mailed out its first
catalog, and last month it ``relaunched'' its Web site. An early
Web site sold only 400 items. At the new version of Macys.Com ,
shoppers can choose from among 150,000 items.
</P>
<P>
   By offering three choices _ stores, catalogs, and Web site _
Macy's expects to see syngergies, savings, and more sales.
</P>
<P>
   Catalogs and Web sites, of course, mean Macy's can sell
merchandise in places where it has no stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you live in Kansas, you can now buy gifts from Macy's,''
says Carol Sanger, spokeswoman for Federated Department Stores
Inc., Macy's parent company.
</P>
<P>
   Not only can the Web help Macy's reach new geographic areas ,
but it will also help Macy's to reach out to new demographic
groups. Most department-store customers range in age from 30 to 50,
but on-line shoppers tend to be younger. Macy's hopes its Web site
will attract this much coveted younger crowd.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sanger, a traditional merchant such as Macy's has
an advantage over pure e-commerce retailers that sell their
merchandise only on the Web. Unlike new companies with strange
names, Macy's has a long history that may allay the fears of
consumers wary of using their credit cards for on-line purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated industry claims that encryption makes such
transactions safe, mall shopper Levine is one who remains wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still concerned about security,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Dempsey is worried about something else; he thinks his
shopping strategy won't work on line. The Web may be great if you
know ahead of time what you want to buy, but if you're looking for
gift ideas, malls are better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to buy theme gifts,'' says Dempsey, a 25-year-old
teacher who prefers to buy several small items for individuals on
his shopping list rather than one big present.
</P>
<P>
   When coming up with themes, window-shopping in malls is a source
of inspiration, he says. And though he often goes on the Internet
for other reasons, he says: ``Right now it's easier to go to the
malls. Besides, I actually like to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Macys.Com president Kent Anderson doesn't think the Internet
will end browsing as we know it; it will simply modify old habits.
Some folks will browse Web sites and buy in stores, and others will
browse stores and then buy on line, he believes. Macy's job is to
be all things to all shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   The shopper of the future may look like Northeastern University
student Leo Wiriadjaja, who buys books on line and clothes at the
mall. Just as Macy's offers customers three ways to buy
merchandise, many consumers will reach a point when they buy some
items on line, some by catalog, and others in stores.
</P>
<P>
   Why won't Wiriadjaja buy clothes on line? ``I'm not a normal
size,'' he says. ``I like to try things on first.''
</P>
<P>
   At its Web site, Lands' End Inc. looks to address such concerns
with a new ``virtual mannequin,'' one of many personalization
features e-commerce retailers are relying on more heavily this
year, as they seek to find ways to make on-line shopping a more
customer-friendly experience.
</P>
<P>
   At Landsend.com, some visitors can type in their measurements
and color preferences for a sweater, and the mannequin will not
only exhibit an image of how it will look on their body type, but
also suggest ideas for color-coordinated skirts and trousers.
</P>
<P>
   Another feature helps men select shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many shirts are available that it can be a daunting
challenge to wade through all of them,'' says Willie Doyle, a
Lands' End Internet executive.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford Express aims to make that task easier. Type in a
fabric preference. (Oxford pinpoint or 60-40 cotton blend?) Type in
a collar preference. (Button-down or tab?) After answering these
and similar questions, customers can quickly zero in on what they
want, Doyle says.
</P>
<P>
   Other Web sites tout similar search features.
</P>
<P>
   At Holtoutlet.com, the Web site of a Waltham company that sells
toys on line, shoppers can use a ``toy detective.'' No, this
playroom shamus won't be able to track down Furby _ but, then,
Furby is also hard to find at stores _ but type in the age of a
child on your gift list, a price range, and the kid's favorite TV
show, and the toy detective is supposed to round up some likely
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Holt debuted something else to help shoppers: a
rating system that lets customers grade the toys they've bought and
publish brief reviews that appear on Holt's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   MotherNature.com employs a similar strategy as it pursues its
goal to become the Amazon.com of on-line vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   Type in a malady at MotherNature.com's Web site, and a range of
possible remedies pop up. Built into the site is a ``health
encyclopedia,'' explains marketing vice president Sharon Rice.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes the best retail Web sites are ``selection and
information,'' she says. People may be reluctant to discuss medical
problems with a store clerk, but they may be more at ease going on
line in the privacy of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Certain commodity-type items such as books and music CDs have
sold well on the Internet. After all, a book is a book, whether
bought at Amazon.com or an old-fashioned book store.
</P>
<P>
   Rice believes vitamins, herbs, and supplements fall into a
similar category; by offering more choices and information, an
e-commerce retailer can gain an edge over brick-and-mortar rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Time _ or a lack of it _ may be the mall's worst enemy and the
Web's best friend. Faced with so many chores and errands,
two-income families want fast, hassle-free ways to shop.
</P>
<P>
   Such realities may explain why some malls are feeling the pinch
from the so-called power center, a much smaller strip mall anchored
by a superstore such as Home Depot, says Simmons College retail
professor Susan Sampson. The appeal? Consumers can zip in and out
of power centers far easier than big malls.
</P>
<P>
   But if consumers are looking to save time, they also want
service. And on that score, many Web sites don't measure up.
According to a recent study by Jupiter Communications, many Web
sites are ``failing miserably'' at service. Seeing an opening,
retail chains such as Filene's are redesigning parts of their store
floor plans to make shopping more convenient and less
time-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Web sites will get things right sooner or later _
even a confirmed mall shopper like Levine acknowledges that.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he can see himself shopping on line some day,
he replies, ``It's probably just a matter of time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
