<HEADER>
A0735 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAVERN-CHEF-2TAKES-HN     12-09 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAVERN-CHEF-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GENTLE GENERAL TAKES COMMAND OF CELEBRATED NEW YORK EATERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's just before noon on a recent Tuesday and the
kitchen at Tavern on the Green appears ready for battle.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two chefs have been preparing sauces, salads and side
dishes for the past three hours. They have now turned their
attention to entrees for the 500 or so patrons expected for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The air is intoxicating as the nose attempts to identify the
different aromas vying for attention. Roasted lobster with rosemary
risotto dominates one cooking station; barbecued baby back ribs
leave a heavenly smell in a nearby area. Activity is in all
directions, but chaos seems to be at a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's because it's only Tuesday and this is only lunch
at one of the Big Apple's top destination-dining spots. Another
reason may be the kitchen's commander-in-chief, Sam Hazen, who is
decidedly down to earth despite his high-profile position.
</P>
<P>
   Marching watchfully through the various kitchen stations,
sampling dishes and nodding or commenting as he passes, Hazen is
the only cook not wearing a toque, the classic tall white chef's
hat. The general with blue-collar roots is attired in a hunter
green baseball-style cap with the restaurant's logo.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a sterling culinary resume, Hazen was named executive
chef at Tavern on the Green in late September. He says he is
committed to making Tavern as well known for its cuisine as it is
for the amazing topiary gardens encircling the Central Park
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is simple. People come here from all over the world
to eat, and we want them telling their friends and neighbors
they've never had a better meal anywhere,'' explains Hazen, a trim
salt-and-pepper goatee wreathing his mouth. ``We want Tavern to be
the talk of the town.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict is not in yet. New York's restaurant critics usually
give a chef a few months to get settled before they review him.
</P>
<P>
   For that Hazen, 41, must be grateful, because few gigs are as
demanding as top chef at Tavern on the Green. It is a massive maze
of a place that seats 850 at a time. In 1997, the restaurant had
revenues in excess of $34.5 million, making it the highest-grossing
independently owned restaurant in the country.
</P>
<P>
   It took Hazen more than two weeks to learn the names of all 70
chefs in the kitchen, not to mention the wait staff and
dishwashers. The restaurant was the host site for the New York City
Marathon in early November. After six weeks on the job, Hazen found
himself serving 21,000 pounds of pasta to a finish-line party for
17,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't lie, it can be insane,'' he admits. ``It's like
driving a car 180 miles an hour in the left lane of the expressway
and then getting off in the right lane. It's a blur and it's
definitely a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a job that pays more than six figures and has the
potential to catapult Hazen into the galaxy of celebrity chefs, the
men and women viewed daily on the TV Food Network and public
television's numerous cooking shows.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty impressive stuff for a guy from upstate New York. Yet
hardly surprising, considering Hazen was practically born with a
cleaver in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Sam Hazen, and uncle, Russell, owned the Fifth
Avenue Diner in Troy. So the kid who was named for his dad spent
every day after school in the diner's kitchen. Summers, he was
there all day, every day.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was old enough to drive, young Sam was adept at
roasting veal shanks and baking pizzas. The family would also own
Three Coins and the Carriage House in Latham, before taking over
Someplace Else in Schuylerville. Sam Jr. stayed at his father's
side with each move.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my inspiration, without a doubt. I wouldn't be where I
am today without him,'' Hazen says of his father, who died of
cancer on Christmas Day 1976. ``I'm the only one left in the family
who's still cooking. Everyone else looks at it like it's too nutty
and too many hours, and they're probably right.''
</P>
<P>
   All four Hazen children worked alongside their parents in the
family's restaurants. Only the youngest, John, is still tied to the
food industry: He's a bartender at the San Remo Hotel in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all helped out, but Sam was with my father cooking more
than any of us,'' remembers Hazen's sister, Ruth Madigan, who now
lives in Schenectady. ``He always had an interest in it. When my
father passed away, I think Sam wanted to do something to carry on
what my father was proud of, preparing good food.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazen married his high school sweetheart, Lisa Leith, who
persuaded him to enter the Culinary Institute of America in Hyde
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the best thing that ever happened to me,'' Hazen
says. ``The CIA was the springboard to where I am today.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   He finished second in his class in 1982, and has been on the
culinary fast track ever since. He was a sous chef at several
acclaimed New York restaurants, La Cote Basque and Quilted Giraffe,
before venturing to London for more training. He was only the
second American to work in the kitchen at Le Gavroche, regarded as
England's premier restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Hazen returned to the CIA to teach for three years, where he was
a popular instructor, according to culinary dean Fritz
Sonnenschmidt.
</P>
<P>
   But he also felt the call to action, and decided to return to
Manhattan's intensely competitive fine dining world ``while I was
still young with some vinegar.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hazen and his wife, along with their 6-year-old son, Jake, live
in an Upper West Side apartment.
</P>
<P>
   He began his reappearance in the New York dining scene at
Cascabel, now closed but at the time a hot spot in the Union Square
area. Hazen was executive chef with a crew of 10, and the New York
Times' demanding critic Ruth Reichl graced his food with two stars
denoting ``very good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hazen's cooking seems to recognize no boundaries,'' Reichl
wrote. ``What is impressive is that he cooks with such confidence
that he never loses his footing.''
</P>
<P>
   Reichl, who is determined to wait until after the first of the
year to see how Hazen is faring at Tavern, remembers he was
particularly impressive with vegetarian dishes at Cascabel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the chefs who are trained the way he was tend to make
vegetarian food that feels like the middle is missing. I was really
struck with what a good job he did with vegetarian dishes,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hazen called Reichl before taking the job at Tavern. He wanted
advice, he says. He wasn't sure if it was a sound career move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for any chef those are difficult, terrible jobs, but
it's an amazing experience running a kitchen that large,'' Reichl
said. ``It's not like doing a regular restaurant. This is like
administering a city as opposed to a room. I would think that any
serious chef at some point would want to run a kitchen like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazen agrees, and that's why he and owner LeRoy Warner agreed to
a two-year contract. ``I decided I couldn't pass up this job. It's
a big job and very few people would be offered a job like this. To
come to this point in my career I had to do a lot beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts me in a different category,'' he adds. ``I could
jump into a hotel job now, if that's what I want to do. I was
always known before this as a white-tablecloth chef, but now I've
expanded my reputation and resume.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that the classically trained chef has been promoted
to a position where he does little cooking.In a teeming kitchen
where more than 50 chefs are working at once on a Friday or
Saturday evening, engaged in conversations in Spanish, Italian,
Portuguese and Chinese, Hazen is a coordinator and administrator.
</P>
<P>
   There are three head sous chefs who supervise the many cooks,
and each answers to the executive sous chef, who reports to Hazen.
There is even one chef whose sole responsibility is preparing
buffet-style ``family meals'' for the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, I don't do a lot of hands-on cooking,'' Hazen
admits. ``I will cook for VIPs, but I do a lot more tasting than
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing is, many nights when I leave here to go home I
realize when I'm on the way home that I'm incredibly hungry. I am
around food all the time, but I don't eat much. I must taste a
thousand different things every day, but I rarely sit down to eat
anything. One of the first things I do when I get home is look
around the house and see what my wife prepared for our son that
day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
