<HEADLINE>
SENATORS SEEK COMMITMENT FROM NORTH CAROLINA BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The two U.S. senators from California have asked
the head of BankAmerica, which was acquired by NationsBank Corp. in
September, to demonstrate its commitment to serving the state.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, a Democrat who serves on the Senate Banking
Committee, on Tuesday requested that the chairman and chief
executive of the company schedule meetings with California
officials to describe the bank's plans for making community
development money available in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recent events have renewed our concerns about the direction of
the new BankAmerica,'' Boxer said Tuesday in a letter to Hugh
McColl, who headed NationsBank of Charlotte, N.C., before its
merger with BankAmerica of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   She referred to the resignation of BankAmerica's former chief
executive, David Coulter, who had been on a track to ultimately
succeed McColl, and called it ``highly troubling.'' She also
mentioned the resignation in the past two months of several senior
executives who are women.
</P>
<P>
   These events raise ``questions about the new BankAmerica's
commitments to continuing its widely praised outreach programs,''
Boxer wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Howard Gutman, a spokesman for Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, also a Democrat, said the senator would be writing ``a
private letter to McColl expressing her concerns'' about reports of
the bank's direction.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, McColl said he was offended by reports questioning
the bank's commitment to promoting women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure our position is crystal clear _ Bank of
America is an inclusive meritocracy,'' McColl said in a letter to
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means we are firmly committed to the advancement of the
most qualified people and we will reward these associates who
achieve results regardless of their gender, religion, sexual
orientation, or any other non-performance-related factors.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past few days, several San Francisco officials, as well
as state Assemblyman Lou Papan, the Democratic chairman of the
Assembly Banking Committee, have said they are considering severing
city and state financial ties with the bank, citing concerns about
cultural and political differences between the North Carolina
headquarters and the San Francisco area.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of the departure of women executives in particular
triggered a sharp response. San Francisco City Attorney Louise
Renne called it ``outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank counters that 1,100 bank officials had ``change and
control agreements'' in their contracts through which attractive
severance packages were made available if they did not wish to
continue with the new bank.
</P>
<P>
   Bank spokesman John Keane said Tuesday that 70 percent of those
covered by the agreements were men and 30 percent were women. He
said more than 30 percent of those employees electing to stay were
women, which, he said demonstrates the bank's attractiveness to
women as a place to work.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer asked McColl to discuss these and other issues with city
and state officials and advocates for community development. McColl
is scheduled to speak to the Commonwealth Club in San Francisco on
Jan. 12 and to Town Hall in Los Angeles on Jan. 13 about
BankAmerica's commitment to California, Keane said.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer also asked McColl to meet with members of the California
congressional delegation and the state Legislature; establish a
California Reinvestment Coalition ``commitment for California,''
and personally ensure that community groups who criticized the
recent merger ``will suffer no retribution in terms of loan
approval or other services received.''
</P>
<P>
   Keane said Boxer may not be aware that meetings with some
community development groups have already taken place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
