<SLUG> BC-OLDEST-ARSENAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY ARSENAL MAY REACH DEAL WITH PRIVATE COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Illinois, Arkansas)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOB GARDINIER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERVLIET, N.Y. _ The U.S. Army's oldest arsenal is in
discussions with defense contractors about taking over some of its
operations, and an announcement about a deal could come soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has resisted the privatization of its arsenals in
Watervliet, Rock Island, Ill., and Pine Bluff, Ark., citing a need
for the United States to preserve its defense industrial base for
security reasons. But the Department of Defense is now conducting
similar privatization studies at the other arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   Watervliet is unique as it makes some of the world's most
expensive long-gun barrels for cannons, mortars and howitzers. The
Benet Laboratories, which employs about 200 and works on materials
testing and development, also is located at the arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been talks concerning private concerns and I think
there will be more on this coming out later this week,'' said
Charlie Diamond, spokesman for Rep. Michael McNulty, D-N.Y. The
arsenal is located near Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The Army is talking with a number of corporations, including
General Dynamics Corp. of Falls Church, Va., and Harsco Corp.'s BMY
Combat Systems Divisions in York, Pa., could set up shop at the
arsenal, said Tony Gaetano, a consultant for arsenal privatization.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are discussions the Army is having with a number of
companies that is a part of a two-year review of gathering
information about the cost of present arsenal operations,'' Gaetano
said. ``That information will be shared with all companies wishing
to make bids to operate in the arsenal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army itself, which now runs the arsenal and employs civilian
laborers, will also be able to bid, but it will have to prove it
can operate it at a profit, Gaetano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Dynamics and other companies are interested in running
the production side of things there but right now much of that is
up in the air,'' Gaetano said. ``I don't think that there are any
hard proposals on the table yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Privatization could affect most of the approximately 970 jobs at
the arsenal, though it is unclear how. The review will began in
October, Gaetano said.
</P>
<P>
   The union representing the workers has opposed privatizing the
185-year-old arsenal, which has lost 2,000 jobs over the past nine
years. Richard Brown, president of the National Federation of
Federal Employees union local at the arsenal, could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have serious concerns about the work force there,'' Diamond
said. ``We don't want someone to come in with their own workers and
force out arsenal workers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
