<SLUG> BC-AIRPLANE-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINER CLOSE CALLS RISE IN THE NORTHEAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Contrary to a nationwide decrease in near midair
airplane collisions, the number of high-altitude close calls over
New York state has doubled since last year, according to the
Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   That increase _ from four during the first 10 months of 1997 to
eight during the same period this year _ is part of an overall rise
in near-collision incidents over the seven-state region that
stretches from Washington, D.C., to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Two harrowing incidents in the past week brought talk of near
midair collisions, or NMACs as they are called by airlines and
controllers, into sharp focus.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, two airliners flying 33,000 feet above Long Island
came within one mile of each other _ a distance the FAA considers
perilously close _ before their pilots quickly banked in opposite
directions.
</P>
<P>
   Five days earlier, two commercial jets cruising high above the
Albany area were flying on a collision course before an air-traffic
controller in New Hampshire noticed the potential for disaster and
alerted the pilots.
</P>
<P>
   In the latter case, in which an on-board computer system appears
to have put the planes on a collision course, one controller later
told officials the two planes ventured so close that their radar
images had merged into one.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the marked increase in near midair accidents in New
York, as well as in Massachusetts and Pennsylvania, reports of such
incidents nationwide decreased almost 19 percent in the past year,
from 204 in the first 10 months of 1997 to 166 during the same
period this year, FAA records show.
</P>
<P>
   Most incidents involve commercial airliners, which are required
by federal regulations to keep several miles between one another
horizontally and thousands of feet of buffer space vertically.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials in New York were unable to explain Tuesday why the
number of near collisions has increased this year. But one airline
industry expert said the increase has less to do with increasing
departures at airports than with a rise in the number of
``overflights,'' long-distance flights through established
air-traffic corridors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the cases I'm familiar with, the problem stems from
overflights mixing with departures of local traffic,'' said Ed
Faberman, executive director of the Air Carrier Association, an
airline trade group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, near midair collisions are more likely to occur over
Chicago, Los Angeles or New York City, all of which lie under
popular overflight paths, Faberman said, as well as some less
populous parts of the country. For many years, Maine, for example,
lay underneath a common flight route to Europe, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1430EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0785 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETIREMENT-SAVINGS-HN     12-09 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIREMENT-SAVINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVVY SAVERS WILL TAKE MARKET FLUCTUATIONS IN STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _20One of the scariest things about working for a
living is thinking you might always be working for a living, or at
least far later into your old age than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Many workers might have feared just that after getting a look at
the third-quarter statements from their retirement plans at work.
That was the period that reflected the 512-point stock market dive
at the end of August. The implications didn't really sink in for
many people until October, when they received their
July-to-September quarterly account statements that detailed what
the market did to their retirement-plan holdings in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was a blessing in disguise, financial planners and
money managers said. Individuals can learn valuable, lasting
lessons about how to handle their retirement planning from this
year's market roller-coaster ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``The September statement was a rude shock from the June
statement,'' when the market was riding high, said Lynn Barnes, a
certified financial planner at Wright &AMP; Barnes in Schenectady, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Barnes' business is to manage retirement accounts for
small companies, whose employees call her directly with questions.
And they did.
</P>
<P>
   She got such questions as: ``What happened? I put money in, and
I lost.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense that many individuals are only now coming to
grips with this year's stock market volatility and what it may mean
for their financial futures. Their retirement-plan statements, and
not the daily fluctuations of the Dow Jones Industrial Average, are
the key.
</P>
<P>
   Many more households _ more than 30 percent in 1995 _ owned
stocks indirectly through vehicles such as retirement plans, than
directly (15 percent in the same year), according to the report,
``The State of Working America 1998-99,'' by Economic Policy
Institute in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, in recent years, some employees got the
unrealistic notion that their retirement accounts would forever
increase in value, because for a time it seemed like the stock
market behaved that way.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened with some people who work at Hannay Reels
in Westerlo, N.Y., a company that makes giant reels for firetrucks
and industrial plants. Some of the 150 employees thought the market
was on a permanent hot streak, said President Roger Hannay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They assumed that life would always be like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not so. The market can and does go down, sometimes inexplicably,
and sometimes hops back up again.
</P>
<P>
   The predominant theory, espoused by New York Comptroller H. Carl
McCall, who oversees 30 outside money managers for the state
employee pensions, is that people need to look at the long haul of
10 to 20 to 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't pull out when the stock market goes down
temporarily,'' McCall said.
</P>
<P>
   There are some strategies and developments, though, that people
need to keep an eye on in their retirement plans in the future.
</P>
<P>
   _ Know when you can make changes to your retirement plans, such
as when you can increase or decrease the amount of money going into
a 401(k) plan, or when you can switch some of the funds from one
kind of mutual fund to another.
</P>
<P>
   Employers usually establish specific periods of time when
employees can change course. This doesn't imply that you should
switch around all the time, or whenever you can.
</P>
<P>
   Hannay said that some employees at his company wanted to move
their holdings immediately after the market dived, and he told them
that their company plan's rules allow such movements only every
three months, at the start of the financial quarter. That's a good
policy, he said, because it makes it ``impossible to do market
chasing'' and focuses people more on long-term goals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consider putting more money, not less, into 401(k) retirement
accounts. Some nervous investors wanted to put a stop to new
contributions from their paychecks when the market tanked, said
Twila Slesnick, co-author of a new book, ``IRAs, 401(k)s and Other
Retirement Plans: Taking Your Money Out'' (Nolo Press, $21.95). But
that's the wrong approach, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Your money can buy more investments when the market is down, she
said. Other stock-pickers have been making the same point, and feel
the market dive was fortunate, because it made some stocks in
well-managed companies much more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do more research on the different investment strategies
offered inside your retirement plan to make sure it is properly
balanced. In bull-market years, some people got invested too
heavily in high-tech stocks, for instance, that they counted on for
big price appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   Some people even underestimated how much they would have to put
away, said Barnes, because they were counting on spectacular
investment growth. But that strategy led to losses for some when
the market tanked.
</P>
<P>
   You may need some stocks that are likely to lead to slower, but
more reliable, financial growth, as well as some bonds with a
predictable rate of return.
</P>
<P>
   Your age will make a big difference in what kind of mix is right
for you. People who are only two or three years from retiring need
at least some of their retirement money in bonds, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Some workers close to retirement at Hannay Reels, for instance,
wished they had some more conservative holdings in their accounts
when the market dived, Hannay said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Going forward, stay abreast of the options your employer
offers in 401(k) or similar plans and the professional
money-management firms the company hires to invest the money.
Employers choose money managers to invest according to certain
parameters _ such as a growth manager or a value manager _ and the
firms have to adhere to those standards.
</P>
<P>
   But within those categories of investment styles, firms can and
do periodically fire managers and switch to other firms they think
will do a better job. There weren't wholesale firings of managers
just because of this last stock market dive, however, because
``everybody was hit with equal pain,'' said Andrew Guillette,
consultant at Boston firm Cerulli Associates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
