<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0793 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-SMUGGLERS-ART-     12-09 1835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-SMUGGLERS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRANT INFLUX GIVES RISE TO TRAFFIC IN HUMAN CARGO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend use) 
 
(Graphic available on NYT database) 
 
By CARL HONORE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ Late last year, after his brother was
jailed and tortured by Saddam Hussein's police, Abdul Saleb began
plotting ways to flee his native Iraq for a new life in the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing for his own safety, the 26-year-old Kurdish physician
did what many would-be migrants lacking EU entry papers do
nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   He turned to the underworld for help.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of a friend put him in touch with a local
``businessman.'' Saleb paid $3,000 for the first leg of his
journey, which was to take him from Chwarta, his hometown in
northern Iraq, to Istanbul, Turkey. From there he hoped to make his
way to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous but also very excited when the deal was done,''
he says of his first brush with the traffickers who smuggle people
into the EU for cash.
</P>
<P>
   But Saleb's escape to freedom turned sour early on.
</P>
<P>
   Along with 10 other Iraqi Kurds and one trafficker, he set off
on foot through the rugged mountains that divide Iraq and Iran. For
six days, they hiked in single file, dodging villages and border
checks, eating dried fruit on the hoof, stopping only to sleep.
Saleb, a slight man with fine features, says his pleas for rest
were ignored.
</P>
<P>
   On the third day, an Iranian border patrol suddenly appeared on
a nearby ridge and opened fire, wounding a Kurd named Ali. The rest
of the group scrambled to safety. The trafficker _ a rough,
taciturn man _ refused to go back for their fallen companion.
</P>
<P>
   Saleb is still not sure what happened to Ali.
</P>
<P>
   ``That trafficker had no human feelings,'' he says, his voice
dropping. ``We were only cargo for him, and one death was no big
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the group made its way across the border into Turkey,
where a dusty truck was waiting. It drove to the city of
Diyarbakir, where a Turkish man made up false documents for the
group. The Kurds then boarded a series of buses for Istanbul.
There, with traffickers peddling trips to everywhere in the EU,
Saleb paid $5,000 _ the rest of his savings _ to a Turk offering
safe passage by land to Bavaria, in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so happy when we thought we had arrived in Germany
that one of the men, an Iranian, bent down and kissed the ground,''
Saleb says, rubbing his bloodshot eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Saleb still remembers with bitterness the moment it dawned on
him that he had been duped.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I realized that the road signs were not written in
German, my heart was broken.''
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish trafficker had dumped his passengers in Kyjov, a
small town here in the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, Saleb still has not reached the promised land of
Western Europe. The unmarried Saleb is now in Prague, the
picturesque Czech capital that has become a key transit point on
the smuggling routes to the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   With no legal right to be here, Saleb is doing odd jobs in the
black economy to scrabble together enough cash for a final run at
the walls of Fortress Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But even as he squirrels away his meager earnings, thousands of
other migrants are queuing up for the chance to buy their way into
the EU.
</P>
<P>
   As in the United States, the tightening of border security is
forcing people such as Saleb into the arms of professional
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   The Vienna-based International Center for Migration Policy
Development estimates that migrants pay gangs promising to smuggle
them into Western Europe $2 billion to $4 billion every year.
</P>
<P>
   Many traffickers along the EU border are small-time operators
trying to make some extra cash on the weekend. But authorities say
the trade is fast becoming a sophisticated branch of organized
crime, with some smugglers also dabbling in guns and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   According to police investigators, EU traffickers _ even more
than their peers in Mexico _ are plugging into networks with
offices and agents across the Third World. They have access to
expert document forgers. Many use high-tech gear often associated
with James Bond movies: satellite phones, high-speed boats and
cars, night-vision binoculars, sensors for eavesdropping on police
radios.
</P>
<P>
   Traffickers of many nationalities operate along every flank of
the European Union. They can be contacted through bars and cafes
dotted along the coast of North Africa. In Ceuta, a Spanish enclave
on the edge of Morocco, top smugglers are folk heroes, with
nicknames like El Nene (The Kid) and El Rey de las Lanchas (The
King of the Motorboats).
</P>
<P>
   Saleb chose Istanbul as his launch pad into the EU. With both
Iraq and Turkey locked in bloody conflict with Kurdish rebels,
European intelligence sources estimate that as many as 3 million
Kurds, many of them dreaming of a fresh start in the West, are
holed up in and around the ancient Turkish port city.
</P>
<P>
   Saleb, whose brother was accused of terrorist activity by Saddam
Hussein's police, stayed in a run-down boarding house in Kucuk
Pazar, an Istanbul neighborhood that draws a steady stream of
EU-bound migrants and the traffickers who seek their business.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the smugglers offered boat rides to Italy and Greece,
Saleb says. But because he has a deep fear of drowning, Saleb opted
instead for an overland trip to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Istanbul ``is like a giant bazaar, with so many people offering
to take you anywhere you want to go in (Western) Europe,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the former Soviet bloc is also crawling with
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Each time Saleb wanders through the old train station in
downtown Prague, a stranger sidles up to him, whispering,
``Germany? Germany?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They make eye contact, they circle around, and then they
approach you,'' he says. ``Usually they ask for lots of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Like any smart business, the trafficking industry offers
products to suit many budgets.
</P>
<P>
   A well-heeled migrant from China can spend up to $30,000 on a
deluxe package deal that includes airplane tickets, good hotels and
a skillfully forged passport. At the bottom of the market, a Sri
Lankan peasant might pay $3,000 to be taken to the EU partly on
foot and partly in the back of a truck packed with people.
Traffickers along the EU border itself charge as little as $1,000
per head per crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say, however, that bargain-hunters often get a raw
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Some are put to work in sweatshops to pay off their trips.
Others are sold telephone numbers of non-existent ``contacts'' in
the EU. Most have little say over their final destination, since
traffickers vary the routes according to current policing, weather
and laws.
</P>
<P>
   Like Saleb, many migrants are dumped somewhere along the
smuggling route and told they have arrived in Germany or the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a cruel and unfair business where the rights of the
consumer, the migrant, count for nothing,'' says Lucie Sladkova,
head of the Migrations Information Center within the Czech
Republic's border police.
</P>
<P>
   At the first sign of danger, traffickers often scamper, leaving
their clients to face capture or worse. In winter, in the freezing
mountains between Germany and the Czech Republic, border police
have come across migrants shivering in thin garments and sandals.
Many have suffered severe frostbite, and some have died.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the main migrant graveyard lies in the treacherous waters of
the Strait of Gibraltar, where the flimsy motorboats used by
traffickers often capsize. Aid agencies put the death toll this
year at around 1,000, compared with 3,000 in the previous 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward smuggling ever-larger groups is most visible on
the open waters of the Mediterranean Sea. Every so often, European
coast guards intercept a large ship packed with migrants. Though
the traffickers charge luxury-cruise prices, the conditions are
usually appalling, authorities say.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Salah Taha, an Iraqi Kurd, paid $4,000 to travel
in a ship from Istanbul to ``somewhere in Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   The vessel was an aging freighter, and the 800 migrants were
locked in the cargo hold. Scraps of stale bread and water were
dispensed once a day, Taha says. The single toilet backed up, so
people relieved themselves on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   After a week, the crew, without warning, cut the engines and
fled in motorboats. After drifting for hours, the freighter ran
aground on the coast of Calabria, in southern Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took all that money from us and put us into hell,'' says
Taha, who, unlike most illegal migrants, was lucky enough to earn
asylum in Italy. ``I still have nightmares about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when they do reach the European Union, many migrants remain
beholden to the criminals who guided them there, police say. Some
traffickers, notably Chinese smugglers called ``snakeheads,'' have
kidnapped their clients to extort money from their families back
home.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, police in London have freed 15 Chinese
migrants held hostage by their fellow countrymen. Many were badly
beaten; one had been tied to a radiator for 12 days and his eardrum
had been punctured by the aerial of the mobile phone used to
blackmail his terrified wife in China.
</P>
<P>
   Police suspect that hundreds, maybe thousands, more migrants are
trapped in similar bondage across Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   EU governments are trying to end the traffic in people with
tougher law enforcement and by pushing neighboring states to clamp
down. But the traffickers still seem to have the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   Though hundreds of smugglers have been sentenced to jail terms
in Western Europe, many more have slipped through the legal
dragnet. Physical evidence of their crimes is often scarce, and
most migrants are afraid to point the finger.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the EU, say experts, many police forces remain corrupt
and inefficient. Another problem is that many non-EU officials
still regard people-smuggling as a relatively benign crime.
</P>
<P>
   In the days of the old Soviet bloc, ``anyone who trafficked
people into the West was a hero for us,'' says Sladkova, the
director of the Czech Migrations Information Center. ``It's one
thing to change the laws. It's another to change people's
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   If the war on drugs is a marker, then authorities are also
waging an uphill battle against the laws of supply and demand. As
long as migrants are willing to tolerate the risk and cost of being
smuggled into the EU, then traffickers will be there for them.
</P>
<P>
   On a clear, breezy evening in Prague, Saleb leans against the
stone railing on the famous Charles Bridge, staring blankly at a
German family posing for photographs.
</P>
<P>
   He talks about traffickers like a junkie talks about his drug
dealer. He cannot bring himself to just say no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they are evil people, that they cheat us and leave us
to die, but what else can I do?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need them, because I cannot get into Western Europe by
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
