<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0794 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-PROSTITUTION-H     12-09 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-PROSTITUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN SEEKING LIFE OF FREEDOM FIND THEMSELVES TRAPPED IN SEXUAL
SLAVERY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend use) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Honore) 
 
By CARL HONORE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands _ On clear evenings, hundreds of tourists
amble through Europe's most famous red-light district, gawking at
prostitutes who stand in the windows wearing only lingerie and
come-hither smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Along the tree-lined canals and narrow back streets that are the
Dutch capital's biggest tourist draw, the atmosphere seems oddly
relaxed. U.S. retirees point and giggle. German teen-agers munch on
french fries. Japanese tour groups pose for photographs. Sometimes
the ``window girls'' join in the fun, putting on a little dance or
blowing a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest profession could almost pass for light entertainment
here. But behind the air-brushed facade, Amsterdam's sex bazaar
holds a sinister secret: Local police believe that many of the
women selling their bodies in the windows are immigrants trapped in
sexual slavery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible thing to see,'' says Ruud Bierhausen, an
Amsterdam vice-squad detective. ``Sometimes, we approach the girls,
and they are so scared that they are white in the face and
shaking.'' Like many investigators, Bierhausen is reluctant to put
a figure on the number of women caught in sexual slavery, saying
only that there are ``lots and lots.''
</P>
<P>
   But Luceia Brusa, a researcher at the De Graaf Foundation, an
Amsterdam-based group that studies prostitution, guesses that more
than half the sex workers in the Dutch capital could be working
under some form of duress.
</P>
<P>
   And Amsterdam is not alone. No one knows how many foreign women
are being trafficked into sexual bondage in the European Union
every year, but estimates range well into the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is getting worse,'' Brusa says. ``The trade in
women is not only becoming highly internationalized and organized,
it is also becoming more violent.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the rise in forced prostitution seem clear.
Authorities say young women in poor countries are aching for a
chance to start a new life in the West. Sex traders can make a
fortune exploiting their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Asians and Africans used to be the main victims, but the demise
of the Soviet Union has created a vast reservoir of desperate white
women. Young blondes from the former Eastern bloc are now the
hottest commodities on the market.
</P>
<P>
   The road to sexual bondage is not always the same. With the help
of traffickers, who are often linked to East European mafias, the
women enter the European Union on tourist visas or with false
documents, or by slipping across a remote stretch of border,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Many come intending to work as prostitutes, only to end up as
someone's indentured servant. But others start off more innocently.
Some are simply kidnapped from their home countries, police say.
Many are lured to the EU by bogus marriage proposals or by the
promise of well-paid jobs as maids, nannies or waitresses. By the
time the dream offers are exposed as lies, it is too late. The
women are already the property of pimps in London or Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Most victims of forced prostitution are reluctant to talk to
reporters. Instead, they tell their stories to social workers, who
pass them on to the press, with last names deleted.
</P>
<P>
   Monika's story is one example.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the 21-year-old Pole answered a newspaper ad seeking
staff for a new ``fashion restaurant'' in Germany. A man picked her
up from her parents' home outside Warsaw, drove her to a hotel near
the German border and raped her.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, she was sold to a brothel in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Her new ``owner,'' Klaus, had a volcanic temper, she later told
counselors. Monika once saw him break the arm of a young Russian
woman. After six months in the brothel, serving several customers
per day, Monika was set free by a police raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every minute was hell,'' she said afterward. ``My dream was to
come to Western Europe, and I ended up being used like an animal.''
</P>
<P>
   Trafficking in prostitutes is a license to print money.
According to police investigators, Western European pimps will pay
$500 to $20,000 for a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, police in Milan, Italy, cracked a gang that put
half-naked women from Slavic countries on blocks and auctioned them
off to the highest bidders. Some of the gang members are now
awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a shipment of illegal drugs, which is only consumed once,
a prostitute can go on earning thousands of dollars every month for
her ``owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Sex slaving is also less risky than drug dealing. Prostitution
is not yet fully legalized anywhere in the EU, but most local
authorities, notably in Amsterdam, tolerate it. Even when arrests
are made, sex slavers often evade prosecution, because most victims
are too scared to testify against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dealing in women is a fast and safe way to get very rich,''
says Brusa, of the De Graaf Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   No longer content with just selling women on the open market,
Eastern European mafias are investing in their own brothels, clubs
and massage parlors inside the EU, police say. This boosts profits
and allows them to keep closer tabs on their ``staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Victims across Western Europe describe the same regime of
terror. Their passports are taken or burned, authorities say. They
are allowed to keep only a fraction, if any, of their earnings.
Some are sold to a pimp in another EU country when police or social
workers get too close. Many are beaten or raped into submission.
</P>
<P>
   Bierhausen, the Amsterdam detective, thinks that pimps from the
former Yugoslavia are the most vicious in the business, perhaps
because their homeland was recently brutalized by civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard rumors of hot irons being used on girls' faces,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, a dozen victims of forced prostitution are believed to
be murdered every year.
</P>
<P>
   Blackmail is another trick of the trade, authorities say. Most
women are warned that if they misbehave, their families back home
will be attacked or sent photos of them having sex with clients.
Many victims are afraid to go to the police, believing them to be
on the traffickers' payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``These women are completely terrorized,'' says Tryntje
Kootstra, director of the Foundation Against Trafficking In Women,
based in Utrecht, Netherlands. ``They don't know where to turn or
how to get out of this nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are trying to stem the traffic in women. To address
the problem, the EU funds public-awareness campaigns in former
Soviet bloc countries and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout last summer, Polish television and cinemas screened a
short film about Kasia, a fictional young woman who emigrates to
Germany to work in a restaurant and ends up enslaved by a sadistic
pimp. Narrated in an actress's tremulous voice, the film shows a
series of harrowing images: young women in G-strings dancing in the
dark, mice scurrying in a cage, a half-peeled orange exploding in a
hand, beds bursting into flames.
</P>
<P>
   Along with publicity campaigns, governments have tightened laws
and assigned more police to investigate forced prostitution.
Authorities are trying to make it easier for victims to testify.
Sex traffickers are on trial or under arrest in several countries,
and some convictions have been secured.
</P>
<P>
   No one, however, predicts an end to the flesh trade any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Witness-protection programs, legal systems and police efforts
still leave much to be desired, critics say. And Western Europe
shows no sign of losing its hypnotic pull on young women from
around the world, who convince themselves that forced prostitution
only happens to other people.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with social workers, Tatyana, a Russian survivor
of forced prostitution, summed up the future thus:
</P>
<P>
   ``My life was ruined by these monsters. And I know that I will
not be the last.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
