<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0796 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-BORDERS-ART-2T     12-09 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-BORDERS-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU SCRAMBLES TO MAKE ITS BORDERS MORE SECURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend use) 
 
(Second of four-part series, with EUROPE-TEXAS, EUROPE-ENTRY and
EUROPE-LAW) 
 
(Photos available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Honore) 
 
By CARL HONORE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EISSENHUTTENSTADT, Germany _ The green van scrunches to a halt
on a bend in the gravel road. Two German border guards, eyes
shielded by sunglasses, pistols bobbing at their sides, leap out
into the morning air.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Steenfatt, lean and blond, scampers up the grassy bank
first. Through binoculars, he patiently scans the woods and fields
that fan out into the distance.
</P>
<P>
   This is the eastern border of the European Union, a political
and economic alliance of 15 states. The narrow Neisse River down
below, which divides Germany and Poland, is a favorite crossing
point for illegal immigrants seeking a better life in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Like the southwestern United States, the EU is wrestling with an
immigration crisis. Even as border security tightens, some experts
estimate that a million people from across the Third World could
attempt to sneak into the EU this year, with many trying to enter
via Germany.
</P>
<P>
   It is up to border guards like Steenfatt to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   On this balmy morning, two suspects have been spotted along the
Neisse River near Eissenhuttenstadt, but there is no sign of them
now. The only sounds are the wind rustling through the trees and
the distant chirping of birds. Even the river is silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Must have been a false alarm,'' shrugs Steenfatt. ``Or else
they're already through and long gone by now.''
</P>
<P>
   A glance at the map explains his nonchalance and why EU border
police are battling against tough odds.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctant to build another Iron Curtain with militarized fences
and fortified walls, Europeans have settled for an external
frontier patrolled mainly by guards and gadgetry.
</P>
<P>
   On its eastern flank, the EU's invisible border snakes for
nearly 2,500 miles through meadows and mountain ranges, along
rivers and past towns and villages. To the south, the whole
underbelly of Europe is exposed to the Mediterranean Sea. Italy
alone has 4,600 miles of coastline.
</P>
<P>
   With so many points of entry and with the help of sophisticated
traffickers who smuggle human cargo for cash, waves of migrants
breach the walls of Fortress Europe every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``With extra policing, we will catch more of them,'' says
Steffen Angenendt, a migration expert at the German Society for
Foreign Affairs, a think-tank partly funded by the German state.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we will never stop illegal immigration altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Western European governments are striving to hold back
the tide.
</P>
<P>
   Every frontier state in the EU, from Finland in the north to
Spain in the south, is shoring up its border defenses. Neighboring
non-EU countries are under heavy pressure, and receiving EU funds,
to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   No state, though, has done as much as Germany to fortify its
borders. The number of guards along its eastern frontier has
tripled since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   New helicopters and high-speed boats with night-vision equipment
have been introduced, as have a dozen vans with thermographic
cameras that can pick out a person five miles away, even in the
fog.
</P>
<P>
   Germany also runs a nationwide telephone hotline that
automatically connects the dialer with the nearest border-police
station. Tip-offs from citizens account for almost half of all
arrests of illegal immigrants in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But even the combined efforts of EU states and their people
cannot halt the flow. This year, some experts estimate that as many
as half a million migrants could slip past EU border defenses, with
more than two-thirds vanishing into the underground economy and the
rest later claiming asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Having hit a dead end at the edge of the Neisse River, Steenfatt
and his partner clamber back into the van to continue their morning
patrol. They drive down country roads and through small villages,
looking for anyone or anything that seems out of place.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour, Steenfatt begins to pine for the night shift,
when crossings are more common.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he is interrupted by the shortwave radio, which
crackles rudely into life. An urgent voice barks something in
German. Another border patrol has caught an Asian man swimming
across the river near Guben, about 15 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Back at base camp, a cluster of low concrete buildings tucked
away in a clump of forest near Eissenhuttenstadt, Steenfatt joins
fellow border guards to await the arrival of their latest catch.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner of the compound, a row of cars confiscated from
traffickers is lined up like trophies on a mantelpiece.
Spanking-new BMWs with German license plates nestle beside beat-up
Ford hatchbacks registered in Poland. The latest addition is a
white Volkswagen Passat with Lithuanian plates. The vehicle was
intercepted by border police while carrying a trafficker and three
young women probably headed for prostitution somewhere in the EU.
</P>
<P>
   A thin rain begins to fall just as the van with the captured
Asian pulls into the compound. Still shivering in his wet track
suit, the man, who appears to be in his mid-20s, slides from the
back seat onto the tarmac. His hands are cuffed. He looks tired and
dazed. Two guards escort him up the steps of the processing center,
through the front door and down a long, dim corridor lined with
holding cells.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside each steel door hangs a sheet of paper bearing the
scratched-out names of recent prisoners: Ho Fong, Vladimir Petrov,
Muhammed al-Qatar. Names from every corner of the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the corridor, in a bleak, unfurnished room, the
still-unidentified Asian, who police guess to be Korean or
Vietnamese, is ordered to pose against a wall for mug shots. He
blinks at each flash.
</P>
<P>
   On a nearby table, two guards wearing plastic gloves empty his
sodden black knapsack. They start sifting through the contents. A
faded pair of Levi's jeans. A bar of soap and a toothbrush. A diary
and some air-mail envelopes in a plastic bag.
</P>
<P>
   The migrant looks on with empty eyes. He refuses to speak. No
doubt he has been briefed on German law.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, EU countries have made it easier to deport
undocumented foreigners. But an illegal migrant who cannot be
identified and whose travel route to the EU is unclear still stands
a chance of avoiding deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the tight-lipped Asian from the doorway, Steenfatt _
his hands resting on his holster belt _ rocks back and forth on his
boot heels. He is itching to get back out into the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there is a feeling of release when you catch someone,
but you always suspect that others are getting through while you're
back here doing the paperwork,'' he says. ``You always wonder if
the traffickers are throwing you a diversion. We get this one guy
here, while they sneak through 15 more.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Border policing in Western Europe has changed profoundly in
recent years. In the early 1990s, migrants openly stormed the
frontiers of the EU, and many were happy to be caught. Once in the
hands of German border police, for example, they could claim asylum
and live off state benefits while their claims were processed.
Sometimes whole villages from the former Yugoslavia turned up at
the border in buses or on foot.
</P>
<P>
   But the tightening of immigration and asylum laws, together with
the beefed-up security, has forced migrants to be more cunning and
to hire professional smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Along this stretch of German border, guards like Steenfatt play
cat and mouse with the traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides dress up as fishermen or as courting couples to scout
the banks of the Neisse and the Oder, the other, wider river that
separates Germany and Poland. Both sides use informers, authorities
say. The traffickers often toss the border police a migrant or two
as a red herring.
</P>
<P>
   According to Steenfatt, each technological or tactical advance
is countered by the other side. Many traffickers now carry
night-vision binoculars. When some smugglers invested in scanners
to eavesdrop on police radio, German police bought scanners to
detect the eavesdropping.
</P>
<P>
   Steenfatt and his colleagues sometimes spend hours watching a
strip of border through night-vision cameras, waiting for a
trafficker to spirit his customers across. To conceal their
surveillance tactics, the border patrol agents often let their prey
advance a couple of miles into German territory before pouncing.
</P>
<P>
   An avid fan of U.S. sports, Steenfatt sums up his job with a
football analogy. ``We are like linebackers,'' he says, smiling.
``We wait to see if they're going to run or throw. We try to guess
what they're thinking, then we try to beat them on the play.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not always clear who is winning the ball game. Last year,
the German border police caught more than 500 traffickers, many of
whom have been sentenced to jail terms of two to four years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the officers who patrol the 160 miles of border where
Steenfatt is posted are catching fewer illegal migrants than
before.
</P>
<P>
   Is that because better policing is forcing traffickers to try
their luck farther south, where the mountainous terrain is harder
to patrol? Or are traffickers just getting smarter at slipping the
tackles?
</P>
<P>
   No one here is complacent. Despite the recent strides in
technology and manpower, border police on the beat still moan about
their handicaps.
</P>
<P>
   The traffickers have digital mobile phones, they say, while
border guards rely on heavy walkie-talkies that have poor
reception. Lumbering police vans are no match for a stolen
Mercedes. It takes 30 minutes for a helicopter to arrive at the
border from the base in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   At official crossings from Poland and the Czech Republic, German
border guards complain that they lack the staff to search every
vehicle for stowaways.
</P>
<P>
   Better border security in neighboring non-EU states,
particularly Poland, is relieving some of the pressure. But experts
say traffickers can still outfox the underpaid and underequipped
border patrols in countries that surround Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Czech border guards were issued
carbon-dioxide detectors for sniffing out migrants concealed in
trucks. According to a police spokesperson, the only hidden cargo
detected so far has been a few horses and a shipment of sauerkraut.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much money in play that the traffickers can afford
to stay one step ahead of the border police, especially in the
non-EU countries,'' says Angenendt, of the German Society for
Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The men and women who man the EU borders talk with pride about
their mission to uphold the law. Still, many feel compassion for
the migrants whom they are paid to hunt down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the situation in their home countries, you
can understand why they risk everything to come all this way for a
new life,'' says Steenfatt. ``If I were in their shoes, I would
probably do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Language barriers make it hard for EU border police to strike up
much rapport with the migrants. A smattering of Spanish can go a
long way on the U.S.-Mexico frontier. But the huddled masses
heading for the EU speak everything from Urdu to Estonian to
Mandarin Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, European border police claim to feel the human tragedy
that is part of their daily grind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not robots, you know,'' says Steenfatt, his angular face
softening slightly. ``When you find a small child in the woods with
big brown eyes, hungry and cold because the trafficker has run away
and left them there, you can hardly hold back the tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Most border police regard traffickers as parasites. They also
fear the smugglers' growing penchant for carrying weapons.
Steenfatt and others have used their own money to buy lightweight
bullet-proof vests to replace those issued by the German state,
which are too cumbersome to wear all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his colleagues, Steenfatt never crosses into nearby
Poland when off-duty, just in case one of the many traffickers
based there decides to settle a grudge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never say anything when you stop them for questioning,
but you can feel that they are remembering your face for next
time,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the silent Asian to his fate back at base camp,
Steenfatt and his partner join a boat patrol on the Oder River.
With the wind flapping through his beige uniform and pop music
wafting up from the on-board radio, Steenfatt stands on the rear
deck of the boat, scanning the shoreline through his binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   The German side is more densely wooded than the Polish side.
Along both shores, children swim and play, and fishermen sit with
rods in the water and baskets of supplies by their sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all looks very quiet and innocent, but you can never be 100
percent sure,'' says Steenfatt, pointing to a fisherman speaking
into a mobile phone on the Polish side. ``Is he chatting to his
wife, or is he tipping off a trafficker about our movements?''
</P>
<P>
   There is a brief flicker of excitement when an old barge is
spotted farther up the Oder. But another patrol boat gets there
first, and its crew is soon combing the vessel and its cargo of
coal for illegal migrants. The police come up empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour of scouring the riverbanks in vain, Steenfatt
finally spots something: a clump of discarded clothes on the German
side.
</P>
<P>
   He jots down the position without urgency, though. A land patrol
will return later to examine the evidence, to see if the clothes
belonged to illegal migrants and, if so, whether the traffickers
have opened up a new route. If migrants did dump the garments, they
are probably half way to Berlin or Frankfurt by now.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the afternoon, with his shift winding down and
the sun sagging below the horizon, Steenfatt begins to realize that
he will not catch anyone today.
</P>
<P>
   As the police boat slices a path through the water and the
wilderness, he allows himself a little gripe about the odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want us to catch every illegal who tries to cross here,
but look at this,'' he says, waving at the trees and bushes that
line both sides of the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much land and so many places to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
