<HEADLINE>
EU LOOKS TO THE U.S.-MEXICO EXPERIENCE FOR GUIDANCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend use) 
 
(Photo available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Honore) 
 
By CARL HONORE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EISSENHUTTENSTADT, Germany _ On trips around Europe, German
border guard Jan Steenfatt likes nothing better than to drop in on
local police stations to swap a little shop talk.
</P>
<P>
   His dream is to spend a day along the Texas-Mexico frontier with
the U.S. Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really want to go over there and visit,'' he says. ``I think
I could learn a lot from their way of doing things.''
</P>
<P>
   As the European Union fights to secure its own borders against
illegal immigration, the experience along the U.S.-Mexico frontier
stands out as a bench mark. Most Europeans concede that Americans
are more experienced in defending a long land border.
</P>
<P>
   Illegal migration via land routes only became a problem in
Western Europe after the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989. Before
then, the Iron Curtain kept the EU's eastern flank secure, and most
undocumented migrants came up from the south, from across the
Mediterranean Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Since the collapse of the Soviet bloc, 10 EU countries have
dismantled entry controls along their shared internal borders,
making their territory even more alluring for illegal migration.
</P>
<P>
   As pressure has built in the 1990s to keep illegal migrants out
of the EU, politicians, police and academics from Europe and the
United States have shuttled back and forth across the Atlantic,
attending seminars and observing border patrols in action.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent years, we've had more and more visitors from
Europe,'' says Doug Mosier, spokesman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service in Dallas. ``I think that, in terms of
technologies and strategies, the U.S. is still seen as the
pioneer.''
</P>
<P>
   A little more than a million immigrants settle legally in the
European Union every year _ about the same number as in the United
States and Canada put together. Of the many people claiming asylum
in the EU this year, about 250,000 _ roughly double the figure for
the United States _ are expected to pass the first legal hurdles to
have their cases heard.
</P>
<P>
   But further comparisons are hard to make. European migration
statistics are patchy, because EU states keep separate records, use
different accounting methods and often keep their findings secret.
</P>
<P>
   According to the INS, U.S. border patrol agents arrested 1.4
million undocumented migrants in the 1996-97 fiscal year. The INS
estimates that 275,000 people slip into the United States illegally
each year.
</P>
<P>
   No such official figures are available for the EU as a whole,
but some experts suspect that up to half a million migrants make it
past border guards into the European Union every year.
</P>
<P>
   Impressed by the American track record in nabbing illegal
immigrants at the border, Europeans have taken up much of the
high-tech gadgetry, such as infrared binoculars and cameras, used
by U.S. Border Patrol agents. EU states are also moving to build a
U.S.-style database that would pool information on asylum-seekers.
</P>
<P>
   In communications, the United States is showing the way with
encrypted two-way digital radios and the growing use of satellite
technology to pinpoint border agents on patrol. ``Our radios are
antiques in comparison,'' grumbles Steenfatt. ``Sometimes they
don't even work (30 feet) away.''
</P>
<P>
   At 2,000 miles, the U.S.-Mexico border is shorter than the
eastern frontier of the European Union, which runs for more than
2,500 miles from Finland to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans seem more willing to install occasional fixed
barriers along their border, such as the 1.2-mile chain-link fence
in El Paso, in an effort to keep illegal immigrants out.
</P>
<P>
   Haunted by memories of the Iron Curtain, many Europeans _
particularly Germans _ prefer to leave their frontiers physically
open, apart from border checkpoints on key roads. Germany even
shuns automated cameras and sensors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our different history gives us some different attitudes than
the Americans,'' says Eckehart Wache, who commands guards along a
160-mile stretch of German-Polish border. ``We do not want fences
and walls or an automated border system. We always want an officer
to be on the spot to make the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and EU border police are caught in the same vicious circle:
The better they get at their job, the more migrants turn to
criminals who smuggle human cargo.
</P>
<P>
   On both sides of the Atlantic, the people-smuggling industry is
thriving, though experts think traffickers in Europe may have
stronger links with organized crime and more sophisticated
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   EU border police face a more diverse mix of migrants than their
counterparts in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   People from all over the developing world are caught sneaking
across the southwestern U.S. border, but the vast majority are
Mexican. Once criminal background checks are run, illegal migrants
from Mexico often are taken to an international bridge, where
Border Patrol agents watch them cross back to their native country.
</P>
<P>
   Things are not so simple in Europe, where most undocumented
migrants hail from countries not directly bordering the EU. Often
they have sold everything and traveled thousands of miles to start
a new life in Europe. Many will try anything _ from refusing to
give their identities to filing weak claims for asylum _ to avoid
being sent back.
</P>
<P>
   Although instant deportation is becoming more common, EU states
still face legal and diplomatic obstacles to expelling illegal
migrants.
</P>
<P>
   In one regard, though, EU border police have a clear edge over
their American peers. Nations on the eastern border of the EU are
helping to clamp down on illegal immigration in ways that U.S.
border guards can only dream about.
</P>
<P>
   Countries such as Poland and the Czech Republic are desperate to
join the EU and know that securing their borders is a precondition
for membership. One result is that former Soviet bloc states are
now catching thousands of illegal migrants before they even reach
the EU border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is important,'' says Steenfatt. ``But even with the
best equipment in the world, you need cooperation from the guys on
the other side'' of the border.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
