<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-ENTRY-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL ACROSS EUROPE IS NOW MORE LIKE U.S. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend use) 
 
(Graphic available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Honore) 
 
By CARL HONORE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In much the same way as Americans cross state lines,
people can now move around much of continental Western Europe
without passing through customs or passport controls.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Schengen agreement, traditional entry controls have
been scrapped along the shared borders of 10 European Union
countries _ Germany, France, Spain, Portugal, Belgium, Greece, the
Netherlands, Luxembourg, Italy and Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to make life easier for EU citizens, the resulting
freedom of movement is a boon to criminals and illegal migrants.
Any undocumented person who manages to sneak across the Neisse
River from Poland to Germany, for example, can expect to make his
way unimpeded to Paris or Amsterdam or Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Border controls remain in effect in EU countries that have not
joined the Schengen group _ Denmark, Finland, Sweden, Ireland and
the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   To compensate for the lack of internal border controls, Schengen
countries invest heavily in joint security. Police carry out random
spot checks of people, particularly in border areas, which means
that Europeans and others must carry ID cards at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Stored in a nuclear bomb-proof vault in Strasbourg, France, a
database keeps records on millions of travelers, many of whom are
non-EU citizens permanently banned from entering the Schengen zone.
Some European police carry mobile computer terminals that can
access the database. Even so, many illegal immigrants travel freely
across the Schengen zone, fueling xenophobia and causing political
sparks to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's porous external borders have earned it a reputation as
the ``leaky sieve'' and the ``soft underbelly'' of Europe. Thanks
to Schengen, Italy is now effectively the gatekeeper for other EU
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from their Schengen partners, the Italians are
clamping down on illegal immigration. But Germany and other
countries remain nervous.
</P>
<P>
   During a surge in the flow of Kurdish refugees from Iraq and
Turkey earlier this year, France and Austria temporarily beefed up
police checks along their borders with Italy.
</P>
<P>
   And in recent months, some German politicians have called for
Schengen to be shelved altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Says Jonas Widgren, director of the International Center for
Migration Policy Development based in Vienna, Austria: ``If Europe
does not win the battle against illegal immigration, then the whole
edifice (of Schengen) is in danger.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1437EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
