<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0801 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-LAWS-HNS &LR;      12-09 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-LAWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU IMMIGRATION LAWS SEEK TO KEEP THE LID ON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend use) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Honore) 
 
By CARL HONORE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Border police are one way to keep people out of
Fortress Europe. Laws are another.
</P>
<P>
   ``European countries are not looking for new immigrants, and our
laws reflect that,'' says Patrick Weill, a Paris-based expert on
immigration legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the European Union is not hermetically sealed.
</P>
<P>
   EU countries grant residency to just over 1 million people each
year, about the same number as the joint total for the United
States and Canada, which have 20 percent less population.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the newcomers rejoin families already settled in Europe.
Others earn asylum or avoid arrest long enough to qualify for
amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   To keep pace with globalization, the EU's 15 member states have
made it relatively easy for highly skilled foreign workers, ranging
from bankers to computer analysts, to take jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Most countries also run programs that allow non-EU citizens to
come in temporarily to perform the low-skill work, such as seasonal
farm labor, that most Europeans no longer want.
</P>
<P>
   But these immigrants are the lucky ones. Millions of other
people are thwarted by mounting legal barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Long gone are the days when people from the Third World could
earn the right to settle in the European Union simply by filling
out a few forms.
</P>
<P>
   After the oil crisis of the 1970s, which triggered an economic
crunch and widespread job losses, northern EU countries abolished
their programs for recruiting foreign workers. Southern EU
countries, where immigration traditionally has been weaker,
followed suit a little later.
</P>
<P>
   After refugees from Eastern Europe and elsewhere began flocking
to the region in the early 1990s, all EU countries moved to tighten
their asylum laws, harmonize their immigration rules and bolster
border security.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, most Western European states have tinkered with
their family reunification rules _ raising the minimum income
requirements or lowering the maximum age of eligibility _ to
restrict the flow of people joining relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious tightening, however, has been in asylum
regimes.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, potential refugees picked an EU country and turned
up at its border to claim asylum. The state supported them while
their cases were considered. If rejected, they applied in another
EU country.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to new EU-wide agreements, asylum-seekers must now apply
for refugee status in their first EU port of call, whether they
wish to stay in that country or not. An applicant turned down by
one member state can no longer apply to another. Benefits paid to
asylum seekers have also been trimmed.
</P>
<P>
   Many EU countries now have laws allowing for the instant
deportation of an asylum-seeker if authorities can prove his or her
identity and that he or she touched ground in a ``safe'' country en
route to Western Europe. Most states bordering the EU, including
Poland and the Czech Republic, are now judged to be ``safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Andreas Muster, a Berlin-based immigration specialist, says,
``The joke is that the only way that anyone can claim asylum in
Germany nowadays is by parachuting in.''
</P>
<P>
   Even traveling to the European Union is harder than it used to
be.
</P>
<P>
   All member states now demand visas of citizens from a long list
of non-Western countries that never used to need them.
</P>
<P>
   Many EU countries post officials in foreign airports to check
Europe-bound travelers for fake documents. Airlines and other
carriers face fines for bringing undocumented passengers to EU
soil.
</P>
<P>
   Around five years from now, most member nations will hand over
the task of generating laws on immigration and asylum to the
European Commission, the EU's executive branch in Brussels. Some
hope the shift will further reinforce the legal ramparts of
Fortress Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In what could be a sign of things to come, Austria, which now
holds the rotating EU presidency, is proposing that the European
Union as a whole scrap the right to permanent refugee status
enshrined in the 1951 Geneva Convention and replace it with a
watered-down offer of temporary protection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1438EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
