<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0804 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-FOREIGNERS-ART     12-09 1620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-FOREIGNERS-ART-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
VITROLLES, France: name changes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``For too long, we've sat back and let these foreigners dance
all over us,'' he says, walking his dog near the center of town.
``It may seem like nothing to change a street sign, but it sends a
signal that enough is enough, that we are ready to take back our
city and our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Front has gone beyond symbolism in Vitrolles.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of immigrant workers have been axed from the City Hall
payroll, and some ``native'' replacements have been hired in from
other towns. Funding for social programs, especially those catering
to immigrants, has been cut.
</P>
<P>
   Early last summer, the youth center in Les Pins, a neighborhood
with a large immigrant population, was closed for repairs. But no
work was done for weeks. In September, the building burned to the
ground. Many locals suspect arson by National Front militants.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Submarine, a cafe-bar that once drew a
multicultural crowd to its rap and reggae concerts, was shut down
by City Hall, which owns the building.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Fayard, the deputy mayor, brushes aside charges that his
party is conducting a witch hunt against all things foreign.
</P>
<P>
   He says the firings at City Hall were colorblind cost-cutting
and that the owners of the Submarine were dealing drugs and
fiddling their accounts. He argues passionately that street names
should reflect ``native'' culture and that state spending should be
aimed at French citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Fayard describes the birth-bonus program as ``a simple gesture
of solidarity to Vitrollais families.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a challenge by France's Movement Against Racism,
a lower court in Marseille ruled that the program violated a
constitutional principle guaranteeing equal treatment in the
apportioning of state aid. Before the ban was announced, 20
payments had been made to French families in Vitrolles. But Fayard
believes that the court in Marseille was wrong and that the
birth-bonus program is a good thing for France. Sitting in his
sunlit office in City Hall beside a French tricolor flag, the
deputy mayor neatly sums up National Front thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We face a clear choice. Do we want a French France inside a
European Europe, or do we want to continue down the current path to
a multicultural, multiracial world where countries and borders and
cultures have all dissolved into a gray nothingness?'' he asks,
pausing for breath before confirming his own preference.
</P>
<P>
   ``As patriotic defenders of the republic, we in the National
Front are proud to make Vitrolles more French.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most right-wing movements, the National Front puts a heavy
emphasis on security, which often means a crackdown on immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   City Hall has more than doubled the number of municipal police
officers in Vitrolles, and it is planning to add more. It has
installed surveillance cameras in immigrant neighborhoods and has
set up a rapid-reaction police unit with a round-the-clock
telephone hotline.
</P>
<P>
   Many locals are delighted by the beefed-up security and by the
falling crime figures trumpeted by City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Take Louise Marchand. She lives in a tidy bungalow near the
center of town. Not long ago, she was awakened by a ruckus outside
her bedroom window. Several North African teen-agers were horsing
around outside on their scooters. She called the hot line, and
police arrived at the scene within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These Arab kids are up all night in the streets, making noise
and getting up to mischief, and we used to have to live with it,''
she says, pruning the rosebush in her front garden. ``Now the
police sort them out right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Many young immigrants, on the other hand, accuse the expanded
police force of harassment and worse. Others complain that the
National Front ethos percolates through every public institution in
Vitrolles.
</P>
<P>
   After a recent strike by trash collectors, the backlog of
garbage lay festering in Les Pins long after it had been cleared
from other neighborhoods. Locals claim that City Hall sent a
cleanup crew only after youths set fire to the piles of stinking
rubbish.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that even the education system has not been immune.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Touzalines, an Algerian family, moved here from
rural Provence. Their eldest daughter, Sofia, who was born in
France, went to register at the local high school. Under French
law, the school was legally bound to take her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went in and told the principal's secretary that I wanted to
sign up. She was silent for a while and then looked up, stared at
me for a moment, and said: `You think you can go to school here
with a face like that?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't move. It was the first time anyone had ever said
something like that to me. Then she just went on with her work. A
few moments later, she looked up and said, `You're still here?'''
</P>
<P>
   Sofia's parents complained to the principal, who backed her
secretary. According to the family, which is now fighting for
redress in the courts, local authorities refused to investigate.
School officials decline to comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Sofia, now 19, and her younger brother commute
three hours every day to high schools in other towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the sort of thing that happens when you have the
National Front running a city,'' says Sofia. ``I just hope it
doesn't get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say it won't, arguing that winning Vitrolles was the
party's high watermark. But others fear that what is happening here
might be a sign of things to come, both in France and the rest of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everywhere in the EU, anti-immigrant parties register on
the political radar.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Party in Austria is the largest far-right political
movement in the EU. Led by the charismatic Jorg Haider, who calls
for an end to immigration and urges foreigners to go home, the
party won 28 percent of the vote in the last general election and
now rivals the country's two mainstream parties in the polls. At
rallies, Haider has told supporters, ``I am your patron saint
against further immigration.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls in France routinely give as much as 15 percent support to
the National Front, which runs three other towns besides Vitrolles.
In October, the party scored a publicity coup when Charles De
Gaulle, the namesake and grandson of the famous French leader,
agreed to run as a National Front candidate for the European
Parliament in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Germany's DVU party, which demonizes
immigrants, snatched 13 percent of the vote in a state election,
the highest score by the far right anywhere in the country since
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Small anti-immigrant parties hold toeholds in other EU nations,
such as Britain and the Netherlands. Last February, Ireland, where
immigration is a recent phenomenon, gave birth to its first
pressure group against refugees. But even though the anti-foreigner
sentiment seems to be hardening everywhere, xenophobic parties are
not riding an unbroken crescendo. Some are stable in the polls;
others have suffered recent setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   In September, France's National Front lost the by-election for a
parliamentary seat it had earlier won in Toulon. In the German
national elections held the same week, extremists fell short of the
5 percent of the vote needed to earn seats in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   One lesson from Vitrolles is that holding office can be a
poisoned chalice for the extreme right. Some National Front voters
here already criticize the party for failing to deliver economic
nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   Even from outside the citadels of power, though, Europe's
extreme right can shape public opinion by whipping up panic about
immigration and thus forcing mainstream rivals to toughen their
rhetoric and policies.
</P>
<P>
   Edouard Balladur, the former French prime minister, has caused a
furor by calling for a debate on ``national preference.'' This
year, mainstream conservatives in four French regions formed
regional governments in coalition with the National Front.
</P>
<P>
   To make their politics even more palatable, extreme
right-wingers are buffing up their image. Polished manners, college
degrees and sober suits are the order of the day. Any admiration
for Nazi Germany is kept under tight wraps.
</P>
<P>
   Among Europe's reconstructed xenophobes, Bruno Megret is a
rising star. Urbane and eloquent, with a degree from a U.S.
university under his belt, he is seeking to wrest control of the
National Front from its founder and current leader, the rough-hewn
Jean-Marie Le Pen. Last month, Megret announced his intention to
run in the mayoral elections in Marseille in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Megret already controls Vitrolles through his wife, who ran for
and won the mayor's job when an earlier campaign violation
disqualified him from the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone like Megret, who seems refined and reasonable, could
lead the National Front to greater political influence,'' says
Denis Babin, a Paris-based political analyst. ``People like him can
make extremist ideas seem more normal, more acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   That is certainly the hope of hard-core National Front
supporters in Vitrolles. Many here are already dreaming of bigger
things: winning a major city like Marseille, then a regional
government or two, then the presidency of France.
</P>
<P>
   Roche, the taxi driver, is sure that one day history will
remember this little town for sending a wake-up call to the rest of
France and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really wants all these immigrants in Europe, but here
in Vitrolles we are at least doing something about the problem,''
he says. ``If we keep on fighting for our country, one day our
grandchildren will thank us.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
