<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0805 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-SKINHEADS-ART-     12-09 1549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-SKINHEADS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ANGRY YOUNG MEN, XENOPHOBIA SPARKS VIOLENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend use) 
 
(Photo available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Honore) 
 
By CARL HONORE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAGDEBURG, Germany _ When immigrants in Europe talk about their
worst nightmare, someone like Dirk is usually the villain of the
piece.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in Magdeburg, a small city in eastern Germany,
Dirk is at the sharp edge of anti-foreigner sentiment. He is a
young neo-Nazi skinhead who says he cannot stand the sight of
non-Aryans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we come across one or two foreigners on their own, we beat
them up,'' Dirk, who refuses to give his surname, says casually.
``It's what they deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the European Union, violence against immigrants is on
the rise. The thriving skinhead movement, whose membership is
measured in the thousands, is often to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Neo-Nazi groups preach a virulent strain of racist nationalism.
Skinheads _ who often shave their scalps and wear black boots,
suspenders and bomber jackets _ are the movement's stormtroopers.
For a laugh, for the homeland, they turn the xenophobia of Fortress
Europe into violence on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   In eastern Germany, where neo-Nazism is strongest, skinheads
fire-bombed shelters for foreign asylum-seekers in the early 1990s
and more recently attacked dark-skinned pregnant women and
immigrant schoolchildren on field trips. Here in Magdeburg, a
hotbed of neo-Nazism, xenophobic crimes are up 19 percent over last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Similar violence is spreading elsewhere in Europe, particularly
in northern countries. Germany recorded nearly 400 attacks on
foreigners last year, up more than 10 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Danish skinheads prowl along their country's borders, beating up
nonwhites with fists and baseball bats. In the rough neighborhoods
of Britain, skinheads and other white thugs get their kicks from
beating up Asians in a practice known as ``Paki-bashing.''
</P>
<P>
   From Sweden to Britain to Spain, young people flock to concerts
where skinhead bands celebrate the Third Reich and vilify
immigrants, Jews and Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Germany may be the most visible example, but this is a
European phenomenon, and it's getting worse,'' says Rheiner Erb, a
researcher at the Center for Anti-Semitism Research in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Experts believe that the skinhead movement is partly fueled by
old-fashioned teen-age rebellion. Youngsters see it as a way to
shock their elders, and they like the camaraderie that comes from
sharing music, clubs and a uniform.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeal may run much deeper than that.
</P>
<P>
   Social workers say that most skinheads are angry young men from
the burgeoning underclass. The movement's nationalism gives them an
identity, while its racism allows them to blame immigrants for
their blighted lives.
</P>
<P>
   Here in eastern Germany, where disillusionment with capitalism
is rife and where foreign faces are a novelty, the crude
certainties of neo-Nazism strike a loud chord. In Magdeburg, being
an immigrant-hating skinhead is almost fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   Although he claims to be drifting from the movement and no
longer shaves all the hair from his head, Dirk, 24, remains an
archetypal ``skin.''
</P>
<P>
   He left school at 14 and has never had a job. He lives in a
grubby apartment in a housing project near the center of Magdeburg.
Paint is peeling off the walls and window frames. Half-eaten bowls
of spaghetti lie on the sofa.
</P>
<P>
   One corner of the living room is given over to a little shrine.
Finely painted war planes _ some German, some foreign _ hang from
the ceiling. Submarines topped with swastika flags sit on a shelf
by the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unification (of Germany) has been very bad for us,'' says
Dirk, blowing dust off a little U-boat. ``Nowadays, the dirty
foreigners get everything, and we get nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Magdeburg, the capital of Saxony-Anhalt, the poorest state in
Germany, is ringed by housing projects left over from the communist
era. Row upon row of concrete apartment blocks rise like barracks
from the scrub land. Anti-immigrant graffiti is painted on walls
and bus shelters. Skinheads and other youths loiter in the bars and
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Here, as in other neo-Nazi enclaves across Western Europe,
foreigners can feel the hot breath of racial hatred on their necks.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants, who make up only 2 percent of Magdeburg's
population, say they live under a reign of terror. Most avoid
public transport and seldom venture out at night. Banana skins and
dog feces are pushed into their mailboxes. Skinheads spit on them,
shout abuse or worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just don't want to behave like Germans,'' Wolfgang, one
of Dirk's skinhead friends, says of the immigrants. ``We have to
show them who is boss here.''
</P>
<P>
   Some immigrants refuse to be hounded out. They dismiss the
skinheads as confused youngsters who rail against ``foreign
garbage,'' even as they wolf down Turkish kebabs and chicken chow
mein.
</P>
<P>
   Erdal Sahbhaz sells ethnic fast food on the main shopping square
in Neu-Olvenstedt, a housing project in northern Magdeburg. A
Turkish immigrant, he seems unfazed by the swastika scratched into
the side of his stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``These skinheads look scary, and they're nasty when they're
drunk,'' he says, sunning himself on a plastic deck chair. ``But at
the end of the day, they're just kids who don't know any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Other immigrants, though, are throwing in the towel. Danny
Mbowa, a young Nigerian who came to Magdeburg a year ago, is
planning to move, perhaps to Paris or London.
</P>
<P>
   ``This skinhead thing is getting really bad,'' he says. ``Last
week, three of them chased me through a park in broad daylight.''
</P>
<P>
   Police warn that the European skinhead movement is growing more
organized.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, the Internet hums with sites and chat boards where the
continent's neo-Nazis swap ideas and invitations to events. Web
page after Web page calls for ``liberated zones'' that are free of
foreigners. There are links with the Ku Klux Klan and white
supremacist movements in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Pan-European cooperation is not confined to cyberspace, however.
German neo-Nazis print their literature in Belgium and other EU
countries. Skinhead bands tour the continent and distribute their
albums and videos through established music labels in Sweden,
Britain and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   Concerts seem to be a central bonding ritual for skinheads. On
stages festooned with swastikas, heavy-metal punk bands with names
like Fortress and Stormtrooper rail against ``foreign scum.''
</P>
<P>
   After the concerts, many fans, giving straight-arm salutes and
shouting ``White Power'' and ``Sieg Heil'' (``Hail Victory'') spill
out into the streets in a froth of xenophobic rage.
</P>
<P>
   Heiko Schmengler used to play bass guitar in one of Germany's
top skinhead bands. He still holds dear much of the neo-Nazi creed.
The sports bar he runs in Neu Olvenstedt is decked out with German
flags.
</P>
<P>
   But Schmengler, who now has a 5-year-old son named Matthew,
thinks the violence is in danger of getting out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young skinheads of today don't discuss or think about what
they stand for like we used to. They just put on the outfit and
start attacking people,'' he says, cradling Matthew on his knee.
``And it's shocking how many weapons you see nowadays.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, police found a cache of dynamite in what was
believed to be a small neo-Nazi bomb-making factory near Jena, an
east German town. Raids elsewhere in eastern Germany have turned up
submachine guns, pistols and silencers. Police warn that baseball
bats are giving way to knives as the preferred weapon of the
street. Some fear the neo-Nazis may soon turn to terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Germany is leading efforts to clamp down. Brandenburg, the state
that surrounds Berlin, has set up an anti-neo-Nazi commando unit
equipped with helicopters, special weaponry and high-speed cars. In
its first weeks, its agents made two dozen arrests.
</P>
<P>
   To monitor racism and xenophobic incidents throughout Western
Europe, the EU is creating a special ``observatory'' in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Yet social workers everywhere sound a note of caution: Better
monitoring and tougher policing will achieve nothing, they warn, if
the underlying social and economic malaise is left to fester.
</P>
<P>
   Helmut Stern, a former chairman of the Berlin Philharmonic
Orchestra, is not very sanguine. A Jewish refugee who fled the
original Nazis during World War II, he recently visited a skinhead
club as part of a social outreach program.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I be optimistic?'' asks the genial 70-year-old. ``Some
of these kids are beyond redemption, and there is not much hope for
the rest unless unemployment falls dramatically, which seems
unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, extreme right-wing politicians are helping to
swell the skinhead ranks by fanning the flames of xenophobia with
pamphlets and speeches.
</P>
<P>
   In the housing projects of Magdeburg, the mood is tense. Hanging
around in the afternoon drinking beer, Dirk and his skinhead
friends look like a brawl waiting to happen. There is an ominous
rumble beneath their banter.
</P>
<P>
   Says Dirk, ``If our politicians don't do something about the
foreigners, we might have to do it for them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
