</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-FOREIGNERS-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BACKLASH: IMMIGRANTS FACE A WORLD OF XENOPHOBIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend use) 
 
(Third of four-part series, with EUROPE-SKINHEADS and
EUROPE-WELCOME) 
 
(Photos available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Honore) 
 
By CARL HONORE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VITROLLES, France _ Like many natives of this small, quiet town
in the deep south of France, Lucien Roche thinks the time has come
to put immigrants in their place.
</P>
<P>
   The burly, blue-eyed taxi driver fears that the French way of
life _ and even the national gene pool _ is under threat from
people with dark skins and foreign backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't want France to be transformed into an African or a
Muslim republic, we have to fight back,'' says Roche, chewing on a
baguette during his lunch break in the center of Vitrolles. ``The
moment has come to stand up for our own people.''
</P>
<P>
   Last January, Roche cheered when Vitrolles City Hall began
paying selected couples $800 for each baby they produced.
</P>
<P>
   Although any resident with a European Union passport was
technically eligible for the controversial program, which now is on
hold because of a lawsuit, most people here assumed that the real
aim was to spur French whites to go forth and multiply.
</P>
<P>
   Vitrolles is run by the National Front, an extreme right-wing
party that wants to rid France of foreigners. The poster
advertising the birth bonuses showed a smiling baby with blond hair
and blue eyes beneath the words: ``For French families.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people in Vitrolles and across Europe decry the birth
bonuses as a throwback to the Nazi obsession with Aryan breeding
and as a crude bid to freeze immigrants out of French society. But
many others welcome any move to tip the scales in favor of native
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``These immigrants have so many children that we are being
swamped,'' insists Roche, a middle-aged father of two.
</P>
<P>
   Though the birth bonuses were unique to Vitrolles, the
anti-foreigner sentiment behind them echoes with mounting force
across France and the European Union, a political and economic
alliance of 15 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``These immigrants have so many children that we are being
swamped,'' insists Roche, a middle-aged father of two.
</P>
<P>
   Though the birth bonuses were unique to Vitrolles, the
anti-foreigner sentiment behind them echoes with mounting force
across France and the rest of the European Union, a political and
economic alliance of 15 states.
</P>
<P>
   EU countries are trying to seal their borders against the river
of economic and political refugees flowing here from Africa, Asia,
the former Soviet bloc and even Latin America. Inside what
observers call Fortress Europe, the welcome mat has been rolled up
and the hosts are turning nasty.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere from Sweden to France to Spain, people of foreign
descent are accused of polluting local cultures, committing crimes,
stealing jobs and freeloading on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by the mood elsewhere in Europe and eager to restart
its birth-bonus payments, Vitrolles City Hall is now appealing a
lower-court ruling that deemed them unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``All over Europe, public opinion has turned against us,'' says
Said Charchira, president of the European Union Migrants Forum, an
advocacy group. ``We are no longer seen as human beings but as an
infection that must be cured.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in Europe vilifies immigrants. But last year, a
poll conducted by the EU found that one-third of the union's
citizens considered themselves ``very racist'' or ``quite racist.''
The same study found that nearly half believe there are too many
foreigners in their countries.
</P>
<P>
   Many Europeans distrust plans to expand the EU alliance to
include countries in Eastern Europe, fearing a westward flood of
migrants from new members such as Poland and the Czech Republic.
Earlier this year, groups opposed to EU enlargement covered town
centers in Denmark with posters bearing the slogan: ``Say Welcome
To 40 Million Poles.''
</P>
<P>
   In much of the EU, media coverage of immigration has taken on a
disapproving, sometimes hysterical tone.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, for instance, the Wexford People, a provincial
newspaper in Ireland, ran a breathless front-page editorial
accusing refugees from Eastern Europe of running through the
streets waving welfare checks, terrorizing old women and trying to
seduce and impregnate Irish girls.
</P>
<P>
   The xenophobia is not confined to the written or spoken word.
Authorities say violence against nonwhites is on the rise
throughout the continent, even in areas, such as Scandinavia, that
are famed for gentle liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   Based on polls, interviews and police statistics, Erb Rheiner, a
researcher at the Center for Anti-Semitism Studies in Berlin,
figures that 10 percent to 15 percent of young men in northern
European countries, and almost as many again in the south, condone
the use of violence against foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Skinheads and other right-wing thugs, who warn that Europe is
heading for an all-out ``race war,'' carry out many attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In much of the EU, extremist parties like the National Front are
tapping into the xenophobia and fueling it. Vitrolles, which lies
10 miles north of Marseille, is on the cutting edge of the
anti-immigrant backlash.
</P>
<P>
   Scratch the ordinary small-town veneer here, and racist anger
oozes to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled at the foot of a rocky ridge, Vitrolles is a small
industrial town built largely after the 1960s. Factories on the
outskirts of town stand idle, and 18 percent of the population is
jobless. As many as one-tenth of the 40,000 inhabitants are of
non-European descent, with most tracing their roots to Morocco,
Algeria and Tunisia but also to sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Drifting among the concrete shopping arcades in the center of
town, his hands deep in his pockets, Marcel Gagnon, an unemployed
young white man, accuses the dark-skinned people of spoiling
Vitrolles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't belong in Europe. They're different from us,'' he
says, scowling. ``Look at their faces, at the way they dress and
behave. They don't want to adapt. They just want to suck us dry.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s and early 1970s, immigrants were welcomed with open
arms into Europe's booming economies. But years of low economic
growth turned the smiles to bile. With the global economic crisis
threatening to bite deeper, nearly 17 million EU citizens, or 10
percent of the labor force, are jobless. In France, the
unemployment rate stands at 11.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It matters little that immigrants often do the work _ from
domestic cleaning to fruit-picking _ that most Europeans no longer
want. With fewer jobs to go around, with welfare systems bursting
at the seams and with globalization and EU integration chipping
away at traditional identities, many Europeans are edgy and worried
and looking for scapegoats. Anyone who seems like an ``outsider,''
who does not fit the old image of what it means to be French or
German or Dutch, is fair game.
</P>
<P>
   Parties like the National Front in France, the Freedom Party in
Austria and Vlaams Blok in Belgium offer simple solutions. They
want to stop all immigration, to send millions of immigrants home
and to give ``native'' citizens priority in everything from jobs to
housing to social spending.
</P>
<P>
   In France, where the National Front has been in politics since
1972, the policy of putting ``our people first'' even has a name _
``national preference.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with their strident nationalism, most extreme right
parties are also opposed to European integration.
</P>
<P>
   The slogans of the far right resonate especially with young
blue-collar men, who are more likely to compete with immigrants for
jobs. But analysts say other parts of the electorate are also
warming to the message.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1997, the National Front won the municipal elections
in Vitrolles with more than half the vote. With some success, the
party is using the town as a testing ground for its philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters of different races still hang out together in the
playgrounds and in the town center, but the us-vs.-them feeling has
sharpened.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more tension and distrust around,'' says a black
Ivory Coast immigrant who gave his name only as Laurent. ``If you
are on the bus or waiting to pay at the supermarket checkout, you
never know if the person beside you voted National Front.''
</P>
<P>
   Corine Ferrer, a youth worker of French descent, discerns a new
ethnic discord. ``You never used to hear kids saying, `You're
white,' or `You're black,' but now it comes out all the time,'' she
says. ``The Front is driving a wedge between ethnic groups, which
is very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the measures taken by the party in Vitrolles are
symbolic. The historic flag of Provence, the local region, has
replaced the European Union flag that once hung from City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen street names have been Gallicized. In front of
City Hall, the square once called Place Nelson Mandela is now Place
de Provence.
</P>
<P>
   Some Vitrollais snicker or shrug at the changes, but critics
warn that symbols put ideas into people's heads and give them the
courage to say what was once unsayable.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Legrand, an unemployed painter, certainly takes heart
from the name changes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(More) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
