<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-WELCOME-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFYING CONVENTIONAL WISDOM, ITALIAN TOWN OPENS ITS ARMS TO
IMMIGRANTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Honore) 
 
By CARL HONORE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BADOLATO, Italy _ Perched on a rugged hilltop at the edge of the
Ionian Sea, Badolato seems to be dozing in a southern Italian time
warp.
</P>
<P>
   Its medieval houses and churches are knotted together in a
tangle of winding, narrow alleyways. Old men in cloth caps sit all
day long on the edge of the main square, moving only to follow the
shade. The dry hills are terraced with ancient farms.
</P>
<P>
   But Badolato is not all sleepy inertia. This small town is a
rare oasis of hospitality and hope for immigrants seeking a new
life inside Fortress Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, when a boat carrying 836 refugees, most of
them Kurds from Turkey and Iraq, washed up on the beach down below,
the town made headlines across the continent. Instead of slamming
their doors and calling in the police, as most other Europeans
might do nowadays, the locals rolled out the welcome mat.
</P>
<P>
   Abandoned houses were thrown open to the refugees. Local
restaurants and grocers delivered boxes of food to their doorsteps.
Neighbors donated clothing, washing machines and television sets as
well as staples found in the cupboards of every Italian kitchen:
crusty bread, bottles of wine and olive oil, tomatoes, garlic and
pasta. The newcomers were given Italian lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our response came from inside the heart,'' says Gerardo
Mannello, the mayor of Badolato. ``That we are such a big media
story shows how far the rest of Europe has forgotten basic human
values.''
</P>
<P>
   But the soft-spoken mayor is the first to admit that altruism is
only part of the equation. Rolling out the red carpet to the
refugees was also a bold stroke of civic self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than the rest of Europe, where low birthrates and
aging populations are causing alarm, Badolato is crying out for
demographic renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, poverty has fueled an exodus of young people,
causing the town's population to tumble from nearly 7,000 in the
1950s to just over 600 today.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 houses stand abandoned. Only two of the dozen
medieval churches are open. Most Badolatans are over 50, and, last
year, the junior high school closed for lack of pupils.
</P>
<P>
   Mannello saw the refugees as a catalyst to rouse the town from
its deathbed slumber. It has proved to be a clever gamble.
</P>
<P>
   By embracing the newcomers, Badolato has won federal funds that
are helping refurbish dilapidated houses and the town square. And
the refugees have injected a new elan into local life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a model for mayors all over Europe,'' says Mannello.
``The humanitarian machine and the economic machine linked
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Badolato could never be big enough for all 836 of the refugees,
so most have moved on since gaining their residency papers, mainly
to EU countries farther north.
</P>
<P>
   But for the 45 Kurds still living here, this town is now home, a
small corner of Fortress Europe where dark skin and a foreign
accent are not a one-way ticket to pariah status.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurds came here after fleeing their strife-torn homeland in
eastern Turkey and northern Iraq. Today, throughout Badolato,
everyday scenes of Italo-Kurdish harmony look like clips from a
promotional video.
</P>
<P>
   Il Castello, the town's only pizzeria, nestles in a corner of
the main square. Young Kurds and Italians hang out together in the
shade of the restaurant terrace, sipping cold drinks, talking about
soccer and girls, laughing over dirty words in their respective
languages.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Serri, a Turkish Kurd, has been working at Il Castello since
July. His command of the language is still shaky, but he answers
the phone in Italian with a cheerful ``hello'' and takes orders
from customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have really opened their arms to us,'' he says,
hoisting a large mushroom pizza in the air. ``They did not turn us
away when we needed help.''
</P>
<P>
   Mimmo Audino, the gregarious owner of Il Castello, credits the
Kurds with putting Badolato on the map.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of fun together socially, but they've also been
good for business,'' he says. ``We get customers from 200 km away,
which never used to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   When Audino moved his pizzeria onto the square in July, he
allowed his family-owned former locale, tucked away down a curling
staircase off the main thoroughfare, to be turned into the first
Kurdish restaurant in southern Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Set up with money from the town coffers, the Ararat, named after
the boat that brought the Kurds to these shores, is a monument to
cultural fusion.
</P>
<P>
   Knee-high tables hug the terracotta floor. Colorful woven
carpets hang from the white walls. Diners wash down Kurdish food
with Ciro, the local wine. One page of the menu is devoted to
pizzas with Kurdish toppings, such as yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Cayundar helps run the busy Ararat. In August, he became the
second Kurd in Badolato to net an Italian girlfriend. He has never
felt more welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear of racism and skinheads in Europe, but I've never
felt any rejection in Badolato,'' he says. ``They have given us a
great chance to make a home here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten Kurdish children are now studying alongside their Italian
peers in the local school. Fifteen Kurds already have full-time
jobs _ in the town hall, on nearby farms, with local butchers and
as live-in maids. There are plans to set up an arts and crafts shop
and a small textile plant, both of which would employ a mix of
Italians and Kurds.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the newcomers are laying down even deeper roots. One
Kurd has started a five-year course in medicine at the University
of Catanzaro, 35 miles up the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Two Kurdish babies have been born in Badolato, the first births
registered here in years. Both children were christened with
suitably Italian names: Angela and Laura.
</P>
<P>
   Badolato is also hoping to parlay its philanthropy into tourist
lira.
</P>
<P>
   The town opened its first-ever tourism office in July and is now
promoting itself as a multicultural getaway. Bookings are streaming
in, mostly from northern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Caterina Carnuccio, whose family has for decades run the local
newspaper-tobacco shop, is delighted by the Kurds' arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``This town was dead, and now things are picking up again,''
says the spry 61-year-old. ``I feel very affectionate toward the
Kurds, and they call me mamma.''
</P>
<P>
   The experiment in Badolato is not to everyone's liking, though.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Italy's refusal to turn away the Kurdish boat
people was harshly denounced in Germany and the Netherlands, both
magnets for illegal immigrants. Mannello, the mayor, has received
threats through the mail and by phone.
</P>
<P>
   A few locals resent the changes here, and some people in nearby
towns accuse Badolato of exploiting the Kurds to extract money from
Rome. Though several Italian mayors have expressed interest in the
way Badolato is handling its refugees, none has yet followed
Mannello's example.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the first euphoria has died down, even Badolatans are
having to come to terms with the fact that a warm welcome is only
the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Integrating the newcomers into the labor force is turning out to
be trickier than expected. Cheated by employers in neighboring
towns or unwilling to take low-paid work, a few Kurds have turned
down job offers, to the annoyance of locals. And even if Badolato
booms, it will always be a small town with limited career
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Sekfan Gunel, a Kurdish immigrant, lives with his wife and
daughter in one of the formerly abandoned houses just off the main
square. After a lunch of tomato and onion salad, he slips out onto
the narrow balcony to drink a cup of strong coffee.
</P>
<P>
   The view would make a tourist's heart sing: red clay rooftops,
stone churches, terraced farms, deep blue sea. Donated clothes flap
on the washing line just above Gunel's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are warm here, and I would like to stay, but if I can't
find good work, then I don't know. Maybe I will have to leave,'' he
says, staring down into his coffee. ``That would be sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their eventual fate, though, the Kurdish newcomers will
always have a soft spot for Badolato. By swimming against the tide
of European opinion, this tiny, picturesque town has shown that, at
least in southern Italy, the art of the warm welcome is alive and
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never forget this reception,'' says a Kurdish woman who
identifies herself only as Dina. ``We'll always remember these kind
Italians who opened their hearts to us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
