<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0809 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-ACCEPTANCE-ART     12-09 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-ACCEPTANCE-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRANTS FACE INGRAINED BIAS AS THEY STRUGGLE FOR ACCEPTANCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend use) 
 
(Last of four-part series, with EUROPE-IDENTITY and
EUROPE-SUCCESS) 
 
(Photos available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Honore) 
 
By CARL HONORE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANTWERP, Belgium _ In this small country famous for chocolates
and diamonds, life is bittersweet for Dennis Amoah.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old is a professional soccer player on a continent
that worships the sport. He lives in a modern apartment with his
sweet, loving wife. He has many friends.
</P>
<P>
   But Amoah also bears a heavy cross on his athletic shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Being a black immigrant from Ghana, he says, makes him a target
for racial hatred in many walks of life.
</P>
<P>
   When Amoah hits the road with his lower-division soccer team,
opposing fans wave bananas at him, call him a ``black monkey'' and
tell him to go back to the jungle where he belongs, he says. Rival
players sometimes taunt him with racist slurs, too. He once tried
to scramble into the stands to silence a foul-mouthed fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to lose my temper, but now it just hurts. It makes you
feel ashamed of what you are,'' says &QL; 
Amoah, the muscles tightening on his smooth face. ``It is not a
good thing for your heart and mind.''
</P>
<P>
   His plight is part of a larger picture. In a Western Europe
proud of its liberal traditions, many immigrants _ particularly
those with dark skins _ say they find it hard to be accepted as
equals and to get ahead in daily life.
</P>
<P>
   Though only a minority suffers racist violence, most grapple
with a culture of discrimination that sends a similar message: You
are not one of us. You are not wanted here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the Berlin Wall has fallen, another wall has been
built within people's minds,'' says Said Charchira, president of
the European Union Migrants Forum, an advocacy group. ``That wall
is made of racism and xenophobia.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic minorities in Europe generally enjoy fewer legal
protections than their counterparts in the United States. But even
where strong anti-discrimination laws do exist, such as here in
Belgium, victims often fail to make them work in practice or to win
much sympathy from the native population.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the U.S., people discriminate quietly. But in Europe, it's
out in the open. It's in your face,'' says Tony Lamptey, an
African-American now living in Antwerp.
</P>
<P>
   Lamptey sometimes feels he has stepped through the looking
glass. Born in Illinois, he worked as a salesman in Louisiana and
Georgia before earning an MBA. In 1992, eager for a change of
scenery, he moved to Antwerp, where he now runs a small African
grocery shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Americans think racism doesn't exist in Europe,'' he
says, ``but people get away with things here they wouldn't even
dream of trying in the States.''
</P>
<P>
   No country in the 15-nation European Union is colorblind.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, where large-scale immigration started earlier than
in the rest of Europe and where minority rights are widely viewed
as more evolved, racial discrimination may be weaker or more
discreet, but it still thrives.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Antwerp, a Dutch-speaking port city where unemployment
is rife and politics lean toward the extreme right, every type of
discrimination is in plain view.
</P>
<P>
   Amoah says he has seen it all. Six years after moving from Ghana
to take up an offer to play professional soccer, he has a full
residency permit and a white Belgian wife. Yet he still feels like
an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Across the EU, non-whites complain of insults in the streets and
withering looks in shops. Many are turned away from restaurants,
bars and nightclubs, either with a racist slight or with a hollow,
``Sorry, we're full.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Amoah and three black friends _ all well-dressed
and sober _ went to a popular discotheque on the outskirts of
Antwerp. The doorman demanded to see their passports, then told
them to scram, Amoah recalls. Minutes later, several white Belgians
were let in with no questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember the music they were playing in the club that
night,'' says Amoah, smiling wryly. ``It was a song called `Don't
Hate Me' by Haddaway, a black singer from Trinidad.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet getting through the proverbial front door is sometimes a
pale victory. Just ask Paul Berko, a young Nigerian immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent car trip from Antwerp to Paris, he and a black
friend stopped in a small Belgian town to eat lunch at a
restaurant. After they paid the bill, the waitress cleared their
table and then made a great show of dumping all the plates and
cutlery into the garbage can, Berko says.
</P>
<P>
   When Berko asked her why, the waitress answered that if she did
not throw everything away, nobody would eat in the restaurant
again, he says.
</P>
<P>
   In Antwerp, which lies just 30 miles north of the European Union
headquarters in Brussels, immigrants can never entirely forget
their outsider status.
</P>
<P>
   De Coninc Square in the city's center is a multicultural haven.
A boarded-up building is covered with bright murals, and the
cobbled streets are lined with ethnic bars, eateries and
nightclubs, many with cheerful names like Tropical Dance. Immigrant
men and women linger on the streetcorners, laughing and chatting in
a babble of languages. Reggae music drifts through the air.
</P>
<P>
   But even here, on one side street, a bar called Non-Stop runs an
informal ``whites-only'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   Lamptey, the African-American grocer whose shop lies around the
corner, is not surprised that such flagrant racism is allowed to
exist inside an immigrant neighborhood. Even though the law is on
their side, non-whites in Belgium lack the confidence to fight
back, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the U.S., black people don't fear white people, and they'll
sue if they think their rights are being trampled,'' he says,
smoothing the sleeves of his purple African robe. ``But black
people have not been here long enough to feel Belgian, and they're
scared of being sent home if they kick up a fuss.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamptey stops speaking for a moment to serve a couple of
customers. A tall Nigerian woman buys a handful of cassava and a
bag of okra. A young man from Ghana picks up some yams and a bottle
of shampoo. Lamptey then turns back to finish his discourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't think they'll get anywhere trying to sue a
Belgian for discrimination,'' he says. ``You just keep your head
down and carry on with your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the European Union, authorities concede that public
institutions are often tainted by racism.
</P>
<P>
   Ask immigrants around the continent to name their bugbears, and
the police will figure on almost every list.
</P>
<P>
   Critics accuse law enforcement officials at all levels,
including judges and prosecutors, of racial bias.
</P>
<P>
   Even supposedly multicultural Britain is not above reproach. In
October, the police chief in Manchester admitted that his force was
infected with an ``institutionalized racism'' that reflected
mainstream British society.
</P>
<P>
   At border checkpoints around the EU, dark-skinned Europeans
complain of being singled out for tough grilling by customs
officials, while their white compatriots sail by with a nod and a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   On streets inside the EU, police hunting for illegal immigrants
or criminals are far more likely to stop and search non-whites,
studies show. Amoah says he is regularly asked by the police to
show his ID.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you ever feel at home somewhere when they are always
forcing you to prove that you have the right to walk down the
street?'' he asks, fiddling with the strap on his mobile phone.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the harassment blurs into brutality or worse, critics
say. Four years ago, a Ghanaian immigrant was hauled into an
Antwerp police station when neighbors complained that his stereo
was playing too loudly. While in custody, the 34-year-old slipped
into a coma and died.
</P>
<P>
   Police claim he was on crack cocaine and that their efforts to
control his epileptic seizures resulted in the coma. Though no one
has ever been charged with his death, fellow Africans say that his
body bore the marks of severe beatings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
``You cannot trust the police here,'' says Amoah. ``They are often
the worst racists of all.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his troubles with native Europeans, though, Amoah was
lucky to land in Europe with a job. He was brought here by a
professional soccer team and now plays for a club in Nijlen, a
small town 15 miles east of Antwerp. Like many successful non-white
players, Amoah _ a high-scoring forward _ is popular with fans of
his own team.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the glamorous world of soccer, however, most immigrants
in Europe struggle to get a foot on the economic ladder and often
languish in unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   European labor practices do not help. Many EU countries have
rigid laws that make it hard for anyone _ especially immigrants _
to break into the mainstream economy.
</P>
<P>
   An enterprising Chinese or Pakistani family can eke out a living
running an all-night grocery in Britain, but not in Germany, where
laws prevent any shop opening after 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Some laws conspire directly against immigrants. In the
Netherlands, regulations make it virtually impossible for a
foreign-born resident to drive a taxi, that favorite first job of
many ambitious newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   In many EU countries, people who have applied for refugee status
are not allowed to work at all while their applications are under
review.
</P>
<P>
   In Antwerp, as in the rest of Europe, job hunting with the wrong
skin color or an exotic surname can be tricky. Recent research by
the Geneva-based International Labor Organization suggests that, in
many European countries, one in three immigrant job applicants
suffers discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ILO study, employers claim positions are filled
when they aren't or they admit openly that ``foreign-looking''
staff might put off customers. Many simply gravitate unwittingly to
candidates with white faces and traditional European names.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they do get hired, immigrants often say they are
treated poorly in the workplace. The racist chants aimed at Amoah
and millionaire soccer stars in the stadiums of Europe echo the
drudgery thrust on immigrants further down the economic scale.
</P>
<P>
   Boldichat Abdeldajid came to Antwerp in 1988 from Morocco. At
the metallurgical factory where he now works on the outskirts of
town, only foreigners are asked to handle the scalding liquid
metal, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a white guy joins, he goes straight to another part of the
factory,`` says Abdeldajid, a big, burly man with a timid smile.
``It's the blacks and the Moroccans who get stuck with the dirty,
dangerous work.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same spirit, say researchers, European landlords and real
estate agents steer immigrants away from ``white'' neighborhoods,
and ``white'' schools turn away immigrant children.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Abdeldajid and his wife tried to enroll their
children in a school down the road from their small apartment in
Antwerp. The principal told them he had already accepted ``too many
immigrants.'' When they protested, he told them to go back to
Morocco, Abdeldajid says. Their children now walk to classes two
miles from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when you really feel like an immigrant, an outsider,''
says Abdeldajid, cracking the knuckles on his meaty fingers. ``We
hear this word `integration,' but how are we supposed to integrate
if Europeans won't let us?''
</P>
<P>
   Education researchers warn that immigrant children are
underperforming in European schools. Some blame economic-class
divisions and the tendency to shunt such children into poor
schools; others blame the lower expectations of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Take Nancy Palaba, a black woman who came to Antwerp from Ghana
to work as a maid 11 years ago. After a long shift recently, she
returned to her tiny apartment to find her 12-year-old son weeping
on the sofa. Ken, a math whiz, had just scored 93 percent on an
exam. A substitute teacher, who knew nothing of his school record,
had accused him of cheating in front of the whole class.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Africa we only knew the word `racism,''' says Palaba.
``Europe has taught us what it means.''
</P>
<P>
   Young immigrants also are hard-pressed to find role models.
Non-whites may thrive in sports and the music industry but, in most
European countries, they are sparsely represented at the top of
politics, business and such professions as law and banking. Only
one of France's 36,560 towns and villages has a dark-skinned mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the United Kingdom and the Netherlands, there are few
dark faces in the mainstream media. When immigrants do crop up in
the European press, it is often in crime reports, and their
ethnicity is usually flagged: Moroccan drug dealer, Nigerian
rapist, Vietnamese burglar.
</P>
<P>
   The dearth of role models, coupled with the racism, is
especially galling for second-, third- and fourth-generation
immigrants, who were born in Europe and speak the local languages
yet still feel like second-class citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In the rundown suburbs that ring the major cities of France, the
children of Arab immigrants seem to be locked into a permanent
underclass. Crime and violence are sometimes the only outlets for
their frustration. Some neighborhoods are virtual no-go zones for
the French police.
</P>
<P>
   Dany Fraitas Santos knows how those Arab youths feel, even
though he stays on the right side of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the Cape Verde Islands, which lie off the west coast of
Africa, the 27-year-old was brought up in Antwerp. He now works for
an insurance company in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak perfect Dutch, and I even speak it with an Antwerp
accent, so I have no problems on the phone,'' he says. ``But as
soon as people see my face, I am instantly something foreign to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Santos dreams of one day leaving behind the discrimination of
Europe for a fresh start back in Cape Verde.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not every native European is an unreconstructed racist.
</P>
<P>
   Many try hard to be colorblind and to welcome immigrants as
equals. And though it seems like a paradox, interethnic socializing
is fairly common in some EU countries.
</P>
<P>
   American visitors to Britain, where the rate of interracial
marriage is 10 times higher than in the United States, often remark
that relations between blacks and whites seem less tense there than
in the States.
</P>
<P>
   Interethnic relationships rankle many Europeans, but others take
them in stride. Amoah, for instance, is on good terms with his
wife's white friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   Taking heart from the social mixing, European politicians are
moving to tackle discrimination. After declaring 1997 its official
Year Against Racism, the EU is setting up a special ``observatory''
in Vienna to monitor and make suggestions on how to combat racism.
</P>
<P>
   Other levels of government are taking steps of their own. Last
summer, Antwerp's City Council hired its first two ``integration
officers,'' who will handle discrimination complaints and work to
promote racial harmony. The police force has launched a drive to
recruit ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Following the British example, Belgian soccer authorities
recently announced a campaign to stamp out racist slurs in the
professional leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But new rules and commissions and inquiries seldom win rapturous
applause from immigrants, who are tired of windy rhetoric that
fails to deliver hard results.
</P>
<P>
   Like other black soccer players in Belgium, Amoah would love to
see his sport purged of racism. But nothing has changed so far, and
he is not holding his breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a black man, you have to fight harder for everything in
Europe, and you have to put up with a lot of garbage,'' he says.
``That is not going to change overnight.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
