<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-GIFTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRONIC GIFTS ARE HOT ITEMS AT THE NORTH POLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Imagine Santa with a cell phone for the sleigh, a
Palm Pilot to store his naughty-and-nice list, and, then, for some
relaxing television viewing after his big trip, a new satellite
dish at the Pole.
</P>
<P>
   It's the perfect high-tech Christmas _ no ho, ho, ho.
</P>
<P>
   Computers and electronic items are now a staple of the Christmas
retailing season and are widely available from sources ranging from
traditional retail stores to television channels and Internet
vendors. In fact, the majority of American households will buy at
least one electronic item for the season, according to the Consumer
Electronics Manufacturers Association, a trade group based in
Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The most highly desired item is a desktop computer, identified
by 11 percent of 1,000 people surveyed in September, the group
said.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Joe Pasquini wants. Of course, as president of the
Capital District Computer Enthusiasts Club in Albany, he already
has a computer. But he'd like a faster model for around $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time. As far as PCs are concerned, it's ancient: 3 years
old,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pasquini family has plenty of company, early sales reports
indicate. Sellers say they are seeing both novice buyers selecting
their first computer, and experienced users upgrading their
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The iMAC, Apple Computer Inc.'s hip product, is selling well at
$1,300 and is attracting buyers to other Apple products, said Jason
Pierce, sales manager at Castle Computers in Latham, N.Y. The other
models include a desktop entry, PowerMac, and the portable
PowerBook.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet and the spread of e-mail are stimulating computer
purchases, Pierce said. Older buyers, including grandparents, are
now evaluating computers because they want to send e-mail to
children and grandchildren, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other computer-distribution channels are also reporting brisk
sales. QVC, the shopping channel, sold more than 18,000 specially
designed IBM-compatible systems on Sunday alone, said Dennis
D'Angelo, director of merchandising for electronics. Many QVC
buyers enjoy the chit-chat between television hosts and callers,
and like the extended demonstrations of product features, he said.
</P>
<P>
   They find buying in that environment less intimidating than
computer superstores or office-supply chains, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cyberian Outpost Inc., a young Internet retailer
based in Kent, Conn., surpassed $1 million in orders on Nov. 30,
said a company spokesman. Even people who are buying their first
computer for the home are making purchases over the Internet, he
said: They just buy from work.
</P>
<P>
   This year's novice buyers may just be starting down the path of
a lifetime of computer-related purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always something to buy,'' Pasquini said.
</P>
<P>
   If it's not a whole new and better system you want, then it
could be an accessory he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many computer owners now want to spend a few hundred dollars on
a digital camera so they can put photos into their computer systems
and e-mail them to friends and family. Cameras range from around
$200 to $1,000 in computer stores.
</P>
<P>
   The market is also supplying scanners for less than $100 to take
images into the computer; portable drives for extra storage are in
the same price range.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Pilots, the hand-held devices that allow people to store
schedules and contact names and phone numbers, are selling for
around $300.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular phone providers are now often providing the handsets
for free as long as people commit to a calling plan.
</P>
<P>
   New stereo receivers with Dolby sound are selling for around
$400, and digital versatile disk players for movies and music range
between $400 and $800.
</P>
<P>
   If the high-tech world seems too confusing, don't seem rushed.
You have plenty of time. You might be able to wait until the new
year to get a computer, Pasquini said, and get an even better
price.
</P>
</TEXT>
