<HEADER>
A0817 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-IDENTITY-ART-H     12-09 1476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-IDENTITY-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MULTICULTURALISM MOVES INEXORABLY FORWARD, EUROPEANS ARE
GRAPPLING WITH IDENTITY CRISIS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend use) 
 
(Photo available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Honore) 
 
By CARL HONORE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Europeans have always had fun with national
stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   The uptight English sipping tea. The snobbish French dunking
croissants in their ``cafe au lait.'' The mechanical Germans
searching for a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, though, such portraits are largely the stuff of comedy
sketches and cartoons. Defining national identity in Western Europe
has become a subtle and slippery matter.
</P>
<P>
   In many countries, a debate rages over a question that never
needed asking before: What does it mean to be French or Dutch or
English?
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the identity crisis is European integration,
which is blurring old borders and binding the people of this
continent more closely together than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Another is immigration. Two generations after migrants started
arriving en masse, native Europeans are struggling to come to terms
with life in multi-ethnic societies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every people in Europe is grappling, in its own way, with the
question of who we are,'' says Roger Morgan, a senior fellow with
the Center for European Integration Research at the University of
Bonn in Germany. ``It's a tricky debate and one in which people can
take quite strong positions for and against.''
</P>
<P>
   Never easy to measure, identity can be roughly gauged by the way
a nation chooses to paint its own self-portrait. Does it banish
immigrants to the fringes or airbrush them out altogether? Or does
it allow immigrants to sit near the center, like full members of
the family?
</P>
<P>
   The final option unnerves many Europeans. Some nations in
Western Europe can trace their history and culture back more than a
thousand years. Embedded in the back of many minds is the belief
that ``European'' still equals ``white Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   When a black woman won the Miss Italy contest in 1996, some
commentators complained that she was ``unrepresentative of Italian
beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   But, at the other end of the spectrum, the Dutch have, for two
years running, sent black pop groups to represent their country at
the Eurovision Song Contest.
</P>
<P>
   European attitudes vary widely on how to embrace immigrants and
their cultures. In a recent poll, citizens in industrialized
countries were asked for their views on multiculturalism. Americans
and Canadians were the most accepting, followed by the British and
the Dutch and then by the Swedes. People in the rest of the
European Union lagged far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Multiculturalism is still a dirty word in France, where,
traditionally, immigrants have been expected to dump their own ways
in favor of ``French'' culture.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, the idea of an ethnically homogenous nation remains
strong. Laws traditionally have made it hard for anyone without
German blood to earn citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Although continental integration has spawned a new ``European''
elite who speak two or three languages and glide across borders
with ease, it is also driving many people deeper into old national
and regional identities.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, immigrants are an undeniable fact of life in Europe,
and they are giving a multi-ethnic flavor to everything from sports
to music to cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   More and more European schools, even in France, permit immigrant
students to wear the traditional dress of their homelands, and many
cater to their dietary preferences. In the Netherlands, white
teen-agers sprinkle their speech with Surinamese, Arabic and
Turkish words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like it or not, Europe is changing on the ground,'' says Mark
Mitchell, an immigration expert at the University of Portsmouth in
England. ``Every country is different, and though you can argue
about the speed, the overall evolution toward de facto
multiculturalism is now unstoppable.''
</P>
<P>
   Social divisions among ethnic groups are also starting to
soften.
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies show that more than 60 percent of the French have
friends in minority groups, not far behind British levels.
Interracial marriages are more common in both countries than in the
United States. In Britain, half of black men and a third of black
women have married or have lived with a white partner.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Germany, where mainstream politicians still insist that
``we are not a country of immigration,'' inter-ethnic marriages are
on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers believe that the bonds of friendship and family
will help draw immigrants into the national self-portrait.
</P>
<P>
   ``When personal relationships are forming across ethnic lines,
people find it easier to imagine a national identity with a
multicultural basis,'' says Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has probably moved farthest down the road to a shared
multicultural identity.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic cooking is a big hit all over Europe, but the British
have gone one step further, virtually adopting Indian food as their
national cuisine. In last summer's World Cup, that great cauldron
of national emotions, one official song of the English soccer team
was a homage to a fiery Indian dish called vindaloo. And the new
``curry pubs,'' where customers wash down Indian grub with pints of
lager, are the ultimate in cultural fusion.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, the British marked the 50th anniversary of the
arrival of the first boatload of immigrants from the Caribbean with
a vivid celebration of multiculturalism, which culminated in a gala
evening of comedy, music and poetry that was broadcast nationally
and attended by top politicians and celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the World Cup may have marked a turning point for the
host country, France. Built around a core of dark-skinned
immigrants, the French team won the championship and, with it, the
hearts of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the victory, hundreds of thousands of revelers
piled into the Champs Elysees. In a rare display of ``fraternite,''
blacks, Arabs and whites danced and sang together, waving the
French tricolor flag.
</P>
<P>
   No one believes that racism in France will end overnight. But
the World Cup victory could prove to be the moment when the French
began to embrace their multiracial society.
</P>
<P>
   ``A World Cup victory does not change social reality,'' wrote
Serge July, editor of the Liberation newspaper in Paris. ``But it
can change the image the French have of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The French victory did not go unnoticed in Germany, whose soccer
team, made up entirely of white men with names such as Jurgen,
performed dismally in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Yet cheering on dark-skinned players who score big goals is the
easy part. Many Europeans still find it hard to accept all
immigrants as full members of the national family or to celebrate
the emergence of a new cultural hybrid.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the Netherlands and Britain, those two multicultural
trailblazers, racism and discrimination run deep.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, millions of dark-skinned people living in Europe,
including those born on the continent, wonder if they will ever be
accepted as ``real'' Europeans. And their defeatism could become a
self-fulfilling prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   Some immigrants and their children make little effort to
integrate, preferring instead to huddle in ethnic enclaves,
speaking their own languages, eating their own food, hanging out
with their own people. That isolation is made easier by modern
technology, which gives immigrants the chance to phone and fly home
often and to watch TV from the mother country on satellite
channels.
</P>
<P>
   Such ethnic cocooning is anathema to thinkers such as Anil
Ramdas, a Surinamese immigrant and a leading commentator in the
Netherlands, who believe that non-whites should work overtime to
earn a place at the center of the national self-portrait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should the white majority be open to us simply because we
are here?`` Ramdas asks. ``It's our business to portray ourselves
as the most modern, the most hip, the most desirable people in the
world. This is not the flower-power era of good will. We live in
the advertising age where you have to sell yourself, and only the
glamorous survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ethnic cocooning could slow the pace, many European
intellectuals think it is unlikely to halt the general drift toward
multiculturalism. Peering into their crystal balls, some see
Europeans of the distant future living at ease in multi-ethnic
melting pots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be people who say that European cultures
cannot or should not be diluted,'' Morgan says. ``But the clear
trend is to redefine national identities along multicultural
lines.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, though, European comedians will continue to
milk those old jokes about the tea-sipping English, the snobby
French and the rigid Germans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1443EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
