A0887 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWER-BATTERIES-HNS &LR;      12-09 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-BATTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTERIES KEEP POWERLESS CITY CLINGING TO TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco's information revolution went to
battery power Tuesday, showing just how dependent
communication-rich lifestyles are on electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The outage that struck the city and adjoining areas also led
some to believe they had witnessed a preview of the much-ballyhooed
millennium bug computer meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, I hope they get things up and running really, really
soon,'' said John Bandermere, a San Francisco programmer who was
trying to get the last drops of power out of his IBM laptop
computer before the batteries were exhausted. ``I only have about
30 minutes left, then I'm hosed. There's nowhere around here to
charge up again.''
</P>
<P>
   A mistake made by a Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co. work crew shut
down a power substation in the San Francisco Bay area Tuesday
morning, leaving 1 million people without electricity for up to
seven hours.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular phone users were quickly sucking up battery power, as
many office phone systems shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a race against time,'' said Susan Werler, an executive
assistant who was holding a cell phone up to her face. ``They keep
putting me on hold, and I think I only have about 10 more minutes
of talk time left.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean Garrett of Alexander Ogilvy, a high-tech public relations
firm, said the outage had created a ``primal'' atmosphere at the
San Francisco-based company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very technology intensive here,'' he said. ``Panic sets
in when e-mail goes down for 10 minutes. Throw in the phones going
down, and you get a crazy workday.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell felt the switch to portable phones. ``Our wireless
phone traffic was up 65 percent,'' said John Britton, a spokesman
for the telephone company. ``We had congestion, and not all the
calls that were made got through.''
</P>
<P>
   Regular phone lines, which use low voltage power from a number
of Pacific Bell generators, continued to operate during the outage,
and handled an extra million-plus phone calls during the power
outage, Britton said. The wired phone power comes from diesel
engines that kicked in at 13 Pacific Bell stations in the San
Francisco area.
</P>
<P>
   During the outage, many Internet companies sent their workers
home, as monitors blinked off and network connections were dropped.
``A lot of people got the day off,'' said Sarah Wright, marketing
director for Surfree.com, a 5,000-employee Internet service
provider.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommuters also got the day off: With power off at many San
Francisco offices, there was no where to send data.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just stayed home and sketched,'' said Terry Colon, a
home-based computer illustrator for a Lycos Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Most large Silicon Valley Internet companies were unaffected
because they are bases south of the affected area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were missed,'' said Erin Schlough of Mountain View-based
Netscape Corp. Schlough said that if a power outage had hit the
Silicon Valley, the redundant nature of the Internet would kick in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most companies replicate their sites on other computers
located pretty much around the world,'' she said. ``Any traffic
that would come to us would be rerouted to those other machines.''
</P>
<P>
   Some saw Tuesday's outage as a sneak peek at the predicted
millennium computer snafu, or the ``YK2 problem,'' when some
computers supposedly will get lost in a time warp.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts fear that many computers originally programmed
to recognize only the last two digits of a year will fail or
malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, when the machines will assume it is
1900.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must of been mentioned around here 20 times,'' Garrett
said. ``People were saying it's a dress rehearsal for Y2K. Very
scary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1509EST &QL; 
