A0889 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOLFEBOOK-IN-OUT-TEX     12-09 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLFEBOOK-IN-OUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOLFE NOVEL IS IN, THEN OUT, IN THE BONFIRE OF THE HIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does the speed of America's pop-culture machine leave you
feeling a bit behind the times? A step slow? Unhep to the latest
jive?
</P>
<P>
   If so, there's a good reason. For Those In The Know are
constantly deciding that the latest Hot Thing is now The Thing That
Was Formerly Hot. In fact, the thing that was once Hot is often
reclassified as Overhyped or _ heavens! _ Laughably Overrated
before you even dragged your out-of-touch rear end to the mall and
purchased whatever it is we're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   What we're talking about is the latest tome by Tom Wolfe, ``A
Man in Full'' (Farrar, Straus and Giroux, $28.95). If you're just
getting around to purchasing one of the 1.2 million copies in its
mammoth first printing, then you are sooooo November '98. I mean,
that book is yesterday's ``Entertainment Tonight'' report.
Following is proof:
</P>
<P>
   July '98: ``Business Week'' notes that the publisher of the
yet-to-be-released novel changed the cover art _ from two men
clashing to a picture of the Atlanta skyline _ after Barnes &AMP; Noble
focus groups proclaimed that the original concept had ``too much
confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   August '98: David Kamp, in a profile of Wolfe in ``Vanity
Fair,'' gets an advance read of the novel and proclaims it better
than Wolfe's 1987 novel, ``Bonfire of the Vanities.''
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 15: ``A Man in Full'' is nominated for a prestigious
National Book Award, nearly a month before the book is released and
before review copies have been sent to most critics.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 2: Time magazine offers the first of many long, slow wet
kisses that the media will plant upon ``A Man in Full.'' In a cover
story, the magazine calls his novel ``bodacious'' and says it
proves he ``still has the right stuff.'' More praise follows in The
Washington Post, Newsweek and The New York Times, which saw fit to
print Michael Lewis' contention that ``The novel contains passages
as powerful and as beautiful as anything written not merely by
contemporary American novelists but by any American novelist.''
America pants.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 7: The disquieting storm of the critical backlash begins to
rumble. Jacob Weisberg, writing in the online journal Slate, says
Wolfe infuses his tale ``with characteristic wit, verve, and
narrative propulsion.'' But Weisberg is disturbed by its lack of
heart, of decency, and he concludes that the book ``remains
sophisticated entertainment rather than literature.'' Those In The
Know take note.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 8: Star-Telegram books editor Larry Swindell has already
read the tea leaves, and in his largely favorable but appropriately
measured review of the book, he declares that it is ``already
overhyped and, I believe, already overrated.'' That same day,
taking its cue from the heartland, the Los Angeles Times says that
despite some ``brilliant riffs,'' the new novel has ``a great deal
of make-work writing and narrative padding.'' The reviewer says its
characters, ``(like) the bumper cars in a fun house ... collide
zanily, but they take us nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 10, 8:57 a.m.: Slate posts the first excerpt of an e-mail
exchange between ``Vanity Fair's'' Marjorie Williams and ``The
Washington Monthly's'' Timothy Noah debating the merits of ``A Man
in Full's'' ending, among other specific discussions about the
book.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 10, 9 a.m.: The bookstores open. ``A Man in Full'' is
available for purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 18: Alice McDermott's ``Charming Billy,'' not Wolfe's book,
wins the National Book Award for fiction. From the dais, esteemed
novelist John Updike, who wrote a bruising review of ``A Man in
Full'' in ``The New Yorker,'' makes fun of Wolfe.
</P>
<P>
   Last week: ``The New Republic'' runs a rip-snorting, brutally
mocking review of the book, the first sentence of which is, ``Tom
Wolfe's novels are placards of simplicity.'' The reviewer, James
Wood, calls Wolfe's mind ``curiously unliterary'' and decries his
writing as ``... this bumptious simplicity, this toy-set of
literary codes essentially indistinguishable from the narrative
techniques of boys' comics. ... '' USA Today later says that ``A
Man in Full'' is both entertainment and literature, and all these
second-guessers should realize that, preparing us for the third
wave of Wolfe-ian discussion: the opinion that Those In The Know
were duped into believing that second round of negative criticism.
</P>
<P>
   This week: A reporter, preparing to describe how Tom Wolfe's
latest novel has been praised and dismissed to such an extent as to
make reading it superfluous, zips through 248 of its 742 pages
before deadline. He thinks it's ``pretty good,'' but he is
admittedly behind the times.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
