<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS CHRISTMAS PICKLES PACK SOME HIGH-POWERED PUCKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jennifer Coolidge cut out the recipe for Texas Christmas pickles
from last year's pages. Her family loved them, but she lost the
recipe. Here it is again. The recipe came to us via Lori J.
Bennett, who entered it in a cooking contest we ran last year.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS CHRISTMAS PICKLES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 gallon
</P>
<P>
   1-gallon jar of dill pickles
</P>
<P>
   5-pound bag sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 small bottle Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Drain all juice from pickles and discard. Slice pickles
lengthwise and place in jar. Add Tabasco and garlic. Add about
one-third of the sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Screw lid back on jar tightly, so no juice will leak out. Gently
tip jar back and forth several times to allow sugar and spices to
mix with pickles. Leave on counter at room temperature for about a
week.
</P>
<P>
   As sugar dissolves, add more until all sugar is used. Gently tip
jar back and forth daily to allow sugar and spices to mix.
</P>
<P>
   When all sugar is absorbed, pickles with be dark-green and
crispy. Serve on deli platter with sliced vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per half-pickle: 35 calories, trace fat, 9
grams carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 287 milligrams
sodium, 2 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet stuff: Sonny Norrell of Fort Worth requests a recipe for
sugar cream pie. Here's one from ``Heartland'' by Marcia Adams
(Potter, $30).
</P>
<P>
   OLD-FASHIONED INDIANA CREAM PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 pre-baked 9-inch pie shell
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Sift first 4 ingredients together.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk egg with sour cream. Add dry ingredients to the egg
mixture and mix well. Add melted butter and vanilla, and whisk
until smooth. Pour filling into pre-baked pie shell and place pie
plate on a baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Bake pie in bottom third of oven for 10 minutes. Reduce heat to
300 degrees and continue baking until filling is set, 20 to 25
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove pie from oven and let cool to room temperature on wire
rack. Serve immediately, topped with fresh fruit, or refrigerate
and serve the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 276 calories, 19 grams fat, 21
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 63 milligrams cholesterol,
194 milligrams sodium, 63 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Cake without the oven: Loyce Clark sends the first recipe for a
no-bake fruitcake. Barbara Raus of Granbury, Texas, sends the
second recipe. She usually substitutes Milnot for the evaporated
milk to cut fat.
</P>
<P>
   NO-COOKING FRUITCAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8-10
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound candied cherries
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound candied pineapple
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound dates, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound pecans, chopped
</P>
<P>
   6-ounce package coconut
</P>
<P>
   14 can sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 box vanilla wafers (broken)
</P>
<P>
   Mix all ingredients well. Pack in a box or pan in waxed paper.
Refrigerate. Also freezes well and will last a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 606 calories, 27 grams fat, 91
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 20 milligrams cholesterol, 93
milligrams sodium, 40 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   NO-BAKE FRUITCAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 16-20
</P>
<P>
   1 cup evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   32 marshmallows, finely cut, or 4 cups small marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   8 cups fine graham cracker crumbs (about 8 dozen 2 1/2-inch
size)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dark seedless raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light seedless raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped dates
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups mixed nuts
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups mixed candied fruit
</P>
<P>
   Combine first 3 ingredients in a 3-quart bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Into another bowl, measure the remaining ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Work the spice-raisin mixture into milk mixture with spoon, then
with hands until crumbs are moist. Pack in tube cake pan. Let sit
48 hours in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 361 calories, 10 grams fat, 66
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 4 milligrams cholesterol, 234
milligrams sodium, 26 percent of calories from fat. Request:
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Nelson of Weatherford, Texas, would like a recipe for a
chocolate cookie that has a deep cracked finish and is covered with
powdered sugar.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
