<HEADLINE>
FRENCH HONOR TEXANS FOR WORLD WAR I SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARMINA DANINI  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ To the French, they were ``Sammies,'' the young
men of the American Expeditionary Force who brought the promise of
ending the bloody stalemate that engulfed Europe.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, more than 80 years after the Armistice ended World
War I, the French awarded two aging veterans from Texas that
nation's highest decoration _ the Legion of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Brig. Gen. Albert Crowther and retired Pvt. William
Martin of San Antonio received the medal from Francois Bujon de
l'Estang, the French ambassador to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is in frail health, Alfred Rihn of Lytle, Texas, will
be presented the same medal at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, the ceremony was held against a backdrop of two World
War I-era ambulances in the U.S. Army Medical Department Museum at
Fort Sam Houston.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac decided to mark the 80th
anniversary of the signing of the Armistice by conferring the
Legion of Honor on all surviving Allied veterans of the 1914-1918
war.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador said France lost 1.3 million men in ``a
devastating war.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States came to France's aid, Bujon said, by sending
more than 2 million soldiers, called Sammies by the French people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French have not forgotten the courage of these young
soldiers,'' the ambassador told about 100 military personnel,
family and friends of the two recipients. ``This underscores the
friendship that has existed between the U.S. and France for over
200 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bujon stood before each man, affixed the medal and red ribbon on
their lapels and said, in French, ``In the name of the president of
the Republic and by virtue of the powers vested in me, we hereby
make you a knight of the Legion of Honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Bujon said it had taken an enormous effort by the
French Embassy and the U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs to trace
and locate surviving American veterans of what had once been called
``the war to end all wars.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legion of Honor, with the rank of ``chevalier,'' or knight,
will be given to all surviving Allied veterans who served in France
prior to Nov. 11, 1918, the day the Armistice was signed.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 veterans from the Allied forces _ including
soldiers from Britain, France and the United States _ have been
identified as eligible to receive the medal.
</P>
<P>
   Crowther, 100, enlisted in the Texas Militia in 1916. He served
with Battery A, Second Texas Field Artillery, in France. He
remained in the Army and served in Italy during World War II. He
said he was greatly honored to receive the medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's given by a nation of people that I admire,'' the retired
banker said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 103, was born in Fayetteville, Texas. He enlisted in the
Army in July 1918 as a private with the 815th Pioneer Infantry.
</P>
<P>
   After his discharge in August 1919, Martin went to work at the
Magnolia Ice Cream factory in Houston. He also worked on his own
farm before joining the United Gas Company in San Antonio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1546EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
