<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0985 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNERAL-ADVICE10-COX     12-09 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNERAL-ADVICE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Industry concedes its price structures hard to understand
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey and Kay Powell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you think car prices are confusing, consider funerals.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a single sheet of charges that can be pasted on a
window, most funeral homes have pages of prices for everything from
refrigerating the body to scattering the ashes in the North Georgia
mountains. When you buy a car, you buy a car. When you buy a
funeral, you're buying a matrix of goods, services and intangibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not retailers; we're professionals. As an industry, we
haven't done a very good job of explaining our pricing,'' says
Kelly Smith, public relations director for the National Funeral
Directors Association, a trade group based near Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Take caskets. Funeral directors have traditionally sold caskets
at a high markup to recoup other costs associated with maintaining
expensive vehicles and real estate. The industry started
re-evaluating its price structures in the 1980s when the Federal
Trade Commission enacted a rule requiring mortuaries to disclose
charges for goods such as caskets and services such as embalming.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC rule also meant that for the first time consumers could
meaningfully compare prices. This year, Woody Bates, a retired
Coca-Cola marketing executive and member of the Memorial Society of
Georgia, spent weeks driving around metro Atlanta collecting price
lists from more than 100 funeral homes. He found that chain-owned
establishments, in general, have higher prices than independents,
charging a basic service fee that averaged $300 more. The findings
concur with surveys in other markets.
</P>
<P>
   Service Corp. International, the largest chain, counters that
its average funeral in the United States costs $4,821, less than
$50 above the national average as computed by the funeral directors
association. Besides, says SCI executive Glenn McMillen, price
surveys oversimplify the picture. They don't take into account
package deals, and they make no allowance for the higher level of
service one expects at a carriage-trade funeral home such as H.M.
Patterson &AMP; Son, SCI's best-known Atlanta property, where
``Preferred Tradition'' packages run from $9,985 to $24,425.
</P>
<P>
   ``In life,'' McMillen says, ``you still get pretty much what you
pay for.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1600EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0986 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNERAL-GLOSSARY10-CO     12-09 0181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNERAL-GLOSSARY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THe vocabulary of the death
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Funeral speak
</P>
<P>
   Undertakers are famous for their euphemisms. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   Cover charge. Somewhat irreverent industry slang for the basic
service fee funeral directors list under the government-required
itemization of charges.
</P>
<P>
   Cremains. The pulverized bones _ not really ashes _ left after
cremation.
</P>
<P>
   Floral tribute. Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Interment space. Grave.
</P>
<P>
   Inurnment. Putting the cremains into an urn.
</P>
<P>
   Earth. What the grave is filled with. Never dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Loved ones. Survivors _ also known as the people who pick up the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Opening the interment space. Digging a grave.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing the body. Embalming.
</P>
<P>
   Removal. Taking away a corpse.
</P>
<P>
   Succession planning. Selling out to a chain, referring to a
major reason independent funeral homes change hands: Junior doesn't
want to be a mortician.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1600EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0987 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNERAL10-2NDTAKE-COX     12-09 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNERAL10-2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: back down.''
</P>
<P>
   A muckraker among morticians
</P>
<P>
   About the time Waltrip and SCI began reshaping the funeral
business, a writer was finishing a book that would reshape the
public's perception of it. Jessica Mitford, a feisty Briton with
leftist political leanings, did for undertakers what Upton Sinclair
had done for meatpackers with her 1963 muckraking best-seller,
``The American Way of Death.'' She was working on an update when
she died two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every family that a funeral director has met with in the past
35 years has brought a conventional wisdom informed by that text,''
laments Lynch, the undertaker author.
</P>
<P>
   Mitford portrayed funeral directors as self-appointed shamen who
took advantage of grieving survivors when they were most vulnerable
and least likely to compare prices. She found embalming ghoulish
and argued that direct cremation was preferable to pumping a corpse
full of arterial fluid.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was partially right,'' Lynch concedes. ``When you have a
dead body on the floor that happens to be someone you were married
to for 50 years, it's hard to let your fingers do the walking.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry's main response to Mitford's critique has been to
sell prepaid funerals that allow customers to make choices and lock
in prices before they need an undertaker. Billions of dollars worth
of funerals have been arranged in this manner. Consumer's Digest
and other watchdog groups discourage prepaying because many plans
are nonrefundable and nontransferable, not to mention mediocre
investments. Still, consumers seem to take comfort in pre-need
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Another response to Mitford's criticisms has come from outside
the industry. Memorial societies _ co-ops in which people band
together to buy low-cost funeral services from selected mortuaries
_ have spread nationwide and now count more than 500,000 members.
The Memorial Society of Georgia has 7,000, twice as many as five
years ago. One group in California has gone so far as to assist
families in caring for and burying their own dead _ the ultimate
do-it-yourself project.
</P>
<P>
   While the vast majority of society members plan to be cremated,
there are exceptions. One is Sandy Whittington, the woman with the
coffin in her attic.
</P>
<P>
   The divorced mother of three didn't want to be a bother to her
children, two of whom live far away, so she decided to make her own
arrangements. A local funeral home quoted a price of $7,000.
Sticker-shocked, she joined the Memorial Society instead. But when
she went to one of the mortuaries the society did business with and
asked to see the casket used in the low-cost burial, the funeral
director showed her a cloth-covered coffin and said, ``Perhaps your
family wouldn't be embarrassed to see you in this.''
</P>
<P>
   The society was outraged and did not renew its contract with
that funeral home.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Whittington _ an enthusiastic history buff _
heard about some carpenters who made 19th-century reproduction
coffins. She ordered a pinch-toed pine box with raised panels and a
cross on top for $800 from Bert and Bud's Vintage Coffins of
Murray, Ky. Then she went back to the first funeral home and told
it exactly what kind of modest rites she wanted. It kept a copy of
her wishes on file _ no money down _ and she gave copies to her
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told everyone that if they want to send flowers, do it
now so I can smell them,'' Whittington says.
</P>
<P>
   Cremains of the day
</P>
<P>
   With the rise of cremation, funeral directors have noticed that
fewer families are having bodies embalmed and displayed at a
service. It's as if disposal of the remains and memorialization of
the life are beginning to diverge in the public mind. No example
demonstrates the trend better than the death of Jessica Mitford.
</P>
<P>
   After the writer died of brain cancer, her body was cremated and
her ashes cast upon the Pacific Ocean, near her Berkeley, Calif.,
home. It was the simplest of committals.
</P>
<P>
   The memorials were another matter. Mitford's friends and
admirers gathered to honor her in San Francisco, Martha's Vineyard
and London, where the theater rental alone cost thousands of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But the splashiest memorial is still to come. Her followers in
Northern California are planning to build a co-op funeral center,
with a crematory and a cemetery that doesn't allow caskets, vaults
or tombstones, like some modern-day Indian burial ground. The
centerpiece will be the Jessica Mitford Memorial Theater, a public
hall where people can hold anything from commemorative services to
concerts.
</P>
<P>
   They may even make it a chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at developing other sites,'' says Karen Leonard,
who heads the Redwood Memorial Society and was Mitford's research
assistant on the new edition of her book (which was published in
August). ``The Grateful Dead wants to help us with fund-raising.''
</P>
<P>
   At Mitford's request, Leonard sent her crematory bill of about
$500 to SCI headquarters, suggesting that the company pay it in
light of all the publicity she had given it over the years. The
request was predictably ignored.
</P>
<P>
   But the folks in Houston haven't completely disregarded
Mitford's passing. She visited the funeral museum shortly before
her death, Leonard says, and was soured by the way the industry
portrayed itself as ``God's headwaiters.'' Now it's the industry's
turn. In the museum, there's a display of memorial bulletins from
recent celebrity funerals: Frank Sinatra, Roy Rogers, Barry
Goldwater _ and, yes, Jessica Mitford, 1917-1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't discriminate,'' says Boetticher, a smile buried
somewhere beneath his solemn expression.
</P>
<P>
   Further information
</P>
<P>
   Memorial Society of Georgia. $35 to join. 404-634-2896. For a
list of societies nationally, contact Funeral and Memorial
Societies of America. 800-765-0107. www.funerals.org/famsa
</P>
<P>
   National Museum of Funeral History. Open year-round in Houston.
281-876-3063. www.nmfh.org
</P>
<P>
   Service Corporation International. To find an SCI facility, call
800-9CARING (922-7464). www.sci-corp.com
</P>
<P>
   Bert and Bud's Vintage Coffins. 502-753-9279.
www.vintagecoffins.com. The carpenters' latest job is a custom
order for Santa Claus _ a Kentucky man who plays Santa and wants to
be buried in a box with a Christmas motif.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
