<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0988 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNERAL10-2TAKES-COX     12-09 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNERAL10-2TAKES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The American way of death, once a bastion of tradition, is
changing as people reconsider their final rites
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One night last year, Sandy Whittington stretched out on her
living room floor in Douglasville(Ga.) and instructed her
disbelieving son to take her measurements. Two months later, it
arrived: a casket in a packing crate labeled ``Coffin _ Empty.''
She had it hauled to the attic, where it holds out-of-season
clothes and waits for the inevitable day that awaits us all.
</P>
<P>
   She isn't terminally ill; at 60, the Veterans Administration
retiree seems livelier than some people half her age. She was
simply appalled at the cost of a traditional funeral and decided to
do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still want to be embalmed,'' she allows. ``I have a fear of
being buried alive, and I figure if you aren't dead when you get to
the funeral home, you'll sure be dead by the time you leave.''
</P>
<P>
   While few people keep mail-order caskets in the attic,
Whittington's desire to take charge of her funeral is indicative of
something larger. The American way of death is changing as a
growing number of people, for a variety of reasons, rethink their
final rites.
</P>
<P>
   Alternative funerals are on the rise. Retail casket dealers
(such as metro Atlanta's first, Peachtree Caskets Direct in
Alpharetta(Ga.)) are opening shop. Cremation, once a rarity, now
figures in almost a quarter of the nation's 2.3 million deaths a
year. Personal touches and quirky tributes are turning up in
services everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost revolutionary, what's happening,'' says Kelly
Smith of the National Funeral Directors Association. His favorite
new-era funeral story? He met a mechanic in a bar who told him
about a buddy of his who was buried with cigarettes, Zippo lighters
and the latest issue of Playboy.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the same forces that have altered America have altered
funerals: mobility, consumerism, the splintering of families and
organized religion. Add to those the growing informality of
American society, which seems to be bringing the spirit of an Irish
wake to many funerals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of what we respond to in funerals is more or less
fashion,'' says Thomas Lynch, a Michigan funeral director who wrote
a poetic memoir of his profession called ``The Undertaking: Life
Studies From the Dismal Trade.'' As he sees it, funerals used to be
about security: dark-suited men who sold protective-seal caskets
and sturdy vaults. Now the watchword is choice: colorful caskets,
eulogies from friends, ashes scattered at sunset, memorial services
where the loved one might not be present but his barbecue grill or
her favorite stuffed animal might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're rolling our own rituals,'' Lynch says.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral museum
</P>
<P>
   The funeral as we know it _ with an embalmed corpse propped in a
shiny casket under the soft glow of a mortuary torchier _ did not
become the standard until early this century. Before then, bodies
stayed home and went swiftly into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Laderman, an Emory University(Ga.) religion professor,
illustrates the transition in his book ``The Sacred Remains'' by
comparing the funerals of George Washington and Abraham Lincoln.
The first president was buried quickly and memorialized nationwide
at processions in which symbolic empty coffins were carried. The
mourning for Abe was more literal; the 16th president's body was
embalmed and touched up repeatedly as hundreds of thousands of
citizens viewed it during an 11-day train journey back to Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil War was the turning point, as undertakers followed
soldiers into the field to preserve their bodies for shipment home.
By the late 1800s, Laderman writes, ``Funeral directors became the
new priests who presided over the corpse.''
</P>
<P>
   The transformation from undertaker to mortician to funeral
director is lovingly documented at the National Museum of Funeral
History, an obscure assemblage of Americana packed away in an
office park building in the northern suburbs of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Open since 1993, the museum has a dazzling collection of vintage
hearses and bizarre caskets, such as the custom-made triple-wide
that a Colorado couple ordered after their son died. (In their
grief, they planned to join him in repose by committing suicide but
changed their minds.) There are displays of embalming equipment,
exhibits on mourning customs and, just arrived, the eternal flame
that burned over John F. Kennedy's grave until it was replaced last
year. It would all seem dreadfully gloomy if it weren't for the
jaunty big band music coming from the speakers _ toe-tappers like
Louis Armstrong's ``I'll Be Glad When You're Dead, You Rascal
You.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to feel upbeat when they leave here,'' laughs
museum president Bob Boetticher, a funeral director for 33 years.
(Who said undertakers don't have a sense of humor?)
</P>
<P>
   Boetticher has a special affection for the Victorian era, when
funeral rituals reached full blossom. He knows that pallbearers a
century ago donned gray gloves and that girls were given dolls
dressed in black because even toys should look sad in a time of
mourning. On weekends, the director haunts antiques shops looking
for cast-off funeraria. Sometimes he dresses up like an old-time
undertaker and trots out one of the museum's horse-drawn hearses
for parades.
</P>
<P>
   ``People knew that death was part of life back then,''
Boetticher says. ``They didn't deny it. They took it seriously. Now
when someone dies, it's, `I gotta get back to work.'
</P>
<P>
   He shrugs. ``I was born in the wrong era.''
</P>
<P>
   The big business of death
</P>
<P>
   In the museum's lobby, there's a bust depicting a jowly man who
may be the most important figure in the funeral industry today.
He's Robert L. Waltrip, founder and chairman of Houston-based
Service Corp. International, the world's largest funeral company.
The bust? He founded the museum, too.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip started his company in 1962 with two local funeral homes
that had been in his family for decades. Now SCI owns 3,370
mortuaries, 430 cemeteries and 180 crematories in 18 countries.
It's one of three public corporations _ the Loewen Group of British
Columbia and Stewart Enterprises of New Orleans are the others _
that have become the talk of the industry for bringing merger and
acquisition to what had been a mom and pop enterprise. Together,
they own almost 15 percent of the nation's 21,900 funeral homes,
accounting for almost a quarter of all funerals.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't know a chain mortuary to look at it. When SCI
purchases a property such as H.M. Patterson &AMP; Son, the blue-blood
Atlanta funeral home it bought in 1993, the name and much of the
staff remain the same. The changes occur out of view. SCI assembles
clusters of properties so it can centralize accounting,
transportation and in some cases embalming.
</P>
<P>
   Some have called SCI the McDonald's of death. Glenn McMillen,
senior vice president of operations, dislikes the analogy. ``The
funeral business just doesn't lend itself to a chain operation,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   The McDeath tag doesn't fit for another reason. Unlike the
burger biz, where competition and economies of scale keep prices
down, the opposite often seems to happen with funerals. Price
surveys in city after city have shown that charges at
chain-operated mortuaries usually are among the highest. In
Houston, a survey by KPRC-TV and the Interfaith Funeral Information
Committee, a consumer group out of Arizona, found that 16 of the 20
most expensive funeral homes were owned by the Big Three
consolidators. (SCI disputes the impression left by such surveys;
see accompanying story.)
</P>
<P>
   Rabun Smith, a longtime funeral director in Warner Robins, has
seen the issue from both sides _ as an independent and as an SCI
employee. In 1988, nearing retirement, he sold the
Christopher-Smith Funeral Home to a chain that was later absorbed
by SCI. He stayed with the business for five years, but didn't like
what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came in here and almost doubled prices,'' he says. ``If
they keep buying up funeral homes, which seems to be their
intention, heaven help us.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as his contract with SCI was up, Smith opened a new
business, the Heritage Memorial Funeral Home, to compete with the
one that still bears his name. A funny thing happened, he says.
``The other people's prices came back down.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
