<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Science and health stories from The New York Times News Service
for Thursday, Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SAFRICA-FOSSIL (Undated) _ Scientists in South Africa
announce they have found what they describe as the most complete
skull and skeleton yet of a very early member of the human family
tree. It is of the afarensis period, like Lucy, but its skull is
much more complete. Also, this fossil, like foot bones found
earlier, suggests that at this stage of its history, humanity was
walking on two feet but also spending a lot of time in the trees.
And other fascinating facts and speculations. By John Noble
Wilford. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEAT-EXTREMES (Undated) _ Extreme summer heat and humidity
of the kind most threatening to health have become more frequent in
the United States over the last half century, two federal
researchers are reporting today. The trend was stronger at night
than in the daytime, making it especially dangerous, particularly
for the elderly. While the increasing frequency of extreme heat and
humidity cannot be directly linked to global warming, if it even
exists, it is consistent with what is predicted in the global
warming scenario.'' By William K. Stevens. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPACE-STATION (Undated) _ Two shuttle astronauts make their
second space walk in continued effort to assemble the International
Space Station. By Warren E. Leary. (500 words)
</P>
