<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL GORE SR. WAS MUCH MORE THAN A POLITICIAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget about political philosophy. Forget about the never-ending
confrontation between conservative and liberal ideas. Forget about
the partisan conflict that seems to dominate American politics.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Gore Sr. was a politician who transcended such concerns.
When Gore died over the weekend at the age of 90, Vice President Al
Gore lost his father, and our nation lost a statesman.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``statesman'' seems almost archaic in today's political
environment, for it connotes a grandness of vision and nobility of
purpose that are sadly lacking in our current crop of politicians.
</P>
<P>
   A statesman is someone who will do what he believes is right
without regard for the political price. A statesman is more
concerned about his country's future than about his own.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Gore, a Democrat, represented Tennessee in the U.S.
Senate from 1953 until 1970. He was an early supporter of civil
rights and an early opponent of the Vietnam War _ positions that
were instrumental in derailing his bid for a fourth term. He lost
the 1970 election to Republican Bill Brock, who vigorously attacked
Gore's liberal views.
</P>
<P>
   He was a liberal, no doubt about it, but he was no knee-jerk
leftist. Here's what ``The New York Times'' said in its obituary:
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1952, Gore was elected to the Senate, where he did not fit
into the mold of either the Northern liberals or the Southern
conservatives. He was known as one of the Senate's best debaters
and was considered a possible Vice Presidential nominee in 1956 and
1960, but he frequently found himself on the unpopular side of an
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is probably best remembered for his role in promoting the
interstate highway system, which could hardly be considered a
liberal issue _ especially by the standards of today's liberal
environmentalists, who look upon concrete as a lethal threat to
nature.
</P>
<P>
   Do you suppose that this energetic proponent of coast-to-coast
paving saw any irony in his politician son's eventual devotion to
ultraliberal environmental causes? He probably did; Al Gore Sr. had
a terrific sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   I discovered that when the former senator visited Fort Worth in
February 1988 to campaign for Al Gore Jr., who was seeking the
Democratic presidential nomination that year. Candidate Gore was
elsewhere that day, but nobody missed him; the candidate's father
was a show-stopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in 35 states so far _ only 15 to go,'' Gore Sr. said
during a campaign breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's having more fun than Al Junior,'' said a family friend
who had seen both men in action on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Gore laughed off a question about Brock, the man who
ended his Senate career and who was serving as campaign manager for
Republican Bob Dole's 1988 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say that's a `verboten' subject,'' Gore said with a
twinkle in his eye.
</P>
<P>
   Gore even saw the humor in a politically oriented comic strip's
send-up of his son as ``Prince Albert,'' a too-good-to-be-true
aristocrat who was bred to be president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have paid for that kind of exposure,'' Gore said.
``I'm just glad they spelled Al's name right.''
</P>
<P>
   I recall a Gore backer saying in '88 that she thought Al Jr.
looked like the actor who played Superman in the movies. Could be.
But Al Gore Sr. looked exactly like a Southern senator _ or maybe
Hollywood's idea of a Southern senator.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was a young-looking 80 back then, with a ready smile and a
firm, enthusiastic handshake. Strands of silver hair curled over
the crisply starched collar of his white shirt.
</P>
<P>
   He could have passed for a character from one of those epic
political novels that were so popular before the public became
disillusioned with politicians.
</P>
<P>
   I would venture the guess that if today's politicians were more
like Albert Gore Sr., there might not be so much disillusionment
about politics.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Al Gore Sr. was more than a politician. He was a
statesman.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
