<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1009 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAMPSON-IMPEACHMENT-H     12-09 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAMPSON-IMPEACHMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LAWMAKER KEEPS HIS IMPEACHMENT CARD TO HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As one of the few Democrats undecided on impeaching
President Clinton, Rep. Nicholas Lampson of Texas insists, ``I'm
not trying to play hard to get.''
</P>
<P>
   With the likelihood of a House impeachment vote growing, the
stakes for Lampson and a dozen or more other fence-sitters are
rising immeasurably. After the Judiciary Committee wraps up
hearings this week, jockeying among pro- and anti-Clinton forces
can only intensify.
</P>
<P>
   Lampson, while making some anti-impeachment comments Wednesday
in a telephone interview from his home town, Beaumont, maintained
his firm straddle. He is among a dwindling number of undecided
Democrats. Virtually all the other wavering lawmakers are moderate
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Lampson says, he is content to wait until the committee
wraps up its proceedings and votes on articles of impeachment
before making up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Three other Democrats _ Ralph Hall of Texas, Rep. Gene Taylor of
Mississippi and Rep. Virgil Goode of Virginia _ either openly
support impeachment or are leaning in that direction. A House floor
vote is expected next week.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Lampson, 53, a former public school science
teacher and tax assessor, said he has paid scant attention to this
week's Judiciary proceedings, in which legal scholars and veteran
prosecutors have defended Clinton. One thing he knows for certain:
The impeachment terrain is shifting as surely as a tectonic plate
during an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get myself out there and start making
statements about something that very likely will change by this
afternoon,'' he explained. ``I honestly believe it would be
premature.''
</P>
<P>
   House approval of impeachment frequently is compared with an
indictment. Approval by the House of impeachment articles would
send the matter to the Senate for a trial.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Lampson sees himself as something of a grand
juror. ``This is a very serious, far-reaching matter,'' he said.
``For me to go on speculating and tipping my hand without all the
information would cheapen the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he added, ``I'd sort of like to keep my cards to myself
for just a little longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Lampson's press secretary, Monette Goodrich, said the lawmaker
has not been pressured by White House officials or any other
Democrat. And Lampson said that while he did discuss impeachment
timing in a recent phone conversation with his Texas colleague,
Rep. Tom DeLay, the strongly anti-Clinton GOP House whip did not
try to sway his vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very clear about his position,'' Lampson said, reciting
DeLay's oft-stated view that Clinton should resign or be removed
from office. ``I can tell you I do not share that feeling, and I
will not make that kind of statement at this point one way or the
other,'' Lampson said.
</P>
<P>
   A few elements of the Clinton defense line put forward by
Democrats raise questions, Lampson said. One is the Democratic
contention that the context of Clinton's misstatements about his
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky _ the
Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit _ may have amounted to a
setup.
</P>
<P>
   Lampson described it as a possible ``sting operation.''
Democrats have charged that the Jones lawyers, Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr and Linda Tripp, the Pentagon employee who secretly
tape recorded Lewinsky talking about her affair with Clinton, were
in collusion with one another to bring Clinton down.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern, Lampson said, is whether Clinton's alleged
perjury and obstruction of justice in the Lewinsky matter are
impeachable offenses. Democrats have insisted they are not. Lampson
said he also worries about the impact of impeachment on the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that being a loyal Democrat has nothing to do with
his own decision-making. ``I feel like I'm a good Democrat but I
also feel like I need to be a good congressman,'' he said. ``I
don't have to follow my party line.''
</P>
<P>
   Lampson won his seat in 1996, dumping one-term Republican Steve
Stockman, who in 1994 had beaten Rep. Jack Brooks, a House
Democratic veteran who was at the time chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Lampson won re-election in 1998, beating GOP challenger Tom
Cottar by 64 percent to 36 percent. Lampson said the
impeachment-related calls and letters he receives have been mixed,
and that he was ``placing the pressure on myself'' to come through
with the right vote.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Lampson said he is focusing on a few unrelated
issues _ establishing a legal system to deal with cases of
international child abduction, and ending international trafficking
of child pornography on the Internet. ``These are things I can have
an impact on,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
