<HEADER>
A1034 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-FIRED-PRIME-MI     12-09 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-FIRED-PRIME-MINISTER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERGEI KIRIYENKO PONDERS RUSSIA IN CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By SERGEI KIRIYENKO  
 c.1998 Moscow News  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   It is important for the international community to sort out the
developments in Russia, for our present financial crisis is the
best proof that the Russian economy is integrated into the world
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Our potential partners in the West cannot grasp the logic of
Russia's leaders' economic and political decision making. And yes,
the main problem that faces the West in trying to figure out
Russian events is not so much their complexity as the country's
unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   I have tried to explain to your politicians, CEOs and other
decision makers that it is probably premature to look for a logical
pattern now.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains: our new Russian government under Prime
Minister Primakov still has not drawn up an economic policy. But
why? _ It has been too busy trying to ensure political stability.
And in fact it has managed to cope with this major task and keep
things from spiraling out of control. So we put up with a tradeoff:
uncertainty in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that Russia may well take a step backward in terms
of market reforms. What is important is WHY it will make this step.
I hope the outcome will be to make two steps forward afterward.
</P>
<P>
   As to checks and balances, the degree to which our economic
program is realistic depends on whether it can get support from
international financial organizations such as the IMF and World
Bank _ and on whether it succeeds in restructuring our foreign
debts.
</P>
<P>
   Three options are still possible to really overcome the Russian
crisis, but they are all related to the degree to which the budget
is balanced.
</P>
<P>
   _ Option One: To return to a rigid budget with revenues
exceeding expenditures. On this basis, an arrangement can be made
with international financial organizations on foreign-debt
restructuring. This would, however, require a total reform of our
tax system, reduction of ineffective expenditures and a way to
provide social protection to those who actually need it. In these
endeavors, the government might find itself taking steps at the
expense of its political prestige.
</P>
<P>
   _ Option Two: To draw up a relatively balanced budget that
presupposes an emission, or printing, of 80 billion to 100 billion
new rubles before the end of 1998. This means that 35 to 40 billion
rubles would go to the budget, 40 to 50 billion would be toward
payment of the foreign debt and 10 to 15 billion rubles would go
into Russia's banking system.
</P>
<P>
   Such a relatively balanced budget would result in a monthly
inflation rate of 5 percent to 8 percent through March. But it
would not lead to hyperinflation, and it would still enable us to
reach agreement on foreign-debt restructuring. In my view, this is
the most realistic option.
</P>
<P>
   _ Option Three: To meet the opposition's populist demands, the
government could try to solve all its problems, including those
that cannot possibly be solved, such as paying off all its debts by
December. This would call for a printing of 150 billion rubles or
so. In this case, inflation would be no less than 10 percent a
month through March.
</P>
<P>
   I think this option would be unworkable. First, it would not
promote economic development; second, it would be fraught with
serious social tensions.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, importantly, I believe that Russia has no economic
problems that cannot be solved. Everything hinges on the political
problem _ the government's weakness in the absence of any accord in
our society over the goals, means and price of reform.
</P>
<P>
   Many say that the democratic movement in Russia has suffered a
big defeat. There surely has been a political recoil. But even if
the idea of building a democracy is defeated, this does not mean
that a normal market economy cannot be built.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as spring, when I was prime minister, I thought the
main thing was to set ourselves an economic task that we could
tackle. I did not realize that in the final analysis, everything
would hinge on politics _ on the stability, wisdom and
trustworthiness of our politicians.
</P>
<P>
   We have made many mistakes, especially in grossly
underestimating the difficulty of remolding social consciousness.
One can speed up the implementation of an economic plan, but one
cannot speed up the remolding of social consciousness in the
various levels of society. All our economic theories, though
correct, tripped over this.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Russia has never seen a mere seven consecutive
years of economic reform. We simply mark time, taking two steps
backward for every forward step. What is important, however, is
that over this time of trial and error, everyone has realized that
no road exists other than the one leading to a free-market economy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Sergei Kiriyenko is Russia's former prime minister, appointed
by President Boris Yeltsin. His duration in office was five months,
preceding the appointment of current Prime Minister Primakov. This
commentary is adapted from an interview conducted by Yefim Barban,
a special correspondent to Moscow News.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
