<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weird, wacky and so South Park Off-color and on target
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gratuitous locker-room offensiveness spun around as
sophisticated chaos, Comedy Central's ``South Park'' is the kiddie
cartoon from hell: a shock-the-bourgeoisie spoof of pop-culture
that's outrageous but also sweet at its core. Likewise, the
inevitable soundtrack spin-off seems like a goof but boasts more
than a weird, eclectic all-star cast (can't think of the last time
I heard Elton John and former Clash frontman Joe Strummer on the
same album). It's actually pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Hayes, the '70s soul great who lends his rumbling bass
voice to the show's omnipresent Chef, gets the meatiest material _
not much of which can be alluded to in a family newspaper _ and
there's some easy laughs as some of ``South Park's'' kiddie
characters obliterate Styx's ``Come Sail Away'' and Bad Company's
``Feel Like Makin' Love.'' The surprises, though, are hilariously
bizarre groupings _ Ozzy Osbourne and Ol' Dirty Bastard? _ and
blast-from-the-past R&AMP;B nostalgia moments, as when Rick James and
Ike Turner hook up to sing ``Love Gravy.''
</P>
<P>
   And who more appropriate than Master P to revisit ``Freddie's
Dead,'' only now called ``Kenny's Dead,'' in homage to the
unfortunate South Parker whose sudden and often violent death is a
staple of each show?
</P>
<P>
   COMEDY
</P>
<P>
   ``Chef Aid: The South Park Album''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists.
</P>
<P>
   American/Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   21 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Cartoon album is no joke.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
