<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Old Dogs' wag some wicked tongues
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   First there was Nashville's Outlaws, then came the Highwaymen
and now come the Old Dogs: Waylon Jennings, Mel Tillis, Bobby Bare
and Jerry Reed. Their satirical concern is not growing gracefully
old, but of glibly defying age (``We can still bury a bone. . .''),
love (``She'd rather be homeless than here at home with me. . .'')
and changing musical mores (``Elvis has left the building and
you're stuck with me. . .'').
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, they take a few shots at Music City USA (``Nashville
is rough on the living, but she sure speaks well of the dead . .
.'') and reach the inevitable conclusion: They never expected to
live this long, but are ``Still Gonna Die.'' They're at their best
baying individually rather than attempting harmony, with Jennings
and Bare's sly styles meshing perfectly with lyricist Shel
Silverstein's wicked words. Radio may pass on these non-hunks'
humor, but country fans are sure to howl with them.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Old Dogs''
</P>
<P>
   Old Dogs. Atlantic. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Still howling after all these years.
</P>
<P>
   Russ DeVault writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
