<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIMUSIC-10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stars pay tribute to Burt Bacharach's mighty canon of elegant
pop hits
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton and Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``One Amazing Night''
</P>
<P>
   Burt Bacharach. N2K. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   This musical souvenir from a televised special that first aired
on TNT in April finds a bevy of past and present stars paying
tribute to Burt Bacharach's mighty canon of elegant pop hits. Not
many of them can pull off the sexy, swingin' '60s tone of the
songs. Sheryl Crow tentatively trips through ``One Less Bell to
Answer,'' while bimbo-pop vocal group All Saints completely
flattens ``Always Something There to Remind Me.'' But full-throated
crooners Chrissie Hynde and Wynonna nail the sumptuous ache of
``Baby It's You'' and ``Anyone Who Had a Heart,'' respectively.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Macha''
</P>
<P>
   Macha. Jetset. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Freshman efforts are rarely this confident and inventive. These
ingenious Athenians(Ga.) take Indonesian instruments (talempong
nipple gongs, anyone?), throw in the Germanic trance rock of '70s
pioneers Can and rock it up with the hard-hitting drums of Mischo
McKay. There are also hints of Chicago post-rock experimentalists
Tortoise and the anarchic pop of Brian Eno-era Roxy Music. From
these influences, McKay and multi-instrumentalists Joshua McKay
(Mischo's brother) and Kai Riedl have created a singular sound that
has sprung fully formed on their first release. Get a good seat on
this band's wagon now, because it's likely to get crowded.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton and Shane Harrison write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
