r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHESTNUTS-COMEBACK-TE     12-09 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHESTNUTS-COMEBACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CHESTNUTS FELL THROUGH THE CRACKS _ AND RETURNED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chestnut is back.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, the mighty chestnut was, if not the backbone, at
least one of the vertebrae of American food, both native and
Europeanized.
</P>
<P>
   Native Americans used the whole nuts as vegetables and also
ground them to make flour for bread. The Europeans who arrived
later cooked with the nuts in the same manner and also introduced a
sweetened paste version in desserts. In eastern America, the nuts
were harvested and used as a cash crop, shipped off to cities such
as New York, Boston and Philadelphia, where they were roasted, sold
by vendors and eaten right out of the shell.
</P>
<P>
   The trees, called ghost redwoods, were mammoth, averaging 5 feet
in diameter and up to 100 feet tall. But mighty as they were, the
trees _ along with the nuts that fed man and forest wildlife _
began to vanish.
</P>
<P>
   In 1904, the chestnut blight first appeared at the Bronx Zoo.
Imported Chinese chestnut trees carried a virulent bark fungus that
killed virtually all the native American chestnut trees. By 1950,
few remained.
</P>
<P>
   But now, in your very own supermarket, there the nuts are, in
among the pecans, the almonds and the cashews. Retailing for about
$4 a pound, chestnuts are starting to crack their way back into
American traditions. Most of the chestnuts we see in the
supermarkets are imported, but American growers are doing their
part to bring back the ``king of trees.'' The American Chestnut
Foundation is one operation promoting the planting of new
varieties.
</P>
<P>
   If chestnuts are new to you, here's what to look for. Shells
should have a little ``give.'' If the shell is firm, the chestnuts
may need to ripen longer.
</P>
<P>
   Store the nuts in the refrigerator or freezer. When they are
ready to cook, wipe off any dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnuts must be scored before cooking. To do this, make an
``X'' with a sharp knife on the flat side of the nut. (If you don't
do this, the nuts will explode when heated.)
</P>
<P>
   In the oven: Lay nuts in one layer in ovenproof dish. Bake at
325 degrees for about 20 minutes. Peel when cool to the touch.
</P>
<P>
   In the fireplace: Use a long-handled pan for roasting chestnuts,
or use a fireplace popcorn basket. Don't overcrowd pan. Shake the
pan as you would popcorn, and hold pan just above flame, not in it.
Nuts should be done in about 15 minutes, or when the outside shell
is black. Remove nuts from pan and peel as soon as they are cool to
the touch.
</P>
<P>
   On the stove top: Place nuts in one loose layer in a heavy pan _
cast-iron is best. Cook over medium heat while shaking the pan.
Cook until you can smell the nuts.
</P>
<P>
   AMISH CHESTNUT STUFFING
</P>
<P>
   Stuffs 18-pound turkey
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh chestnuts in shell
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup melted butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   4 cups bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 well-beaten eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons poultry seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   Wash chestnuts, make two slits on each shell and bake for 15
minutes at 475 degrees. Shell while still hot. Boil nuts in water
to cover for 20 minutes. Chop finely. Mix with the melted butter,
bread crumbs, salt, poultry seasoning, eggs and celery. Toss well.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 206 calories, 11 grams fat, 23
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 43 milligrams cholesterol,
583 milligrams sodium, 48 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Nut Factory Kitchen
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The equipment
</P>
<P>
   You don't need special equipment to roast chestnuts, but it
certainly brings a little extra glamour to the task.
</P>
<P>
   Sur La Table, a mail-order operation based in Seattle, has just
opened a store in Dallas. The store stocks chestnut roasting pans
(a metal skillet with holes in the bottom called a ``rotisseur
marron'' by the French) that sell for $9.95. Pick one up at 4527
Travis St., Suite A, in the Knox-Henderson retail district, (214)
219-4404, or order by calling (800) 243-0852.
</P>
<P>
   Williams-Sonoma also carries a chestnut cooker in its catalog.
The lidded stoneware roaster is meant for the oven and is packaged
with 2 pounds of chestnuts for $44. The roaster, sans nuts, is
$24.50. The company also sells a hooked knife for scoring the tough
nuts; it's $5. Call (800) 541-2233.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
