<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRADYSPEARS-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COWBOY'S HAUTE CUISINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AUTHORS: Grady Spears is the hometown boy who happens to be
executive chef at Fort Worth's celebrated Reata, the cowboy-cuisine
restaurant that has earned some mighty nice press this year from
Texas Monthly, Gourmet and other magazines. Spears was punching
cows at an area ranch before he stumbled into the restaurant
business about a decade ago, and he is poised to take his upscale
home-cooking concept to a Beverly Hills Reata next spring. Robb
Walsh is an Austin-based food writer who recently won a James Beard
Journalism Award and whose work is frequently seen in American Way
magazine and heard on NPR's ``Weekend Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   THE FORMAT: This beautiful 212-page hardback features stunning
photography by Marathon-based shooter James Evans, who offers
landscapes and personality portraits from West Texas, where Spears
discovered his passion for cooking. Lovely food pictures done by
Dallas photographer Dick Patrick make you want to cook up some of
Spears' spicy tomato soup and catfish cakes as quickly as possible.
Ten chapters of recipes range from ``Scorching a Steak'' and
``Chuck-Wagon Game Birds and Seafood'' to ``Ranch-House Soups and
Salads'' and ``Pies, Sweets, and Cowboy Coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Each chapter has an intro _ written in a folksy way, so reading
it is much like listening to Spears' friendly drawl _ that
describes how the chef observed and learned various cooking methods
taken from years of Texas traditions. But don't skip the main
introduction, Spears' genuine, aw-shucks reflection on his amazing
food career. Loath to take much credit for his own success, Spears
likewise credits Walsh for making the book work: ``Robb was the one
to put the puzzle together. I had no idea what I was doing _ and
still don't. I'm just lucky,'' Spears says.
</P>
<P>
   THE RECIPES: What's best about the recipes is that the
self-taught Spears made them user-friendly for the home cook; not
even the bock-battered quail with cider adobo looks threatening. As
often as possible, he has kept the ingredient list fairly short and
accessible, and there are never 15 or 20 steps in the directions.
The only hitch is in those occasional recipes that refer you to
other recipes for an ingredient, such as red chile sauce or roasted
shallots.
</P>
<P>
   THE AUDIENCE: Anyone who likes flavorful, hearty and fattening
foods _ Spears never met a stick of butter or jug of cream he
didn't add to a dish _ will have a ball with this book. And talk
about impressing dinner guests: Unless your friends have eaten at
Reata, they won't have experienced cornmeal-crusted oysters or
oven-roasted pork tenderloin with apple-poblano chutney.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO FIND THE BOOK: Spears says the book should be in
bookstores before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   YALLER BREAD WITH PINTOS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cooked pinto beans
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fresh corn kernels
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups fine yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup melted butter
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Combine buttermilk, eggs, sugar and
soda and mix well. Add beans and corn. Sift together the flour and
cornmeal. Slowly add flour mixture to liquids, whisking until
well-incorporated. Whisk in the melted butter. Pour the batter into
a greased 8-by-8 pan or cast-iron skillet and bake for 40 minutes,
or until a toothpick comes out clean.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 321 calories, 15 grams fat, 40
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 112 milligrams cholesterol,
295 milligrams sodium, 42 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   JALAPENO BEEF STEW
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   6 shallots, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 pound beef chuck, cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   4 jalapeno chiles, stemmed and seeded
</P>
<P>
   2 carrots, peeled and cut into 2-inch rounds
</P>
<P>
   1 large potato, peeled and cut into 2-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 red onion, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup port
</P>
<P>
   2 cups beef stock and 2 cups canned beef broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dried sage leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dried oregano leaves
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt to taste; freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Toss shallots with olive oil, place
them in a small pan, and toast them in the oven for 35 minutes or
until they are soft and brown. Heat butter in a large, deep
saucepan (one that has a cover) over medium heat. While the butter
is melting, toss beef cubes with flour to coat. Place beef in hot
butter, increase the heat, and saute the cubes on all sides for 5
minutes for rare and longer for more well-done. Do not crowd the
meat, or it will steam rather than brown. Remove the pan from the
heat, transfer meat to a bowl, cover it loosely with foil to keep
it warm, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Mince the jalapenos. Place pan over medium heat, and in the
remaining butter, saute chiles, carrots, potato and onion, tossing
to prevent burning, until onions turn translucent. Add the wine,
stock or broth, sage and oregano, stirring gently on the bottom of
the pan to release any solidified pan juices. Cook stew over low
heat, with the lid slightly ajar, for 40 minutes. Add the reserved
shallots and the beef, stir to combine, and continue cooking for an
additional 20 minutes. Test to see if meat and vegetables are done.
Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 476 calories, 25 grams fat, 30
grams carbohydrates, 33 grams protein, 125 milligrams cholesterol,
100 milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``A Cowboy in the Kitchen''
</P>
<P>
   By Grady Spears and Robb Walsh
</P>
<P>
   Ten Speed Press, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
