A1072 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-SOUNDTRACK10-CO     12-09 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-SOUNDTRACK10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Bug's Life' leads soundtrack parade
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the advent of movies as big-screen jukeboxes in the early
1980s (``Flashdance,'' ``The Big Chill'') cinematic scores have
given way to hit parades (really, a new kind of product placement).
The latest batch of ``original soundtrack'' albums has arrived, and
one _ composer Randy Newman's charming score for ``A Bug's Life''
(Walt Disney, 20 tracks) _ is, actually, original. More typical is
the sugary oldies revue of ``You've Got Mail'' (Warner
Sunset/Atlantic, 15 tracks), with puppy-cute fluff from Harry
Nilsson, Bobby Darin and Jimmy Durante to match puppy-cute stars
Meg Ryan and Tom Hanks. . . . Adam Sandler's puppy-cute, too, but
he's not housebroken, so the soundtrack for ``The Waterboy''
(Hollywood, 13 tracks) rocks out like a frat row beer blast with
tunes from Joe Walsh, Rush, Creedence Clearwater Revival and the
Doors . . . The murderous new theme for the remake of ``Psycho''
(Geffen, 14 tracks) is twisted tunesmith Danny Elfman's winking
homage to Hitchcock composer Bernard Herrmann. The ironic tone is
constant (remakes of ``Psycho Killer'' and the spooky country
ballad ``Psycho''). Best track is Steve Earle's haunting ``All of
My Life.'' . . . Tunes from the British art film ``Little Voice''
(Capitol, 11 tracks) revel in show-biz camp and brassy melodrama, a
reminder of the days when divas (Judy Garland, Billie Holiday)
really were.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
