<HEADER>
A1111 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NEWYORK-1000&AMP;     12-09 1498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NEWYORK-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 WRITING NEW YORK
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Literary Anthology.
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Phillip Lopate.
</P>
<P>
   1,050 pp. New York: The Library of America. $40.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; EIGHT MILLION STORIES
</P>
<P>
   BY GARRISON KEILLOR
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Wherever you go in New York, you are walking through somebody's
literary turf. If I hike over to Central Park, I pass through Isaac
Bashevis Singer's neighborhood and the site of Poe's cottage and go
by the hotel where Holden Caulfield sat on the bed with the
prostitute and the building on 78th Street near Amsterdam Avenue
where Sister Carrie lived with Hurstwood, her paramour, before she
rose in society and he fell. In the park I breathe in a rich
fragrance richly described by John Cheever and look down the
horsepaths of ``The Age of Innocence'' toward the buildings of
Fitzgerald's 59th Street (``my lost city, wrapped cool in its
mystery and promise'') and think of E. B. White's saying, that New
York bestows ``the gift of privacy, the jewel of loneliness.''
</P>
<P>
   So many great writers have lived here, their homes cannot be set
aside as museums: they are needed for housing. Everyone came
through town, even Thoreau, who spent a few months on Staten Island
in 1843. He rode the ferry to Manhattan, hoping to interest editors
in his work; he thought New York ``a thousand times meaner than I
could have imagined. It will be something to hate -- that's the
advantage it will be to me.'' He failed to interest anyone, he got
homesick and left town grumping about the crowds: ``It must have a
very bad influence on children to see so many human beings at once
-- mere herds of men.''
</P>
<P>
   In Phillip Lopate's excellent anthology, ``Writing New York,''
you get writers who love crowds and writers who hang out alone and
brood, the diaries of businessmen and homages to ``the sweet slums
of Bohemia and beatnikdom, where sunflowers and morning glories
would bloom on fire escapes in the summer and old ladies weighed
down by breasts leaned on goosedown pillows in windows,
self-appointed guardians of the street'' (from Joyce Johnson, who
``sat up till dawn in Rappaport's, where they gave you a whole
basket of rolls free, drinking coffee with a jazz trombonist from
St. Louis and a poet just arrived from Chicago''). And Elizabeth
Hardwick on Billie Holiday: ``The sheer enormity of her vices. The
outrageousness of them. . . . Her ruthless talent and the opulent
devastation.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry James looks dimly at the ``vast bristling promontory'' of
Manhattan, where ``the shores are low and for the most part
depressingly furnished and prosaically peopled,'' and fusses about
the impermanence and commercialness of it all, and A. J. Liebling,
a sociable fellow from 93rd Street and Lexington, sees impermanence
as a civic virtue: ``It is one of the oldest places in the United
States, but doesn't live in retrospect like the professionally
picturesque provinces,'' he says. ``Any city may have one period of
magnificence, like Boston or New Orleans or San Francisco, but it
takes a real one to keep renewing itself until the past is
perennially forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   The gassiest of the city's admirers may have been Lewis Mumford,
hiking across the Brooklyn Bridge, observing the skyscrapers
against the sky and the river below, the ferryboats, the tramp
steamers -- ``And there was I, breasting the March wind, drinking
in the city and the sky, both vast, yet both contained in me,
transmitting through me the great mysterious will that had made
them and the promise of the new day that was still to come.''
</P>
<P>
   O.K. Whatever you say, pal. Contain as much of the sky as you
like. What really shines in this anthology isn't the literary set
pieces but the journalism, from Poe's column about a 10-mile foot
race in front of 11,000 spectators in May 1844, won by a man named
Stannard in 1 hour 4 minutes 3 seconds for a $300 purse, to Alfred
Kazin's memoir of Brownsville and Joseph Mitchell rambling around
the Fulton Fish Market at 5:30 in the morning and Joan Didion on
her way home: ``I remember sitting in a lot of apartments with a
slight headache about 5 o'clock in the morning. I had a friend who
could not sleep, and he knew a few other people who had the same
trouble, and we would watch the sky lighten and have a last drink
with no ice and then go home in the early morning light, when the
streets were clean and wet (had it rained in the night? we never
knew) and the few cruising taxis had their headlights on and the
only color was the red and green of traffic signals.''
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising journals are those from a city long
disappeared, from when cows were pastured on Bowling Green and pigs
ran loose and Wall Street was a ``narrow thoroughfare, baking and
blistering in the sun'' and the English actress Fanny Kemble ruled
the stage and merchants and lawyers streamed into the eating houses
for lunch, where a barker stood in the doorway and chanted:
</P>
<P>
   ``Biledlamancapersors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rosebeefrosegoorosemuttonantaters --
</P>
<P>
   ``Biledamancabbage, vegetables --
</P>
<P>
   ``Walkinsirtakaseatsir.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is Grant Thorburn of 22 Nassau Street, a grocer who began
selling potted plants and found that they sold better if he painted
the pots green. Here is Miss Kemble, writing, ``The women here . .
. ripen very early and decay proportionally soon. They are,
generally speaking, pretty, with good complexions, and an air of
freshness, but this I am told is very evanescent.'' And here is the
Wall Street lawyer George Templeton Strong, writing in 1851: ``I'm
sadly vulgarized and degraded of late by the itching for money that
has come over me. Oh, for $100,000 -- well invested! A skillful
operation resulting in an enormous profit with no risk has all the
charm for me now of poetry or romance.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-NEWYORK-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: romance.'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The diaries of Strong and his contemporary Philip Hone provide
such clear accounts of early 19th-century New York as to make the
literary wits of their day unreadable by comparison. Try to read
the whinnying of the great Washington Irving and then check out
Hone's diary entry for Saturday, Dec. 8, 1838, when he and family
and guests are eating dinner and a week-old infant boy is left in a
basket on the doorstep, the name ``Alfred G. Douglas'' written on a
label pinned to his muslin frock. Hone reports on the autumn
foliage, a concert by Ole Bull, a charity ball, the Astor Place
riots, the rebuilding of Trinity Church, the death of his wife. He
observes John Jacob Astor, worth $15 million, sitting at dinner,
mumbling, drooling, fed by a servant -- ``a painful example of the
insufficiency of wealth to prolong the life of man.'' Hone is
chairman of the committee that plans the reception in 1842 to
welcome Mr. Charles Dickens (``a small, bright-eyed,
intelligent-looking young fellow, 30 years of age, somewhat of a
dandy in his dress'') and is pleased that all goes well, all except
the coat-check operation: Hone trudges home hatless and coatless on
a February night.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman gazed on it from the Brooklyn ferry, ``mast-hemm'd
Manhattan,'' and Poe rowed a skiff along Roosevelt Island to look
at the Manhattan shore, ``the magnificent cliffs, and stately
trees'' that he knew would be soon replaced by warehouses and
wharves. Maxim Gorky, looking across the harbor, saw a city
quivering like a mirage, ``a fantastic city all of fire. . . .
Thousands of ruddy sparks glimmer in the darkness.'' Helen Keller
took a boat around Manhattan and her companions spelled into her
hand the names of boats, Bella, Floradora, Rosalind, Pearl of the
Deep, Minnehaha, Sister Nell. Dawn Powell looked down from the
Empire State Building and saw ``a garden of golden lights winking
on and off, automobiles, trucks winding in and out, and not a
sound. All as silent as a dead city -- it looks adagio down
there.'' Fitzgerald saw it from a ship sailing up the Hudson at
early dusk, ``the white glacier of lower New York . . . a miracle
of foamy light suspended by the stars.'' And the Englishman Stephen
Graham saw it in 1927 as we all see it, on foot: ``It is 5 A.M.
Something of the burden of the city has been lifted. The air is
light. The heart seems freed. I feel happy to be walking. I love
the space and the quietness. I have got rid of the idea of going to
bed, got rid of the routine of daily life. New York and its
millions, its wealth, its mysteries, are mine. There is a sense of
conquest. The bustle has died down and I am still walking. The
majority of people are asleep -- but I am not the least sleepy. It
seems as if life has just begun.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Garrison Keillor is the author of ``Wobegon Boy'' and the
creator of ``A Prairie Home Companion.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1633EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1112 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SHERIDAN-1000     12-09 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SHERIDAN-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 A TRAITOR'S KISS
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Life of Richard Brinsley Sheridan, 1751-1816.
</P>
<P>
   By Fintan O'Toole.
</P>
<P>
   519 pp. New York: Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $30.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; IN THE WINGS
</P>
<P>
   BY SARAH KERR
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Brinsley Sheridan (1751-1816) is one of those attractive
but vague figures, remembered for vastly different events that add
up to -- well, what they add up to is fascinating, but not at all
clear. Two centuries after Sheridan's heyday in London, his fame
rests mostly on the comedies he wrote as a young man. ``The School
for Scandal'' and ``The Rivals'' are hilarious, perfect little
exposes of base aristocrats, lying journalists and moralists
without moral cores. Yet by the author's own admission the plays
were a mere stepping stone, a bid for money and social cachet to
help him pursue his real passion. Sheridan was elected to
Parliament in 1780 and rose to the very top ranks as a reformer
within the Whig party. These were the fabled glory days of English
political rhetoric, and for a while Sheridan No. 2, the politician,
outshined his illustrious colleagues Charles James Fox and Edmund
Burke as the best orator in the land.
</P>
<P>
   The journey from facile golden boy to persuasive liberal
statesman is hard enough to trace. The real challenge for
Sheridan's biographer is to fit those first two acts with a very
different third. Later in life Sheridan became a laughingstock,
famous not for his way with words but for his notorious debts, his
desperate sucking up to patrons and, most embarrassing of all, his
bright red drinker's nose. This Sheridan lost most of his money and
all of his pride. When he died, London gossip pronounced that he'd
ended up a pauper, with hardly a chair left for furniture.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think some consolidation of the three Sheridans would be
in order, but in ``A Traitor's Kiss,'' Fintan O'Toole takes the
bold and, in the end, pretty convincing step of introducing a
long-ignored fourth Sheridan into the mix. No. 4 was born in
Dublin, and O'Toole believes that through all his later ups and
downs Sheridan remained, first and foremost, an Irishman. When he
wrote plays, Irishness was the outsider's point of view that
supplied the double-entendres. When he entered politics, Ireland's
plight fed his sympathy with oppressed pawns of colonialism and
with humble people everywhere who lived under laws that failed to
serve them. His torn allegiances, as a Protestant high up in the
British Government who thought the Irish had been given a raw deal,
drove him to seek a humane compromise. But this position was
lonely, irksome to enemies across the political spectrum and hard
on his nerves.
</P>
<P>
   We're speaking somewhat rhetorically here, of a sentimental
rather than a concrete patriotism, since Sheridan left Ireland for
English boarding school at 11, never to return. But O'Toole makes a
good case for the Irish question's powerful resonance within the
Sheridan clan; one 17th-century ancestor got swept up in a quixotic
effort to refashion Protestantism for the Irish language. And
Sheridan appears to have suffered one of those awful childhoods
that lead to nostalgia in the adult. As a boy he was sickly,
neglected by his family and teased by his peers for his father's
low profession as an actor and theater manager. (Theater then was a
guilty pleasure, enjoyed but frowned upon, rather like the
contemporary talk show.)
</P>
<P>
   At first Sheridan channeled his hunger for love, status and
vindication into romantic mischief, eloping with a well-known
singer, casting himself (falsely, O'Toole implies) as her protector
from an unwanted suitor and provoking two duels. Our instant
celebrities shop around for book contracts; Sheridan moved to cash
in on his 15 minutes by writing plays. O'Toole is a theater critic
for The Daily News in New York, and he's insightful about the
social atmosphere of the 18th-century stage: the rowdy informality
that sometimes climaxed in a riot, the barely camouflaged gossip,
the minor but suggestive fact that the lights didn't go down before
a show, which made the audience feel like full-fledged participants
in the entertainment. O'Toole has less to say about the plays
themselves, but it could be that Sheridan's plays, while close to
flawless, don't bear much talking about except to acknowledge that
their author was a comic wizard. I was constantly reminded, reading
this book, that the 1700's predate the 1800's. That is to say,
before the Romantics arrived, literature tended to be an arena of
wit, intrigue and idealized lovers -- of rhetoric more than
conflict or ambiguity. O'Toole dutifully looks for unplumbed depths
in some of Sheridan's strongest characters, like the vicious prude
Joseph Surface or the confused Mrs. Malaprop. Trotting out a little
rhetoric of his own of the jargony academic type, O'Toole argues
that Sheridan's constant awareness of the untrustworthiness of
language led inevitably to his lonely, radical choices in politics.
</P>
<P>
   But is the road from satire to politics really so straight? A
contemporary of Sheridan's named Jane Austen possessed as fine an
ear for linguistic untrustworthiness as has ever existed, but in
political terms she was a conventional Tory. Besides, while most
satirists are out to expose some ugly truth, Sheridan was the rare
humorist who dreamed of a kinder, gentler world. He could be as
sentimental, and as ruthlessly persuasive, as a Disney song. His
most celebrated speech, charging the Governor General of India with
corruption and brutality, was a classic of the 18th-century cult of
sensibility and by all accounts a show-biz masterpiece -- a
five-hour torrent of facts, unanswerable accusations and tugs at
the heartstrings that were achingly sincere, and utterly shameless.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-SHERIDAN-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: shameless.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Away from the podium, his politicking was rougher around the
edges. A maverick within his own party, he fatally allied himself
with the fickle, selfish Prince Regent. His position grew even
trickier in the repressive 1790's, when his defense of the Irish,
and of basic civil liberties like habeas corpus, opened him to
charges of treachery. Was his thinking on Ireland a lost model for
an enlightened Third Way, a course of nonsectarian compromise, as
O'Toole -- again indulging in a little rhetoric -- seems to imply?
Absolutely, but then again, not quite. Sheridan's heart was in the
right place, but even at the height of his power his political
method was too compromised by social climbing and pipe-dream
idealism to apply usefully to today. After his first wife died, he
compromised himself even more. His drinking stood out in an era in
which it was hard to stand out for drinking. When an aristocratic
lady broke off an affair with him, a combination of depression and
class rage sent him off on a pathetic campaign of harassment that
today would put him on trial as a stalker.
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying it: Sheridan had his weak spots. (Or, as
Byron once put it, after recalling all Sheridan's gifts, ``But
alas, poor human nature!'') Still, the decline was not wholly his
fault. O'Toole's very moving point is that as an Irishman, Sheridan
was doomed to remain on the fringes; as a self-made man he found no
home in the rigid upper reaches of English power. The irony is that
when Sheridan died, his Irishness was put away in the closet. His
plays were safely absorbed into a harmless pageant of English comic
literature. His irresponsibility was greatly exaggerated, and his
glittering wordplay and rakish reputation made him seem like the
prototype of the feckless English fop.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the lesson of Sheridan's life, it helps to look
not at his politics but back at his plays. Elites close ranks to
resist outsiders, they told us. People in power aid people in
power, and society runs on lies. In the plays, the message was
comic, with the happiest of endings. In life, it proved
depressingly real.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Kerr is a regular contributor to Slate, an Internet
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
