A1113 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BALLS-NYTSF     12-09 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BALLS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BALLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Nanci Kincaid.
</P>
<P>
   396 pp. Chapel Hill, N.C.:
</P>
<P>
   Algonquin Books of Chapel Hill. $21.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; PIGSKIN WIDOW
</P>
<P>
   BY ERICA SANDERS
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Gibbs may be blond and pretty, she may have a smile for
everyone and give a successful after-game party, but as the wife of
the head coach of the Birmingham Black Bears, she is a flawed
individual. She doesn't care much for football. She doesn't even
know the rules. In Alabama that is plenty cause for suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   The wife of Dick Tomey, the head coach of the University of
Arizona Wildcats, Nanci Kincaid knows the rules, and for her
carefully constructed second novel she has recruited a shadow team
of wives, mothers, sisters and girlfriends to recount the lonely
and frustrating life on the sidelines. Kincaid also knows her
readers, which is why, despite its drolly macho title, ``Balls'' is
about women and marriage as much as it is an insider's view of a
college football recruiting scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Dixie, the main character, grew up in ``HamU'' country, the
local handle for fictitious Birmingham University. In high school,
she vowed to marry a football player and picked the star
quarterback, Mac. Years later, she and their two children stand by
as he accepts the head coach's mantle from his mentor, Catfish
Bomar. It is the end of an era. The fans and money people all
expect Mac to carry on the winning tradition. By then, Dixie, still
a dispassionate spectator, has figured out the game: football comes
before marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Dixie's first teacher is the big-hearted Leeta Sparks, who works
two jobs so her husband, Hemp, can pursue his first love, coaching
high school football. When the newlywed Dixie asks Leeta if she
still loves Hemp, she says, ``I love him the same way I love my
kids,'' because, Leeta thinks to herself, ``any other answer would
half kill her.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a more seasoned Dixie who meets the ambitious Romalee May,
the defensive coordinator's wife at HamU. During games, Romalee, a
former Miss Georgia, talks strategy and player histories while
Dixie is content to scan the crowd. But as Dixie observes,
``Romalee's experiential expertise lasts only until the rum and
Coke she's sipping sets her free from it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a luncheon, Catfish Bomar's wife, Celeste, a ghoulish
augur, boozily declares about her husband: ``He's killing me. I am
one step closer to dead every . . . football season.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Dixie, her marriage has evolved into a chilly union. Mac
canceled their first vacation to play golf. He missed his son's
first steps and first words. During the season, Mac is gone before
Dixie wakes and comes home after she is asleep. Off-season, he
travels on recruiting trips, and summer weekends he spends on the
links. When she asks him to attend a reading of a short story she's
written, he answers, ``I'll just wait until the movie comes out.''
Dixie's forbearance, however, is maddening. One minute she is
pricked with rage, the next she is in awe, comparing Mac to Jesus
``casting his net into the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid cleverly mines the small moments to communicate Dixie's
deepening sadness. A car ride home becomes symbolic of the journey
of her marriage. The mood is celebratory: Mac has just been named
head coach. Dixie is exuberant because they have realized their
dreams. Then she sees it's a success she had no part in creating.
</P>
<P>
   It's an obvious conclusion that these women are mad -- and
cynical -- as hell. Ultimately they are outsiders. When the illegal
inducements Mac doled out to recruits are made public, Dixie learns
of his resignation in the newspaper. Though painstakingly
developed, the characters do not have enough to do except watch and
talk. Divided into short chapters, the book is narrated in the
first person from 18 different perspectives. Kincaid loses time by
reorienting the reader with each shift, which prevents her from
telling her story. And what of these rogue spouses? The husbands
are the supposed focus here, but they are relegated to the
background. Like the wives, readers are left sitting on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Erica Sanders, a freelance writer living in New York, is
completing a novel.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
