<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1120 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MOVIES-1000&AMP;A     12-09 1505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MOVIES-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MOVIES AND MONEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   By David Puttnam with Neil Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 337 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf. $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; ONE PICTURE WAS WORTH A MILLION BUCKS
</P>
<P>
   BY BERNARD WEINRAUB
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It was two tough and strong-willed sons of an Italian immigrant
farmer from the Santa Clara Valley near San Jose, Calif., who
revolutionized the movie business. The time was 1906. The young
men, the bankers Amadeo Peter Giannini and his brother Attilio,
made a $100 loan to Sol Lesser, a 17-year-old nickelodeon owner who
needed the money to pay for the delivery of a film. (Lesser later
became one of the major exhibitors in California.) Over the next
few years, the Giannini brothers expanded their business with
several other movie companies and began to develop relationships
with some of the most powerful men in the fledgling industry. ``The
Gianninis were the first bankers to recognize the motion picture
business as a legitimate industry,'' David Puttnam writes in
``Movies and Money.'' He adds, ``The extent of the affinity between
the Gianninis and the pioneers of the movie colony was
extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giannini brothers are two of the lesser-known, if colorful,
figures in a sober book about the movie business that struggles to
deal with several overlapping themes: the birth of the film
industry and the rivalries among the early innovators; the
inevitable and long-running collision between art and commerce;
Hollywood's hegemony over European films and the sometimes angry,
sometimes silly intellectual posturing in which European (mostly
French) filmmakers sputter about all those beastly American values
polluting Continental shores. (Jean-Luc Godard claimed that his
struggle against Hollywood's commercial imperialism was analogous
to the workers' struggle against capitalism. But as Puttnam points
out, Godard was forced to concede that ``workers don't come to see
my films.'')
</P>
<P>
   Puttnam is now Lord Puttnam, one of Tony Blair's life peers. He
is also an Oscar-winning producer, responsible for such impressive
films as ``Chariots of Fire,'' ``Midnight Express,'' ``Local
Hero,'' ``The Killing Fields'' and ``The Mission.'' But in
Hollywood Puttnam is best known for his tumultuous 15-month reign
in 1986-87 as chairman and chief executive officer of Columbia
Pictures, then owned by Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   No studio head had challenged so many top producers, agents and
movie stars in such a short period of time. Puttnam contended more
than a decade ago that the costs of filmmaking were out of control,
that movie stars were treated like spoiled children and that
studios had yielded too much power to agents and producers. He may
have had a tendency to pontificate and, surprisingly, never quite
understood Hollywood's rules of behavior, which fall somewhere
between ``The Godfather'' and a Kabuki drama. But he was right.
</P>
<P>
   If only Puttnam had used ``Movies and Money'' to explore those
turbulent months when he tangled with Ray Stark, Michael Ovitz,
Dustin Hoffman, Bill Murray and numerous others. What happened?
What did he learn? Instead, Puttnam vaguely addresses his Hollywood
tenure: ``Many factors contributed to my eventual departure,'' he
remarks. With the kind of stiff-upper-lip reticence that seems
entirely uncharacteristic of the author, he says that ``it became a
conflict between two differing ideas of cinema which, in some ways,
seemed to be at the heart of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this reticence is symptomatic of a sometimes
dramatic, sometimes thoughtful and often ambiguous book (written
with Neil Watson), one that is based on a series of lectures
Puttnam gave in Berlin in 1994 and at Oxford University one year
later. ``Movies and Money'' leaps only sporadically from its
academic roots, and rarely makes the movie business any more alive
-- or zany -- than the insurance business. In fact, it starts
pulsing only at midpoint, when Puttnam deals with the eccentric and
often brilliant moguls of the 1930's and 40's, like Irving
Thalberg, Louis B. Mayer, Darryl Zanuck and David O. Selznick.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the stories may be old, but they're priceless. Like Jack
Warner telling Albert Einstein, who was visiting the studio,
``Well, professor, I have a theory of relatives too -- don't hire
'em.'' Or Harry Cohn betting his brother Jack $50 that he couldn't
recite the Lord's Prayer. Jack started, ``Now I lay me down to
sleep. . . .'' Harry interrupted and gave him the money. ``That's
enough -- I really didn't realize you knew it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Puttnam observes shrewdly, ``if there was one thing
that bound the bosses together, moguls and production chiefs alike,
it was their passion for gambling. Cards, horses, roulette --
despite their cultural differences gambling became an all-embracing
passion.'' He goes on, ``It was hardly surprising that such men
should find their natural home in a high-risk business like the
movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Puttnam seems less interested in moguls, though, than in the
unresolvable debate over whether movies are an art or merely a
commodity like cars or jeans. His focal point is the contentious
1993 trade talks between the Clinton Administration and Hollywood
on one side and many European countries on the other. The Americans
wanted films to trade freely like any other manufactured goods. The
Europeans objected, believing that their own industries would
collapse under the weight of all those Sylvester Stallone and Bruce
Willis movies. The issue, which is, of course, about American
culture dominating Europe, was left stalemated.
</P>
<P>
   As Puttnam observes, the conflicting visions of filmmaking --
and filmmakers -- date back to the birth of the business. ``The
physical and intellectual remoteness of Los Angeles from the rest
of America, combined with the feelings of hope and optimism
engendered by the California sunshine, all played a part in shaping
the distinctive ethos of Hollywood cinema,'' he writes. ``The
situation was very different in Europe, where filmmaking was
overwhelmingly concentrated in Berlin, London, Paris and Rome --
cities that were also centers of traditional culture. Consequently,
in Europe there was far more interaction between the film community
and those involved with theater and literature.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-MOVIES-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: literature.'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In short, although European directors and producers have
naturally wanted to make money, their film tradition was often far
more intellectual, and suffused with a cultural lineage missing in
Hollywood. Unfortunately for them, Hollywood films, with their
fantasy and sheer entertainment value, have dwarfed European
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Puttnam sides with the Europeans, but only up to a point. ``It
is frankly dangerous to allow Hollywood's extraordinary dominance
in the field of filmed entertainment to go on intensifying,'' he
writes. Films and television, he says, shape attitudes, reinforce
or undermine values. Yet he also points out that film audiences
abroad have all but fled from locally made films; American movies
account for at least 80 percent of the box office across most of
the Continent. One of the reasons, he explains, is that ``European
filmmakers have on occasion, most notably in the late 1960's and
1970's, displayed varying degrees of irresponsibility toward their
financial backers, and something approaching contempt toward the
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   PUTTNAM'S conclusions are blurry. He suggests that the Europeans
should probably forget about competing head on with Hollywood
because ``Americans understand, better than anyone else, how to
produce and market films, just as the Germans make cars, the French
make perfume and the Scots make whisky.'' He raises the idea that
Europeans should focus more on new technologies in information and
education.
</P>
<P>
   While he seems unmistakably ambivalent about the studio system,
Puttnam clearly admires the men who created it: ``Whatever else
happened to them, they were determined to have the priceless sense
of security that came from wealth and power. That was why, when it
came to fighting for overseas markets, they found it so easy to put
aside all the personal hatreds, their internecine rivalries and
their quarrels over talent. Cinema might aspire to become an art
form or be a wonderful vehicle for the dissemination of political
and ethical values, but finally it was a business like any other.''
</P>
<P>
   American movies were built on what Puttnam terms the twin
pillars of investment and profit. ``The Europeans,'' he declares,
``never really seemed prepared to address these obvious and simple
realities.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Weinraub covers entertainment for The New York Times in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
