 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Thursday, Dec. 10. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Tim Hilchey (E-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com); phone:
(888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET (London) _ Britain's Home Secretary Wednesday turned
down Gen. Augusto Pinochet's plea to be set free, ruling that a
Spanish extradition case against the former Chilean dictator can
could go forward in English courts. The 83-year-old general now
faces an indefinite stay in England and must appear Friday at a
hearing on a Spanish petition to have him stand trial in Madrid on
charges of crimes against humanity. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ARMS (United Nations) _ U.N. inspectors are stymied in
Baghdad, dropping a plan to enter a building after Iraqis demand
written list of what they're looking for. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-STUDENTS (Jerusalem) _ In a landmark ruling, the Israeli
Supreme Court says that yeshiva students are not exempt from
military service. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SAFRICA-FOSSIL (Undated) _ In a discovery that may answer
some of the ``missing-link'' questions of human evolution,
scientists in South Africa have found what they describe as the
best preserved and most complete skull and skeleton yet seen of a
very early member of the human family tree. The specimen is older
and much more complete than the famous ``Lucy'' skeleton found in
Ethiopia in 1974. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Republicans on the House Judiciary
Committee are expected to unveil four articles of impeachment
against President Clinton Wednesday evening, charging him with
perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse of power, just minutes
after the White House counsel wraps up the two-day defense of the
President. By Eric Schmitt. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-DEFENSE (Washington) _ The President's top lawyer
conceded Wednesday to Judiciary Committee Republicans that
``reasonable people'' may conclude that the president lied in the
Monica Lewinsky matter. In a final, point-by-point defense before
committee members, Charles F.C. Ruff, the White House counsel,
insisted Clinton's testimony did not amount to perjury because the
president believed it to be true _ albeit misleading. By James
Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-POLITICS (Washington) _ When Rep. J. Hyde proclaimed in
September that the impeachment of a president could not succeed
unless it was bipartisan, Republicans expected the Monica Lewinsky
scandal to fracture the Democratic party. Instead the issue is
driving a wedge through the Republican party, with some moderates
charging that impeachment fever could imperil them and their
congressional majority. A news analysis by Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER WASHINGTON &LR;  (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-POLLUTION (Washington) _ The Better Business Bureau said
Wednesday that the nuclear industry has been lying by claiming in
advertisements that nuclear power makes electricity without
polluting the air or water.The finding contradicts the central
argument that the nuclear industry has made in the last few years
to justify its existence. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-LOITERING (Washington) _ In a spirited Supreme Court
argument Wednesday, the city of Chicago defended an anti-loitering
law that permits arrests not only suspected gang members but anyone
else who, standing with ``no apparent purpose'' on a public street
near a gang member, defies a police order to move on. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-YOUTH (Undated) _ Several new studies are calling into
question whether the surge in juvenile crime in the late 1980s was
the result of a dangerous new class of juvenile ``superpredators''
and whether the spate of tough new state laws to try teenagers as
adults was justified. The new studies show that the major change in
the late 1980's was that virtually all the tripling in juvenile
homicides were in crimes committed with handguns. By Fox
Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEAT-EXTREMES (Undated) _ Extreme summer heat and humidity
of the kind most threatening to health have become more frequent in
the United States over the last half century, two Federal
researchers are reporting in Thursday's issue of the journal
Nature. By Stevens. With Graphic.
</P>
