<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1122 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LION-NYTSF     12-09 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LION-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 IF A LION COULD TALK
<TEXT>
<P>
   Animal Intelligence and the Evolution of Consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen Budiansky.
</P>
<P>
   219 pp. New York: The Free Press. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; STUPID LION TRICKS
</P>
<P>
   BY JERRY A. COYNE
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A premier tourist attraction of Edinburgh is a statue of
Greyfriars Bobby, arguably the most famous dog in British history.
In 1856 John Gray, a Scottish constable, acquired this small Skye
terrier as a working pet. Two years later Gray died, and until his
own death 14 years after, Bobby kept a constant vigil at his
master's grave.
</P>
<P>
   Sentimental Victorians, touched by the dog's loyalty and hopeful
that they would be remembered, made him a national celebrity.
Bobby's tale has spawned several movies and dozens of books,
obviously plucking a deep emotional chord.
</P>
<P>
   Valuing animals in proportion to their apparent possession of
human emotions and mentality is the subject of ``If a Lion Could
Talk,'' an extended critique of anthropomorphism in animal behavior
research.
</P>
<P>
   According to Stephen Budiansky, a writer for The Atlantic
Monthly, professional biologists are almost as sentimental as the
admirers of Bobby, a trait that has produced dozens of flawed and
biased studies showing that animals, particularly primates, have
emotions, intellect and consciousness similar in kind if not in
degree to those of humans.
</P>
<P>
   He abhors such work because it yields false scientific
conclusions and buttresses the political agenda of ``animal-rights
advocates and New Age mystics,'' who base their ethics on the
similarity between humans and animals. He takes on many areas of
behavioral science infected by anthropomorphism, including
communication, navigation, intelligence and consciousness. Although
the descriptions and dissections of experiments are occasionally
confusing, they form a lively summary of the problems inherent in
this field (his analyses of animal ``counting'' and the use of sign
language by apes are particularly absorbing, while the discussion
of honeybee navigation is less successful).
</P>
<P>
   Budiansky sees three major problems with such research. First,
experimental designs are often flawed, as in the famous case of
Clever Hans, the counting horse whose ``mathematical abilities''
resulted from unconscious cues given by credulous onlookers.
Similar cues have cast doubt on studies of sign language in apes as
proof of their semantic abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Second, some reports of animal emotion or intelligence could
merely be human misinterpretations of simple learning by
association. Casting a cold eye on Greyfriars Bobby, one might say
that he felt neither love nor bereavement, but, like a Skinnerian
pigeon pecking in vain for a tidbit, showed only a conditioned
response (association with his master) that gave rewards in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, some supposed signs of animal consciousness may be only
evolved responses that do not involve subjective feelings. When I
poke an earthworm with a stick, does it recoil because it feels
pain, or merely because stimulating the proper nerves produces an
automatic (and adaptive) response?
</P>
<P>
   The main problems with Budiansky's own conclusions are clear to
those familiar with the scientific literature. The author makes
seemingly devastating and unrebutted attacks on experiments, but in
reality many of these studies seem quite credible. Budiansky, for
example, dismisses with withering scorn the use of mirrors by apes
as evidence for self-awareness, but many of his criticisms have
been answered already.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, his citation of ``the total failure of experiments to
support the idea that monkeys or apes are capable of imitation'' is
a gross distortion: recent work shows that apes may indeed perform
complex acts by imitating others. Conversely, the evolutionary
origins of some behaviors --such as ``alarm calls'' produced by
animals when they see a predator -- are still under debate, but
Budiansky writes as if the final answers are known. He does his
readers no favor by purveying such simplified and one-sided views.
</P>
<P>
   Budiansky concludes that work on animal intelligence is futile,
and that we should simply respect and treasure species as unique
products of natural selection. To a biologist this seems better
than valuing animals for their human qualities, although it does
not tell us whether it is acceptable to eat oysters but not veal.
</P>
<P>
   I am not convinced, however, that a few flawed studies negate
the whole venture of seeking the roots of human behavior by
studying our relatives. Comparative work on primates has given
valuable clues about the evolution of some human traits, and there
is no reason why well-designed work could not shed light on our
emotions and intellect.
</P>
<P>
   By far the book's biggest failing is the confusion and
contradiction imbuing the discussion of animal consciousness, which
occupies but one scant chapter. Budiansky simply finesses this
complex problem by defining consciousness in a way that limits it
to humans. Although virtually all philosophers of mind agree that
consciousness is the capacity to have subjective experience (e.g.,
to feel pain or pleasure), Budiansky's definition is ``the ability
to have thoughts about thoughts -- 'secondary representations' or
'meta-representations' '' -- in a word, to think about one's
motivations and to fathom the motivations and desires of others. He
admits that this requires the ability to think symbolically --
``language is so intimately tied to consciousness that the two seem
inseparable.'' Since only humans (but not infants!) have language,
only humans can be conscious. Moreover, he gives a controversial
scenario for the evolution of consciousness, suggesting that it
``may have been an adaptive strategy precisely because it provided
the material for speculating about the thoughts (and thus the
motives) of others.'' But such selection could operate on any
highly social animal, whether or not it has language. Budiansky
also ignores an important alternative theory: consciousness may not
have been a direct product of natural selection, but simply a
feature that arose in brains reaching a certain level of
complexity.
</P>
<P>
   In his last two pages, Budiansky considers the looser definition
of consciousness, concluding that no nonhuman species has
subjective experience, feels pain or is self-aware. In our state of
ignorance, this declaration is foolish. Whether members of other
species are conscious (and, if so, what aspects of the nervous
system produce this phenomenon) may never be known, for solutions
require either self-reporting animals or a very deep understanding
of the brain. Nevertheless, I find it quite plausible that my cat
feels pain when I inadvertently step on his tail. (Cats also
produce endorphins, molecules whose main function is to relieve
pain.) And who can be certain that Greyfriars Bobby did not miss
his master?
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Jerry A. Coyne teaches in the department of ecology and
evolution at the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
