<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1128 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BRIEFS-NONFIC     12-09 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BRIEFS-NONFICTION-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BRIEF: NONFICTION
</HEADLINE>
  Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 SINGING LESSONS
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Memoir of Love, Loss,
</P>
<P>
   Hope, and Healing.
</P>
<P>
   By Judy Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Pocket Books, $25. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At 7:30 A.M. on April 19, 1978, Judy Collins writes, she had her
``last drink -- by the grace of God -- eight ounces of vodka out of
a jelly jar, in a stall in the ladies' room at the airport in
Reading, Pennsylvania.'' In ``Singing Lessons,'' Collins discusses
the personal turmoil that played counterpoint to the songs that
brought her fame. Provoked by her struggle to come to terms with
the suicide of her son, Clark, in 1992, this often moving but
unevenly written memoir is as contradictory as the life it
chronicles. Wonderfully lyrical language too often is juxtaposed
with cliches and psychobabble. Collins, now 57 years old, is at her
best describing growing up in a household in which ``glorious
music'' was underscored by darker themes. The eldest of five
children, she idolized her father, Charlie Collins, one of the
pioneers during the early years of radio. Blind since the age of 4,
he began every day by singing in the shower before inserting his
specially ordered blue glass eyes. Along with confidence, social
conscience and musical talent, Collins inherited from her father
the family ``failing.'' The man who ``celebrated each new day,
singing at the breakfast table'' could also be ``drunk, morose . .
. unpredictable . . . angry, terrifying.'' ``Music,'' she writes,
``gave me shelter from the pain of thinking'' that her father's
alcoholism ``was my fault.'' Almost seven years after her son's
death, Collins credits singing, a healthy life and an idyllic
second marriage with helping her battle grief and ``the black dog
of depression,'' a beast that has stalked her since childhood. ``I
see my son everywhere, in the glint of the diamonds on the snow,
the songs of birds,'' she writes. ``You are the music of the
spheres now,'' she writes to Clark, ``in your death, even more
vibrant.'' _ LESLIE CHESS FELLER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HITLER AND GELI
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Hayman.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomsbury/St. Martin's, $24.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Geli Raubal was Hitler's niece, the daughter of his half sister,
Angela. For two years, beginning in November 1929, she and her
uncle lived together in Munich, and though the precise nature of
their relationship is unclear, Hitler declared repeatedly that she
was the only woman he ever loved. In September 1931 she was found
dead in their apartment. The police reported a suicide, but
questions have surrounded her life and death ever since. In
``Hitler and Geli,'' Ronald Hayman, the author of biographies of
Nietzsche, Kafka and the Marquis de Sade, has collected every bit
of information he can find about the couple. Some of it is
fascinating, some of it is merely prurient and some of it is
fascinatingly prurient (one chapter is entitled ``Things He Makes
Me Do''). Unfortunately, there is not very much of it, so Hayman is
forced to fill out his pages with a banal recitation of Hitler's
rise to power and wobbly speculations based on rumor and hearsay.
The book is crammed with probablys, seems-to-haves and
it-is-unlikelys. Hayman devotes four chapters to the circumstances
of Geli's death, examining everything from the angle of the bullet
wound to Hitler's whereabouts at the time. It is clear that he
would like to say that Hitler pulled the trigger, yet all of his
labors on this point are not only inconclusive but also
anticlimactic and redundant. For even if the evidence were more
substantial than it is, the worst that Hayman would be able to show
is that -- surprise! -- Hitler was a murderer. _ BARRY GEWEN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROSALYN YALOW
</P>
<P>
   Nobel Laureate:
</P>
<P>
   Her Life and Work in Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   By Eugene Straus.
</P>
<P>
   Plenum, $26.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, a year after winning the Nobel Prize, Rosalyn Sussman
Yalow was called ``a Madame Curie from the Bronx.'' Only the second
woman ever to win the prize for medicine, she identified closely
with Curie, the ideal scientist, wife and mother, three roles in
which she also sought to excel. In this biographical memoir, Eugene
Straus, a longtime friend and colleague, pays tribute to an
extraordinary woman. Yalow emerges from these pages as brilliant,
ambitious and driven in her professional life, rigid, humorless and
cold-blooded on a personal level. According to her biographer,
Yalow believes that women scientists should marry, rear children,
cook and clean in order to be fulfilled; while pursuing her career,
she had a son and daughter. Outside her family, though, Yalow could
appear unfeeling; when Solomon Berson, the dazzling colleague with
whom she shared dozens of important discoveries and prizes, died
suddenly in 1972, her public display of grief surprised several
onlookers. Five years later, she achieved the Nobel -- to universal
acclaim if not universal affection. _ LYNN KARPEN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONE RIVER MORE
</P>
<P>
   By W. D. Wetherell.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons, $25. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   W. D. Wetherell wants us to think that he is writing about
fishing, but clearly that is just an excuse for this series of
thoughtful, evocative meditations on the environment, culture,
relationships and, incidentally, fly fishing. In ``One River
More,'' his third and, he says, last book on the subject, Wetherell
takes us through three seasons and 15 years of fishing in the upper
Connecticut River region and Montana. He writes entertainingly of
family trips and stratagems to slip in fishing while spending time
with his children. He muses on the benefits and drawbacks of clubs
(``private water'') and speaks lovingly of the Rangeley Lakes of
western Maine. He sometimes skirts perilously close to
curmudgeonhood as he decries changes in a sport ``that requires
thinking and creativity in a culture that often punishes both.''
But frequently he is right on the mark. ``American consumerism at
full throttle is not a pretty sight,'' he grumbles. And he is
exceedingly grumpy about the new breed of fisher-folk, ``their
competitive fires fully stoked,'' who bring their ``new
sullenness'' and cellular phones to a ``quiet and simple pursuit.''
The most important factor in fly fishing, he says, is ``not casting
ability . . . but coming to appreciate and understand something of
the landscape, terrain, history and culture of the region through
which your river flows.'' Respect for such ``interconnectedness''
is all-important because ``the brutal fact is that our future
depends on our culture's attitude toward the natural world.'' _
MARY GRACE BUTLER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-BRIEFS-NONFICTION-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: GRACE BUTLER) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIBET: Through the Red Box
</P>
<P>
   By Peter Sis
</P>
<P>
   Frances Foster/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A man returns to his childhood home in Prague after many years
and nervously climbs the stairs to his father's empty study. On the
desk he finds a mysterious red-lacquered box, which was off limits
to him as a child. He unlocks it with a rusted key, and finds
inside ``pages and pages of fragile paper covered with faded
handwriting and fine drawings and maps blending into the text, all
of it barely holding together, like brittle autumn leaves.'' It's a
diary kept by his father when he was lost in Tibet in the 1950's --
and ground zero for all the magical stories that later captivated
his son. That is the swift and surefooted set-up for the enchanting
TIBET: Through the Red Box (Frances Foster/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$25) by Peter Sis, best known as a writer and illustrator of
children's books. His father, a documentary filmmaker drafted by
the Czechoslovak Army and sent to China to teach and make movies,
was stranded in Tibet during the construction of a highway across
the Himalayas. His diary, embellished with factual notes in the
margins, is interwined with Sis' own recollections of his father's
encounters with nomads, yetis, lamas who fly like kites -- and with
a magical blue lake where the fish have human faces. His wanderings
culminate in a visit to the Forbidden City of Lhasa, where he tries
to warn the Dalai Lama of the threat posed by the coming highway:
``It might well bring hospitals, electricity and technology, but
little roads will then go to the lake, to the Valley of the Yetis,
to the caves and monasteries. What will it take away? It might take
more than it brings.'' All this is accompanied by exquisite
illustrations of his father's adventures, finely detailed mandalas
and dreamlike images that provide a rich counterpoint to the
simple, direct text. Younger readers will be transported by the
folk tales and the artwork, but this is more than a ripping yarn:
with its mystical underpinnings and the muted sadness that washes
over the whole enterprise, it is a personal account of a son still
struggling to understand the absence of his father, and poetic
testimony to the power of the imagination to transfigure reality. _
SCOTT VEALE
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
