<HEADER>
A1130 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-1000&AMP;AD     12-09 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME
</HEADLINE>
  By Marilyn Stasio 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harold Adams is not a flashy writer; but in his quiet way, he
applies his spare, unruffled style to the creation of a modest
kingdom of the imagination where the landscape has a comforting
familiarity, where values seem certain and where characters come
and go with the confident step of people who know they belong here.
In NO BADGE, NO GUN (Walker, $22.95), as in earlier books in this
offbeat series, the stranger in this land is Carl Wilcox, an
itinerant sign painter and sometime sleuth who wanders across South
Dakota during the Great Depression, settling in a town just long
enough to get the lay of the land, spruce up the drugstore or dance
hall and maybe solve a murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like getting to know a place in a day or two,'' Carl says.
``Who runs it, why, all that. It's easy to get acquainted.'' Here,
Carl's traveling feet take him to Jonesville, where a stern pastor
hires him to solve the murder of his 15-year-old niece, who was
raped and strangled in the church basement. Carl pursues this one
to the bitter end; but being a keen student of human nature, he
also picks up on the local prejudices about sex and strangers,
adding to his already considerable store of knowledge about life in
rural America during a period when irresistible social changes were
beginning to sweep across the prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Edith Skom evokes ``the indefinable essence of dormitory'' to
transport us to a women's residence hall at the University of
Chicago in the late 1940's for her academic mystery THE CHARLES
DICKENS MURDERS (Delacorte, $21.95). Wafted on eau de tuna
casserole, Tabu and the hormonal heat of virginal intellectuals,
this smartly plotted whodunit progresses from incidents of petty
theft and boyfriend poaching to a murder that destroys the girlish
loyalties of a group of friends. ``The whole dorm looks at each
other now,'' one says, ``sort of suspicious, sort of scared.''
Years later, the survivors still wonder which one of them is a
murderer -- and if the killing is truly over.
</P>
<P>
   When Beth Austin, a professor of literature and the brainy star
of this series, learns of the unsolved crime from her mother, a
member of the dorm clique, she hunts down all the old girls and
puts them through some Dickensian analysis. This one reminds her of
Lady Dedlock; that one, of the cruel and conniving lawyer
Tulkinghorn; while the actual murder, ``like the case of Jarndyce
and Jarndyce'' in ``Bleak House,'' ``stretched back to the past and
blighted the present.'' Even when the Dickens connections become
forced or intrusive, Skom maintains the wit to deliver a lively and
affectionate picture of dorm life in an earlier but hardly innocent
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Lynda S. Robinson has an interesting theory about how Queen
Nefertiti died. (Hint: it was not of the plague that scourged Egypt
during the reign of her husband, the heretic King Ikhnaton.) Having
raised the tantalizing issue of regicide in ``Eater of Souls,''
Robinson now resolves it in DRINKER OF BLOOD (Mysterious Press/
</P>
<P>
   Warner, $22) through gorgeously textured vignettes that trace
the Queen's career from Pharaoh's 12-year-old child bride to ``the
focus of court intrigue'' as the true power behind the throne. Even
in fragments, the story has a dark, romantic power.
</P>
<P>
   But why the fragmentary treatment in the first place? Within the
broader scheme of this vividly dramatized series, Nefertiti's fate
is the obsessive concern of the fictional hero, Lord Meren, the
subtle spy master who serves as ``the Eyes and Ears of Pharaoh'' in
the court of Tutankhamen. Despite Meren's convincing argument that
the dead queen's enemies threaten his own monarch, the double
narrative is a double distraction. For all that, it's always a
pleasure to negotiate the treacherous corridors of power with Lord
Meren and his wily associates, eavesdropping on the priests in
Pharaoh's court, ducking the knife fights on the back streets of
Memphis -- and picking up beauty tips from Nefertiti.
</P>
<P>
   Would you believe that Russian spies, Mafia gangsters and rogue
C.I.A. agents are running amok in Vermont? I have trouble with that
one, too, and Archer Mayor is less than persuasive on the matter in
THE DISPOSABLE MAN (Mysterious Press/Warner, $22). Lieut. Joe
Gunther, the local lawman in this series, keeps his rock-jawed face
from cracking when a dead Russian mobster is found floating in a
soapstone quarry. ``I prided myself on keeping cool, keeping my
emotional cards out of sight, maintaining a professional stance,''
Gunther says. But after tearing around the state chasing renegade
spooks and landing himself in jail, the stoical hero finally blows
his composure. Despite a sensational mountaintop shootout that
clinches the action, this one is on hostile territory.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look now, but Patricia Carlon is back with another novel
of psychological suspense that confounds every neat notion about
what an intellectual thriller is supposed to be. CRIME OF SILENCE
(Soho, $21) opens as a conventional kidnapping case: Evan Kiley's
little boy has been snatched by the same villains who took George
Winton's little girl, but later returned her for a ransom and her
father's promise of silence. Appealing to Winton's guilty
conscience, Kiley enlists his aid in dealing with the kidnappers,
and on that level alone, the tension is terrific. But Carlon, an
Australian novelist whose work has just recently begun to surface
here, turns the formula inside out to raise the deeper issue of
what a man must do to pay off a moral debt. The game of nerves that
Kiley and Winton play is so manipulative that only one thing is
clear: this is a writer who is good enough to make up her own
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
