 (Editors: Following is a list of slugs and titles of the books
reviewed in the New York Times Book Review for Sunday DEC. 13.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   ON THE COVER
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-NEWYORK-NYTSF, WRITING NEW YORK, A Literary Anthology.
Edited by Phillip Lopate. 1,050 pp. New York: The Library of
America. $40. A new anthology of writing about New York, starting
with Washington Irving.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-BROOKLYN-NYTSF, THE NEIGHBORHOODS OF BROOKLYN, John B.
Manbeck, consulting editor. Illustrated. 246 pp. New Haven:
Citizens Committee for New York City/Yale University Press. $29.95.
Far from the lights of Manhattan, the real diversity of New York
City can be found in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-GOTHAM-NYTSF, GOTHAM, A History of New York City to
1898, By Edwin G. Burrows and Mike Wallace. Illustrated. 1,383 pp.
New York: Oxford Press. $49.95. A study of New York City traces the
Big Apple from the last ice age to this century.
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   FICTION
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-DUCHESS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF, THE SILENT DUCHESS, By Dacia
Maraini. Translated by Dick Kitto and Elspeth Spottiswood. 261 pp.
New York: The Feminist Press. $19.95. The heroine of this novel, a
Sicilian duchess, is unable or unwilling to speak.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-BALLS-NYTSF, BALLS, By Nanci Kincaid. 396 pp. Chapel
Hill, N.C.: Algonquin Books of Chapel Hill. $21.95. The hard times
of a football coach's wife, by a novelist who knows the territory
firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-MEMORY-NYTSF, COUNTRY OF MEMORY, By K. C. Frederick. 240
pp. Sag Harbor, N.Y.: The Permanent Press. $24. Set in a fictitious
Eastern European country, a novel drips with gray skies and runny
noses.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-FEUD-NYTSF, BLOOD FEUD, By Annabel Thomas. 195 pp.
Knoxville: The University of Tennessee Press. $24.95. This first
novel details the violent feud between two Appalachian families.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-HOSPICE-NYTSF, SOON, Tales From Hospice, By A. G.
Mojtabai. 190 pp. Cambridge, Mass.: Zoland Books. $22. A. G.
Mojtabai's stories are set in a hospice in Amarillo, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------
</P>
