<SLUG> BC-STATES-BUDGET </SLUG>
  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR DEC.
9, 1998. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT 202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA -- FEMA. Berkeley won a federal emergency-disaster
relief award Wednesday, earning recognition for its efforts at
limiting damage when earthquakes and mudslides hit. While the city
is sometimes known derisively as the ``People's Republic of
Berkeley,'' city officials said it is precisely because of the
city's high taxes, which it uses for seismic retrofitting, that led
to the honor. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO -- SOCIAL. Lawmakers seem to be moving toward a rough
consensus around a group of proposals to invest Social Security
money in the market to save the benefits program from future
insolvency -- a position backed by Sen. Wayne Allard. One of his
party's most vocal advocates of reform, Allard is one of 12 Senate
Republicans who took part in a five-hour closed-door meeting with
President Clinton at the White House. Davant
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT -- CUBA. Sen. Christopher J. Dodd on his recent trip
to Cuba. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   -- IMPEACH. What delegation members are thinking about next
week's likely impeachment vote. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA -- FEC. The lack of competition in South Florida House
races this year has left most of the region's eight-member
delegation with piles of money to throw into their 2000 campaigns.
Williams
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA -- FEC. U.S. Sen. Fritz Hollings outraised and outspent
U.S. Rep. Bob Inglis in this year's South Carolina Senate race by
more than 2-1 on his way to winning a seventh term. Cookie magnate
Michael Coles, able to draw on his personal fortune, was more
financially competitive with Sen. Paul Coverdell in the Georgia
Senate contest. But he also lost the battle for campaign dollars to
the incumbent as he came up short in the vote tally. Williams
</P>
<P>
   MAINE -- SOCIAL. Lawmakers seem to be moving toward a rough
consensus around a group of proposals to invest some Social
Security money in the market to save the benefits program from
future insolvency -- a position advocated by Sen. Susan M. Collins.
She is one of 12 Senate Republicans who attended today's White
House conference on the subject, and, as a member of the Social
Security task force appointed by Majority Leader Trent Lott, she is
likely to have a role in shaping any reform measure that makes it
to the Senate floor for a vote. Davant
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS -- WELD. Former Massachusetts Gov. William Weld
testified today before the House Judiciary Committee. Preston
</P>
<P>
   -- WELD2000. Former Massachusetts Gov. William Weld took himself
out of the running for a 2000 Senate campaign. Preston
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN -- CONGRESS. With at least four representatives
undecided on their vote, Michigan's congressional coalition may
hold the key to whether President Clinton is eventually impeached
by the House. Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- NEY-IMPEACH. Rep. Bob Ney, R-St. Clairsville, is
garnering national media attention as an ``undecided'' Republican
when it comes to the possible impeachment of President Clinton. CNN
and the New York Times plan to follow him around the district on
Thursday as he meets and greets constituents. However, the St.
Clairsville Republican said he is simply doing what he said he
would do when he voted for the impeachment inquiry: waiting to hear
the facts before making a decision. Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -- FARM-BILL. (WORKING FOR WEEKEND) With bad weather and
plummeting commodity prices, the 1996 Freedom to Farm Act faced its
first real test this year since its passage. This year, Congress
ended up doling out nearly $7 billion in emergency spending to help
farmers through a tough season -- problems that may have been
solved through the crop subsidies that were slashed in the farm
bill. Does the bill adequately address the needs of farmers? Hurt
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA -- SOCSEC. Republican Sen. Rick Santorum had the
president's ear on his plan to privatize social security. The two
emerged side by side from a closed door meeting Clinton held today
with lawmakers to discuss the reform of social security. Santorum
said he feels Democrats, like Clinton, are more open to some form
of privatization than he ever thought they would be. The two-day
conference ended today. Fine
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA -- GRAHAM. U.S. Rep. Lindsey Graham is unmoved by
President Clinton's defense to impeachment charges, and appears
poised to vote with fellow Republicans on the House Judiciary
Committee to send the case to the House floor. (Working.) Williams
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- REAX. Rio Grande Valley lawmakers are refraining from
commenting on the Judiciary committee hearings. Brown
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN -- IMPEACH-REACT. Reaction from the Wisconsin
delegation about the impeachment hearings. (Possible.) Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -- IMPEACH-NEW. After spending a long election season and its
aftermath setting goals for their first session in Congress,
Wisconsin's newly elected members may find themselves returning to
a Washington that is paralyzed by a Senate trial of President
Clinton. (Possible.) Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
