</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCROLLS-SON-OF-GOD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `SON OF GOD' IN THE DEAD SEA SCROLLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative NIRDI
RELIS in New York at (800) 972-3550 or (212) 499-3333, or fax her
at (212) 499-3382.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Editors: A photo to accompany this article is available free of
charge, via email or diskette, by e-mailing a request to
dcrowder(at)compuserve.com.
 &HT;    
 By NEIL ALTMAN and DAVID CROWDER  
 c.1998 NEIL ALTMAN and DAVID CROWDER  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by N.Y. Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Was a key part of the Christmas story borrowed from the Dead Sea
Scrolls?
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars think it was and point to a scroll they say was
written a generation before Jesus' birth that sounds like the angel
Gabriel's announcement to Mary that her son would be the messiah.
</P>
<P>
   But overlooked for the 50 years since that little-known scroll
was discovered is evidence that the scholars are wrong and that it
-- along with other Dead Sea Scrolls -- could not have been written
until long after the rise of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the ``Son of God'' text, the scroll reads, in part:
``He shall be hailed as son of God, and they shall call him the son
of the most high ... . His kingdom will be an eternal kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   In Luke's New Testament account of the annunciation, the angel
Gabriel told Mary: ``He will be great, and will be called the son
of the Most High ... and of His kingdom there will be no end.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Dead Sea Scroll scholars have used the scrolls to
support an increasingly popular view that there was little
originality in the divine claims of the carpenter from Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   But University of Chicago scholar John Collins goes farther than
most in discussing the titles ``Son of God'' and ``Son of the Most
High.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is overwhelmingly probable that Luke borrowed these titles,
either from this text or from a common tradition to identify Jesus
as the messiah,'' Collins writes in his 1997 book, ``Apocalypticism
in the Dead Sea Scrolls.''
</P>
<P>
   One scholar, John Walvoord, chancellor of Dallas Theological
Seminary, said the implications of Collins' statement are profound
because he ``implies that Luke's gospel is not divinely inspired.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dead Sea Scrolls are right and the Bible is wrong? How do
they know this?'' Walvoord asked.
</P>
<P>
   For Christians and Jews, questions about the significance and
dating of the scrolls are as important as the Bible itself.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming that the Son of God text and other Dead Sea Scrolls are
ancient, scroll scholars have convinced publishers of Christian
Bibles to make hundreds of changes to some recent editions of the
Old Testament.
</P>
<P>
   But the Son of God text contains long-ignored Hebrew letters,
vowel marks and tiny letters that did not come into use until after
600 AD.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars who have seen the vowels cannot explain their presence.
</P>
<P>
   And just as important as the physical evidence attesting to the
scroll's age are the ideas it contains and the way they are
expressed.
</P>
<P>
   For any Jewish scribe before Christ to have described a man --
even the coming messiah -- as immortal, divine and the son of God
would have been far beyond the bounds of Jewish tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that a Jew of that time didn't write this,''
said Rabbi Kenneth Weiss of El Paso, Texas. ``It's not a Jewish way
to refer to a messiah, and I don't believe a Jewish source would
ever use that phrase.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray Friedman, director of Feinstein Center for
American-Jewish History at Philadelphia's Temple University, was
shocked to hear that a document like the Son of God text was found
among the Dead Sea Scrolls at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable!'' he said. ``If this is real ... Jesus has
been authenticated. If it's a BC document, it announces in strict,
clear-cut terms the arrival of the messiah. But if it's after, it's
worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Also disagreeing with the views of established scroll scholars
is Milton Fisher, professor of Old Testament at Philadelphia
Theological Seminary and the former president of that institution,
who said he does ``not think the Son of God text was written before
the time of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanoch Guy, professor of Hebrew and coordinator of Hebrew
Studies at Temple University in Philadelphia agrees that ``the
language is absolutely Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that this is a Christian text,'' Guy said of
the Son of God text.
</P>
<P>
   The Dead Sea Scrolls supposedly were written by a Jewish sect
over a period that began as early as 200 years before the birth of
Christ and ended early in the first century.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   About 68 AD, most scholars believe, the scrolls were stashed in
caves overlooking the Dead Sea, where they remained undisturbed
until 1947 when an Arab shepherd boy stumbled upon them.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   But more than 50 years after the first scrolls came to light,
many questions remain about their origins.
</P>
<P>
   While the scrolls are a national treasure to Israel and the
basis for changes being made in the Old Testament of some Christian
Bibles, publishers of Jewish Bibles are reluctant to make the same
changes, even though the scrolls are thought to be the oldest
existing copies of Jewish holy texts.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we are really leaving the (Bible) as is,'' said
Helaine Denenberg, editorial assistant with the Jewish Publication
Society, North America's foremost publisher of Jewish Bibles.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Jews are even more adamant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scrolls are not from mainstream Judaism, but from an
extremist sect,'' said Rabbi Yehoshua Kaganoff of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the existence of the Son of God text was known only
to a handful of scholars. But in the mid-1990s, the entire text was
published, revealing striking New Testament themes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to describing a divine messiah, the text also echoes
the New Testament description of Jesus' return and of the end
times:
</P>
<P>
   ``One nation shall trample on another nation ... (Then) his
kingdom (shall be) an everlasting kingdom ... He shall judge the
earth in righteousness, and everyone shall have peace ... and every
nation will submit to Him.'' (Parentheses represent reconstructed
passages.)
</P>
<P>
   In their efforts to portray the Son of God text as a
pre-Christian document, some scroll scholars theorize that it
referred to a figure who lived a century or more before the birth
of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   But the evidence -- so hard to explain, so easy to overlook --
repeatedly suggests that the writer of the scroll was aware of New
Testament theology, of Jesus and of the end of the world that he
described.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   (Neil Altman is a Philadelphia-based writer who specializes in
the Dead Sea Scrolls and religion. David Crowder is an
investigative reporter and former editorial page editor for the El
Paso Times.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
