<SLUG> BC-BBA-HENDERSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAKLAND NEEDS RICKEY HENDERSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Rickey Henderson could be an Athletic again,
even if it is only as a slab of bronze in Cooperstown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Let's put it this way, though. Neither possibility is very
likely, and given the latest bum's rush he has been given, neither
should be. After all, if you're out after three strikes, what ought
to happen after four?
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the team's refusal to offer him arbitration for 1999
sort of fits the profile for this team as it enters the new
millennium _ if it looks familiar, it looks better somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Now this won't be a salute to Henderson's long and illustrious
career, of which we know plenty already. And this won't be another
cautionary tale about what happened to Mark McGwire, whose 1996
trade to the Hall of Fame via St. Louis is still indefensible, even
though some CPA with more courage than sense will occasionally try.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, this is just to ask the musical question, ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Henderson's numbers in 1998 (.236 batting, .376
on-base, and other than his 66 steals, a bunch of ordinary
ordinals) do not cry out in his defense with their usual verve. He
often looked, frankly, like a guy who is going to turn 40 on
Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   And granted, it isn't as though he brought thousands of people
into the ballpark on the strength of his name alone, because
nothing could have overcome the foul atmosphere offered up by a
flinty ownership that takes its cut first. The best you can say for
him, in fact, is that he didn't chase thousands more away.
</P>
<P>
   And granted again, sentiment is usually wasted on the modern
athlete. If your time has come, it's come, and those who try to get
that one last squeeze out of the toothpaste tube usually end up
with a sore arm and gingivitis.
</P>
<P>
   But even though there is nothing that could logically return him
to Oakland now, the question deserves to be asked by someone _ what
harm would it have done bringing him back?
</P>
<P>
   For one, as near as anyone knows, there is no glorious leadoff
hitter waiting in the wings. The A's have some interesting young
talent, but interesting is not the same as foolproof, or even
necessarily good. Ben Grieve, the Rookie of the Year, isn't really
any better positioned as a left fielder than he was in right, Matt
Stairs is a designated hitter pure and simple, and there is nobody
else who makes you whistle and go, ``Here's the offensive spark
they need.''
</P>
<P>
   For two, most observers found Henderson to be a veritable
delight in the clubhouse, openly helpful to the younger players,
agreeable to the manager and coaches, and downright charming to
those usually ungrateful swine in the press box.
</P>
<P>
   And for three, and this is the clincher, what is the gain in
telling a Hall of Famer to take a hike for the fourth time? At this
point in their development, with a fan base small enough to fit
around a hermit's holiday table and well-earned cynicism greeting
their every decision, just knowing that he might not want to be
remembered in Cooperstown as an Athletic should sober general
manager Billy Beane and what else is left of the front office.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the only unambiguous bit of good news the A's have
brought us since the end of the season was Grieve's Rookie of the
Year Award. Even retaining Kenny Rogers had a slightly bittersweet
taste to it, since nobody believes he will survive until the next
in-season trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of it has surrounded the asking price for a sale of the
team, or a place to move the team, or settling lawsuits with the
city. Every time a free agent signs somewhere, A's fans yawn,
because they knew their team wasn't involved. Every time a trade is
announced, A's fans remember with nostalgia the days when Oakland
made trades itself. Baseball isn't happening in Oakland these days.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Rickey Henderson's departure, for either New York or
Seattle if the speculation is true, should tug at you a bit more
than it already has. Not because there will be such a hue and cry
when he breaks his next record, but because it would have been an
affirmative decision to keep him at a time when the A's need all
the affirmations they can get.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
