<HEADLINE>
REMEMBER THE REASON FOR THE TREE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was in elementary school, my family had a silver
Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   I loved that tree. It was about 5 feet tall, and no matter where
I stood, I could see right through it because the branches were
sparse and so far apart. I don't know what the tree was made of,
but I think it might have been aluminum, because after Christmas
we'd stick a couple of the sparkly limbs on top of the television
to improve the reception.
</P>
<P>
   My friends all had live trees that dwarfed the furniture in
their living rooms. Their humongous trees shed needles all over the
floor. Our tree never shed unless you grabbed a strand of that
silver stuff and tugged real hard, which was dangerous, because the
tree was so lightweight that it would fall over if you sneezed.
</P>
<P>
   We decorated our tree with red and green ornaments and 12 feet
of some more silver stuff that looked like a showgirl's feather
boa. It was awesome. Dad topped it with a silver star studded with
plastic gems. Then we plugged in the rotating spotlight that cast
alternating beams of red, blue, yellow and green on the artificial
tree.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, that sounds like an awfully ugly tree, doesn't
it? But I clearly remember lying on the floor next to that tree
every night, imagining all of the wonderful things that Santa was
going to bring me.
</P>
<P>
   Waking up on Christmas morning and finding those colorful
presents snuggled beneath that tree gave me a feeling that words
cannot describe. Sometimes Santa even used the same wrapping paper
that my mother used on the gifts for grandma. Now, people say that
this holiday is ``too commercial'' and that those of us who
celebrate Christmas have forgotten the reason for the season.
</P>
<P>
   I agree with the over-commercialization aspect of that
criticism, but I don't believe that most of us have forgotten the
Christ in Christmas. However, it is easy to become distracted by
all of the secular holiday traditions. I'm not sure how to fix
that. It is an issue to be considered and addressed in each
household.
</P>
<P>
   What I am certain of is that with the proper perspective and
attitude, Christmas can still be a time of tremendous joy, sharing
and love.
</P>
<P>
   So, as we endure the hustle and bustle of the next few weeks,
let's remember the real reason for the celebration and do what I
did years ago as I watched that pathetic little tree change colors.
</P>
<P>
   Just smile, smile, smile.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
