<SLUG> BC-SAMARITAN-BILL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA LAWMAKERS SEEK GOOD SAMARITAN LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The bathroom rape and murder of a
7-year-old girl, a crime seen in progress but not reported by a
University of California student, has prompted three lawmakers to
introduce ``good Samaritan'' laws requiring people to report
assaults they may witness.
</P>
<P>
   The outrage surrounding student David Cash's failure to save
Sherrice Iverson when he happened on the assault and his decision
not to tell the police about the May 25, 1997, killing prompted
protests at the Berkeley campus and calls for the expulsion of
Cash.
</P>
<P>
   But neither state law nor campus rules allow punishment for
refusing to report a crime. Cash, meanwhile, continues to attend
Berkeley while his former friend, Jeremy Strohmeyer, serves a life
sentence for the girl's death.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the opening of the state Legislature's 1999-2000
session on Monday, three bills were introduced that would impose
various criminal penalties for failure to report crime,
particularly if the victim is a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us who have children know the worst fear is that
something terrible could happen to them and that it could have been
prevented if someone had intervened,'' said Assemblyman Tom
Torlakson, a Democrat from Antioch.
</P>
<P>
   None of the bills would allow authorities to retroactively
prosecute Cash and subsequently kick him out of school. The
university has said it can expel students convicted of crimes, but
it has no authority to kick out students for failing to report a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., recently introduced a measure in
the Senate that would penalize states for not enacting so-called
good Samaritan laws. Boxer's bill would make the states ineligible
for federal child-abuse prevention funds if they failed to enact
such laws.
</P>
<P>
   California law already requires teachers, health care workers,
the clergy and day care providers to report suspected child abuse.
Doctors must report certain gunshot wounds to the police. And
hunters who witness the wounding or killing of another hunter or
domestic animal must report the incident to the Department of Fish
and Game _ or face a misdemeanor charge.
</P>
<P>
   But the three bills introduced Monday would significantly
broaden that area of the law to require the same kind of morality
from all California residents. Several states, including
Massachusetts, Ohio, Washington and Rhode Island, already have good
Samaritan laws that contain various degrees of punishment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
