<HEADLINE>
GREAT PIANISTS COLLECTION IS HUGE AND FULL OF HOLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 20th century has been the best of times and the worst of
times for the piano.
</P>
<P>
   Philips Classics is celebrating the place of the piano in the
century with the most ambitious commercial recording release of all
time, the ``Great Pianists of the 20th Century,'' a collection of
200 discs by such familiar artists as Van Cliburn and Vladimir
Horowitz. The first discs began appearing in stores in August; they
will be released through August 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The set looks back on a century in which the piano's prestige
has fluctuated. In 1900, the piano was the dominant force in
music-making, with a huge, wonderful repertoire, a large group of
skilled practitioners, and the prevalent notion that no European or
American home was complete without one.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, electronic equipment had replaced the piano as the
center of home life, and ``serious'' composers went out of their
way to avoid any traditional use of the instrument. Although the
piano was still the most popular concerto instrument on orchestral
concerts, not one new piano concerto had entered the standard
repertoire since mid-century.
</P>
<P>
   But as of 1998, the piano is on the way up again. The piano solo
recital, declared dead in 1975, is back. More good pianists are
alive today than ever before. Composers are rediscovering the
special qualities of the instrument. And, yes, it's still the
favorite concerto feature at orchestral concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, whatever one might say for the fine qualities of other
instruments, you won't find a 200-disc set devoted to great
violinists of the 20th century, or great saxophonists of the 20th
century, or great anything else.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes 70 pianists, from Geza Anda to Krystian
Zimerman, each represented by at least one two-disc set, except for
two ``teams'' included in one volume each. Several _ the likes of
Rubinstein, Richter, Gilels _ are represented in more than one
two-disc volume, bringing the total to 100 separate volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, you don't have to buy all of it. Each two-disc
volume is available for $23.99 _ or you can pay $2,399 for the
whole set, if you're that serious about it.
</P>
<P>
   And there are a few reasons you might not want to be that
serious about it. Before you start collecting, make sure your
favorite pianist is on the list. All of the obvious greats are
there, of course _ Cliburn, Paderewski, Horowitz, Gieseking,
Hofmann _ but there are some disturbing omissions.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Fort Worth favorite and internationally renowned
Mozart, Schubert and Bartok expert Lili Kraus is not included. Nor
is Tatiana Nikolaieva, the Russian muse who, through her
performances of keyboard music of J.S. Bach, inspired
Shostakovich's Preludes and Fugues, and whose sublime performance
of those is on record. Or Kurt Masur's favorite pianist, Cecile
Ousset. Or John Browning, who inspired Barber's Piano Concerto.
</P>
<P>
   How much record company politics went into making the list? If
Andre Previn, with his high-profile name, is on the list, why not
real pianists such as Emanuel Ax, Abbey Simon, Philippe Entrement?
</P>
<P>
   If Mitsuko Uchida, why not Mischa Dichter, Peter Serkin or Ruth
Laredo? One could almost build a major collection out of recordings
by pianists not included in Philips' 70.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are plenty of names on the list included solely
because they really were great pianists who, fortunately, were
captured on record. That the set exists at all is a testimony to
the recording industry's faith that, at the end of the 20th
century, music lovers will invest time and money to hear great
piano music played by great artists. How much that faith is
justified will be evident if, at the end of the 21st century,
there's another list of great pianists, some playing masterpieces
we know, some playing masterpieces yet to be composed.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
