<SLUG> BC-BILLY-THE-KID-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS AUTHOR HAS A FEUD WITH THE BILLY THE KID LEGEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In legend and song, one William Bonney _ Billy the Kid to you _
killed 20 or 21 or 22 men. How many was it, really?
</P>
<P>
   ``Four,'' snaps Willard Ballow, pleased to have a question that
he can answer at some length.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may have been more, but only four killings have been
proved.'' It was a convenience, Ballow implies, to pin just about
any unsolved murder during New Mexico's fabled, notorious Lincoln
County range war of 1880-81 on Billy the Kid.
</P>
<P>
   Willard Ballow, a bantam of a man with wispy white hair, at 68
resembles a slick riverboat gambler or perhaps a more raffish
hustler. He is inhaling satisfaction, fulfillment, redemption, for
now he is an author. More than that, he is a revisionist historian.
</P>
<P>
   The creator of ``Billy the Kid: A Graphic History'' is a native
and lifelong resident of Weatherford, Texas, high school Class of
1949. He was in that kid cycle that romanticized the old Wild West
by playing cowboy _ with or without Indians, but always with
desperate hombres. At his own insistence, he was always Billy the
Kid in those skirmishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always fascinated by him, long as I can remember,'' Ballow
says.
</P>
<P>
   Most people shelve their childhood fascinations when they ``grow
up,'' but Ballow claims never to have grown up so completely, and
his interest in Billy the Kid intensified over the years.
Researching Billy's life became first a hobby, then an obsession,
long before there was any notion of a book.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 10 or 12 years ago that it struck me I really was going
to write a book,'' he says. ``It was slow going for a time, but
then in 1993 I retired (after 42 years in the art department of the
company that evolved into General Dynamics), and I really got busy
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   His investigation was not confined to old newspapers and other
library resources, or even to interviews with descendants of those
who knew or were crossed by William Bonney. He has, of course, read
every existing account of Billy and the Lincoln County War, and has
seen ``The Outlaw'' and other movies, which always display someone
prettier than Billy really was. But Ballow literally hit the trail,
or the trails _ all of them _ tracking the Kid's rather extensive
odyssey in the western reaches of the Southwest frontier.
</P>
<P>
   One immediately senses in Willard Ballow a romantic disposition
that is anchored in an Old West not inhabited exclusively by Billy
the Kid. Ballow is also keenly knowledgeable about Jesse and Frank
James and perhaps other notorious outlaws and gunfighters. But he
has no literary aspirations beyond the disarming book that he
wrote, illustrated and essentially designed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas A&AMP;M wanted to publish the book, but I wasn't pleased
about the royalty they offered,'' he says. Reminded that the stated
royalty was standard, Ballow grins and says: ``Well, I knew that.
Maybe I just needed to have control, which I wouldn't have had if
anyone but myself was the publisher.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballow's ``Billy the Kid'' is an altogether smart job of
book-making, and his illustrations are as captivating as they are
professional. As a free-lance artist, Ballow has illustrated for
``True West, Frontier Times'' and other magazines; back in the
1970s, he even did a Christmas comic strip for the
``Star-Telegram.''
</P>
<P>
   He found in Fort Worth the resources _ mainly Leway Composing
and Westbridge Printing Services _ for assuring first-rate
production of an oversized, horizontal book to be looked through
and read.
</P>
<P>
   So how about it, Willard _ what was Billy the Kid really like?
</P>
<P>
   ``I leave it to the reader to make his own judgment about
Billy,'' Ballow says. ``When he killed his first man, the fellow
was a loudmouth who sort of asked for it; but that set the pattern
for a good boy to go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``good boy'' is a revelation in Ballow's well-documented
text. The New York-born Bill Bonney was a surprisingly
sophisticated young man, schooled in social graces and quite
literate. He was even in demand as a singer for social occasions.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps he truly was wronged. Ballow writes that Billy was
promised a pardon if he would give testimony in a case. Billy kept
his part of the bargain, but the other side reneged. The governor
in question _ an important figure in Billy's story _ was Lew
Wallace, former Union general in the Civil War, whose ``Ben-Hur''
was published at the time of the Lincoln County War.
</P>
<P>
   Billy the Kid was eventually captured, convicted of murder and
sentenced to hang. He broke out of jail but was tracked down and
killed by Pat Garrett _ the sheriff who, by many accounts, was a
former friend of the Kid. Ballow isn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably knew each other, because at different times they
were in the same places,'' he says, ``but there's nothing to
indicate they were buddies or even well-acquainted. One thing I'm
sure of, though: They made Pat Garrett sheriff for the sole purpose
of killing Billy.
</P>
<P>
   William Bonney was slain before reaching age 22. Ballow may
believe that his narrative of Billy's grim misadventures is
``objective,'' and it may well be that. But the reader is swayed in
Billy's favor, liking as well as pitying him, without condoning the
Old West violence that consumed him.
</P>
<P>
   Publication of Ballow's ``graphic history'' has been a splashy
event in Weatherford, reflecting local glory on its author and
instilling pride in Wanda Ballow _ Willard's wife for 47 years _
and their daughters Vickie, Jacque and Tammie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's happy for them,'' attests Leway Composing's John
Hoover, who runs interference for Ballow on the promotion route.
``Willard wants people to read his book for what they can learn
about Billy the Kid, not what they can learn about himself. He's
totally without ego.''
</P>
<P>
   But not without joy. Billy's ebullient biographer is eternally
Willard the Kid.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
