<HEADER>
A1349 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-PUBLIC10-COX     12-09 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-PUBLIC10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT VIRGINIA COUNTRY STORE, THEY'RE NOT BUYING IMPEACHMENT PITCH
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE HALL, Va. _ The time has come, the people in these parts
say, to speak of things like the unusually dry and warm weather,
the poor hunting season, and rising property taxes _ not about what
is going on down the road in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten real old,'' Lauren Morris said Wednesday as the
House Judiciary Committee, 135 miles away, entered the final stages
of its hearings on whether to impeach President Clinton. ``They've
really overdone it. I disagree with his lying, but he didn't bother
me so much to think that he should be impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old mother of two, a pharmaceutical sales
representative, has joined a handful of craftsmen, farmers and
hunters who gather in the mornings at her father's country store
and, over coffee and Marlboros, discuss the news of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Their cracker-barrel wisdom this day helps prove the point of
Democratic pollster Fred Yang: ``The farther away you are from
D.C., the less people care'' about the scandal and impeachment
drama that's consuming Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're wasting time and money,'' said Morris's father, Larry
Wyant. ``And if you threw everybody out of Congress who's done what
the president did, you wouldn't have hardly anybody in Congress to
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyant's store has been here at the foot of Virginia's Blue Ridge
Mountains for decades. His grandfather ran it before him. It's the
local source for $1 bologna sandwiches, fishing lures, bow-hunting
videos and Flatt and Scruggs cassette tapes. On the shelves behind
the cash register are baseball mementos and a framed newspaper
clipping about his son, Hunter, signing to play baseball at the
University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The store and the white cement block community center across the
highway are ``downtown'' White Hall, one of the regulars jokes. The
``mayor'' is the nickname they've given ``this fellow down the road
who's never been to school a day in his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyant's store is one of the many so-called ``disconnect'' points
beyond Capitol Hill that so exasperates congressional Republicans
bent on throwing Clinton out of office for lying about an affair
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't watch the TV or read the newspapers,'' said Dennis
Taylor, a 26-year-old carpenter who stopped by Wyant's for coffee
on the first cool, crisp day of December. ``I don't follow
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor doesn't like it that Clinton lied about his affair with
Lewinsky. But he has other priorities: ``I'm just trying to support
my family.'' He and his wife, Angie, have a 2-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``that's what most folks around here are concerned
about _ their families,'' said Wyant. Times are good, with plenty
of work for everyone, he added. So when the morning talk does
occasionally turn from hunting and the weather to politics, the
topic is usually ever-rising local property taxes, not Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all these Yankees coming in,'' said Charles Ryan, a
45-year-old painter. He is referring to the scores of
multimillion-dollar estates with names like Fox Chase, Mountvue and
Garth Gate that have been carved out of the farmland surrounding
nearby Charlottesville.
</P>
<P>
   When the subject does turn to Clinton, it is clear that the
folks in White Hall are simply ignoring the Judiciary Committee's
televised impeachment hearings, even if they are history in the
making.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Americans are paying so little attention to the hearings
that, if the House votes to impeach the president, most of them
will be shocked, former White House spokesman Mike McCurry told a
University of Virginia audience dining in the Thomas
Jefferson-designed Rotunda Dome on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are going to wake up and say, 'They did
WHAT?' `` said McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
