<HEADLINE>
POWER OUTAGE: PRACTICE SESSION FOR QUAKE-PRONE CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD and CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Plunged into a power failure, city officials
launched a well-rehearsed plan to maintain vital emergency, medical
and transportation services.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Public Works dispatched street sweepers to
direct traffic. The police guided trapped passengers from subway
tunnels. Firefighters freed people from frozen elevators. And with
half its lines dead, the Municipal Railway deployed dozens of
reserve diesel buses.
</P>
<P>
   Services were largely restored when power returned by the end of
the day Tuesday, and the officials _ from Mayor Willie Brown on
down _ declared the city's response an overwhelming success. And
many of them saw the episode as an almost welcome test run for a
big earthquake or other major disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went very well. We had rapid response from department
heads. They came in knowing what they needed to do,'' said Lucien
Canton, director of the mayor's Office of Emergency Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make light of it,'' Canton said, ``but it was
an opportunity to learn. This was an opportunity to deal with a
real emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   A mistake made by a Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co. work crew shut
down a power substation in the San Francisco Bay area Tuesday
morning, triggering an outage that left 1 million people without
electricity for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Brown, the department chiefs coordinated their response
efforts from the Office of Emergency Services, a command center of
computers, cellular phones and bulletin boards housed in a
low-slung, non-descript building several blocks from City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Divided into teams wearing color-coded vests, officials from
city departments and PG&AMP;E huddled around a horseshoe-shaped group
of tables in the Operations Room, keeping in constant touch with
colleagues in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Next door in the Planning Room, officials wearing blue vests
prepared situation reports for the decision makers, who wore purple
vests in yet another room and were led by Fire Chief Bob Demmons
and the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs, amateur radio operators were connected to a network
of 50 volunteers across the city, including in fire stations.
</P>
<P>
   For Brown and other officials, Tuesday began routinely enough.
When the power died at 8:17 a.m., the mayor was in his car heading
to work.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Canton immediately summoned city officials to the
command center, where the mayor stayed throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency generators at the Hall of Justice and city jails
kicked in, maintaining essential power to the police switchboard
and computers. But the Hall of Justice was closed to the public,
its corridors darkened and its court hearings rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Fred Lau called in extra dispatchers to handle a
flood of calls from people to be freed from elevators and from
behind automated garage doors. Some just wanted to know what was
happening.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, the police said, they received no reports of looting
during the outage. To ease traffic, Parking and Traffic Director
Stuart Sunshine sent 130 parking control officers and street
sweepers to 60 key intersections.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Unified School District kept all public
schools open Tuesday, and district officials did not release
students unless their parents picked them up.
</P>
<P>
   At San Francisco General Hospital, emergency generators kicked
in within seconds, powering operating rooms and critical and
neonatal intensive care units first, said Jene O'Connell, chief
administrator of the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the beauties of living in San Francisco,''
O'Connell said. ``We plan for the worst, so this is actually
minimal compared to what we are prepared for. We can handle this.''
</P>
<P>
   At 1:50 p.m., Brown declared a state of emergency, allowing
passengers to ride buses free and city employees to work overtime.
The declaration also extended the property tax deadline of Thursday
to the close of business Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Most areas of the city had power a short time later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
