<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV13-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE 20TH CENTURY, ONE OF MONUMENTAL CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 13)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During the next year, regardless of the outcome of
the Clinton impeachment drama, this country will explode with
evaluations of the 20th century and the events and personalities
that shaped it.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the brink of the millennium, we will be inundated
with reminiscences and retrospectives as well as predictions about
the future as we prepare to leave one century and enter another.
</P>
<P>
   A vivid panorama, stretching from Jan. 1, 1900, to Dec. 31,
1999, will pass before our eyes. It will recount great victories
and advances in human achievement while also recording tragedies
and declines in moral values.
</P>
<P>
   We will learn from historians and other observers who they
believe should be enshrined in the century's pantheon of greatness
_ the political leaders who made and expedited the great decisions
to safeguard and improve our well-being, the scientists and
inventors who guided us far beyond our old horizons, the titans of
business who developed great industries, the military heroes who
won the wars that were critical to our survival, the writers and
performers who illuminated our souls, the social crusaders who
extended justice to those who had not previously known it, the men
and women who nourished our spiritual health, the adventurers who
explored the universe and those who triumphed in the sports arena.
</P>
<P>
   The 20th has been a century of monumental change. Individuals
born in 1900 grew to adulthood in a far different world than those
born a half century or more later.
</P>
<P>
   As the 20th century began, our nation, having won the
Spanish-American War and gained dominion over Cuba, Puerto Rico,
Guam and the Philippines, was just emerging as a world power. Today
it is the single great world power.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the imperialist nations of old, America did not
simply take from other lands. It also gave to other lands. In the
wake of World War II, it provided the money and the leadership to
guide its former enemies, Germany and Japan, to democracy and
economic rejuvenation.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with aid to Greece and Turkey and continuing with the
remarkable Marshall Plan, America demonstrated to the world that it
was as adept at winning the peace as it had been at winning the
war. The republic's days of isolationism were but a vestige of the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Our passage through the 20th century has been both tumultuous
and torturous.
</P>
<P>
   At the dawn of the century, people everywhere traveled by
horse-drawn vehicles and sailing vessels. But by 1917 when America
entered World War I, many were riding in automobiles and staring
skyward in awe of flying machines. Since the radio and television
had not been invented, newspapers provided people with their
primary source of information.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, most American homes depended on water from wells
for drinking and bathing. Indoor plumbing was found primarily in
the homes of the well-to-do. Houses were heated by wood-burning
stoves or coal-burning furnaces that required constant attention.
</P>
<P>
   Before I was born, my parents lost a 13-year-old son to tetanus
and, some years later, a dear family friend to peritonitis.
Pioneers of medical science eventually made those ailments a part
of history, along with smallpox, diphtheria and typhoid fever.
</P>
<P>
   When I was about 10 years old, I was whisked off to a hospital
because my parents and our family physician feared I had polio _
the most dreaded disease of childhood. Fortunately, they were
wrong, and even more fortunately, thanks to Drs. Jonas Salk and
Albert Sabin, polio is now a disease of the past.
</P>
<P>
   In this century, medical scientists have done a spectacular job
of abolishing illnesses that once led inevitably to death. They
have not yet conquered cancer, stroke, heart disease and AIDS, but
they continue to make important strides.
</P>
<P>
   In 1900, the man of the family worked 10 or 12 hours a day. His
income, small though it was, bought a home, food, clothing and
schooling for his family. His wife stayed home, cooked the meals,
did the laundry and reared the children.
</P>
<P>
   It was rare for a woman to work outside the home, but some _ who
were teachers, nurses, secretaries and seamstresses _ did so. No
women were able to vote until the 19th Amendment was ratified in
1920.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Day provided most workers with their only guaranteed paid
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   There was no job security. When my father joined a union early
in the century, he was blacklisted from finding employment
elsewhere in his home town, Los Angeles. He was forced to go to
other communities in search of employment.
</P>
<P>
   When a working man reached his 60s in the early decades of the
century, he had no retirement income to depend on. Neither business
nor government provided him with a pension.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security did not become law until 1935, and its first
payments were not made until 1940. It then took another 26 years
before Medicare also became part of our social fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 63 years after the passage of Social Security, bipartisan
leaders are seeking ways to safeguard it when the post-World War II
baby boomers begin to retire.
</P>
<P>
   The savings that a working family had laid away often
disappeared during hard times. In the Great Depression of the
1930s, millions of Americans lost their homes and their jobs. Older
Americans often were forced to move in with their children.
</P>
<P>
   In the century now ending, we have fought five major wars on
foreign soil, triumphed in the Cold War with the communist empire,
finally dismantled the barriers to equality of opportunity for
minorities and women, and learned in Vietnam that while we are
powerful, we are not omnipotent. At the moment, we are working with
our former Cold War opponents on an international space station 240
miles above the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Hunger, poverty and crime continue to haunt us. But life
expectancy is longer than ever, and today more Americans may be
living more comfortably than ever.
</P>
<P>
   We've come a long way and learned a great many lessons.
</P>
<P>
   But our learning is not over. The 21st century holds great
challenges and opportunities as well as probable disasters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
