<HEADER>
A1365 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAHOOD-IMPEACHMENT-HN     12-09 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAHOOD-IMPEACHMENT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 CALM, COOL LaHOOD IS PICKED TO KEEP PEACE DURING IMPEACHMENT VOTE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Ray LaHood, the unflappable congressman from
Peoria, Ill., who will preside over the House during the historic
impeachment vote next week, promised Wednesday that he will work to
assure that all members are heard during the debate.
</P>
<P>
   LaHood, who was asked by Speaker Newt Gingrich to chair the
debate, said he understands why Gingrich did not want to be
remembered in the history books for presiding over the House when
it takes up the controversy over President Clinton's role in the
White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a high honor and a privilege to be asked to do this,''
said LaHood. ``The fact that Speaker Gingrich is the one who
selected me, I think, speaks volumes for the fact that he believes
I have the experience and the knowledge and the know-how to conduct
this most historic debate in a way that dignifies the House.''
</P>
<P>
   LaHood said he foresees ``a high spirited debate with a lot of
theatrics.'' His role will be to ensure that ``the debate is
conducted in a fair and balanced manner so all members have an
opportunity to feel heard.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee is expected later this week to
approve articles of impeachment and send them to the House floor.
The full House, with LaHood in the chair, would then vote on
whether to approve the articles of impeachment. If the House
approved the articles, the Senate would then conduct a trial. If
the Senate voted by a two-thirds majority to convict him, Clinton
would automatically be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   LaHood, 53, has worked to bring civility to the House since he
was first elected in 1994 with the Republican insurgents who won
control of the House for the first time since 1954. He was one of
the main organizers behind a week-long retreat in Hershey, Pa., for
House members in March 1997 that was intended to ease conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Skaggs, D-Colo., said he enlisted LaHood to help
organize the Hershey retreat because Lahood ``seemed to be the kind
of guy that might take an interest in getting the place calmed down
and on some kind of more mutually respectful terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Skaggs said chairing the House requires a lot of instinct and
intuition and is essentially ``an art form.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to know when members are on the verge of getting out
of line, or when something that is fermenting can use a little bit
of humor or a little bit of time out to help neutralize it,''
Skaggs said. ``Ray is one of the people who has that talent and can
make the place get the business done with as little as grief as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   LaHood, a conservative Republican, has staked out his
independence from the GOP leadership on some hot issues. For
example, he refused to sign Gingrich's 1994 Contract with America,
saying its tax cuts and increases in defense spending would worsen
the federal deficit. In 1995, LaHood also refused to vote with the
Republican leadership on a $17 billion package of spending cuts
because it would be used to pay for tax cuts instead of cutting the
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   However, LaHood said he has had ``a very cordial friendly
relationship'' with Gingrich for a decade, going back to the time
when he was a staffer for House Republican Leader Robert H. Michel
and Gingrich was the party's chief vote counter. After Michel
retired in 1994, LaHood won his congressional seat.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Peoria, Ill., LaHood, 53, is a former junior high school
social studies teacher and was for 12 years an aide to Michel,
rising to become his chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Michel, now senior counsel at the Washington law firm of Hogan &AMP;
Hartson, said LaHood became an expert in House floor procedure
while working for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a good reputation on both sides of the aisle for being
very fair and conciliatory and always keeping his cool and not
blowing his stack,'' Michel said.
</P>
<P>
   Michel said LaHood knows the House rules and how to ``make sure
the debate is carried on in a fair manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Another of LaHood's former employers, retired Rep. Tom
Railsback, R-Ill., who served on the House Judiciary panel in 1974
when it voted to impeach President Richard Nixon, said LaHood will
need to use every ounce of the civility that he is known for.
</P>
<P>
   Railsback appointed LaHood as his district director because ``he
gets along very well with people, he treated everyone with respect
and was very well liked.'' ``He is a very decent, well-intentioned
smart person who is going to do what he thinks is right and that's
why the Democrats and the Republicans both respect him,'' Railsback
said.
</P>
<P>
   Railsback, who has watched the impeachment hearings from his
Rancho Mirage home near Palm Springs, Calif., said this time around
the atmosphere is much surlier and tinged with a greater degree of
``rancor, finger pointing and condemnation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the civility and gentility has gone by the wayside,''
Railsback said. ``You have people who are ready to go into
combat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   William Hall, chairman of the political science department at
Bradley University in Peoria, Ill., LaHood's alma mater, said
LaHood has shown an ability in his home district to balance
competing interests.
</P>
<P>
   When LaHood chaired a committee of the members of the Peoria
Catholic Diocese a dozen years ago that was charged with the heated
matter of closing one of the city's two Catholic high schools, he
managed to ease tensions while steering the board to close down the
oldest school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feelings ran high and a lot of tough calls had to be made,''
Hall said. ``Ray not only presided but helped guide them toward the
resolution of the problem by knowing when to let people vent and
when to shut them off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
