<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1366 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     12-09 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING AT LIFE IN BLACK AND WHITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The little boy came to my door dressed as a skeleton. I didn't
see him, but my husband said that he was no more than 5 or 6 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   We'd seen a lot of children around the same age that night,
dressed in similar fashion. Because it was Halloween, this was not
all that unusual. What happened next was.
</P>
<P>
   As the little boy left, he called out to those standing watch at
the end of our walkway, ``Mommy, Mommy, a black man.''
</P>
<P>
   I shared this story with some colleagues, and laughter filled
the newsroom. The more I thought about it, though, the more
horrified I became. I wondered how was it that that little boy
could have been surprised (I don't think he was frightened) at the
sight of an African-American male.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the black men he had seen didn't stand in doorways,
handing out candy. Maybe what he was used to seeing were black men
being led away in handcuffs, or worse.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, I kept thinking about that little boy, his
innocence and his honesty. I realized that I really didn't know
what to make of his reaction to my husband. It saddened me to think
that someone could live in a world so small, so confining. But the
more I thought about him, the more I was forced to look at my own
life. What I finally realized was that my world isn't much larger
than his.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen men and women of all races and ethnicities, met people
from every walk of life. Every day, I work with a diverse group of
colleagues. I talk to them. I laugh with them. I've shared meals
with them, and I've joined them in a common cause.
</P>
<P>
   When they've been met with good fortune or tragedy, I've called
to offer congratulations or condolences. I send and receive cards
and telephone calls marking special occasions. Occasionally, one of
these friends from work, such as Wilma Campbell, will reappear out
of the blue, and it's as if we never parted. Friends are like that.
</P>
<P>
   Wilma surprised me recently with an appearance at my office
while she was visiting Fort Worth. I screamed. We embraced, and I
called my husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll never guess who's at my desk,'' I told him. After he
had offered several misses, Wilma suggested, laughing, ``Tell him
it's a white woman.''
</P>
<P>
   I met Wilma while working at the Sacramento Bee. I liked her
because she was honest and she made the best Mississippi mud pie
I'd ever tasted. She was also kind enough to take care of my dog,
Snuggles, when I went out of town.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other white women like her in my life, women
I've felt close to, but the truth is that I've never known one to
be a close friend _ someone with whom to share secrets, to push
back the darkness in each other's lives and to go forward together,
still loving each other.
</P>
<P>
   And so when I recently read an Essence magazine column by a
black woman about her friendship with a white woman, I was at once
saddened and elated.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the same feelings I have watching my daughters'
friendships with their white schoolmates. The same sorts of
feelings you feel when you see something for the first time, the
same feeling that little boy must have felt on Halloween night.
</P>
<P>
   Watching my daughters and their friends, I wonder what drew them
together, what they like about one another and if their friendships
will mature into adulthood and deepen like the one I'd just read
about in Essence.
</P>
<P>
   As moving a piece as it was, their relationship and those of my
daughters are as foreign to me as my husband's blackness was to the
little boy on Halloween night.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
