<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS Q&AMP;A 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Checking Out New Software &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I tell whether certain software applications I am
interested in will run under Windows 98? Products in stores are
often in boxes printed before Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   A. For most applications, if ``Windows 95 or later'' or just
``Windows 95'' is specified, it is generally understood that any
Windows operating system released later than Windows 95 _ Windows
98 in this case _ is acceptable. There are exceptions to the rule,
of course, like maintenance programs (Norton Utilities and so on)
for a specific system and device drivers for the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's not comprehensive and the search function can be
erratic, Microsoft maintains a list of software and hardware that
has proved to be compatible with Windows 98 at
www.microsoft.com/windows98/guide/Win98/Compatible/default.asp.
</P>
<P>
   And just about every software company has a Web page to
advertise and even sell its products. Such sites often offer
up-to-date information, including system requirements, for the
company's products. The Web page for Macromedia's Dreamweaver 2
(www.macromedia.com/software/dreamweaver/productinfo/sysreq), for
example, says it runs under Windows 95 and 98 and NT version 4.0 or
later.
</P>
<P>
   If software problems have been discovered, many of these sites
will also offer free upgrades and patches to download.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
