<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barnes re-creates another ugly chapter in South
 &HT;    By Don O' Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you want to know about murder and corruption in the South,
ask Margaret Anne Barnes. ``Murder in Coweta County,'' the Newnan
native's Edgar Award-winning book about a Georgia sheriff who
pursued a rich man for murder, was made into a television movie
starring Johnny Cash and Andy Griffith. The book and movie were so
popular, Barnes' publisher clamored for another sensational tale of
the gothic South.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken 14 years to find and write such a story, but Barnes
discovered one just across the state line from Columbus in Phenix
City, Ala. ``The Tragedy and the Triumph of Phenix City, Alabama''
(Mercer University Press, $24.95) is a true account of events as
dramatic as any novel. Until 1954, the Alabama town was known as a
Southern sin city because of prostitution, gambling and rampant
crime. Soldiers from nearby Fort Benning who ventured into the town
frequently lost their money and sometimes their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' story focuses on three heroes: Hugh Bentley, a
sporting-goods store owner who campaigned against the criminal
elements in Phenix City; Albert Patterson, an attorney general who
vowed to fight racketeering, but who was murdered in 1954; and Gen.
Walter ``Crack'' Hanna, who led the National Guard in cleaning up
the town. The next year, Phenix City was voted an All-American
City.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who said she received several threatening calls while
writing the book, sees parallels between this work and ``Murder in
Coweta County.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both show the integrity of the South,'' she says. ``The local
folks took care of the problem without any help from the federal
government.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mailer on Wolfe: Norman Mailer's review of Tom Wolfe's novel
``A Man in Full'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $28.95) should be
called a review in full. Mailer's assessment of the novel covers
five pages in The New York Review of Books and opens with a long
excerpt from Mailer's book ``Cannibals and Christians'' about the
obligation of American writers to tackle grand themes. Noting that
he and Wolfe were comrades in arms on that subject, Mailer praises
much of Wolfe's writing, but criticizes the deus ex machina ending.
What bothers Mailer the most, however, is that Wolfe chose the
commercial, best-seller route rather than the literary one. Had he
not sold out, Mailer says, he ``might at least have tried to bring
off one of the most important books of the half-century.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Whole hog: The timing couldn't have been better for William
Hedgepeth's tome on things porcine. The paperback edition of ``The
Hog Book'' (University of Georgia Press, $17.95) arrives in stores
at a time when ``Babe'' is back on the big screen and interest in
pigs is greater than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta writer's book is a tongue-in-jowl look at everything
to do with hogs, from swine in art, sport and show biz to hog lore.
Throughout history, hogs have had a negative connotation, Hedgepeth
says, citing such derogatory terms as ``sweating like a hog'' and
``fat as a pig.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My mission is to change the status of the hog,'' he says.
``Our motto is `Livestock no longer.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hedgepeth will sign copies of his book from 10 a.m. to 2 p.m.
Saturday at, appropriately, Dusty's Barbecue, 1815 Briarcliff Road,
404-320-6264.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Country life: Nothing sells a book quicker than a good title,
and Jim Minter has a great one for the collection of columns he has
written for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. ``Some Things I Wish
We Wouldn't Forget (and others I wish we could): Adventures in
goat-keeping, big-city newspapering &AMP; semi-rural living'' (Midtown
Publishing Corp., $24.95) pretty much says it all. As author Terry
Kay aptly writes in his introduction, ``This is the work of a
gifted man who finds joy in the tall tales of gossip, a man who can
be righteously indignant over absurdity, a man who can make you
swallow tears over moments so tender you swear you can taste
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The columns _ which range from humorous tales of goat farming
and rural life to poignant memories of loved ones and war heroes _
do just that. And the proceeds go to a good cause. Minter, a
retired editor of the Journal-Constitution who lives in Fayette
County, is donating profits to the Inman Heritage Trust, a
nonprofit foundation devoted to preserving slices of the rural
past.
</P>
<P>
   Don O' Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
