<HEADER>
A1383 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FINANCIAL-DISTRICT     12-09 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FINANCIAL-DISTRICT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL ST. LIVING: STILL QUIET AFTER THE BULLS GO HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl) 
By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At 8:30 on a Saturday night, the holiday shooting
stars suspended above Nassau Street are aglow, illuminating only
blocks of rolled-down aluminum security shutters. There are no
coffee shops still open, no magazine shops, no bars _ and even more
strikingly _ there are no people.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, men on giant cranes are stringing colored
lights and hanging giant red and green balls on the second-largest
Christmas tree in Manhattan. No one is watching. Tracey White, in a
lipstick-red coat, runs out the door of her apartment at 25 Broad
St., hails a taxi and heads up to the Village for some night life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I moved in last February, there was supposed to be a
grocery store coming,'' she said, looking back pointedly at the
empty ground floor windows in her building, one of the financial
district's new rental conversions. ``It's really dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two years ago, the air was filled with the babble of
developers outbidding one another for the old limestone office
towers along Wall, John and Broad streets, which they announced
they would turn into 7,000 new apartments. Would-be tenants could
be seen on weekends toting newspapers advertising the first wave of
rental apartments. One magazine trumpeted Wall Street as ``New
York's Next Hot Place to Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and developers announced goals for the vast
conversion of vacant office space into rental and condominium
apartments, and dreamed of transforming the Wall Street canyons _
the area roughly bounded by Fulton Street, South Street and
Broadway _ into a 24-hour, seven-day-a-week neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   It is a dream delayed. While no one is labeling the Wall Street
experiment in living a bust, the pace has definitely slowed. In the
last six months, residential development ``has been chilled,'' said
Carl Weisbrod, president of the Alliance for Downtown New York, a
business group that has lobbied hard for that development.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for co-ops and condominiums have fizzled, said developers
and real estate agents interviewed in the last two weeks. Major
projects slated for conversion to condominiums have changed
direction _ either to rentals or to offices, as the market for
downtown office space unexpectedly rebounded. Other developers
backed off from investing when building prices tripled and
quadrupled.
</P>
<P>
   To date, fewer than 2,500 new apartments have been created _
almost all rentals, and the turnover in some of them has been high.
Just ask Todd Parsapour, 24, who moved to Wall Street in July 1997
and left a year later for the West 50s. ``When I graduated in 1997,
10 of my friends went to live at 45 Wall St.,'' he said of a
popular rental conversion. ``I don't think any of them are still
there.'' (Soon, no one will live there. The 441-apartment building
is slated for demolition as part of the New York Stock Exchange's
expansion plans).
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, the financial district ``was billed as either
the Promised Land or the new Wild West,'' said Barbara Corcoran,
chairman of the Corcoran Group. ``But Wall Street still has a
commercial image: when it comes to actually living there, customers
think of dark canyons at night, and that seems foreboding.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Corcoran's company had hung a big red banner outside 17 John
St., advertising condominiums for sale. A month ago, the owners
yanked down the flag and announced they would create 111 rental
units. Greystone &AMP; Co., which owns the office building at 75 Broad
St., has decided the building will remain commercial. Because of
the area's growing popularity with high-tech companies, Greystone
plans to create a technologically ``smart'' building and name it
the New York Technology Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Some developers blamed the increasingly stingy banks for the
lack of condos. Time Equities chief executive Francis Greenburger
said, ``It's hard enough to find anybody to lend money for a rental
down here _ never mind a condo, where the market is considered
riskier.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, developers add that because of the lack of services
in the financial district, including a perceived dearth of schools,
people hesitate to buy a co-op or condominium, but they don't mind
signing a one- or two-year lease at a rent the Corcoran Group says
is at least 15 to 20 percent below those in more established
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The developers call the rental conversions a success, and
Weisbrod said that 1,000 more rental units are in the pipeline.
Nevertheless, he said, three years ago _ right after tax incentives
were passed to speed residential redevelopment _ construction
activity exploded. ``We thought we'd hit 7,000 units a lot
sooner.'' The financial district, he said, is still ``a community
in the making, a community on the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Turri likes living on the edge. Turri, a disk jockey and
aspiring record producer who goes by the name Joe T. Turri, lives
with his label manager, Janine Sugawara, in the curvy red-brick
building at 56 Beaver St. that houses the restaurant Delmonico.
They moved in almost two years ago and pay $1,915-a-month rent.
</P>
<P>
   The couple say they are happy in their one-bedroom apartment,
where the decor is basically a keyboard and a wall of speakers _
along with a large television set. ``I really pump music in here,''
said Turri, 30. ``It's loud, but the walls are thick.''
</P>
<P>
   The desolation appeals to him. ``This is heaven,'' he said,
surveying the empty streets from the building's roof deck. ``This
is like the closest thing to living in the suburbs.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
