<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1745EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FINANCIAL-DISTRICT     12-09 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FINANCIAL-DISTRICT-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the suburbs.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The opening of Cipriani Wall Street has ``brought in a fashion
element,'' Ms. Sugawara said of the limousines pulling up with Puff
Daddy, Martha Stewart and other celebrities. But then she sighed.
``I really wish they'd get a clean, modern grocery store.''
</P>
<P>
   A supermarket _ or the lack of one _ seems to be the rallying
cry of the disenchanted here _ and developers and politicians know
it. Last week, Henry Elghanayan, whose family owns Rockrose
Development, said he was negotiating with supermarket chains,
trying to entice them with ``better rents _ yes, subsidizing them,
in effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The supermarket is targeted for the company's building at 99
John St. And two days ago, Weisbrod announced that the Amish Market
would open a third Manhattan store near Battery Park City _ partly
subsidized by some financial-district developers.
</P>
<P>
   It was Elghanayan who approached Mayor Rudolph Giuliani about
offering developers like himself tax incentives to reinvent the
ailing financial district.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market crash of '87 caused the big office shells
here to empty out,'' he explained. ``There was a flight from
downtown to midtown, where there was an oversupply of brand-new
office space, which was going cheaply.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I had a chat with Rudy at a wedding, where he was
officiating,'' Elghanayan said with a chuckle. ``The tax incentives
_ to give developers eight years with no taxes if they converted
the buildings to residential use _ seemed like a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   The incentives were passed in 1995, and developers started
trading the grand old office towers lining Wall, Broad and Beaver
streets like Monopoly hotels.
</P>
<P>
   But as the developers were ripping apart the venerable buildings
_ putting in new wiring and air-conditioning ducts _ the market
changed in a way that almost no one predicted. Because of the
seemingly endless bull market, the office market came roaring back
(stockbrokers and investment bankers have to work somewhere). And
developers, in the midst of renovations, realized they could make a
lot more money creating new office space _ no gourmet kitchens and
a lot fewer bathrooms. So they changed their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Now the concierge at 40 Wall St., a landmark that Donald Trump
bought with the announced intent of selling condominiums in the
tower, turns apartment hunters away. ``No condos, no apartments,''
the smartly uniformed man said. ``This is Corporate America now!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's winging it down here,'' said Chris Miele, who
bought a loft on Broadway between John Street and Maiden Lane six
months ago. ``On Sunday morning, I have to go to the World Trade
Center to get a newspaper. There's a little store across the
street, but toilet paper is $2 a roll, and my friends say it costs
$10 or $12 for a six-pack of beer.'' For groceries, she goes to the
Gourmet Garage in SoHo and takes a cab home.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miele is one of the area's rare apartment owners. There are
a handful of small co-op buildings, most of them converted in the
early 1980s, with varying success. Catharine Lover and her husband,
Richard Brotherton, bought their apartment at 3 Hanover Square 15
years ago. ``It was cheap,'' he explained. ``And we're not around
on weekends anyway.'' Sales figures, however, show that apartments
there have not appreciated much in value; one owner, who has left
the city, said his apartment had actually depreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miele, who, with a partner, owns Regeneration, a shop full
of 1950s furniture and objects near the Holland Tunnel, bought her
loft for $175,000 _ less than half the price of apartments she'd
looked at in Tribeca. ``I had been looking for a year,'' she said.
``I wanted light, a terrace and a fireplace.'' She laughed. ``I got
none of them.'' She paused. ``But I got 1,100 square feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miele spent last Monday night showing a reporter spots that
stay open _ on weeknights _ and discovered a few places herself.
</P>
<P>
   She began at the Roxy, a diner at 20 John St., which says it is
open 24 hours but closes at 1 p.m. on Saturday and all day Sunday.
Then on to the John Street Bar &AMP; Grill, a vast basement with a pool
table, where bartender Denis Kinkela reports that the clientele has
become a lot younger in the last couple of years. At 55 Liberty
St., Ms. Miele came upon the Divine Bar, which at 7 was crowded
with suits and jackets.
</P>
<P>
   In the back of the bar, David McElroy, 40, an insurance
underwriter, said he moved to Nassau Street because he hated
commuting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you live here, you're serious _ you get to know where
everything is,'' he explained. ``People know where to shop. They
get value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down here, it's not Tribeca. It never will be Tribeca. But
that's OK. It's really OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
