<P>
   COLLEGES
</P>
<P>
   FBC-LAST-HEISMAN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Ricky Williams could soon
become the 63rd college football player to be presented the
prestigious Heisman Trophy by the Downtown Athletic Club . ``He may
be the last,'' said Jim Spitzer, a lawyer representing a group that
holds the club's mortgage. ``He ought not to be.'' The Heisman
Trophy, given each year to the player judged to be the best in all
of college football, is synonymous with success. But the grand old
club that awards the Heisman, and which has one decorating its
lobby, has fallen on some troubled times. The DAC owes $3 million
in back taxes, has filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy and has a $9.5
million mortgage held by a group of outsiders, B&AMP;D Management, very
actively pushing for changes. B&AMP;D could be presenting a plan for
the club in bankruptcy court within a few days of when Williams
picks up the Heisman. (Maher, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   w/FBC-HEISMAN-TROPHY _ Sculptor Frank Eliscu once said of the
Heisman Trophy, ``It was not one of my best works of art, but it
turned out to be like the Statue of Liberty: not beautiful, but
it's dear to people's hearts.'' Eliscu, who died two years ago,
created a wide variety of works during his lifetime, including the
Cascade of Books outside the Library of Congress and a Presidential
Eagle for the Oval Office. Yet, his most coveted work, the one that
every college football player in this country would love to own,
was his first commission. And yes, there was a real, live,
football-playing model that posed for Eliscu, although he would not
find out his role in creating the Heisman Trophy until decades
later. (Maher, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-HEISMAN-VOTERS _ How does the Heisman Trophy process work?
Who votes? What do the voters look for? How are the votes counted?
What part of the country usually swings the vote? All like that.
(Maher, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-DOAK-WALKER-HOME-DEPOT _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Previewing the Doak
Walker and Home Depot college football awards show. (Wangrin,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   UT-WOMENS-VOLLEY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas has reached the Sweet
16 again in volleyball. The women's team plays Stanford in one
semifinals Friday and if it wins, the Longhorns play Saturday at
7:30 p.m. against Illinois or Long Beach State for a trip to the
Final Four. Developing. (Rosner, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
