<P>
   BENGALS-FRANCIS _ CINCINNATI _ National Football League players
don't have the right to choose their own successors, but James
Francis is going to have some input when the Cincinnati Bengals
start looking for a new left outside linebacker. In recent weeks,
the 30-year-old Francis' playing time has diminished, partly
because of a knee injury and partly because the 2-11 Bengals want
to look at younger players such as rookie linebackers Adrian Ross
and Steve Foley. Francis sees nothing extraordinary about helping
younger players who are trying to take his job. (Williams, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NUHN-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ I'd have fired him. You'd have
fired him, too. Lee Johnson wrote his own ticket out of Cincinnati
on Sunday when he said there was no way he'd attend a Bengal game
as a fan. It doesn't matter if it's true. This is about common
sense. Mike Brown did what Johnson forced him to: He released his
punter and went on to the next page. (Nuhn, Dayton Daily News )
MOVED
</P>
