</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-MISSILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT PRESSES RUSSIA ON MISSILE SALES TO IRAN  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
pressed the Russian foreign minister Wednesday for a Russian
commitment to limit cooperation with the Iranian missile program.
</P>
<P>
   An American official said Albright, who is here for a NATO
meeting, had reminded Igor Ivanov, the foreign minister, that the
United States provided financial support to keep Russian scientists
from going to work on foreign weapons programs and had urged the
Russian government to ``make a maximum effort'' to limit technology
transfers.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after meetings with Ivanov, Albright
described the issue of Russian cooperation with Iranian programs as
``an issue of major concern to us.'' She said she hoped to begin a
new round of talks on reducing United States and Russian nuclear
arsenals next month on a visit to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov told allied foreign ministers that by the end of the
month the Russian Parliament would ratify a treaty that the two
countries signed in 1993 to cut nuclear stockpiles, to 3,000 to
3,500 warheads each.
</P>
<P>
   Delays in ratification of the treaty had made it uncertain when
the next round of cuts in nuclear arms would begin.
</P>
<P>
   NATO foreign ministers met Ivanov here after frictions resulted
from the alliance's decision in October to threaten Serbia with
bombing unless its forces stopped attacking ethnic Albanians in the
Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russia objected, and Ivanov said here Russia still believed that
NATO could not use force outside its territory without a mandate
from the U.N Security Council, a mandate that Russia blocked for
Kosovo. But he said Russian relations with the alliance were much
better than they were a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Russia was smarting from a NATO decision in July
1997 to admit three former Warsaw Pact members, the Czech Republic,
Hungary and Poland, to NATO next year.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ivanov said Russia still believed that expanding the
alliance was a mistake, he added that Moscow was considering
whether ``technical problems'' stood in the way of a NATO
invitation to join air surveillance over Kosovo to monitor the
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Russian civilian monitors will also be in Kosovo, with a
European team protected by a NATO force in Macedonia, and Russian
troops are working with NATO forces in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Albright invited Ivanov or Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov to
Washington in April to meet President Clinton and other allied
leaders. The allies agreed to regular meetings with the Russians
after Moscow had reluctantly acquiesced in the Czech, Hungarian and
Polish NATO memberships. Ivanov did not say whether the Russian
leadership would accept the invitation to the meeting, which would
be on the fringes of a celebration of the 50th anniversary of the
alliance and include its three new members.
</P>
<P>
   Albright and other allied officials said the Foreign Minister
had reacted positively to NATO proposals to adapt a treaty that
would limit conventional forces in Europe to take into account the
collapse of the Warsaw Pact. The Soviet-led alliance signed the
treaty with NATO in 1990, shortly before it collapsed, and many
former members started trying to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Talks on adapting the treaty will begin next year in Vienna and
are to end by November 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The allied proposal for reworking the treaty said many NATO
countries were prepared to accept significant reductions in their
arsenals of tanks, artillery and armored vehicles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1746EST &QL; 
