A1394 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PINOCHET-CHILE-NYT &LR;      12-09 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-CHILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILE RECALLS AMBASSADOR TO LONDON TO PROTEST PINOCHET RULING  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ The Chilean government recalled its ambassador
to London Wednesday to protest the British home secretary's refusal
to block a Spanish extradition request for Gen. Augusto Pinochet,
Chile's onetime dictator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government energetically rejects the decision by Secretary
Jack Straw,'' said Interior Minister Raul Troncoso, speaking for
President Eduardo Frei, who was in Brazil when the British decision
was announced. ``No tribunal of a foreign country has the right to
judge a Chilean citizen who has committed crimes in our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Warning of ``worrisome passions'' that might still be set loose
here, Troncoso pledged that Chile would continue appeals to try to
block the extradition, a process that could take months or even
years.
</P>
<P>
   The recall of Ambassador Mario Artaza follows weeks of public
criticism by senior conservative opposition politicians that the
government was not using all its diplomatic influence to defend
Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   In recent private meetings of military commanders, several
officers called for the government to cut off diplomatic relations
with Britain and Spain despite their importance as Chilean trading
partners, sources of foreign investment and arms suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   The newest legal setback for Pinochet came as no surprise. The
early reaction in Santiago was muted compared with the anger
expressed by some and the joy expressed by others two weeks ago
when England's highest court, drawn from the House of Lords, ruled
that Pinochet did not have immunity for crimes committed when he
was a head of state. Spanish courts are seeking the extradition of
the 83-year-old general on charges of genocide, terrorism and
torture in connection with the murders or ``disappearances'' of
3,179 people in the years after he seized power in Chile in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrations by activists of the left and right have been
largely orderly, with only sporadic incidents of violence, since
Pinochet was first arrested in London two months ago. But some
political analysts have suggested that violence will become more
likely if Pinochet is blocked from returning home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to be calm, but let's not forget that General
Pinochet created all we have today in Chile,'' said Hernan Guiloff,
head of the Pinochet Foundation, a group dedicated to promoting the
former dictator's image.
</P>
<P>
   Viviana Diaz, leader of the Group of the Families of the
Detained and Disappeared, said: ``We're satisfied and we're happy.
After 25 years of being denied justice in Chile, we're finally
getting somewhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1747EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1399 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KNIGHTS-OF-INDULGENCE     12-09 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNIGHTS-OF-INDULGENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMMUNITY OF ACTORS, BUT HARDLY COMMUNITY THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.C., Del., Texas, Nev.)   (bl)  
 By SHAWN G. KENNEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRUCKEE, Calif. _ A man and woman locked in an amorous embrace
tumbled again and again across three folding chairs. At first jerky
and self-conscious, with each repetition the actors' movements
became smoother and more confident. As the choreography of their
entanglement was refined, dialogue was added and other characters
joined the skit; a slapstick Marx-brothers-style bit emerged.
</P>
<P>
   The Knights of Indulgence Theater United States were being
serious about being silly. For the next few hours, rehearsing in a
community center gymnasium here, members of this small theater
company polished ``Marxist Quack'' and other comedy sketches,
pantomimes, monologues and dance numbers for ``Punch and Cookies,''
the troupe's current show.
</P>
<P>
   ``With `Punch and Cookies' everyone is just sort of getting
things out of their brains,'' said Brent Lindsay, a company member
who is directing ``Marxist Quack.'' ``It is experimental, very
unstructured, even for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Knights of Indulgence audiences, Lindsay added, have come to
expect the unexpected. ``People who come to our shows are
curious,'' he said during a break in the rehearsal. ``They know by
now that they won't be getting just another road company version of
`Grease.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Other pieces in the show are as esoteric as ``Marxist
Quack'' is zany and accessible. ``Glass Cage,'' for example, was
inspired by the music of Philip Glass and John Cage. Frida Kahlo,
the Mexican painter, figures into the plot of another vignette.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of material is not the only expression of risk-taking
for the Knights of Indulgence players. Last year, seven of them _
Lindsay, Margret Moreira Valdes, Beth Lorio, Stephen Patterson,
Andy Thornton, Amy Pinto and Barry Morgan _ pulled up stakes after
four years in Delaware and headed for Truckee, a town in the Sierra
Nevada mountains near Lake Tahoe that only Lindsay had visited
before. Like some traveling New Age circus, they just showed up and
started performing.
</P>
<P>
   Their faith that an audience would emerge for their
anything-goes brand of theater was rewarded. The company's first
show, ``Hallows Eve in Brickeltown,'' drew more than 150 children
and adults. In June the Knights of Indulgence presented ``Silent
Night,'' three short plays without dialogue that recreated the
silent screen for the stage. It played in Truckee as well as at
nearby Tahoe City.
</P>
<P>
   Though much of the troupe's work is shaped by a reverence for
medicine shows, vaudeville and silent films, nothing seems beyond
its consideration. ``We're thinking of developing a lounge act,''
said Thornton, with no hint of sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   The Knights of Indulgence players, whose average age is 30, met
in the mid-1980s at the North Carolina School of the Arts in
Winston-Salem. They kept in touch, and five years ago the former
classmates were reunited when Morgan, now on a leave of absence,
invited some of his college friends to join him for a summer of
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan had the use of a one-room schoolhouse on a farm his
mother owned in Roxana, Del.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been trying since college to figure out a way to work
together,'' said Patterson, who was playing in a band in Austin,
Texas, when he heard from Morgan. ``After five years it seemed like
it was never going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   They were drawn to the project by the prospect of theater on
their own terms. Ms. Lorio said, ``A big part of our sensibility as
a company, particularly in the beginning, had to do with us wanting
complete control over everything, because coming out of school,
coming out of our respective experiences with charismatic but
controlling theatrical leaders gave us a need for that.''
</P>
<P>
   They are also musicians and dancers as well as actors, and they
write their material and most of the music for their shows, build
sets and take turns directing.
</P>
<P>
   What started as a summer theater project gradually grew into a
full-fledged company as more in the group settled in Delaware. But
after four years, the Knights of Indulgence decided that their
commune-style living and location, in the middle of chicken-farming
country, were liabilities to their development. Seven of the nine
members agreed to give Northern California a try.
</P>
<P>
   Truckee, with its proximity to Lake Tahoe and Reno, Nev., held
the prospect of larger audiences and flexible jobs in restaurants
and shops that allow the performers to devote as much time as
possible to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Knights of Indulgence have not turned a profit on
any production, many costs, such as rent on the rehearsal space,
are covered by members. The next goal is to find a permanent home
for the company, which is looking for someone to donate space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to up the ante,'' Ms. Valdes said. ``We want expand
our repertory and to be out in front of audiences more than two or
three times each year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
