<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GANGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES SKEPTICAL OF CHICAGO'S ANTI-GANG LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for Chicago and the American Civil
Liberties Union squared off Wednesday before an apparently divided
Supreme Court over the constitutionality of a city ordinance that
increases the authority of police in combating gang violence.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Rosenthal, Chicago's deputy corporation counsel, told
the justices that the threat of violence justifies the ordinance,
which allows police to disperse people congregating on street
corners if an officer believes a gang member is present.
</P>
<P>
   But ACLU attorney Harvey Grossman countered that Chicago's Gang
Congregation Ordinance is unconstitutionally vague, making it too
easy for police to act arbitrarily and punish law-abiding citizens
in the officers' zeal to frighten gang members.
</P>
<P>
   Several justices questioned the law's constitutionality, asking
Rosenthal what protection it provides to innocent residents who
unknowingly find themselves on the same street corner as a gang
member. However, justices also asked Grossman whether the
Constitution is flexible enough to let police take extraordinary
steps to prevent the scourge of gang violence.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU's argument has won before Illinois judges as the state
Supreme Court said the ordinance unreasonably infringes on the
liberty of people standing in public places. Chicago appealed the
case to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal, pressing Chicago's case, urged the justices to uphold
the ordinance, which the city suspended after the state appellate
court decision three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter, addressing Rosenthal, expressed concern
that the ordinance enables police to arrest law-abiding people who
are perhaps doing nothing more threatening than watching cars go by
while standing near a stranger on a street corner. Under the
statute, police can order the people to leave if the stranger is a
suspected gang member; officers can then arrest the people if they
refuse to leave, Souter said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal responded that the city was justified, due to
escalating violence, in passing a reasonable ordinance to give
police greater authority to disperse suspected gang members,
particularly in high-crime neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these neighborhoods, police can't tell if people are just
watching cars go by,'' Rosenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   Souter also noted that the ordinance gives people no guidance
for determining when they are running afoul of the law. ``It's a
judgment that's left entirely to the police,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said the controversial statute has
the ``potential for arbitrariness by the police.'' Even a good
Samaritan urging gang members to abandon their violent ways can be
ordered to leave if a policeman sees her dispensing the advice on a
sidewalk, O'Connor added.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer said the ordinance might discourage
law-abiding residents from leaving their homes, fearing arrest if
they innocently walk near a gang member when a policeman is
present.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Rosenthal said the ordinance's goal is not only to
scare gang members but to protect law-abiding citizens from
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Police, by dispersing groups of individuals, protect innocent
residents from the potential harm of being near a gang member if a
rival attempts a drive-by shooting, Rosenthal said. In addition,
the police dispersal of people makes it more difficult for gangs to
recruit new members on public streets, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU's Grossman said the ordinance unconstitutionally lets
police target anybody loitering on a street corner, whether they
belong to a gang or not.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Antonin Scalia and Breyer asked Grossman whether the
authority the ordinance gives police is any different than the
recognized right of officers to set up roadblocks and arbitrarily
test motorists to determine if they are driving drunk. Both police
actions are designed to prevent people from getting hurt or killed,
the justices said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Grossman said a drunken driver presents a more
immediate threat to public safety than do people standing on street
corners. Grossman argued the case on behalf of Jesus Morales and
about 65 other people arrested under the controversial law.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
