<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Dec. 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL FORECAST Thursday, December 10, 1998  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy snow fell Wednesday afternoon in the mountains of southern
Colorado as moist air from the southeast was drawn up the sloping
terrain ahead of an upper-level low pressure system pressing slowly
over Arizona. Thursday, the sluggish low will expand its inclement
sphere of influence to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A chilly rain will soak parts of southern, central and eastern
Texas as invading moist air from the Gulf of Mexico glides over
cooler air near the ground. Under assault from invading Gulf air,
cool air will retreat westward during the day, eventually halting
across central and northeast Texas. It is here that rain may be
heaviest as advancing moist Gulf air clashes and rises over defiant
cool air. Between one and three inches of rain are possible, with
thunder punctuating some of the rain. Thunderstorms are also
possible in the milder, moister air that will replace cool air
along the Texas seaboard. Rain will spread to parts of Arkansas and
Louisiana, while snow will fall on the high ground of west Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Winds gusting as high as 100 mph will course through mountain
passes in southern California as air circulating westward around
the periphery of strong high pressure in Nevada accelerates through
narrow canyons. Near the core of the cold high, temperatures will
again plummet below zero degrees Fahrenheit early Thursday morning
in a few spots across northern Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, patches of morning fog will develop across the still
parched northern Middle Atlantic States, where welcome rains
moistened the ground early this week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Focus: Canyon Winds &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Winds gusted to 100 mph through narrow canyons of the Santa Ana
Mountains in southern California Wednesday. These infamous Santa
Ana winds blow when air moving westward around strong high pressure
over the Great Basin accelerates as it squeezes through mountain
passes on descent from the high deserts on southern Nevada,
southern Utah, southern California and eastern Arizona. The Great
Basin high derived its strength from weighty cold air at low levels
in addition to the weighty convergence of air at high altitudes.
Gusts to 100 mph will roar through narrow canyons again Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
