<SLUG> BC-U.N.-RACISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL ASSEMBLY LISTS ANTI-SEMITISM AS A FORM OF RACISM  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ For the first time in more than half a century,
the U.N. General Assembly decided Wednesday to list anti-Semitism
as a form of racism.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was adopted by consensus on the 50th anniversary
of the international convention against genocide and a day before
the United Nations celebrates the 50th anniversary of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   In a resolution introduced by Indonesia on behalf of more than
100 developing nations, the Assembly also warned against new
avenues for disseminating the ``repugnant views'' of racist
organizations, and asked governments to monitor communications for
misuse. Germany and Turkey co-sponsored the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   General Assembly resolutions do not carry the force of Security
Council resolutions, but they reflect world opinion. In the past,
the Assembly had voted to equate Zionism with racism.
</P>
<P>
   After the Cold War ended, the United States was able to have
those definitions removed from annual Assembly resolutions on human
rights. This year the Clinton administration lobbied hard to
include a condemnation of anti-Semitism in the resolution, titled
Measures to Combat Contemporary Forms of Racism, Racial
Discrimination, Xenophobia and Related Intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.N. is about tolerance and inclusion,'' said Felice Gaer,
director of Jacob Blaustein Institute for the Advancement of Human
Rights, at the American Jewish Committee. ``But this is the first
time that the U.N. has used the phrase `anti-Semitism,' which has
been fought over for years and kept out of any resolutions.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase just narrowly made it into the resolution. In a
paragraph whose language Geraldine Ferraro helped negotiate four
years ago when she was the chief American representative at the
U.N. Human Rights Commission, the General Assembly listed a number
of targets to be investigated by the United Nations monitor on
racism.
</P>
<P>
   The monitor, known as a special rapporteur, was asked to examine
racist incidents ``against blacks, Arabs and Muslims'' and
``xenophobia, Negrophobia, anti-Semitism and related intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary General Kofi Annan has lent his voice to broadening
definitions of intolerance, and for changes in the attitude of
members toward Israel, which is still denied a place in any of the
organization's regional groups. It is these groups that choose
candidates for rotating Security Council seats and other positions.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in March in Jerusalem to the Israel Foreign
Relations Council and the U.N. Association of Israel, Annan said he
was aware that ``the United Nations is regarded by many as biased
against the State of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Israelis see hypocrisy and double standards in the
intense scrutiny given to some of its actions, while other
situations fail to elicit the world's outrage and condemnations,''
he said. ``I know that Israelis are offended when other nations'
delegates leave the room as Israelis rise to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan said it was time ``to usher in a new era of relations
between Israel and the United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1755EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1419 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHORS-REMNICK-SPI &LR;      12-09 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-REMNICK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW NEW YORKER EDITOR RE-ENTERS BOOK RING WITH A MUCH-PUMMELED
ALI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali has been inspected, dissected, recapitulated,
covered in every form of print and picture, as befits one of the
most famous icons of this media-saturated century.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that deterred David Remnick from pursuing Ali once
more for his own book. Part of that decision came from the fact
that Ali was one of Remnick's youthful heroes, along with Bob
Dylan. But Remnick _ who won the Pulitzer Prize for ``Lenin's
Tomb,'' his first book on the Soviet Union _ was also drawn to
Ali's story because of what it represents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to write a book that had the lines of a traditional
American novel,'' Remnick said in an interview. ``Most readers may
think of Ali as the most famous mug and pug on the face of the
Earth, someone with an electric presence. But after two big baggy
books on Russia, with too many characters and subplots, Ali's
story, focused on a finite time, really has the classical lines of
a novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have an American character who creates himself, a hero who
faces obstacles, overcomes them and changes over time, and you have
antagonist characters who reflect and oppose the hero. I can tell
you I was damn grateful to get a story with that narrative
possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Remnick's ``King of the World: Muhammad Ali and the Rise of an
American Hero'' (Random House, 306 pages, $25) delivers a knockout
punch of a book, as quick-paced as an Ali Shuffle, but also slyly
deceptive in its economy. For in this era of doorstop biographies
of minor-league luminaries, Remnick uses a modest 300 pages to zero
in relentlessly on that fascinating, formative period when Cassius
Clay became Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   This subject might seem an odd choice for someone esteemed for
foreign correspondence and who recently was named the editor of The
New Yorker, to a five-minute ovation from the staff, after working
six years there as a staff writer and producing more than 100
articles.
</P>
<P>
   But the 40-year-old New Jersey native, a Wunderkind of the print
world, has a resume that includes a stint as a sportswriter on The
Washington Post and has always been known for his willingness to
cover anything that moves across the wide open spaces of his
eclectic interests.
</P>
<P>
   That might be reportorial chutzpah, but, in Remnick's case, it
is tempered with modesty, humor and self-awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of the World'' showcases Remnick's great talent for
mining vast resources of material and then forging that material
into a compelling narrative. Remnick's writing distinguishes itself
through adroit use of telling quotations, pivotal incidents and
such high-wire descriptions as ``(Sonny) Liston trained the way
Liberace played piano; it was a garish representation of a boxer at
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Remnick also manages to provide insight and context about such
disparate subjects as the mob's onetime stranglehold on boxing,
Malcolm X's split with the Black Muslims and the practice of sports
photography.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of the World'' is a book about boxing, but a book about
boxing in the way that ``The Old Man and the Sea'' is a book about
fishing. The subject is merely an entree to examine more
fundamental questions.
</P>
<P>
   How Cassius Clay transformed himself into Muhammad Ali is
depicted by Remnick as an inspired and willful act of
self-invention squarely in the long American tradition of Davy
Crockett, Walt Whitman and Buffalo Bill. But behind Ali's acute
instincts as a showman was an often-overlooked work ethic that
dated from the days when he first put on boxing gloves as an
89-pound 12-year-old who pronounced himself ready for a fight after
having his new bike stolen.
</P>
<P>
   As Remnick writes: ``(Ali) proved to be one of the
hardest-working athletes anyone had ever seen in Louisville. From
the moment Clay won that first fight, he would come home in the
evening and tell his parents how he was going to become champion of
the world, was going to buy them all new cars and a new place to
live. ... He didn't just talk about it. Cassius practically lived
in the gym. He never smoked, never drank. ... Clay was training
like a professional when he was still in his mid-teens. At 18, he
had already compiled an amazing amateur record: 100 wins and only
eight losses, two national Golden Gloves championships, and two
national Amateur Athletic Union titles.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali still had to surmount his own demons, his great fear of
flying that prompted him to don a surplus parachute during his
first airplane flight to the Rome Olympics. But perhaps no fear was
greater than that of entering the ring as the underdog challenger
to the fearsome champ Sonny Liston. It was the first and only time
that Ali admitted he felt fear in the ring, fear that he usually
KO'd through outrageous pre-fight antics designed to psych out
opponents but also to fortify his own psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Ali now is a shell of his former self, shackled by all the
punishment he received in the ring and also by Parkinson's disease.
But Remnick, whose father also has Parkinson's, found the champion
at peace with himself during the day they spent together at his
Michigan farm.
</P>
<P>
   Remnick considers that time with Ali _ much of it spent watching
tapes of his ring exploits _ to be ``a great gift.'' The writer
uses that original material to open and close the book on lingering
high notes of power and poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ali is an American myth who has come to mean many things to
many people: a symbol of faith, a symbol of conviction and
defiance, a symbol of beauty and skill and courage, a symbol of
racial pride, of wit and love,'' Remnick writes. ``Ali's physical
condition is shocking not least because it is an accelerated form
of what we all fear, the progression of aging, the unpredictability
and danger of life. In Ali we see the frailty of even a man whose
job it was to be the most fearsome figure on the globe.''
</P>
<P>
   Remnick, like Ali, has enjoyed great success at an early age.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated summa cum laude from Princeton after studying with
writing legend John McPhee. He was posted to Moscow at 28 for what
became ``the most incredible experience of my life'' as he
chronicled the collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Then he succeeded media star Tina Brown as editor of The New
Yorker a few months before his 40th birthday. That plum job came
his way, even though his past editing experience was limited to his
stint at the helm of the twice-yearly Pascack Valley High School
Smoke Signal. And ascension to his dream job occurred only after
New Yorker owner S.I. Newhouse rescinded his day-old offer to
Michael Kinsley, the editor of Microsoft's online magazine Slate.
Kinsley draws nothing but praise from Remnick.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing that Remnick seems to have failed to
achieve was his onetime dream of becoming a rock musician. His
rhythm-guitar work contributed to what he now considers the
necessary demise of Derek and the Dialectics, a truly terrible
group that assaulted the eardrums of fellow Princeton students just
twice.
</P>
<P>
   Remnick looks back at what he has achieved and attributes it to
``luck and elbow grease.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a pretty good writer and a pretty good reporter,
but luck is not to be overestimated,'' he said. ``Luck is why I got
sent to Moscow and luck may be partly why I got this new job at The
New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   Remnick readily admitted that he is ``still learning'' in his
new job, but delights in shouldering the responsibility to choose
and edit the articles in the prestigious magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm over the moon in love with The New Yorker,'' Remnick
emphasized. ``I want it every week to be as great as it can be.
There are very few venues where there is no excuse for not being
great. We have no excuse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
