A1423 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAUGHING-AT-DEATH-TEX     12-09 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUGHING-AT-DEATH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBITUARY GAME AMUSES, ENRAGES RADIO LISTENERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first day it was Carroll O'Connor. Then it was David
Letterman. The bonus round one morning was the woman with Marty
Feldman eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Can you pick which of the photographs on The Dallas Morning News
obituary page most resembles those celebrities? Be the ninth caller
to get it right, and you win CDs and a T-shirt. If you're real
lucky, you take home the camcorder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrity Stiffies,'' a game on Dallas station KDGE (94.5 FM),
is the latest radio gag to raise the questions of what's funny, and
what's offensive.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, it's not Howard Stern. It's not gay jokes, sex
talk or racist jabs. This time, radio hosts are making fun of the
one thing we all have in common, besides taxes: death.
</P>
<P>
   While entertainers try to put the ``fun'' into funeral, not
everyone agrees that it works.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does `beneath contempt' sound?'' said Bob Mong, Morning
News president and general manager. ``Those are two words that pop
into my mind. It's grotesque and it's horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas journalism Professor Marvin Olasky said
society has long made light of the things it didn't understand,
death included. But the trend he sees is no laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   The movie ``Pulp Fiction'' broke ground with its dark-humor view
of death and torture. Since then, films such as ``Very Bad Things''
have taken death to new highs, or new lows, depending on your
taste.
</P>
<P>
   Olasky said the problem with the radio game is that it takes
mankind's nervousness about death and unleashes it on a ritual that
helps people mourn: the obituaries. ``It's a theater of cruelty,''
Olasky said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jagger, the radio host who invented the game, said death
is part of the human experience, and therefore, fodder for humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death is so scary you do one of two things: You huddle and
you're afraid, or you do what I do, the opposite _ you find
something humorous in it, and go with that angle,'' Jagger said.
``I know, there's a real divided line; it's either a sacred thing,
one of those you-shouldn't-go-there areas, or it's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea came to him last week when a co-host was reading the
morning obituaries. Why would a 32-year-old man read about
strangers who died? The question was a topic of banter when Jagger
noticed one of the dead men looked like Archie Bunker. So he asked
listeners if they agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Jagger said that some callers are offended, but that every time
the alternative rock station plays the game, the ``phone lines are
jammed.'' They play only on the mornings he finds a celebrity
look-alike in the obituaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people understand what we're doing is harmless, bringing
notoriety to these people who got no recognition in life, and we're
giving them one more plug on the way out,'' Jagger said.
</P>
<P>
   Mong, at ``The Morning News,'' did not know about the contest
until asked for his reaction. He said he didn't know what action,
if any, the newspaper will take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of us feel there is a sanctity to the passing of a
human being, and to make light of it is sort of beyond belief,''
Mong said. ``This whole thing violates what human beings feel is a
decent and good way to behave.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's DJs asked callers one morning to find which of the
men in military uniforms most resembled Billy Baldwin. Another day,
the only possible match was a man who favored Ed McMahon ``after
eight chemo treatments,'' Jagger said. ``So we drew the line there.
We didn't play that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jensen, a University of Texas professor of media law and
ethics, said the game is part of a trend in which sick humor sells,
and humanity suffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This death stuff even pushes it further,'' Jensen said. ``Our
collective humanity doesn't mean anything. In a way, it's more
frightening. It's not targeting groups that can be easily trashed.
It's saying everybody is up for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Jagger stands by his game. ``We don't sit there and think,
`Let's do this game and see how much money we can make.' Why did
CBS run Jack Kevorkian whacking off some guy? Is it about ratings?
Absolutely it's about ratings. My job is to get as many listeners
as possible. How do I get them? Here you go.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDBO/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
