<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S KEROSENE KING, LIKE GATES, WAS TITAN OF CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a man who's been dead for 61 years, John D. Rockefeller sure
gets his picture in the newspaper a lot. His visage glares down
from articles on the proposed Exxon-Mobil merger. He is widely
compared with Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   It is an apt comparison. Each saw a future that others didn't,
and started a company from scratch. Each was a success by 25 and a
tycoon by 35. Each held a 90 percent market share. Each was
vilified by rivals and targeted by trust-busters. Each was
convinced of his own good and treated his accusers with some
disdain.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ron Chernow's bestselling book, ``Titan,'' when
Rockefeller created Standard Oil in the 1860s, all the petroleum in
the world was produced in one corner of Pennsylvania.
(``Pennzoil,'' indeed.) Nobody knew when the wells would play out,
or whether ``rock oil'' could be extracted anywhere else. The price
of oil was at the mercy of each new gusher.
</P>
<P>
   Oil was then refined into kerosene, which competed with a
distillate of turpentine for use in lanterns and stoves. Refining,
writes Chernow, was largely conducted by Civil War veterans who
``betrayed little sense of how to fashion a stable, lasting
business.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1890, Rockefeller had changed everything. He had connected
the wells by pipeline. He had bought out the little refineries,
which were constantly catching fire, and built big ones. He had
built his own barrels, then railcars and then ships. He had
provided his blue cans of kerosene to customers all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   He was a master negotiator. In 1868 he cut a deal with rail
tycoon Jay Gould for a 75 percent discount on the Erie Railroad.
This was attacked as an unfair rebate. Journalist Ida Tarbell wrote
years later that it allowed Rockefeller to succeed though he ``had
no legitimate superiority over those competing with him.''
</P>
<P>
   That depends on what's legitimate and what's not. His deal cut
the Erie's unit costs. It required Rockefeller to run his Cleveland
refineries at full bore, regardless of the markets.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller would use rebates for decades. Most controversial
was his 1872 scheme in which Standard and its allies would get
rebates not only on their business but their competitors'. (And
Microsoft used to charge on a PC maker's entire volume, Windows and
non-Windows.) The 1872 scheme provoked a boycott by well owners and
quickly fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller has been charged with cutting prices in one market
in order to block a competitor. He occasionally did that, Chernow
writes. But Rockefeller's main way of forestalling competitors was
to keep prices low everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Chernow writes, ``He was obsessed with high-volume, low-cost
production to maintain market share.'' In 1890, Rockefeller boasted
that in 20 years, kerosene had plunged from 23.5 cents a gallon at
retail to 7.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller didn't try to stamp out competitors so much as bring
them under one tent. A master competitor, he hated unruly
competition. Yet the opening of the first gas station in 1907
increased competition by vastly expanding the market.
</P>
<P>
   Globally, Shell was already challenging Standard's blue cans
with its red ones, which were filled with kerosene from Russia.
Sun, Texaco and Gulf were formed after the gusher at Spindletop,
Texas, in 1901. By 1911, when Standard Oil was broken up into what
now includes Exxon, Mobil, Chevron, Arco and Conoco, its market
share had already slipped.
</P>
<P>
   It had, however, been dominant for years. Most of those who had
challenged it, including Tarbell's father, had cause to regret it.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the reason was Rockefeller himself. He was ``a matchless
executive,'' Chernow writes. A sponge of information, he was ``an
unerring monitor of the stream of proposals channeled to him
daily.'' He was a math whiz, and used numbers to ``cut through the
false claims of subordinates'' and impose rationality on the
farthest corners of his business.
</P>
<P>
   His success forestalled the plans of others. Whether they would
have developed the industry faster if he hadn't done it first is a
question ``that allows no easy answer,'' Chernow writes. All we can
say is that he did it and they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said of Gates. One difference: Kerosene was a
commodity; Windows is a copyrighted product. That may make Gates's
position harder to break in the market, but easier to explain to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   Gates also has a more favorable public. When Standard Oil was in
the dock, muckrakers and socialists had businessmen under withering
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Today, said Chernow to Fortune magazine, ``we are living through
a period that glorifies business heroes.'' The average American is
less likely to curse Microsoft than to buy shares in it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1803EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
