<HEADLINE>
NEWS ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cars that Open up to Computers, Literally &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, computers are on a collision course with cars.
On Dec. 5, the British journal New Scientist reported a new
automotive use for the infrared port on the popular Palm Pilot
handheld organizers.
</P>
<P>
   After modifying the Pilot to capture and retransmit infrared
signals from a television set, in an attempt to use the Pilot as a
replacement for the standard remote control device, a computer
journalist discovered that it could also duplicate the signals that
control some automobile security systems.
</P>
<P>
   After the owner locks the car using a remote control device
(typically on the keychain) and walks away, the Pilot could capture
the signal, send it back to the car and unlock the doors. According
to the Insurance Information Institute in New York, 23.5 percent of
all cars built in North America in 1997 had electronic anti-theft
systems, though many use radio waves, not infrared, systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Pilot represents a potentially cheaper alternative for those
auto thieves thinking of paying thousands of dollars for
black-market devices that perform similar tricks.
</P>
<P>
   According to the newspaper LA Weekly, some car thieves in Los
Angeles are using custom-made electronic devices the size of a
walkie-talkie that send out volleys of automobile security code
combinations. Thieves park near the target car and bombard it
electronically for a couple of minutes until the car's security
system chirps and the doors unlock.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier this year, the Mercedes-Benz division of what is now
DaimlerChrysler Corp. warned that the electromagnetic radiation
generated by the microprocessors in mobile phones could disrupt the
computer circuitry in airbag restraint systems, anti-lock brake
systems and potentially other electronic systems in the car.
</P>
<P>
   And you thought talking on a cellular phone while driving was
dangerous. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter H. Lewis &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Low-Tech Companion For High-Tech Goofing Off &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the low-tech innovation file comes a new way to evade the
snooping eyes of Big Brother, Corporate America, siblings, spouses
and all other off-line interlopers. It's a device known as ``Cyber
Eyes.'' So what exactly is this high-tech-era digital defender?
Nothing more than a rear-view mirror specially built to be affixed
to a monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that a corporate citizen who might be surfing the
Net rather than crunching a spreadsheet, or playing Minesweeper
instead of catering to a client, can check to see if the boss is
coming up quickly from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It prevents bad hair days, and it keeps you from getting
ambushed in your cubicle,'' said its creator, Ellen Hendin, the
Cleveland entrepreneur behind Cyber Eyes Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hendin meant the $4.99 mirror as a gag gift, but there has
been nothing funny about the strong sales, she said. Now Ms.
Hendin, a former financial securities analyst, has taken on the
business full time. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps We Should Be Amazed That It Can Surf the Web at All &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since 3Com announced its newest version of the popular Palm
Pilot, the Palm VII, it has been criticized by some users for
offering only limited Web access. That access, called Web
Clippings, allows Palm users to see updated, albeit abridged,
information from 22 corporate Web sites through a wireless
connection.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Sipher, director of wireless products for 3Com, of Santa
Clara, Calif., said the company had concluded that it would be too
costly and unwieldy to offer full Web access on its personal
digital assistant. ``Try hooking into the Web on a Windows CE
device,'' he said. ``It's a terrible, terrible experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The information available through Web Clippings is restricted to
that which is well suited for the Palm's small screen and very slow
access speed of 8 kilobits per second. For instance, Etrade will
allow access to stock quotes, but not trades; the Yahoo function
will allow telephone and address searches, and USA Today Online
will provide a digest of news and sports.
</P>
<P>
   The service is not designed to offer general Web access, nor is
it cheap. The wireless access will cost $9.99 a month for about 6
transactions a day, or $24.99 for up to 18 a day, Sipher said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lowly PDA Stylus Is Going Multimedia &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With personal digital assistants continuing to add more
functions, it was only a matter of time before some company decided
that the stylus _ that inkless pen used to write on and access data
from PDAs _ needed upgrading, too.
</P>
<P>
   Pilot Corp., a pen maker, has joined a handful of smaller
companies in marketing styluses that aren't just styluses anymore.
The new-fangled Pentopia line, due out in stores in January,
combines a stylus, a ballpoint pen and, in one case, a pencil. This
triple-threat will sell for $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may want to get information with the stylus _ at times
they have to sign something and they turn around and there are no
pens available,'' said a company spokeswoman, Cindy Jecusco.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even now someone's working on a laptop tote bag that
doubles as a briefcase. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Virgina Panel Recommends Tough New Penalties on Spam &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Virginia will not be the first state to pass a law against mass
producers of electronic junk mail. But what the state lacked in
speed, it may make up with strength, and the impact could be
widespread.
</P>
<P>
   A commission appointed by Gov. Jim Gilmore has recommended
imposing criminal and civil penalties, including possible jail
terms, for sending spam using Internet service providers based in
Virginia. In an interview this week, Gilmore said that the
recommended penalties suited him just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a model for many other states,'' said the
governor, who has referred to Virginia as the ``Internet capital of
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion from the panel, the Commission on Information
Technology, suggested extending the Virginia Computer Crimes Act to
cover people who sent spam using a Virginia ISP or who falsified
e-mail return addresses, harvested e-mail addresses from an ISP for
purposes of sending spam or sold spam software.
</P>
<P>
   Violators could be subject to fines of $500 per e-mail, and even
to criminal prosecution by the attorney general's office, Gilmore
said.
</P>
<P>
   That potential impact is large because Virginia is home to some
of the most widely used ISPs, including America Online. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On-Line Journalists Meet to Form an Association &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A journalistic barn-raising of sorts took place in Chicago on
Friday, as new media reporters and newsroom expatriates hammered
together the framework of a new association of online journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to create an organization whose members would know
the languages and folkways of the old world and the new, and would
have high-bandwidth connections to both. Its members would ideally
help the online world understand journalism and help hidebound
journalists understand new media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new medium. We've got a lot to learn about how this
works,'' said Douglas B. Feaver of Washingtonpost.com. ``If you're
looking for a grand mission statment, you're ahead of where we
are.''
</P>
<P>
   ` ``We're looking at the most difficult questions journalists
are facing in all mediums _ the question of journalistic standards
and how they should be applied and the question of how you maintain
peace in the family that has both a business and editorial side,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The organization came about when Rich Jaroslovsky, the managing
editor of The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition, flipped
through his Rolodex earlier this fall and called the people with
whom he had been swapping war stories for months _ people like
Feaver, Jai Singh of C-Net's news.com, Bernard Gwertzman, editor of
The New York Times on the Web, Lynn Povich of MSNBC.com., Janice
Castro of Time Daily, Beau Brendler of ABCnews.com, Jamie Heller of
thestreet.com, Paul Maidment of The Financial Times' site, ft.com,
and a dozen others.
</P>
<P>
   Jaroslovsky said representatives of any online news
organizations missing from the inaugural gathering, particularly
online sports sites, were absent simply because they weren't in his
Rolodex and could join any time.
</P>
<P>
   Felicity Barringer &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nice, but Can It Fix A Flat Tire When You Need It? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Microsoft Corp. and the Clarion Corp. introduced
the Auto PC, a Windows CE-based dashboard computer that uses voice
commands to control a digital radio, a CD player, a cellular phone
and a navigation system. It also uses voice synthesis to read
traffic reports, incoming e-mail and the driver's personal contact
directory.
</P>
<P>
   The Auto PC is currently available only in California and
Washington State, but Microsoft says it will soon be offered
nationwide as an option on high-end automobiles, with prices
starting at $1,299.
</P>
<P>
   Peter H. Lewis
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
