<SLUG> BC-OUTAGE-AIRPORT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTAGE GROUNDS BUSY AIRPORT, BUT NOT FOR LONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nobody was going anywhere. Planes couldn't take
off. Passengers couldn't check in. Baggage couldn't be picked up.
And there wasn't a caffe latte or toasted bagel to be had for any
price.
</P>
<P>
   At the San Francisco International Airport, when the lights went
out, the world stood still. The good news was that the delays
lasted less than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   A mistake made by a Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co. work crew shut
down a power substation in the San Francisco Bay area Tuesday
morning, triggering an outage that left 1 million people without
electricity for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Like hospitals, the airport is deemed an essential facility,
meaning that restoring power there was a priority for PG&AMP;E and
other utilities, said Ron Wilson, the airport spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   By 9:10 a.m., less than an hour after a massive power outage hit
the city, the lights were back on, computers were humming, and all
was OK _ or as OK as things get at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The airport has backup generators that kicked in as soon as the
first lights flickered, so the heart of the airport _ the
air-traffic control tower _ never lost radio contact with pilots.
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways, San Francisco International is like a
miniature city, a microcosm of businesses and cars and public
transit and people. And the effect of the blackout on the airport
illustrates how much modern life relies on electricity and its
high-tech dependent, the computer.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco International consumes 15 million watts of
electricity every second. That adds up to a $20.2 million annual
electricity bill, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Without power, baggage carousels and conveyor belts didn't work.
No computers meant passengers couldn't check in, get seat
assignments or change their ticketing. And the monitors showing
arrival and departure times were blank.
</P>
<P>
   Getting around the airport also was a hassle. With elevators,
escalators and people-movers out, there was no choice but to hoof
it, up and down stairs and through the interminable terminals.
</P>
<P>
   With the X-ray machines out at the security checkpoints,
passengers got the once-over with hand-wands and their carry-ons
were searched by guards.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 40 planes sat stranded on runways, Wilson said. Some
had not fuel because the pumps run on a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Up in the air, traffic was slowed, and 18 planes were diverted
to other airports, Wilson said. But even those that landed couldn't
release passengers because those accordion bridges between the gate
and the plane door run on electric motors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
