<HEADER>
A1474 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX     12-09 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Epiphany''
</P>
<P>
   By Paul McCusker
</P>
<P>
   Zondervan, $12.99
</P>
<P>
   ``One Shenandoah Winter''
</P>
<P>
   By T. Davis Bunn
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, $12.99
</P>
<P>
   ``In the midst of life we are in death.'' You wouldn't think
that phrase from the Book of Common Prayer could serve as the theme
for a pair of short holiday novels, but Christmas has long been a
season for surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this is terribly befuddling for a relaxed Baptist like
myself,'' Richard Lee thinks in the opening pages of ``Epiphany.''
It's a bit of an understatement, considering that he has just
dropped dead near his house in the small town of Peabody.
</P>
<P>
   Paul McCusker's title proves to have been well-chosen, as
Richard ``haunts'' the members of his family and their memories,
and as all parties involved learn how flawed their knowledge of one
another has been. Each of the three adult children gradually comes
to grips with an inner struggle: Jonathan with his frustrated
creativity, Ruth with her failures in the big city, and David with
his cynical misunderstanding of his father's life.
</P>
<P>
   McCusker's story is simple, simply written and not overly
sentimental _ perhaps just the proper comfortable prelude for a
long winter's nap.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a glance at the dust jacket of ``One Shenandoah
Winter'' might send visions of the Currier-and-Ives era dancing in
one's head. And yes, T. Davis Bunn's latest novel is traditional _
but it's not THAT tradition.
</P>
<P>
   It's 1961, and Connie Wilkes _ assistant mayor of the
Appalachian town of Hillsboro, Va. _ has problems. Not only has a
friend's vibrant daughter taken up with a man for whom Wilkes has
little use, but the community's new, handsome and desperately
needed doctor is as prickly as a pine-cone mattress. Connie soon
learns the reason behind Dr. Nathan Reynolds' anger, even as the
physician begins to work his way through it _ but not without a
sorrow that still has its redemptive qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Shenandoah Winter'' ends with a striking baptismal scene,
although its subject seems to be a long time getting there. Bunn's
book mirrors McCusker's in its simplicity, although Bunn plays more
spiritedly on the chords of emotion and evangelism. Neither empty
sugarplums nor theologically heavy turkey-and-dressing,
``Epiphany'' and ``One Shenandoah Winter'' may provide readers with
something to chew on during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1818EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
