<HEADLINE>
FOR THE COMPUTER-BOUND: CELEBRATING THE HOLIDAYS ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If your idea of a social evening is to call tech support, you
might want to consider celebrating at least part of the holiday
season online. Beyond shopping, the Net has:
</P>
<P>
   _ Advent calendars. These countdowns to Christmas, with the
little windows that children used to open to get candy or see a
picture, are all over the Web. Choose from animated, musical,
Episcopal or German-American Advent calendars 
(www.yahoo.com/societyandculture/holidays/christmas/adventcalendars/
) or one that has a different cookie recipe for each day before
Christmas (www.cookierecipe.com/cat/christmas.asp).
</P>
<P>
   _ Holiday cards. The folks, or actually the software at
americangreetings.com/index.pd, will send e-mail greetings and
arrange for cards to be delivered via snail mail to friends who
don't have modems, the sort who waste good online time outside
singing Christmas carols.
</P>
<P>
   _ An online menorah. You can find out how many lights to light
each day of Hanukkah at torah.org/chanukah.html. (Add one if you
view the site from Australia.) The site also offers this advice:
``Note! Rabbinic authorities agree: You can't fulfill the Mitzvah
by looking at a computer screen!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Letters to Santa. Kids can write to Santa at emailsanta.com.
For parents worried about their children's writing to strangers
online, the site doesn't require much personal information, just a
first name, age, city and state, so Santa can reply (an e-mail
address is optional).
</P>
<P>
   _ Carols. At rememberjosie.org/xmas/toc.html, there are lyrics
and tunes for 77 old favorites.
</P>
<P>
   _ Live cameras. You can see the Christmas market in Nuremburg,
Germany, at www.christkindlesmarkt.de/live/elivecam1.html, or check
out Rockefeller Center, at www.ftna.com/ cents.cgi.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kwanzaa events. The calendar at the Kwanzaa Information Center
(new.melanet.com/apps/calendar/calendar.cgi) includes
Kwanzaa-related events across the country.
</P>
<P>
   _ Script. Need to stage a Christmas pageant? Download the script
at ccvp.com/hatfield/CAPNSLA.TXT.
</P>
<P>
   _ For Web treasure-hunters, there is a contest on at
excape.excite.com/howto.html to piece together clues to figure out
where on earth Excite's correspondent Mike Cerre is during his
search for the origins of holiday traditions. The top prize: a trip
around the world for two.
</P>
<P>
   _ Twelve Days of Commerce. At
www.pncbank.com/12days/cardindex.html, you can learn the cost of
the gifts My True Love Gave to Me. ``In a significant triumph in
the age-old wage dispute among the sexes, the song's nine ladies
dancing received a wage increase to $3,932.72 or 20.69 percent,
this year, moving their salaries ahead of the carol's men, the 10
lords-a-leaping, 11 pipers piping and 12 drummers drumming (based
on the assumption that during medieval times, when the song was
written, pipers and drummers were male).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1819EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1480 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIFTS-FORGIRLS-TEX     12-09 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFTS-FORGIRLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAAAY COOL GIFTS FOR WAAAY KEWL GRRRLS
</HEADLINE>
 (for use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One year, the Barbie Dream House does it for them. The next,
it's all over. Your little girl has metamorphosed into a
peer-pressured, fashion-forward,
way-too-cool-to-be-seen-at-the-mall-with-you, picky preteen.
</P>
<P>
   And although pandering to pre-pubescent whims isn't a parenting
path worth considering, a certain challenge arises during the
holiday season: We want our kids to be happy. We want to give them
gifts they'll like. Which brings us to the great question, which
even Freud was unable to answer: What exactly does a little diva
want?
</P>
<P>
   To help us with this timeless quandary, we turned this season to
the experts in all things kewl: the editorial gurus of our nation's
top teen magazines.
</P>
<P>
   For parents searching for a clue: our look at the top 10 trends
for young girls who love glam.
</P>
<P>
   1. Makeup is all about glitter. ``Anything glittery and sparkly
with makeup is hot,'' says Dawn Yoselowitz, senior market editor at
``Seventeen,'' who adds that silver nail polish would make a good
stocking stuffer. At ``Teen'' magazine, Beth Lawrence, senior
market editor, says the look of the moment is bright colors ``in
long strips of glitter and big hunks of sparkle.'' In the
magazine's December issue, this translates into models boasting
silvery mascara (like Revlon StreetWear in Chill or Lancome Mascara
in Frost), shimmery metallic eye shadows (try Revlon Custom Eyes in
Iced Silver), and toenails alternatively bedecked in shades of
silver and gold. U.K. teen mag ``Sugar'' takes the look to
extremes: Beauty editors suggest applying bright-pink lipstick,
coating heavily with lip gloss and then pressing on loose glitter,
in pink, from art shops and stationers.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pajamas are big news. Maybe it's the Ally McBeal inspiration.
Big and baggy men's-style pj's are hot. ``There's a cherry print in
the Alloy catalog that is the cutest thing I've ever seen,''
Lawrence says. ``And Delia's catalog has a snowflake print that's
great.'' ``YM'' editors give their nod to the look with a pair of
clothes-print pj's from GapKids in its current ``Groovy gifts for
$20 or less'' feature.
</P>
<P>
   3. Hair matters. ``Give a flowerpot full of little jeweled hair
pins shaped like bugs,'' suggests Lawrence, ``or try the red and
green hair elastiques (translation: headbands) with sassy French
sayings _ Fantastique! _ from Frederic Fekkai.'' Yoselowitz
suggests barrettes (again, think sparkly, glittery, and pink!, or
little butterflies) _ ``they're really into those these days.''
California-based Moxie Girl, a new hybrid ``magalog'' or
``catazine'' features a gardenful of jeweled hair clips, including
butterflies, flowers and bugs.
</P>
<P>
   4. Girls just wanna wacky wake-up call. ``In our January issue,
we feature of bunch of funny alarm clocks,'' says Yoselowitz.
``Like one in the shape of a pineapple, one that looks like Lego
pieces, and one out of a can of Spam.'' Lawrence suggests looking
for the Roxy brand: ``Their hula girl would, like, really cheer you
up in the morning.'' Other time-keeping ideas: ``really cool
watches like the pastel pink and blue ones from G Shock,'' suggests
Yoselowitz; and the editors at the new ``Girl'' magazine like Mine
Design magnetic clocks for your daughter's locker (which they found
at L.A.'s Pickett Fences where, gasp, Calista Flockhart shops!).
</P>
<P>
   5. They like to bag it. Day or night, small beaded handbags _ in
velvet or satin _ are the scene-stealers this year. For school, go
with a more durable and fun messenger bag, says Yoselowitz, who
offers this advice on what to look for: a big, long strap, a
rectangular shape, and a big flap in the front. (Our hint: try Old
Navy.)
</P>
<P>
   6. Room stuff rocks. ``Beaded curtains used to be big,'' says
Lawrence, ``but the car-wash curtain is new _ it's plastic and it
comes in all different colors.'' Lawrence says she saw one recently
that has inserts where your daughter can put photos of friends, or
even stash jewelry. ``It's like a wallpaper you can take off and
update,'' she says. Also kewl: CD holders in fun colors, picture
frames, plastic blow-up furniture, and sheets and pillowcases in
prints such as butterfly patterns.
</P>
<P>
   7. Shoes should have attitude. ``Birkenstocks come in wool
now,'' says Yoselowitz, ``and they're a great item to have.'' For
the more princessy preteen, Lawrence says the Prada-inspired loafer
is modern and minimalistic.
</P>
<P>
   8. Tiaras aren't just for nighttime anymore. We had trouble
believing this one, but a recent trip to sorority-sister-favorite
Cotton Island in Dallas convinced us that the kids today really are
wearing these. Look for silver headbands with rhinestones and
feathers. ``You can wear them to school with jeans and a T-shirt,''
assures Yoselowitz. ``You can totally get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   9. Beading is the best. Again, this traditionally formal look
gives a twist to casual styles. ``A beaded cardigan could be
vintage or new,'' says Lawrence. ``Pastels are really popular, but
follow the person's tastes. Black is a great option.'' Also: Look
for beading detail on dresses and bags.
</P>
<P>
   10. Gift certificates rock. ``So cool,'' says Lawrence.
Suggestions from the front lines on where to get 'em: movie
theaters (so kids can catch the latest Leonardo flick), Contempo
clothing stores, Gadzooks, Claire's, beauty salons (where they can
get their toenails done), bookstores and Blockbuster. Or try one of
the newish teen catalogs, where they can find all the trends fit to
print: Delia's, (800) 335-4217, www.delias.com; Alloy, (888)
552-5569, www.alloyonline.com; Brat (800) 598-5264,
www.bratcatalog.com; or catazine Moxie Girl (888) MOX-STUF,
www.moxiegirl.com..MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
