<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERGROUND-MAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`UNDERGROUND MAN' FLED ITALIAN DRUG SENTENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.Y.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the clock ticking toward eviction, underground man Thomas
Johnson said Wednesday he will not provoke a confrontation when
Nantucket authorities come to remove him from his 8-foot-deep home.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm not going to make a standoff,'' Johnson said. ``I'll move
when they tell me to move. But I'll stay in here as long as I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   A Nantucket deputy sheriff served Johnson with a 30-day eviction
notice Saturday at his secluded hideaway on a Boy Scout camp. If he
does not leave by that time, Johnson said, the eviction notice
states that the Nantucket district of the Boy Scouts will go to
court to remove him.
</P>
<P>
   Bertyl Johnson Jr., a Nantucket lawyer who represents the local
Scouts in this matter, did not return phone calls Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Johnson said the eviction notice represents a change by
the Scouts, who apparently did not know he had been living for 10
years in a remote part of Camp Richard until a deer hunter stumbled
on the home's stovepipe several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   One island official familiar with the situation said the Scouts
had been willing to let Johnson remain on the property through the
winter. But when the news media last week wrote of Johnson's
elaborately furnished, three-room home, the Nantucket Scouts felt
pressured to speed up the eviction process, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Scout executive Michael Riley of the Cape and Islands Council,
which includes Nantucket, said he had been unaware of Johnson's
presence at Camp Richard until last Thursday. Scouting officials on
the island, he said, ``are going to do what has to be done and
whatever's the right thing to do in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time,'' Riley continued, ``they're trying to show
some compassion and dignity for Tom Johnson in accordance with the
three points of the Scout code: to be courteous, friendly, and
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, Johnson said, local support for him has been
heartening. ``It's incredible,'' added Johnson, who created a
subterranean life on Nantucket after fleeing an Italian prison
sentence for heroin smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   The two years he spent in a Rome prison changed his life,
Johnson said, and led him to an underground existence where he
could strengthen himself morally and avoid the chafing routine he
sees in mainstream living.
</P>
<P>
   Italian authorities confirmed this week that Johnson fled the
country in 1985, following 26 months in a Rome prison and one month
of subsequent house arrest on a heroin-smuggling conviction.
</P>
<P>
   An Italian law enforcement official, who did not wish to be
identified, said authorities had not known if Johnson was still
alive. &UR;  &LR; The prospect of extradition is not high, he said, because
the United States generally does not return one of its citizens on
such a charge.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he was apprehended at the Rome airport in May 1983
while attempting to smuggle 2 kilograms of Thai heroin into Italy
via Amsterdam. The heroin had a street value of $2.6 million at the
time, he estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he was to have been paid $10,000 for stashing the
heroin, stitched into a suitcase, in a locker at the Rome train
station. The trip was his third in Europe as a heroin courier,
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Other details about Johnson's past also have been confirmed,
including statements that his father was a city judge in
Binghamton, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   According to Broome County historian Gerald Smith, Johnson was
one of seven children born to William H. Johnson Jr., a prominent
arts supporter, judge, and municipal official who resigned from the
Binghamton Housing Authority after he alleged there had been
political interference in tenant selection.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Johnson served as city judge from 1959 to 1962. He
also had been chairman of the Tri-Cities Opera.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Johnson said his father died in his arms, of liver and
colon cancer, in 1981. The family fell apart after the death,
Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
