A1494 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCKETTES-DANCE-LADN     12-09 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKETTES-DANCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROCKETTES-STYLE CHRISTMAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rockettes dancer Anne Mason's Christmas job has
legs _ 40 of them.
</P>
<P>
   As a performer with the mighty 20-member dance troupe known for
its world-famous kick line, Mason is looking forward to bringing a
Gotham holiday tradition to sunny Los Angeles for 40 performances
at the Universal Amphitheatre.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Universal is a concert hall, so the logistics of putting
on the Rockettes was a challenge,'' explains Houston-bred Mason, a
Rockette for almost eight years. ``So many brilliant minds were at
work, especially in terms of making room for everything
backstage.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast of 55 includes the high-stepping Rockettes, 22 singers
and dancers, four children, two ice skaters and Santa Claus _ plus
a dog, three camels, five sheep and two donkeys.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the amphitheatre stage had to be nearly doubled by the
use of an annex that extends out the back of the venue. On a recent
visit to rehearsals, 30 truckloads of props, costumes and staging
materials were in use as the production came together under the
expert eye of director-choreographer Linda Haberman, who has worked
with the Rockettes since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Radio City Rockettes' ``Christmas Spectacular'' opened
Wednesday and runs through Dec. 29 at the Universal Amphitheatre.
</P>
<P>
   When the curtain goes up, you can expect to see a nonstop
extravaganza of colorful costumes, high-kicking routines, holiday
music, animals, Santa, elves, dancing snowmen and baby bears
featuring a cast of more than 100 actor-dancers performing in
what's billed as the world's biggest Christmas show. Classic
holiday numbers among the show's 10 scenes include ``Parade of the
Wooden Soldiers,'' ``Carol of the Bells'' and ``Living Nativity.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Radio City Christmas Spectacular,'' which premiered at
Radio City Music Hall in 1933, is known as the most successful live
theatrical production in the nation, grossing a record-setting $68
million in 1997. Last year, five simultaneous productions were seen
by more than 1.7 million people in New York; Chicago; Detroit;
Branson, Mo.; and Myrtle Beach, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a three-year process bringing the Rockettes to Los
Angeles,'' said Alex Hodges, senior vice president of Universal
Concerts. ``Some of the questions we asked were: Can it work in a
warm climate, in a city this spread out? We had to wrestle with the
issue of, will this work in a city where you can play golf in
December, in a city that doesn't have four distinct seasons?''
</P>
<P>
   To achieve the transformation from concert hall to Rockettes
launching pad, the seating capacity of the amphitheatre was scaled
down from 6,200 to 3,400. Sightlines from the very last row to the
stage are now just 130 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This production is bigger and better than any of the other
traveling Rockettes shows,'' said ``Christmas Spectacular''
producer David Nash. ``And we needed a lot of room to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The original concept of the Rockettes dance line was to achieve
absolute precision, as if the dancers were moving as one.
Everything _ height, costumes and steps _ were kept identical. The
illusion of uniform height is maintained by putting the tallest
dancers in the center and gradually decreasing the height until the
shortest women are at either end.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really feel you are part of history,'' Rockette Mason
said. ``To be part of that tradition _ that's why it's a such a
thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
