<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1496 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUFF-PROFILE-HNS &LR;      12-09 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUFF-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUFF TRIES TO TORPEDO CHARGE OF PERJURY AGAINST CLINTON  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff abandoned his
customary behind-the-scenes approach Wednesday to wage a public
campaign to sidetrack House Judiciary Committee preparations to
vote articles of impeachment against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff, urging an outcome sought by the White House, told the
panel that the president is ``looking for an end to this process''
with a speedy congressional vote of censure imposed upon the chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it does not advance the public weal to drag it out
further,'' Ruff said. ``We are open to any reasonable suggestion
from any side as a way of finding an end to this.''
</P>
<P>
   The 59-year-old lawyer climaxed the White House's two-day legal
and public relations offensive before the committee with a
relentless recitation of facts and arguments designed to scuttle
the articles of impeachment being weighed by the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans released four draft articles of impeachment before
Ruff completed his testimony. Two articles accused Clinton of
perjury, one cited alleged obstruction of justice and one cited
alleged abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats quickly countered with a proposal to censure
Clinton for ``reprehensible conduct'' with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky. Democrats vowed to insist upon Clinton's
signature on the instrument of his censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``No person is above the law and the president remains subject
to criminal and civil penalties for this conduct,'' the Democrats'
proposal said.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-member panel is expected to approve one or more articles
of impeachment by week's end. The vote would set the stage for a
vote on impeachment by the full House next week _ action that could
refer the matter to the Senate for the first impeachment trial
since the 1860s.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said Clinton's misleading statements in legal proceedings
since his affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky
came to light fall short of federal prosecution or the gravity
required to justify impeachment by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's misstatements in a civil deposition and before a
federal grand jury were either unintentional or irrelevant or in
response to an ambiguous question, Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cannot be the rule, to add to an old phrase, that `Close
only counts in horseshoes, hand grenades and perjury,''' Ruff
declared.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff appealed for each committee member to ask: ``Am I prepared
to impeach the president because, after having admitted to having
engaged in egregiously wrongful conduct, he falsely described the
particulars of that conduct?''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff, a former Watergate prosecutor and long-time partner in a
Washington law firm, offered lawmakers the preferred White House
response: ``The answer must be no.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff, who uses a wheelchair because of paralysis from polio
contracted on a youthful trip to Africa, offered a contrast to the
telegenic style of White House lawyer Gregory Craig, who appeared
on the president's behalf on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff painstakingly tried to build a record that Clinton didn't
commit perjury and that he didn't deserve impeachment for his
actions in the White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're obviously the president's clean-up hitter,'' Rep. F.
James Sensenbrenner Jr., R-Wis., told Ruff at the outset of several
hours of questions and answers.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff ducked repeated questions about whether Clinton had
``lied'' about his conduct in his January deposition in the Paula
Jones' civil lawsuit and in his Aug. 17 videotaped testimony before
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff stuck with the phrasing offered repeatedly by Craig the day
before _ that Clinton had ``misled'' the legal proceedings,
admitted doing so and has apologized for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the difference between misleading and lying?'' inquired
Rep. Bob Inglis, R-S.C. ``You like the word misleading better than
lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., bluntly told Ruff: ``I believe the
elements of perjury are here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., told Ruff: ``I believe when the
president gave those answers he was lying. I am concerned that
we're still not getting straight talk and the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Ruff, appearing before a congressional panel for
afternoon-long nationally broadcast testimony was a long way from
his preferred method of dealing with clients' legal difficulties
away from the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   A partner in the prestigious law firm of Covington &AMP; Burling,
Ruff has the reputation of working off stage to negotiate graceful
exits for clients.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff worked a deal five years ago to enable Sen. Charles Robb,
D-Va., son-in-law of the late President Lyndon Johnson, to appear
at the last minute before a grand jury investigating his Senate
office's acquisition of an illegally recorded tape of a phone call
by a political rival. Robb's appearance helped persuade the grand
jury not to return an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff also steered clear of the limelight in working to extricate
Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, from the legal repercussions stemming form
the scandal surrounding savings-and-loan owner Charles Keating.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff, a graduate of Swarthmore College and Columbia Law School,
joined the White House as Clinton's fifth counsel in January 1997.
A former attorney for the government in the District of Columbia,
Ruff had been considered for the No. 2 post at the Justice
Department at the outset of the Clinton administration but he was
selected after questions arose over his failure to pay Social
Security taxes for a semi-retired household worker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1824EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1499 &Cx1f; ttj-z
s a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWER-TALES-HNS &LR;      12-09 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-TALES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO POWER TO THE PEOPLE, BUT THE CITY DOESN'T SLEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Susan Lee, who just passed the bar exam and
works in a law office, stayed at work even though there was no
electricity in the building.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour, one elevator was operating on a generator, but
when she looked out the window, she could see two window washers
stuck high on the outside of the Maritime Plaza Building, unable to
move their power-operated perch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were there in one spot for two or three hours,'' Lee
said. ``That one window got pretty clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside her building it was a little dark and a little cold, she
said. Oh, and the toilets wouldn't flush without power. ``They
could get the elevator going, but not the toilets,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A mistake made by a Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co. work crew shut
down a power substation in the San Francisco Bay area Tuesday
morning, triggering an outage that left 1 million people without
electricity for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of people tried to look at the bright side of the
situation. ``The power outage doesn't bother me. I can't see
anyway,'' said Johnny Serrano, a blind musician.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan van Rijn, a sophomore at Lowell High School, said the
power failure had given him and his friends the bright idea of
going to Baskin Robbins for ice cream after school. ``We were
hoping they would give us some free ice cream, that maybe it would
be melting, but that turned out not to be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   There were more than a few students waiting in line hoping for
the same thing, ``but they ended up paying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Workers who were locked out of their offices flocked to nearby
taverns.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding the morning hour, Harrington's Irish Bar on
Front Street became a lively, noisy center of conviviality, though
only dimly lighted.
</P>
<P>
   Among those gathered around a table was Don Querio, a lawyer
with Sevrson &AMP; Werson, who had fled his office. ``There is very
little in the way of lights and no water,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And how was it that Harrington's remained an island of light
while all around it, including a McDonald's next door, remained in
darkness? ``God must be an Irishman,'' Kathleen Harrington said
with a laugh, admitting she didn't really know the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Avid morning gym goers also suffered through the blackout.
</P>
<P>
   When Michael Ostrofsky emerged from the Nikko Hotel Health Club
shortly after 9 a.m., his hair was wet. The club's hair dryers had
ceased to function along with the club's sauna, its Jacuzzi
whirlpool, its stair climber and its treadmill machines.
</P>
<P>
   Showers were operating for those who didn't mind showering in
the dark, with only cold water.
</P>
<P>
   The rowing machines worked, said Wes Tanaka, the club's chief
trainer. ``They operate on human power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
