<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PERJURY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THE PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES AN `ORDINARY CITIZEN'? 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: STANDS for CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White House witnesses told the House Judiciary
Committee Wednesday that President Clinton is being held to a
tougher standard of conduct than ordinary citizens would be and
therefore should not be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of former federal prosecutors called by the White House
to defend Clinton contended that if he was not the president of the
United States, no prosecutor in the country would bring a case of
perjury against him.
</P>
<P>
   That argument came under heavy fire from Republicans on the
committee, who noted that numerous people have been convicted of
perjury and are currently serving time for it. In state courts
thousands of people are convicted of perjury every year, and as of
this October, 115 people were serving sentences for perjury in
federal prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas P. Sullivan, who served as U.S. attorney in Chicago from
1977 to 1981, told the committee that ``if the president were not
involved, if an ordinary citizen were the subject of the inquiry
... the case simply wouldn't get in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``undoing an election'' over a case that would not
even be considered by prosecutors was ``wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard J. Davis, a member of the Watergate special prosecution
force in the early 1970s, also said that in the ``real world'' a
case of perjury against Clinton would never be pursued.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said perjury would be difficult to prove in Clinton's case
because Monica Lewinsky, the former intern with whom the president
had an affair, would be considered an unreliable witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case would not be brought by a prosecutor since it would
not be won at a trial,'' he argued.
</P>
<P>
   White House Counsel Charles Ruff also contended that House
Republicans were holding the president to a higher standard than
ordinary citizens. ``I can't conceive of this case going forward to
a jury,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican committee members disputed the argument that no
prosecutor would take the case, and others contended that the
president of the United States is not an ordinary citizen and
should be held to a higher standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton holds the most powerful position in the world ...
and sets an example for us all,'' said Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas.
He added that the president has a ``special responsibility'' that
goes beyond that of average Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Chabot, R-Ohio, said the president should ``set a
standard for all the citizens of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., disagreed that a perjury case would
never be brought against Clinton if he were not the president. He
said that each year there are more federal perjury prosecutions
than kidnapping prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this in mind, I would not be so quick to say this is an
impossible case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson added that regardless of whether a federal prosecutor
would bring charges against Clinton, allowing the chief law
enforcement officer of the country to commit perjury would have
``terrible consequences for the fabric of our legal system.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., said the perjury case against the
president was about ``more than just the law. It's about the
national interest. If the president is guilty of perjury, that
undermines the country's trust in the office, and no president can
lead without the trust of the people,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
