<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1536 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT10-COX     12-09 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IS MICROSOFT AN UNWELCOME FRAT BOY AT THE JAVA PARTY?
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. portrayed itself in federal court
Wednesday as a rich and clever member of the software fraternity
who, because of either jealousy or fear, wasn't invited to the
party that Sun Microsystems Inc. threw for its Java technology.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Microsoft charged that Sun had welcomed Netscape
Communications Corp., a Microsoft rival in the Internet browser
wars, to join the big Java blast, even though Netscape showed signs
of being a badly behaved guest.
</P>
<P>
   With the landmark Microsoft antitrust trial in its eighth week,
Tom Burt, the software's giant's associate general counsel, put
into evidence an ``Attorneys Eyes Only'' 1996 e-mail message
between two high-level Sun executives titled ``Netscape Sneaky
Move.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressed to Eric Schmidt, then Sun's chief technology officer,
the message complained that Netscape was six weeks late in signing
Sun's licensing agreement for JavaScript, which Sun was pushing as
an industry coding standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This episode illustrates why I think throwing our lot back in
with Netscape is foolish,'' the message read. ``They are completely
untrustworthy. They don't do what they say they will and they do
what they say they won't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No agreement with Netscape is worth the ink it's written
with,'' the Sun message concluded. Go sign a deal with Saddam
Hussein. It has a better chance of being honored.''
</P>
<P>
   Burt put the bitter complaint into evidence in a bid to
undermine the testimony of James Gosling, Sun's chief scientist and
the creator of the Java programming language, who claimed that it
was Microsoft who had refused to play by the industry rules by
writing its own version of Java.
</P>
<P>
   ``We viewed what (Microsoft) was doing as something of a poison
pill because the Microsoft (Java) standard was not supported on any
platform except Windows,'' Gosling said in a second day of
cross-examination by Burt. ``Neither we nor our other licensees
were willing to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep harping on those licensing difficulties'' with
Netscape, Gosling added. ``But it was Microsoft who said they
weren't going to comply until the (federal) court (in California)
ordered them to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burt, however, asserted that when Sun began working to improve
the ability of Java-written programs to work on a host of
computers, Microsoft, unlike Netscape and other favored Java
licensees, was deliberately frozen out of the revived
standards-setting process.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's exclusion, Burt contended, did not stem from the
software's giant's go-our-way arrogant attitude, as Sun and
government antitrust officials who have sued Microsoft have
alleged.
</P>
<P>
   By way of proof, he cited an e-mail message that Russ Arun, a
Microsoft Java developer, wrote to his Sun handler in May 1996:
</P>
<P>
   ``Please to keep us in the loop on the other interfaces that you
mentioned. It was not clear to me whether the (Java) interface you
had written has already been shared with other licensees. If so, we
were not in the loop and would like to be. The same goes for any of
the other forthcoming interfaces.''
</P>
<P>
   In a preliminary ruling, a U.S. District Court judge in San Jose
found last month that Microsoft may have used unfair methods to
undermine's Sun's bid to develop Java as a potential replacement
operating system for Windows.
</P>
<P>
   But the stakes in this case are far higher. The Justice
Department, joined by 19 states, has accused Microsoft of illegally
using Windows, which is being shipped with more than 9 out of 10
personal computers, to retain and extend its dominant status to the
Internet and to other budding technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Burt said he would conclude his cross-examination of Gosling,
the ninth of 12 scheduled prosecution witnesses, sometime Thursday.
David Boies, the lead government attorney in the case, said his
next witness was likely to be Edward Felten, a Princeton computer
professor who has ``deconstructed'' Windows 98 in an experimental
effort to exclude the Internet Explorer browser code from
Microsoft's flagship operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
