<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1539 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEMPLETON-PURPOSE-NYT     12-09 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEMPLETON-PURPOSE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLDWIDE LAWS OF LIFE:
 HAVING A PURPOSE FOR YOUR LIFE LETS YOU ENDURE ANYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Sir John Templeton, the Tennessee-born billionaire and founder
of the Templeton funds, built his fortune on his legendary ability
to perceive value that others overlooked. In his column, he urges
us to recognize the value of spirituality in life.)
</P>
<P>
   (``He who has a `why' for which to live, can bear with almost
any `how.' -- Friedrich Nietzsche Never do anything that you'll
have to punish yourself for.'' -- Anonymous)
</P>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative NIRDI
RELIS in New York at (800) 972-3550 or (212) 499-3333, or fax her
at (212) 499-3382.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Man's Search for Meaning,'' Austrian psychiatrist
Viktor Frankl documents the profound power that a life purpose
exerts over an individual under even the worst of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Frankl, who survived the Nazi concentration camps, described how
prisoners who felt they had nothing to live for succumbed, while
those who perceived themselves as having a mission to complete
struggled to survive. Deprived of all external supports that might
give life meaning, these survivors came to realize that, in
Frankl's words, ``It did not really matter what we expected of
life, but rather what life expected of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Their sense of an inner purpose pulled them through the most
horrible physical and emotional experiences so that they might make
their unique contribution to the world.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has a purpose in life beyond one's immediate interests
and gratifications, though that purpose frequently goes
undiscovered. Since God has given us everything potentially, we
need to learn how to discover his gifts by making them spiritually
active in our lives.
</P>
<P>
   Many people devote their entire lives to the pursuit of greater
ease and pleasure. Those who have not found the ``why'' that gives
meaning to existence may achieve material success, yet the real
goodness of life eludes them. One true meaning of life lies in
sharing our particular qualities of greatness with others.
</P>
<P>
   There is a simple way you can discover your special purpose in
life. Draw up a list of all the qualities you value in yourself and
that other people admire in you. If you're a humorous person, you
have the ability to uplift and entertain. If clear thinking is your
strong suit and you're skilled at developing ideas, accept this as
a gift that can benefit those around you in many ways. Since we
sometimes think poorly of ourselves, it is important to dig a
little to unearth those skills and talents that may lie hidden.
</P>
<P>
   Next, examine the ways in which you interact with other people
and make a list of those ways that work the best. Does it excite
you to teach someone a skill that will help him? Do you enjoy
simply listening while someone shares a problem with you? Are you
happiest when organizing a group for a project, or perhaps when
encouraging someone who feels hopeless about himself?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, imagine what your world would be like under the best of
all possible circumstances. Would it be clean, peaceful, and
productive? Form a mental picture of the world that you'd like you
and your loved ones to live in, and write down that vision in as
much specific detail as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Your mission in life is to have a ``why'' to live for, to use
your best qualities in the service of the kind of world in which
you would like to live. That is your purpose. This is what life
expects of you.
</P>
<P>
   And when you live according to your purpose, setting goals that
support it, you may find the pieces of your life drawn together
into a strong internal whole. Then, no matter how difficult life's
experiences may prove to be, you can be able to endure and even
prevail.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Excerpted from ``Worldwide Laws of Life'' by John Marks
Templeton. Published by Templeton Foundation Press)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1842EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1540 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT10-COX     12-09 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IS MICROSOFT AN UNWELCOME FRAT BOY AT THE JAVA PARTY?
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. portrayed itself in federal court
Wednesday as a rich and clever member of the software fraternity
who, because of either jealousy or fear, wasn't invited to the
party that Sun Microsystems Inc. threw for its Java technology.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Microsoft charged that Sun had welcomed Netscape
Communications Corp., a Microsoft rival in the Internet browser
wars, to join the big Java blast, even though Netscape showed signs
of being a badly behaved guest.
</P>
<P>
   With the landmark Microsoft antitrust trial in its eighth week,
Tom Burt, the software's giant's associate general counsel, put
into evidence an ``Attorneys Eyes Only'' 1996 e-mail message
between two high-level Sun executives titled ``Netscape Sneaky
Move.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressed to Eric Schmidt, then Sun's chief technology officer,
the message complained that Netscape was six weeks late in signing
Sun's licensing agreement for JavaScript, which Sun was pushing as
an industry coding standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This episode illustrates why I think throwing our lot back in
with Netscape is foolish,'' the message read. ``They are completely
untrustworthy. They don't do what they say they will and they do
what they say they won't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No agreement with Netscape is worth the ink it's written
with,'' the Sun message concluded. Go sign a deal with Saddam
Hussein. It has a better chance of being honored.''
</P>
<P>
   Burt put the bitter complaint into evidence in a bid to
undermine the testimony of James Gosling, Sun's chief scientist and
the creator of the Java programming language, who claimed that it
was Microsoft who had refused to play by the industry rules by
writing its own version of Java.
</P>
<P>
   ``We viewed what (Microsoft) was doing as something of a poison
pill because the Microsoft (Java) standard was not supported on any
platform except Windows,'' Gosling said in a second day of
cross-examination by Burt. ``Neither we nor our other licensees
were willing to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep harping on those licensing difficulties'' with
Netscape, Gosling added. ``But it was Microsoft who said they
weren't going to comply until the (federal) court (in California)
ordered them to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burt, however, asserted that when Sun began working to improve
the ability of Java-written programs to work on a host of
computers, Microsoft, unlike Netscape and other favored Java
licensees, was deliberately frozen out of the revived
standards-setting process.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's exclusion, Burt contended, did not stem from the
software's giant's go-our-way arrogant attitude, as Sun and
government antitrust officials who have sued Microsoft have
alleged.
</P>
<P>
   By way of proof, he cited an e-mail message that Russ Arun, a
Microsoft Java developer, wrote to his Sun handler in May 1996:
</P>
<P>
   ``Please to keep us in the loop on the other interfaces that you
mentioned. It was not clear to me whether the (Java) interface you
had written has already been shared with other licensees. If so, we
were not in the loop and would like to be. The same goes for any of
the other forthcoming interfaces.''
</P>
<P>
   In a preliminary ruling, a U.S. District Court judge in San Jose
found last month that Microsoft may have used unfair methods to
undermine's Sun's bid to develop Java as a potential replacement
operating system for Windows.
</P>
<P>
   But the stakes in this case are far higher. The Justice
Department, joined by 19 states, has accused Microsoft of illegally
using Windows, which is being shipped with more than 9 out of 10
personal computers, to retain and extend its dominant status to the
Internet and to other budding technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Burt said he would conclude his cross-examination of Gosling,
the ninth of 12 scheduled prosecution witnesses, sometime Thursday.
David Boies, the lead government attorney in the case, said his
next witness was likely to be Edward Felten, a Princeton computer
professor who has ``deconstructed'' Windows 98 in an experimental
effort to exclude the Internet Explorer browser code from
Microsoft's flagship operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
