<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-INSPECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ BARS INSPECTION OF PARTY HEADQUARTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Iraq blocked a team of UN weapons inspectors
from conducting a search Wednesday of the country's ruling party
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   American and British officials said that the violation was not
enough to trigger an immediate military response, but it undermined
Iraqi efforts to persuade the Security Council to conduct a
comprehensive review of Baghdad's compliance with UN demands. Iraq
insists that such a review will lead to the lifting of economic
sanctions against it.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Wednesday that it is waiting for Richard
Butler, the chief UN weapons inspector, to assess Iraqi compliance
since the United States forced Iraq on Nov. 14 to allow
inspections. Butler is expected to issue a report as early as
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no comprehensive review if they are not
cooperating,'' warned Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright.
``And if they are not, the use of force is an option that is on the
table and I think that needs to be made very clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq accused the United Nations of conducting a ``provocative''
search of the headquarters of the country's ruling Baath political
party, which is controlled by Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   General Hossam Mohammed Amin, Iraq's chief liaison to the UN
inspectors, said that a party official demanded that the United
Nations provide a written description of the materials they were
seeking. He said the United Nations rejected the demand and left
the site. The UN team, he charged, had ``the clear goal of creating
crises and problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler countered Wednesday that the inspection was a legitimate
test of Baghdad's willingness to meet its obligations to provide
unimpeded access to any facilities suspected of containing evidence
of a secret weapons program. ``This was an absolutely legal,
no-notice inspection and they blocked us,'' said Butler. ``It was
blockage and it's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The US initially opposed such a review, first proposed by UN
Secretary Genral Kofi Annan last February. But Washington relented
on Oct. 30 after persuading other Security Council members that the
review must address a series of outstanding Iraqi obligations
including disarmament, the return of Kuwaiti property, and the
status of prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   US officials predict that the comprehensive review may backfire
on Iraq by providing a forum to demonstrate that Baghdad has failed
repeatedly to honor its disarmament obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Ritter, the American who resigned as a UN inspector, told
reporters at a breakfast press conference this week that the
comprehensive review is the beginning of the end of US efforts to
contain Iraq. He maintained that the review will increase the
burden on UN inspectors to demonstrate that Iraq possesses banned
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter is concerned about growing opposition in the Security
Council to US efforts to maintain economic sanctions against Iraq.
``This administration doesn't have the intestinal fortitude,'' he
said. ``Unless we go to war for UNSCOM right now, Iraq is going to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest action by Baghdad follows two weeks of Iraqi
evasions. Two weeks ago, Iraq refused to hand over a series of
Iraqi air force documents containing an account of the country's
use of chemical warheads. Since then, the UN inspectors have
charged that Baghdad has denied one UN team access to a rebel camp
used by Iranian rebel fighters and harassing another team with a
low-flying Iraqi helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats at the United Nations said they were surprised that
Iraq had begun to challenge the UN inspectors so quickly. ``We
thought they would be compliant coming up to comprehensive
review,'' said one senior European diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Washington's apparent willingness to use force to back
the inspectors, the Clinton administration is growing increasingly
convinced that its policy of containing Iraq with weapons
inspections and economic sanctions cannot be sustained
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer this standoff continues, the harder it will be to
maintain the international support we have built for our policy,''
said Samuel R. Berger, the President's national security adviser,
during a speech at Stanford University on Tuesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
