<HEADER>
A1548 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TEXANS-1210-C     12-09 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TEXANS-1210-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXANS ON JUDICIARY PANEL CLING TO OPPOSING STANCES
 &HT;    350 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The two Texans on the House Judiciary Committee
appeared unswayed by two days of testimony from witnesses defending
President Clinton and instead solidified their positions _ one
Texan for, and one against, impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. Lamar Smith of San Antonio refined his
pro-impeachment argument Wednesday as he repeated his contention
that Clinton's misleading statements were not concocted to conceal
a sexual affair, but ``were designed to thwart or impede the
investigation of the independent counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   The distinction is important as the Judiciary Committee prepares
to vote, perhaps as early as Saturday, on articles of impeachment
against Clinton. Smith is among the Republicans who see an
impeachable crime in Clinton's statements.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, including Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of Houston, insist
Clinton's actions, no matter how reprehensible, are not crimes
worthy of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me again clearly state that I find the president's
behavior unacceptable and morally wrong,'' Jackson Lee said
Wednesday. ``Unfortunately, what I would offer to say is there's
been no new thinking in this room, because as I read the provision
`treason and bribery and other high crimes and misdemeanors,' I do
not hear the claim `treason and bribery and unfit morally.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're discussing, (in) actuality, apples and oranges for
the American people,'' Jackson Lee said. ``That confusion causes
the divide and the inability for us to come together in a
collaborative and bipartisan manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he found ``incredible'' the assertions from Clinton's
lawyers that the president was not deliberately trying to thwart a
criminal investigation into his false statements in the Paul Jones
sexual harassment case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not just talking about that one instance, but the repeated
instances of admitted misleading, evasive answers, perhaps lying
under oath,'' Smith said. ``Let me just say to you, if there's 1
percent of the American people who don't think that he was trying
to, and intentionally trying to, mislead or impede the
investigation, I would be surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
