<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1549 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PINOCHET-EXTRADITE-BO     12-09 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-EXTRADITE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATH CLEARED FOR PINOCHET EXTRADITION TO SPAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain cleared the way Wednesday for the extradition
to Spain of ex-Chilean dictator General Augusto Pinochet on charges
of torturing and murdering political opponents and ordinary
civilians during his 17-year reign.
</P>
<P>
   Home Secretary Jack Straw, who as a college student marched
against the Pinochet regime, agonized over whether to send the
83-year-old former leader home to Chile on compassionate grounds.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Straw upheld the Nov. 25 decision by five judges
in the House of Lords, who ruled that Pinochet could not claim
sovereign immunity for human rights violations committed while he
ruled Chile between 1973 and 1990. A Chilean government report says
at least 3,197 people were killed or disappeared during Pinochet's
reign, while human rights organizations say the figure is much
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Straw's decision, which Pinochet's attorneys vowed to challenge,
further strained relations between Britain and Chile, which in
protest recalled its ambassador from London.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government emphatically rejects Straw's decision that
allows the continuation of the extradition process to Spain of
Senator Pinochet, infringing the sovereignty of Chile,'' Interior
Minister Raul Troncoso said at a news conference in Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   But human rights activists hailed the decision, noting that it
came on the eve of Thursday's 50th anniversary of the Declaration
of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous birthday present to celebrate the 50th
anniversary,'' said Reed Brody, advocacy director for Human Rights
Watch, a New York-based group.
</P>
<P>
   Straw's decision clears the way for Pinochet's appearance Friday
in a London court to formally face the extradition charges lodged
by Spanish authorities. Pinochet learned of Straw's decision at the
mansion 20 miles west of London where he is living, under armed
guard, while the legal drama unfolds. A London hospital ordered
Pinochet to leave last week, saying he was an unwanted patient who
no longer needed care.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say the extradition process in Britain could drag
on for months. Even if Pinochet is shipped to Spain and is
convicted, however, he will not be sent to prison because under
Spanish law no one over age 75 can be incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
   But Pinochet could spend the twilight of his life on an endless
merry-go-round of trials. Other countries have lodged warrants for
his arrest or have hinted that they want to try Pinochet for
murdering and torturing their citizens who got caught up in his
regime's brutal crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   A Spanish judge, Baltasar Garzon, wants Pinochet to answer for
the deaths of 94 civilians, including Spaniards. Spain, France, and
Switzerland have formally asked that he be extradited to face
charges in the murders of their nationals, while Italy is
considering making a similar request.
</P>
<P>
   Straw said he had ``given precedence to the Spanish request, and
notified the French and Swiss governments accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Under British law, the decision whether to allow extradition
proceedings to proceed rested solely with Straw, who is in charge
of all matters related to law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Straw's predicament was Britain's. While a liberal activist as a
college student, Straw, like the rest of Prime Minister Tony
Blair's cabinet of ``old lefties,'' has moved toward the center,
part of a shift that helped the formerly ideologically leftist
Labor Party take power after 18 years of Conservative rule.
</P>
<P>
   Liberals in this country are appalled that Pinochet traveled
regularly to Britain to avail of its exclusive boutiques and
medical care, which he was receiving after back surgery Oct. 16
when Metropolitan Police served him with an arrest warrant at his
hospital bedside.
</P>
<P>
   But conservatives, including former Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, who hosted Pinochet for cocktails at her home two weeks
before his arrest, argue that he was a valued ally during Britain's
1982 war with Argentina over the Falkland Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives also say Pinochet rescued Chile from a disastrous
form of socialism imposed by Salvador Allende, the elected Marxist
leader who Pinochet overthrew in a CIA-backed coup. Conservatives
say the number of murders attributed to Pinochet's regime, while
horrible, pales in comparison to the atrocities committed by other
despots this century.
</P>
<P>
   Some, including Alastair Hardy, chairman of the Chilean-British
Chamber of Commerce, complain that Britain is damaging commercial
and cultural links with Chile by following an uncharted legal path.
Noting that Chilean voters had approved a deal in which Pinochet
was given immunity from prosecution in exchange for stepping down
and allowing free elections in 1990, Hardy said the British
government was ``jeopardizing the goodwill of nearly two centuries
and acting against the wishes of the democratically elected
government of Chile.''
</P>
<P>
   But Straw refused to allow the effect on relations with one of
Britain's biggest trading partners in South America to sway his
decision. While Pinochet made himself a senator for life when he
stepped down, Straw said that title did not entitle him to
diplomatic immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's attorneys will be hard-pressed to come up with a way
to prevent his extradition, although they could delay the
proceedings indefinitely, so that Pinochet could live out his final
days in the slightly claustrophobic luxury of the mansion at
Wentworth.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Pinochet's attorneys complained that one of the law
lords who ruled against him was associated with Amnesty
International, which has been one of the human rights groups
arguing for Pinochet's extradition. But few legal experts here
believe that alleged conflict of interest offers much hope for the
former dictator.
</P>
<P>
   While Thatcher had led calls to show Pinochet mercy because of
his age and poor health, Straw rejected appeals on humanitarian
grounds, but said it could be ``reexamined in the light of any
developments,'' meaning if Pinochet's health deteriorates.
</P>
<P>
   Thatcher criticized Straw, saying ``he had ample power to put an
end to this shameful and damaging episode.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a political decision and it represents a failure of
political leadership,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservatives say the Blair government is playing fast and
loose with the doctrine of diplomatic immunity and interfering with
another sovereign government's democratically endorsed decision to
forgive and forget a messy chapter of its own history. They say
Blair is orchestrating the prosecution of Pinochet behind the
scenes to mollify left wingers in his party, who accuse Blair of
selling out traditional Labor policies for political expediency.
</P>
<P>
   Straw, however, rejected suggestions that Pinochet is being
punished for political reasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
