A1550 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IDCRIME-COX     12-09 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDCRIME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New study discounts juvenile crime wave
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fear rather than fact is fueling unnecessarily harsh juvenile
justice policies throughout the United States, according to a
national study released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The MacArthur Foundation's two-year study of juvenile crime
statistics charges that tougher laws aimed at youthful lawbreakers
are based on ``deeply flawed analyses of juvenile violence
statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not any more violent than we were 10 or 20 years ago.
We're just paying more attention to the violence,'' said Franklin
Zimring, author of the study and a law professor at the University
of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Rick McDevitt, president of the Georgia Alliance for Children,
said the findings of the study are not news to many advocates for
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens,'' said McDevitt, ``is that 2 percent of the bad
actors get 100 percent of the notoriety. It's the two percent that
are driving public policy. The other 98 percent of the kids out
there just need a little help and guidance before their problems
get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimring's findings will be published as a book by Oxford
University Press but were released at a news conference Wednesday
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The study was funded by the private MacArthur Foundation, which
is best known for its annual ``genius grants'' but also funds
public policy research.
</P>
<P>
   Zimring said a change in how police report juvenile crimes,
particularly assault and aggravated assault, has resulted in ``an
artificial crime wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimring said his study shows that ``what you find out about
aggravated assault and assault since the mid-1980s, quite
independent of whether youth behavior has been changing, police
behavior has been changing significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have been reducing the threshhold of what constitutes
assault and aggravated assault, the study charges, thus the
apparent increase in crime.
</P>
<P>
   Some other major findings of Zimring's study include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Arrest rates for juveniles age 13-17 accused of rape and
robbery show no significant trend either up or down since 1980 and
have actually declined slightly over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   -- The homicide arrest rate for juveniles ages 13-17 rose
sharply between 1984 and 1992 but fell by more than a third by
1996, according to FBI crime figures. The number of juveniles
arrested for homicide dropped another 16 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Zimring said that in order to counter what is seen as a ``coming
storm of juvenile violence,'' many states have enacted laws that
lower the age at which juveniles can be charged as adults for
certain crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia was among those states, enacting what is commonly known
as Senate Bill 440. Under provisions of this law, juveniles 13-17
are treated as adults if they are charged with any one of seven
crimes generally referred to as ``seven deadly sins.'' They are
murder, voluntary manslaughter, rape, aggravated sodomy, aggravated
child molestation, aggravated sexual battery and armed robbery with
a firearm.
</P>
<P>
   From May 1, 1994, when the law went into effect, through June
30, 1998, about 2,300 juveniles have been arrested as adults under
Senate Bill 440. But not all of them were prosecuted as adults,
since local district attorneys have discretion whether to prosecute
juveniles as adults.
</P>
<P>
   The Juvenile Advocacy Division of the Georgia Indigent Defense
Council, which tracks Senate Bill 440 statistics, said it has been
able to determine the disposition of only 1,095 of those 2,300
cases because there is no central repository for that information.
</P>
<P>
   Of those 1,095 cases, 25 percent were transferred to juvenile
court, 29 percent pleaded guilty (but not necessarily to the
offense charged) and 22 percent were convicted, the council
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of a juvenile crime wave, ``either current or on the
horizon, is no more substantial than the evidence that supports the
existence of the Loch Ness Monster,'' Zimring said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
