u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-EXECUTE-BOS &LR;      12-09 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-EXECUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA PURSUES STAY OF EXECUTION IN TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ In Huntsville, Texas, it's just business as usual:
Another day, another execution. But Canada is recoiling in horror
at the prospect of a native son going under the lethal needle in
America's busiest death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled to die Thursday is Stanley Faulder, a 61-year-old
former mechanic from Alberta convicted of killing an elderly oil
matriarch in a botched 1975 robbery. He would become the fourth man
executed this week alone at the Huntsville Unit prison, in an
extraordinary surge of executions that has grabbed world attention.
</P>
<P>
   Canada is waging a desperate final-hour diplomatic offensive to
win the killer a reprieve, claiming Texas violated international
law by failing to give Faulder access to consular assistance or
advise Canadian officials of his arrest and conviction. Officials
in Ottawa suggest the case has the potential to seriously strain
US-Canadian relations.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles Wednesday refused to
grant clemency. Although a federal judge shortly afterward ordered
a stay of execution, that ruling was expected to be quickly
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Canada's ambassador to the US, Raymond Chretien, made
an unusual personal appeal to Texas Gov. George W. Bush, imploring
the governor to grant a 30-day reprieve to Faulder to allow for a
review of Canada's claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``At issue is not guilt or innocence, but our belief that there
has been a violation of his rights under Article 36 of the Vienna
Convention,'' said Rodney Moore, spokesman for the Canadian Embassy
in Washington. ``This is not a minor point, but a serious lapse.''
</P>
<P>
   The US State Department agrees. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright has added her voice to the growing chorus of concern,
asking Bush to stop the execution to give time to consider whether
international law was violated by Texas's failure to notify Canada
of Faulder's situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Vienna Convention on Consular Relations, which the United
States joined in 1969, requires that an individual arrested on
foreign soil be allowed to seek help from diplomatic
representatives from his own country. The treaty is routinely used
to protect the thousands of Americans arrested every year while
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials admit they failed to inform the Canadian
Consulate General in Dallas of Faulder's arrest or his 1981
conviction in the torture-slaying of a 75-year-old widow, Inez
Philips, in Gladewater, Texas. But they say the mistake is not
serious enough to warrant reconsideration of the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The case has become a cause celebre in Canada, dominating front
pages and televison newscasts in a country that -- like most
Western nations -- outlawed capital punishment in the 1970s. Japan
and the United States are the only industrialized democracies that
sanction the killing of criminals by the state.
</P>
<P>
   If Faulder is executed, he will become the 498th prisoner put to
death since the US Supreme Court restored lethal punishment in
1976, according to the Death Penalty Information Center in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of Canadians have descended upon Huntsville to
demonstrate against the scheduled execution. Foreign Minister Lloyd
Axworthy has asked Washington to intercede on Faulder's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Texas pleading for clemency in Faulder's case was former
American prizefighter Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter, who in the 1960s
faced the death penalty in New Jersey before his conviction for
triple murder was overturned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in his shoes. This is real. We're talking about a
man's life,'' said Carter, now executive director of the
Toronto-based Association in Defense of the Wrongfully Convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Texas leads the US by far when it comes to executing criminals:
162 men and woman have died in the Huntsville death chamber since
1982. All Texas executions are carried out by lethal injection at
Huntsville's 19th Century prison, the largest employer in the small
east Texas city. Local inhabitants take executions in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Detroit and making cars -- it's what we do. No big
deal,'' said John Strickland, owner of the Cafe Texan.
</P>
<P>
   But this week's surge may set a deadly national record, with
executions carried out every day since Monday, and Faulder set to
die at 7 p.m. EST.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
