<SLUG> BC-MILLENIUM-CALENDARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURN THE CENTURY WITH SOME REAL PAGE-TURNERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are 387 days left till the year 2000. Do you know where
your calendar is?
</P>
<P>
   You do if yours is designed for the biggest marketing moment of
the last 1,000 years. The millennium is what the calendar people
have been waiting for: the ultimate countdown.
</P>
<P>
   Want trivia? Try 1,000 Years of Trivia.
</P>
<P>
   Something reflective? Check out the Countdown 2000 Calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Trivial and reflective? Pick up Life magazine's Millennium: A
Look Back at the Past 1,000 Years. Or Great Events of the 20th
Century, compiled by Time, or The New York Times, or the Library of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   What else but a millennium calendar can remind you that the king
and queen of England tasted their first hot dogs at a White House
picnic on June 11, 1939?
</P>
<P>
   Did you forget that Virginia Dare was the first child born in
America to English parents? That happened Aug. 18, 1587.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's first no-hitter? July 15, 1876.
</P>
<P>
   The day the Korean War began? June 25, 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Bach's birthday? March 21, 1685.
</P>
<P>
   It's all in there, somewhere. One calendar found enough to fill
three calendars. The 21st Century Countdown Calendar: Brief
reflections on the beginnings of things, or 1096 easy steps
describing our passage, more or less intact, from the Big Bang to
the Third Millennium is now selling Part II.
</P>
<P>
   All the calendars are so crammed with history nuggets that you
may find yourself mesmerized, turning page after page. With 387
days left, it's not a bad way to pass the time.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
