<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1562 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY10-COX     12-09 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOCIAL SECURITY CONFERENCE DECLARED A SUCCESS
 &HT;    520&AMP;add
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Participants in a two-day White House conference on
reforming Social Security declared it a stunning success Wednesday,
but warned that unless action occurs early next year the
opportunity will be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sense that there is a willingness to reach a consensus,''
said Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., after a closed-door morning session
with President Clinton and congressional leaders held next door to
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, said the conference ``engaged the president,
congressional leaders and all Americans in a constructive
discussion'' about Social Security's problems and the alternatives
to solve them.
</P>
<P>
   The conference _ one day partly open to the public held at a
local hotel, the second day devoted to private meetings between
congressional leaders and administration officials _ was designed
to cap a year-long public discussion about Social Security's future
and set the stage for negotiations over a reform plan next month.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Social Security is reformed, income into the Social
Security trust fund will fall below benefit payments by 2013, and
the system's reserves will be depleted by 2032, leaving only enough
operating money to pay about three-fourths of benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The closed session focused on two main questions: how to proceed
politically, and to what extent private investments would play a
role in bolstering the nation's retirement and disability program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very candid conversation, and there was, I thought,
(a remarkable) amount of good will and bipartisanship,'' said Gene
Sperling, the White House chief economic adviser. ``People felt
that the effort this morning of bringing everybody together had
been, as one key member called it, 'a sign of real momentum.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties said Clinton indicated he would offer a
plan to reform Social Security if lawmakers thought it would be
helpful _ rather than polarize positions _ but they said no
decision was made on when that would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Archer again called on Clinton to offer a detailed plan soon,
but Democratic lawmakers suggested that the White House might delay
offering a plan until there was greater agreement over its main
points.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, at Clinton's suggestion, congressional
committees will begin compiling information to be given to all
members of Congress detailing the Social Security problem and
offering an objective analysis of the impact of various reform
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton suggested another meeting with the same group of 48
congressional leaders for the end of December, to be followed by
further meetings with smaller groups early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats warned that efforts to reach a quick agreement on a
plan that could be enacted before next summer would be seriously
impaired if the House votes next week to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a severe, if not fatal, insertion,'' said Sen. Bob
Graham, D-Fla., ``We've got to get this thing done in the next six
months, and if half is taken in an impeachment trial'' it would
lessen the chances.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the question of how to proceed, Clinton and lawmakers
began wrestling with the question of how to reform the program.
</P>
<P>
   Various proposals revolve around two main alternatives, but both
involve some investment in private markets, a departure from Social
Security's 63-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and some Democrats have called for using a portion
of the 12.4 percent payroll tax for individual investment accounts.
Many Democrats have suggested allowing the government to invest the
Social Security surplus in private markets, the way many states
invest their pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., who has advocated
allowing individuals to voluntarily add a private investment to
their Social Security payroll deduction, said he'd be willing to
consider some form of personal investments out of the Social
Security trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could also consider, although it has grave complications,
using a part of the Social Security trust fund that's assigned to
individuals who can then assign those monies to plan A, B, or C,''
Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
