<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1567 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-YORK-DEBT-HNS &LR;      12-09 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-YORK-DEBT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TREASURER SEEKS OVERHAUL OF STATE BORROWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES M. ODATO  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Comptroller H. Carl McCall said Wednesday he
wants state borrowing to rise and fall with the incomes of New
Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Delivering on a campaign promise to introduce ways to control
state debt, the Democrat called for placing a cap on borrowing at
3.5 percent of total state personal income, which is running at
$550 billion. That would bring debt down to about half the current
6.5 percent level.
</P>
<P>
   McCall called the growth and reliance on debt during the 1990s
``scandalous.'' The state owes $34 billion and its public
authorities owe another $64 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The recently re-elected comptroller, now considering running for
U.S. Senate in two years, proposed a second control: Debt payments
each year could not be above 5.75 percent of the state budget.
</P>
<P>
   Payments reached 4.8 percent of the $71.4 billion budget this
year and are on line to meet the proposed cap by the 2000-2001
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said his plan could be phased in by the Legislature
before a constitutional amendment is voted on in two years by the
public.
</P>
<P>
   The last time debt reform was attempted, in 1995, voters
overwhelmingly defeated the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal I have now has no loopholes,'' McCall said. The
new proposal also has a lower cap, 3.5 percent instead of the 4.4
percent cap three years ago. Plus, the previous proposal did not
include a cap on debt payment.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal received mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Schulz, who has filed numerous lawsuits against state
officials for issuing bonds without voter approval, called McCall's
package a ``warmed over'' version of the one defeated by voters
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debt limiting provisions we now have in the constitution
are adequate. We we have the best cap available _ voter approval,''
Schulz said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, a Republican, seemed receptive to the reform
package, saying: ``It is certainly worthy of consideration and we
think there are some good ideas there.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall's plan would make sure the state only borrowed for
capital projects, such as highway or building construction. In the
past and as recently as this year, the state has borrowed to pay
for expenses and for items that have a short life span, such as
fire equipment and vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said the debt control is needed to improve the state's
low credit rating and to reduce the high debt level.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kurtter, a senior vice president at Moody's Investors
Service, which rates bonds, said that states with high credit
ratings have some form of debt control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comptroller's proposal, all of his proposals, would be an
important step in that direction,'' Kurtter said. But he predicted
the proposal would face ``difficult negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall proposes a bipartisan debt management board and public
hearings on capital spending plans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 1856EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
