<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-COLLEGES-TEXAS-1210-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXANS DEBATE EFFECT OF OMISSION FROM LIST OF TOP SCHOOLS FOR
BLACKS
 &HT;    620 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Students and faculty at Texas universities
expressed concerns Wednesday that their exclusion from a list of
top schools for blacks could further wound a reputation already
marred by the affirmative action debate.
</P>
<P>
   When Black Enterprise on Tuesday unveiled its ranking of top 50
schools for black students, no Texas schools made the list.
</P>
<P>
   The only Texas schools mentioned were the University of
Houston-Downtown, which ranked No. 3 among regional liberal arts
colleges and Prairie View A&AMP;M, which received an honorable mention
among all colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The rankings, expected to hit newsstands late this month, come
at a time when Texas colleges are grappling with the demise of
affirmative action after a 1996 ruling, known as ``Hopwood,'' by
the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In sheer numbers, the University of Texas and Texas A&AMP;M
University have boosted black and Hispanic enrollments above last
year, but neither school has reached the pre-Hopwood minority
enrollment levels of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some speculated that UT didn't make the cut because of the low
percentage of the black student population.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of students don't graduate or transfer because it's so
big and they feel lost,'' said UT senior Demitris Williams. ``That
becomes multiplied with students of color, because there are so few
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said though university life has been good to her, the
numbers of minority students may be small because some prospective
students believe the university fosters an atmosphere hostile to
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Burt, director of the campus Minority Information Center,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our image is awful in the community, and it's awful because of
things like Hopwood ...,'' Burt said. ``When our students who leave
the campus don't go back and relay the positive things that go on
here, it does create a bad image.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Black Enterprise senior editor Marjorie
Whigham-Desir, Burt and Williams are partially right. She said what
ultimately set many schools apart in the rankings was not only
their ability to attract students, but their success in retaining
and graduating black students.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Texas schools want to know what they have to do, then I
guess it's time for their administration to look at what kinds of
efforts are being made toward African-American students and getting
those students through the process and graduating them,''
Whigham-Desir said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Perry, executive associate provost at Texas A&AMP;M University,
said the rankings may further enhance the negative perception some
black students have of Texas schools, especially in the
post-Hopwood environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe these different rankings that are put out by
different newspapers and magazines that are widely publicized do
have an impact on the perceptions of high school students,'' Perry
said. ``When a school fails to be mentioned, you don't get a
positive stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry declined to comment further until he had seen the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Ashlock, A&AMP;M executive director of university relations,
wasn't so sure students would give much weight to the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will have any effect on their perception,''
Ashlock said. ``Students looking at A&AMP;M either know they want to go
here or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jennings, an A&AMP;M senior, also was skeptical of the
rankings, but said some potential students might take it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they can personally tell me what is a good
race-relations campus and what is not,'' Jennings said. ``I think
it will scare high school students, but it's up to high school
students to look into the college setting, and it shouldn't be your
sole decision why you don't go to the school.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
