<HEADER>
A1613 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHANUKAH-AUSCHWITZ-NY     12-09 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHANUKAH-AUSCHWITZ-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEATH-CAMP MENORAH CONVEYS THE MESSAGE OF CHANUKAH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative NIRDI
RELIS in New York at (800) 972-3550 or (212) 499-3333, or fax her
at (212) 499-3382.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RABBI ELI HECHT &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When the holiday of Chanukah comes around I think of the
children of all religions who are extremely busy looking for the
latest toys and gadgets. They hope for holiday gifts that their
parents and friends will buy.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish children anxiously wait for Sunday, December 13, the
night Chanukah begins. As soon as the menorah lights are lit, the
presents will miraculously appear.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I wonder if they understand the holiday message of
freedom. Lighting the menorah has not always been easy. Let me
share a story I heard from friends who were World War II Holocaust
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Daily the death-train cattle cars full of starving, frightened
Jews arrived in Auschwitz. From the platform one could see the
tall, smoking chimneys. The main furnaces were filled with burning
bodies of gassed victims.
</P>
<P>
   One day a new group of victims arrived at the camp. Standing by
the main entrance they read the inscription:Arbeit Macht Frei --
Work is Freedom. A feeling of dread filled their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   The chief guard, a sadistic man, infamous for his unbridled
cruelty, greeted the victims. ``Jews, it is Chanukah,'' he said.
``The great Satan told me that you want to brighten your life with
a Chanukah light. So today, instead of killing you, I send you to
the nearby cabin. There you can rest.''With that, the Jews were
herded into the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   A young man stood up, pointing out the window to the burning
ovens. ``We will soon be the Holy Chanukah lights,'' he said. A
great wailing broke out.
</P>
<P>
   A yeshiva student said what good was there in Chanukah if they
had no menorah and oil and wicks to light. The children began to
cry and were soon joined by their parents.
</P>
<P>
   In the group was an old rabbi, Reb Yossef. Strangely, he was
very much in control of himself, ignoring the pandemonium all
around him. He began to speak in a sweet, holy voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who needs candles, oil and wicks. In every Jew there is a
Godly fire. Our holy books state that the soul of man is the light
of God. In time the world will realize that we have an ever-burning
light. No nation in the world can extinguish our flame.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the chief guard entered the room. ``Filthy Jews, I'm
going to give you a treat. In this Arbeit Lagar (work camp) we give
a 20-gram slice of bread to each of you. Today I'll play a game. I
will soon put one loaf of bread down and you, my Jewish animals,
will have to divide it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that you will fight each other trying to get a piece.
That will make great Chanukah entertainment. Right now I will give
each of you two grams of fat. And to you, old man, I give a double
portion.''
</P>
<P>
   The wicked guard, looking like the devil himself, threw the fat
on the floor and ordered the old rabbi to lick it up. Reb Yossef
fell to the floor and carefully put the fat into the fold of his
coat.
</P>
<P>
   The guard laughed, thinking that he had degraded the rabbi and
the Jews. When the guard had finished his fun he went out of the
cabin to summon his fellow henchmen. They would watch the Jews
fight over the bread that he would soon hand out.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brothers and sisters,'' said Reb Yossef, ``Today we have
witnessed a miracle. I now have the oil for lighting a menorah. My
coat has plenty of threads -- so now we have wicks. Come join me
for the lighting.''
</P>
<P>
   The people gave their portion of fat and soon there was enough
fuel for the wicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is a small silver cup I have hidden in my clothes. You
can use it for a container,'' said a young man.
</P>
<P>
   Another person gave the cover from an old pocket watch. A mother
of small children ripped off the buttons from her coat. Removing
the cloth from the buttons, they now became little containers. In a
few minutes there was a home-made menorah ready for lighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brethren,'' the rabbi began, ``Let us show our tormentors
that they may be able to extinguish our bodies but never our
spirit. As I light the menorah for this last Chanukah, let us all
pray that our sacrifice is not in vain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Jews have witnessed many miracles. I am sure that our
people will in the end triumph over evil and cruelty. Come sing
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The people were now calm. What had been a frightened people now
turned into a composed and calm group. They were no longer
frightened of death. The Chanukah spirit had put them into a
peaceful trance.
</P>
<P>
   The guard, seeing the flickering light in the cabin window, was
beside himself. He couldn't understand how the Jews did it. How in
the world could a starving, beaten, frightened people celebrate
Chanukah in Auschwitz!
</P>
<P>
   Truthfully speaking, you need a soul to understand a miracle and
that was something the guard had lost to Satan. Very few survived
the camp. But the one who did told the story.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night I will light the menorah and tell my children
about the menorah in Auschwitz. How the spirit of people can never
be broken. I hope to impress them with a message of Chanukah that
is more than toys and games.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vicepresident of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and pastpresident of the Rabbinical Council of California.
He is the director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
