<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: COURT DEFENDS ANNE FRANK; COMMEMORATING ELEANOR
ROOSEVELT; FRENCH HONOR RUSSIAN; STEINER WINS CAPOTE AWARD; MEARA
HOSTS WOMEN'S EVENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., Netherlands, Russia)   (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Dutch court Wednesday banned all publications that cast doubt
on the authenticity of Anne Frank's diary. Declaring that such
questions insulted and offended Jews, the court ruled in a case
arising from the unsolicited distribution to Dutch libraries in
1992 of a book that alleged that Anne's father, Otto, was the true
author of her journal chronicling her family's years of hiding from
the Nazis. In the case, brought by the Anne Frank Foundation of
Amsterdam and the Anne Frank Fund of Basel, Switzerland, the court
barred the publishers and authors of ``Anne Frank: A Critical
Approach,'' from distributing it on pain of a $12,500 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Memory's Music
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Philharmonic of San Francisco will offer the world
premiere of ``Eleanor's Gift'' Thursday in San Francisco with the
actress Jean Stapleton as narrator and the cellist Paul Tobias of
the faculty of the Manhattan School of Music as featured soloist.
The work for solo cello and orchestra, by the Chinese composer Chen
Yi, commemorates Eleanor Roosevelt on the 50th anniversary of the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Roosevelt was a co-author of the U.N. document, signed
across the street from the Herbst Theater, where ``Eleanor's Gift''
is to be performed. Presented in partnership with Amnesty
International, ``Eleanor's Gift'' is a project of New Heritage
Music, which commissions works commemorating people, events or
themes central to American history.
</P>
<P>
   Honorable Cause
</P>
<P>
   In St. Petersburg, Russia, the director of the Hermitage,
Mikhail Pyotrovsky, received the Legion of Honor Wednesday from the
French ambassador, Hubert Colin de Verdiere. The envoy saluted him
as a researcher, administrator and ``a great friend of French
culture.'' Pyotrovsky, 54, has directed the Hermitage, with its 2.5
million works of art, for six years.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen
</P>
<P>
   George Steiner, whose books include ``The Death of Tragedy'' and
``Language and Science,'' is the winner of the $100,000 Truman
Capote Lifetime Achievement Award, established in memory of the
critic Newton Arvin. The prize is awarded to a distinguished critic
every four years.
</P>
<P>
   Festivities
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The comedian and actress Anne Meara will be the
mistress of ceremonies when New York Women in Film and Television
celebrates its 20th anniversary and honors the actress Candice
Bergen; the HBO senior vice president for original programming,
Sheila Nevins; and the cinematographer Dyanna Taylor, next Thursday
at the New York Hilton and Towers. The actress Gena Rowlands will
accept a posthumous lifetime achievement award on behalf of the
director and actress Ida Lupino.
</P>
</TEXT>
