<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FAVORS PRIVATE INVESTMENT FOR SOCIAL SECURITY, ADVISER
SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To keep Social Security solvent in the next
century, President Clinton supports some form of private market
investment for the retirement fund, a key adviser said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made clear that he favored using a more aggressive
investment strategy in comments to a bipartisan group of lawmakers
who caucused privately on the final day of a White House summit on
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, director of the president's National Economic
Council, said that Clinton told lawmakers that ``we should be
looking for ways to get higher rate of return into Social
Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Sperling said Clinton believed that of all the options, which
include raising taxes or lowering benefits, increasing the rate of
return on Social Security contributions was the least painful.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sperling said, the president has not endorsed any
specific investment plan. One option would allow the government to
invest Social Security monies, including more than $700 billion in
reserves, in higher yielding funds than the government securities
where the money is now placed.
</P>
<P>
   The other more controversial option would allow individuals to
take some of the taxes they now pay to Social Security and invest
that money in the private market.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton were to support this plan he would enrage some of his
Democratic base, including organized labor, which has vowed to
oppose such investments as too risky and inequitable.
</P>
<P>
   While the president has not spelled out specific legislation for
Social Security reform, he told members of Congress gathered for
the morning session that he would be willing to submit a plan first
if they believed that was the best way to advance the process.
</P>
<P>
   That has been the preferred route of Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas,
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, who attended the
session and has repeatedly said that Social Security reform will
not happen unless Clinton takes the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Archer praised the meeting, where various options were
discussed, for its ``wonderful spirit of bipartisanship.'' But he
warned that those involved have to get beyond the talk and come up
with something concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Others also said that they came away with the belief that
Clinton was willing to tackle the politically touchy subject next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, a staunch conservative who rarely
praises Clinton, said ``I believe the president is committed to
dealing with the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm has proposed a plan that would allow individuals to invest
a portion of their Social Security contributions in the private
markets.
</P>
<P>
   All of Wednesday's sessions were held behind closed doors to
allow lawmakers to ``let their guard down and avoid
grandstanding,'' as one participant said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton's first term health care initiative got off to
a rocky start because the plan was devised by a task force that met
privately and did not solicit enough public input.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Republican members of the House Judiciary Committee
want to impeach the president, Archer said he could still work with
Clinton on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Archer said he will decide how to vote on impeachment after the
Judiciary Committee makes its decision.
</P>
<P>
   Archer said he had ``stayed out of the loop'' on the impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not my cup of tea,'' he said. ``I like substance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
