<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEENEY BACK BOLSTERING BRUINS' DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON _ He missed 23 games last season with a fractured
shoulder blade _ a rare injury, to be sure _ suffered March 1
against the New York Islanders. For Don Sweeney, one of the Bruins'
true iron men, it was a frustrating injury that required a long
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   It took two surgical procedures to resolve the vexing problem,
and it wasn't until late October that the 32-year-old defenseman
felt like himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came back off the (West Coast) road trip not feeling great,
not feeling as aggressive as I like to be and tentative,'' said
Sweeney. ``Not necessarily hittingwise but in all facets of the
game. We went into Montreal (Oct. 28), and obviously, everybody had
a great game (in a 9-2 Bruins rout). Then we played them at home
(the next night), and I felt like I was much more back on my toes.
I was jumping to things and not sitting back and maybe waiting for
plays to develop and then reacting.''
</P>
<P>
   What was happening was exactly what coach Pat Burns had told
Sweeney would happen. After holding Sweeney out of the exhibition
games to make sure the shoulder blade was healed, Burns told him
his game wouldn't come back immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `It may take you 10 regular-season games to get
back,' '' said Sweeney. ``I was laughing. I said, `It took eight.'
He was pretty damn close.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney has always played a fearless, physical style, which he
feels is necessary for him at the NHL level. It wasn't the contact
that gave him pause, it was the other necessary components of his
game _ namely, aggressiveness and stepping up on the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't apprehensive about getting hit,'' said Sweeney. ``I
didn't have a fear about it. It's more or less a game situation
where you're sitting back, you're not dictating a lot of times. As
a defenseman, you want to read the play but you can make people
make bad plays by forcing them in areas. I felt like I was sitting
back and giving them time and space. That's a big part of my game.
I have to eliminate time and space especially, because guys are
getting bigger and bigger. I have to use that quickness and smarts
and physical attributes to the best of my ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, who has one goal and five assists in 24 games, is best
appreciated by his teammates. To a defensive defenseman, the best
compliment is not to be noticed. To others in the dressing room
such as Ray Bourque, Sweeney's contribution is huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been playing great,'' said Bourque, who frequently the
last few years has been asked to carry too heavy a load. ``It
probably took him about three weeks to a month to really get back
to where he was, and he's been playing great for over a month now.
It gives us so much depth. We've got six guys _ actually, seven _
we've been using, and we've really got a good rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney has terrific speed, and though he's not nearly as big as
some blue-liners (5 feet 10 inches, 185 pounds), he has shown
throughout his 11-year pro career that he's among the most
dependable and durable in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got as good a `D' as any team in the league,''
said Bourque. ``We have guys with experience. Our youngest guy has
more than three years' experience (Kyle McLaren). It's allowed us
to go out and use three solid combinations, which has been good for
everybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
