<SLUG> BC-MA-EXAMS-PARENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS CAN'T HELP MAKING COMPARISONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Thousands of Massachusetts parents spent Wednesday
doing exactly what the state asked them not to do with the MCAS
test results: They immediately compared individual schools and
districts to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding the state Department of Education's Internet site with
more than 10,000 hits by midday, then sharing the information at
bus stops and through telephone trees, parents descended on the
most detailed test data ever released on their community's schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is information every parent dreams about,'' said Abby
Doherty, a Natick parent of a sixth-grader. ``It's silly to say
we're not comparing the Brown with the Memorial School, or
whatever. It's natural . . . Later we're going to take a hard look
at exactly where our kids stand. Some of us will realize they need
more of our help. It's not just the schools that may need to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   While superintendents and principals declared publicly that they
are not using the data to rank classrooms or schools, some
acknowledged privately Wednesday that that is exactly what they are
doing.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Superintendent of Schools Mihran Keoseian _ whose
district scored highest in the state among those that offer K-12,
according to a Globe computer analysis _ said, ``They are telling
us not to do it, but who isn't going to do it?''
</P>
<P>
   But many parents said they won't view the scores as the sole
determination of a good school.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a parent is unhappy with a school, they will use this as a
tool to move on,'' said Hannah Stokes, a Newbury parent of a
fifth-grader who took the test last year. ``Those who like their
schools will stay.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials have insisted repeatedly that the MCAS data for
grades 4, 8 and 10 is only a baseline by which to measure future
improvement _ not a good indicator of which schools are doing the
best job.
</P>
<P>
   In Stokes's Newbury district, English scores were low and other
scores fairly high: only about 17 percent of elementary school
students scored in the proficient category in English, and none
scored in the advanced category. But in math, 30 percent scored in
the top two categories, and 70 percent scored that high in science.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scores show me that we have to get back to the basics of
reading and writing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, others said it is simply too early to tell exactly what
the test scores show _ and it will be several weeks or months
before schools determine why some schools did better than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, people have been overreacting,'' said Irwin
Silverstein, a high school parent and vice chairman of the Needham
School Committee. ``You have to spend time digesting the
information and not go right off and say this is awful or this is
terrific. It is going to take us a while to know what the numbers
mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Deanne Peterson is a mother of two in the Agassiz Elementary
School in Cambridge, which had not a single student scoring
``advanced'' in English. However, 51 percent of its students scored
proficient or advanced in science, and 29 percent in those
categories for math.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said that while she is unsure how she'll feel after she
pores over the data on her school, she's optimistic because,
``Education is now out in front of the public like it never has
been before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
