<HEADLINE>
MIDWEST GRAIN FINDS NEW USES FOR GLUTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: A Kansas company is doing wonders with wheat these
days. It has learned how to turn the state's biggest crop into tent
pegs and cosmetic agents, dog chews and golf tees, meat extenders
and disposable forks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As varied as these items seem, each began with protein extracted
from wheat. The protein, called gluten, is in every slice of bread
you eat. Gluten is what gives bread the strength to form a loaf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at Midwest Grain Products Inc. in Atchison have found
ways to modify the gluten for new uses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Modified one way, gluten takes on a fibrous, soft, stringy
structure that looks and feels like cooked chicken. But it doesn't
taste like much at all, which makes it an easily flavored meat
substitute or extender. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Modified another way, gluten becomes like plastic. In this form,
it can be injected into molds, just like petroleum-based plastics.
But the gluten-based products are biodegradable and can be made
edible under one formulation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company also has made a strengthener for seasoned pastas,
and foaming agents and proteins for hair- and skin-care products. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Researchers cooked up all these wonders with the ultimate aim of
modifying the nature of Midwest Grain itself, which historically
has sold basic commodities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``These are different products than we have rolled out before,''
said Ladd Seaberg, Midwest Grain's president and chief executive
officer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, Seaberg expects that in three years, these specialty
gluten products will generate about $30 million in revenue, about
equal to its sales of wheat gluten. That's no small goal, given
that Midwest Grain has been selling gluten since 1953. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Polytriticum is the company's newest modified gluten product. It
is essentially plasticized gluten resin. It melts. It flows. It
cools and hardens. Just like plastic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showing off the stuff, Seaberg produces plastic cutlery, golf
tees, saucers and a tent peg, all made from modified gluten.
Essentially, anything made by injecting plastic into molds can be
made from Polytriticum, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bury the items in soil and they break down. Depending on the
formula Midwest Grain uses, the material will degrade in three to
six months or even longer, Seaberg said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we can fine-tune,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Midwest Grain doesn't make the forks and golf tees. It makes
pellets that it hopes to sell to companies that make
injection-molded products. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seaberg says Polytriticum costs about 20 percent more than
regular plastic, a common problem for biodegradable alternatives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Polytriticum comes in two varieties. Polytriticum 200 is edible,
though it's too hard for human jaws. Polytriticum 2000 is not
edible, but it lasts longer and stands up to heat better. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Kansas City, Mo., company already uses Polytriticum 200 to
make dog chews. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judy and Joe Roetheli make Greenies from the material, adding
breath fresheners. Joe Roetheli says that most dog chews are made
from starch but that the gluten-based Polytriticum makes Greenies a
source of protein for the dog. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we have in Greenies is human-grade edible
material,'' said Roetheli, whose Kansas City company is S&AMP;M NuTec
LLC. ``I frankly chew on the resin myself.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Midwest Grain doesn't recommend people eat its Polytriticum 200,
but only because it is so hard. However, the company sells Wheatex,
fully intending it for humans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wheatex is the company's brand name for a texturized wheat
gluten. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dry, it looks like frozen noodles, but in lumps rather than
strips. Wet, it looks like cooked chicken. It can be made to look
like beef, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``With this kind of structure, you can add it to virtually any
kind of meat product,'' Seaberg said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The product is a potential rival for other gluten- and
soybean-based meat extenders or substitutes. Consumers already buy
seitan, which is made from gluten but isn't texturized. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Seitan is primarily a washed dough,'' said John Moore, who
does research and development work at Gardenburger Inc. in
Portland, Ore. ``They found a way to make fiber out of it,'' Moore
said of Midwest Grain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wheatex has another trait that could put it in competition with
soybean-based meat substitutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Wheatex is much blander,'' Moore said. ``Soy has a taste that
a lot of people find objectionable, and it's very hard to cover
that taste.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gardenburger uses Wheatex in its Garden Vegan Veggie Patties.
It's listed as texturized wheat gluten in the ingredients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pasta Power is another edible modified gluten product from
Midwest Grain. John Brewer has been using it in seasoned pastas at
Heartland Pasta Factory in the City Market since testing it three
years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brewer says the product increases the protein in his pasta,
which he mostly sells to restaurant chefs. He uses Pasta Power in
place of egg whites. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He also adds Pasta Power to seasoned pastas for strength. Brewer
says anything, such as spinach or tomatoes, that is added to the
semolina weakens the resulting pasta. Pasta Power makes up the lost
ground and allows Brewer to turn up the flavor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our spinach (pasta) looks and tastes like spinach instead of
just having the color,'' Brewer said. &QL; 
Seaberg expects the line of modified gluten products to modify
Midwest Grain's profit-and-loss statement.
</P>
<P>
   Since forming in 1941, Midwest Grain has made and sold basic
commodities, starting with alcohol, then adding gluten and wheat
starch. Each is a basic commodity, and that makes the company
susceptible to price cuts by rivals that sell the same basic
commodities.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, gluten prices have fallen sharply largely
because of heavy imports from the European Union. In June, the U.S.
government placed a quota that limits gluten imports from European
Union nations for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Seaberg plans to use those three years of protection to invest
about $30 million to establish Midwest Grain's line of modified
products. The idea is that Midwest Grain ends up with a higher
profit and steadier business when the gluten quotas end and the
commodity market reopens to full imports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
