A1655 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISTORIANS-TESTIMONY-     12-09 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORIANS-TESTIMONY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW HISTORIANS MAKE HISTORY, NOT JUST RECORD IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Tuesday marked a most visible descent of historians
from their ivory towers.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Wilentz, history professor at Princeton University,
appeared before the House Judiciary Committee to argue that
President Clinton's offenses, however serious, did not amount to
impeachable ones.
</P>
<P>
   This followed the October release of an open letter, signed by
Wilentz and about 400 fellow historians, that argued much the same.
</P>
<P>
   Both events have sparked debate among historians as to the
propriety of taking sides in a partisan battle. Some critics wonder
whether historians are trying to make history instead of write it.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of American Historians, the country's largest
group of professional historians, has issued no official response
to the controversy. But that hasn't stopped individual academics
from debating the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Their opinions, however, have not always reflected their
political interests.
</P>
<P>
   Herb Parmet, a New York author of recent biographies of George
Bush and Richard Nixon, believes Wilentz's appearance, as well as
his message, to be entirely proper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historians have responsibilities as citizens, too,'' said
Parmet. ``They should express their points on view of history, just
as lawyers express their views on points of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Smist, chairman of the political science department at
Rockhurst College in Kansas City, Mo., is a longtime Democrat who
voted for Clinton. But he feels differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historians should be there as resources,'' said Smist. ``But
to take the lead, as these historians did, suggests a hubris that
is unwarranted and unjustified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed to think that historians would choose to get
involved in a very partisan debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Smist argues that when historians enter the fray as Wilentz has
done, they damage the efforts of those who want to portray the
social sciences _ such as history _ to be as neutral as the
physical sciences, such as biology and chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When historians take positions like the ones they are taking
here, they are getting away from that ideal,'' Smist said.
</P>
<P>
   Some historians, in recent years, have not been shy about taking
sides in controversies. In 1994, Truman biographer David McCullough
led an ad hoc group of historians, preservationists and
environmentalists in protesting a proposed 3,000-acre Disney
history theme park slated to be built near a Civil War battlefield
site in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Disney later backed down.
</P>
<P>
   That case focused, however, on preservation of a historical
resource.
</P>
<P>
   Historian Arthur Schlesinger, one of the 400 who signed
Wilentz's letter, worked in the Kennedy White House.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hechler, a former special assistant to Harry S. Truman, has
West Virginia's secretary of state for the past 14 years. He was a
U.S. representative for 18 years before that.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that didn't stop him from writing ``Working With Truman,'' a
memoir that was reprinted in 1996 by the University of Missouri
Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historians not only have a right but an obligation to speak
out on issues that concern them,'' Hechler said. ``They ought to
offer their superior perspective and knowledge on social issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Hechler, for the record, agrees with Wilentz that Clinton's
offenses are not impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   Even a century ago, historians fit the description of
propagandists.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most spectacular local example was John Newman
Edwards, a former Confederate soldier who later went on to write
for The Kansas City Times and serve as a vivid historian of that
cause. Edwards' 1867 book, ``Shelby and His Men,'' described the
exploits of Confederate Gen. Joseph Shelby, who took his soldiers
to Mexico at the end of the Civil War rather than surrender.
</P>
<P>
   And Edwards' editorial on the April 1882 murder of outlaw and
former rebel guerrilla fighter Jesse James was the 19th-century
equivalent of scorched-earth rhetoric. Edwards was incensed that
the Missouri governor played a role James' assassination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tear the bears from the flag of Missouri,'' Edwards wrote in a
Sedalia newspaper. ``Put thereon in place of them as more
appropriate, a thief blowing out the brains of an unarmed victim,
and a brazen harlot, naked to the waist and splashed to the brows
in blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, those following the Clinton impeachment proceedings can
consider the testimony of Sean Wilentz as only one more opinion,
said Hechler.
</P>
<P>
   But for Washington not to allow historians the chance to offer
their wisdom to the world is short-sighted, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Harry Truman said, the only thing new in the world is the
history that you haven't read,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
