<HEADER>
A1658 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-CLINTON-1210-COX     12-09 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-CLINTON-1210-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEC PLAYS SANTA FOR DOLE AND CLINTON
 &HT;    500 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Election Commission decided Wednesday
that President Clinton and Republican challenger Bob Dole won't
have to repay millions of tax dollars for breaking the spending
limits in their 1996 campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting advice from its staff auditors and attorneys, the FEC
decided against ordering Dole to repay nearly $18 million and
Clinton about $7 million of the taxpayer funds they used in 1996.
Instead, commissioners began a series of votes that will reduce the
maximum repayment figures to less than $4 million for Dole and less
than $100,000 for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Santa Claus came early for Bob Dole and Bill Clinton,''
grumbled Russell Verney, national chairman of the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Gross, attorney for the Dole campaign, retorted, ``I think
what happened is that Scrooge came in early with the staff report,
and now they're rejecting him.''
</P>
<P>
   Verney said that as a practical matter, Wednesday's FEC action
``means there is no longer any regulatory limit on spending by
political parties to influence a presidential election prior to the
day that the candidate is actually nominated at a convention.''
</P>
<P>
   The FEC staff had charged that each candidate broke the spending
limit he agreed to as a condition of getting the federal funds. The
staff said the candidates evaded the limit by having his party's
national committee pay for millions of dollars' worth of extra
campaign ads.
</P>
<P>
   However, in two key votes Wednesday by the six political
appointees on the commission:
</P>
<P>
   All six voted for a technical motion that reduced the maximum
repayment order that could be imposed against Dole to about $7
million _ the same level as Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   Only two commissioners _ Democrats Scott Thomas and Danny
McDonald _ supported the staff's finding that the commission has
authority to order a candidate involved in ``excessive spending''
to repay part of his federal funds. That is short of the four votes
required for the FEC to issue any repayment order.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing them were Republicans David Mason, Darryl Wold and Lee
Ann Elliott, who voted to deny that the commission has such
authority. Democrat Karl Sandstrom, who said he thinks the
commission has the authority but should not exercise it, abstained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, from now on, there won't be four votes for any
repayments related to alleged excess spending,'' said Lyn Utrecht,
attorney for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Formal votes at which the commission can eliminate the rest of
that type of repayment order were set for Thursday. Preliminary
estimates indicated that would cut the $7 million maximum liability
at least in half for Dole and to less than $100,000 for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The commission will consider reducing those figures further when
reviewing its auditors' recommendations on matters other than
excess spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission moved in the right direction,'' said Dole
attorney Gross. ``But I'm not counting my chickens before they
hatch.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
