<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S TO A STATE SENATOR WHO UNDERSTANDS HONESTY IN PUBLIC
POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: _ It's a bit early for year-end awards ceremonies, but
a Missouri state senator is a cinch to win 1998's Diogenes Award.
</P>
<P>
   Diogenes, legend has it, plied the streets of Athens with a
lighted lamp in daylight looking for an honest person.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Diogenes, meet David Klarich, who wants Missouri voters to
decide whether the state's share of the tobacco extortion windfall
should be rebated to taxpayers or entrusted to government.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri stands to receive $6.7 billion over 25 years as a
result of the tobacco industry's $206 billion settlement with state
governments. Klarich, a Republican from Ballwin, believes the money
would be subject to the Hancock Amendment, which limits state
revenue growth. Klarich says he's pursuing a vote on the issue to
prevent a court battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is too important for the big spenders of the state to
decide,'' Klarich said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Hear, hear!
</P>
<P>
   If the state is allowed control of the windfall, it probably
will evolve into a source of patronage and vote-buying to promote
politically correct vogue causes as they come to the fore. These
will no doubt change because a quarter of a century is a long, long
time.
</P>
<P>
   The current administration is indicating a spending preference
for anti-smoking initiatives. This is predictable, because the
rationale for mugging the tobacco industry was to recoup public
money spent remedying health problems suffered by smokers.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded plausible, except for overlooking the considerable
research showing that tobacco users more than pay their way. Not
only do they live shorter than average lives, and thus consume less
government resources, but they also pay humongous taxes on their
tobacco purchases while alive.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, big tobacco decided to cut the best deal it could
rather than fight forever. The tobacco business is, after all, a
money machine. Besides, most of the tab probably will be picked up
by those who can't get along without the product because their
dedication to their habit is nothing short of fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   Given the way smokers have taken the recent per-pack price
increase of four bits or so in stride, there doesn't seem to be any
limit to how much committed puffers will pay for their smokes.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Klarich's proposal so attractive is its bedrock
honesty. When governments decided to extort money from a highly
unpopular business, it was essentially committing theft in the name
of the citizenry. If the people were willing to be complicit in
this taking of another's property because it was politically
possible, then the money should be returned to those in whose name
the money was taken.
</P>
<P>
   There once was a quaint idea abroad in this fair land that
nothing, absolutely nothing, justified taking something that didn't
belong to you. Government's legitimization of greed, however, has
since superseded moral, ethical and religious admonitions against
such behavior and made it not only legal, but also respectable.
</P>
<P>
   Given public attitudes, it's impossible to believe Missourians
would vote to allow state government to keep the money. This is how
it should be. What distinguishes Klarich is that he's honest enough
to acknowledge the taxpayer's right to a first claim on the loot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
