<HEADER>
A1665 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASHCROFT-CONTRIBUTION     12-09 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASHCROFT-CONTRIBUTIONS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERAL STATE ELECTION LAWS THWART FEDERAL GOVERNMENT'S INTENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under federal election law, a corporation cannot
make a direct contribution to Sen. John Ashcroft, and even through
a political action committee, it could kick in no more than
$10,000.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are Virginia's election laws.
</P>
<P>
   Using that state's vastly different legal thresholds, the House
of Lloyd, a Grandview, Mo.-based direct sales gift company concern,
was able to give the Missouri Republican $400,000 last summer.
</P>
<P>
   That check helped pay for an advertising blitz to promote
Ashcroft's $1.7 trillion tax cut program in Iowa and New Hampshire,
two early presidential states.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a mind-boggling amount compared to the (federal) legal
limit,'' said Ellen Miller, executive director of Public Campaign,
a public interest group concerned about campaign financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly ethical,'' said Tony Trimble, the attorney for
Ashcroft's Virginia PAC, American Values, which accepted the
contribution. ``It's clearly in accordance with the law and with
the legal and permissible uses of contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft _ like several other would-be presidential contenders _
had found a way to legally step around federal financial limits on
campaigning: Incorporate a political action committee in a state
where campaign rules are extremely lax compared to Washington's.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal rules, individuals are allowed to contribute up to
$2,000 to a candidate and up to $10,000 to political action
committees for a two-year election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The $400,000 House of Lloyd check may be the largest single
donation that any individual or corporation made to a political
action committee associated with one politician during the 1997-98
election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Saul Kass, vice president and senior adviser at House of Lloyd,
confirmed that the company made the $400,000 contribution to
Ashcroft's American Values political action committee, as Virginia
records indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Kass was quoted by the St. Louis Post-Dispatch as characterizing
Ashcroft as a ``man who has religious principles and fights for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the man,'' Kass said. ``We think he'd make an
excellent president.''
</P>
<P>
   Trimble said the senator and the Lloyd family have been friendly
for many years, and the Lloyds have been supportive of his focus on
traditional values as a political message. The firm was founded by
Harry Lloyd, who died last year after building his company into a
leader in the field of direct-sales marketing. Lloyd also created
the Loch Lloyd Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   He said the liberal nature of state laws enables potential
presidential candidates to more freely spend money to help other
candidates and bring about political change.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows large contributions if the money collected is
used for ``issue advocacy'' as opposed to ads saying vote for a
specific candidate, Trimble said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go into a state like Iowa, like North Carolina, South
Carolina, like New Hampshire,'' Trimble said, ``and you can impact
the future of policy-making extensively by being there early, by
using that money to energize volunteers, assisting candidates who
are running for state office, and really having a massive effect on
the political process.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans considering a White House bid, including
former Vice President Dan Quayle and former Tennessee Gov. Lamar
Alexander, have incorporated similar PACs in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft has been traveling the country for more than a year,
gauging the extent of support for a campaign for the Republican
presidential nomination. He plans to announce his intentions Jan.
5, but several people close to his camp have indicated that he
probably will run. He also intends to run for re-election in 2000
to his Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Ashcroft will need a lot of money, particularly if
he is running two campaigns, at least for a while. State law allows
him to run for both seats until he wins or loses the presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Most estimates put the cost of a presidential primary campaign
at a minimum of $20 million. A competitive Senate race, as his
re-election battle promises to be _ he will likely face Democratic
Gov. Mel Carnahan _ could cost upward of $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft has another political action committee, the Spirit of
America PAC, which he has used to finance his travel on behalf of
other candidates. As of mid-October, that PAC had raised nearly $2
million this year. His American Values PAC has raised $508,150,
according to Virginia records.
</P>
<P>
   Financial disclosure advocates argue that liberal state laws
like Virginia's thwart the intent of the federal controls and turn
campaign financing into a shell game.
</P>
<P>
   ``By having this sort of secret method of moving money from
committee to committee, it's a great way to avoid scrutiny and
disclosure and keep voters and the public in the dark,'' said
Charles Lewis, director of the Center for Public Integrity. ``I
think that's antithetical to democracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
