<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1675 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-09 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TRUST THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the House sent the charges against President
Clinton to the Senate for trial, said White House counsel Charles
Ruff, it would be ``putting the country through the horror that we
all know would follow.'' Trying the president on such charges would
be ``a nightmare for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what has become the essence of Clinton's case against
impeachment: horror. Nightmare. And how long would the unbearable
senatorial torture have to be endured? Four months, say some; other
Clintonites direly warn that the country would be ``paralyzed''
most of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, say the scaremongers; because the chief justice
of the United States would preside at the trial, the Supreme Court
would be out of business, too.
</P>
<P>
   This drumbeat of alarm is noisy malarkey. When asked when the
Senate would take up an impeachment if one came over from the
House, Majority Leader Trent Lott answered, ``Jan. 6.'' How long
would the trial take? ``Three days to three weeks,'' was his
estimate. They'd have to work Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Would it be in the Senate's interest to drag out the proceeding?
Hardly; its members know the majority of the public wants to turn
away from the tawdry business of what Rep. Barney Frank calls ``who
touched what.'' Lott speaks for the Republican desire for dispatch,
and surely Democratic leader Tom Daschle _ who has more than the
needed 34 votes for acquittal _ would not filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world's greatest deliberative body'' would deliberate
intelligently. Ruff, a confirmed stonewaller but an eloquent
advocate, would be heard out in defense of legalism. Henry Hyde or
some other manager from the House would educate the public about
the sanctity of the oath.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Senate, unwilling to either remove or exonerate the
president, would work out a resolution of censure. The House would
agree and send it to the president for his signature. That would be
his confession and his punishment.
</P>
<P>
   That would not be a horrific nightmare. It could be over in time
for the State of the Union address. The Supreme Court would not
miss a beat. Why, then, the phony scare campaign?
</P>
<P>
   Because Democrats do not want the historic black mark of House
impeachment placed against a Democratic president. They want only
censure of sin _ and we're all sinners, ``everybody does it'' _ not
of the crime of perjury connected to the higher crime of abuse of
power, which not everybody does.
</P>
<P>
   Why are most Republicans willing to take a public-relations
beating to insist on bringing the president to a limited form of
constitutional account? Because this would not be Censure Lite;
impeachment in the knowledge of no Senate removal is censure most
serious.
</P>
<P>
   And what drives the impeachers? Not blind Clinton-hatred or pure
partisanship or blood-lusting bluenose-ism. There's a context to
this that Ken Starr failed to summon: This specific, demonstrable
crime is emblematic of a five-year series of abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Starr failed to file thorough and timely reports on Filegate and
Travelgate and will let Clinton get away with hushing up Web
Hubbell in Whitewater. Janet Reno, defying FBI and Justice
professionals, is letting Clinton off scot-free in his conspiracy
to break the election law and solicit Asian money. His success in
slipping away from judgment is, in his lawyer's word,
``maddening,'' and he remains in a state of mendacity.
</P>
<P>
   This rankles. Poetic justice is not genuine justice, and rough
justice is not as smooth as a gifted line of perjury, but escaped
chickens have a way of coming home to roost. The narrow but
definable set of crimes the House is now dealing with is a
synecdoche for all the abuses he has been and is getting away with,
as well as his sustained contempt of Congress and the truth.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the people who have been following this Houdini-like
performance want the Censure Serious: House impeachment without
Senate removal.
</P>
<P>
   We should not let Clinton put a scare into us about national
paralysis. Trust the Senate; it won't happen. The House should put
a scare into him that will deter future presidents from playing
fast and loose with the truth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
