<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIBA-CLARIANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIBA SPECIALTY AND CLARIANT END $7 BILLION MERGER TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A month to the day after they announced they would join forces,
Ciba Specialty Chemicals AG and Clariant AG, the two Swiss chemical
companies, said their merger talks had collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   If the $7 billion deal had gone through, the merger would have
created the world's largest maker of dyes, additives and other
so-called specialty chemicals, with $13 billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company would elaborate on the reasons for the broken
engagement. ``There were no catastrophic problems with either
company,'' said Rolf Meyer, Ciba's chairman. ``But putting them
together seemed to change the balance between risks and benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The vagueness contributed to speculation throughout the industry
on the possible reasons. Several analysts suggested the companies
had realized that monopoly commissions overseas might have forced
them to divest themselves of too many assets. And a few suggested
ego clashes at the top of both companies.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed deal, Meyer would have become chief executive
of the merged company, while Rolf Schweizer, Clariant's chairman,
would have been chairman. Meyer said that he and Schweizer never
argued over the suggested balance of power, and remain on good
terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the media blitz is over we're going to go out and have a
beer,'' Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the merger's collapse may not be confined to Ciba
and Clariant. As long as the two Swiss behemoths were occupied with
integrating their staffs and operations, they would have been
sidelined from the acquisition game. Now analysts expect that each
will be looking for other companies to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both have aggressive objectives for top line growth and
returns above the cost of capital, and acquisitions will be the
best way to achieve those,'' said Bardia Mesbah, a chemical
industry consultant at Kline &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts cite Cytec, Morton International, Great Lakes
Chemical and Crompton &AMP; Knowles as potential targets.
</P>
<P>
   The collapsed talks come against a backdrop of depressed stock
prices among chemical companies. The Salomon Smith Barney Specialty
Chemical Index, composed of 61 specialty chemical companies in the
United States, is trading at 14.2 times estimated 1999 earnings;
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 is trading at 25 times 1999 earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a 43 percent discount to the market, so these stocks
could use an element of merger speculation,'' said Timothy
Gerdemon, Salomon's specialty chemical analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Clariant shares fell 11 Swiss francs, to 613, or about $452,
while Ciba dropped 1.25, to 115.75, or $84.50. The announcement
came after the close of stock trading in Switzerland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
