<HEADER>
A1685 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-SOCSEC-PA     12-09 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SOCSEC-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SANTORUM OPTIMISTIC FOLLOWING SOCIAL SECURITY CONFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec 9. -- An unlikely pair emerged together
Wednesday, whispering to each other, at the conclusion of a two-day
White House conference on the future of Social Security: President
Clinton and Pennsylvania Sen. Rick Santorum.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic president might not be ready to jump aboard the
staunchly conservative senator's plan to save Social Security by
investing the funds privately. But the duo were at least listening
to each other's ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and I had a very good discussion'' Santorum,
R-Pa., said. ``He didn't rule privatization out. He did not close
the door to it. I think it is very beneficial to have developed
this bipartisan working relationship with the president on this
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Santorum said he felt the conference was able to advance the
idea of privatization with Clinton and even liberal Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``People started out going in different directions,'' Santorum
said. ``But they found themselves a lot closer to where I am than I
ever thought possible. It's like a mudslide that throws you back
down together.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference focused on how to prevent the program from going
bankrupt, which officials say will happen in 2032 unless it is
reformed. As early as 2013, the system will be paying out more in
benefits to retirees than it is takes in from taxes on workers,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On the topic of privatization, Clinton would only remark
publicly at the conference that a system should be created that was
not vulnerable to the volatility of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum said reforming Social Security is especially important
to a state like Pennsylvania. ``In Pennsylvania we have one of the
highest concentration of seniors in the country,'' Santorum said.
``It is of course crucial to us at home.''
</P>
<P>
   While 12.6 percent of the nation is 65 years of age or older,
Pennsylvania has 15.9 percent, the third highest percentage of
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Census data, which includes Cambria and Somerset counties in the
Johnstown regional count, said last year 18.7 of the population
here is at least 65 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum said he and the president agreed that it is imperative
to increase the rate of return on money coming into Social
Security, other than by the 6.2 percent of each worker's paycheck
that is withheld. Employers kick in an additional matching 6.2
percent for Social Security taxes. All sides represented at the
conference agreed that those taxes should not be increased to meet
the growing demand of Social Security benefits as the baby boomers
retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could do it by investing funds, or personal savings
accounts,'' Santorum said. ``He didn't rule anything out. He
referred to my comments about growing wealth among the poor during
the meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Santorum said that he and the president also agreed reform
should happen sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to propose next month a plan that would allow a worker
to make investments in the stock market, by putting a portion of
their withholding tax in a personal account.
</P>
<P>
   The idea to privatize Social Security is one that has been
typically backed by conservative economists, and shunned by labor
unions and liberal economists.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Murtha, D-Johnstown, who did not attend the
conference, said in a prepared statement that he thought people
would be concerned about the stability and sureness of payments and
opposed to the idea of gambling in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Everett, did not return repeated calls on
this issue.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the resistance to Santorum's plan, he said he hopes
the president's open-mindedness will influence other Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``With his leadership, a lot of Democrats who were not receptive
to the idea might become so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
