<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLECKNER-BENEFIT-ART-     12-09 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLECKNER-BENEFIT-ART-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.) 
 UPTOWN AND DOWNTOWN TYPES MIX FOR A GOOD CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CHRISTOPHER MASON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I never invite people over _ it's so
anxiety-producing,'' Ross Bleckner said, contemplating the imminent
arrival of 120 guests, many of them uptown swells who had paid
$1,000 for the privilege of climbing six flights of stairs for
cocktails and dinner with the celebrated artist.
</P>
<P>
   An avowed recluse who resists forays north of 14th Street,
Bleckner was the host of a benefit last week for Community Research
Initiative on AIDS in the minimalist Xanadu that is his home, a
former loft building that he owns in TriBeCa. Pausing for a moment
in his vast fifth-floor kitchen, Bleckner seemed momentarily
transfixed by the play of light and color as caterers laid out 840
bright green asparagus spears on pristine white plates.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, a dinner downtown for AIDS research is not at the
top of everyone's list,'' said Bleckner, who is the president of
the organization's board. ``It's tough getting all those rich
uptown people down here.''
</P>
<P>
   Such implausible expressions of modesty aside, Bleckner, 49, is
not oblivious to his formidable drawing power for many prosperous
New Yorkers: talent, well-connected friends, fame and riches
(though not necessarily in that order). ``I want everyone to feel
like they're getting value, you know _ dinner, a house tour, a
workout,'' said the Long Island-bred artist, whose conversation is
merrily peppered with expletives and who adds the rhetorical
``youknowwhatImean?'' to most sentences.
</P>
<P>
   By ``workout,'' he seemed to refer not to his private gym, but
to the hefty climb required of his guests to reach his penthouse
living room. Fortunately, distractions along the way were
plentiful. Many were captivated by a sofa made of Manhattan
telephone books created by the artist Tom Sachs. ``I guess it's
art, so we better not sit,'' said Richard Mishaan, a guest, who
stared wistfully at the sculpture as he paused for breath.
</P>
<P>
   As others, including Calvin Klein, Diane Von Furstenberg,
Claudia Cohen, the cosmetics entrepreneur Gale Hayman and relatives
of the Italian industrialist Gianni Agnelli exchanged handshakes
and air kisses, the nervous Bleckner confessed his social strategy.
``The trick is to say as little to as few people as possible, and
to keep moving,'' he said. ``That way, it looks like you're
circulating, when you're actually just walking away.''
</P>
<P>
   Befitting the madcap mix of uptown, downtown and European chic,
the evening abounded with improbabilities. Dinner was catered by
Mortimer's at Home, a new outfit run by Mortimer's former maitre
d'hotel, Robert Caravaggi, and its former chef, Stephen Attoe,
which has sprung Phoenix-like from the recently shuttered uptown
society restaurant, where Bleckner confessed he rarely dined. ``I
only went when good friends of friends invited me,'' he said,
referring to Bob Colacello, a Vanity Fair contributor, and Reinaldo
and Carolina Herrera, all of whom are on the charity's board and
were among the co-hosts for the evening.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of some, the event was underwritten by
Traditional Home, the shelter magazine that is based in Des Moines
and is associated in many minds with cozy New England clapboard
cottages and English Tudors. Asked whether she agreed that
Traditional Home seemed an unlikely participant at a benefit in a
TriBeCa loft, the editor in chief, Karol DeWulf Nickell, replied:
``Not at all. For us, it's a natural fit.'' She clutched three
strings of pearls around her neck and adjusted her immaculate bob
of chestnut hair. The magazine's publisher, Wilkie Bushby, chimed
in that they were pursuing ``a hipper audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Bleckner's Des Moines visitors were not the only ones curious to
meet some of his groovier downtown guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is Chi Chi Valenti?'' Judith Peabody, the Fifth Avenue
philanthropist, asked of her dinner partner, Reinaldo Herrera,
examining place cards. ``Sounds like some marvelous tango dancer,''
he replied.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the blonde Ms. Valenti is a veteran of the downtown
demimonde, an editor of the niche magazine Verbal Abuse, and is
known as a spirited emcee on the fetish circuit. She and her
husband, the deejay Johnny Dynell, revealed that they had met in
Bleckner's building nearly two decades ago, when the lower floors
were occupied by the Mudd Club, the infamous nightspot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place holds special memories,'' Dynell said, wearing a
cutaway black leather vest that showed off his tattoos. ``Chi Chi
and I met here 18 years ago, and we consummated our love right here
in Ross' studio.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Bleckner insisted, his studio is a haven of
tranquillity. A few days before the benefit, he led a visitor on a
private tour of the six-story former warehouse, which is on the
cusp of Chinatown and has served as his home and studio for the
last 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   Success in the art world is not the only source of Bleckner's
good fortune. He was raised in prosperous Hewlett Harbor on Long
Island, and in 1974 he purchased the building with a loan from his
father, a manufacturer of precision parts. Ten years ago, the
artist commissioned the firm 1100 Architects to carry out extensive
renovations, which included demolishing the third-floor ceiling to
create two soaring, side-by-side painting studios, where last
week's dinner was held.
</P>
<P>
   During the last year, he has redesigned his spare, airy living
space on the sixth floor with the assistance of Jaime Rojo, a
Mexican-born interior designer at Jed Johnson &AMP; Associates. ``Ross'
command was that his bedroom should be serene and romantic,'' said
Rojo, who replaced the pine bed with a roomier mahogany model. He
also added a small chair designed by Jean-Michel Frank with a
matching ottoman, as well as a rug designed by Rojo that was
hand-woven in Guatemala, and a Scandinavian ceiling light fixture
with a soothing, inviting glow.
</P>
<P>
   The room overlooks a leafy, glassed-in terrace and beyond it,
Bleckner's elegantly appointed living room, which he claims he
never uses, with a giant television set whose controls he is
certain he will never master. ``I was horrified when he bought
it,'' Rojo confessed. ``So I'm encouraged that he's thinking of
getting rid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the fifth floor of his house, whose interior looks as though
it may have been devised by his close friend Calvin Klein as an
advertisement for the idealized life of an artist, he showed off
his private gym and flexed a bicep.
</P>
<P>
   Bleckner works out every morning before hitting his studio. His
domain is immaculately ordered, like his new paintings currently on
view uptown at the Mary Boone Gallery and downtown at Lehmann
Maupin (which ``features some of the best paintings he has made in
years, maybe ever,'' Roberta Smith, an art critic at The New York
Times, wrote of the Maupin show while expressing reservations about
the Boone show).
</P>
<P>
   Neatly stacked on shelves are dozens of saucepans stained in
myriad hues, which Bleckner uses to mix his own pigments. ``I see
my studio like a laboratory, where I work like an investigator _
it's almost forensic,'' he said. ``I love the discovery process in
painting.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On a shelf amid the saucepans sits a neat stack of music CDs.
``I look at them, but I never play them,'' Bleckner said. ``I gave
away my stereo, because even having to choose what kind of music to
listen to makes me anxious. I like my surroundings to be pretty
spare and severe,'' he added with a grin. ``It helps me to
concentrate on my work.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``All I ever do here is go from my studio to my
bedroom. Everything else is extraneous. I never entertain, because
to me, New York is about meeting people in public spaces, absorbing
a little bit of their energy.''
</P>
<P>
   After the dinner in his studio, which had been transformed into
an oasis of glowing candles and virgin, white canvases, Bleckner
introduced the performance artist John Kelly, who serenaded guests
with compelling renditions of songs by Joni Mitchell. For the
occasion, Kelly donned vintage platform shoes, a becoming long
black dress and a blond wig that seduced some in the audience into
believing that they were in the presence of the moody songstress
herself. Was his choice of ``Shadows and Light,'' with its lyrics
about ``the perils of benefactors, blessings of parasites,'' a
response to the roomful of well-heeled guests?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a song about the contrast of rich and poor, and people's
differing experiences of life,'' Kelly said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Warmly regarded by many young artists for fostering their
talents, Bleckner invited Tommy Payne, an independent curator, to
assemble a small collection of works by emerging artists. Those who
found yellow Post-Its under their chairs, placed randomly by
waiters before dinner, got to take a piece of artwork home.
</P>
<P>
   One sculpture, a notably ghoulish twin-pronged candelabrum by
Sachs, with a lighted torch on one side that illuminated a pig's
foot on the other, attracted the most attention. ``Change hoof
weekly, or as desired,'' the helpful tag said, in Gothic script.
</P>
<P>
   Informed that the sculpture was now hers, Kate Hampton, a
daughter of the late society decorator Mark Hampton, seemed taken
aback. ``No kidding, really?'' exclaimed Ms. Hampton, an actress.
``Well, I don't have one of those,'' she said, perhaps unconvinced
of her good fortune. Someone assured her that duct tape holding the
torch in place was one of the artist's signature materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey, it's a real pig's foot,'' Ms. Hampton said, turning to
her date.
</P>
<P>
   ``But is it kosher?'' he replied, warily.
</P>
<P>
   Colacello looked dubious. ``If it is,'' he said, ``it's very
Reformed.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 2008EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
