<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE EYE OF THE BEHOLDER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traveling in Australia,  &UR; Walter Nelson-Rees &LR;  of San Francisco
forwards a column written by  &UR; Geoff Roach &LR;  of Adelaide in the
newspaper the Advertiser. Roach's subject is mentally disturbed
people ``living rough in many parts of this state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``True,'' he writes, ``it's nothing like the human carnage, most
of it drug-inflicted, you encounter in the seamier cities of
Germany and Holland, certain streets of San Francisco or Edinburgh
estates.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; William Bennett &LR;  and Senator  &UR; Joseph Lieberman &LR; , D-Conn.,
have bestowed a Silver Sewer _ not a tailor; a gutter drain _ award
on CBS for broadcasting  &UR; Howard Stern &LR; 's show and for the ``60
Minutes'' episode in which Dr.  &UR; Jack Kevorkian &LR;  offed a patient.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally,  &UR; Don Hewitt &LR; , executive producer of ``60 Minutes,''
wasn't happy about the honor. ``For them to link us with Howard
Stern just shows they are desperate to get their names in the
paper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The battery-powered reading lights that Jossey-Bass publishers
in San Francisco presented to staff members for Christmas on Monday
came in handy during Tuesday's blackout, when workers made their
way through darkened corridors by the light of matching lanterns.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Mike Pincus &LR;  has merged a corporation and a nonprofit: TWAA
is a 12-step program for problem fliers. And an East Bay reader
says that with IDG Books, the publishers &LR;  of the ``For Dummies''
books, buying Cliffs Notes, it could produce ``Cliffs Notes for
Dummies.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The People Magazine Almanac has dropped  &UR; Andre Agassi &LR; ,
 &UR; David Geffen &LR; ,  &UR; Jennifer Jason Leigh &LR; ,  &UR; Geoffrey Rush &LR; ,  &UR; Mike
Tyson &LR;  and  &UR; Karl Lagerfeld &LR;  from its list of the top 400 people to
invite to a party.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; James Hewitt &LR;  is suing the law firm handling the estate of
his former lover  &UR; Princess Diana &LR;  to get back love letters she
wrote to him. He claims they were stolen from his home.  &UR; Anna
Staiano Ferretti &LR; , a post-Diana lover of Hewitt's, was arrested in
April on charges that she tried to sell the letters to a tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Sammy Sosa &LR;  visited  &UR; Hugh Hefner &LR;  in Los Angeles on Sunday,
reports the Chicago Tribune, and the two passed the time by
watching a screening of ``Babe: Pig in the City.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAKING ADVANTAGE OF PRESIDENTIAL HOSPITALITY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 100 reporters and 1,200 members of Congress and staff
showed up Monday for a White House Christmas party, including ``a
wonderful mixture from both sides of the aisle,'' White House
social secretary  &UR; Capricia Marshall &LR;  told the Washington Post. ``I
think quite a few people put partisan politics aside during the
holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   A former White House official put it another way: ``You'd be
stunned at the biggest bashers who bring the whole family and want
the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Soap Opera Digest is distributing T-shirts saying, ``Don't
impeach the president if it interrupts my soaps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were responding to the frustration we sensed from visitors
to our site and readers of the magazine,'' Digest's
 &UR; Jason Bonderoff &LR;  told the New York Times, ``who tell us on an
ongoing basis that they're unhappy with constant news
pre-emptions.''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. The BBC reports that clay figures of  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR;  and
 &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  are being sold in Naples to place around nativity
scenes. Neapolitan tradition includes the placing of nonreligious
figures around the creche.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOLIDAY GIFT GUIDE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kathy Guerrero &LR;  is captivated by coordinating person-and-pet
umbrellas from the J.C. Penney catalog. ``Vinyl with nylon trim and
chrome metal frame. Clean with damp cloth.''
</P>
<P>
   The person umbrella is $24; the doggie umbrella, $20. The design
on both is paw prints. The dog's umbrella has the handle coming out
of the top, &LR;  to enable the dog-walker to shelter the pooch.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Trying to find that perfect something? Researchers at the
University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign cq  &LR; have determined that
``of nearly 150 gift experiences ... 58 percent were emotionally
negative.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Thoughts are very powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The deep-thinking singer  &UR; Jewel &LR;  in Rolling Stone.
</P>
</TEXT>
