</P>
<P>
   Nearly 100 reporters and 1,200 members of Congress and staff
showed up Monday for a White House Christmas party, including ``a
wonderful mixture from both sides of the aisle,'' White House
social secretary  &UR; Capricia Marshall &LR;  told the Washington Post. ``I
think quite a few people put partisan politics aside during the
holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   A former White House official put it another way: ``You'd be
stunned at the biggest bashers who bring the whole family and want
the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Soap Opera Digest is distributing T-shirts saying, ``Don't
impeach the president if it interrupts my soaps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were responding to the frustration we sensed from visitors
to our site and readers of the magazine,'' Digest's
 &UR; Jason Bonderoff &LR;  told the New York Times, ``who tell us on an
ongoing basis that they're unhappy with constant news
pre-emptions.''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. The BBC reports that clay figures of  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR;  and
 &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  are being sold in Naples to place around nativity
scenes. Neapolitan tradition includes the placing of nonreligious
figures around the creche.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOLIDAY GIFT GUIDE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kathy Guerrero &LR;  is captivated by coordinating person-and-pet
umbrellas from the J.C. Penney catalog. ``Vinyl with nylon trim and
chrome metal frame. Clean with damp cloth.''
</P>
<P>
   The person umbrella is $24; the doggie umbrella, $20. The design
on both is paw prints. The dog's umbrella has the handle coming out
of the top, &LR;  to enable the dog-walker to shelter the pooch.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Trying to find that perfect something? Researchers at the
University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign cq  &LR; have determined that
``of nearly 150 gift experiences ... 58 percent were emotionally
negative.''
</P>
