<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELD OFFERS PLAN TO CENSURE PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES AND BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ William F. Weld has a plan.
</P>
<P>
   The former Massachusetts governor Wednesday appeared before the
House Judiciary Committee, surprising his fellow Republicans and
the White House with a four-point proposal to punish President
Clinton, but not impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said it would entertain the idea, which some
House Republicans found entertaining _ but not much else.
</P>
<P>
   And while Weld said he was not carrying Clinton's water,
administration officials plainly hoped his testimony would help
persuade a small band of undecided Republican moderates not to vote
for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Weld proposed a censure that would include a written report of
the president's wrongdoing, a written acknowledgment by Clinton
that he did wrong, a large fine that could not be paid from his
legal defense fund and the possibility of criminal prosecution once
he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining this censure-plus remedy, Weld said, ``Personally,
the dignity of Congress and the dignity of the country demands
something more than merely censure here.''
</P>
<P>
   And in remarks that seemed directed at undecided members of his
party, Weld, who was an associate minority counsel for the
Judiciary Committee during the Watergate investigation, called
impeachment a ``prophylactic remedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not punitive. If any of you are thinking, we've got to
vote yes on impeachment to tarnish the president, he's already been
tarnished,'' Weld said. ``Nobody's going to forget this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no immediate indications that his comments started a
stampede against impeachment among moderate Republicans. ``I don't
think any one person is going to persuade these guys,'' said one
senior White House official.
</P>
<P>
   Representative John Edward Porter, a Republican of Illinois, who
had expressed reservations about impeachment because of the
potential negative consequences of a long Senate trial, said
Wednesday that he was still open to impeaching Clinton, though he
had made no final decision.
</P>
<P>
   With political pressure building on moderate Republican members,
whose declarations before a vote could swing the momentum either
way, Chairman Henry Hyde warned House members to hold back on
making statements about how they would vote until the committee
sends up any articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Several moderates contacted Wednesday passed up the chance to
say whether Weld's testimony had influenced them either way.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Jim Kolbe, Republican of Arizona and a moderate
who supported Weld's nomination last year to become ambassador to
Mexico, may not have been persuaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing Bill Weld had to say ... that seemed to
dovetail with what the congressman has said privately,'' said
Kolbe's spokesman, Ron Foreman. ``I don't think they share the same
interpretation of what ought to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Weld, who headed the Justice Department's Criminal Division
under President Reagan, sprung his censure-plus plan on the White
House when he walked into the Judiciary Committee hearing room and
spotted Gregory Craig, Clinton's special counsel, and told him what
he was going to say.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said they had not seen the proposal beforehand
nor did they know he was going to offer one. ``The reality is that
he is an accomplished former elected official who is known for his
independence and known to speak his mind and that's why he is also
credible and today was another example of that,'' said the White
House official.
</P>
<P>
   Of the substance of Weld's offer, White House press secretary
Joseph Lockhart said: ``We think that people who come forward in
good faith with proposals to deal with this matter, we will look at
and we will listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Weld was questioned by committee Republicans about statements he
made in a September interview suggesting Clinton should resign if
he loses the public's confidence. Weld said that the president had
not lost his ability to lead. ``I will confess that I was somewhat
surprised at the alacrity with which all seemed to be forgiven and
forgotten in terms of people saddling up and doing business with
the president and taking him seriously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Lamar Smith, a Republican from Texas, read from a
column that appeared in The Boston Gobe. It was written by a
headmaster who had asked his students, aged 12 to 18, to accept the
president's apology for lying about an affair with Monica S.
Lewinsky. The students would have none of it because the
president's relationship with a former White House intern was not a
one-time lapse in judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't those students right in their assessment?'' Smith
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Mr. Congressman, I don't think anybody's saying this is
a day at the beach or a walk in the park,'' Weld answered. ``I find
those statements as depressing as you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative George Gekas, a Pennsylvania Republican who
serves on the Judiciary Committee, said afterward that Weld's
conflicting responses to the Lewinsky scandal may have made his
censure proposal less persuasive to some GOP lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, the governor has called for resignation,'' Gekas
said. ``He comes to the table now with a changed perspective and
testifies against impeachment. ... Overall, I think his testimony
does not sway many opinions, at least not among committee
members.''
</P>
<P>
   Weld, who was contacted about testifying on Monday by Susan
Brophy, a Quincy, Mass. native and former White House legislative
affairs deputy who has been called back to help out with the
impeachment inquiry, was unfazed by the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've testified before Congress so often that it's like
brushing my teeth,'' he said. Weld said he had not talked to any
moderate Republicans in the House about the impeachment issue and
has no plans to do so.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that his committee appearance may not help him
politically. ``It's probably not a plus for the political future.
But I thought it was important to try to contribute to a
resolution, conceivably even a lowering of voices. People seem
pretty hot around here. That's usually not a good thing when it's
decision time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weld said he doesn't plan to enter the Senate race in 2000,
specifically with regard to challenging Senator Edward M. Kennedy.
``I'm going to be a good boy for the next five years and stay out
of the public eye.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
