<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net firm rewriting online retail
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The personal computer may go down in retailing history
as the cultural _ and economic _ equivalent of the 19th century
department store, without the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   In its cover story, Business Week (Dec. 14) says Amazon.com, the
Internet company, has come close to perfecting online shopping, or
``e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More than ever, Amazon.com is jolting the titans of retail
into rethinking whether their traditional advantages _ physical
size, mass-media branding and even the sensory appeal of shopping
in stores _ will be enough to thrive in the New Economy,'' the
magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   As for Amazon.com stock, Business Week says it and other
Internet companies will have a tough job producing the kind of
earnings growth that investors are looking for, based on the prices
they are paying for the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Count on the Fed
</P>
<P>
   An old Wall Street saying _ ``don't fight the Fed'' _ is good
advice considering what has happened to the stock market any time
the Federal Reserve has made two successive cuts in its discount
rate _ the rate it charges banks for loans.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual Funds (January) says the Fed has made successive pairs of
discount rate cuts 19 times since the central bank was founded in
1913. On average, the Dow Jones industrial average has risen 7
percent within three months of the second cut, and 18 percent after
12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow has already risen 8 percent since the Fed's most recent
discount rate cut on Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping fast company
</P>
<P>
   Fast Company (December) spotlights people who ``make a
difference'' out of the limelight, the ``unsung heroes and rising
stars.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine profiles 16 men and women it regards as ``fast''
because of ``how they dream, how they think, how they lead, how
they contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston Philharmonic conductor Ben Zander, author Ron Chernow and
Milwaukee Mayor John Norquist come closest to having a public
identity. Among the others are a hotel general manager, a vice
president of an executive search firm, a consumer lobbyist in
Washington and a university vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning...
</P>
<P>
   _ Respectable tax professionals and corporate clients are using
modern corporate finance techniques to indulge in extravagant
tax-dodging schemes, Forbes (Dec. 14) says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia Trend (December) profiles a ``small band of economic
developers'' on a mission to bring a better economic future to
communities along U.S. Route 441. The interstate highways took
business away from the once primary north-south route the runs from
the Georgia mountains to the Okefenokee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
