<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Overseas anxiety hurts Coke shares
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shares of Coca-Cola sagged Wednesday on concerns that
economic turmoil abroad will slow sales growth through the first
half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The stock closed at $67.12 1/2 on the New York Stock Exchange,
down $1.50 after earlier falling as low as $65.62 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   The dip was triggered by a report from Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
analyst Emanuel Goldman, who predicts below-average growth in the
fourth quarter and into next year because of currency fluctuations
and economic instability in Russia, Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns, coupled with tough comparisons to last year's 10
percent sales increase in the fourth quarter, have been blamed for
Coca-Cola's 18 percent stock slide in the past 3 1/2 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the moment, the stock is sort of taking a pause, but on a
long-term basis this is a knock-your-socks-off company,'' said
Goldman, who is maintaining his ``near-term neutral'' rating on
Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman is maintaining his earnings estimates of 30 cents a
share for the fourth quarter, $1.45 a share for 1998 and $1.60 a
share for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The company is expected to release its fourth-quarter volume
update as early as next week, spokesman Rob Baskin said. Investors
and analysts use the update, which comes about a month before
earnings, to fine-tune expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who register expectations and ratings with the First
Call service have given Coca-Cola an overall below-average
recommendation, compared with other blue chips, since the company's
September warning that fourth-quarter earnings would be lower than
previously expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analysts aren't in love with the stock,'' said First Call's
Chuck Hill. ``They have gotten a little disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
