<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Land acquired near Coca-Cola
 &HT;    By Sallye Salter
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A mystery buyer continues to acquire property in the
area south of the Coca-Cola Co.'s North Avenue headquarters. In the
latest transaction, the buyer paid $2.3 million for two blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Financial Group, an Arlington, Texas -based firm that
has spent $5.5 million since June buying properties in a half dozen
transactions, bought nearly two acres one block north of Centennial
Olympic Park, according to Fulton County deed records.
</P>
<P>
   The seller was Maxwell &AMP; Hitchcock Construction Co. The company,
which was located at 191 Simpson St., recently moved to
Chattahoochee industrial district. The property, bounded by
Simpson, Lovejoy, Alexander and Fowler streets, had been on the
market at $44 a square foot, but sold for $33 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Financial, which buys property and leases it to
corporations, says it is buying downtown land for a corporate
client who does not want to be identified. Coca-Cola has repeatedly
declined to comment on whether it is that client.
</P>
<P>
   The company spent $8 million buying land for its Olympic City
festival adjacent to the park and is a major player in the
city-business community efforts to redevelop the area around
Centennial Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Coca-Cola made a $4 million loan to assist Downtown
Atlanta Revitalization, a nonprofit redevelopment group, in
assembling land for a business park across Marietta Street from
Coca-Cola's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the soft drink giant has been considering
several options for adding office space to accommodate its growing
workforce that has spilled over from its North Avenue headquarters
complex into several facilities in Midtown, downtown and the
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Coca-Cola planned to buy Inforum, an office
building adjacent to Centennial Park, but the deal fell through.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past several years, the company considered construction
of an office tower as high as 48 stories as well as a smaller
building.
</P>
<P>
   The company won't say if it still plans another building or what
it will do with the property it is known to own near its
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
