<SLUG> BC-DELTA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta decentralizing international operations
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hoping to fortify its multibillion-dollar global
business, Delta Air Lines Inc. is creating three international
units to closely run its Asian, Latin American and European
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The move gives autonomy and direct decision-making power to the
top executives who will manage the new operations. Other airlines
such as American Airlines have adopted similar strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``By moving accountability to the field, we expect faster
decision-making and even better execution,'' marketing chief
Frederick Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions for international markets, which bring in $2.8
billion, or about 20 percent, of the airline's operating revenue,
previously were made from Delta's Atlanta headquarters. The new
units now will have full operational responsibility for such issues
as service, sales, marketing, human resources and corporate
representation within their regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's decentralization. It's a good move,'' said Julius
Maldutis, aviation analyst for CIBC Oppenheimer in New York.
``History has shown that a vast international route network such as
Delta's cannot be effectively managed from a headquarters.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the change:
</P>
<P>
   _ Stephan J. Egli will be vice president of the Atlantic region
and the airline's top person in Europe. A native of Switzerland,
Egli has been vice president of Delta's Atlantic/Pacific Business
since joining the company in July 1997. He is based in London.
</P>
<P>
   _ J. Daniel Burrus becomes director of Delta's Tokyo-based
Pacific region and will oversee the airlines' Asian market. Burrus
has been with Delta since 1976 in several management jobs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rudi Forster, managing director, will serve as acting head of
the Latin American region. Forster has been with Delta since 1978,
serving as station manager in Stuttgart, Germany, and Moscow and
St. Petersburg, Russia.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its international strategy, Delta and Austrian
Airlines agreed to expand their co-marketing pact. Starting Friday,
Austrian Air will put its code on Delta's daily flights between
Atlanta and Guatemala City.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's stock closed down $2.50 Wednesday at $52.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
