<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1741 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-EXAMS-BOS &LR;      12-09 1674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-EXAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFLUENT DISTRICTS' STUDENTS DO BETTER ON ASSESSMENT EXAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With failure rates on the state's tough new
standardized exams disappointingly high across Massachusetts, the
wealthiest school districts _ places like Harvard, Newton, Acton,
Needham, Sudbury, and Concord _ performed best, according to scores
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But even though higher per-pupil spending generally meant higher
test scores, some of the higher-spending districts faced unsettling
results.
</P>
<P>
   Some 23 percent of Newton sophomores failed the math test; 32
percent of Sudbury 8th-graders failed or need improvement in math.
More than half of Acton 4th-graders scored in the ``needs
improvement'' category in English/language arts.
</P>
<P>
   But state Board of Education Chairman John Silber said it would
be wrong to congratulate or criticize any district based on
first-time scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage, this is where we find the information to
improve our schools, not evaluate them,'' Silber told a crowd of
reporters at the Morse Elementary School in Cambridge, where the
report was released. ``This is a standard against which to measure
things. I believe we will see great progress in the next five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that most of the lowest-performing students are from
city schools showed that they clearly face the greatest challenges
as state officials now begin their push for improved scores within
two years. State officials are asking low-performing districts to
show significant improvement within five years or face being taken
over by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure is particularly intense for this year's 8th-graders,
who are the first class that will to have to pass the Massachusetts
Comprehensive Assessment System test in 10th grade to get their
high school diploma. Special-education and bilingual students also
will have to pass to graduate, unless they are given an exemption
from taking the test. Most special-education students this year
took the test.
</P>
<P>
   Silber and other education leaders said they found the most
promise in 4th-graders' scores, and that their generally superior
performance may reflect the fact that their entire school career
has been affected by the higher standards demanded by the 1993
Education Reform Act.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on the particularly high failure rates among
10th-graders, Silber said, ``We have failed our older students.
They have been the products of lowered expectations. This is not
only a failure of schools, but of a culture that talks about how
school should be fun . . . not how much work it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Silber said, 75 percent of students in each grade, and
each subject, should fall in either the ``advanced'' or
``proficient'' test categories. But the majority of last year's
209,000 4th-, 8th- and 10th-graders landed in the ``needs
improvement'' or ``failing'' areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not good enough for the 21st century and it
isn't good enough for these kids,'' said state Education
Commissioner David Driscoll.
</P>
<P>
   While it had been expected that large urban areas would post the
lowest scores, the relatively low scores of ``average'' towns, like
Milford, show how far the state remains from Silber's goal.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 208 K-12 districts ranked in a computer analysis by The
Boston Globe, Milford was representative: it ranked exactly in the
middle, at number 104.
</P>
<P>
   Its scores were not good: 80 percent of 4th-graders failed or
needed improvement in English; 67 percent of that class failed or
needed improvement in science, and 66 percent failed or needed
improvement in math, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Parents, anxiously calling their schools and the education
department, and swarming the department's web site, said it is hard
to avoid judging, given the unprecedented level of detail in the
scores. Districts begin mailing scores out to families Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it is the first test, but it is natural to want to
judge the schools,'' said Alan Donati, a software engineer from
Whitinsville in Northbridge, a town about an hour west of Boston.
Donati was anxious to see his district's results, even though his
two daughters, a kindergartner and 2nd-grader, are not even close
to test-taking time. ``As parents, we are looking for
accountability and the ability to evaluate our schools.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I think how much (parents) invest their time
and interest in their child's education'' is at least as important
as a teacher's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Provocative results abounded in the myriad statistics, showing
the need for a much more in-depth look at the figures.
</P>
<P>
   Most districts, for instance, followed the national trend in
standardized testing of students doing progressively worse the
higher the grade tested. But Marblehead showed the opposite results
in English and math, with 10th-graders outperforming 4th-graders.
</P>
<P>
   Marblehead Superintendent of Schools Philip Devaux speculated
that his town's students may be learning material at different
points than students in other elementary and middle school
districts. But by 10th grade in Marblehead, most are well-prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Of Marblehead 10th-graders, 75 percent scored in the proficient
or advanced categories in English. In 4th grade, no students scored
in the advanced category in English, and only 37 percent scored in
the proficient category.
</P>
<P>
   Other interesting results came out of Medfield. According to a
Globe computer analysis, it scored much better than many other
districts that outspend its $5,565-per-pupil each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an anomaly,'' said Medfield Superintendent of Schools
Chris Martes. ``We've had a long history of that. We don't spend a
lot. Yet, we have always done quite well on tests. I look at the
staff and families of the town as the reason why. We have terrific
families with great kids. They come prepared every day to learn. We
have a caring and dedicated staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Brookline, which ranked below Medfield, spends more than $8,000
per student each year, according to state figures, while Harvard
spends more than $6,415 per student.
</P>
<P>
   Many superintendents said they expect they will have to explain
their ``failing'' and ``needs improvement'' scores to outraged
parents who have not heard the state's warnings about taking the
first year's scores too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do expect a reaction from parents. Our real challenge is
trying to educate people who have not been paying attention to
this,'' said Sudbury Superintendent of Schools William Hurley. ``We
have to share with them that this is an indicator and not the
descriptor of their child.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in the cities, however, that the failure rates in all
three subjects were the most overwhelming. In one Boston elementary
school, every 4th-grader failed science &AMP; technology, and 70
percent failed math.
</P>
<P>
   ``To our parents, I say, remember, this is the beginning of the
journey and not the destination,'' said Cambridge School
Superintendent Bobbie D'Alessandro.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potential for misuse of the data, the millions of
scores from 1,800 schools and more than 350 districts will be
valuable, educators say, for illuminating the state's education
gems, tucked away where no one expects them _ high-performing
schools and districts that can offer ideas to others who are
struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind these numbers are great stories,'' said Driscoll.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the Morse School in Cambridge as an example. With
40 percent of its students living in poverty _ well above the state
average of 26 percent _ 67 percent of the school's 4th-graders were
proficient and 8 percent advanced in science &AMP; technology; 17
percent were advanced and 33 percent proficient in math, well above
many of the well-heeled suburban elementary schools. Morse
8th-graders scored less impressively, although 41 percent were
proficient or advanced in math, the data show.
</P>
<P>
   Morse math teacher George Baccus, seated Wednesday with two of
his 8th-graders, Sharoda Das and Joseph Morpeau, said he teaches
the same students from grades 6 through 8, giving him a three-year
planning cycle that allows him to get to know his students.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what they believe they are doing right, other
superintendents in the high-scoring districts were quick to say
that their education battle is already partly won based on the
families who walk through their doors.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Superintendent of Schools Mihran Keoseian, whose
1,175-student district ranked number one in the Globe's computer
ranking, said, ``Our kids come in (to kindergarten) at the
2nd-grade reading level, which is only a slight exaggeration.'' And
he gave kudos to his teachers and administrators.
</P>
<P>
   But Keoseian also noted what he considered shortfalls, such as
more than half of his 4th-graders only reaching the ``needs
improvement'' category in English.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not emphasize analysis in writing to the degree that the
MCAS test is pushing,'' he said. ``I might look into changing that,
but the way I will look at it is more K-12 as a whole rather than
react to one class.''
</P>
<P>
   Other suburban school superintendents Wednesday were generally
hesitant to explain their good or bad scores, saying they needed
more time to determine what the numbers really mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at it with any satisfaction or disappointment
because the information is in a vacuum,'' said Sudbury's
Hurley.``The only thing you can compare them to are the state
scores. We did better than the state average and we would expect
to. But what does it mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll Wednesday said that while districts have begun applying
for $20 million in remedial funds for such things as after-school
tutoring programs, there is not enough money to go around for all
the lower performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be able to reach all the kids,'' he said Wednesday.
``But if we can show results and success, we won't have trouble
getting extra money from the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe reporters Beth Daley and David Armstrong contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
