<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALARMCLOCK10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta businessman has gentle wake-up call
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Patrick Herold believes his invention is going to make
the world a more pleasant place to wake up, ``one morning at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Herold, an Atlanta businessman, was recently issued U.S. patent
No. 5832067 for a ``method and apparatus for integrating telephone
signals with an alarm clock.'' He calls it a ``new clock radio.''
</P>
<P>
   It's more than a clock radio, however. It's a telecommunications
device that delivers predetermined messages in the morning when you
awake _ more pleasant messages than commercial radio broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like any other clock radio, except it has both a
phone line and power line,'' said Herold, who operates a billing
and collection service for telecommunications and Internet firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hook it up, then call an 800 number and arrange with the
provider what you want to hear when you awake,'' he said. ``It
could be your favorite song, an inspirational message, a reminder
of your mother's birthday, whatever.'' The service could also
operate via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, when homes become more automated, Herold envisions
the system could be used to trigger other electronic or
computerized devices that would permit people to wake up not only
to desired messages, but to pleasant surroundings of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, you could arrange to be awakened by classical
music and, if it's sunny outside, your blinds could be opened
electronically,'' he said. ``If it's raining, the coffee pot could
be switched on, along with a slow turning on of dim lights.''
</P>
<P>
   The fast way up
</P>
<P>
   A woman struggling to change a flat tire on her car alongside
the expressway sparked an idea for Ricky Vann. ``Gee whiz,'' he
thought, ``wouldn't it be nice if she could just push a button to
lift the car?''
</P>
<P>
   The thought _ and Vann's subsequent efforts to make it reality _
recently led to Vann being issued U.S. patent No. 5813661.
</P>
<P>
   The patent protects an ``electromagnetic jack system'' for
lifting portions or all of a vehicle. ``It could be installed on
new vehicles when they are built, and added to older vehicles,''
said Vann, a Loganville resident.
</P>
<P>
   The system consists of four electromagnetically operated jacks
attached to the bottom of the vehicle at each corner, and a
dashboard-mounted console to control current flow to the
electromagnets. The jacks can be used individually to lift one
tire, or all together to lift the entire vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Vann said each jack consists of two electromagnets placed within
a shaft with a flat base that lowers to the ground when needed.
When activated from the control panel, the two electromagnets are
charged with like polarity, which _ as science students will know _
causes a repelling effect that pushes the two electromagnets apart.
This provides the lift to jack up the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   When the tire is replaced, the control panel changes the current
flow to cause unlike polarity between the two electromagnets.
Unlike polarity attracts, which permits the two electromagnets to
come together, retracting the jack and lowering the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a push-button world in many ways,'' said Vann. ``Why
not this?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
