A1749 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHIPGRANT10-COX     12-09 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIPGRANT10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech to take lead in microchip development
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech President Wayne Clough, who has set a
course to bolster the research power of his school, takes a large
step in that direction with an agreement this week to help lead
microchip development over the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Tech will take charge of one of the lead elements in a new
national research network created by the national semiconductor
industry, the U.S. government and 16 top universities. Called the
Focus Center Research Program, the program, when it hits its
stride, will sustain some $60 million a year in development of chip
technology, the consortium said in an announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program is the most ambitious research project that the
U.S. chip industry has undertaken since 1987, when the
Semiconductor Industry Association companies agreed to form
SEMATECH,'' said Craig R. Barrett, president and chief executive of
Intel Corp. and chairman of the SIA's technology strategy
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Focus Center program is the centerpiece of our new
long-range plan to maintain the industry's growth by making sure we
address the technological challenges that surface during the next
decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Contracts for the first round of research work have been awarded
to schools in six states, organized into two teams headed by
Georgia Tech and the University of California at Berkeley. Tech
heads a team that will try to advance knowledge about
``interconnect'' technology as it applies to microchips. The
Berkeley group, including 10 universities, will focus on ``design
and test'' issues in chip development.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Tech team, directed by Professor James Meindl, will
address the wiring that connects the millions of transistors on a
microchip. The team will include Stanford, Rennselaer Polytechnic
Institute, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Cornell and the
State University of New York at Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Some $12.5 million is already committed to the Tech team
research, and an additional $7 million could be awarded if work
progresses satisfactorily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our overarching goal is to discover and invent new solutions
that enable the U.S. chip industry to transcend the known limits on
interconnections that would otherwise slow the progress of
semiconductor technology,'' Meindl said.
</P>
<P>
   The Microelectronics Research Center on the downtown campus will
house most of Tech's work.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the initial focus centers, headed by Tech and Berkeley,
will be funded through 2001. They will be guided by the technology
challenges outline in the National Technology Roadmap for
Semiconductors. It projects industry needs over the next 15 years
and identifies critical issues that need solutions, such as the
connectivity problems that will get attention at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
