r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN     12-09 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BCS SYSTEM PROVES, WELL, NOTHING MUCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Those Bowl Championship Series rankings were
supposedly brought in to eliminate the feelings that college
football was too tongue-tied and indecisive about crowning its
national champion.
</P>
<P>
   There was a school of thought that too many loose ends existed
when a pair of top 25 polls subjectively picked that nation's No. 1
team.
</P>
<P>
   So, did the BCS system work? Yes. And it proved absolutely
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   All the decimal points, computer rankings and strength of
schedule evaluations deemed Tennessee and Florida State the top two
teams in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Congrats to the BCS for picking the two most deserving teams,
but if it had not existed, nothing would have changed, because the
Volunteers and Seminoles were 1-2 in both top 25 polls anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta Bowl would have been the same with or without the
BCS. It will just make everybody feel better Jan. 5 when the winner
of the Fiesta Bowl is unanimously crowned national champion.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the BCS didn't provide some interesting moments Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Was anything scarier than the revelation that computer expert
Jeff Sagarin had Kansas State No. 1 in his power ratings, despite
its loss to Texas A&AMP;M? Thanks a lot, BCS folks, you've really put
our minds at ease with this system.
</P>
<P>
   A guy living in Indiana and working out of his basement can pick
a team No. 1 following a loss, and gets to be one of three power
ranking formats used by the BCS to pick its No. 1 team. Maybe
college basketball needs to re-evaluate those power rankings they
use so often for their NCAA Tournament selections.
</P>
<P>
   It may be complex, but the BCS is not completely worthless. It
brought unprecedented fan interest and media coverage to college
football's race for No. 1. The NFL has been dwarfed this season by
the heightened awareness the BCS brought to college football.
</P>
<P>
   This was the one thing sports fans were talking about in the
late fall, not the Denver Broncos' chances of going undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, teams like Kansas State would never have received
so much scrutiny over their schedule. And BYU would have never won
its championship if the BCS existed 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, there is one redeeming quality of the BCS
rankings. Athletic directors all over the country will be forced to
schedule better teams if they harbor any hopes of capturing a
national title.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is, by the time ADs start scheduling tough games,
college football will probably have ditched the BCS in favor of a
national playoff system.
</P>
<P>
   Politics, as usual: It sure looked like something fishy was
going on when the Pac-10 just happened to pick UCLA's Cade McNown
and Oregon's Akili Smith as co-offensive players of the year, and
both received first-team all-conference honors.
</P>
<P>
   The only way that could actually happen is if the 10 coaches
voted 5-5 on both honors. And that certainly did not occur.
</P>
<P>
   What did happen?
</P>
<P>
   The coaches chose one player (McNown) as the offensive player of
the year, and another (Smith) as the first-team quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it dawned on them that it didn't look too cool to have
your offensive player of the year as second-team quarterback,
especially when he was still a Heisman Trophy candidate. So a
compromise was struck, and two quarterbacks were named to the first
team.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial first-team pick was Arizona State center
Grey Ruegamer. He was criticized by coaches from USC, Oregon and
California this season for dirty play.
</P>
<P>
   Top freshman: Last year at this time, UCLA and USC both coveted
linebacker Jashon Sykes of Serra High School in Gardena. It's easy
to see why today because he's easily one of the best young
linebackers in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes, who signed with Colorado, had 13 tackles in the
Buffaloes' loss to Nebraska, and was named player of the game by
ABC.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played incredible . . . like a madman,'' Colorado senior
linebacker Brandon Southward said.
</P>
<P>
   With USC losing Chris Claiborne and UCLA losing Brendon
Ayanbadejo, Sykes' defection to Boulder will hurt even more next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting in the wings: Former El Toro High coach Bob Johnson, the
father of former UCLA quarterback Bret Johnson and former USC
quarterback Rob Johnson, will become UNLV's offensive coordinator
if Notre Dame assistant Mike Sanford turns down the job.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Johnson has been a tutor for USC quarterback
Carson Palmer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Scott Wolf's college football column appears
Thursdays in the Daily News. He can be reached via e-mail at
Scwolf1aol.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
