<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-MOCEANU10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge forbids Moceanu's father from contact for 1 year
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As gymnast Dominique Moceanu cried on the witness
stand Wednesday, her parents didn't move a muscle in their seats 20
feet away. The judge handed her a tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Judge John D. Montgomery, citing evidence of family
violence, granted Dominique's request that Dumitru Moceanu stay at
least 500 feet away from his daughter for one year. The protective
order does not apply to Camelia Moceanu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared,'' Dominique, 17, said of her father, who was in
the same courtroom fighting his daughter's suit for emancipation
six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a legal adult, Dominique refused to tell her parents where
she lived, which she said led to Dumitru stalking her, hiring a
private investigator to follow her and allegedly trying to arrange
the murder of her coach, Luminita Miscenco and Brian Huggins, a
32-year-old male friend.
</P>
<P>
   In a soft voice, her father _ who appears less domineering since
shaving off his mustache _ denied everything or took the Fifth
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're her parents; we're concerned about her,'' Dumitru said.
``Nobody is as concerned as us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a dark blue sweater with light blue and yellow stripes,
blue pants and platform shoes, Dominique looked like a normal
teen-ager, not like the diminutive gymnast who won a gold medal at
the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like my life was interrogated,'' she said. ``I couldn't
do any move without him knowing what I did, calling me, harassing
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't lead my life. I was trapped.''
</P>
<P>
   She dissolved into tears when Dumitru's lawyer, Katherine
Scardino, pressed her for the exact dates that her father was in
the school parking lot waiting for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been scarred basically for life,'' Dominique said, ``with
verbal assaults he used in scaring me and intimidating me.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said her father slapped her in the face. The last time
was late 1997, when she had gained weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you understand that's a discipline?'' asked Scardino.
</P>
<P>
   ``To hit me in the face?'' retorted Moceanu.
</P>
<P>
   She said her autobiography, the best seller, ``Dominique
Moceanu: An American Champion,'' which was written with a co-writer
before the Olympics was ``the fantasy story'' that her parents
wanted to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique, who testified for 95 minutes in the 4-hour hearing,
said she was ``relieved'' by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since detectives came to my house, my life has been upside
down,'' she said, referring to Nov. 13, the day three Houston
homicide detectives told her of the murder-for-hire plot that sent
her into hiding. Police are still investigating the scheme, which
Dominique has heard likened to the famous Texas Cheerleader Mom
case.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he did not have to listen to three cassette tapes
which allegedly detail the plot to make his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not unlike a lot of families, just a higher profile,''
said Montgomery, a no-nonsense Texan. ``I don't think anyone was
intending deliberately to cause harm, but there has been a lot of
unnecessary harm.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Humpty Dumpty has fallen off the wall, let's try to
put him back together, folks.''
</P>
<P>
   However, money remains a divisive issue and the family tragedy
has played out in the media, with some portraying Dominique as an
ungrateful child, others charging that her parents exploited her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are very high right now,'' said Dominique, who has
a 9-year-old sister and was the primary family bread-winner with
her gymnastics success. She says that her father squandered her
earnings on a multimillion dollar suburban gym which is regarded as
the best in the world, but is not being used at capacity and is
losing students. There is a ``Coaches Needed, Happy Holidays'' sign
out front.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu has not been in any gym in two months. Her competition
has been in courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've just been really tough through this whole
thing,'' Moceanu said by telephone the day before the hearing,
sounding like she did after winning the Goodwill Games in July.
``It's been really hard and really stressful, but I've become
really strong. I'm gonna make it through it.''
</P>
<P>
   She could understand that Dumitru's afraid of losing his
daughter, ``but that's no reason to go and commit (the) murder of
two people. Parents lose their children all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Scardino said Moceanu's parents are ``devastated'' by the
ruling. ``Dumitru can't believe that his daughter has turned her
back on him. She wouldn't speak to him today.''
</P>
<P>
   During breaks as Dominique chatted with friends, her mother sat
on the opposite side of the room, casting sad, sometimes stern
glances at her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique is receiving emotional support from a woman she has
known only three weeks, her new agent, Janey Miller, who has been
staying with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see her stare out the window at one in the morning, crying,
saying 'I'm losing my family,''' said Miller. ``Despite all of it,
he's still her father.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Moceanu put up her Christmas tree Monday, she was
joined by Miller, friend Brian Huggins and Jeff Pudlo, another
coach whom Dumitru Moceanu believes is influencing his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins, who has a wife and child, was one of the targets of the
alleged murder plot, and he and Dominique hid in Las Vegas,
Colorado and the Cayman Islands. Scardino tells anyone who will
listen that she believes they had a sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't pass the smell test with me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu and her friends say that's ridiculous. ``I would put my
life on it,'' said her best friend, Adriana Montero, 18, who has
known her nine years. She said Dumitru doesn't want Dominique to
have friends of her own age, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought I was a bad influence,'' she said, ``because we
would talk about something else other than gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   ``All she ever saw was four walls around her.''
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Moceanu roared off at the wheel of her
Mustang convertible with her agent and two friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully my family might get back together,'' Dominique said.
``Who knows, in two years we might be back together. It might have
taught him a lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   THE MOCEANU FILE
</P>
<P>
   Occupation: Gymnast.
</P>
<P>
   Honors: 1996 Olympic gold medalist, women's team gymnastics,
Atlanta; youngest member of that team, at age 14; gold medal,
all-around, 1998 Goodwill Games, Uniondale, N.Y.; individual golds,
balance beam and vault, 1998 U.S. Championships, Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 17.
</P>
<P>
   Birthday, birthplace: Sept. 30, 1981, Hollywood, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Parents Dumitru and Camelia; sister Christina.
</P>
<P>
   Situation: Sued for independence from her family; declared a
legal adult by the judicial system in Texas; sought injunction to
keep her father away from her, alleging that he had threatened her
hit here and misspent her earnings from gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings: An estimated $2 million-$2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Goal: Probably the 2000 Olympics, Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
