<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1771 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADIAN-DEATHROW-HNS     12-09 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADIAN-DEATHROW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MOVES TO PUT EXECUTIONS BACK ON TRACK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
and CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State's attorneys scrambled late Wednesday to
try to convince an appeals court to put the execution of Canadian
Joseph Stanley Faulder back on track for Thursday night after a
federal judge earlier in the day put his lethal injection on hold.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks of Austin also stayed the
execution of Danny Barber less than an hour before Barber was to be
taken to the death chamber in Huntsville for the 1979 beating death
of a Balch Springs woman.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks stayed Faulder's execution and ordered an evidentiary
hearing Dec. 21 on whether the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles
had violated Faulder's due process rights in denying the condemned
man's clemency requests. A Dec. 22 hearing on the same issue was
set for Barber.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Tisdale, spokesman for Attorney General Dan Morales, said
lawyers immediately filed a request with the 5th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in New Orleans to vacate both stays.
</P>
<P>
   If the 5th Circuit overrules Sparks, Faulder could be executed
on schedule, but Barber's date would have to be set off at least 30
days.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday the 18 parole board members _ casting their
ballots, as usual, in secret and without explaining their reasoning
_ rejected the 61-year-old Faulder's pleas to commute his sentence
to life imprisonment or delay the execution 90 days. The vote was
17-0, with board member Bennie Elmore of Huntsville abstaining, as
is his customary practice.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder was convicted of the 1974 robbery and murder of
75-year-old Inez Phillips, the matriarch of a wealthy oil family in
Gladewater, 110 miles east of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   On a 15-0 vote with one abstention the board also rejected
Barber's requests for commutation or a 30-day reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   Barber was condemned for the 1979 attack on Janice Louise Ingram
at her home in Balch Springs, a suburb southeast of Dallas. He
described it as a burglary that went wrong. He also confessed to
three other slayings and received life sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder's case has see-sawed in various courts this week,
primarily on the issue of the parole board's practice of not
convening public meetings and not voting publicly on death row
prisoners' clemency requests.
</P>
<P>
   In granting Faulder's stay, Sparks noted: ``The court cannot
tell whether the Texas clemency procedure comports with the minimal
due process standard required (in an earlier U.S. Supreme Court
case from Ohio). It is unclear how the board can document that its
procedures are not arbitrary if it does not document its procedures
at all. Nevertheless, the court will hold an evidentiary hearing to
determine whether the Texas clemency procedure satisfies the
minimal due process requirements as identified (in the Ohio
case).''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times joined a growing chorus of individuals and
organizations calling for a halt to Faulder's execution. In an
editorial Wednesday, the paper urged Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a
potential presidential candidate in 2000, to commute Faulder's
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder has become an international cause celebre, with U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, high-ranking Canadian
government officials and a host of anti-death penalty organizations
contending that Faulder's rights under the 1969 Vienna Convention
on Consular Rights were violated because authorities never informed
him of his right to contact his embassy after he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Texas authorities have insisted that they did not know Faulder
was a Canadian because he was carrying a U.S. driver's license and
he never told them of his nationality.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder is one of 18 foreign nationals awaiting death by
injection in Texas, according to Texas Department of Criminal
Justice figures. He is the only Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   Should the courts clear the path for Faulder's execution _ along
with Barber, the fourth slated this week _ the parole board's
denial of clemency leaves the governor with only one option:
granting a 30-day postponement.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he wouldn't make that decision until all court appeals
have been exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   At a Capitol news conference, he defended the death penalty as
he calmly fielded numerous pointed questions from Canadian
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a Canadian and you come to our state, don't murder
anybody,'' he told one Canadian reporter who asked if Texas ``is
running kind of a wild west show down here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he wanted to assure Canadians that ``this man
(Faulder) will be afforded all the due process of our court
system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in swift and sure punishment, and Texans support
the death penalty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his two primary concerns in any death penalty case
were whether there was any doubt of the defendant's guilt and
whether he had been afforded due process.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that, in his review of Faulder's case, he had seen
``no new evidence that questions the jury's verdict that he is
guilty of this crime. In fact, his request for commutation was not
based on any claim of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Wednesday, several Canadians who met
briefly with parole board Chairman Victor Rodriguez complained to
Texas journalists that Rodriguez had an ``extremely belligerent
attitude,'' treated them rudely and ordered them escorted out of a
state building under threat of arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to put across the point of view of Canadians,'' said
Patrick ``Sid'' Ryan, a labor leader from Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we pointed out to him we felt he was being belligerent
and ignorant, he tossed one of us out of the room. The rest of the
delegation was invited to leave. We were then threatened with
criminal offenses if we didn't leave the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, however, said the Canadians were ``pretty
aggressive'' in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to set the agenda, say how the meeting would take
place,'' he said. ``It was an effort on their part to dictate what
would be heard and whom by. I made it very clear we wanted to hear
exactly what they wanted to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez added that the meeting turned sour when one of the
Canadians accused him of executing somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're administering a process here, but I am not personally
executing anybody, and I take offense to that,'' Rodriguez said he
told the visitors. ``He wouldn't withdraw that statement, so I
asked him to leave and then (another individual) got profane and
said ... `If he's got to leave, so do we.' They chose to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they forsaked an opportunity for all of them to
express what they wanted to say.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ryan, the Toronto labor leader, added, ``If we can't even
get a fair hearing from this gentleman, how the hell is Stanley
Faulder going to get some due process and fair process?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
