<HEADLINE>
4-YEAR CONGRESSMAN TO PRESIDE OVER HOUSE IMPEACHMENT DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., La.)  (See also: IMPEACH, IMPEACH-DEFENSE, IMPEACH-LEGAL, IMPEACH-STARR,
IMPEACH-SCHIPPERS, IMPEACH-GRASSROOTS, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-RUFF,
IMPEACH-POLITICS, IMPEACH-TEXT, EDIT-IMPEACH) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill., is to preside next week in
the speaker's chair when the full House debates articles of
impeachment against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   LaHood was picked by the outgoing speaker, Newt Gingrich, whose
aides asked LaHood on Monday whether he wanted the job. Republican
aides said Gingrich did not want to end his four-year tenure by
presiding over what is expected to be a highly divisive debate, and
that the incoming speaker, Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., did not want
his tenure to begin on that note.
</P>
<P>
   LaHood, 53, a former high school teacher and counselor to
delinquent teen-agers, has a reputation for fairness that
Republican leaders hope will translate into a calming influence on
the proceedings and will help give the party an aura of
even-handedness. He has not indicated how he would vote on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was elected to the House only four years ago with
the Republican rebel class of 1994, LaHood has not been associated
with the rebels. He was one of three of the new freshmen who did
not sign Gingrich's Contract With America. He also helped organize
a bipartisan House retreat in Hershey, Pa., last year to help
members get to know each other better and treat each other with
more civility.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, LaHood has presided in the speaker's chair perhaps
more often than any other Republican in recognition of his
knowledge on procedure, said his spokesman, Tim Butler. He accepts
the assignments willingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He views it as a high honor,'' Butler said. ``This will be one
of the most momentous votes taken in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   LaHood is in a seat once held by Everett McKinley Dirksen and
Bob Michel, both former Republican leaders. He is the grandson of
an immigrant from Lebanon and the son of a restaurant manager.
After teaching in Catholic schools for six years and working as a
counselor, he served as Michel's chief of staff in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
