<HEADLINE>
SPANISH JUDGE DRAWS UP HIS INDICTMENT OF PINOCHET
</HEADLINE>
  (See also PINOCHET, PINOCHET-CHILE) 
(bl)  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ The Spanish judge who issued the arrest warrant
for Gen. Augusto Pinochet of Chile will complete the criminal
indictment against him this week and immediately send it to London,
a Madrid court official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The indictment will support the accusation against Pinochet
and it's logical that it be sent as soon as possible to show the
charges against him,'' said the official, who spoke on condition
that he not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment could come as early as Thursday and is the next
legal step after the formal extradition request, which the Spanish
judge, Baltasar Garzon, sent to Britain last month. It listed more
than 3,000 people who were killed or disappeared under Pinochet's
17-year military rule.
</P>
<P>
   Garzon, an investigating magistrate at Spain's National Court,
requested permission in October to interview Pinochet in London,
but British officials are unlikely to allow it while the
extradition hearing is pending, the court official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
