<HEADER>
A1789 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-TORTUREKILLING-     12-09 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-TORTURE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLER GETS DEATH SENTENCE FOR TORTURE SLAYING
</HEADLINE>
 KILLING-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GABRIELLE CRIST 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Over the past nine months, Robert Neville
Jr. has sought fame for murder, boasting about killing a
19-year-old Arlington woman whom many loved.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Neville got one last moment under the bright lights
of the TV cameras when jurors decided in four hours that he should
die for killing Amy Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   When the verdict was read and the interviews were done, Neville
shuffled back into the holding cell with his legs shackled and his
moments in the limelight fading.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old with the trademark smirk knew that a death
sentence was likely, his attorneys said, and has time to prepare
for death.
</P>
<P>
   But Robinson didn't have that luxury, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Neville and his friend, Michael Hall, 19, offered
Robinson a ride when they saw her peddaling her bike to work Feb.
15 in Arlington, a Fort Worth suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who cherished her grocery sacking job and tried to
arrive at work early, climbed into the car ``not knowing that
within an hour, she would die in a painful, brutal, ugly way,''
Assistant District Attorney Christy Jack told jurors during her
closing argument. ``She never knows she's surrounded by death.''
</P>
<P>
   First, the two men shot at her with a pellet gun and a
pistol-grip crossbow. Then, as Robinson begged for her life,
Neville shot Robinson in the chest with a rifle ``and drops her to
the ground right behind a hill of garbage,'' said Jack, who
prosecuted the case with Alfie Owens and Alan Levy. ``And when he's
done amusing himself, he shoots her in the head.''
</P>
<P>
   Neville and Hall were arrested March 3 in Eagle Pass, Texas.
Neville horrified the community by boasting about the murder, and
then telling several investigators, as well as TV and newspaper
reporters, that he laughed as Robinson lay gasping for air.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys Tim Moore and Sam Smith tried to use Neville's
irrational behavior as a defense, contending that he is a manic
depressive, an illness brought on by lupus, a disease in which the
immune system attacks internal organs.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that Neville's life span will be shortened because
of the illness, and they asked the jury to let him die in prison
without the death penalty. Had Neville not been sentenced to death,
he would have automatically received life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   During closing arguments, Moore walked jurors through the
execution, explaining to them how the poison would seep through
Neville's veins until he died.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... He'll still have that same silly grin,'' Moore told
jurors. ``Let him meet his maker on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors sided with the prosecution, but as the verdict was read,
three of them cried. None wanted to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys said they are disappointed that Neville's life
was not spared. ``You do the best you can with what you have to
work with,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Neville's demeanor was a factor in the verdict, and it was a
factor that the defense attorneys had to tolerate. ``I'm not sure I
would say working with Robert was easy,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   To prosecutors, the verdict hardly called for celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be more satisfied if we didn't have the case in the first
place,'' Levy said after the verdict was announced. ``It's not a
win-win proposition by any means.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Neville's mother, Cathey Hill, the verdict meant saying
goodbye to her son.
</P>
<P>
   As visiting District Judge Harry Hopkins read the verdict, Hill
ran out of the courtroom, sobbing. When TV cameras focused on her
tears, she pushed a cameraman, shouting, ``Get out of my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's relatives said they empathize with Hill and Neville's
other kin. They said that although justice was done, they
sympathize with a family that will also have to deal with the death
of a child.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's father, Ben Grogan, was allowed to confront Neville
after the verdict was read in what is called victim allocution.
</P>
<P>
   Grogan looked Neville in the eye and told him he will pay for
his crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've had your 15 minutes in front of God and everybody for
your fame,'' Grogan said. ``But you're going to be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
