</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUS-HEISMANVOTERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How the Heisman Trophy winner is selected
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Downtown Athletic Club of New York presents
the Heisman Trophy. By its own rules, it ``has no voice in
selecting the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   That voice belongs mainly to the media. At one time, there were
1,050 voters from newspapers, radio and television stations. A
decade ago, the DAC streamlined the process.
</P>
<P>
   This year there are 870 media voters _ 145 in each of six
regions: Northeast, Mid-Atlantic, Midwest, Far West, Southwest and
South.
</P>
<P>
   Past Heisman winners also vote. Last year, 51 former winners
were eligible, for a total of 921 voters.
</P>
<P>
   Each voter casts a ballot with three names, ranked in order.
Players get three points for a first-place vote, two for second and
one for third.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's winner, University of Michigan defensive back
Charles Woodson, received 433 first-place votes and 1,815 points.
Runner-up Peyton Manning, Tennessee quarterback, had 281
first-place votes and 1,543 points. Williams finished fifth last
year with four first-place votes and 135 points.
</P>
<P>
   He's expected to do a lot better in the voting this year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
