<HEADER>
A1795 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HEAT-EXTREMES-ART     12-09 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEAT-EXTREMES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARMFUL HEAT IS MORE FREQUENT, ESPECIALLY AT NIGHT, STUDY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Extreme summer heat and humidity of the kind most threatening to
health have become more frequent in the United States over the last
half century, two federal researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   According to their study, in Thursday's issue of the journal
Nature, the frequency of extremely hot, humid days and of heat
waves lasting several days increased substantially from 1949 to
1995. In terms of the threat to health, however, another finding
was especially significant: The trend was stronger at night than in
the daytime.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts say that extremely high temperature and humidity
over successive nights is a crucial factor in heat-related deaths.
When nearly 600 people died in a heat wave in Chicago in 1995, for
example, many of the deaths were attributed to an unremitting
combination of record high nighttime heat and humidity that allowed
no respite from daytime heat stress.
</P>
<P>
   Some studies have shown that extreme summer heat has more impact
on the health of Americans than any other kind of severe weather,
and that the elderly are most vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these climate trends continue, they may pose a public
health problem, particularly as there are increasing numbers of
elderly people,'' wrote the authors of the study, Dr. Dian Gaffen
and Rebecca Ross, research meteorologists at the National Oceanic
and Atmospheric Administration's Air Resources Laboratory in Silver
Spring, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent trend toward more extreme heat generally coincides
with a warming of the Earth's surface in recent decades, both
globally and in the United States. The dominant view among
scientists is that at least some of this warming has been caused by
emissions of heat-trapping gases like carbon dioxide, which is
emitted by the burning of coal, oil, natural gas and wood. The
Earth's temperature is projected to rise substantially over the
next century, further increasing humidity and making heat waves
more frequent and intense.
</P>
<P>
   While the increasing frequency of extreme heat and humidity
cannot be directly linked to the warming trend, Dr. Gaffen said it
was ``consistent with what is predicted in the global warming
scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Karl, director of the National Climatic Data Center,
agreed. ``I think these are the types of conditions that will
become more frequent and more intense when they do occur'' if the
climate warms as projected, Karl said. ``We've already seen
examples of that this past year,'' he added, referring to last
summer's heat wave in Texas. The projected increases in global
temperatures, he said, ``would make this rather commonplace.''
</P>
<P>
   By and large, Karl said, the Gaffen-Ross findings ``seem to be
consistent with what we know from other analyses.'' He said that if
data through 1998 were included in the study, ``I'm sure they would
find even stronger trends.''
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, the last two years have been the two warmest on
record.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gaffen and Ms. Ross had for some time been studying global
distributions of temperature and water vapor, and they found an
increasing trend of rising humidity accompanying rising
temperatures. So, Dr. Gaffen said, they decided to see whether this
meant that extremes of heat and humidity were also increasing.
</P>
<P>
   They defined ``extreme'' as the highest 15 percent of
temperature and humidity measurements, as recorded every three
hours around the clock in July and August from 1961 through 1990.
This threshold, they report, is ``closely correlated'' with levels
above which, according to other researchers, human mortality
increases sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gaffen and Ms. Ross analyzed records at 113 government
weather stations around the country, mainly at airports, in search
of information on two variables: the combination of temperature and
humidity that meteorologists call ``apparent temperature,'' and
temperature alone.
</P>
<P>
   Apparent temperature is a measure of the combined impact of heat
and humidity on people and the sensation they experience as a
result. It is increasing faster than temperature alone, the
researchers said, because humidity is increasing faster. This would
be expected in a warmer climate, since more water evaporates and
the atmosphere can hold more.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers computed their thresholds of extremity for the
average daily temperature, the daily maximum temperature and the
daily minimum temperature for July and August at each weather
station. They found that from 1949 to 1995, the annual frequency of
days on which the thresholds were surpassed increased at all but 16
of the 113 stations. The increases were largest for the minimum
``apparent temperature,'' which basically translates to a measure
of combined nighttime heat and humidity.
</P>
<P>
   At some stations, Dr. Gaffen and Ms. Ross found that over the
half century, the number of nights with extremely high apparent
temperatures doubled, to about 18 days a year from about 9 days a
year in some places. The largest and statistically most significant
trends were found to occur in some of the nation's most populated
areas, especially from the Middle Atlantic States south to Florida,
as well as along the West Coast and in big cities in the Southwest.
Eight of the 15 cities in which the trend was most pronounced were
in the Southeast _ including Miami, which headed the list
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Daytime increases were found to be not nearly as dramatic. In
fact, the upward trend was statistically significant only west of
the Rocky Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   East of the Rockies, the apparent temperature increased more
than temperature alone. West of the Rockies, where summertime
humidity increases are less marked, the trends of the two variables
were similar.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators defined heat waves as periods of three or four
days in which the average daily apparent temperature exceeded the
top 15 percent threshold. On average, they found, each weather
station experiences 1.7 three-day heat waves and one four-day heat
wave a year. In the contiguous United States, the number of heat
waves increased by 88 percent from 1949 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Two caveats have been attached to the study. To some extent,
said Dr. Gaffen and Ms. Ross, the rising heat probably reflects
increased urbanization; the concrete and asphalt in urban areas
absorb and retain more heat than rural areas. But Ms. Gaffen said
that most of the trend cannot be explained this way.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, she said, not all the weather stations in the
study were in urban areas. For another, the researchers looked for
but did not find a correlation between population growth _ a
measure of urbanization _ and trends in extreme weather.
</P>
<P>
   The other caveat was offered by Dr. Laurence Kalkstein of the
University of Delaware, who has long studied heat and health. The
threshold of extreme heat adopted by the researchers was not really
selected on the basis of the relationship between health and
extreme heat, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies by Kalkstein have found that the threshold at
which heat begins to kill people varies from one city to another.
``That's my only disagreement'' with the study, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-AUS-LASTHEISMAN     12-09 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUS-LASTHEISMAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Downtown athletic club falls on hard times
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ On Saturday, University of Texas running back
Ricky Williams could become the 64th recipient of the prestigious
Heisman Trophy, presented annually by the Downtown Athletic Club of
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be the last,'' said Jim Spitzer, a lawyer representing
a group that holds the mortgage on the Manhattan building the club
has called home for more than a half-century. ``He ought not to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heisman Trophy, given to the player judged to be the best in
college football, is synonymous with success. But the grand old
club that awards the Heisman, and which has one decorating its
lobby, has fallen on troubled times.
</P>
<P>
   The DAC owes $3 million in back taxes, has filed for Chapter 11
bankruptcy and is in conflict with the investment group that holds
the $9.5 million mortgage on the building.
</P>
<P>
   Even as DAC members are making final preparations for Saturday
evening's nationally televised Heisman announcement, the company,
B&AMP;D Management, could be in bankruptcy court presenting a
reorganization plan for the club.
</P>
<P>
   That's just what club members sought to avoid when they filed
for bankruptcy. But their ranks aren't exactly full. Membership has
dwindled from an estimated 4,000 two decades ago to about 1,250
today.
</P>
<P>
   And ``a lot of those are promotional members, they pay less than
you would at a typical health club,'' said Spitzer, who represents
B&AMP;D Management and claims that the club's membership is pumped up
with new members getting a cut-rate deal. ``If you just looked at
the regular members, you'd be hard-pressed to get a basketball game
going.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a private place for 200, 300 or 400 members. They're the
ones that have run up the debt. The place needs a ton of money, but
they don't want to change. We've said we'll fix it up and make it
first-rate with a first-class hotel. But at the end of the day,
they like what they've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Members dispute that claim, saying the club is healthy and has a
lot of options for its considerable assets, including perhaps
creating a Heisman restaurant or hotel on what many consider a
highly desirable piece of the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at the Statue of Liberty right now,'' member Rudy
Riska said during a recent telephone interview. ``We're at the tip
of Manhattan. Our 35-story building is the tallest athletic club in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The DAC is located in a 68-year-old Art Deco building. The 35
floors include 137 hotel rooms, one of which will be occupied by
Ricky Williams this weekend. The DAC also has seven banquet rooms,
pool tables, a dining room and a 70-foot bar on the third floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time it was the longest in New York. It may still be,''
said Riska, executive director of the Heisman Memorial Trophy
Trust.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel rooms are used by members who want to stay over in the
city rather than commute, or by members of other athletic clubs
around the country who are visiting New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make arrangements through the clubs,'' Riska said. ``If
you're in the athletic club at Los Angeles or Dallas, you get a
letter of introduction. It's not open to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heisman Room, where the trophy will be presented in a TV
special, sports dark wood paneling and portraits of past winners.
</P>
<P>
   The athletic facilities for DAC members include Stairmasters and
other trappings of modern health clubs, an indoor pool, squash,
racquetball, handball, basketball and volleyball courts, and an
18th-floor boxing ring where heavyweight Gerry Cooney sometimes
gives lessons.
</P>
<P>
   The members, Riska said, are typically Ivy League-educated Wall
Street types. Squash is their game of choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be handball,'' said Riska. ``But it has gotten so
we're dinosaurs. It's a lost art. It's hard to learn the four-wall
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Early years
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the grand club was conceived in the Roaring '20s,
but it opened in 1930, shortly after the stock market crashed and
as the Depression tightened its grip. In those days, the club was
in something of a no-man's land after dark as, in the interest of
saving money, lights were turned off from Borough Hall to Battery
Place. The first athletic director, John Heisman, had to promote
the club during those years. Heisman was one of the biggest names
in college football, having won as a coach at a number of schools,
including Rice University in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   At the DAC, Heisman had some success mixing banquets and
football, and the club came up with the idea of honoring the best
college football player in 1935. The first recipient of the DAC
Trophy was Jay Berwanger of the University of Chicago. Berwanger
still attends some of the club's functons.
</P>
<P>
   Heisman, however, died of bronchial pneumonia on Oct. 3, 1936,
before the second trophy was awarded. It was renamed in his honor.
Since then, the award has only increased in prestige.
</P>
<P>
   As for the club, it struggled for survival until after World War
II. That's when the U.S. shipping industry boom, and much of the
aid to rebuild Europe, passed through thriving New York harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the shipping companies had their headquarters here,''
Riska said. ``At one time, that was probably 95 percent of our
members. The shipping companies had unlimited expense accounts and
would use the club to entertain.''
</P>
<P>
   Those heady days lasted until around 1965, when changes took
place in the industry. Bustling, crowded and expensive New York
City didn't have the kind of dock space conducive for storing and
loading the huge containers. Shipping companies were moving to New
Jersey and other locations.
</P>
<P>
   Change in clientele
</P>
<P>
   As the shipping people left, the DAC became more Wall
Street-oriented. It admitted women in the late 1970s. Today, about
10 percent of the members are women.
</P>
<P>
   Newer members typically haven't been as free-spending as the old
shipping clientele. And downtown clubs around the country took a
hit in the 1990s when Congress eliminated tax deductions for club
dues.
</P>
<P>
   Like other old-style athletic clubs, the DAC also lost potential
young members to trendier, sleeker clubs downtown or in the
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Hart said that while some small downtown athletic clubs closed
around the country, many are being revitalized and shifting
emphasis. That appeared to be the case at the DAC, but the one
thing the club hasn't overcome was $3 million in back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Club members decided that a way to get out of the debt was to
sell its main asset, the building, pay off the debts and lease back
part of the building.
</P>
<P>
   In a hot hotel market, the DAC attracted a number of offers. The
club picked one by B&AMP;D Management, a real estate company with four
partners. B&AMP;D offered a $15.5 million deal, with $1.5 million
earmarked for renovation. But when the deal was put to a vote, the
members chose not to take it.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the club's lawyer, Hal Hirsch, said that a
study done by Deloitte &AMP; Touche showed that under that proposed
arrangement, the club would once again be in financial trouble
after five years.
</P>
<P>
   B&AMP;D sued for breach of contract. Then, the company negotiated
with the holder of the club's mortgage, the Bank of New York, and
in February made a deal to acquire it.
</P>
<P>
   The DAC, fearful that B&AMP;D would foreclose even if payments were
current, filed for bankruptcy. Now B&AMP;D, as the holder of the
mortgage, is readying to file its own plans for reorganization with
the court. That's happening right at the biggest moment of the year
for the DAC, when football fans nationwide are watching to see who
wins the Heisman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the club. The Heisman gave it great identification,''
Riska said. As part of the ceremonies this year, the late Doak
Walker, who won the trophy 50 years ago, will be honored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of sad,'' Spitzer said of the club's current
financial straits. ``It's a great institution. We'd like to see it
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
