<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1799 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSURE10-COX     12-09 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSURE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Supporters of middle ground gain small victory
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the House Judiciary Committee virtually
certain to approve articles of impeachment against President
Clinton this week, Democrats are pinning their remaining hopes on a
strongly worded motion of censure.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the committee won a small, but significant victory
Wednesday when Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) said he would allow
them to offer a censure resolution in committee after a vote on
articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to have a vote on a resolution of censure,
and we will have one,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Censure also received a boost from former Massachusetts Gov.
William Weld, a Republican moderate, who urged the committee to
devise a tough punishment for the president that stopped short of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic censure resolution, released Wednesday and
carefully crafted to appeal to undecided Republican moderates,
rebukes Clinton for failing in his obligation to ``set an example
of high moral standards and ... respect for the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying Clinton violated the trust of the American people and
dishonored the presidency, the resolution states that Clinton made
false statements concerning his ``reprehensible conduct with a
subordinate'' and took steps to delay discovery of the truth. The
resolution would also bind Clinton to the proposition, stated in
the text, that he is still subject to ``criminal and civil
penalties for his conduct'' by requiring him to sign the document.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution does not accuse Clinton of perjury. It also does
not require that he stand on the floor of the House to hear it or
pay any kind of financial penalty _ although Democrats indicated
that such provisions could be negotiated voluntarily with the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the White House declined to comment on the specifics
of the Democratic resolution. ``While we are certainly willing to
listen to what people propose, this is a matter for the House to
decide,'' said White House spokesman Jim Kennedy. ``I'm not in a
position to rule in or rule out any of the particulars.''
</P>
<P>
   But a vote in committee, even if unsuccessful, would create the
justification for advancing a censure alternative if the full House
votes on articles of impeachment next week, said Rep. William
Delahunt (D-Mass.), who worked to draft the censure resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that the Republican leadership would understand
that for many this is a vote of conscience,'' said Delahunt. ``For
many moderate Republicans, it does give them an opportunity to vote
their conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt and other Democrats appealed to Speaker-designate Bob
Livingston (R-La.) to permit the censure resolution to come to the
floor for a vote, even if it is defeated in committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be unseemly ... if the resolution favored by the
majority of Americans would be walled off from consideration,''
said Rep. Rick Boucher (D-Va.). Livingston had no comment, said his
spokesman Mark Corallo.
</P>
<P>
   Getting some sort of censure motion on the House floor is
critical to heading off impeachment. With no possibility of
censure, Democrats and Republicans alike are faced with either
voting to impeach the president or doing nothing. The president
will have a difficult time convincing moderate Republicans not to
vote for impeachment if they lack an alternative that expresses
their condemnation of his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think an awful lot of people, in their heart of hearts,
would like to have another option to just up or down impeachment,''
said Rep. Amo Houghton (R-N.Y.), who Wednesday became at least the
fifth Republican to say he will vote against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Many hard-line Republicans are opposed to censure precisely
because they don't want members to have a third way out.
</P>
<P>
   Others have signaled that they would not support a censure
resolution, either because they believe it is unconstitutional for
Congress to censure the president or because they don't think that
it would be a strong enough punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Censure is wholly and entirely inappropriate,'' said Rep. Bob
Barr (R-Ga.). ``It is inappropriate to consider censure as a
substitute for impeachable offenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also face opposition to censure from the liberal wing
of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler (D-N.Y.) said he could not support a censure
resolution that stated as facts allegations that the president
hasn't admitted or that have not been proven.
</P>
<P>
   But Nadler said he could swallow some of his qualms if push came
to shove.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was necessary to vote for censure to head off
impeachment, I'd do it despite my reservations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are not even sure they will have unanimous Democratic
support for censure in committee, Delahunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
