<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-SHORTFALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN SEES FOURTH-QUARTER EARNINGS SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Amid continuing uncertainty about how easily big
banks will rebound from the losses inflicted by economic turmoil
overseas, J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. said Wednesday that its fourth-quarter
earnings would fall far short of analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's fourth-largest bank blamed the weak results in
trading it does for its own account for the downturn and said that
profit in the quarter would be less than the 58 cents a share
posted in the third quarter. Analysts had been expecting
fourth-quarter earnings of $1.03 a share, according to consensus
estimates set by First Call Corp., which tracks company earnings.
In 1997, Morgan posted fourth-quarter earnings of $1.33 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Citigroup, the banking giant recently created by the
merger of Citicorp and Travelers Group Inc., said it was
considering the sale of its Phibro Inc. commodity trading unit.
Citigroup, which has been scaling back riskier trading activities,
said that federal banking regulations required it to dispose of
businesses that traded commodities for Citigroup's own account.
</P>
<P>
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Morgan's shares fell
$2.375, or 2.2 percent, to $104.1875. Citigroup rose 75 cents, or
1.55 percent, to $49.25, also in trading on the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's continuing problems improving profitability _ its
earnings peaked in the second quarter of 1996 and profits have
declined in each of the last two years _ is certain to invite
renewed speculation about how easy it will be for the bank to
remain independent in a world of new, global banking behemoths.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Morgan has repeatedly stated its intention to determine
its own fate. The bank has been laying off employees to cut costs
and said it would incur a $100 million pretax charge in the fourth
quarter as part of that campaign. And the bank has posted a sharp
upturn in businesses such as advising on big mergers, like the
Exxon Corp.'s recent agreement to acquire the Mobil Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is strong going into the New Year as markets
recover,'' said Joseph Evangelisti, a Morgan spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Morgan's disclosure will have analysts and
investors scanning Wall Street for signs of other firms that are
having difficulty recovering from the financial upheaval that began
when Russia effectively devalued the ruble and declared a debt
moratorium in August.
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude of Morgan's earnings shortfall surprised many
analysts. Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.'s banking analyst, Judah Kraushaar,
who estimated that Morgan would post fourth-quarter earnings of 43
cents a share well before Wednesday's announcement, was the only
Wall Street analyst to correctly predict the magnitude of the
shortfall, according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not be surprised if they had modest trading losses,
but they probably were not huge,'' said Kraushaar, who added that
Morgan offered him few details on its trading problems.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, according to analysts and people close to
Morgan's trading operations, stemmed from missteps the bank made
when it used derivatives and other financial devices to protect
itself from economic volatility in the fourth quarter. That was a
reasonable enough position to take given the brutal trading swings
of the third quarter, but markets have unexpectedly stabilized, and
Morgan's conservative moves went against the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The trading portfolio will also not benefit from some of the
handsome equity gains Morgan racked up recently, such as $157
million in the third quarter and $164 million in the fourth quarter
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually was surprised by the size of the losses,'' said
Charles Peabody, an analyst with Mitchell Securities Inc., who said
he expected Morgan to post healthier returns in 1999, but largely
because of cost-cutting rather than robust revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they going to generate top-tier returns anytime soon?''
asked Diane Glossman, an analyst with Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc.
``I think the answer is no. But they've clearly stated that they're
in this for the long term and intend to remain independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as proof of its financial wherewithal, Morgan also
announced an increase in its quarterly dividend, to 99 cents a
share from 95 cents, effective Dec. 31. The bank also said it might
buy back as much as $750 million of its stock in 1999 or later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
