<HEADLINE>
DEAL TO OPEN NORTHEAST LAND TO PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., N.Y., Vt.) (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Nearly 300,000 acres of privately owned forests,
tumbling wild rivers, lakes and wetlands in New York's Adirondack
region, Vermont, and New Hampshire will be opened to public use in
a $76.2 million land deal announced on Wednesday, with about
one-third of that acreage set aside forever as preserves.
</P>
<P>
   The land was put up for sale last year by Champion International
Co., one of the world's largest paper companies, as part of a broad
effort to cut costs and sell off unneeded assets.
</P>
<P>
   For the paper company, which owns or manages more than 11
million acres of forest in North and South America and has more
than $5 billion in annual sales, the all-cash agreement is a minor
accounting maneuver. For hikers, canoeists, bird watchers, hunters,
and other outdoor enthusiasts, it is nothing short of spectacular,
a variety of state officials and private environmental groups said
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups had feared that the Champion lands would be
subdivided for housing or intensively logged. But now the land will
be bought by the Conservation Fund, a private group in Virginia
that acts as a middleman in transactions that preserve land with
significant environmental or historic values.
</P>
<P>
   The governors of New York and Vermont said that the
land-preservation deal was the largest in their states' histories.
And the Conservation Fund says that it did not know of a larger
pricetag for a preservation effort involving governments and
private investors in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   At a complicated closing, expected to be held in the spring, the
title for various tracts would immediately be transferred to a
variety of purchasers ranging from the state governments to private
investors, said Jack Lynn, a spokesman for the Conservation Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, the three states would buy fragile river
corridors and woodlands brimming with threatened wildlife, while
private investors would buy the remaining forested land for
logging.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here, Gov. George Pataki of New York said
the deal was an ideal meshing of public and private interests, with
thousands of acres preserved and other land opened to the public
for recreation while still generating logging jobs and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody comes out ahead,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   The twin threats of intensive logging and development have
imperiled a broad swath of woodlands from northern New York to
Maine in recent years, according to a variety of private and
government studies. Champion said that this spring, it had more
than 40 potential bidders for the parcel, including companies that
would have subdivided the land.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Noonan, chairman of the Conservation Fund, said that the
unorthodox deal, involving state governments, private investors,
and foundations, was needed to raise enough money to compete in the
intensifying market for forest lands.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, under pressure from shareholders, paper
and timber companies have been selling off enormous tracts, with
905,000 acres of forest land in central Maine sold for $180 million
by a South African company in October. Altogether, Maine has seen
more than 2 million acres of land sold this year, with less than
2,000 acres targeted for preservation, Noonan said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
