<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1844 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWEETER-HOME-BOS &LR;      12-09 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWEETER-HOME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWEETER LOOKS NATIONWIDE WITH PURCHASE OF HOME ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing to expand outside its New England home base, Tweeter
Home Entertainment Group said Wednesday it plans to acquire Home
Entertainment Inc., a Houston-based chain of seven consumer
electronics stores, for about $8.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is Tweeter's third in two years, its first since
becoming a publicly traded company this summer, and part of a
strategy to transform Tweeter into a national retailer focused on
mid- to high-end audio and video equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by the demise of Lechmere and the recent invasion of
its home turf by Best Buy Co., Tweeter has nearly quadrupled
revenues in the last few years, largely by acquisition. In 1996,
Tweeter bought Bryn Mawr Stereo &AMP; Video in suburban Philadelphia,
and last year it added HiFi Buys in Atlanta. Sales now total $232.3
million, up from about $60 million in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to become a national specialty chain,'' said
Jeffrey Stone, president of the Canton, Mass. company.
</P>
<P>
   Tweeter, whose local stores do business under the Tweeter etc.
nameplate, keeps the names of the chains it buys. The president of
Home Entertainment will join Tweeter. The Texas chain has annual
sales of $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Giants such as Circuit City and Best Buy may battle each other
for the customer who wants the lowest prices for TVs and audio
equipment, but Tweeter claims there's a profitable niche for a
chain that caters to customers who want better service and the
superior quality of mid- and high-range product lines.
</P>
<P>
   And with new digital technology coming onto the scene, Tweeter
believes its well-trained staff has an edge over larger rivals as
consumers begin to buy digital-video-disk players, digital
camcorders, and high-definition televisions.
</P>
<P>
   Said Stone: ``When there's confusion about new products, who do
consumers go to? The store with the best reputation for service.
Confusion benefits us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tweeter claims to own the early adapter _ the affluent customer
who has to be the first on the block to buy a satellite dish or
big-screen TV. Tweeter also claims to attract customers who buy
gear bit by bit _ a subwoofer one year, a DVD player the next _ as
they gradually assemble a home-theater system.
</P>
<P>
   New products and a booming economy finally seem to be lifting an
industry that struggled in the mid 1990s. With no new products to
spur sales, prices for items such as TVs and VCRs plummeted, and
one result was a shakeout in the consumer electronics industry.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dain Rauscher Wessels analyst George F. Sutton,
more than a thousand stores closed between 1995 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But with chains such as Lechmere, the Incredible Universe, and
Nobody Beats the Wiz either shutting down or retrenching, survivors
now see opportunities in a $22 billion industry for audio and video
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   A strong economy means many pricey new homes now include media
rooms for home-theater systems, and that plays ``directly into
Tweeter's strengths,'' Sutton noted in a recent report.
</P>
<P>
   And while Best Buy and Circuit City may dominate the low end of
the market, Tweeter is ``the only known consolidator of the
high-end consumer electronics channel,'' Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   According to legend, founder Sandy Bloomberg opened the first
Tweeter in 1972 because ``it was a good way to meet girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg was not alone in launching a regional chain. With the
advent of stereo sound, a heyday in rock-and-roll, and then-young
baby boomers eager to buy Beatles records and fancy stereos to play
them on, the 1960s and early 1970s saw a host of small
entrepreneurs go into the consumer electronics business.
</P>
<P>
   As the founders of these chains approach their 60th birthday,
many are looking for an exit strategy, and an acquisition offer
from Tweeter is a good way to cash out their investment, said
Joseph McGuire, Tweeter's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg and Stone hit upon this strategy in the mid-1990s
after they concluded there wasn't much room to expand in New
England, a mature market with little population growth.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the pair turned to venture capitalists to finance
acquisitions in areas of the country growing more rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   To retire debt from these acquisitions, Tweeter became a public
company this summer. A $30 million credit facility from BankBoston
adds to Tweeter's warchest for future acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   One reason why PaineWebber analyst Aram Rubinson has a ``buy''
rating on Tweeter is that its concept of competing against giants
has been battle-tested.
</P>
<P>
   Tweeter has been able to ``duplicate its niche in three distinct
markets,'' said Rubinson, referring to Boston, Philadelphia, and
Atlanta. ``Tweeter's niche has stood the test of time and
geography.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it's a good bet that Tweeter can achieve its goal
of becoming a national retailer by piecing together regional chains
that sell mid- to high-end merchandise, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And because it focuses on the higher-end, profit margins are
less likely to suffer in the price wars that sometimes flare up
between discount chains, Rubinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Tweeter claims to have another strength: It focuses only on
audio and video equipment. Though Best Buy and Circuit City dwarfed
Tweeter with annual sales of about $8 billion each last year, the
two giants sell a far broader range of products, including personal
computers, appliances, and music CDs.
</P>
<P>
   In Best Buy's case, there's only about a 20 percent overlap in
products, and because Tweeter buys merchandise through a
cooperative of regional chains, its prices are competitive when all
three chains stock the same item, Stone claims.
</P>
<P>
   Tweeter is opening only about two stores a year in New England,
but its acquisition plans are more ambitious. In Texas, Tweeter
thinks Home Entertainment can quickly grow into a 25-store chain
with locations in Houston, Dallas, and Austin. Each new store
represents an $850,000 investment and looks to generate sales of $3
million to $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole strategy of site selection is to be between a
Circuit City and a Best Buy,'' Stone said. ``We want to be right in
the path of the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   On purchases of big-ticket items such as DVD players, consumers
carefully check prices and the levels of service that retailers
offer, he said. Tweeter thrives when it locates stores near rivals,
and customers shuttle back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, many chains selling consumer electronics seem to
be thriving, thanks to the economy and new products. Both Best Buy
and Circuit City have recently reported sales gains.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Sept. 30, Tweeter said revenue rose 22.3
percent to $53.5 million. Sales at stores open at least a year rose
15.3 percent. Profits before charges were $1.08 million, compared
with a loss of $459,000 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   When Tweeter went public in July, the opening price of its stock
was 17 a share. On Nasdaq Wednesday, shares rose 1 3/8 to close at
24. Tweeter's transaction was announced after US markets closed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
