<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANGUAGE PARSING AND MORE ON JAVA AT MICROSOFT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVE LOHR and JOEL BRINKLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Microsoft trial focused Wednesday on an
esoteric issue that is crucial to the outcome of the antitrust
case: What is a computer operating system?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is important because the government contends that
Microsoft Corp. illegally tied its software for browsing the World
Wide Web to its industry-standard Windows operating system to
stifle competition in the Internet software market. Microsoft says
its browser is not a separate product unfairly tied to Windows but
merely a feature of its operating system.
</P>
<P>
   For hours, Steven Holley, a Microsoft lawyer, battered away at
the government's expert witness, David Farber, a computer science
professor at the University of Pennsylvania, asking him arcane
questions about fine distinctions in programming files.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the questioning was intended to try to get Farber to
concede that drawing a neat, sharp line separating the operating
system _ which controls a computer's basic operations _ from other
software was tricky, if not impossible.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Farber held his own, batting away the
challenges to the central tenet of his testimony, which was that
there is no obvious technical or user benefit to integrating the
operating system and the browser as Microsoft did.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft apparently has had its own difficulties in defining
just what an operating system is. The government offered into
evidence a dictionary of computer terminology published last year
by Microsoft. The entry for operating systems makes no mention of
Internet software or anything related to it. And the definition for
a Web browser seems squarely at odds with Microsoft's courtroom
contention that its Internet Explorer browser is an inextricable
element of Windows rather than a separate software product, or
application.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft dictionary states that a Web browser is an
``application that allows users'' to navigate the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And Microsoft, it seems, had some trouble finding a
distinguished expert witness to agree entirely with its view of the
operating system and the browser. In September, when Microsoft
initially named its 12 witnesses, the list included Michael
Dertouzos, director of the computer-science laboratory at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. He was listed as Microsoft's
technical expert.
</P>
<P>
   But Dertouzos was soon dropped from the Microsoft witness list
after giving a deposition in the case, part of which was entered
into evidence Wednesday. When asked, ``Is a browser an
application?'' Dertouzos responded, ``Historically and today, it is
the case that browsers are treated as applications.''
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, James Gosling, an executive for Sun
Microsystems Inc., whose cross-examination began last week, took
the stand again. With sharp questions and the introduction of
e-mail evidence, the Microsoft legal team attacked the government's
allegation that Microsoft unfairly tried to ``pollute'' Java, an
Internet programming language developed by Sun, because Microsoft
viewed the new technology as a threat to its dominance of the
personal computer software market.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Microsoft tried to portray its own work with Java,
which it licensed from Sun in 1996, as an effort to make the new
Internet programming language work smoothly with Microsoft's
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft introduced an e-mail sent on Aug. 31, 1995, by
Gosling, one of Java's creators, to Scott McNealy, Sun's chairman,
sketching out a number of options on how to exploit Java as a
business. One option, he wrote, was to use Java to ``go after
Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   But later he wrote: ``I wouldn't `go after' Microsoft. I'd want
to work with them, but beat them at their own game ... or at least
give them the illusion of working with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Accusing Sun of dealing with its rival in bad faith, Thomas
Burt, a Microsoft lawyer, asked, ``Isn't that exactly what you
did?''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also introduced e-mail from Sun to its closely aligned
Java partners, led by Netscape Communications Corp. and IBM, which
are also archrivals of Microsoft, to establish industry working
groups to develop Java software. Microsoft, Burt noted pointedly,
was left off those groups.
</P>
<P>
   In the antitrust case and in a private suit in California,
Microsoft is accused of deliberately making its version of Java
incompatible with Sun's standard Java. Burt insisted that the split
was Sun's fault. ``Isn't it true that Sun had no interest in making
Java work especially well with Windows?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Gosling replied that any lack of cooperation on Sun's part was a
result of Microsoft's stance that its version of Java would work
smoothly only on Windows and would not include the Sun software to
make it work on several operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we drew the line was when Microsoft's work blocked out
other software platforms,'' Gosling said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 2132EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1855 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREST-LAND-SALE-ART-     12-09 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREST-LAND-SALE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ALBANY, N.Y.: Noonan said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Another 500,000 acres in Alabama just went on the market _ all
cash, no contingency bids,'' he said. ``We don't have that kind of
money in the conservation world.'' With the Champion lands, he
said, ``we had to try to make a stand, to find a new way, to cobble
together the various interest groups in three states.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of conservation and recreation groups said the
deal represented the future of land preservation efforts, by
creating a blend of state-held preserves in the most fragile,
unspoiled areas, surrounded by private lands with easements
guaranteeing public access and environmentally sound tree
harvesting methods.
</P>
<P>
   In New York's Adirondack Park, the deal would add 29,000 acres _
about the area of the island of Manhattan _ to protected
state-owned forest preserves. Another 110,000 acres of land would
be bought by a private investing group for timber harvesting, but
opened to the public for recreation.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, New York state has committed to paying $24.9 million
for the 29,000 acres and for an easement controlling the uses of
the private land, Pataki said. The money will come from the 1996
Clean Water/Clean Air Bond Act.
</P>
<P>
   Once the sale is complete, Vermont will see 133,000 acres
preserved, with somewhere between 39,000 and 48,000 acres of that
land eventually protected as publicly owned preserves, depending on
final negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Howard Dean of Vermont said of the deal, ``We've done
30,000 acres, 33 miles along the Connecticut River, but this by far
dwarfs all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the national land conservation group to link the
interests of the states, the project could not have succeeded, he
said. ``If the Conservation Fund hadn't stepped in,'' he said,
``all this land would've been subdivided and turned into game farms
and things of that sort and the public would have lost access.''
</P>
<P>
   The land, in the state's northeast corner, includes the complete
shorelines of 15 lakes and ponds and 33 miles of frontage on the
Nulhegan River, a major headwater of the Connecticut River, said
Nancy Bell, the Vermont representative of the Conservation Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Vermont land would be sold by the Conservation
Fund to private investors who agree not to develop housing and
conduct only environmentally sensitive logging, more so than what
had been done in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The sale also includes 18,000 acres in New Hampshire, including
28 miles of land along more than a half dozen woodland streams.
Specific details of this deal are still being ironed out.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An essential element of the deal was the involvement of The
Forestland Group, a private investing group that specializes in
buying and managing forest stands for the long term, only
harvesting as much timber as is being replaced by new growth.
</P>
<P>
   It has agreed to buy the 110,000 acres of Champion's commercial
timber land inside the boundaries of the Adirondack Park, along
with some nearby acreage, with the understanding that New York
state will hold an easement that guarantees public access and
restricts logging to methods that preserve the forest.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 acres in conservation easements are already in
place in New York, but those are focused mainly on preventing the
subdivision for building homes, said Timothy Burke, the executive
director of the Adirondack Council, a private group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sets a precedent by dealing with forest management,'' he
said. ``There will be no clearcutting.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke, who was previously a commissioner of environmental
protection for Vermont, said that residents of the Adirondacks and
Vermont shared a deep suspicion of sales of land or land rights to
the state. But by keeping most of the property in private hands, he
said, this agreement would help allay concerns.
</P>
<P>
   When the patchwork of Champion-owned lands went on the market as
a single block last year, environmental groups and state
environmental officials found themselves scrambling to compete with
foreign investors and large paper and logging companies.
</P>
<P>
   The effort was complicated by the fact that the parcels were in
three states, while Champion preferred to sell all the land to a
single buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few months, the Conservation Fund pulled together
a combination of state commitments of money, private investors, and
grants from philanthropic foundations that was big enough to cover
most of the $76.2 million cost.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, in an interview, said that the deal shared qualities
with some of the complicated transactions in professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a three-way trade in baseball, where you need a
third baseman and the team that wants your player has a pitcher,''
he said. ``It's much more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, sometimes the results are much more rewarding.
``I can't wait to get up there,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of private recreation and conservation groups in the
Adirondacks said the deal would open rivers to the public that had
been in private hands for more than 100 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
