<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX GM SAYS `CHICKEN LITTLES' NEED NOT WORRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette used the occasion
of introducing his newest acquisition, 36-year-old pitcher Mark
Portugal, to decry the ``Chicken Littles who say the sky is
falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette, who has endured harsh criticism for letting Mo Vaughn
depart without replacing him, insisted that the team can still
thrive without the slugging first baseman, who took his 40 home
runs, 115 RBIs, and .337 batting average to the Anaheim Angels. The
Red Sox attempted to sign free agent Bernie Williams but were
rebuffed when he elected to return to the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is we are returning the core of our team with
the exception of Vaughn,'' Duquette said Wednesday at Fenway Park's
600 Club, where Portugal waited patiently to answer questions while
the GM was surrounded by TV cameras and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our good defense back, we have a good pitching staff,
and now it's a matter of replacing Vaughn's power,'' Duquette
added. ``That is substantial, but we're confident we can put
somebody out there who is professional and can do a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said the Red Sox already have replaced Vaughn's on-base
capacity with free agent Jose Offerman, whom he continues to
describe as one of the best offensive players in the American
League. ``Our fans are going to like this kid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is a matter of locating another power source, and though
40-homer hitters are not in abundant supply, Duquette did not sound
terribly concerned. He said clubs that cannot afford to have a high
payroll may be willing to part with a proven hitter for prospects.
The bottom-of-the-economic-barrel Montreal Expos would seem to fit
that profile, but Duquette said he doesn't expect outfielder
Rondell White to be available and insists he has never had
discussions with Montreal regarding White.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed the suggestion that the Red Sox would rescind their
decision to raise ticket prices 15 percent because they haven't
signed a high-profile player to replace Vaughn. ``It's an exciting
team,'' he said. ``You can't go anywhere else and see Nomar
Garciaparra play every day. You can't go anywhere else and see
Pedro Martinez or the Rolaids man (Tom Gordon, who was the league's
top reliever under a ratings system sponsored by the antacid
maker).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of Chicken Littles who say the sky is falling,
but we've got the core of our team back. You're going to see a
competitive team.''
</P>
<P>
   With the winter meetings opening this weekend in Nashville,
Duquette said pitching remains a priority, even after the addition
of veteran righthander Portugal, who last season went 10-5 with a
4.44 ERA for the Phillies after missing six weeks with a knee
injury and figures to be the No. 4 starter behind Martinez, Bret
Saberhagen, and Tim Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he would like to add both starters and relievers.
But he said the club would not pursue free agent prize Kevin Brown
because it refuses to offer the 34-year-old pitcher the six-year
deal his agent, Scott Boras, said he is seeking. The club made an
offer last week to Toronto for Roger Clemens, Duquette said, but
``we're not encouraged by what we've heard back from Toronto. We
think they'll go in another direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks with Toronto never progressed to the point where the Blue
Jays asked the Sox to improve their offer, Duquette said, and it's
highly doubtful Clemens would have consented to return here,
especially in the wake of Vaughn's departure.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said if the team makes a trade in Nashville, he
probably will deal prospects, not big leaguers. ``I'm not putting
all these guys on the market,'' he said. ``I'm not putting all
these guys out there. We're not looking to take away two to add
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette had high praise for Double A outfielder Dernell Stenson
and acknowledged the club might look at him at first base next
spring. Wilton Veras, who played third base at Trenton last season,
may also get a look at first, though Duquette acknowledged both
players probably require more seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   While saying the Red Sox were ``very aggressive'' in their
pursuit of Williams, Duquette said that was not the case with other
free agent hitters. He never made an offer to Albert Belle, he
said, though he would not say whether that was because Belle was
seeking no-trade protection, which the Red Sox do not offer. He
made an offer to first baseman Rafael Palmeiro but dropped out when
other teams offered five-year deals, including the Rangers, who
signed him. No offer was made to Will Clark, who signed with the
Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's departure, Duquette reiterated, is not insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still talking about some excellent offensive players,''
he said. ``You need a number of good hitters in the lineup. One
hitter is not going to make or break your lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   That position is contrary to the opinion voiced by numerous Sox
players _ Garciaparra, Mike Stanley, John Valentin, Martinez _ that
Vaughn was an indispensable part of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't open until April 1 (actually 5),'' Duquette said. ``I
wouldn't be too concerned right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, who lives in Barrington, R.I., is a big Providence
College fan, and brought sons Derek and Jacob with him to the press
conference, agreed to a one-year deal for $2.7 million. The club
holds a $3.3 million option for 2000, with a $300,000 buyout that
guarantees Portugal $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal missed nearly all of the 1997 season after undergoing
surgery to reattach the flexor muscles to his right elbow and made
just one start in 1998 before missing six weeks because of
arthroscopic surgery on his right knee. He also had surgery on his
left knee in '97, and the Phillies thought him too much of a health
risk to exercise a $2.75 million club option for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging he was disappointed the Phillies cut him
loose, Portugal insisted he's not worried about his physical
condition. He went 7-3 with a 3.69 ERA after the All-Star break
last season and pitched at least seven innings in eight of his last
16 starts, including two complete games. He also beat the Red Sox,
3-2, last June in Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' he said. ``I don't have the little things
piling up. My arm feels good. My legs feel good. I'm looking
forward to getting back out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal has been on the DL 10 times in a big league career that
began in 1985 with the Twins and has continued with the Astros,
Giants, Reds, and Phillies. ``I've broken everything,'' he said
with a laugh. ``There's nothing left to fix.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
