<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton's best hope in House vote is GOP moderates
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Impeachment proceedings against President Clinton
entered a dramatic new phase Wednesday as Republicans, unmoved by
the White House defense of the president, unveiled a strongly
worded draft of four articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, pushed a resolution of censure, a less
harsh alternative to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The competing proposals to punish Clinton overshadowed two
carefully choreographed days of testimony before the House
Judiciary Committee from administration lawyers and a dozen
scholars, lawyers and politicians who oppose impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But the target audience of both sides in the historic debate is
not the committee, where an impeachment vote is considered a
foregone conclusion, but the 20 to 30 undecided, mainly moderate
Republicans in the House whose votes could tip the balance either
for or against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican and Democratic proposals dwelt exclusively on
Clinton's sexual relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky and his efforts to conceal it.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the four proposed articles of impeachment charge Clinton
with perjury, one in his grand jury testimony in August and the
other in his January deposition in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A third count accuses the president of obstructing justice by
encouraging Lewinsky to submit a false affidavit and testify
untruthfully, among other actions.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth article claims the president abused his powers when
he ``frivolously asserted executive privilege'' to fight
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the Judiciary panel hammered away at Clinton's
defenders throughout the day Wednesday, repeatedly citing as lies
the president's denials of a sexual relationship with Lewinsky and
his inability to recall being alone with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe when the president gave those answers, he was
lying,'' said Rep. Charles Canady (R-Fla.).
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the committee were not much kinder in their call
for Clinton's censure by Congress. Their proposal accuses the
president of violating Americans' trust and dishonoring his office
in his affair with Lewinsky, ``a subordinate,'' and in the
subsequent cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' resolution would not impose a fine, but it would
require Clinton's signature. It also points out that Clinton could
be subject to criminal prosecution when he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is expected to approve at least one of
the perjury articles of impeachment. Votes could come by week's
end, said committee Chairman Henry Hyde, an Illinois Republican.
</P>
<P>
   In that event, the full House would convene next week for only
the second time in U.S. history to consider impeaching a president.
Andrew Johnson is the only president to be impeached, and he
survived an 1868 trial in the Senate by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon resigned the presidency in August 1974 after the
Judiciary Committee adopted three articles of impeachment against
him.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich would be the leader to summon the
435 members of the House to Washington, but neither Gingrich nor
his presumptive successor, Robert Livingston of Louisiana, is
expected to preside.
</P>
<P>
   That chore would be handled by Rep. Ray LaHood (R-Ill.), a
second-term member with a reputation for fairness and experience in
presiding over controversial debates.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich and Hyde cautioned members to withhold judgment. ``The
committee deserves the respect of the House, and the House should
see the committee's work before rushing to judgment,'' Gingrich
told reporters outside the committee's hearing room.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker, however, said he would most likely be voting with
Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the proposed bill of particulars against Clinton
diverted attention from White House counsel Charles Ruff, who
wrapped up the White House's presentation to the committee by
calling Clinton's actions ``morally reprehensible,'' but not
impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff, the last Watergate special prosecutor a generation ago,
came closest of any administration official to conceding that the
president may have lied, not merely misled, in the Jones
deposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reasonable people ... could determine that he crossed over
that line and that what for him was truthful but misleading or
nonresponsive and misleading or evasive was, in fact, false,'' Ruff
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the attorney stuck to the White House insistence that
Clinton did not commit perjury since he believed he was telling the
truth, and intent is an element of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   With presidential friend and counselor Bruce Lindsey and Clinton
lawyer David Kendall in the row behind him, Ruff acknowledged that
Clinton would be subject to possible prosecution, promising the
president would not accept a pardon from his successor.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the administration's bid to derail impeachment, Ruff
said, ``We are open to any reasonable suggestion from any side as a
way of finding an end to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats believe that some Republicans in the House would
vote against impeachment if they are given the opportunity to
rebuke Clinton through a resolution of censure.
</P>
<P>
   The panel of witnesses that preceded Ruff's testimony included a
moderate Republican, former Massachusetts Gov. William Weld, who
made it clear that he thinks the case against Clinton is ``thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Weld, a former Justice Department official himself, echoed the
other former prosecutors on his panel when he said he did not
believe adultery or making a false statement about adultery or
fornication constituted a ``high crime or misdemeanor'' as defined
by the framers of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Weld added a novel approach to sanctioning Clinton, combining
censure with a written report of Clinton's wrongdoing and a fine.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said Wednesday he would allow committee Democrats to offer
such a censure resolution. But the House leadership has as yet
given no indication of what it will do.
</P>
<P>
   Most committee Republicans reject censure as an indecisive, if
not unconstitutional, way out. ``At this point, I think the
appropriate action is to impeach him or not to impeach him,'' said
Rep. Steve Chabot (R-Ohio).
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats said they were pleased by the two days of
testimony, Florida Democratic Rep. Robert Wexler called Wednesday
``the saddest day in my life'' following the release of the
Republicans' draft impeachment articles.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
