<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Davis flap: Mac 1, Sampras 0
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pete Sampras should just say he doesn't want to play
Davis Cup and leave it at that. Instead, he made a couple of
unforced errors last week trying to justify his decision not to
play this year or to commit to the U.S. team for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' most persistent critic has been John McEnroe, whose 9-1
singles record in Davis Cup finals is the U.S. record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy for McEnroe to criticize,'' Sampras said, ``because
he was only playing 13, 14 events (per year). I'm playing 22
events, so it's a different ballgame. I think these guys should get
their facts straight before they pop off.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon further review, it's Sampras who didn't do his homework. In
McEnroe's best six-year run (1979-84), he played 518 singles
matches, 19 more than Sampras has played during his current streak
of six consecutive years at No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe's six-year singles record (456-62, .880) is superior to
Sampras' (415-84, .832). McEnroe was ranked No. 1 in four of those
years and captured seven Grand Slam singles titles while playing
for three winning U.S. Davis Cup teams.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has won 10 Grand Slam singles titles the past six years
but has played for just one U.S. team that won a Davis Cup (1995).
</P>
<P>
   Also worth noting is that McEnroe added to his workload by
winning seven Grand Slam doubles titles from 1979 to '84. Sampras
has only two pro doubles titles of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not knocking Pete, but just sit back for a minute and have
a look at the two records,'' said International Tennis Federation
president Brian Tobin, who used former Aussie great Roy Emerson in
the comparison. ``Pete has 11 Grand Slams and two Davis Cups (and
didn't play in the final of one of those). Emerson has (a record)
12 Grand Slams and eight Davis Cup final wins on his record. So how
would you compare the two?''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras also argued that it's not feasible to be No. 1 today and
play Davis Cup full time. ``If I play Davis Cup,'' he said, ``my
ranking goes to No. 4 or 5 in the world. You can't have
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   By that logic, though, Jonas Bjorkman could've been the tour's
best player last year. He finished No. 4 despite playing singles
and doubles in three rounds of Davis Cup for winning Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis Cup debate stirred again when last week's final, won
by Sweden over Italy in Milan, became the first played without a
player ranked in the world's top 30. The U.S. was without a top-25
player in its embarrassing 4-1 loss to Italy in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Tobin said the ITF, which runs Davis Cup, is
considering changes to ensure better Davis Cup participation. His
ideas include reducing early-round ties to a best-of-three-sets
format, giving the previous year's finalists a first-round bye and
awarding ATP Tour points to players for their victories.
</P>
<P>
   COMPARING ERAS
</P>
<P>
   The McEnroe era
</P>
<P>
   Year W-L Pct. Matches Ranking Slams
</P>
<P>
   1979 87-12 .879 99 3 1
</P>
<P>
   1980 79-17 .823 96 2 1
</P>
<P>
   1981 74-10 .881 84 1 2
</P>
<P>
   1982 71-9 .888 80 1 0
</P>
<P>
   1983 63-11 .851 74 1 1
</P>
<P>
   1984 82-3 .965 85 1 2
</P>
<P>
   Total 456-62 .880 518 _ 7
</P>
<P>
   The Sampras era
</P>
<P>
   1993 61-17 .782 78 1 2
</P>
<P>
   1994 55-12 .821 67 1 2
</P>
<P>
   1995 65-11 .855 76 1 2
</P>
<P>
   1996 72-16 .818 88 1 1
</P>
<P>
   1997 77-12 .865 89 1 2
</P>
<P>
   1998 85-16 .842 101 1 1
</P>
<P>
   Total 415-84 .832 499 _ 10
</P>
