<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Advantage to Vikings in home-field battle
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Falcons have already clinched a playoff berth and
assured themselves of their first home game in the postseason since
the 1980 season. But the odds are long against them wrestlng
overall home-field advantage from the Minnesota Vikings, and a loss
Sunday would be doubly costly _ both in the race for home-field
advantage and for the NFC West title.
</P>
<P>
   If Minnesota (12-1) and Atlanta (11-2) end up with the same
record, the Vikings currently have a huge advantage in the
tiebreaker that would most likely come into play.
</P>
<P>
   The first tiebreaker is head-to-head competition, which doesn't
apply. The second is won-loss percentage within the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings, who have games remaining at Baltimore, home against
Jacksonville and at Tennessee, finished their NFC games with a
record of 11-1.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is 9-1 in the NFC, with a game Sunday at NFC West rival
New Orleans and Dec. 20 at Detroit (where the Lions have beaten
Atlanta five straight times).
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta must win those games to finish 11-1 in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons do that, and also finish with the same overall
record as Minnesota, the third tiebreaker is won-lost percentage in
common games.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota was 6-0 against St. Louis, Detroit, Chicago and New
Orleans. If the Falcons beat New Orleans and Detroit, they would
would be 6-0 as well.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth tiebreaker is net points _ or the difference in
points scored vs. points allowed _ in NFC games.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings, who are on a pace to break the NFL's single-season
scoring record, outscored their 12 NFC opponents by 179 points.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has outscored 10 NFC opponents by 101 points.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Falcons would have to win their next two games by
a combined 79 points to win this tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   If Atlanta loses Sunday, and the Vikings win, Minnesota will
lock up overall home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for the NFC West title, the Falcons and 49ers (10-3)
split their two games this season, eliminating the first
tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   The next tiebreaker is record within the division, where both
teams are 6-1. The Falcons' final division game is Sunday. The
49ers' last division game is against St. Louis the final weekend of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   The third tiebreaker is record in the NFC, where Atlanta is 9-1
and the 49ers are 8-2.
</P>
<P>
   A Falcons loss at New Orleans would give San Francisco a
tiebreaker edge, provided the 49ers beat the Rams, which they have
done 16 straight times.
</P>
<P>
   But if Atlanta wins Sunday, and San Francisco loses to Detroit,
the Falcons will lock up the NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons also could lock up the division by winning their
next two games.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Lester Archambeau did not practice Wednesday, as
the Falcons did not work out in pads, but he's scheduled to
practice today for the first time since breaking his left thumb in
Sunday's 28-21 win over the Colts. Archambeau, who had surgery
Sunday night to insert pins in the thumb, will wear a cast and test
it today. If Archambeau can't play, John Burrough will replace him.
... Wide receiver Tim Dwight suffered either a cramp or a strained
hamstring in the middle of practice. The Falcons' punt and kickoff
returner did not practice again, and his status for today is
unknown. ... Reserve cornerback Randy Fuller, who missed the Colts
game with a strained/bruised shoulder, returned to practice and is
expected to play Sunday. ... For the Saints, middle linebacker
Kevin Mitchell (knee) is out, replaced by rookie Chris Bordano, the
team's sixth-round draft choice from Southern Methodist. ...
Reserve linebacker Vinson Smith (knee) is questionable. ... Reserve
linebacker Ink Aleaga (hamstring), tight end Scott Slutzker (knee),
defensive tackle Wayne Martin (knee) and reserve tight end Tony
Johnson (groin) are all probable.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson update
</P>
<P>
   James Sims, the agent for running back Jamal Anderson, continues
to talk with Atlanta general manager Harold Richardson about a
contract extension, using the contracts of Terrell Davis, Barry
Sanders, Emmitt Smith, Robert Smith, Dorsey Levens and Curtis
Martin as a framework.
</P>
<P>
   Those contracts average 6.3 years and $5.3 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons reach a deal before the end of this season, they
could lessen the impact on future salary caps by spreading the
pro-rated portion of a signing bonus over this year and future
years. ``If it's feasible, yeah (the deal could get done soon), but
we're not going to rush this thing,'' Sims said. ``This is going to
be a significant deal, and significant deals don't get done in a
hurry. We're going to see how far Jamal can push this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ticket talk
</P>
<P>
   Falcons ticket manager Jack Ragsdale said about 5,500 of the
team's 6,900 or so season ticket ``accounts'' have reserved playoff
tickets. Those 6,900 accounts add up to 29,715 season tickets, but
Ragsdale said it's too early to say how many playoff tickets have
been reserved. Current season ticket holders are allowed to reserve
twice the number of tickets they have.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the team has taken down payments on about 1,500 new
season ticket packages for next year, with fans making those down
payments guaranteed playoff tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Remaining playoff tickets are tentatively scheduled to go on
sale to the general public Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Gaining ground
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have won nine of their last 10 games in the NFC
West. If they beat the Saints, it will give them a 7-1 mark in the
division. The team has gone through the division with one loss just
twice before, going 5-1 in 1980 (division champions) and '91 (wild
card).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
