</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    36-point buck may be a record
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell and Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A young Telfair County farmer might have taken a new
state record buck on Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-point buck taken by Billy Joe Padgett, 23, of
Jacksonville, Ga., could score as much as 240 points on the Boone &AMP;
Crockett scoring system for game animals under the nontypical
heading. The deer was approximately 5 years old and had a gross
weight of 170 pounds, not bad for a normal eight-pointer, but it
seemed small under the massive rack.
</P>
<P>
   State Wildlife Resources Division biologist Bill Cooper checked
out the deer, and said, ``I'd say it's going to score at least in
the 230s. It will probably be a state record in nontypical.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said the rack has to age for 60 days, so the official
measurements won't be taken until the end of January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not one of those weird, bizarre racks. It's a genuine
pretty-regular-looking rack except it's so massive. You don't see a
rack like that down here in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The deer was killed on the 9,000-acre Whiteoak Plantation
Hunting Club, co-founded by Bob Heath and Kim Adamson of Atlanta.
It is adjacent to the Horse Creek Wildlife Management Area and only
a mile from Lake Montgomery, where the world-record largemouth bass
was caught 66 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Heath said Padgett and his father, Ernest, both had taken shots
at the big buck earlier in the season and were actively hunting it.
</P>
<P>
   The club is managed for trophy deer, 15-inch spread or better,
and has a membership cap of 32.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're filled up and have a waiting list,'' said Heath.
</P>
<P>
   Former armory owner dies
</P>
<P>
   Bob Watt, former owner of Stone Mountain Armory and one of
Georgia's finest muzzleloading firearms makers and shooters, died
Monday in Columbia, Miss., of a massive heart attack. He was 62.
Watt was in the process of moving to Mississippi at the time. ``He
was something to shoot with,'' said Jack Crockford, retired
director of the Wildlife Resources Division, who also makes
muzzleloaders. ``He was so relaxed you'd think he was going to
sleep (when shooting).''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Collectors will have a busy weekend in Kennesaw on Saturday and
Sunday at the Vintage Arms Show. Held at the Big Shanty Antique
Mall, the show features arms from before 1946 and earlier eras. For
more information, call 770-975-1128. ... The Sportsman's Deer
Cooler in Haralson sponsors a bass tournament Saturday at Lake
Jackson, launching at Kersey's Marina. Cost is $100 per boat.
Payback is 80 percent. For information, call 770-707-0094. ...
Russell Dam Drive, which leads to the dam on Lake Russell, will be
closed for repairs and maintenance all day Saturday until 8 a.m.
Sunday this weekend. There will be no public access to the dam or
fishing pier.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call the operation manager's office at
800-944-7207 or 706-213-3400.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
