<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BofA Loses Diversity Champion   By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The woman who ran the nationally recognized diversity program at
the old BankAmerica resigned after the bank's new owner, North
Carolina's NationsBank, removed her from her job.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Crane, executive vice president and director of
corporate diversity, left the bank at the end of November, two
months after NationsBank took over the San Francisco bank and
adopted its name. She was replaced by Lorraine Stimmel, previously
in charge of operations in the human resources department of the
old BofA.
</P>
<P>
   News of Crane's departure came after The Chronicle reported that
the 10 highest-ranking female executives of the old BofA were
demoted or left the bank when their jobs were given to NationsBank
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said the resignations reflected individual decisions
plus opportunities to collect big severance packages, not a pattern
of bias at the bank. The executives who stayed still have important
jobs, it noted.
</P>
<P>
   Current and former BofA employees said they didn't know why
NationsBank removed Crane from the diversity post. They said they
didn't know whether she was offered another job.
</P>
<P>
   The employees noted that Crane was an impassioned and outspoken
advocate for opening the bank to people from all backgrounds and
that her style might not have fit the more-controlled NationsBank
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was feisty. She spoke her mind, and she was direct,'' said
one former BofA executive.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Crane from BofA ``is a major loss,'' said
Michael Reed, a San Francisco diversity consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of her colleagues and subordinates feel she was critical
to BofA's assertive diversity program,'' Reed noted. ``She
championed many causes that were cutting-edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Contacted by telephone, Crane declined comment on her
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Melba Spencer, a BofA spokeswoman, said the bank doesn't comment
on the departure of specific executives. She stressed that the new
BofA remains committed to advancing employees regardless of gender,
race or sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diversity is a core part of the culture'' of the new BofA,
Spencer said. ``We are looking forward to Lorraine Stimmel's
leadership in driving our company's commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Former California Treasurer Kathleen Brown, now the bank's
co-head of services for wealthy customers in California, said in an
interview that the new bank is keeping the old BofA's
equal-opportunity tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience with the new BofA is that the values of the old
BofA are very much there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Crane joined BofA in 1979 and held a succession of increasingly
senior marketing jobs. Beginning in 1995, she took over the program
designed to make the bank a more hospitable place for women,
minorities, gays and lesbians to work.
</P>
<P>
   Her diversity training program was the largest
internal-education initiative ever carried out by the bank. Under
the program, more than 20,000 managers attended two-day sessions
aimed at sensitizing them to workplace discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Crane's program was cited in August by Fortune Magazine, which
ranked the old BofA as the third-best place to work for blacks,
Latinos and Asian Americans among the nation's largest companies.
</P>
<P>
   One BofA manager who went through Crane's two-day workshops
described it as ``pretty intense,'' particularly the role-playing
sessions in which participants acted out workplace interactions
among people of different races, genders and sexual orientations.
</P>
<P>
   Crane pushed BofA's domestic partners program, which grants
medical and other benefits to partners of bank employees, including
same-sex couples. The program has been adopted by the new bank.
</P>
<P>
   Such policies generally are seen at innovative companies in
emerging industries, such as technology, Reed said. ``You don't
tend to see these things at conservative financial institutions,''
he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Senator Barbara Boxer wrote BankAmerica Chairman and
chief executive Hugh McColl on Monday urging him to reach
agreements with activist groups setting targets for community
lending and investment in California.
</P>
<P>
   In her letter, Boxer said she was troubled by the resignation of
David Coulter, chief executive of the old BofA, and by recent
resignations of senior female executives.
</P>
<P>
   McColl has promised to meet with California political leaders
next month when he visits the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
