<HEADER>
A1872 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOUSE-SFCHRON &LR;      12-09 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOUSE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Celebrating a Mouse That Revolutionized the World  &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
It's December 1968. Lyndon Johnson is president, the Grateful Dead
is performing at Winterland and computers are giant
number-crunching machines that use punch cards. During a conference
in San Francisco, an unassuming computer scientist named Doug
Engelbart demonstrates an invention called the mouse _ and changes
the face of computing.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse and other innovations Engelbart showed off, such as
word processing and hyperlinking as a way of moving from document
to document, wound up transforming computers and making them
accessble to the average person.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, on the 30th anniversary of Engelbart's demo, dozens
of computer-industry luminaries gathered at Stanford University to
celebrate the 73-year-old inventor and to ponder what the next 30
years might bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``This demonstration set a brushfire burning that spread across
the computing landscape,'' said Paul Saffo, a longtime technology
forecaster and director of the Institute for the Future in Palo
Alto. ``It was a mind-opening demonstration of possibilities that
had not occurred to the computing establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   What the researchers saw in 1968 was a new vision of computing.
Instead of big machines accessible only to technicians and used
only for business automation, Engelbart and his team at Stanford
Research Institute wanted to create a network of computers for
people to use to solve the world's problems.
</P>
<P>
   During the 90-minute demonstration using a custom-built
workstation _ there was no Fry's in those days _ they showed off
the graphical user interface, integrated text and graphics and
two-way video conferencing.
</P>
<P>
   Their work and the demo inspired many of those who went on to
build the systems we use today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a mind set that computers were for adding and
subtracting. The idea that computers would be developed to interact
with humans was unthinkable. It was a radical shift in what we
thought computers were for,'' said Charles Irby, who went to work
with Engelbart in the early 1970s on the networked computer system
called Augment.
</P>
<P>
   Engelbart's group lost its funding in the 1970s, which prompted
many of its researchers to migrate to Xerox Palo Alto Research
Center (PARC) and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Irby later co-designed the Xerox Star, the first commercially
available personal computer. Like an earlier model, the Xerox Alto,
the Star incorporated Engelbart's innovations of a mouse for
navigation and a graphical user interface.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Kay was a graduate student at the University of Utah in
1968 when, despite a fever, he flew to San Francisco to see
Engelbart's presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, he was Moses opening the Red Sea,'' said Kay. ``It
reset the idea of what it was to do personal computing. It wasn't
just a place where you went to do a few important transactions. It
was a place where you could spend all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay went on to co-found Xerox PARC, where some of the computer
industry's most important innovations were born _ among them, the
first personal computer, desktop publishing, laser printing and
Ethernet. Kay is now a Disney Fellow and vice president of research
and development at the Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Andreessen wasn't even born in 1968. But he credited
Engelbart and others with laying the groundwork for the explosion
of the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like waves on a beach, where each wave goes
further onto the beach,'' said Andreessen, who co-founded Netscape
Communications in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   As an undergraduate at the University of Illinois, Andreessen
helped create Mosaic, the friendly point-and-click method for
navigating the Web that led to the development of Netscape's
Navigator browser.
</P>
<P>
   When he first put out Mosaic in March 1993, Andreessen said,
``the building blocks were there. The PC was becoming widely
available and the network was built. The Web was able to unlock the
power that was in the network.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the speakers yesterday worried about the future of
computing _ about whether the Internet would be taken over by
commercial interests and how the increasing presence of computers
in our lives would affect personal privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the PC did was move the power to the individual. With
pervasive networking, you can move the power back. So you have
companies that can read all your e-mail. Unless we deal with that
as a social problem, it will be built into the technology,'' said
Stuart Card, a Xerox Research Fellow and manager of the User
Interface Research Group at Xerox PARC.
</P>
<P>
   As for Engelbart, he feels his job is only half-done. Although
many of the technological ideas he advanced have been widely
adopted, his idea of people using the network to improve the world
hasn't come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the world has really bought it (the idea.) For
me, it's been a totally serious goal _ the idea of collective IQ,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 2145EST &QL; 
