<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-BANKBOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI BREAKS UP ALLEGED MONEY-LAUNDERING SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The FBI arrested Wednesday an employee of BankBoston's
West Newton branch and two bank customers for participating in a
scheme involving a group of Russian emigres who sought to launder
$2.7 million in alleged drug profits.
</P>
<P>
   Oksana Galchanskaya, 24, of Needham, was among nine people from
New York and the Boston area arrested and charged in the 43-count
indictment issued by a federal grand jury in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, federal undercover agents, posing
as narcotics dealers, provided $2.7 million in cash to three
members of the group and with the assistance of Galchanskaya. In
return, the undercover agents received wire transfers, cashiers
checks and other checks drawn on accounts set up at BankBoston's
West Newton branch and at Citibank and Chase Manhattan Bank in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   According to federal officials, most if not all of the nine are
Russian emigres living in Boston and New York.
</P>
<P>
   A four-year employee of the bank, Galchanskaya worked as a
customer service representative.
</P>
<P>
   The two other defendants also charged in the case, Roman Luban
of Newton and Samuil Lyubomirsky of Brighton, opened and maintained
accounts at BankBoston that were used in the money laundering
operation, the indictment stated.
</P>
<P>
   A BankBoston spokesman said Wednesday night that the bank had
been cooperating with the FBI investigation for nearly a year and
would now begin an internal investigation into how the bank's West
Newton branch could have been used in the scheme for more than two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The integrity of BankBoston is our most important asset,''
said spokesman Bruce Spitzer. ``All of us feel disappointed, hurt
and outraged when any action appears to tarnish that integrity or
violates the public trust.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, federal undercover agents met some
of the defendants numerous times in Manhattan and in Dedham,
Allston and Taunton over the past two years. During the meetings,
the agents would exchange large amounts of cash and receive the
wire transfers, cashiers checks and checks drawn on accounts at
BankBoston and other financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Narcotics traffickers and other criminal enterprises that deal
with large amounts of cash customarily seek to have their currency
turned into checks and other financial tender that can then be
transferred through the worldwide banking system and used in
legitimate businesses. In recent years, federal and local law
enforcement officials say they have detected an increased
involvement in money laundering by criminal groups comprised of
Russian emigres.
</P>
<P>
   During the past 20 years, Congress has enacted several bills to
improve law enforcement's ability to strike at money laundering,
including legislation requiring that banks and other institutions
report all cash deposits of more than $10,000 to the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, the defendants received more than
$200,000 in commissions from the federal agents for laundering the
cash proceeds. The defendants' goal was to ``function as a
financial institution'' by accepting large amounts of cash from the
undercover agents and exchanging it for ``wire transfers and
checks,'' without filing the required cash transaction reports.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment stated that Galchanskaya accepted at least one of
the deposits, for $25,000, at BankBoston's West Newton branch in
January 1998 without making out a currency transaction report on
the deposit, as required by federal law. On that same date,
Galchanskaya issued several checks drawn on an account set up at
the bank. Those checks later were given to the undercover agents.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted on all money laundering and conspiracy charges,
each defendant faces a maximum of 20 years in prison and a fine of
$500,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
