<SLUG> BC-NLRB-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NLRB Sides With Nurses At Adventist Hospital  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A federal labor official said yesterday that nurses have the right
to organize at an Adventist-run hospital in Ukiah that had argued
that its religious character should make it exempt from U.S. labor
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Miller, regional director of the National Labor Relations
Board, ruled that Ukiah Valley Medical Center must follow the same
labor laws as other nonreligious hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a practical matter, the employer provides health care
services similar to those provided by any other acute-care
hospital,'' Miller wrote in a 31-page decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``To grant an exemption to the employer and to other
church-operated health care institutions would potentially impact a
significant segment of the workforce in the health care industry
and ... interfere with the fulfillment of the government's
compelling interest in promoting national labor peace,'' Miller
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Ukiah Valley, a 101-bed hospital owned by the Seventh-day
Adventist church, had sought exemption from federal labor laws
after 75 percent of its nurses signed cards last summer asking for
a union election.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials told the NLRB in hearings that Adventist
teachings have long prohibited church members from joining unions.
They said forcing Ukiah Valley executives to bargain with a union
would impede their ability to seek policy guidance directly from
God.
</P>
<P>
   The Ukiah Valley dispute has been watched closely by labor
organizers and management at other religious hospitals, including
Catholic hospitals facing union drives in Sacramento and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers have said it could set a national precedent on
the issue of whether religious hospitals should be required to
follow labor laws.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Ukiah Valley executives said they are likely to
appeal the NLRB ruling to the full board in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We disagree with the ruling and are sure that at some point we
will be appealing it, but we don't know what the time frame would
be,'' said CEO ValGene Devitt.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the nurses union hailed the ruling as a major victory
for workers everywhere, not just at religious hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a chilling moment in history if the
employer's objections were upheld,'' said Rose Ann DeMoro,
executive director of the California Nurses Association. ``I could
see Catholic Healthcare West claiming an exemption next, followed
by every other religious order. In fact, I could even see Bill
Gates starting to talk about his relationship with God if it would
help him deny employees their rights.''
</P>
<P>
   With about $38 million in revenues, Ukiah Valley is one of 14
hospitals in California and 159 hospitals worldwide operated by the
10-million member Seventh-day Adventist church.
</P>
<P>
   The only full-service hospital in Ukiah, it was formed when
Ukiah Adventist Hospital took over Ukiah General Hospital in 1988.
Of its 170 registered nurses, fewer than 20 are Adventists.
</P>
<P>
   Ukiah Valley's nurses launched their union organizing drive for
several reasons. Because of budget troubles, the hospital had to
cancel some planned pay raises and bonuses. And _ like nurses at
many other hospitals _ the Ukiah nurses felt that patient care has
declined because of cost-cutting measures related to the spread of
managed care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
