A1882 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CADENCE-SFCHRON &LR;      12-09 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADENCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Cadence to Buy Quickturn, Foiling Mentor Takeover  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Cadence Design Systems Inc. yesterday agreed to a $253 million deal
to buy Quickturn Design Systems Inc., which has spent the past four
months fending off a rare high-tech hostile takeover bid by rival
Mentor Graphics Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Cadence's friendly offer tops Mentor's unsolicited bid of $216
million made in August. Cadence and Quickturn, both of San Jose,
plan to close the deal in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Mentor Graphics, which had hoped to get Quickturn stockholders
to approve its offer at a special Jan. 8, 1999, meeting, did not
indicate whether the firm would increase its bid. In a brief
statement, the Wilsonville, Ore., company said it was ``reviewing''
its options and had no further comment on the Cadence offer.
</P>
<P>
   Cadence, the largest seller of advanced-design software for
chips and electronic products, plans to turn Quickturn into a
wholly owned subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Quickturn makes systems and software used by chip designers to
test their creations, an area of chip development that Cadence
wanted to offer, especially with chip designs becoming more
complicated, said Cadence CEO Jack Harding.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a technological perspective, they have a lot of things
that we need,'' Harding said.
</P>
<P>
   Harding said he started investigating the idea of a merger with
Quickturn because of Mentor's hostile takeover attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Mentor's offer of $12.16 per share of Quickturn stock ``made us
ask, `What are we missing?''' Harding said. ``We did some analysis
on our own. Once we realized what was going on, we realized, `Hey,
we needed this company.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Cadance agreed to swap one share of its stock valued at $14 per
share for each share of Quickturn stock. Mentor had offered
Quickturn shareholders $12.13 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Cadence fell 81 cents to $29.19, while Quickturn's
shares rose $1.63 to $13.81. Shares in Mentor fell $1.25 to $8.75.
</P>
<P>
   ``A merger with Cadence is a superior outcome for our
shareholders, our employees and our customers and allows Quickturn
to continue to pursue its business strategy,'' Quickturn CEO Keith
Lobo said in a statement. ``We believe our shareholders will
recognize the value of this combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Mentor Graphics won a key court ruling that
appeared to clear the way for its hostile takeover attempt of
Quickturn. A Delaware Court of Chancery judge ruled that Quickturn
directors breached their responsibilities to stockholders by
amending the company's ``poison pill'' provisions to defeat
Mentor's takeover attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Cadence announced last month that it was laying off about 560
workers, or 12 percent of its workforce, and taking a
fourth-quarter charge of $36 million to trim costs and focus on
more profitable parts of its consulting business.
</P>
<P>
   Harding said there was little overlap between Quickturn and
Cadence employees and that he expects the merger to cause few
layoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
