A1897 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MACARTHUR10-COX     12-09 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACARTHUR10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MacArthur members to pick Florida development firm
 &HT;    By Joel Engelhardt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Today in Chicago a Nobel-Prize winning
physicist, two former presidential advisers and an epidemiologist
who helped rid the world of smallpox will cast aside the vexing
questions of global population growth, environmental degradation
and nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   For a few moments, large swaths of South Florida land will be
the center of attention for the board of the John D. and Catherine
T. MacArthur Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-member board, normally focused on giving away money to
cure world ills, will turn to making money and, in so doing, shape
the future of northern Palm Beach County and the Treasure Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The board will pick between two bidders: WCI Communities, a
Bonita Springs homebuilder partly owned by the foundation; and the
St. Joe Co., the Jacksonville development company that owns 1.1
million acres, most in Florida's Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   WCI offered the highest bid, between $200 million and $240
million, sources close to the bidding said, but asked MacArthur to
provide some financing. St. Joe offered a cash deal for about 20
percent less.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will control the pace of development on 14,808 acres
in Palm Beach, Martin and St. Lucie counties. The land is all that
remains in South Florida from the holdings of the foundation's
namesake, the late insurance magnate John D. MacArthur.
</P>
<P>
   The board will base its decision on a recommendation from its
staff, a consultant and the board's investment committee, made up
of seven board members and two outsiders. The foundation refuses to
identify the investment committee's members or to comment on the
bids.
</P>
<P>
   Board members refuse to comment, as well. They follow a policy
of leaving the talking to staff, assuring the board speaks to the
grants community with one voice. Their decision may not be
announced for several days, said MacArthur attorney Josh Mintz, who
is overseeing the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Board members oversee a 20-year-old foundation with $4.3 billion
in assets, the eighth-largest in the nation, The Chronicle of
Philanthropy reported in January.
</P>
<P>
   Board meetings are a ``phenomenal'' experience, bringing
together top thinkers in their fields to grapple with health
concerns in Nigeria or discrimination in America, Mintz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being at a university. Every board meeting they're
talking about serious intractable problems. It's absolutely
facsinating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is best known for its so-called genius grants to
``exceptionally creative individuals,'' but those represent a small
proportion _ $6.5 million _ of its $150 million a year in
gift-giving.
</P>
<P>
   The board will judge the Florida land sale with the same
approach it brings to judging grants, Mintz said.
</P>
<P>
   They form a jury of remarkable peers.
</P>
<P>
   One member, Murray Gell-Mann, holds the 1969 Nobel Prize for
physics. He is a co-discoverer of the subatomic particle known as
the quark.
</P>
<P>
   Another, Dr. William Foege, led the successful campaign to
eradicate smallpox in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Two members served at the highest levels of the federal
government: Laura D'Andrea Tyson, President Clinton's former
national economic adviser, and Shirley Mount Hufstedler, President
Reagan's first secretary of education. A third, Drew Saunders Days
III, spent three years as President Clinton's solicitor general.
</P>
<P>
   Three others, steel company executive George Ranney Jr., builder
Alan Hallene and banker Thomas Theobald, ran large corporations.
Elizabeth McCormack counsels the Rockefeller family.
</P>
<P>
   Only one member, Tyson, was born after World War II (1947). Ten
are men, six are women, two are black.
</P>
<P>
   They are paid from $27,000 to $40,500 a year, depending on
expenses and committee assignments. President Adele Simmons, who
has run the foundation since 1989, received $468,729 in salary and
benefits in 1996, the most recent year available.
</P>
<P>
   Original member Paul Harvey, the ABC radio commentator known for
his staccato delivery and ``The Rest of the Story,'' voluntarily
accepts less, $2,300.
</P>
<P>
   The original board had six members, chosen by MacArthur, who
died in 1978. He picked his wife, Catherine; his son, Roderick;
three business associates; and Harvey, his longtime friend from
Chicago. Only Harvey, now 80, still serves.
</P>
<P>
   Board Chairman John Corbally arrived in 1979, with the
foundation in its infancy. A university president, he ran the
foundation until 1989, surviving Roderick MacArthur's accusations
of overspending and board misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   A committee of board members picks new members. They are limited
to three four-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   What are they looking for? ``Good thinkers and broad-minded
people,'' Mintz said.
</P>
<P>
   How is the board perceived?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is considered a very prestigious and impressive board,''
said Dorothy Ridings, president and chief executive of the Council
on Foundations in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not people who are doing this to get their name on
some expanded resume. These are people who really care.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
