<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE OPENS TODAY ON ARTICLES OF IMPEACHMENT AGAINST PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee opens a historic
debate on Thursday on articles of impeachment accusing President
Clinton of 17 counts of perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse
of power.
</P>
<P>
   A draft version released on Wednesday asserts that Clinton
``willfully corrupted and manipulated the judicial process'' to
cover up his illicit affair with Monica Lewinsky. The resolution
declares that Clinton should be removed from office for ``high
crimes and misdemeanors'' against the people of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans released the draft as Clinton's lawyers
wrapped up a two-day defense presentation that failed to slow the
impeachment drive.
</P>
<P>
   With the Judiciary Committee on a fast track to approve
impeachment articles by the end of the week, Clinton's defenders
stepped up efforts to reach a compromise that would result in a
censure of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be our last opportunity to avoid going over the
precipice and triggering a genuine constitutional crisis,'' Rep.
William Delahunt, D-Mass., said in releasing a draft resolution
condemning Clinton's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   White House counsel Charles Ruff told lawmakers that the
president is ``open to any reasonable suggestion'' that would avoid
an impeachment showdown. He also assured Republicans that Clinton
would not accept a pardon to avoid possible criminal prosecution
after his term ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for an end to this process,'' the White House
lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments to the House panel, Ruff acknowledged that
Clinton deliberately misled investigators and the American public.
He also agreed that reasonable people could conclude that the
president lied under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``His conduct, although morally reprehensible, does not warrant
impeachment, does not warrant overturning the mandate of the
American electorate,'' Ruff said. ``The president did not obstruct
justice. He did not tamper with witnesses. He did not abuse the
powers of the office.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense failed to sway Clinton's critics, who remained
convinced that the president committed a series of crimes to hide
his extramarital relationship. The panel of 21 Republicans and 16
Democrats is expected to formally recommend the president's
impeachment in a series of votes tomorrow and possibly Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The full House is expected to take up the issue next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only believe your defense if I check my common sense at
the door and I forget the way the world really works,'' said Rep.
Lindsey Graham, R-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Only two other presidents _ Andrew Johnson and Richard Nixon _
have been subjected to articles of impeachment. Nixon resigned to
avoid a House vote in 1974. Johnson was impeached by the House, but
the Senate fell one vote short of the two-thirds majority needed to
remove him from office in 1868.
</P>
<P>
   The draft resolution against Clinton alleges 17 offenses in four
articles of impeachment:
</P>
<P>
   Article 1 accuses him of lying to a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Article 2 accuses him of lying in Paula Jones' sexual harassment
lawsuit in a deposition and in an affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Article 3 accuses him of obstructing justice by lying to White
House aides, plotting to hide gifts that he had given to Lewinsky
and encouraging the former White House intern to lie about their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Article 4 accuses him of abusing his power by asserting
executive privilege against independent counsel Kenneth Starr and
by lying to the American public, to executive branch officials and
to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``In doing this, William Jefferson Clinton has undermined the
integrity of his office, has brought disrepute on the Presidency,
has betrayed his trust as President and has acted in a manner
subversive of the rule of law and justice, to the manifest injury
of the people of the United States,'' the draft resolution states.
</P>
<P>
   The censure alternative would condemn Clinton's behavior without
calling for his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   The draft released yesterday concludes that Clinton dishonored
his office and ``violated the trust of the American people'' by
making ``false statements about his reprehensible conduct.'' It
also accuses him of trying to ``delay discovery of the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution does not call for a fine or any other penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers in both parties agreed that the strongest case for
impeachment hinges on the perjury allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case _ I hate to say it _ I think the president
lied,'' said Rep. Howard Berman, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But Berman and other Democrats contend that lying under oath
about a consensual sexual affair does not meet the constitutional
standard for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're about to impeach a president because we think he gave
false answers about sexual relations and about touching,'' said
Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is scheduled to begin debating the
proposed impeachment articles this afternoon after final summations
by the panel's staff. No votes are expected until tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt, who drafted the censure proposal with other committee
Democrats, acknowledged that the committee is almost sure to reject
the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker-elect Bob Livingston of Louisiana has not said whether
he will permit a censure vote in the full House, but other GOP
leaders, including Majority Leader Dick Armey of Irving and Whip
Tom DeLay of Sugar Land, adamantly oppose the idea.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 2201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
