<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HOWZE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEN. HAMILTON HOWZE, ARMY AIR STRATEGIST, DIES AT 89
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN ROUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas, _ Gen. Hamilton Hawkins Howze, whose vision
of a ``sky cavalry'' transformed the Army's use of helicopters
before the Vietnam War, died Tuesday in Fort Worth. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the Army fights today'' is due to Howze, said Bob
Leder, spokesman for Bell Helicopter Textron, where Howze was a
vice president after he retired from the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral for Howze, a West Point graduate and fourth-generation
decorated veteran, will be at 11 a.m. Saturday at Saint Andrew's
Episcopal Church in Fort Worth. Burial will be at the cemetery at
the U.S. Military Academy at West Point, where Howse was born.
</P>
<P>
   Howze presided over the Army's Tactical Mobility Requirement
Board in the early 1960s.MDBU/.MDNM/. Later known as the Howze
Board, it explored the effectiveness of air mobile operations, said
Jack Moran, executive director for military aircraft at Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Howze the ``father of air mobile operations,'' Moran
said the four-star general ``was instrumental in the Army
organizing the First Cavalry Division, which fought so valiantly in
Vietnam (between) 1965 and 1971.''
</P>
<P>
   Howze was born Dec. 21, 1908, at West Point, N.Y. His father,
Major Gen. Robert L. Howze, was commandant of cadets at the time.
Hamilton Howze, who entered the academy in 1926, graduated in 1930,
according to an academy spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   His grandfather, Brig. Gen. Hamilton S. Hawkins, participated in
the charge up San Juan Hill during the Spanish-American War. His
great-grandfather, Hamilton S. Hawkins, was an Army surgeon who
died in the Mexican War.
</P>
<P>
   Howze graduated from an El Paso high school and attended Ohio
State University for one year. He was commissioned a lieutenant in
the cavalry after graduating from West Point.
</P>
<P>
   For his service in World War II, he received two Legions of
Merit awards, one in Italy and one in North Africa. He won a Silver
Star for service in North Africa, among other service awards.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1950s, Howze was commanding general of the 82nd
Airborne Division and later of the 18th Airborne Corps. In 1955, he
was named director of Army Aviation in the Office of the Deputy
Chief of Staff for Military Operations. He was later chief of the
United States Army Advisory Group in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   From 1963-65, he was commanding general of the 8th U.S.
Army/United Nations Command.
</P>
<P>
   Other service included three years in the Department of the Army
in Washington, and an assignment in Europe that included being
deputy chief of staff for operations of the Seventh Army.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Lt. General Robert Williams, 80, of Fort Worth, was
president of the Army Aviation Test Board in 1955 when he Gen.
Howze.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Howze's concept was one in which ``air vehicles,
particularly air helicopters'' replaced ground vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of aviation aircraft performing supplementary
functions, such as transportation or observation or supplementing
the firepower, the air vehicles became the primary means of doing
those things, particularly the helicopter gun ships.''
</P>
<P>
   Howze led the introduction of helicopters ``carrying rockets and
machine guns, delivering fire power,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams described his friend as an ``impressive individual''
who ``acted like a general'' but ``never took anything too
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from active duty in 1965, Howze moved to Fort
Worth and was vice president for product planning at Bell
Helicopter until 1971, when he retired but remained a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Howze served on the board of Fort Worth's Museum of Science and
History and was elected president in 1970. He also was on the
city's Traffic Safety Committee.
</P>
<P>
   As a frequent contributor to the ``Star-Telegram'' opinion
pages, Howze wrote about issues such as terrorism in the late 1970s
(he advocated media restraint in reporting about terrorist
activity), the U.S. mission to rescue hostages in Iran in 1980 and
women in the military (he opposed the admission of women to
military academies).
</P>
<P>
   He wrote ``A Cavalryman's Story: Memoirs of a Twentieth Century
Army General.''
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Mary Henry Howze of Fort Worth; two
sons, William G. Howze of Harker Heights and Guy R. Howze of
Austin; four grandchildren; and five great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
