<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSAL-CUTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSAL-POLYGRAM MERGER EXPECTED TO MEAN LAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. -- Seagram Co. is expected to announce
today massive layoffs in its music business that may affect as many
as 3,000 employees as it completes the $10.4 billion acquisition of
PolyGram NV.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram executives have already said they plan to cut $300
million in annual costs from the combined Universal and PolyGram
music groups, which have 15,500 employees. The restructuring would
be designed to improve profit margins at the the combined
operation, which will have a 25 percent share of the world's
recorded music business.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram will close the deal, announced last May, for Polygram
today as the Montreal-based concern continues its transformation
from a beverage specialist to an entertainment conglomerate.
Analysts have said the deal makes sense because it will broaden
Universal's roster, which has strong domestic appeal with acts like
Reba McEntire, the Wallflowers and B.B. King. Labels include MCA,
Geffen, Interscope, GRP and Universal.
</P>
<P>
   Amsterdam-based Polygram, already the world's largest music
company, has a massive roster including Hanson, Elton John, Sheryl
Crow, U2 and Luciano Pavarotti. Labels include Decca, Def Jam, A&AMP;M,
Verve, London, Island, Mercury, Motown and Deutsche Grammophon.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an analyst, I can't estimate how many jobs will be cut, but
the number that's been kicked around is 3,000,'' said Linda
Bannister of Edward Jones. ``The two companies could mix fairly
well, given Universal's domestic and PolyGram's international
strength, but any time you have a merger of this size, there's
bound to be some integration pains.''
</P>
<P>
   Bannister noted it's crucial for the Universal-PolyGram
integration to go smoothly. ``The last thing you want is turmoil
because you want to attract new artists and keep your stable
intact,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has given a generally positive response to Seagram's
purchase because it came at a time when music sales have been
stagnant, ensuring that the price of assets would be favorable to
buyers. Philips Electronics put PolyGram up for sale because it did
not fit in with its core business.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram is under pressure from Wall Street to improve its
performance. It announced Wednesday that Universal Studios' dismal
performance at the box office during the fall will give the
division a $65 million loss in its second fiscal quarter. Pricey
disappointments included ``Meet Joe Black'' and ``Babe: Pig in the
City.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
