r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NHRA-LADN     12-09 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHRA EVENT GETS NEW SPONSOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDORA -- The Automobile Club of Southern California has
reached a multi-year agreement with the Glendora, Calif.-based
National Hot Rod Association to replace R.J. Reynolds and its
Winston cigarette subsidiary as title sponsor for next year's
season-ending event at Pomona Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   The event, formerly known as the Winston Finals, now will be
called the Auto Club of Southern California NHRA finals and will
conclude the NHRA's 22-race circuit. Last month's Winston Finals
attacted an NHRA-record 138,000 fans during the four days of racing
that concluded on Nov. 15. Cash and contingency awards of more than
$1.7 million were paid.
</P>
<P>
   While the NHRA has yet to announce the indvidual prize purses
for each national event, NHRA president Dallas Gardner said there
would be no change in guidelines for the Auto Club of Southern
California Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rewarding to see an organization with such an impressive
membership significantly increase its presence in NHRA Winston drag
racing by sponsoring one of our marquee events,'' Gardner said.
``The Automobile Club of Southern California NHRA Finals will
continue to be one of our greatest traditions, showcasing
tremendous competition as well as the exciting drama that unfolds
as all NHRA Winston champions are crowned.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the sponsorship change comes less than a
month after a settlement was reached between U.S. tobacco companies
and several state governments, including California.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the settlement states that each tobacco company is
entitled to the sponsorship of one (racing) series. Speculation is
that R.J. Reynolds will choose to remain with NASCAR stock car
racing and its immensely popularWinston Cup series.
</P>
<P>
   However, an R.J. Reynolds spokesman denied the company was
dropping out of Pomona event for that reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process for (the agreement with Auto Club) started over a
year ago, so it has nothing to do with (the tobacco) settlement,''
said Greg Littell, director of sports marketing for R.J. Reynolds.
``This was just a chance for us to give up a property and allow
another company to increase its involvement (in NHRA drag
racing).''
</P>
<P>
   Littell said R.J Reynolds is willing to do that because next
season it has a number of special events planned to celebrate its
25 years of association with the NHRA, including the Winston
Showdown. That special non-points event will showcase Top Fuel
dragsters racing Funny Cars next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to step aside so that another company could be a
title sponsor,'' said Cliff Pennell, president of R.J. Reynolds'
Sports Marketing Enterprises. ``We've enjoyed a fantastic 24-year
sponsorship of the Winston Finals. However, a year ago, we were
advised that if we ever wanted to give up the Winston Finals, the
Automobile Club of Southern California would like to have it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed that given the importance of the event to them, it
was a good idea. Otherwise, we would never have given up the
Winston Finals. Allowing a sponsor that is already involved with
NHRA Winston drag racing to get even more involved is definitely
good for the sport. The Automobile Club of Southern California and
a race at Pomona are a perfect match.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner, who said he began talking with the Auto Club nearly two
years ago, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   R.J. Reynolds previously announced it would not to renew its
sponsorship contract with Funny Car driver Whit Bazemore, but
Pennell maintains the company will remain heavily involved in drag
racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite not having the Winston Finals, our commitment to NHRA
Winston Drag Racing in 1999 remains the same,'' Pennell said. ``All
of the money, energy and effort that went into the Winston Finals
will stay in the sport. We are focusing our event sponsorship on
the Winston Showdown (at Bristol, Tenn.) next summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with the Auto Club should take some of the heat
off the NHRA, which has received pressure from members of the Los
Angeles County Board of Supervisors who don't want an event
sanctioned by a tobacco company held on L.A. County property.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win-win proposition for the both of us,'' Gardner said.
``We know it will be good for the NHRA, good for Winston and good
for the entire sport. With the the Auto Club and its nearly five
million members, it's a perfect match.''
</P>
<P>
   The Auto Club's sponsorship of the event is not the
organization's first involvement with the NHRA or motorsports. AAA
has been an associate sponsor for Gary Densham's Funny Car
operation the past three seasons and has backed the Auto Club Road
to the Future Award since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The automobile organization has also been title sponsor for the
NASCAR Winston West Auto Club 200 at California Speedway the past
two seasons as well as being an associate sponsor at the Long Beach
Grand Prix since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Auto Club of Southern California has a rich history in
motorsports, including sanctioning and promoting track and
endurance races in the early 1900s. Although it stopped sanctioning
events until a few years ago to focus on member services, the Club
for decades has worked closely with manufacturers, mechanics and
state agencies to improve vehicle technology and safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this has a way to reinforce our brand,'' said Tom
McKernan, Auto Club president and CEO. ``We've been involved with
Densham, the Road to the Future Award and the NHRA California Hot
Rod Reunion. This is just another way for us become more visible
and reinforce our brand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
