last February should think again: The 27-year-old Olympic captain
is far from ready to say die. ``If you have a lot of passion still
left in you and you still want to play the game of hockey ... then
you can't give it up,'' she says. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WINDSOR, Conn. -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- PREPPIE-HATE-BOS,
12-09 -- Last year, 15-year-old Lucy Weber discovered a virulent
anti-Semitic note on her dresser at The Middlesex School, then a
swastika, and later, a note in the shower: ``Gas for the Jew.''
Though the case was never solved, the school sent a letter to
parents suggesting that Lucy had written the notes to herself. Last
month, Middlesex was forced to pay a settlement and issue an
apology. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) JERUSALEM -- Dec. 9, 1998 --ISRAEL-STUDENTS, 12-09 -- An
ultra-Orthodox Jewish student walks past Israeli soldiers marching
through a street in Jerusalem during ceremonies marking the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the Jewish state on Wednesday. In a
landmark decision that touches a deep divide between strictly
religious and secular Israelis, the Israeli Supreme Court ruled
Wednesday that a longstanding exemption for rigorously Orthodox
Jewish yeshiva students from army service was illegal. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- BLECKNER-BENEFIT, 12-09 --
Ross Bleckner lights candles before his guests took their seats
during a party he held to benefit the Community Research Initiative
on AIDS. Some 120 guests paid $1,000 for the privilege of climbing
six flights of stairs for cocktails and dinner with Bleckner, an
artist. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- IMPEACH-RUFF-3, 12-09 --
White House counsel Charles Ruff makes a point before the House
Judiciary Committee on Wednesday. Ruff presented the committee with
a summation of Clinton's defense against impeachment. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) OMAGH, orthern Ireland -- Dec. 9, 1998 --
SUB-NIRELAND-BOMBTOWN-2, 12-09 -- Mick Grimes arrives for a
counseling session to help him cope with the loss of relatives in a
car bombing last August. The blast killed his wife, Mary, 65; his
granddaughter, Maura, 18 months; and his daughter, Avril, 30, and
destroyed the seven-month-old twin fetuses in Avril's womb. (Carlos
Lopez-Barillas/New York Times Photo)
