<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUFF INSISTS CLINTON DID NOT COMMIT PERJURY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wrapping up President Clinton's defense at
impeachment hearings, White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff
conceded Wednesday that ``reasonable people'' might conclude that
the president made false statements under oath about his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But Ruff insisted that the president did not commit the crime of
perjury because Clinton's testimony was based on his understanding
that sexual relations meant sexual intercourse. He contended that
the president's goal was to be ``evasive'' and ``as of little help
as possible'' to prosecutors trying to build a case against him.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff's painstaking efforts to draw distinctions between legal
wrongdoing and what he described as ``morally reprehensible''
conduct came on the second day of the White House defense effort
before the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Before he had concluded his testimony, the Republican committee
members released four draft articles of impeachment against the
president, including two accusing him of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the action, Ruff continued to contend that there was no
convincing evidence in independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report
on the Lewinsky matter to support his contention that Clinton
committed perjury, sought to obstruct justice or abused his
presidential powers to keep his affair with Lewinsky private.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has not committed a high crime or misdemeanor.
His conduct, although morally reprehensible, does not warrant
impeachment, does not warrant overturning the mandate of the
American electorate,'' Ruff said as the 37-member panel sat in rapt
silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to have committed an impeachable offense, the
president must have acted to subvert our system of government. And
members of the committee, that did not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff added that what Clinton had done essentially with his
``wrongful relationship'' was violate ``his sacred obligations to
his wife and daughter,'' not to mention the trust placed in him by
the American people. For that, Ruff suggested, Clinton has suffered
enough ``privately and publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he said the president would accept any ``reasonable
suggestion ... to end this process'' short of impeachment. His
statement raised the possibility that Clinton would agree to appear
on the House floor to be censured, or publicly reprimanded for his
conduct, and pay a financial penalty as well. Both have been raised
as alternatives to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff's concession, under questioning from Rep. James
Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., that Clinton may have made false statements
surprised some GOP panel members who have pressed the White House
repeatedly to admit that the president lied under oath. But the
lawyer stopped far short of that, insisting that none of Clinton's
statements to the grand jury or in a deposition for the Paula Jones
sexual harassment case amounted to perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We firmly believe that the president testified truthfully
before the grand jury,'' Ruff declared. ``I have no doubt he walked
up to a line he thought he understood. Reasonable people could
determine he crossed that line. But in his mind, and that is the
heart of perjury, what he thought he was doing was being evasive
but truthful.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff's interpretation of what constitutes perjury was supported
by a panel of legal scholars and practicing attorneys who offered a
point-by-point rebuttal to Starr's charges that Clinton had lied
under oath.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, which included the former Republican governor of
Massachusetts, William Weld, and a former Watergate prosecutor,
argued that no ``responsible federal prosecutor'' would even think
of bringing perjury charges in court like those outlined by Starr
because conviction would be difficult, if not impossible, to
obtain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president were not involved, if an ordinary citizen
were the subject of the inquiry, no serious consideration would be
given to a criminal prosecution ... having to do with an alleged
cover-up of a private sexual affair with another woman,'' said
former Illinois U.S. attorney Thomas P. Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't get in the door; it would be declined out of
hand,'' Sullivan added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not perjury for a witness to evade, obfuscate or answer
nonresponsively,'' Sullivan told the panel of 21 Republicans and 16
Democrats. ``The evidence (in the Starr report) simply does not
support the conclusion that president knowingly committed perjury,
and the case is so doubtful and weak that a responsible prosecutor
would not present it to the grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, the Supreme Court ruled that in perjury cases
prosecutors must prove that lies were ``knowingly'' made under oath
and that they were ``material'' to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans, however, were indignant at the claim that
Clinton should be treated as an ordinary citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that we're still not getting straight talk and
the truth,'' said Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., adding that Clinton
``is not just any ordinary citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As president he has a higher responsibility to set an example
and uphold the law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his defense of the president, Ruff described several
instances of ``facts and evidence'' favorable to the president that
Starr left out of his report to Congress. They involved both
testimony from Lewinsky and others that Ruff said support many of
the president's statements that Starr claims are lies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ruff claimed that testimony from Betty Currie, the
president's personal secretary, supports Clinton's contention that
he never asked Lewinsky return his gifts and that the prosecutor
never bothered to ask Lewinsky if that testimony was correct.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff also pointed to the independent counsel's claim that
Clinton lied to reporters last March when he said he had not held
discussions with his lawyers about claiming executive privilege to
prevent certain White House officials from testifying before the
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a transcript of that exchange with reporters, Ruff said
Starr failed to note that Clinton was responding to a question
about whether first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton should be included
as a protected official in the privilege claim, something Ruff said
had not been discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff's defense on that issue stunned some members of the
committee because some Republicans have repeatedly referred to
Clinton's comment on executive privilege as evidence that he has
``engaged in a pattern of lies and misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (Republicans) were listening, I think Mr. Ruff was
compelling,'' said Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, a committee
member who supports censure for Clinton, but not impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, leaving out information that could be material to a
case ... at least in my neck of the woods, is appalling,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
