<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, DECEMBER 10
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-UNICEF-LITERACY-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Dec. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Dec. 8,
about Unicef's annual report on the world's children misstated the
number of those in the poorest nations who are in school. It is 3
of every 4 children, not 1 of every 4.
</P>
<P>
   BC-REPUBS-WATTS-NYT (moved on Sunday, Nov. 15.)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Nov. 15,
about Representative J.C. Watts Jr. misstated the name of Mr.
Watts's Democratic opponent in Oklahoma. He was Ben Odom, not Bruce
Ober.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CHICAGO-DALEY-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Dec. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Dec. 8,
about the announcement that Mayor Richard M. Daley of Chicago will
run for re-election omitted the name of his predecessor. Mr. Daley
first won election in 1989 by defeating Eugene Sawyer, who had been
appointed interim Mayor after Harold Washington died in office in
1987. Because of an editing error, the article also misstated the
number of blacks who have held the post. Mr. Washington was the
first of two; Mr. Sawyer was the second.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-GORE-NYT (moved on Monday, Dec. 7)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of former Senator Albert Gore Sr. of Tennessee
moved by the New York Times News Service on Monday, Dec. 7,
misstated the age he had reached when his son was nominated for
vice president, in 1992. It was 84, not 82.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SUN-JAVA-NYT (moved on Monday, Dec. 7)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Dec. 7,
about Sun Microsystems' new version of the Java programming
language misstated the extent of technical cooperation provided by
Microsoft to be sure Java works properly on computers using Windows
operating software. Microsoft agreed to add to its own version of
Java an element known as J.N.I. to comply with a recent Federal
Court order. Microsoft has not agreed to add features to Windows
that would enhance the performance of Jini, the Java technology
distributed by Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Because of an editing error, the headline also misstated a
change in Sun's strategy for programming development. Sun has moved
a step closer toward an ``open source'' model, in which programming
work is freely shared. It has not switched to that model.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CUBA-SHIPWRECK-NYT (moved on Thursday, Nov. 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Nov. 26,
about a deal by Visa Gold Resources of Canada to search for sunken
treasure in Cuban waters overstated the number of 16th- and
17th-century Spanish galleons believed to have sunk in the
Caribbean. Most scholars agree that it is far less than 500, not
``as many as'' 500.
</P>
</TEXT>
