<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON PUBLIC PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By JAMES BARRON  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One will that will not be found on the Web site created by
HERBERT E. NASS _ www.willsofrichandfamous.com _ is that of the
director Alan J. Pakula, who died in a freak accident on the Long
Island Expressway last month.
</P>
<P>
   The reason has to do with ethics. Nass, a probate lawyer who
wrote a book called ``Wills of the Rich and Famous'' (Warner,
1991), has clients like Pakula and the artist Roy Lichtenstein, who
are, well, rich and famous. ``I feel uncomfortable putting their
particular wills on my Web site, even though wills are public
record,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site has more than 100 wills Nass did not handle,
including those of Truman Capote, Thomas Jefferson and Alfred
Hitchcock. As for Pakula, his will, filed in Surrogate's Court in
Manhattan, left his estate of more than $500,000 to his widow,
HANNAH PAKULA. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot of talk about hand holding on Tuesday at Central
Synagogue's service of appreciation for firefighters, police
officers and city officials who helped fight the blaze that scarred
the twin-towered landmark on Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   MAYOR RUDOLPH W. GIULIANI praised RABBI PETER RUBINSTEIN for
``accomplishing what I thought no religious leader in this city
could accomplish: getting me to hold hands with MARK GREEN.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was referring to a moment on the night of the fire,
when several city officials joined hands while Rubinstein led a
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' the mayor said at the Tuesday service. ``It
won't become a habit.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Rubinstein praised city officials, including
JEROME HAUER, the director of the mayor's office of emergency
management, ``who really held our hand for a long time.'' This,
apparently, was metaphorical hand holding. ``I don't remember
whether he was in there'' for the Aug. 30 prayer, Rubinstein said
Wednesday. ``He was so busy directing things outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the reconstruction of the synagogue is completed in 2000,
the congregation will be ``nomadic,'' scheduling many services in
other large places of worship or auditoriums. The one on Tuesday,
for example, was at the Fifth Avenue Presbyterian Church, on 55th
Street. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a flash, Anonymous vs. Anonymous _ the custody trial in which
the billionaire RONALD O. PERELMAN is squaring off against his
third wife, PATRICIA DUFF _ was back on the docket in JUSTICE
EILEEN BRANSTEN's courtroom Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Bransten summoned the couple after Perelman lost his bid
to have the trial delayed while his appeal of a five-day-old
appellate division ruling was being argued. Perelman had wanted the
custody proceedings closed to the public; the appellate division
ruled last Friday that they must be open. Wednesday, JUSTICE JOSEPH
SULLIVAN of the appellate division refused Perelman's request to
halt the trial until the appellate division has ruled on other,
related issues.
</P>
<P>
   So Judge Bransten began hearing testimony. ``We put on a
court-appointed security expert,'' said one of Perelman's lawyers,
ADRIA HILLMAN. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five years after the Surgeon General warned that smoking
was hazardous to one's health and three years after New York City
adopted antismoking regulations for restaurants, a cigarette bar
has opened in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 1,400 restaurants in this city that exclude
smokers,'' said BRIAN MICHELS, the owner of Circa Tabac, at 32
Watts Street. He stocks more than 100 brands of cigarettes,
including some that go for $8 a pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air in here will be cleaner than the air outside,'' he
said. ``We've invested in an air purification system like the one
they have on the Space Shuttle.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it does the job. ``I expected to leave reeking'' of
cigarette smoke,'' said LAURIE ABRAHAM, the health editor of
Mirabella and a hostess of a party at Circa Tabac on Monday. ``I
was really surprised because I left there and my hair didn't
smell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
