<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAULDER-EXECUTION-COX     12-09 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAULDER-EXECUTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COURT BLOCKS TWO TEXAS EXECUTIONS
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Austin federal judge on Wednesday blocked the scheduled
executions of convicted killers Joseph Stanley Faulder and Danny
Lee Barber, raising new legal questions about the secretive process
by which Texas considers clemency for its condemned criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, after the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
refused to overturn the delay of Barber's execution ordered by U.S.
District Judge Sam Sparks, prison officials moved him from the
``Death House,'' a building in a downtown Huntsville prison that
houses the execution chamber, back to death row at the Ellis prison
unit just outside of town.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials said the New Orleans-based appeals court
indicated it would decide today whether to let Faulder's execution,
scheduled just after 6 p.m. today, also be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said they were unsure what effect Wednesday's
rulings might have on other pending executions. But they agreed the
development marked a new and possibly ominous turn for Texas'
long-controversial clemency system, which has survived several
similar legal challenges in past months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This action affects two cases right now _ and that's all,''
said Glen Castlebury, a prison system spokesman in Huntsville.
``We'll await further word from the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen Texas convicts have been executed so far this year, two
so far this month. One other execution is scheduled in December,
and four are set in January. Since it reinstated the death penalty
in 1982, Texas has executed 162 men and one woman _ a record _ and
has 451 prisoners awaiting execution.
</P>
<P>
   Spark's order came less than an hour before Barber was to be
executed at a Huntsville prison for killing a Balch Springs woman
in a 1979 robbery. Faulder, a Canadian national, was to be put to
death today for killing a Gladewater widow in a 1975 robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, the state Board of Pardons and Paroles had
vetoed clemency requests for both convicts _ fueling a growing
storm of international protest in Faulder's case.
</P>
<P>
   In a seven-page order signed at mid-afternoon, Sparks ruled
there are enough questions about Texas' clemency process to warrant
a Dec. 21 hearing and determine whether Faulder received the proper
legal review of his request to have his death sentence commuted to
a lesser penalty.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:10 p.m., he signed a similar delay for Barber based on the
delay he granted Faulder. He set a Dec. 22 hearing in that case.
Earlier this year, Sparks refused to halt the execution of Karla
Faye Tucker _ the first woman executed by Texas since the Civil War
_ over the same questions about Texas' clemency process. Other
execution-bound convicts also have tried to delay their deaths with
similar filings, all without success.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent U.S. Supreme Court ruling in an Ohio case could
change that, Sparks noted in his order. That ruling questioned
whether unspecified ``minimal procedural safeguards'' might be
required in clemency proceedings to guard against arbitrary
decisions, a process that remains unclear in Texas because state
officials have refused to detail how they review and decide
clemency cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unclear how the (Board of Pardons and Paroles) can
document that its procedures are not arbitrary if it does not
document its procedures at all,'' Sparks' order in Faulder's case
states.
</P>
<P>
   At another point in his order, Sparks quoted from the Supreme
Court ruling: ``Judicial intervention might, for example, be
warranted in the face of a scheme whereby a state official flipped
a coin to determine whether to grant clemency, or in a case where
the state arbitrarily denied a prisoner any access to its clemency
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Babcock, a Minneapolis lawyer representing Faulder, could
not be reached for comment about Sparks' order. But Maurie Levin,
an Austin attorney handling a separate civil-court appeal on
Faulder's behalf, said his legal team was encouraged by the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Parole Board Chairman Victor Rodriguez said he remained
confident the clemency system will survive the legal test. ``We
believe we operate properly and constitutionally, with adequate due
process,'' he said. Barber, 43, a onetime roofer from California,
was sentenced to death by lethal injection for the October 1979
slaying of Janice Louise Ingram of Balch Springs, just east of
Dallas. Police said she was beaten to death with a piece of pipe,
then stabbed in the throat, by an intruder who she surprised
burglarizing her home.
</P>
<P>
   Barber also is serving life sentences for three other murders
and a 20-year-sentence for a Dallas burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder, 61, was convicted of the July 1975 murder of Inez
Phillips, the matriarch of a wealthy Texas oil family who was
fatally stabbed during a robbery at her East Texas home. Beaten
with a blackjack when she resisted, then gagged and bound with
tape, police said a maid found Phillips' body with a knife imbedded
in her chest.
</P>
<P>
   If executed as scheduled just after 6 p.m. Thursday, Faulder
would be the first Canadian put to death in the United States since
1952.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's chain of events began at 8 a.m. when the 18-member
parole board voted against commuting the death sentences of either
Barber and Faulder to lesser terms. Without comment, it also vetoed
their requests for a 30-day reprieve. The recommendations were
forwarded to Gov. George Bush, who was left only with the option of
delaying each case 30 days. At a Capitol press conference a few
hours later, Bush gave no indication he planned to delay either
execution.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a two-hour delay, then cancellation, of Barber's
execution, relatives of his victims expressed anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so stunned,'' said a sobbing Lisa Turner, Ingram's niece,
who was to have watched Barber's execution. ``When are we going to
have another chance? The courts are going to have to get off their
butts and do what's right for the families of who he killed. It's
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think it's right,'' cried Ruth Rae Clowers, another
niece. ``They bring us down here, we lose a day's pay of work and
they don't execute him. Why should he have rights? I feel awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
