</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELFARE REFORM IN TEXAS SHOWS SOME PROGRESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the first major snapshot of Texas welfare
reform, a new survey shows more than half of those weaned from cash
payments are working nearly full-time and earning more than minimum
wage.
</P>
<P>
   Yet more government supports are needed _ transitional benefits,
high school equivalency diplomas, expanded child care _ to ensure
the goal of permanent self-sufficiency, said DHS Commissioner Eric
M. Bost.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people come into our offices, it is no longer what can we
do to help put you on welfare. Our focus is what can we do to help
you get a job to stay off welfare,'' Bost said.
</P>
<P>
   Findings of the survey, conducted by Texas A&AMP;M University and
the Texas Department of Human Services, are based on responses of
1,396 individuals or 51 percent of those contacted.
</P>
<P>
   Questions explored what is actually happening to those who leave
welfare or are directed away from it before they apply for
assistance. Bost said the results could help state legislators
strengthen the system when they reconvene in January.
</P>
<P>
   At a Capitol news conference Wednesday, Gov. George W. Bush
touted the survey as evidence welfare-to-work programs and
faith-based support systems are succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas now recognizes it is more compassionate to help people
find a job than it is to make them dependent upon government.
Welfare reform is working in Texas,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that 100,000 families have left welfare rolls
since the state enacted reforms four years ago. Another 146,000
still receive Temporary Assistance for Needy Families, roughly $188
monthly for a mother and two children.
</P>
<P>
   The latest survey shows 55 percent of those who either left
welfare or were diverted from applying were working at the time
they were surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   They averaged 34 hours of work a week and hourly pay of $6.28 an
hour, higher than the federal minimum wage of $5.15 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The most common jobs included restaurants/fast food (15
percent), clerical (13 percent), retail and sales (13 percent),
nursing (12 percent) and janitorial (6 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always asked if 45 percent of the people in the survey
were not working, what are they doing? How are they existing?''
Bost said. He added that half of those said they are supported by
relatives while only 10 percent to 11 percent said they need help
from food banks or other charitable services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not indicate to us that there is a significant number
of people out there who are seeking assistance from food banks or
are homeless as a result of welfare reform,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The most common items cited when asked about needs in getting
work were a high-school equivalency diploma, work clothes, reliable
transportation, child care, health care, education and training to
improve job skills.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Bresette, an analyst at the Center for Public Policy
Priorities in Austin, questioned why respondents were not asked
about hassles they might have in dealing with DHS and the Texas
Workforce Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is so dramatic in getting them off the
benefits,'' he said. ``It would have been useful to ask about
clients' experience with the system in the current environment. Are
they being offered the opportunities to get a GED or get some
training so that job isn't $6.28 an hour but $8.28?''
</P>
<P>
   Other key findings of the survey, taken between December 1997
and May 1998, reveal:
</P>
<P>
   _ Thirteen percent reported being employed at some point during
the six-month survey even though they were not currently working.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forty-one percent said their jobs offered advancement
opportunities, while 26 percent reported receiving a raise and 40
percent had jobs with health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sixty-six percent received food stamps; 70 percent continued
on Medicaid; 37 percent got the supplemental nutrition through the
Women, Infants and Children program; and 15 percent lived in public
housing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thirty-two percent had a mentor who inspired or motivated
them.
</P>
<P>
   Bost said more in-depth studies are planned with larger samples
in order to detect problems that cause former welfare mothers to
cycle back onto assistance. The next study will also ask how
children formerly on welfare are faring if their families are
doubling up with others in crowded living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, University of Texas anthropologist and author Laura
Lein said Wednesday that she is launching a nine-month study to
closely follow the personal experiences of selected families who
tend to fall off and on the welfare rolls. Lein is the co-author of
a book that explored the real-life budgets of welfare mothers and
how they supplement benefits to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   Bresette and Lein said it is important for people leaving TANF
rolls to continue receiving support from Medicaid, food stamps and
child care assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The following over time is going to be critical,'' Bresette
said of the state's efforts. ``In a snapshot like this you could
argue that this is not that different than welfare recipients in
Texas have behaved in the past. Our grant is so low, work is a
better deal. Many of the clients use TANF as unemployment
assistance of sorts.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
