exhibit began in January. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- IMPEACH-POLITICS, 12-09 --
Followed by members of the Cabinet and Rep. Richard Gephardt, left,
President Clinton leaves Blair House in Washington on Wednesday
after a meeting on Social Security reform With the House Judiciary
Committee moving closer to critical impeachment votes, Democrats
prepared a censure alternative that would condemn the president and
save him from articles of impeachment. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- IMPEACH-REPUBLICANS, 12-09
-- Rep. Brian Bilbray, R-Calif., center, in his Capitol Hill office
as the impeachment hearings were broadcast on a television above.
Bilbray is one of as many as three dozen undecided moderate
Republican still undecided about a possible vote on impeachment.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- IMPEACH, 12-09 -- Former
Republican Governor of Massachusetts William Weld is shown to his
seat by Lanny Bruer, a member of the White House legal team, before
his testimony before the House Judiciary Committee on Wednesday.
With Clinton's fate now largely in the hands of as many as three
dozen undecided moderate Republicans, the White House reached out
to friendly Republicans like Weld to join their defense of the
president. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- IMPEACH-SCENE, 12-09 -- As
members of the House Judiciary Committee contiuned their
questioning of the White House's witnesses, Rep. Howard Coble,
R-N.C., took a break to smoke a cigar while watching the
proceedings from a doorway in the hearing room. With the 37-member
panel moving closer to critical impeachment votes, Democrats
prepared a censure alternative that would condemn the president.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK-- Dec. 9, 1998 -- TENEMENT-MUSEUM, 12-09 --
Natalie Dickstein looks from a window in her grandmother's former
apartment in New York's Orchard Street. The tiny three-room
apartment, circa 1918, is part of a permanent exhibit at the Lower
East Side Tenement Museum which opens on Thursday. The museum has
restored several apartments in the building which was built at the
turn of the century. (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- TWA-JETS, 12-09 -- Artist
renderings of a Boeing 717, top, and Airbus Industrie A318. Trans
World Airlines split a $3.9 billion order for short-range jets
between Boeing and Airbus Industrie, giving the European consortium
the bigger share. The airline ordered 50 Boeing 717 jets, valued at
about $1.4 billion, and took options on 50 more, and it places
orders with a total value of about $2.5 billion for 75 Airbus
A318s, taking options for 75 more. The order is Boeing's first
major contract for the 106-seat 717 in three years. (Boeing
Aircraft, top, Airbus Industrie, bottom/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- IMPEACH-RUFF-2, 12-09 --
White House Counsel Charles Ruff, left, and President Clinton's
personal attorney David Kendall during testimony Tuesday by the
House Judiciary Committee. Ruff will present the committee with a
summation of Clinton's defense against impeachment on Wednesday.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- IMPEACH-RUFF-1, 12-09 --
White House Counsel Charles Ruff, right, listens to the House
Judiciary Committee's minority counsel Abbe Lowell during hearings
on Tuesday. Ruff will present the committee with a summation of
Clinton's defense against impeachment on Wednesday. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
