<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 12/09/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) SPARROWS POINT, Md -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- STEEL-COMPETE,
12-09 -- Curtis Barnette stands in front of a ``charge'' in action
at his plant in Sparrows Point. Barnette is chief executive of
Bethlehem Steel, and he sees the American steel industry fighting
for its life. ``The American consumer would not benefit from the
extinction of the American steel industry,'' Barnette says. (Ann
Grillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- IMPEACH-SCENE-2, 12-09 --
House Judiciary Committee Chairman Rep. Henry Hyde, center, talks
with fellow committee members during a break Wednesday in testimony
defending President Clinton against impeachment charges. In the
foreground are Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., right, and Howard
Coble, R-N.C. All the labors of high-priced lawyering that have
marked the struggle to impeach and defend Clinton seemed to have
converged before the committee on Wednesday in a clash that, at a
minimum, showed no lack of combative lawyers. (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- IMPEACH-2, 12-09
--President Clinton, flanked by, from left, Chicago Cubs Sammy
Sosa, Sosa's wife Sonia, and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton take
part in ceremonies lighting the national Christmas tree on
Wednesday. The House Judiciary Committee heard summations on
Wednesday from Clinton's lawyers defending him against impeachment
charges. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WALPOLE, Mass. -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- WOM-GRANATO-BOS, 12-09
-- Those who thought Cammi Granato might retire after leading the
U.S. women's ice hockey team to an Olympic gold medal in Nagano
last February should think again: The 27-year-old Olympic captain
is far from ready to say die. ``If you have a lot of passion still
left in you and you still want to play the game of hockey ... then
you can't give it up,'' she says. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WINDSOR, Conn. -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- PREPPIE-HATE-BOS,
12-09 -- Last year, 15-year-old Lucy Weber discovered a virulent
anti-Semitic note on her dresser at The Middlesex School, then a
swastika, and later, a note in the shower: ``Gas for the Jew.''
Though the case was never solved, the school sent a letter to
parents suggesting that Lucy had written the notes to herself. Last
month, Middlesex was forced to pay a settlement and issue an
apology. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) JERUSALEM -- Dec. 9, 1998 --ISRAEL-STUDENTS, 12-09 -- An
ultra-Orthodox Jewish student walks past Israeli soldiers marching
through a street in Jerusalem during ceremonies marking the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the Jewish state on Wednesday. In a
landmark decision that touches a deep divide between strictly
religious and secular Israelis, the Israeli Supreme Court ruled
Wednesday that a longstanding exemption for rigorously Orthodox
Jewish yeshiva students from army service was illegal. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- BLECKNER-BENEFIT, 12-09 --
Ross Bleckner lights candles before his guests took their seats
during a party he held to benefit the Community Research Initiative
on AIDS. Some 120 guests paid $1,000 for the privilege of climbing
six flights of stairs for cocktails and dinner with Bleckner, an
artist. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- IMPEACH-RUFF-3, 12-09 --
White House counsel Charles Ruff makes a point before the House
Judiciary Committee on Wednesday. Ruff presented the committee with
a summation of Clinton's defense against impeachment. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) OMAGH, orthern Ireland -- Dec. 9, 1998 --
SUB-NIRELAND-BOMBTOWN-2, 12-09 -- Mick Grimes arrives for a
counseling session to help him cope with the loss of relatives in a
car bombing last August. The blast killed his wife, Mary, 65; his
granddaughter, Maura, 18 months; and his daughter, Avril, 30, and
destroyed the seven-month-old twin fetuses in Avril's womb. (Carlos
Lopez-Barillas/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) OMAGH, orthern Ireland -- Dec. 9, 1998 --
NIRELAND-BOMBTOWN, 12-09 -- A single cross stands as a memorial to
the victims of the bombing in Omagh which killed 29 people and
injured 400. Nearly four months after the blast, locals still are
trying to recover from the bombing which was claimed by a group
calling itself the Real IRA. The cross is located near the site of
the bomb blast. (Carlos Lopez-Barillas/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- NY-FINANCIAL-DISTRICT-2,
12-09 -- A man walks down a lonely street in New York's financial
center. Only two years ago, developers were outbidding one another
for the old office towers to turn into new apartment buildings.
While no one is labeling the Wall Street experiment in living a
bust, the pace has definitely slowed. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 12-09
-- During the fall, homeowners often awaken to find their windows
fogged over. In the winter, the windows may be covered with a thin
layer of frost. Both the fog and the frost are examples of
condensation. Moderate condensation is not a cause for concern.
Heavy persistent condensation will flow past the sill to saturate
the wall. Damp walls will encourage mold and mildew. Eventually the
moisture will penetrate through the walls and rot the framing. (New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Dec. 9, 1998 -- NY-FINANCIAL-DISTRICT-2,
