<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0543 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1957 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PRESIDENTS-NORMAN     12-09 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PRESIDENTS-NORMAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MELBOURNE, Australia _ You've heard of made-for-TV sporting events.
<TEXT>
<P>
   What you may not have heard is the Presidents Cup that begins
today is a made-for-Greg Norman event, especially when it takes
place in his backyard at Royal Melbourne Golf Club. Which would be
fine if this were any other year in Norman's life and his golf game
was in its usual, faultless groove.
</P>
<P>
   But after seven inactive months to rehabilitate his surgically
repaired left shoulder, and only one month of swinging a golf club
in preparation for this week, Norman admits this may not be the
best timing for him to put on a heroic show for the home folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can ever knock the rust completely off in
this game, to tell you the truth,'' Norman said. ``One thing that
is great about this game is that the day you think you're swinging
great, you can get humbled the next day. Like when I play with
Steve (Elkington), he sees there might be something I am missing
(in my game) because we play so much golf together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that because of the layoff? Possibly, yes. Is that because
I haven't played enough tournament golf lately? Possibly, yes. To
say I might be a little rusty? Yeah, I might be a little rusty. But
I'm ready to go. I'm not worried about the rust being there.''
</P>
<P>
   But his doctor is. Norman said he has been communicating with
his medical advisers on a regular basis and that they are not
pleased about how much golf he has played in the early portion of
his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very concerned that I've played too much golf to this
moment,'' Norman said. ``I haven't had a day off in over two weeks
now, and he's very concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants me to sit back and re-evaluate things on Sunday
night. He'd like to see me stop playing for six weeks after Sunday
and just let my shoulder get strong again.''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't exactly sound like the prescription for a Norman
domination this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But Norman knows this is his party. He was the loudest voice in
getting the PGA Tour to bring the Presidents Cup away from America
for the first time. And whether he's rusty or tweaking his swing or
whatever, he has to be ready to be the anchor for the international
team that will try to wrest the Cup away from the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   It is a match that brings together 24 of the world's greatest
golfers, even if some of them might not be household names. There's
Paraguay's Carlos Franco, who lived in a one-room shack in Asuncion
until he was 14 and occasionally putts with his driver when his
traditional flatstick is more of a flatsick. There's Shigeki
Maruyama, who is funnier speaking Japanese than most American
golfers are speaking English.
</P>
<P>
   And there are the big boys like Fred Couples, Ernie Els, Tiger
Woods, David Duval, Elkington and Vijay Singh.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody is a bigger heavyweight this weekend than Norman. He
is a legend in Australia. And before his shoulder surgery, his game
was as strong as anybody's in the world and he was atop the global
rankings because of it.
</P>
<P>
   But on April 22, he had bone spurs that caused tendinitis shaved
out of his shoulder. He didn't hit a golf ball again until Sept. 4.
That 4{-month layoff provided Norman with the chance to spend more
time with his family than ever before. They did what families do in
the summertime _ take vacations and do other things together.
</P>
<P>
   Norman returned to competitive play at his Shark Shootout, which
he won with Elkington. But even Norman admits Elkington carried the
brunt of the load.
</P>
<P>
   In his first four-day tournament since the surgery, Norman
barely made the cut at the Australian Open last week. He had a
second-round 82 and finished far out of contention against a modest
field.
</P>
<P>
   And now, as Elkington said, Norman will be thrust into a tough
position _ even for a player with a well-tuned game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us are never really playing under any big pressure at
this time of year, and this is a big-pressure event,'' Elkington
said. ``I don't think we're going to catch them off-guard. They
probably have the greatest team they could ever get together. They
have such a strong team that we'll have to play very well to keep
up with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Norman said, confidence is at an all-time high for the
international squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rate it (his team's chance of winning) very highly,'' Norman
said. ``We have an extremely good balance to the team. We've got
guys who fit together well. And that's why I think from my
perspective and from hearing the players talk, I rate our chances
very, very highly.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Elkington: ``This is the best team we have had out of the
three (Presidents Cup) teams. And we only got beat by a point (in
'96) on their soil. We feel like our team is maybe a little
stronger this year, and we are playing on our home soil. We're
pretty pleased with our team, and we feel pretty confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he likes to think of it as a team effort, it was Norman
more than anybody else who coaxed PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem
and other golf honchos to stage the third Presidents Cup in a
country other than the U.S. The clincher in moving it to Royal
Melbourne came in the hours right after Fred Couples' dramatic
30-foot putt clinched the Cup in '96 for the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times like that Sunday evening two years ago, in our villa
there, those are the things that last forever in a player's mind
and in Tim Finchem's mind, because very seldom do you get a chance
to express yourself the way we expressed ourselves then,'' Norman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The story goes like this: After Couples' putt doomed the
international team, the players congregated in a room adjacent to
the course. For more than an hour, they drank beers together and
talked about what had just transpired. It was an outpouring of
emotion that swayed Finchem to send the Presidents Cup to
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had done so well in that match, even though we lost by a
whisker,'' international captain Peter Thomson said. ``Something
was proved, that this was a team with some power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the end of the week, and we had done so well, and
somebody started the speech-making and then everybody wanted to
have a go. So as the beer flowed, I think we got very emotional. I
think they wanted to play the next week and reverse the result.''
</P>
<P>
   That Finchem was in the room made the moment all the more
spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty emotional, with stuff said from the heart,''
Elkington said. ``Finchem was there, and we told him that we didn't
know if we could all get together and play this one more time in
America, because if this was going to grow as an event, you have to
play it away from America sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, here they are, 23 of the world's greatest golfers and
one guy who is expected to be the brightest star of them all,
Norman.
</P>
<P>
   Now if only his shoulder will let him be the life of the party
for the international side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
