<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADENCE-ACQUIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CADENCE TO ACQUIRE QUICKTURN DESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Playing the white knight, Cadence Design Systems
Inc. agreed Wednesday to acquire Quickturn Design Systems Inc.,
which has been the subject of a hostile takeover bid by the Mentor
Graphics Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Cadence said it would swap stock worth $14 a share, a total of
$253 million, for Quickturn. Mentor had bid $12.13 a share in cash,
but its offer was rebuffed by Quickturn, which has been battling
the deal in the Delaware courts. Mentor said Wednesday that it was
reviewing its options in light of the competing offer.
</P>
<P>
   Cadence's shares closed at $29.1875, down 81.25 cents on the New
York Stock Exchange. Quickturn's shares closed at $13.8125, up
$1.625, and Mentor's shares at $8.75, down $1.25, both in NASDAQ
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Cadence, based in San Jose, Calif., and Mentor, based in
Wilsonville, Ore., are bitter rivals in the market for the
electronic automated design software used to fashion new chips.
</P>
<P>
   Quickturn is a leader in the related market for specialized
computers that can emulate a new chip design before it is crafted
in silicon, providing a kind of virtual verification that the
circuitry will work as intended.
</P>
<P>
   Mentor acquired a small French company with an emulation and
verification product last year, but cannot market it in the United
States because of a court order stemming from a patent-infringement
suit by Quickturn. That suit comes to trial in Oregon in February.
</P>
<P>
   Mentor originally proposed the merger as a friendly deal that
could put an end to the litigation, but the offer was spurned by
Keith R. Lobo, Quickturn's president and chief executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 2237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0547 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1966 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS &LR;      12-09 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS OWNER HINTS HE   WOULD MAKE CONCESSIONS ON DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD _ New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft, grilled for
hours by legislators Wednesday, defended the widely publicized plan
to move the football team here but privately said he would agree to
changes in the $350 million proposal to make it more palatable for
legislators and taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Before the marathon hearing before the General Assembly ended
late last night, Kraft and state negotiators were already tinkering
with the agreement, looking for a graceful way to lessen
controversial luxury seat guarantees that could cost taxpayers as
much as $17.5 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Those guarantees, agreed to in a memorandum of understanding
signed last month between Kraft and Governor John Rowland, would
make up the difference if the team was unable to sell all of the
expensive club seats and corporate boxes in the stadium Connecticut
proposes to build.
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with the deal said the team was willing to make
concessions that would lower the state's potential liability, but
nothing so drastic that it would endanger the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   While no one would say just how the outline could change,
discussions were expected to continue almost around the clock until
the exact language is agreed upon and a final bill is ready for
state legislators. A special session vote is scheduled for Tuesday.
The legislation, if approved, will amount to a binding contract to
move the team here from Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're negotiating a host of things _ the guarantee, the exit
fee ...'' said House Majority Leader Moira Lyons, a Stamford
Democrat, referring to penalties Kraft would pay if the team left
the state before the 30-year lease concludes. She said she did not
know how the guarantee would be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Others familiar with the negotiations said the legislation could
be written without a specific stadium site in mind, in the event
the current proposed location, on which a steam plant now sits, is
deemed to have overwhelming environmental problems that would
prohibit construction. The bill would also authorize the state to
borrow more than is needed to cover the stadium costs, perhaps $407
million in all, to cover infrastructure and part of a proposed
convention center, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft, looking nervous as he took the hot seat in the largest
hearing room available at the state Capitol, answered lawmakers'
questions on just about every aspect of the project.
</P>
<P>
   While he tried to allay fears about environmental costs, luxury
seating guarantees, and how a maintenance slush fund will be used,
Capitol police tried to dispel another potential problem: About 75
labor protesters chanting ``What do you want? Good jobs. When do
you want them? Now.'' The group was quickly diverted out of the
Legislative Office Building.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters also passed out slices of cheese before the hearing
to symbolize other human service needs in the state, but Kraft kept
his composure throughout the ordeal, which was reasonably tame _
certainly not as rowdy as a community meeting in South Boston where
Kraft unsuccessfully tied to sell a stadium plan.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing Wednesday, few lawmakers said they opposed
the plan to move the team to a site along the Connecticut River
here by 2001, although many voiced skepticism over the benefits of
luring an NFL franchise and the total pricetag.
</P>
<P>
   Even the state representative from the neighborhood within
walking distance of the proposed stadium site seemed contented by a
promise from Kraft's son, Jonathan, that the team would rely on
local small-business owners for stadium operations and Robert
Kraft's assertion that property values around the facility will not
go down.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Evelyn Mantilla, a Hartford Democrat, later said
she wanted a 30 percent job guarantee for people in the
neighborhood that abuts the site. She said she is also worried
about displacement, traffic, noise, and air pollution resulting
from the stadium and she hoped the team would tell her what she
wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not opposed to the Patriots coming to Hartford,'' Mantilla
said. ``I'm concerned because none of my questions have been
answered.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kraft, who also testified, said he was not discouraged
by the tough questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were treated in a warm way,'' the younger Kraft said. ``...
People were open-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   As for any changes in the agreement signed last month, the
younger Kraft said: ``We would expect it to materially embody'' the
original language. ``If we were going to negotiate, we certainly
wouldn't do it in the press.''
</P>
<P>
   But sources said both sides were finding room to negotiate parts
of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, who secretly negotiated the deal with Kraft, was the
first to testify, spinning figures and pitching the plan as the
only option for revitalizing Hartford, a city that exudes poverty
just beyond its clean and corporate downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vote on Tuesday is not about them,'' Rowland said,
referring to the Krafts and their team. ``This vote on Tuesday is
about us. It's about Hartford, it's about Connecticut, a vision for
the future of our entire community. ... The alternative is to lay
dormant.''
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that $650 million in public funds was spent
revitalizing Bridgeport, one of the poorest cities in the nation,
by doing things such as luring a minor-league baseball team there.
</P>
<P>
   He also apologized for the secretive and hasty process that led
to last month's dramatic announcement that he had struck a deal to
lure the team away from Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft, who met privately with legislators for several hours
before the hearing, was the second witness who appeared and he
spent nearly 90 minutes emphasizing three points: That the 10
percent tax on stadium revenue that will help pay for the stadium
was the equivalent of an $8 million annual lease payment that will
grow over time; that the team is paying for the operational costs
of the stadium, something he said is unusual in publicly financed
deals; and that the team is being generous in its commitment to
develop the University of Connecticut football team, which will
also play in the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal has been portrayed as a sweetheart deal,'' Kraft
said. ``I don't want to do a deal that isn't a good deal both ways.
... We are committing to spending $70 million of our capital for a
hotel, and an NFL retail and virtual reality development. These two
projects will only succeed if the Adriaen's Landing project
succeeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Adriaen's Landing is a $1 billion project that would include the
stadium, possibly a convention center, housing, retail stores, and
entertainment along the river.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft also said he was not approaching the deal as a cold,
bottom-line-fixated businessman. If he were, he said, he could have
sold the franchise to Los Angeles or Houston and made more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to go to L.A. We're not going to Houston. Our
family will not move this team out of New England ... and we want
to be able to compete with the other stadiums in the NFL,'' Kraft
said.
</P>
<P>
   The seat guarantees, he said, ``force us to work together very
closely to make this a successful project and we want to feel the
private capital investment we're making in this project will
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft received polite applause before he left the hearing, hours
before the public was allowed to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the citizen commentary _ the strongest of the day _
focused on union jobs, worries about increased property taxes, the
environment, traffic, and the secrecy of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Panzarella, a part-time musician, drove up from New Haven
to voice his opposition, and waited in an anteroom to put in his
two cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the biggest boondoggle and waste of a half
billion dollars the Legislature can come up with,'' he said. ``But
I think it's a done deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
