<SLUG> BC-NY-VACCO-ELECTION-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACCO FAILS IN BID TO VERIFY VOTERS IN RACE FOR ATTORNEY GENERAL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lawyers for Attorney General Dennis Vacco
acknowledged on Wednesday that their effort to have the police
verify the registration of thousands of New York City voters could
not proceed because the Giuliani administration would not cooperate
without a court order.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of telephone conferences and trips between New York
City and Albany, aides to Vacco and his Democratic challenger,
Eliot Spitzer, both sought judicial intervention to determine who
would be certified as the state's next attorney general next
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call Wednesday morning, Justice Thomas Keegan of
state Supreme Court in Albany made clear to campaign officials and
city lawyers that he would not order the police to conduct
door-to-door searches to determine the eligibility of thousands of
residents who the Vacco campaign contends voted illegally in the
Nov. 3 election.
</P>
<P>
   In unofficial results by the state Board of Elections, Spitzer
led by 26,011 votes out of 4.2 million cast. While Spitzer has
declared victory, Vacco has not conceded, asserting that there was
widespread fraud in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Vacco campaign said a comparison of voting rolls
with credit reporting data indicated that 103,000 people in the
city might have been fraudulently registered. It invoked a
seldom-used state law providing for the police to question
residents whose eligibility had been challenged.
</P>
<P>
   An impasse ensued, however, over the interpretation of the law.
The Vacco campaign argued that it required only a single
commissioner's complaint for a police canvass to be set in motion.
The president of the city Board of Elections said it was a matter
for the whole board to decide. Keegan said it was an electoral
matter, not a judicial one. And Mayor Rudolph Giuliani declined to
act without the judge's order.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Spargo, a lawyer for Vacco's campaign, said Wednesday
that even without the police canvass, the Republican incumbent
still intended to prove that tens of thousands of votes were
fraudulently cast in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for alternatives to address the unwillingness of
the police to act,'' Spargo said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the campaign was considering using dozens of
volunteers to make telephone calls and conduct their own
investigation of the eligibility of voters and would present its
evidence to Keegan at a hearing on Monday. But he added that the
options being weighed would produce ``nothing with the
admissibility of police checks.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Spitzer's lawyers filed two motions in state
Supreme Court in Albany. One was to overcome an obstacle created
Tuesday by the New York City Board of Elections, whose 10 members
split along party lines and failed to certify the election returns
from the city.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's lawyers asked the court to compel the city's board to
meet on Saturday and not adjourn until it had certified the
election results and sent the figures to the state. Under state
law, elections are to be certified by the Board of Elections by
Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York City board's function is ministerial and they
have no jurisdiction over fraud,'' said state Sen. Martin Connor,
the Democratic minority leader and a lawyer for Spitzer's campaign.
``The action they took was inappropriate. It was a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Keegan signed an order requesting representatives
of the New York City Board of Elections to appear in court Friday
morning to explain why they failed to certify the results of
balloting in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's lawyers also asked Keegan to dismiss lawsuits by the
Vacco campaign that had asked for a new election to be held or for
the attorney general to be declared the winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Vacco campaign's effort to compel a police canvass of more
than 100,000 homes in heavily Democratic New York City produced an
outcry from Democrats who said it was aimed at areas where
Spitzer's lead was widest, particularly black and Hispanic
neighborhoods, and would intimidate voters and suppress turnout in
future elections.
</P>
<P>
   While the use of police officers produced predictably sharp
differences between the two parties, it also exposed some fissures
within the GOP. While the strategy has been championed by Vacco and
William Powers, the Republican Party state chairman, Gov. George
Pataki has distanced himself from the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican who is widely considered to have in
interest in national office, said he was concerned about using the
police to investigate voter fraud. ``You want people to become part
of the political process,'' he said. ``We want to do everything we
can to encourage people to come out and vote.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the law is so rarely used that election
officials have had to employ it only four times in the last two
years and only to check on a handful of voters, according to Naomi
Bernstein, a spokeswoman for the Board of Elections ``We certainly
haven't had anything on a scale like the latest case,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Giuliani said the Police Department could conduct a
check on the registration of as many as 10,000 residents without
substantial interruption of other police functions. But Wednesday,
administration officials said that they feared that the city would
be the target of a wave of lawsuits from civil liberties groups if
it began the police checks and reaffirmed that the city would not
undertake such an action without the protection of a court order.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco has appeared in public only once since the Nov. 3
election. But Spitzer is assuming the role of attorney
general-elect, with appearances Thursday in Rochester and Buffalo
on a tour of upstate cities.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Goldstein, Spitzer's campaign press secretary, said,
``Just because Vacco has been in hibernation for a month, that's
not going to stop Eliot Spitzer from meeting his new constituents
across New York State.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
