</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-PRESIDE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4-YEAR CONGRESSMAN TO PRESIDE OVER HOUSE IMPEACHMENT DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to modify lede graf. No other changes.)  (See also: IMPEACH, IMPEACH-DEFENSE, IMPEACH-LEGAL, IMPEACH-STARR,
IMPEACH-SCHIPPERS, IMPEACH-GRASSROOTS, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-RUFF,
IMPEACH-POLITICS, IMPEACH-TEXT, EDIT-IMPEACH) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill., is to preside next week in
the speaker's chair if, as expected, the full House debates
articles of impeachment against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   LaHood was picked by the outgoing speaker, Newt Gingrich, whose
aides asked LaHood on Monday whether he wanted the job. Republican
aides said Gingrich did not want to end his four-year tenure by
presiding over what is expected to be a highly divisive debate, and
that the incoming speaker, Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., did not want
his tenure to begin on that note.
</P>
<P>
   LaHood, 53, a former high school teacher and counselor to
delinquent teen-agers, has a reputation for fairness that
Republican leaders hope will translate into a calming influence on
the proceedings and will help give the party an aura of
even-handedness. He has not indicated how he would vote on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was elected to the House only four years ago with
the Republican rebel class of 1994, LaHood has not been associated
with the rebels. He was one of three of the new freshmen who did
not sign Gingrich's Contract With America. He also helped organize
a bipartisan House retreat in Hershey, Pa., last year to help
members get to know each other better and treat each other with
more civility.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, LaHood has presided in the speaker's chair perhaps
more often than any other Republican in recognition of his
knowledge on procedure, said his spokesman, Tim Butler. He accepts
the assignments willingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He views it as a high honor,'' Butler said. ``This will be one
of the most momentous votes taken in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   LaHood is in a seat once held by Everett McKinley Dirksen and
Bob Michel, both former Republican leaders. He is the grandson of
an immigrant from Lebanon and the son of a restaurant manager.
After teaching in Catholic schools for six years and working as a
counselor, he served as Michel's chief of staff in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 2253EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981209.0557 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SPACE-STATION-NYT     12-09 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SPACE-STATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 ASTRONAUTS INSTALL ANTENNAS ON THE INTERNATIONAL SPACE STATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASA's astronaut construction workers Wednesday added
communications antennas and removed unneeded equipment from the
exterior of the space station in another spacewalk from the shuttle
Endeavour.
</P>
<P>
   Starting a scheduled seven-hour spacewalk early, Col. Jerry Ross
of the Air Force and Dr. James Newman, a physicist, emerged from
Endeavour's airlock at 3:34 p.m. Eastern time with the primary task
of improving the communications systems aboard the two station
sections docked to the shuttle's cargo bay.
</P>
<P>
   Less than half through the excursion from the shuttle, the two
astronauts completed their primary objective _ installing two,
100-pound communications antennas on opposite sides of the
American-made Unity connecting module.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts wrestled with the suitcase-sized antennas as they
pulled them through a narrow tunnel into the cargo bay. Then, with
Ross riding the shuttle's 50-foot robot arm and Newman moving up
the side of the module on a tether line, the spacewalkers moved the
antennas halfway up the 35-foot-tall module.
</P>
<P>
   Each astronaut installed an antenna and Newman hooked his to a
video cable running down from the Russian-built Zarya module. On
Thursday, when the six-member crew enters the station modules for
the first time, the astronauts will hook the antennas to equipment
on the inside and test a video conferencing system that will be
used in the early stages of station construction.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's spacewalk, the second of three planned for the
11-day mission, was less difficult than the one conducted on
Monday, when the astronaut team had to hook up 40 electrical and
data connectors attached to stiff cables.
</P>
<P>
   Successful completion of that task allowed electricity to flow
from Zarya's solar power panel into Unity, activating the module.
</P>
<P>
   The new antennas also will give NASA's Mission Control at the
Johnson Space Center, in Houston, the ability to monitor Unity and
to have direct control over operations on the station without
having to go through Russian ground stations.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts quickly moved through the other objectives of the
spacewalk, which included erecting a folding sunshade over a
computer mounted outside Unity.
</P>
<P>
   Working around the 7-story, 35-ton Zarya-Unity stack, the
astronauts also were to remove restraints used to stabilize four
Unity hatchways during launching. These hatches will be docking
ports for other station modules, including the framework for a
giant solar array and a cupola viewing port, that will be added in
the five-year construction period.
</P>
<P>
   Newman also was to install insulating covers on trunnion pins
that held Unity in Endeavour's shuttle bay when launched last
Friday. Leaving the pins exposed would allow heat to escape the
module and make it more difficult to regulate temperatures inside.
</P>
<P>
   As the astronauts worked their way around the station's aluminum
exterior, bright sunlight illuminated the ``Unity'' emblem, causing
Ross to remark to his partner: ``Kind of neat working up here right
by the Unity sign, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the spacewalk, ground controllers gave the
astronauts permission to try to unstick one of two rolled-up
antennas on Zarya. The astronauts confirmed on Monday that
explosive bolts that were to unfurl the four-foot long antennas had
fired after Zarya was launched on Nov. 20, but failed to deploy the
devices, to be used to help dock other ships to the Russian module.
</P>
<P>
   Newman tapped one of the antennas free with a 10-foot-long
extendable grappling hook that was being delivered aboard Endeavour
for later station crews to use. Newman, attached to the robot arm
maneuvered by Lt. Col. Nancy J. Currie of the Army, was kept at a
safe distance while prodding the antenna into its correct position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
