<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2102 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      12-09 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS UNVEIL ARTICLES OF IMPEACHMENT AGAINST CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Unmoved by two days of White House defense
arguments, Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee unveiled
four articles of impeachment Wednesday accusing President Clinton
of lying under oath, obstructing justice and abusing his power.
</P>
<P>
   Draft copies of the articles, which the committee begins
debating late Thursday, were handed to committee members as they
listened to White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff conclude his
lengthy, meticulous arguments against impeaching the president.
</P>
<P>
   Prepared with no input from Democrats on the committee, the
articles accuse Clinton of behavior that meets the ``high crimes
and misdemeanors'' standard for presidential impeachment written
into the Constitution 211 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Alleging that Clinton's effort to conceal his affair with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky betrayed the public trust, each
of the articles concludes: ``William Jefferson Clinton, by such
conduct, warrants impeachment and trial, and removal from office
and disqualification to hold and enjoy any office of honor, trust
or profit under the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House immediately blasted the Republican-controlled
committee for distributing the drafts of the articles of
impeachment before the president's defense had been completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``After denying the president the right to see the charges
against him before offering his defense, the committee majority
decided to proceed with impeachment without even listening to his
defense,'' said White House spokesman Jim Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said he will
press the panel to vote on the articles by late Saturday. He also
has agreed to let the committee vote on a Democratic alternative to
impeachment, a resolution censuring the president and demanding his
signature on the resolution document rebuking him for
``reprehensible conduct with a subordinate.''
</P>
<P>
   If any of the articles of impeachment are approved _ the panel
is expected to send at least one to the full House _ Clinton will
become only the second president in U.S. history to face an
impeachment vote by the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   House debate on any article of impeachment or the
Democratic-sponsored censure resolution, if it clears the
committee, would be scheduled next week. If impeachment is
approved, the president would go on trial in the Senate, a process
some experts predict will take six months.
</P>
<P>
   Only one president, Andrew Johnson, has been impeached by the
House. Following his Senate trial in 1868, Johnson was acquitted by
one vote. In 1974, President Richard Nixon resigned after the House
Judiciary Committee approved articles of impeachment against him
for his role in the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting across the street from the Capitol in the same
wood-panelled room where the articles against Nixon were debated,
the Judiciary Committee on Wednesday heard Ruff concede that
Clinton might have been more than misleading in his behavior
surrounding the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   When Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., asked if Clinton had lied
under oath, a hush fell over the committee room as Ruff, carefully
measuring each word, said that ``reasonable people ... could
determine that he (Clinton) crossed over that line and that, what
for him was truthful and misleading or nonresponsive and misleading
or evasive, was, in fact, false.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ruff argued, Clinton's sworn testimony did not
amount to perjury, which requires an intent to lie. ``The president
has not committed a high crime or misdemeanor,'' Ruff said.
Clinton's ``conduct, although morally reprehensible, does not
warrant impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   When the panel's nationally televised hearings resume in the
Rayburn Office Building on Thursday, the committee's Democratic
counsel, Abbe Lowell, and Republican counsel David Schippers will
make their closing arguments before debate begins on the articles
of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the committee were prepared to push through a
motion to allow Schippers to show portions of a videotape of
Clinton's Jan. 17 testimony in the Paula Jones sexual harassment
lawsuit. It was out of this testimony, a sworn deposition leading
up to a trial of the now settled-case, that the president's
impeachment troubles emerged.
</P>
<P>
   The tape shows an uneasy Clinton at times speaking barely above
a whisper, at others hesitating and stammering as he responds to
questions. He denies under oath that he had ``sexual relations''
with Lewinsky, then pauses 14 seconds before answering ``I'm not
sure'' to one question, then hedging his response when asked if he
and the former intern were ever alone.
</P>
<P>
   While transcripts of the deposition were released by Jones'
lawyers and later by the House Judiciary Committee, the videotape
of his testimony has never been seen in public. Republicans who
want the tape shown Thursday consider it damaging to the
president's case.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's testimony in the Jones case forms the basis for one of
the two articles of impeachment accusing the president of perjury.
The second alleges that he lied during his Aug. 17 testimony before
a federal grand jury being used by independent counsel Kenneth
Starr to investigate the Clinton-Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   While modeled after the impeachment resolutions from the
Watergate scandal, the articles of impeachment were based largely
on Starr's 453-page report to Congress. The article accusing
Clinton of obstruction of justice outlines seven instances when the
president attempted to ``delay, impede, cover up and conceal''
evidence related to the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   The abuse of power article alleges the president ``frivolously
and corruptly'' asserted executive privilege to keep aides from
having to cooperate with Starr's investigation. In addition, the
article accuses Clinton of making false and misleading statements
about the affair to Cabinet members, aides, the House Judiciary
Committee and the American people.
</P>
<P>
   While the article accusing Clinton of lying to the grand jury
seems assured of winning approval from the 21 Republicans on the
Judiciary Committee, it is unlikely to draw support from any of the
16 Democrats on the panel
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, one or two of the committee Republicans have
expressed reservations about the articles accusing Clinton of
abusing his power and lying in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Rep. Amo Houghton, a New York Republican who is
not on the committee, announced that he would vote against any
article of impeachment that reaches the full House. He is the fifth
Republican _ all moderates _ to declare their opposition to
impeaching Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Three Democrats have said they will vote for impeachment.
Several other Democrats list themselves among the undecided should
the issue reach the full House.
</P>
<P>
   The House has 228 Republican members, 206 Democrats and one
independent, who is expected to side with the Democrats on
impeachment. Democrats picked up five seats in last month's
elections, which means there will be a 223-211-1 division of the
House beginning in January.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton said he opposes impeachment but will support censure
because it ensures that Clinton's behavior is punished if
impeachment fails. ``I think an awful lot of people, in their heart
of hearts, would like to have another option to just up or down
impeachment,'' Houghton said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar sentiments were expressed by Texas Rep. Sheila Jackson
Lee, a Democrat on the House Judiciary Committee and one of the
four authors of the impeachment resolution the panel will debate
late this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find common ground, and this gives us another place
for people to go in punishing the president short of impeachment,''
Jackson Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hyde said he thought it was fair to have the committee
vote on the censure resolution, he personally opposes it. Even if
the committee, as expected, rejects the resolution, Hyde's decision
to allow a vote could put pressure on Republican leaders to allow a
similar censure vote by the full House. Incoming House Speaker Bob
Livingston of Louisiana has not indicated whether he will allow a
censure vote in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde confirmed that he plans to discuss the case against the
president with some of his GOP colleagues who are not on the
committee, but he does not intend to lobby them to support
impeachment. Instead, he said, he will urge them to ``keep their
powder dry'' until they have all the facts and the committee has
finished its work.
</P>
<P>
   The committee chairman also wrote a letter to all House members
to ``respectfully request that you withhold making any decision''
until the committee votes on articles of impeachment and committee
members ``have had an opportunity to discuss the merits with you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
