</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRUDENTIAL-REDEVELOPMENT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY PROPOSING COMPLEX OF OFFICES, EATERIES AT PRUDENTIAL SITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES  &UR; -- &LR;  sprawling 1.3-million-square-foot campus-style
office complex with up to nine buildings is planned for a 35-acre
site in the Warner Center area of suburban Woodland Hills where
Prudential Health Care has its western regional headquarters,
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lennar Partners, a unit of Miami-based LNR Property Corp.,
recently bought a piece of land and is willing to spend more than
$200 &UR;  &LR; million on the development. It will be the most ambitious
project proposed for the Warner Center area during the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Lennar purchased the land, widely considered a prime site, from
Prudential in August for an undisclosed price. The project will
feature a collection of buildings between three and five stories
tall, several restaurants and a day-care center.
</P>
<P>
   Lennar will build in four phases with the tallest buildings
placed farthest fromthe street. The site will be subdivided into
18 parcels, in part to facilitate financing, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Read, vice president of acquisitions for Irvine,
Calif.-based Lennar Partners, said said the company hopes to start
construction in the second or third quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Lennar is leasing two buildings totaling 450,000 square feet
back to Prudential and would like to keep that company as a tenant,
Read said. Prudential officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to speculate on who the new tenants might be,
Read said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would love to do a build-to-suit (project) but we are fully
prepared to go forward on speculation. There are really no large
blocks of contiguous space in that market right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call the existing buildings to be torn down so the net
amount of expansion at the site will be about 800,000 square feet.
About 60 &UR;  &LR; percent of the land will be left as open space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current buildings were built in the late 1970s to
Prudential's specifications. They are football fields. We think
that we can make better use of the site and make a nicer
environment than is currently there,'' Read said.
</P>
<P>
   Lennar's project will, in general terms, mirror what is in vogue
in the west San Fernando Valley's office market
 &UR; -- &LR;  lush landscaping and campus-style complexes. The market is
tight, with a vacancy rate of under 10 &UR;  &LR; percent.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Reitmann, an analyst at the valley office of commercial
broker Grubb &AMP; Ellis, said about 200,000 square feet of space was
leased in the west valley during the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The west valley is definitely strong. It's one of those areas
that it really going,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lennar has already briefed Los Angeles City Councilwoman Laura
Chick and her staff on the plan and discussed it Wednesday night
during a meeting of the Woodland Hills/West Hills Neighborhood
Advisory Planning Council. Some directors of the Woodland Hills
Homeowner Organization got a briefing earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Chick said she will make a decision on whether to support the
project after homeowners mull it over and it is evaluated by city
planners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say this. I am very eager to see development come to
Warner Center. I have seen some (drawings) and I think it would be
quite an amenity. There is lots of open space and pathway areas.
It's almost a parklike setting,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chick did note that the city has a ``very detailed'' specific
plan that stipulates the kind of mitigation that would need to be
done for increased traffic.
</P>
<P>
   David Shender, a principal at the Pasadena, Calif.-based traffic
engineering consulting firm of Linscott, Law &AMP; Greenspan, estimates
that the project would add about 2,800 vehicles to the area a day.
</P>
<P>
   Lennar would pay about $3.5 &UR;  &LR; million on mitigation factors,
including widening streets and adding turn lanes to intersections.
The traffic management plan was based on guidelines set by the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We analyzed 21 intersections in the Warner Center area and
determined on a preliminary basis that 10 would require traffic
mitigation measures to alleviate the project's impact,'' Shender
said.
</P>
<P>
   So far nothing has been proposed for the freeway ramps at De
Soto or Canoga avenues or Topanga Canyon Boulevard which are
typically congested during rush hours. Shender declined to discuss
specifics of the traffic management plan because it is being
reviewed by the city.
</P>
<P>
   But since the project is located on Canoga Avenue, he expects
that ramp to bear the brunt of new traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Murley, president of the Woodland Hills Homeowners
Organization, said the project sounds good in general terms but he
is concerned about the parcel being split into lots and the
additional traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some problems but there isn't enough information for
us to tell them what we think will work and won't work. If you
can't improve the flow of traffic, just leave it the way it is,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   New large developments in Warner Center have been blocked since
1994 when the Los Angeles Unified School District sued the city,
claiming the Warner Center Specific Plan did not adequately
consider the effects of expansion on noise, traffic and pollution
problems at area schools. However, projects of 2 million square
feet or less, or those already approved, can go forward.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
