<SLUG> BC-GLF-WILCOX-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTS CUP HAS HIS VOTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Golf's goofy season, so named because of the
embarrassment of riches left on the greens after all the official
money has been claimed, finally gets serious this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion is the third biennial Presidents Cup, an
us-against-the-whole-world-except-Europe team competition held
every year the Ryder Cup isn't. This is not as unfair as it seems
because the U.S. team has about 10 of the world's top 20 players.
</P>
<P>
   And it's an event actually worth watching since it's about
winning a trophy rather than a check.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a rare opportunity to glimpse one of the world's best
courses, Australia's Royal Melbourne Golf Club. Contoured greens
and Santa Ana-like conditions forecasted will cause Melbourne to
look a lot like the Valley in July _ or this week minus the heat.
</P>
<P>
   And while this tournament does not have the impact of a Ryder
Cup, it sure got respectable in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   For this we can thank Fred Couples, who secured the Cup with a
dramatic last-hole putt in the 1996 matches at the Robert Trent
Jones Golf Club in Manassas, Va., and some teammates who thrust him
in that position.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. entered the Sunday singles (one-on-one) play with a
lead but as the day wound down, Couples and Vijay Singh came to the
17th hole with the team match square. Couples was clinging to a
one-stroke lead as he lined up a 40-foot birdie putt.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure? Davis Love III, who had completed play, thought (begin
ital)his(end ital) head was going to blow up and he wasn't the one
holding the putter.
</P>
<P>
   Couples rolled his putt in and the Americans, who can't seem to
beat Europe anymore, celebrated what was considered a consolation
prize.
</P>
<P>
   Once order was restored, Singh took a stab at a 25-footer to
prolong the match, but his putt veered off to the right.
</P>
<P>
   That dramatic finish helped validate a competition that many
thought Australia-Florida native Greg Norman cooked up because he
can't play in the Ryder Cup matches.
</P>
<P>
   The fact the international team went on a crying jag in the wake
of its defeat also helped give the Presidents Cup a boost in
stature.
</P>
<P>
   The international team, angered at losing a close match and the
unfeeling television producers that ordered up shots of Singh's
wife crying after her husband's missed putt, vowed not to let it
happen again.
</P>
<P>
   So they retired for a grief fest at their cabin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could have been in the cabin after we lost. . . I don't
think any of us really realized how important it was,'' Nick Price
told the Associated Press this week. ``Any of us who were sitting
in that cabin that evening understand the importance of this event
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that came out of that session was a demand the match
be played played outside the U.S. on an alternating basis.
</P>
<P>
   So the team from ``up over'' headed ``down under'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   On top of it online: The PGA Tour's Presidents Cup web site at
www.pgatour.com features real-time scoring and you can even listen
in on press conferences.
</P>
<P>
   At the completion of each hole, a scorer enters results into a
hand-held device, which transmits the data to an IBM PC server.
Hole-by-hole results are updated in real-time across the network
and distributed to broadcasters, scoreboards, on-site IBM
information kiosks and to sports fans worldwide via Internet.
</P>
<P>
   College signings: Three top-flight high school golfers have
signed letters of intent with USC. They are David Oh of Whitney
High in Cerritos, Candi Kung of Fountain Valley High and Mikaela
Parmild of Goteborgs Hogre Samskola in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Oh is one of the best young players in the country and is ranked
seventh in the Titleist/Golfweek national junior rankings. He won
the 1997 CIF championship and is an American Junior Golf
Association Rolex All-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an excellent recruiting year on both the men's and
women's sides,'' said Kurt Schuette, USC's director of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Saying goodbye: Swing guru David Leadbetter has ended his
two-year teaching relationship with Korean star Se Ri Pak.
Leadbetter could not handle the circus atmosphere that now
surrounds one of the world's top women players. He quit via a
letter to one of her many managers. He must have learned that from
former pupil Nick Faldo, who this year informed Leadbetter his
services were no longer needed via a letter. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-98 2313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
