<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2152 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SANDERS-T     12-09 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SANDERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' SANDERS PRACTICES, BUT STILL IFFY FOR CHIEFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys defensive coordinator Dave Campo walked
off the practice field yesterday and tried to explain life without
star cornerback Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an impact player,'' Campo began. ``He takes part of the
field away. That's what he does. He makes the opposing offense have
to account for his whereabouts. We've had to change some things.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the more Campo talked, the more antsy he became
regarding Sanders' absence during the past 3 1/2 games with a
sprained big toe on his left foot, and his iffy status for Sunday's
road matchup with the Kansas City Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the most important thing is his health,'' Campo
said. ``We want him ready for down the road. But I just wish it was
one way or another, where he was going to play or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Sanders practiced yesterday for the first time since
suffering the injury against the Arizona Cardinals Nov. 15, his
availability against the Chiefs is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, whose left shoe has been fitted with a metal plate to
restrict his movement, gingerly tested his toe in some team passing
drills, and did some rehabilitation work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt a little,'' Sanders said. ``I don't know yet. We still
got quite a few days to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey was more optimistic about Sanders'
chances of playing than he has been in some time, but remained
noncommittal.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders ``was out there with his pads on, pushed off on his toe,
changed directions,'' Gailey said. ``We'll have to see how he's
doing after doing that. It's good to have him on the field. We'll
just see how it goes the rest of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said cornerback Charlie Williams is scheduled to start
against the Chiefs, who feature one of the league's hottest passing
attacks. Kansas City quarterback Rich Gannon has thrown for six
touchdowns the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   While Sanders' availability is uncertain, what is clear is the
Cowboys are a different team without him.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are 0-5 without him in the starting lineup the past
two seasons, including losses against Minnesota and New Orleans the
past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   What appears to be more telling is the play of the Cowboys'
defense, which has seemingly crumbled since Sanders was injured
against the Cardinals. Before that game, the Cowboys ranked seventh
in the NFL in total defense, 13th against the pass and had given up
nine touchdown passes through nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Cowboys' defense has dropped to 14th overall,
24th against the pass and has given up 15 touchdown passes the past
four games.
</P>
<P>
   But the impact of Sanders' absence goes beyond giving up big
chunks of passing yards. Schematically, the Cowboys have had to
change roughly 30 percent of their defense.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, his chief replacement, said the Cowboys played more
man coverages and more press defense with Sanders. Without him,
they are playing more zone and laying off the receivers. Safety
Kenny Wheaton said the Cowboys are also playing a larger variety of
coverages to make up for the loss of Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We mix it up to keep teams on their toes,'' Wheaton said.
``They never know which way we are going to roll our coverage. With
him, everybody knows we are going to roll to the other side and
leave him alone.''
</P>
<P>
   And considering Sanders' knack for the big play _ he has
returned one interception for a touchdown, two punts for touchdowns
and has a 55-yard pass reception _ the Cowboys also miss his
psychological influence.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, pointing to Sunday's 22-3 loss to the Saints, said
Sanders' big-play ability can jump-start a team. And his mere
presence would have forced the Saints to account for his
whereabouts and likely alter their strategy.
</P>
<P>
   His absence has also impacted the Cowboys emotionally. Defensive
tackle Chad Hennings said the team has missed Sanders, and his
return against the Chiefs would be a huge boost for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having a safety blanket as a little kid that you had
to go to bed with all the time,'' Hennings said. ``The security
puts you more at ease, knowing that he's back there ... it's going
to be all right. I don't know if he's going to play, but we've been
praying for him to come back for a long time now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
