<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BRASS MEETS WITH BROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT MCHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin Brown, baseball's top free agent right-hander, spent most
of Wednesday meeting with Dodgers officials and will let the club
know Friday if he is still interested in playing in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone did not make an official
offer, but the parameters are a six-year deal worth more than $72
million.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who appeared in the past two World Series for Florida and
San Diego, returned to his home outside Atlanta immediately after
the meetings. Brown and his agent, Scott Boras, spoke to the Angels
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 33, told Malone that playing closer to home would be
critical to his decision. But Brown also told Malone that he liked
the Dodger commitment to winning and the successful track record of
manager Davey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is we are serious players,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding for Brown is expected to lead the agenda at the
four-day baseball winter meetings, which begin Friday in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis is considered the favorite, but Colorado and Baltimore
also are interested. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
