<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-PROMOTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SCHOOL TO END SOCIAL PROMOTION FOR FAILING STUDENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY AND DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Vaughn Next Century Learning Center has ended
the practice of promoting failing students to the next grade,
taking a lead in the district's effort to comply with the new state
ban on social promotion, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state law that will first apply during the 1999-2000
school year, students who are not performing at grade level at the
end of the term will have to attend summer school or take other
remedial tutoring. If they do not progress, they will be held back.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, a nationally renowned charter school in suburban
Pacoima, is launching its push to comply with the law by holding an
informational meeting tonight for parents of 200 students who have
been identified as needing extra help in reading. Those students,
in first through fifth grades, will attend an intensive weeklong
literacy program starting in January.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to bring the students up to grade level by the end of
the school year and prevent them from slipping further behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' said Tami Dozal, a first-grade teacher at Vaughn
who referred five students to the program. ``There are kids going
on (to the next grade level) when they're not ready. We have to do
something about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   By starting midway through the year, instead of waiting to bring
students up to speed in summer school, Vaughn should be able to
catch students who might otherwise fall even further behind during
the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wait for summer school?'' principal Yvonne Chan asked.
``Why let them fail for six more months?''
</P>
<P>
   The school board two weeks ago adopted a districtwide policy to
end social promotion that will take effect July 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Collins, director of curriculum, instruction and assessment
for the Los Angeles Unified School District, said he wasn't aware
of any other campus complying with the new state law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, a student's performance will be gauged on grades
and scores on the statewide Stanford 9 standardized test.
</P>
<P>
   Districts will be required to hold back poor-performing students
in grades two, three, four and five -- the grade between elementary
and middle school -- and eight -- the grade between middle and high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he did not know how much it would cost to end
social promotion but said the LAUSD expects to receive $13 million
from the state to implement summer school and intercession programs
at elementary schools -- an amount that will pay for needed
remedial classes.
</P>
<P>
   At Vaughn, 384 students in grades one through five have been
identified as performing below grade level, according to
standardized test scores and report-card grades.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly how many LAUSD students performing below
grade level are passed on every year, but estimates range from 20
percent to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's new system establishes three tiers of students testing
below grade level.
</P>
<P>
   One group -- the 200 students whose parents were invited to
tonight's meeting -- needs a little more help to catch up. Those
pupils aren't in serious danger of repeating a grade but are
scoring around the 37th percentile on standardized tests for their
class.
</P>
<P>
   In the second group, about 120 students, learning significantly
slower than their peers, are at risk of being held back a year and
already are receiving intensive tutoring, Chan said. Administrators
will decide in mid-May whether they will be retained or sent to
summer school.
</P>
<P>
   In the third tier are 64 students with learning disabilities who
will be referred to a special-education program.
</P>
<P>
   Parents welcomed the help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good idea,'' said Marta Ramirez, whose 7-year-old son
is having trouble writing and will attend the January literacy
program. ``He's a little slow. He needs to write more.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
