<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-CANAL-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANAL FEVER
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By JAMES WILSON 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    PANAMA CITY, PANAMA _ The United States will forever hand over
control of the Panama Canal to the Panamanian government on Dec.
31, 1999. It will be a proud day for Panamanians, but they won't
have much time to bask in the historic moment. Private investors
are already busy drawing up plans to take away a piece of the
canal's abundant business.
 &HT;    Around 13,000 ships pass through the canal each year, hauling an
estimated 4 percent of the world's goods around the globe.
Moreover, about 70 percent of all trade through the canal is coming
from or headed to the United States.
 &HT;    To maintain its competitive edge, the current Panama Canal
Commission (PCC) _ which will become the Panama Canal Authority
following the management change next year _ is well into a US$1
billion improvement program that includes a widening of the narrow
Gaillard Cut, where the canal was gouged through the Continental
Divide. Galvanized by a big rise in canal traffic in 1995 and 1996,
the widening was speeded up and is due for completion by 2002.
Two-way traffic will be possible for even the largest ships and
canal capacity will rise.
 &HT;    But with steadily increasing traffic, projected at 2 percent per
year, there are plenty of entrepreneurs who scent an opportunity.
Schemes abound for capturing a slice of the action from the canal.
 &HT;    These so-called ``dry canal'' schemes are built on analysts'
bullish predictions for growth in containerization of about 8
percent per year. A dry canal system would include new ports where
containers would be unloaded and rushed across land to a waiting
ship on the other side. Nothing has come to fruition, yet, but
dreams are alive and on the drawing board.
 &HT;    ``Nicaragua will become the crossroads of world inter-oceanic
commerce,'' says Don Bosco, whose group, CINN, has been working
with Nicaragua's government on a dry canal plan since 1995 and
recently submitted its viability studies. The government's verdict
is expected by the end of the year. CINN would head a private
consortium to build two new ports and a 375-kilometer railway. The
estimated cost: at least $2.3 billion.
 &HT;    Bosco harks back to the days of the California gold rush _ when
both Nicaragua and Panama became favored routes from the U.S. east
coast to the gold mines _ to show there is ``historical precedent''
for a Nicaragua crossing. ``There is a clear and compelling market
demand for a certain kind of transportation service ... a new
trans-Isthmian service to exclusively transport containerized cargo
in a high-volume, high-speed mode,'' says Bosco.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, a U.S.-based group, Owl Securities and Investments,
plans a deep-water port on Costa Rica's Atlantic coast that could
also serve as a 'dry canal' terminal.
 &HT;    So will the Panama Canal have to live with some sharp new
competition muscling in? Although Alberto Aleman, who is the PCC's
senior administrator, acknowledges the canal does face competition
_ a change from 20 years ago _ he chuckles at such talk. ``Panama
has much more to offer,'' he says, describing it as ``the only port
in the world that has two oceans plus a canal that runs through it.
You can look at it as one big port.''
 &HT;    Indeed some big names _ port operators Hutchison Whampoa of Hong
Kong, Taiwan's Evergreen, and U.S.-based Stevedoring Services of
America _ all run ports in Panama, on both Atlantic and Pacific
coasts. The growth of SSA's Manzanillo International Terminal, set
up in 1994 in a joint venture with a Panamanian partner, has been
breathtaking. Last year, it handled 600,000 20-ft equivalent units
(TEUs, the standard container measurement). Hutchison and Evergreen
are presently unrolling their own operations.
 &HT;    Add in the historic old Panama railroad, which Kansas City
Southern Railways and Mi-Jack, a U.S. terminal operator, are
rebuilding after paying $60 million for a concession, and Panama
already has the key elements of the sort of dry-canal transshipment
operation being talked about elsewhere.
 &HT;    So why are other hopefuls so bullish? CINN's Bosco say there is
plenty of trade to go around. ``In 2005, when we are up and
running, the available east-west market for dry canal services will
be 12.5 million TEUs. From that we will try to grab 10 percent,''
he says.
 &HT;    They also say that dry canals are tailor-made to accommodate the
new generation of `post-Panamax' ships, huge container vessels that
generate large economies of scale for their owners but which are
too big to travel through the canal's 1,000-feet-by-110-feet lock
chambers. ``Back in 1965 there was only one percent Panamax vessels
in the canal,'' says Aleman. ``Now it is 30 percent.''
 &HT;    These ships can only fit in single file through the canal's
narrowest reaches, meaning more headaches trying to get all boats
through canal waters within the benchmark 24 hours.
 &HT;    ``We are seeing more and more delays,'' says Roy Newall, a
shipping agent in the city of Colon at the canal's Atlantic
entrance, who says it is one of his clients' prime concerns. ``If
you have a ship sitting here for two or three or five days, it is
catastrophic. I have been here for 30 years and I just don't
remember so many lengthy delays as we have had in the last five
years.''
 &HT;    The PCC, says Aleman, is tackling the problem. ``The shipping
industry is more and more like the airline industry. Time is of the
essence. You cannot have ships waiting a week to go through the
canal. You have to make sure that they can rely on getting through
the canal in time. That is why we are focusing on building
reliability.'' Panamanian officials are not ignoring the trend
toward larger vessels, he says.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, after the current improvement program ends, the
only way to raise capacity would be to build another set of locks.
In 1993, a study by the United States, Panama and Japan concluded
that additional locks should be able to handle larger ships.
 &HT;    Will a new canal be built? At a likely cost of $7 billion,
nobody is rushing to make a decision. It's being considered, but,
says Aleman, ``It does not make any sense to build that sort of
project if you do not have the demand.''
 &HT;    Says Newall: ``I feel quite sure that by 2010 or 2015, we will
have an extra canal.'' Shippers watch with interest. Next
December's transition ushers the canal not only into a new era of
ownership, but into a time of critical decisions.
 &HT;    Part of the interest and concern surrounds the circumstances of
the change. The world's richest nation is transferring the canal
into the hands of a small, relatively poor country. Charges of
nepotism and cronyism have already surfaced in Panama. Some
criticize Panama President Ernesto Perez Balladares for naming some
family and political allies to the governing board of the Panama
Canal Authority, which takes over after the United States leaves.
 &HT;    ``It is a way of life here. I think the industry is concerned
about nepotism and bribery and corruption in this part of the
world. I think it is a genuine concern,'' says one shipping agent
in Panama.
 &HT;    A political football and cash cow? ``I don't buy it,'' says
Aleman, who has held his post since 1996. The 47-year-old
Panamanian engineer has been named to head the PCA until 2005.
 &HT;    The makeup of the PCA board is filled with experience, says
Aleman, who notes that of the 11 people on the board, four are
already on the PCC; another three already sit on a
canal-consultation committee; and one used to work at the PCC. As
for future appointments, a president can only name three new
members every three years, making it difficult to pack the board
with favorites.
 &HT;    ``Panama is really committed to running the canal in an
efficient way,'' says Aleman.
 &HT;    Shipping industry officials agree. ``We do not expect any
changes. We have a lot of confidence,'' says Kim Gadegaard, vice
president for Latin American services of the Denmark-based Maersk
shipping line, a major canal customer. That confidence will be
tested in the next century.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
