<HEADER>
A2180 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-TX-WELFARE-REFOR     12-09 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TX-WELFARE-REFORM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Post-welfare study: 55% get steady jobs
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Many people who have been denied government aid
as a result of Texas' new welfare law have found steady jobs that
pay more than the minimum wage, according to a study released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush said the survey, conducted by the Texas
Department of Human Services and researchers from Texas A&AMP;M
University, suggests that welfare time limits and work requirements
push people into jobs, not poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more compassionate to help people find a job than it is
to make them dependent on government,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But some say the results may be skewed because those who chose
not to respond or couldn't be reached _ almost half of those in the
survey sample _ are the ones most likely to be in dire straits.
They also note that many of the jobs offer little chance of
advancement, and that the average annual salary of respondents _
about $11,100 _ is below the federal poverty standard for a family
of three, which is $13,650.
</P>
<P>
   State officials point out that when food stamps and Medicaid are
factored in, a mother who works full-time at the minimum wage earns
107 percent of the federal poverty level, as opposed to 73 percent
of the poverty level on the welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Human Services Commissioner Eric Bost acknowl- edged
that the state's booming economy is at least partly responsible for
the success of those who have made the transition from welfare to
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real test of welfare reform will be when we have a major
downturn,'' said Chris King of the Center for the Study of Human
Resources at the University of Texas. King said Bush and President
Clinton are ``the luckiest guys in the world in terms of reforming
welfare'' because state and federal changes have corresponded with
a strong economy.
</P>
<P>
   Texas instituted work requirements and time limits on benefits
for welfare recipients in 1996. Under the new rules, a person is
limited to 12, 24 or 36 months on welfare, depending on their
education and work experience. After the time limit is reached,
five years must pass before a person again becomes eligible for
help. Work or job training is required for most people between the
ages of 18 and 59.
</P>
<P>
   The federal welfare reform law passed by Congress in 1996 also
includes work requirements and time limits. In addition, the
federal government now distributes a limited amount of welfare
money to each state rather than providing a bottomless pool of
money to guarantee that everybody eligible for benefits receives
them.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has a waiver to to pursue its own welfare reform plan, but
the waiver runs out in 2002. At that time, the state will have to
comply with federal rules, some of which are more strict.
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials say the state's welfare caseload declined to
148,750 in September 1998, down from 285,632 in January 1994. They
attribute the drop to changes in welfare rules, a strong economy
and efforts to combat fraud. The point of the study, they say, was
to find out what happened to the people who left the welfare rolls,
as well as those who requested aid but didn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers randomly chose 3,298 people from each category, and
were able to conduct telephone interviews with 1,159 of them. The
rest of the people either refused to answer the questions or
couldn't be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-five percent of respondents had jobs at the time of the
interview, working an average of 34 hours a week at an average
hourly wage of $6.28. The federal minimum wage is $5.15. The most
common jobs were restaurant/fast food (15 percent), clerical (13
percent), retail and sales (13 percent), nursing (12 percent) and
janitorial (6 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The state's 51 percent response rate is respectable for a survey
of this kind, experts say. But it elicits the question: What
happened to the remaining 49 percent?
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they didn't respond inherently raises questions
about their condition,'' said Mike Lucas, and aide to Rep. Elliott
Naishtat, D-Austin. Naishtat sat on an interim legislative
committee examining the welfare-to-work law.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas and King also questioned the quality of the jobs that many
respondents found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are these jobs going to lead them anywhere? Can they support a
family? Is there any career path here?'' King said. ``Most of these
jobs don't provide these people with further access to education
and training, and that's the huge difference between people who are
working out well and those who aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Many respondents said they needed better training and education,
better child care, or better health insurance to be able to find
jobs or advance their careers. Bush and Bost said Wednesday they
will urge the Legislature to boost child-care assistance,
strengthen child-support enforcement and allow welfare recipients
who have found a job to continue to receive benefits for some time
in order to address those concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
