<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2185 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DEFENSE-BOS &LR;      12-09 1553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAWYERS REBUFFED IN FINAL APPEAL TO HOUSE PANEL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's lawyers were rebuffed Wednesday
in their last appeal to the House Judiciary Committee, as the panel
sent them home with four proposed impeachment counts arguing the
president should be removed from office because he ``willfully
corrupted and manipulated the judicial process of the United States
for his personal gain and exoneration.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the White House lawyers ended an impassioned,
marathon defense against the allegations, the Judiciary Committee
released a draft impeachment resolution that charges Clinton with
two counts of perjury and one each of obstruction of justice and
abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all of this, William Jefferson Clinton has undermined the
integrity of his office, has brought disrepute on the presidency,
has betrayed his trust as president, and has acted in a manner
subversive of the rule of law and justice, to the manifest injury
of the people of the United States,'' each article of impeachment
states. The entire case arises from the president's sex scandal
with the former White House intern, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the tumultuous buildup to Thursday's opening debate by the
committee on the historic charges, Chairman Henry J. Hyde, an
Illinois Republican, also cleared the way for the panel to vote on
a Democratic alternative resolution of ``censure and
condemnation.'' The proposed rebuke, in biting language, would
require Clinton to admit he has ``violated the trust of the
American people, lessened their esteem for the office of president
and dishonored the office which they have entrusted to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The competing proposals emerged as Clinton's foes and allies
sought to sway a critical group of undecided lawmakers who are
expected to decide on impeachment in the full House next week.
</P>
<P>
   Both plans became public as the White House counsel, Charles
F.C. Ruff, issued a final, emotional plea in Clinton's two-day,
21-hour defense presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that Clinton's conduct was ``wrong'' and ``morally
reprehensible,'' Ruff argued that his actions fell short of meeting
the standards for the ultimate sanction of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He betrayed the trust placed in him not only by his loved ones
but by the American people,'' Ruff testified. ``But the president
has not committed a high crime or misdemeanor.''
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton's prospects in the House too close call, the White
House also called a last-minute Republican witness, former
Massachusetts Governor William F. Weld, who recommended the
president be fined, censured and compelled to submit a written
apology for his misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is expected to approve at least one, if
not all, of the impeachment counts by Saturday. If the House votes
to impeach Clinton, the resolution would be forwarded to the Senate
for the first presidential impeachment trial in 130 years and the
second ever.
</P>
<P>
   The White House assailed the timing of the draft resolution's
release as the latest injustice in an impeachment process it says
has been tainted from the start by partisan fervor.
</P>
<P>
   ``After denying the president the right to see the charges
against him before offering his defense, the committee majority
decided to proceed with impeachment without even listening to his
defense,'' said James A. Kennedy, spokesman for the White House
counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the unfairness of the timing of the charges, however,
we can now say with certainty that nothing in the record, nothing
in the facts, or the law, or the Constitution or these charges
compels the Congress to take the solemn step of impeaching and
removing the president,'' Kennedy added.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the fray, independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr countered a
184-page rebuttal the White House issued Tuesday that portrayed
Starr's report on the Lewinsky affair as biased. Starr issued a
statement citing ``many misleading statements in the White House
submission.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigative phase of the Judiciary Committee proceedings
is expected to reach a dramatic finale Thursday. Hyde's chief
investigator, David P. Schippers, is expected to show, for the
first time publicly, excerpts of Clinton's videotaped deposition
last January in the sexual harassment case that Paula Corbin Jones
brought against him and settled last month.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers also plans to play segments of Clinton's videotaped
testimony in August before a federal grand jury investigating the
Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   In both proceedings, the impeachment articles allege, Clinton
repeatedly committed perjury to cover up his illicit affair with
Lewinsky and impede justice.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed obstruction-of-justice charge cites seven instances
when Clinton attempted to ``delay, impede, cover up and conceal''
evidence in the Jones case. The abuse-of-power article alleges
Clinton ``frivolously and corruptly'' invoked executive privilege
and made false and misleading statements to his Cabinet, aides and
the American people.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the impeachment resolution charges that Clinton
made false statements when he responded in an affidavit to 81
questions from the committee asking him to admit aspects of the
Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   Each count concludes: ``William Jefferson Clinton, by such
conduct, warrants impeachment and trial, and removal from office
and disqualification to hold and enjoy any office of honor, trust
or profit under the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats quickly issued a 13-page response to the
draft resolution, citing rebuttals that ``erode the foundation for
the majority's allegations and establish that there is no basis for
an impeachment of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Several committee Democrats, while conceding the GOP majority on
the panel will prevail on at least one count of the impeachment
resolution, focused on the censure proposal. One of the plan's
chief architects, Representative William D. Delahunt of Quincy, had
been the first committee member to announce he would seek a censure
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt said Hyde's agreement to allow a vote on the measure,
after first indicating he would block such a vote, could be
critical to resolving the protracted impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be our last opportunity to avoid going over the
precipice and triggering a genuine constitutional crisis,''
Delahunt said in a statement with his Democratic co-sponsors,
Representatives Rick Boucher of Virginia and Tom Barrett of
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is expected to be thwarted by the panel's Republican
majority. But by allowing the committee vote, several Democrats
said Hyde effectively increased pressure on GOP leaders to permit a
vote in the full House, which many lawmakers favor as a way to
sanction Clinton without the trauma of a protracted Senate trial
and a possible transition of power if he were convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the censure proposal could argue that standard
House procedures dictate a measure that fails to pass the committee
should not be considered by the full House.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.3l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The censure movement received a boost Wednesday when a key
moderate Republican, Representative Amo Houghton of New York,
announced he will oppose impeachment and called on GOP leaders to
help push for an alternative such as censure.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.3l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The lame duck House speaker, Newt Gingrich of Georgia, said he
will play no role in the impeachment matter, other than to vote
when the resolution reaches the House floor. ``I'm not getting near
that,'' Gingrich said in a brief interview. ``It's entirely up to
Livingston,'' he added, referring to the speaker-designate, Robert
L. Livingston of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.3l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Livingston has not committed whether to allow a censure vote,
although the majority whip, Tom DeLay of Texas, whom Livingston has
effectively designated to oversee the impeachment process through
the House, staunchly opposes the scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the 31 Democrats who voted with every Republican
House member in September to launch the open-ended inquiry sent
Livingston a letter Wednesday denouncing Clinton's actions as
``immoral, reckless and harmful to our nation'' but not
impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, led by Representative Tim Roemer of Indiana,
called on Livingston to allow a ``vote for an alternative form of
punishment, such as a resolution to censure the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Roemer, in an interview, accused GOP leaders of ``cajoling and
arm-twisting'' lawmakers to vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The White House tried to bolster anti-impeachment sentiment by
calling Weld, a former US attorney for Massachusetts, and several
other former federal prosecutors to testify that Clinton's actions
were not impeachable and also would not warrant criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case is a loser,'' said Richard J. Davis, a former
Watergate prosecutor who also served as assistant Treasury
Secretary for enforcement under President Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans stood by their proposed charges, however,
citing numerous allegations of false and misleading statements by
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Wisconsin Representative F. James Sensenbrenner
Jr., who asked: ``Who's going to stand up for the truth here?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
