<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2188 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETH     12-09 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1,050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS MAKE FORMAL CALL FOR IMPEACHMENT ON 4 COUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: SUBS to raise and expand on Democrat's 13-page rebuttal in
grafs 10-11 bgng, And committee ...; updates and tightens
elsewhere; No pickup.) 
 (See also: IMPEACH-DEFENSE, IMPEACH-LEGAL, IMPEACH-STARR,
IMPEACH-SCHIPPERS, IMPEACH-GRASSROOTS, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-RUFF,
IMPEACH-POLITICS, IMPEACH-PRESIDE, IMPEACH-TEXT, EDIT-IMPEACH) 
 (htv) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT and LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee on
Wednesday formally called for President Clinton's removal from
office in four draft articles of impeachment accusing Clinton of
perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed charges were disclosed even before the White House
had finished presenting its two-day defense of the president to the
panel.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the White House, top Democrats and a handful
of Republicans intensified their push to let the full House vote
next week on censuring the president as an alternative to
impeachment. But Republican leaders are resisting such a vote,
fearing it would siphon some moderate Republicans from voting for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In harshly worded language, the proposed articles pushed beyond
the grounds for impeachment outlined in the Starr report sent to
Congress three months ago, which accused the president of lying
under oath about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, of
obstruction of justice and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   But Judiciary Republicans folded the many allegations into four
counts: two counts of perjury, one count of obstruction of justice
and one count of abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   The perjury count was divided into two parts, one on the
president's testimony to the federal grand jury and one for his
deposition in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct case. The split was
devised to address the concerns of some Republicans who are
reluctant to support a charge of perjury stemming from a civil
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all of this,'' the eight-page draft of the articles
concluded, ``William Jefferson Clinton has undermined the integrity
of his office, has brought disrepute on the presidency, has
betrayed his trust as president, and has acted in a manner
subversive of the rule of law and justice, to the manifest injury
of the people of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which had for weeks demanded to know the
specific charges the Judiciary Committee was considering in order
to prepare its defense, immediately dismissed them as unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in the articles, there's nothing in the
allegations, there's nothing in the record, there's nothing in the
Constitution that brings anything here up to the standard of an
impeachable offense,'' said Joe Lockhart, the White House press
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   And committee Democrats immediately issued a 13-page rebuttal to
the articles of impeachment, denouncing the Republicans for issuing
the charges before the committee begins hearing closing arguments
on Thursday. Charge by charge, the rebuttal attacks the credibility
of several witnesses, pointedly assailing Ms. Lewinsky's testimony
on several different matters.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed articles of impeachment will form the basis for the
committee's deliberations this week. On Thursday, the investigative
counsel for the Republicans, David Schippers, plans to show
Clinton's videotaped deposition in the Jones case as part of his
closing arguments. His Democratic counterpart, Abbe Lowell, also
will give a summation on Thursday. On Friday, the 37-member panel
begins debating the articles and is almost certain to vote along
party lines for impeachment by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Release of the panel's draft articles capped an extraordinary
two days of testimony by the president's top lawyers and legal
scholars and former federal prosecutors who argued that Clinton's
misleading statements and misconduct in the Lewinsky affair did not
rise to the level of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Few opinions were swayed as sharp exchanges marked the hearings,
with committee Republicans challenging Clinton's representatives
over and over to acknowledge that the President had committed
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., was among those who pushed the
president's defenders for more information. ``Your presentation has
helped point us to the portions of that record before us that you
believe are relevant to your client's defense,'' Canady said. ``But
let me say that I am still frustrated by what I consider to be
legal arguments that don't really meet the test of common sense and
human experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In a counterattack, committee Democrats issued a censure
alternative that would condemn the president for ``making false
statements concerning his reprehensible conduct'' and wrongly
taking steps to ``delay the discovery of the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic censure proposal _ drafted by Reps. Rick Boucher
of Virginia, Bill Delahunt of Massachusetts and Tom Barrett of
Wisconsin _ also states that Clinton ``remains subject to criminal
and civil penalties for this conduct.'' Clinton would be obligated
to sign the censure. The proposed wording does not include
imposition of a fine.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, the committee chairman, said he would allow a
committee vote on the measure, but then added that he would vote
against it. Even the measure's sponsors conceded that censure has
no chance of passing the Republican-controlled panel. But Democrats
voiced hope it would win enough support from moderate Republicans
to force Republican leaders to allow a floor vote on some form of
censure.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum for censure received a boost from a prominent
Republican, former Gov. William Weld of Massachusetts, who
announced his own version of an alternative at the committee
hearing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Weld's plan, which White House officials said they did not know
of in advance, mirrors the Democratic alternative, but would also
include a fine to penalize Clinton for his misconduct. Democrats
say they would be open to the president's negotiating a fine, to
get around constitutional hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dignity of the House would be upheld if something like
that were to be approached,'' said Weld, who testified in defense
of the president on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a significant shift, the White House moved from a crouch to
aggressive support of a censure option. ``The president's general
position is that he's done something blameworthy,'' Lockhart said.
``If members of Congress want to come to him with an idea short of
impeachment, it's something he would consider.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the majority of the House wants a vehicle to vote on some
other option than impeachment, then they should be given that,''
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart declined to comment on the details of any censure
motion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Those who support a censure option still face an uphill battle.
Rep. Robert Livingston, the speaker-designate, has not ruled out a
censure vote on the floor, but the Republican whip, Rep. Tom DeLay,
is actively blocking any attempt to let lawmakers vote on censure.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the 31 Democrats who in October voted for the
Republican impeachment inquiry resolution _ Tim J. Roemer of
Indiana, Ellen Tauscher of California and Jim Moran of Virginia _
collected signatures from the group for a letter to Livingston,
urging a floor vote on a censure motion.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the Democratic
leader, started calling the 31 Democrats to see how they would vote
on impeachment. Between three and five Democrats might vote for
impeachment, Democratic aides say, meaning that 14 to 16
Republicans would have to oppose impeachment to kill it on the
House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Bonior, the Democratic whip, was calling to make sure
all Democrats _ even those who are retiring or who lost re-election
bids _ are planning to return for next week's momentous vote on the
House floor.
</P>
<P>
   The draft documents were released as the White House counsel,
Charles Ruff, was finishing an eloquently meticulous defense of why
Clinton should not be removed from office for his admitted
misconduct in the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House official said the timing of the release of
the articles of impeachment was clear evidence of the partisan
nature of the judiciary proceedings and of closed-mindedness on the
part of the Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the hearing room after the proceedings, Hyde told
reporters that he planned to vote for all four articles of
impeachment, and he predicted that at least one of the perjury
counts would be approved by the full committee.
</P>
<P>
   The first article in the drafts charges Clinton with perjury
before the grand jury on Aug. 17, and outlines four accusations.
Among them, Clinton is charged with ``false and misleading
testimony'' about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, and his
efforts to influence the testimony of witnesses in the Jones sexual
misconduct case.
</P>
<P>
   The second article on perjury charges Clinton with signing an
affidavit in the Jones case on Dec. 23, 1997, pledging to tell the
truth and then lying about whether he had a sexual relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky. The article also accuses the president of giving
false statements under oath in his Jan. 17 deposition in the Jones
case.
</P>
<P>
   The third article of impeachment accuses Clinton of obstructing
justice in an effort to ``delay, impede, cover up and conceal the
existence of evidence'' in the Jones case. The article lists seven
acts that the Republican committee staff believes bolster the
charge.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, on Dec. 17, the article charges, Clinton
encouraged Ms. Lewinsky, who is not named in the draft, to lie in a
sworn statement and to give false testimony. The article also
accuses the president of helping create a plan to hide evidence _
the gifts that he gave Ms. Lewinsky _ and of successfully pressing
to get Ms. Lewinsky a new job in New York to buy her silence in the
Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth article of impeachment charges that the president
``misused and abused his office,'' laying out four instances. Among
them, the article charges, is that Clinton lied to the American
people, gave false and misleading statements to White House aides
and his Cabinet officers, and ``frivolously asserted'' executive
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The committee reorganized the 11 main charges contained in the
report by Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel. In addition, the
committee added at least three supporting instances.
</P>
<P>
   In the obstruction of justice article, the committee charged
that Clinton did not correct his lawyer, Robert Bennett, during the
Jones deposition, when Bennett asserted that Ms. Lewinsky's
affidavit proved that ``no sex of any kind'' had occurred and
should foreclose any questioning of Clinton on that matter.
</P>
<P>
   In the article alleging abuse of power, the committee added the
accusation that the president lied to the American public and that
the president committed perjury by lying in his answers to 81
questions submitted by the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``These four articles of impeachment reflect the evidence we
have had before us and the testimony we have had before us,'' said
Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders have tentatively set aside Dec. 16
through Dec. 19 for debate and votes, Republican aides said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
