<HEADER>
A2193 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIMATE-COX     12-09 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIMATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientists seek more detail in global weather forecasts
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The dramatic flip-flop from the withering
drought of this year's long, hot summer to October's sudden
historic floods could have been no more than the usual feast or
famine of Texas weather.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists say the flip-flop also fits a tentative forecast
for global warming: more weather extremes, from dryer drys to
wetter wets, and a particularly heavy increase in rainfall in many
parts of the world because warmer air holds more moisture.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, the computer climate models that make such
predictions contain too few of the multitude of things that
influence climate _ and too many built-in fudge factors _ to be
wholly reliable.
</P>
<P>
   Working to improve those models is James Famiglietti, an
assistant professor of geological sciences at the University of
Texas. He is using ground observations and satellite imagery to
enhance the climate model of the National Center for Atmospheric
Research in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The Boulder model and a similar one developed by German
scientists are considered the most reliable in predicting the
weather effects of global warming _ changes in climate tied to
accumulation in the atmosphere of gases from the burning of coal,
oil and gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the climate models now,'' Famiglietti said,
``is that they have no rivers in them. They began as atmospheric
models only. The frontier of modeling is coupling the atmosphere to
the influence of the oceans and the surface water of the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite continued debate in Congress on global warming,
scientists are steadily amassing evidence that it already may be
under way, including a recent finding that the 1990s have been the
warmest decade in 600 years.
</P>
<P>
   But, as tempting as it is to see last summer in Texas as more
proof of global warming, it only tied for fifth place in the number
of 100- or 100-plus-degree days _ 33. The most such days on record
in Texas came in 1923 with 66, according to the National Weather
Service.
</P>
<P>
   And the prediction that global warming will produce flip-flops
from one weather extreme to another in Texas and elsewhere is
little more than a hunch that global warming researchers share.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of one simulation that says the cycles will be more
extreme,'' said Gerald North, chairman of the meteorology
department at Texas A&AMP;M University. ``But another model found the
opposite. The models have too much play in them. You need to narrow
them down (to) constrain the fudge factors.''
</P>
<P>
   To help constrain them, Famiglietti is trying to do on a global
scale what David Maidment, director of UT's Center for Research in
Water Resources, is doing regionally.
</P>
<P>
   Maidment and his colleagues are working to improve flood
forecasting by creating the first precision digital map of Texas
terrain elevations and their influence on runoff into creeks and
rivers. Radar rainfall measurements by the National Weather
Service, for instance, now focus only on areas of 1.24 miles,
called rainfall cells.
</P>
<P>
   The digital map will sharpen the focus so the weather service
can measure the runoff effect of rainfall on terrain-elevation
cells as small as 97.5 feet in area.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Famiglietti is trying to use satellite imagery and
ground surveys to reduce the 155-mile area focus of most global
climate models to as little as 31 miles, which should improve
forecasting of the hydrological cycle, or movement of water from
evaporation into the atmosphere and back again in the form of rain
and other precipitation.
</P>
<P>
   Famiglietti also plans to use data gathered by the twin GRACE,
or Gravity Recovery And Climate Experiment, satellites whose
international development is being coordinated by UT's Center for
Space Research.
</P>
<P>
   The satellites, built by German scientists and set for launch by
Russian ones in 2001, will monitor the climate-influencing effects
of ocean circulation and evaporation from rivers, lakes and
reservoirs by measuring tiny variations in the planet's
gravitational field.
</P>
<P>
   But improving the climate models ultimately will depend on
advances in computer technology. Even today's fast processing
speeds and large computer memories aren't enough for a global
climate model focused as finely as 31 miles in area to forecast for
longer than 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Famiglietti, who is from Rhode Island, would
just as soon not see any more global-warming hints in Texas
weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really hope we're not in for more summers like this (last)
one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
