<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2194 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-JANKOVICH-LADN     12-09 2002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-JANKOVICH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMILIAR CHALLENGE FOR JANKOVICH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ They know nothing of the athletic
department turmoil of the past three years, or of the burdensome
budgetary restraints. They've never heard of Michael Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   They know nothing about Cal State Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   But those who have worked for Sam Jankovich know one thing about
CSUN's athletic program:
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the mess may be, Jankovich will clean it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a doer, a guy that gets things done,'' University of
Miami men's basketball coach Leonard Hamilton said. ``He's
extremely focused, very thorough. He has a great feeling for solid
issues and for dealing with all different aspects of an athletic
department. It won't take him long to figure out what the problems
are at Northridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Named CSUN's interim athletic director Dec. 1, Jankovich has
seven months to work his magic on a program trying to push itself
into the quasi big-time, only to continually bumble and stumble
over itself.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich's former employees at Washington State University and
at the University of Miami speak of his ability to sway public
perception and raise funds, to build a network of individuals who
remain supportive after 20 years, of a no-nonsense approach that
doesn't tolerate complacency or failure.
</P>
<P>
   And they speak of a man with vision, and of a man with the
capacity to implement a plan that should carry CSUN through the
next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't always agree with his methods, but I agreed with what
got done,'' former Washington State football coach Jim Walden said.
``If you got your feelings hurt along the way, it didn't matter.
All I know is he got it done. He doesn't back up to get a paycheck.
Not everyone will like him, but those that like him will work hard
for him and be better for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich is 64 years old and, admittedly, this is his last
significant undertaking in collegiate athletics. It doesn't mean
he's any less ornery, or tough, than he was 22 years ago when he
was named athletic director at Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich's guidelines are simple: work hard and together, be
honest, perform within the rules and communicate _ or else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give everybody an opportunity, but they're going
to have to perform under these ground rules,'' Jankovich said.
``People who don't want to perform under those ground rules, this
isn't going to be the place for them because we're not going to
saddle somebody coming in here in six, seven or eight months from
now who is going to inherit a cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes surprises. But the big problem you're faced to
deal with is that small problem that nobody addresses, and it
develops into a cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider Jankovich CSUN's chemotherapy. He was brought in after
Paul Bubb resigned last month in the wake of Abraham's arrest by
the FBI for alleged crack cocaine trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Bubb came under scrutiny when it was learned former players
approached him nearly two years before Abraham's arrest, voicing
concern about their coach's behavior and a possible tie to drugs.
Bubb said he investigated and found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the many gaffes Jankovich, an eloquent and
persuasive speaker, must fix. He must revive the program's public
image and somehow build support for a program that dropped four of
its men's sports _ only to reinstate them later _ in the spring of
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Among the financial problems he faces, the football program's
might be the worst. Trapped in an outdated, undersized stadium and
limited by an unheard of $5,000 recruiting budget, Jankovich must
find a way to continue the program's rise in Division I-AA.
</P>
<P>
   And those are just some of the problems. Gender equity issues
and the constant search for money plague the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving to put stability in the short term and permanence
in the long-term appointment of an athletic director,'' CSUN
president Blenda Wilson said. ``What we need is a full-fledged, in
place, athletic director willing to make a commitment to work seven
or 10 hours a day, or whatever it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been on the job for nine days, not long enough to identify,
in detail, what is wrong at the school. But before he leaves the
post June 30, 1999 _ or later if finding a successor takes longer _
he wants to set up an agenda on how to run the department. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASSESSING PRIORITIES
</P>
<P>
   CSUN wants to build new athletic facilities for football,
baseball, softball and intramurals, but surrounding neighbors are
resisting. The Big Sky Conference has mandated CSUN to build a new
football facility. The penalty for not doing so, in the most severe
case, could be expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   This situation is nothing new for Jankovich.
</P>
<P>
   When he began his seven-year tenure at Washington State in 1976,
the Cougars' football team played in a 27,600-seat stadium. With
growing fear the NCAA would institute a rule mandating Division I
programs play in a stadium with a capacity of at least 30,000,
Jankovich pushed to expand the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents wanted to use the funds elsewhere, and said the
residue of expanding the stadium would adversely affect the
baseball and track programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got resistance from nearly everyone,'' Walden, the former
Cougars football coach, said. ``When it was all said and done,
Washington State had a state-of-the art track, a beautiful baseball
field and a football field that sat 40,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich was creative in financing the venture, enticing local
businesses to donate time, money and services so the project
wouldn't be financed solely with cash.
</P>
<P>
   A $250,000 donation was given by the Martin family, for which
the football stadium is named, but a final figure wasn't totaled
because much of the construction was done through gift-of-kind
contributions, Washington State assistant athletic director of
communications Rod Commons said.
</P>
<P>
   The construction of the three athletic venues also solidified
Washington State's standing in the Pacific-10 Conference _ which
was in jeopardy, Commons said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was kind of a visionary. He knew what it would take at
Washington State to get the job done,'' Commons said. ``He put the
first buyout clause in a contract. When Warren Powers was coach he
put in a clause saying if Warren was to leave he would owe the
school money, and if he was fired the school had to pay him. It
gave Sam protection.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STEPPING UP
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich parlayed his success at Washington State into the
athletic director's job at Miami. In 1983 he left for Coral Gables,
where he built the Hurricanes into one of the most feared, most
hated, and most successful programs in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Most know about the three national championships in football,
but there were national championships in baseball, men's tennis,
women's tennis and women's golf.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Jankovich resurrected the men's basketball program after a
15-year absence and had the Hurricanes join the Big East
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under his watch a lot of things changed for us,'' Miami
president Edward T. Foote II said. ``He's a strong athletic
director.''
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich also unified a frayed athletic department, primarily
through his intense, aggressive fund-raising policy.
</P>
<P>
   The year before his arrival at Miami, the school's athletic
fund-raising efforts brought in $750,000. One of the first things
Jankovich did was organize a booster club for the athletic program,
and not for individual sports. Five years into Jankovich's regime
Miami's fund-raising efforts brought in $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will immediately take (the Northridge) community and work
it,'' said Larry Wahl, Miami's senior assistant director for
communications and executive producer of Hurricanes Productions.
``Everyone in the community will know him. When he came here we had
three different athletic departments; a baseball department, a
football department and the rest of the athletic department. Sam
changed that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich hopes for a comparable turnaround at CSUN. Michael
Rehm, CSUN's assistant athletic director/development and the
school's point man on fund raising, said Northridge raised $340,000
last year.
</P>
<P>
   With 1.3 million people in the San Fernando Valley and several
opportunities for corporate support, Jankovich figures CSUN's
budget woes can be cured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think fund raising has to be (a big part of this),''
Jankovich said. ``I have to learn more about the marketplace, but
with the population I can't help but think (it should be better). I
have to see what they have in place, and how they're doing it. I
would anticipate there would be some changes about the approach,
and what has to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich also pioneered the current way athletic departments
deal with shoe and apparel companies while at Miami. Instead of
individual coaches signing with companies, Jankovich struck a deal
with a sneaker company to outfit all of Miami's teams and wrote a
portion of it into coaches' contracts.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jankovich's tenure at Miami was not perfect. The NCAA
noted several major infractions, including the distribution of
excessive financial aid to athletes, a fraudulent use of Pell
Grants, improper employment of football players during the school
year and a lack of institutional control.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Reed, chancellor of the Cal State University system,
worked with Jankovich in Florida's state system and pushed for his
hire at CSUN because the good heavily offset the bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got someone who knows what they're doing,'' Reed said in
understating the issue. ``In the sports business, he has a great
network that will work well at Northridge.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUITED TO THE TASK
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich, who resides in Hayden Lake, Idaho, comes from the
big-time but understands the Big Sky Conference. He is a University
of Montana graduate and a former Grizzlies assistant football
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich molded Washington State and Miami in his personality,
though his stayover as CEO of the New England Patriots, which
lasted from 1990 to 1992, was short-lived. He hired
ultra-successful Syracuse coach Dick MacPherson to coach the
Patriots, but both met the same fate. The professional game
differed greatly from college, and neither man lasted in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't detract from Jankovich's accomplishments at the
collegiate level. Instead, it fueled the thinking Jankovich was
best suited as a college administrator.
</P>
<P>
   It's why college presidents, trustees and athletic directors
continue to lean on him. Nearly a decade after Jankovich left
Miami, he's still active with the school, working as a consultant
on Miami's $35 million civic center.
</P>
<P>
   He also has done consulting work for San Diego State, the
University of Tulsa, Temple, Arizona State, the University of
Oklahoma and the University of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich's stay at CSUN is expected to last seven or so months.
At $9,334 per month the school is paying more than it has
historically for an athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   However, when the investment matures the dividends are expected
to be fruitful.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich won't just outline what must be done for the athletic
department to succeed 20 years down the line, he will meticulously
detail and document what should be done.
</P>
<P>
   He'll conduct more interviews than Ken Starr, at a fraction of
the cost. Jankovich pledges to talk with students,
student-athletes, coaches, administrators, former athletes, alumni,
community leaders and anyone else who will offer an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The title is interim, but Jankovich wields the power to make
changes to a program in dire need of change. He will ask the
questions and provide the comprehensive answers that have some
coaches at CSUN shaking in anticipation of what might happen, while
others rejoice in the long-awaited arrival of such a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a colorful, fun, interesting person. He's hard-working,
very intense,'' Foote said. ``If it can be done, Sam's the guy to
do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
