<HEADLINE>
GUSTS PUSH BLAZE IN SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. -- Santa Ana winds fueled a brush fire that
burned at least 30 acres in Glendale's Brand Park on Wednesday
afternoon, putting residents of the Hillcrest Avenue neighborhood
on edge, but not getting close enough to threaten their homes,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire crawled up the hillside quickly after it started around
3:20 p.m. Fortunately, about an hour into the fire the high winds
that had been gusting in the community north of Los Angeles since
noon started to die down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the winds continued to grow it could have been a problem,''
said Glendale Fire Department Capt. Eric Indermill.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the fire is under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters expected to contain the blaze during the night, but
were concerned high winds might pick up again.
</P>
<P>
   The flames were about a quarter-mile away from homes, and
residents who live nearby started preparing to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   Susan DiCato, who has lived in the community since 1986, said
she packed her Ford Explorer with precious belongings and dropped
them off on the front yard of a friend. DiCato was scared because
the winds had been so high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a mini-tornado and then the fire started,'' DiCato
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lynch, who has lived in the area for 20 years, said she has
never seen a fire get so close to her home. The high winds woke her
up from a nap.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I got up and started to make some nachos and I thought this
cheese smells like smoke,'' Lynch said. Then the phone rang and a
neighbor told Lynch that the hills were on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Zakarian rushed home from work in Southern California's
City of Industry after his niece called to tell him about the fire.
He packed up his car with family photos and his best suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took all the pictures. The rest you can replace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While he was confident firefighters had the blaze under control,
he did run back in the house for something he forgot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I better take some underwear for tomorrow,'' Zakarian said.
``Just in case.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
