<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2200 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      12-09 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETOUR ON THE ROAD TO DAMASCUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After James Hamm got dumped by the invertebrates running Arizona
State University, I decided to look around for a profession that
wouldn't automatically reject an articulate man with degrees from
college and law school only because he also happened to have killed
another human being in cold blood.
</P>
<P>
   And I found one.
</P>
<P>
   It's up to Hamm to follow up on this, of course. But since
university officials decided a convicted murderer is not morally,
ethically and spiritually equipped to teach a couple of classes,
Hamm can enter vocational training for a less blindly restrictive
profession.
</P>
<P>
   The clergy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, that is possible,'' said Rabbi David Rebibo. I'd been
sent to him by administrators at the Phoenix Hebrew Academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our patriarchs, our forefathers, used to be idol worshipers,''
Rebibo said. ``They changed. Any person who recognizes the wrong he
does, and takes appropriate action, expresses regret, learns,
progresses, can see a black paper made white.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is said in classical Judaism that the idea of repentance
was created before the world, before man, because God knew how we
would be, and repentance was the therapy for man to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Coffelt from the Presbyterian Church's Arizona Presbytery,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disturbed by what happened in the Hamm case,'' he
said. &QL; 
SOME RULES APPLY
</P>
<P>
   Coffelt said a man convicted of murder who was interested in the
ministry would first have to be a member of a church. He'd have to
get their governing body to endorse him, then apply to the
presbytery for permission to enter the three-year program for
becoming a minister. After that, a congregation would have to hire
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I was told the same thing by the Arizona Southern Baptist
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been former felons who have graduated from the
seminary,'' said the convention's Sandy de Jesus. ``Something like
that wouldn't automatically disqualify an individual.''
</P>
<P>
   A man with Hamm's background also could become a Catholic
priest, depending upon where he'd like to practice.
</P>
<P>
   If he were to enter a monastery, it would be no problem. To
become a parish priest, however, he'd need approval from the office
of the pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to be practical,'' said Father Paul Orel of the Roman
Catholic Diocese of Phoenix. ``We recognize that we have human
beings who, in the ideal, should be merciful, loving and forgiving
in their hearts. But sometimes in practical ways they aren't there
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Not at ASU, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And not among all the churchgoers who left less-than-Christian
comments concerning Hamm on my voice mail. Some of them probably
don't believe a man declared unqualified to teach the laws of man
would be permitted to teach the laws of God. &QL; 
The gospel story
</P>
<P>
   But there's a precedent.
</P>
<P>
   You may have learned in Sunday school about another murderer who
landed an important job. His name was Saul. The story goes that,
years ago, in Jerusalem, Saul and some pals participated in the
stoning death of a very nice man named Stephen. Saul then hired
himself out as a kind of vigilante, rounding up Christians.
</P>
<P>
   One day, as he approached the city of Damascus, Saul was said to
have been struck by a shaft of light from heaven, and called upon
by God to preach the gospel. And he did. He changed his name to
Paul, traveled and wrote ``letters'' that become the cornerstone of
the New Testament. And he became a saint.
</P>
<P>
   James Hamm is no saint. He's not looking to become a priest or
minister or rabbi. And he doesn't deserve redemption. All he
deserves, from having served his time in prison and improved
himself, is the benefit of the doubt. The chance to stand in front
of a classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the dictionary translations for the word ``rabbi,''
there's one that seems to apply here more than others:
``Teacher.'' &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
