<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREZNEXT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSTITUTION'S MAP ON IMPEACHMENT HAS LOTS OF DETOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The rules governing impeachment are like an
interstate highway: clearly marked, but with lots of possible exits
into more uncharted territory.
</P>
<P>
   Although approval of one or more articles of impeachment by the
House Judiciary Committee this week seems almost certain, almost
nothing else is. The pitfalls of politics seem likely to bring
detours from the impeachment road map set out in the Constitution,
congressional rules and precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold onto your hats, it could be a bumpy ride,'' Senate
Parliamentarian Robert Dove said.
</P>
<P>
   Expect minority Democrats in the full House to try to get a vote
on a measure that would censure, rather than impeach, President
Clinton. With the help of some Republicans, that maneuver on what
is called a ``motion to recommit'' could stop the impeachment
process cold. There also could be a move in the House to block the
appointment of ``managers'' of the impeachment trial, a requirement
before the Senate could hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   Twists and turns aside, a simple majority vote on one or more
articles of impeachment would send the case to the Senate. The
House is also required to appoint those managers, traditionally
members of the House, who will act as prosecutors of the case. When
President Andrew Johnson was impeached in 1868, the House voted in
seven managers, said George Washington University history Professor
Leo Ribuffo.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate then would vote to allow the managers to read the
articles and form itself into a court of impeachment, where the
chief justice of the Supreme Court presides. Once the Senate
becomes an impeachment court, its normal rules, such as the
filibuster, do not apply.
</P>
<P>
   Such a vote could happen as soon as Jan. 8, Dove said.
</P>
<P>
   Things could get kind of weird in the Senate, though, Ribuffo
said. There, a simple majority vote can change the rules: for
example, the rule that says senators cannot talk during any
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that 100 senators will sit silent like jurors is
just wacky. It defies logic,'' Ribuffo said.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Dove said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can change the rules, but they almost never do,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Almost.
</P>
<P>
   While the chief justice presides, he doesn't have the final say.
When Johnson was tried, the Senate overruled him 17 times, said
Ribuffo.
</P>
<P>
   The case might not even get that far. Ribuffo says the Senate
could simply decide not to hear the matter on the grounds that the
House was incorrect, an opinion that Dove disputes. Or it could
decide that the articles of impeachment expire with the current
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   That situation is unlikely, many scholars agree, because there
is ample precedent of one Congress impeaching a government official
and another Congress trying that official. Probably the best known
example is that of Florida Judge Alcee Hastings, who was impeached
by the House in 1988 despite his acquittal in a court trial, and
convicted by the Senate in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   His case is also famous because the Senate declined to impose a
political ``death penalty'' _ a separate vote the Senate can take
to bar the politician from a position of honor, trust or profit for
life. U.S. Rep. Alcee Hastings, a Democrat, was elected to Congress
in 1992 and still serves. He will vote on the Clinton case.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that impeachment is largely a political
process that only mimics a legal one, and anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really need to know the deals being discussed in the
background,'' Ribuffo said. ``The public show of the Judiciary
Committee doesn't tell us much.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, when the committee voted to impeach President Nixon,
the background drama being played out was the eventually successful
effort to get him to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can do anything they want,'' Ribuffo said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adrianne Flynn can be reached at (202) 662-7262 or at
adrianne.flynn(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
