</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VACCO-ASSESS-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S BEHIND THE VACCO CASE? MORE THAN A SINGLE ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: NY-VACCO-ELECTION) 
 (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In politics, the partisan warfare usually ends the
day after the election, when candidates metamorphose into courtly
ladies and gentlemen, dutifully uttering pleasantries about their
opponents, and move on. But after a race that he apparently lost by
the slimmest of margins, Attorney General Dennis Vacco has refused
to stand down, even as he suffers repeated setbacks, as he did
Wednesday, in his stubborn quest for resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, in challenging the outcome of the balloting, Vacco, a
Republican, is seeking to avoid becoming one of the few statewide
officials in New York to be ousted after a single term. Yet there
are also other, more purely political motivations in play, in the
view of some analysts and participants in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leadership seems to be trying to taint the
ostensible victory by the Democratic challenger, Eliot Spitzer, in
an effort to undercut his tenure and stoke resentment among upstate
Republicans. The party is also using the Vacco case to hone its
longstanding attacks on the way elections are conducted in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, though, even Vacco's aides acknowledge privately
that he is bruising his reputation. Democrats deride him as the
sorest of losers, a graceless politician who has reacted to his
defeat by throwing a legal temper tantrum. Some Republican
consultants grumble about the image that he and the party are
presenting.
</P>
<P>
   In the final unofficial count, Vacco trailed Spitzer by 26,011
votes out of 4.2 million cast, one of the closest statewide races
in New York in this century. Facing such a margin, the incumbent's
camp has adopted a variety of tactics to discredit the results in
the Democratic stronghold of New York City, raising the specter of
voting by the ineligible (illegal immigrants), as well as the
incorporeal (the dead).
</P>
<P>
   This week, Vacco's lawyers have argued unsuccessfully that there
was so much fraud that police officers should be required to fan
out across the city to verify the registration of tens of thousands
of voters. That move quickly highlighted the risk in his tactics:
many Democrats contended that the Republicans were seeking to
intimidate black and Hispanic voters in poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Even Vacco's Republican ally, Gov. George Pataki, has kept his
distance, saying that he was concerned about discouraging people
from taking part in elections.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief time in elective office, Vacco, a former U.S.
Attorney in Buffalo, has occasionally seemed to lack political
sophistication. Early in his tenure, he famously said that suing
the tobacco companies for health-care costs would be like suing
milk producers for high cholesterol. The attorney general's refusal
to concede this election may be an instance of him relying more on
prosecutorial instincts _ win a case at all costs _ than political
ones.
</P>
<P>
   The muscle behind the Vacco effort comes from the Republican
State Committee, which in recent years has cultivated a reputation
for dogged fund-raising and organizing. In this election, though,
the Republicans were somewhat humbled, as Sen. Alfonse D'Amato went
down to defeat, Pataki won by less than expected and the state
Assembly remained solidly in Democratic control.
</P>
<P>
   If Spitzer is certified the winner, it will be the final
embarrassment for Republican Chairman William D. Powers, a former
marine who rebuilt the party after it fell into disarray in the
late 1980s. One way to cushion such a blow would be to depict
Spitzer's victory and tenure as irrevocably sullied by city
chicanery. That might also help Vacco with upstate voters if he
chooses to run for another office or seek his old job in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, the Republicans repeatedly tried to stir
ill will among upstate residents toward the city _ without much
success, say some political strategists _ so such a motive in the
skirmish over the balloting would not be surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are hoping that if they muddy the waters with this
election, they might have a step up four years from now,'' said
George Arzt, a spokesman for Spitzer. It is not clear, though,
whether such a tactic will work. In 2002, how many people will
remember how this race was decided? Who recalls that Karen Burstein
was Vacco's opponent in 1994?
</P>
<P>
   Vacco and Powers have declined to speak to reporters in recent
days. But on Tuesday, Powers issued a statement decrying the
Democratic criticism. He said the Democrats were trying to scare
and mislead people about Vacco's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats would rather divide New Yorkers than follow the
law,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like many Republican leaders, Vacco and Powers seem to have a
simmering mistrust of election practices in New York City. It has
become doctrine in some Republican circles that the Democrats use
their overwhelming majority in many city neighborhoods to
manipulate the balloting in close races. (Democrats have their own
complaints about Republican tactics in Republican bastions like
Nassau County.)
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the Republicans believe that even if they lose
their challenge to the Spitzer vote, they will at least have
demonstrated that the party intends to keep scrutinizing election
practices in the city. And by using technology like computer
databases to evaluate the voter rolls, as they have done in this
case, they are showing that there are new ways of ferreting out
possible misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The background of this litigation is the deep suspicion that
the Republican Party has had about elections in the city,'' said
Lawrence Mandelker, an election lawyer who works for the party but
is not involved in the Vacco challenge. ``There is this ongoing
series of operations designed to convince the Democrats that they
are not out there alone, that somebody is watching them.''
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Powers put it another way. The Democratic
Party, he said, ``is not interested in determining in a fair and
objective way if our right to vote as citizens was illegally
diluted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
